<HEADLINE>
MAYBE A-ROD WILL SHOCK HIS AGENT _ AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ So, the Mariners will meet Wednesday with Alex
Rodriguez and his agent, Scott Boras. Does anyone believe beyond a
shadow of a doubt that No. 3 will be at Safeco Field on opening
day?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only person with reason for hope is Mariners CEO
Howard Lincoln, the man who can make Rodriguez far richer than,
let's say, Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are willing to pay whatever it takes to make A-Rod
the centerpiece of the franchise. Not that money always matters.
Look at Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   However, regardless of the mega-dollars the M's are willing to
shower upon A-Rod, the shortstop and his agent have held their
position. Rodriguez wants to play out the season in Seattle, then
make a decision about a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the Mariners have executed nearly every personnel
move suggested by A-Rod during the November meeting with club
officials, it seems Lincoln wants the chance to make sure the
shortstop has not changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because Rodriguez has twice waved off Boras during
negotiations with the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The first time was when A-Rod first signed with the M's for a $1
million bonus after they made him the No. 1 pick in the 1993 draft.
Boras had his client about 12 hours away from attending classes at
the University of Miami, just to stick it to the M's.
</P>
<P>
   Boras, who a few years later held out the Phillies' top draft
pick, J.D. Drew, because the Phillies wouldn't pay free-agent
dollars, wanted to make A-Rod his test case against underpaid draft
picks.
</P>
<P>
   During an emergency meeting with Mariners officials, A-Rod
finally relented, against Boras' direction.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Rodriguez accepted a four-year contract
extension from the Mariners _ a deal that will keep him below
market value this season, considering buddy Derek Jeter is making
almost $10 million for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For that extension, A-Rod again went against his agent's wishes,
because at the time, A-Rod wanted to set his family financially.
Since then, though, Rodriguez has said he will listen to Boras this
time around.
</P>
<P>
   In no uncertain terms, A-Rod knows this next deal is for all the
marbles. And despite his low-key, wait-and-see, boy-next-door
demeanor, A-Rod has been licking his chops.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to make a big splash. Somewhere. Bigger than Griffey
going home. Bigger than Sammy Sosa holding out for $160 million in
Chicago. Bigger than Jeter in New York, if any of those things are
possible.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the final hand of poker will get interesting
because, deep down, the M's know there is a bit of the little boy
in A-Rod.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln hopes history might repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure I know what his agent thinks, but I want to
hear what Alex has to say,'' Lincoln said a few weeks ago during
the Mariners' FanFest.
</P>
<P>
   Should A-Rod stick to his guns, though, Lincoln surely will give
general manager Pat Gillick the green light to commence the
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Having watched Randy Johnson and Griffey both demand out of
Seattle, the Mariners are getting used to this rejection stuff, and
Gillick, remember, is far less sentimental about M's draft picks
who become the biggest thing since Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, behind Gillick's willingness to accept the Reds'
cut-rate deal for Griffey was Lincoln's insistence to take whatever
it could get for the former No. 24.
</P>
<P>
   As for A-Rod, it is interesting to remember that he wears No. 3
_ not for Babe Ruth but for Dale Murphy, the former Atlanta Braves
outfielder whom Rodriguez idolized.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta isn't New York, Los Angeles or Chicago, where the White
Sox have talked about trading for the marquee shortstop. But A-Rod
is intrigued by the Braves' potential to reach the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Braves didn't want to part with Andruw Jones for
Griffey. But that's because their first choice in the trade market
was the other Mariners superstar, the one who would play next to
Chipper Jones in the infield and shore up their suddenly anemic
batting order.
</P>
<P>
   You don't think the Braves would do a little better against the
Yankees in the World Series should A-Rod be vying for the spotlight
against Jeter?
</P>
<P>
   It hardly seems possible that the Mariners are up for another
round of high-powered trade talks, not after what they've just been
through to clear Griffey out of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, it is the Mariners who have control, since
Rodriguez cannot veto any trade. Probably, the Mariners have saved
their kick for the finish.
</P>
<P>
   As the Griffey deal ground on noisily over the winter, Rodriguez
and the Mariners have been making cooing noises. All is well, both
sides have said. Time will tell what happens.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's time to tell.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the standoff between the Mariners and their shortstop
will no doubt begin in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, A-Rod shocks everyone, including his agent.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
