<HEADLINE>
WHITE, HOLLANDSWORTH BEGIN THEIR BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ The two principals involved in what surely
will be the best battle of the Los Angeles Dodgers spring arrived
Monday. And though manager Davey Johnson said Devon White is his
starting center fielder, Todd Hollandsworth will have every chance
to win the job.
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation White isn't used to, nor was he expecting it
after signing a three-year free-agent deal with the team after the
1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the organization is saying that Hollandsworth is the player
to play center field, so be it,'' White said. ``When the time
comes, if I have to speak out, I speak out. I can't worry about it
at this time. I'm going to continue to do what I've done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is people might say, 'Oh, they're trying to
light a fire under him.' What the hell is that? I can't even answer
that. I'm coming in here with a positive attitude and no one is
going to make that change. I'm not going to be bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, White said he's anxious to show the Dodgers that he
shouldn't be judged because he's 37 but rather by what he does on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Dodgers are hoping. When he's healthy, White is
one of the best defensive outfielders in baseball. But there was
concern last season when he missed games because of neck, hamstring
and groin problems.
</P>
<P>
   He hit .268, had 14 homers, drove in 68 runs and stole 19 bases
but was limited to 122 starts. White's also had offseason shoulder
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what anyone is saying, that I have to fight
for a job,'' White said. ``The bottom line is I'm here to do what
they're paying me for, and that's what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wants his center fielder to bat leadoff, whether it's
White or Hollandsworth. White, who prefers not to bat first, said
that's fine, as long as he stays there. He said it was difficult
jumping around in the batting order last season. Most of the time,
White hit fifth or sixth (a combined 91 starts) but also led off 13
times and batted second (seven times), third (twice) and seventh
(nine times).
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything to be said, last year I did everything for
the organization from (batting) first to second to third, to fifth,
sixth and seventh,'' White said. ``I accommodated everyone. This
year I think I have to be the selfish player and get in a spot I'm
comfortable with and know who's around me. That's the way I have to
look at things now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's got to be the scapegoat. If it's on my shoulders
now, I can handle it, but I'm going to handle it on my terms. I'm
not going to be all over. I don't want to be all over the lineup to
accommodate everybody else. I need to be in a spot. When the time
comes, Davey and I will talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Hollandsworth unseats White as the Dodgers' opening-day
center fielder depends a lot on White. But Hollandsworth said he's
not worrying about it. Instead, his focus is on avoiding the
disabled list for a full season, something that hasn't happened
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have as good a chance as anybody,'' Hollandsworth
said. ``I'm going to try to take my best game out there each and
every day during spring training and during the season, just like
any other time, and let the actions speak for themselves. The
opportunity is there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Extra bases: The rest of the Dodgers are expected to report
today and the first full-squad workout is Wednesday. . . . Tommy
Lasorda arrived in town Sunday and was in uniform and helping out
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
