<HEADLINE>
GORE, BRADLEY WIVES CAMPAIGN IN WASHINGTON STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LACEY _ The initially troubled presidential campaign of Al Gore
became resilient and successful when he moved out of the vice
president's supporting role and began speaking his mind, Tipper
Gore said here Monday night after a day of campaigning for her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the transition from being a sitting vice president to
a candidate campaigning with his vision of the country,'' she
added. ``The vice president is, of course, part of a team ... in
the background, a team player, what you hear on the late night talk
shows. It goes with the territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore and Ernestine Schlant Bradley, wife of former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, made separate appearances last night at
an annual crab feed sponsored by the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Both women are campaigning in what will be for Democrats a
two-part process of picking their party's delegation to this
summer's national convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Republicans, Democrats are treating next Tuesday's
presidential primary as a beauty contest. It will show the relative
strength of Gore and Bradley, but delegate selection will be based
on results of the March 7 precinct caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 Democrats devoured crab, with Olympia lobbyists
clustering and chatting during last night's speechmaking. Those who
bothered to listen were treated to two ebullient women, each
professionally talented, each an intense and full partner in her
husband's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ernestine Bradley argued that a prosperous America should again
dream big dreams. ``Now is the time, with the economy as good as it
is, that we move to get health insurance for all Americans,'' she
declared. ``It is an issue of social justice.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that President Franklin D. Roosevelt embarked on the
country's most sweeping social program of the century, Social
Security, in the midst of the Great Depression. A president should
display ``leadership and obstinacy'' in insisting that reforms be
carried through, she argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is the more radical and inclusive (candidate),'' she told
the audience, citing such proposals by her husband as a ban on
those pistols known as Saturday night specials as well as
registration of all handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage, Mrs. Bradley, known professionally as Dr. Ernestine
Schlant, talked intensely and in detail about an issue facing the
United States and its European allies _ entrance of the far-right
Freedom Party under its leader Joerg Haider into Austria's
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has said, and I concur, that we must join the European
Union countries that have cut off relations (with Austria),'' she
said. ``This (Haider) is not an acceptable person. I am very much
in favor of telling Austria this is not the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   An immigrant and the daughter of a Luftwaffe officer, Ernestine
Schlant Bradley is a professor of German language and literature at
Montclair State University in New Jersey. She is best known
professionally for the book The Language of Silence: West German
Literature and the Holocaust, which examines the work of post-World
War II German authors and their treatment (or lack thereof) of Nazi
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore, who has known her husband since the age of 17, went
public last year with the fact that she had experienced clinical
depression and undergone successful treatment. The period of
depression came after the Gores' son, Albert III, was nearly killed
when hit by a car outside Baltimore's Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore, who has a grduate degree in psychology, said last
night that by going public she hoped to ``help erase the stigma''
surrounding mental illness. ``In so doing, I would be doing
something that was meaningful to me,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's spouse has been known mainly in happy
settings. A talented photographer, she has turned her lense on the
press corps and TV cameras that are part of her husband's life. The
result has been picture books on a family striving to hold onto
normalcy in the fish bowl life of high office.
</P>
<P>
   But the causes of mental illness, its treatment and changing
perceptions, has been Tipper Gore's special passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to talk about it, deal straightforwardly with it, and
embrace employers and fellow employees in curing it,'' she said
last night. ``We need to have insurance policies that do not
discriminate against this illness that originates in the brain. The
brain is, after all, part of the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has paid 13 visits to Washington since the 1996
election, and is due back in the state Saturday night for a
Democratic chili dinner. In his wife's view, the vice president
became most deeply tied to the state on one visit that was not
publicized _ the trip last July when Al Gore and Albert III climbed
Mount Rainier in the midst of lightning, high winds and blowing
snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the proudest things he has ever done,'' Tipper
Gore said last night.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, too, has a link to the state's natural environment. He
visited the Elwha River in 1992, and became convinced of the wisdom
of removing two dams that blocked upstream migration of salmon. He
guided through the Senate legislation authorizing dam removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked his talk,'' Ernestine Bradley told Democrats at
their dinner last night.
</P>
<P>
   She was unable to join her husband on his 1992 trip to the
Elwha. ``It was when I had breast cancer,'' she said quietly. When
he wasn't legislating rivers, Bill Bradley stepped in and took
charge of every facit of his wife's treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are both survivors,'' state Rep. Val Ogden, who has also
experienced breast cancer, said in introducing Ernestine Bradley
last night.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore and Ernestine Bradley did not actually meet last
night. They did exchange cordial greetings at a Boise, Idaho,
dinner late last year. Gore was being escorted by Bethune Church,
widow of the late Sen. Frank Church. Bradley was with former Idaho
Gov. Cecil Andrus. In the small world of Democratic politics, one
of Andrus' daughters is married to one of Church's sons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
