<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGSID-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MIGHT HEADLINE IN VEGAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ At this time next year the Los Angeles
Dodgers could be training in Las Vegas instead of Dodgertown.
</P>
<P>
   Talks with representatives from Arizona are on hold, a bill is
awaiting introduction to provide funding in Florida, but
discussions between the Dodgers and representatives of Las Vegas
are going strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an interest in Las Vegas,'' said Bob Graziano, Dodgers
president and chief operating officer. ``Obviously, we'd have to
work in conjunction with other teams to form a complex there.''
</P>
<P>
   The site in Las Vegas would have to house four teams, but
officials from the city want to make the Dodgers the nucleus. The
Texas Rangers, Houston Astros, Toronto Blue Jays, Baltimore Orioles
and Kansas City Royals are the other teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers would like a long-term solution to the
spring-training site by the end of the 2000 season, but Graziano
said that might not be possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, from our perspective, we want to move fairly quickly
on this,'' Graziano said. ``It's hard to tell (when a decision
would be made). It depends on what happens in the Florida
legislature, it depends on Arizona, and it depends on what's going
to happen in Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida Sen. Jack Latvala (R-Palm Harbor) is expected to
introduce a bill this week that could allocate as much as $7
million to the local municipalities for purchasing Dodgertown from
the club, then renovating it. But a decision isn't due until June.
The city of Vero Beach and Indian River County already have $12.5
million in funding.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Phoenix residents will vote in November on a tourism
tax to raise $329 million to build the NFL's Arizona Cardinals a
new stadium. The tax would also provide funding to aid the Cactus
League.
</P>
<P>
   One concern with Las Vegas is the gambling issue. But Graziano
said that based on previous discussions with Major League Baseball
over training on an Indian reservation that has a casino, it
shouldn't be a problem. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
