A4241 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      02-22 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTING BEGINS TODAY IN ARIZONA'S REPUBLICAN PRESIDENTIAL PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (News analysis) 
 By JEFF BARKER 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
The Republican presidential race arrives in Arizona Tuesday. Sort
of.
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 900,000 registered Republicans are eligible to vote in a
sleepy primary that has seen home-state Sen. John McCain playing
the role of absentee landlord.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's state campaign seems to be running pretty well without
him. He didn't spend much time in Arizona, nor did he seem to need
to. Polls show him with a commanding lead over Texas Gov. George W
. Bush, who opted to concentrate on the close Michigan contest
instead of campaigning over the holiday weekend in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   While the candidates have been conspicuously absent, the large
demand for absentee ballots suggests a healthy turnout. That may be
due to several factors: the excitement of McCain's success and his
media bonanza outside of Arizona, and a certain soap-opera quality
unique to the Arizona contest.
</P>
<P>
   The once-intriguing story line opened when Republican Gov. Jane
Hull not only endorsed Bush last year, but told stories about
encounters with the senator suggesting he had a volatile temper.
</P>
<P>
   National pundits wondered why McCain seemed to alienate some top
Republicans in his state. A New Hampshire television anchor
pointedly asked McCain during an early debate why those who knew
him best seemed to like him the least.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull later sought to downplay her comments about McCain's
temper. Asked by ``The Arizona Republic'' during January's New
Hampshire campaigning whether voters should even consider the issue
in their deliberations, she replied, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never expected to win this state,'' Hull said Monday,
even though the Bush campaign spent thousands on television ads
that have run since December.
</P>
<P>
   While the McCain-Hull split has been uncomfortable for party
regulars, Hull stressed that she respected McCain, downplaying the
very public rift. But she added that Bush was the better man for
the job.
</P>
<P>
   When McCain won the New Hampshire primary Feb. 1, it seemed to
give him momentum everywhere, including in his home state. What
remains to be seen is whether McCain's loss to Bush Saturday in
South Carolina will dampen any of that enthusiasm, although the
late polls suggested it would not.
</P>
<P>
   When McCain's Senate chief of staff, Mark Salter, was asked by a
reporter early in the year whether he was concerned about Arizona,
he simply shook his head and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Salter's confidence was certainly boosted by the clout McCain
holds in the party.
</P>
<P>
   In other states, McCain has run as anti-establishment reformer
challenging the party apparatus. In Arizona, McCain ``is'' the
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has close ties to many Arizona companies: America West,
US West and Phelps Dodge, to name a few. Not only have state
businesses contributed to his presidential bid, some have loaned
him lobbyists to help with advance work on the campaign trail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 0048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4243 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CA-HATE-LADN     02-22 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-HATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ANTI-HATE LAWS INTRODUCED IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sparked by the Jewish Community Center shooting,
Gov. Gray Davis proposed a series of tough anti-hate laws Monday
and urged schools to adopt anti-hate curriculums.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, speaking at the Simon Wiesenthal Center Museum of
Tolerance, said the legislation, which he expects to receive
bipartisan support, would give California the toughest hate-crime
laws in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would add three years to any prison sentence for
a felony hate crime, and extend the statute of limitations for
filing hate crime charges to three years from one year.
</P>
<P>
   Davis focused his legislation on so-called hate groups,
proposing to expand their definition to include two or more people
who associate for the purpose of committing hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate groups strike at the very heart of what it means to be an
American, and we are obligated to fight back,'' Davis said. ``We
are the most diverse people on the planet Earth. That was God's
plan. We need to start living like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is drawn from a blue-ribbon panel Davis
appointed, shortly after a white supremacist was accused of
wounding five people at a North Valley Jewish Community Center and
the fatal shooting of a postal carrier in August 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In its 66-page report, the panel co-chaired by former Secretary
of State Warren Christopher and former California Gov. George
Deukmejian, found that a rise in hate crimes is fueled by
California's rapid growth and increasingly diverse population.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, more than 1,800 hate crimes were reported in the state
involving 1,985 suspects and 2,136 victims, 70 percent of which
involved violent crimes. In the San Fernando Valley, hate crimes
rose by 22 percent from 1998 to 1999, rising from 169 to 206.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the crimes appeared to be the work of people
acting on their own, the influence of hate groups frequently was
found in their backgrounds, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   The report identified 36 hate groups in California, including
the Nazi Low Riders in the San Fernando and Antelope valleys, the
Peckerwoods in Chatsworth and the Antelope Valley, the Aryan
International Movement in Los Angeles and the World Church of the
Creator in Monrovia and Redondo Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience is 70 percent of hate crimes we investigate are
committed by thrill-seeking individuals who don't have a commitment
to hate ideology,'' said Deputy District Attorney Carla Arranaga,
who leads the office's hate crime suppression unit.
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates there are more than 60
paramilitary-type organizations in the state, including militia,
``patriot'' and anti-government groups.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' legislation would make the violation of anti-paramilitary
laws a felony rather than a misdemeanor. Currently, it's a
misdemeanor for paramilitary groups to meet for the purposes of
practicing with weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Also, paramilitary group members who teach or demonstrate
firearms- and explosives-related activities can also be charged
with misdemeanors. The new law would make them felonies.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would simplify the removal of false liens by
perpetrators of ``paper terrorism,'' a technique hate groups use to
harass by filing legal or pseudo-legal documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think these recommendations are a good beginning in
addressing hate groups and we ask everyone to help us in what we
hope will launch an all-out, overall attack on the problem of hate
groups,'' Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' legislation calls for the creation of a human relations
curriculum in schools to teach tolerance and constructive ways to
resolve conflicts. He also wants to promote better training for
teachers about tolerance and hate-motivated behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The instruction of young people is absolutely essential for
youth to have greater tolerance for one another,'' Deukmejian said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 0052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4244 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-VERDE-AZR &LR;      02-22 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBES GAIN CLOUT WITH GAMBLING DOLLARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
CAMP VERDE, Ariz. _ A decade ago, the Camp Verde Yavapai-Apache
Indian Community was mired in the Third World.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Its members drifted from one agriculture and service-industry
job to the next, never doing much more than getting by.
</P>
<P>
   Then came gaming _ and the shining new Cliff Castle casino.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the wealth to buy back the tribe's traditional land.
</P>
<P>
   Then came political power.
</P>
<P>
   So much power that when this neighboring town demanded a permit
for the tribe's sand-and-gravel operation inside town limits, the
tribe essentially shrugged it off.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe's economic transformation is one small chapter in a
political and cultural drama being played out all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Gaming profits rolled into tribal coffers throughout much of the
1990s. At first, the tribes tended to address problems at home like
poor housing, infrastructure and social services.
</P>
<P>
   Then they started making their influence felt elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Just in Arizona:
</P>
<P>
   _The Fort McDowell Mohave-Apache Indian Community seriously
courted the Los Angeles Dodgers for a new spring training base on
its reservation.
</P>
<P>
   _The Pascua Yaqui Tribe bought a good chunk of downtown
Guadalupe in hopes of opening another casino.
</P>
<P>
   _The Quechan Indian Tribe sits at the table of Yuma's most
powerful marketing group.
</P>
<P>
   _The Gila River Indian Community is a major sponsor of Valley
professional sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Indian tribes backed by casino profits have been
building outlet malls in California, plants to make audio parts for
cars in Mississippi and ice-skating rinks in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Which was exactly why the 1988 Indian Gaming Regulatory Act,
which allows individual tribes to negotiate gaming compacts with
states, was passed, said Sheila Morago of the National Indian
Gaming Association in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's done a wonderful job of bringing tribes economic
empowerment,'' Morago said. It's not an even distribution, she
said, noting that tribes with the 20 largest casinos rake in 50
percent of all Indian gaming revenues.
</P>
<P>
   None is in Arizona, she said, ``but there are a number of
(Arizona) tribes doing well, nonetheless.''
</P>
<P>
   Like in Camp Verde.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the 1990s, the tiny tribe had barely a
square mile of land, with houses and trailers in various states of
disrepair. Now, 80 percent of the homes have been remodeled and the
tribe is the largest employer in the Verde Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Vince Randall shakes his head when he thinks about the
humiliations of the past: Tribal members begging for low-end jobs
in Camp Verde; people living on handouts from social-service
agencies; men following the vegetable harvests around the West.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the tribe has bought nearly 3 square miles of the land it
controlled before the arrival of the Europeans. Among those
purchases was the Cloverleaf ranch, which put the tribe at
loggerheads with the Town of Camp Verde as the ranch is within town
limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're buying back the land that the White man stole,'' Randall
said, ``and we're trying to develop those lands economically so we
can get more of our people back on the reservation.''
</P>
<P>
   The tribe started negotiations with the town early last year for
a permit to extract sand and gravel from the ranch. But tribal
officials took offense after the town refused to issue a permit
despite approving all but the remediation measures the tribe had
proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The council decided that the tribe's application for a use
permit was lacking completeness,'' said Nancy Buckel, a Camp Verde
town planner.
</P>
<P>
   So Randall said the tribe went ahead with its mining plans. It
also hired a high-priced attorney to back its claim that it doesn't
need a permit because it's extracting the resource for personal
use.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the town of Camp Verde has blinked. Randall said he
understands why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed around here,'' he said with a smile.
``We've even got more college graduates on our Tribal Council than
they do on their Town Council.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 0053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4245 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a MONTINI-COL-AZR     02-22 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
MAPPING THE LANDSCAPE OF INVISIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
 MONTINI-COL-AZR  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most mornings, I park my car in the open air of the garage's
seventh floor and return after dark, almost always pausing to feel
the breeze on the roof and look over the rough carpet of city
stretching in all directions to the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   South and slightly east of the garage are the towers of St.
Mary's Basilica, then the giant tortoise shell of Bank One
Ballpark. Beyond that, past the freeway and the city's oldest
neighborhoods is the dark silhouette of South Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Turning east on a clear day you can see all the way to the
Superstition Mountains, and at the same time watch planes make the
long, slow descent into Sky Harbor. Other planes rise lazily from
the airport, looking as if they'll scrape their bellies on the
office towers downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Several blocks north of the garage are the tall buildings of
uptown Phoenix, set at angles to one another like the last
remaining pieces of a chess game. Farther in the distance is Squaw
Peak, tilted like a witch's hat in the direction of Camelback
Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to know exactly how long the man was on the roof of
the garage Sunday night. They don't know if he got there during the
day and was able to enjoy the glorious sunset, or if he sneaked
into the building under cover of darkness and made his way slowly
to the top floor, sixteen steps per level, seven levels up.
</P>
<P>
   Police on Monday said they had no new information. The man
appeared to be in his 50s and, based on his attire, may have been
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't say for certain if he fell or was pushed or
jumped, though they suspected suicide. There were cigarette butts
near the railing on the seventh floor.
</P>
<P>
   This would have been near the spot my family and I paused to
watch the last of the fireworks on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Night is as lovely as day from this roof, maybe more so, as the
lights of the city melt into the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know how long the man stood on the seventh floor Sunday
evening, enjoying the view. We don't know if he was angry or sad,
or perhaps even ill. We don't know whether he was in trouble with
the law or mentally incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know where he was born or where he'd grown up or if
he'd ever been in love.
</P>
<P>
   He was facing west when he went over the rail.
</P>
<P>
   The sidewalk along Second Street is lined with palm trees.
They're set parallel to one another like a procession of skinny
flop-haired boys.
</P>
<P>
   From where he stood, the man could have heard the palm fronds
rustling in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The ground around the garage is landscaped with oleanders and
rosemary. The herb's heavy scent lingers on the fingers of those
who touch it as they walk by. In the Middle Ages, it was a symbol
of remembrance and fidelity. Sprigs of it were dipped in gold and
given as keepsakes to honored wedding guests.
</P>
<P>
   The man on the roof landed among the rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   He had gone unnoticed on the streets of the city, as do all
those like him. He had been invisible on the roof of the garage. It
took only a few seconds for him to fall, hard and quiet, coming to
rest where he could no longer be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Security found him on the ground near the garage's entrance, an
unknown man, silent, still, surrounded by the strong scent of
remembrance. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 0059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4246 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k MONTINI-COL-AZR     02-22 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
MAPPING THE LANDSCAPE OF INVISIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
 MONTINI-COL-AZR  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
