<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PREDATORS-TEX </SLUG>
 DAZED STARS TUMBLE TO NASHVILLE (For use
by NYTimes News Service clients) By JENNIFER FLOYD c.2000 Fort
Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Six days ago, the Nashville Predators tossed
18 shots at Stars backup goalie Manny Fernandez and couldn't score.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, it took the Predators 26 seconds and one shot to do
what they couldn't in 18. It didn't get much better from there for
the Stars. By the time the Predators reached 18 shots last night,
they had scored four goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it, the coaches talked about it; they were
going to come out hard,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said. ``For
some reason, we weren't ready. No excuses. ... I think maybe we
took them a little lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure to properly prepare turned into a nightmarish
result, a 5-2 loss in a game the Stars say they really couldn't
afford to lose. Tomorrow, the Stars begin a stretch of six games in
12 nights, playing Detroit, Chicago, Colorado, Philadelphia,
Phoenix and Detroit again. The Nashville game was supposed to be an
easy entry onto a hard road. ``Supposed to'' being the key phrase.
There was nothing easy about last night's game for the Stars, who
sat down and talked about what went wrong afterward. The team
meeting focused on putting this game behind them, learning from
what happened and remembering what's at stake. ``We're in a race
here,'' Hatcher said. ``I think the top seed in the Pacific
Division, there is an advantage to it. Tonight's a game we feel we
need these points.'' Fernandez said it was his fault they didn't
get them. The Stars' forwards said it was their fault. The Stars'
defensemen said it was their fault. They could all find clips from
last night's game to support their claim. The Predators' fourth
goal, at 14:53 of the second period, basically summed up
Fernandez's night. He probably should've stopped it, but it sailed
over his shoulder. ``We can't have one guy not show up like that,''
Fernandez said. ``It's even worse when it's a goalie.'' The Stars'
frustrating power play basically summed up the forwards' night.
They had four power plays. They scored on one but failed on a
crucial one midway through the third period that seemed to suck all
of the life out of what until then had been a surging offensive
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power play was frustrating again,'' Stars center Mike
Modano said. ``We've been winning, and when you're winning you
don't bring up those things. But when you lose, you start digging
for areas that let you down.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the stingy defense that is a big reason why they're
winning just wasn't there. That was evident on the first three
Predators goals. The most costly was Nashville defenseman Kimmo
Timonen's goal at 4:43 of the second period. His goal came 33
seconds after Stars winger Brenden Morrow had cut the Predators'
lead to 2-1. ``I think the reality check is with the lineup we have
right now we're really no better than anybody,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``It's our focus and discipline and positional play
that gives us a chance to win games. We're not an offensive
juggernaut now.'' The Stars did add another goal at 1:53 of the
third period when Guy Carbonneau scored on a backhanded spin shot
that looked a lot like Morrow's goal. With the lead slashed to 4-2,
the Stars began peppering Predators goalie Tomas Vokoun with a
flurry of shots. The third period was only five minutes old and the
Stars do have an NHL-best six victories when trailing after two
periods. But the aforementioned power play killed any chance at No.
7. ``Nobody ever mentions the power play when we win and it doesn't
score,'' Stars winger Brett Hull said. ``If you lose, you got to
find something. ... We're not an offensive team, and if we give up
too many goals, we're not going to win.'' The Stars gave up the
fifth and final goal into an empty net with 61 seconds left; the
so-called ``easy'' game before the rough stretch was officially in
the books as a loss. The Stars go into tomorrow's game in Detroit
with a tenuous two-point lead in the Pacific. ``You've got to
understand what happened tonight,'' Modano said. ``I think you have
to take a hard look at what the problem was. We had some areas of
our game that were really exposed tonight. I think that kind of
opens eyes. You go into Detroit on Wednesday, and it's not going to
get any easier.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
