<HEADLINE>
DARK MOONDANCER TAKES FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ With heavy rains throughout Monday's card at
Santa Anita, few would have predicted the packed house at the
track, most of whom played hooky from work, hoping to open a wallet
with a $50,000 cash voucher inside.
</P>
<P>
   This was all part of Santa Anita's $100,000 promotional
giveaway, in which wallets with prizes were given to patrons as
they entered the track.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Dark Moondancer's victory covering the marathon
distance of 1 miles over the turf course in the $200,000 San Luis
Obispo Handicap, the day belonged to Los Angeles resident Jose
Ramos, who opened the wallet with the $50,000 cash prize.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, a 29-year-old postal worker, took his mother and
grandmother to the track. He thought about staying home because of
the heavy rains but now has a good idea of how he'll spend the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will use it (the money) to buy a car,'' said Ramos. ``And to
help my mom buy a house.''
</P>
<P>
   Dark Moondancer, the other big winner, beat a short field of
five to return $3, $2.20 and $2.10 for trainer Ronald McAnally.
</P>
<P>
   When Public Purse was withdrawn from the San Luis Obispo last
week, Dark Moondancer became the heavy favorite to win his first
stakes in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't come that easy, however. The five-year-old European
import took the lead past Astra Ridge on the bend, then had to fend
off The Fly down the stretch to secure the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he was the class of the race,'' said Dark
Moondancer's rider, Chris McCarron. ``All I had to do was hope we
got away well and then place him forwardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got a little exciting at the quarter pole when The Fly came
to us but only briefly.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Vienna, trainer of The Fly, said Dark Moondancer
benefited by only carrying 120 pounds, spotting only six pounds to
his horse, carrying 114 pounds with jockey Corey Nakatani aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The San Luis Obispo is the the second leg in Santa Anita's
series of distance turf races, which culminates in the $400,000 San
Juan Capistrano on April 22.
</P>
<P>
   Dark Moondancer, owned by Charles Cella, finished ninth in the
Breeders' Cup Turf last November, his first start since winning the
Group I Gran Premio di Milano in Italy last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
