<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ELECT (Tehran) _ Iran's triumphant reformers, looking
beyond the stunning victory they appear to have won in last
Friday's parliamentary elections, have begun to temper their zeal
for sweeping change out of fear of a dangerous backlash from the
weakened conservative forces. Hossein Valeh, the chief political
adviser to President Mohammad Khatami, says in an interview that
based on his analysis of the returns, pro-Khatami reform candidates
could well find themselves controlling nine of 10 seats after a
second round of voting in April. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Nazran, Russia) _ A story of how Zina
Labazaneva died, in a west Grozny neighborhood called Aldi, and of
how a woman she never met, a plump, 40-ish mother of teen-agers
named Sapiyat, helped give her peace in death. But it is much more
than that. For Sapiyat and the other survivors of Aldi _ refugees,
trickling only now out of Chechnya into the makeshift camps that
pock the Caucasus Mountain foothills near Nazran _ are bringing
previously unreported stories of one of the worst civilian
massacres known to date in the Chechen war. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   QUEBEC-ITALIANS (Montreal) _ Language wars. After two years of
petitions from Montreal's 200,000-strong Italian community,
Quebec's official place names commission voted two months ago to
rename a 32-year-old suspension bridge after Pietro Rizzuto, a
Sicilian who arrived here penniless in 1955, made a fortune in road
construction, and died three years ago, a senator in his adopted
land. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-DANIEL (New York) _ Clifton Daniel, the courtly North
Carolinian who served as managing editor of The New York Times from
1964 to 1969 after a career as a correspondent in wartime London,
war-torn Europe and the Middle East, died Monday at his home in
Manhattan. He was 87. The cause was complications of a stroke and
heart disease, said his wife, Margaret Truman Daniel. By Eric Pace.
</P>
