   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPETING-SPERM (Undated) _ rimatologists have developed
some surprising ideas about the nature of the human mating system,
suggesting that women may not be as faithful as their mates may
suppose. And some biologists think that the deceits of the mating
game may even be reflected in the hapless spermatozoon. People's
two closest evolutionary cousins, gorillas and chimpanzees, have
evolved two very different patterns of sexual behavior and social
organizations. Gorillas practice ``female defense polygyny,'' with
one male guarding a harem of female, whereas chimpanzees band
together in multi-male, multi-female groups. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QUANTUM-PHYSICS (Undated) _ Some physicists believe they are
coming closer to an answer to a mystery of quantum mechanics,
explaining it through a phenomenon called decoherence, in which the
very particles that make up the universe constantly ``observe'' one
another, breaking down the delicate quantum juxtapositions and
yielding the familiar world of solid objects. In recent weeks this
theoretical notion received what may be its strongest support yet.
Experimenters at the National Institute of Standards and Technology
in Boulder, Colo., observed decoherence in action. They put a
single atom in two places at once and measured the breakdown of
this quantum state more methodically than ever before. By George
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-LOGEVITY (Undated) _ A gene known to govern the rate of
aging in yeast cells has been found to be active in mice, yielding
a new insight into why mice and people age and into possible ways
of enhancing life span. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HABITAT-EDGE (Undated) _ A study of the burrowing beetle has
led researchers to conclude that one of the basic tenets of modern
conservation theory _ that a wild species would persist most
abundantly and robustly in the center of its geographical range _
might be misguided, to the possible detriment of many endangered
species. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MUSIC-PATTERNS (Undated) _ A neuroscientist and concert
pianist has discovered what he says are clues as to how exactly the
masters would have wanted their pieces performed. He has identified
patterns, or pulses, that show how a composer favors louder and
longer notes at consistent points in a musical phrase, or series of
notes, much the same way poets resort to consistent patterns of
phrasing or painters favor certain brush strokes. He also argues
that similar patterns also exist on higher levels in musical
compositions, such as how composers stress certain bars within a
movement. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on how
the Moon got its tilt, nitrogen runoff and plans to view more
comets. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-RACE (Undated) _ The racial mortality gap for breast
cancer is widening. A National Cancer Institute study reported in
November that a black woman's risk of dying from breast cancer,
which was slightly lower than a white woman's in 1980, was 16
percent greater in 1990. By 1995, that gap had jumped to 29
percent. Some people say it's habits and environment; others wonder
if there are underlying genetic reasons. By Alexis Jetter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PATIENT-PROGNOSIS (Undated) _ Cases column. No matter what
the chronic disease, doctors and their patients are bombarded by
breaking news these days: new studies, new machines, new enzymes,
new organs, new genes, and new drugs upon drugs, all with new side
effects. And to many patients' chagrin, only a sorcerer could feel
comfortable measuring out most patients' life spans. But the
science of predicting marches on anyway, for better or worse. By
Abigail Zuger.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-POPULAR-STUDENTS (Undated) _ Researchers studying the
qualities and dynamics of popular students have found that
especially among boys, a significant minority is abusive and overly
aggressive. By Susan Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health: Sore throat is a
symptom, not a disease. But according to the findings of a recent
nationwide survey of 1,000 adults, slightly more than half of
Americans do nothing to relieve a sore throat unless it becomes so
severe that they can't swallow. The American Academy of
Otolaryngology warns people to seek medical attention when a sore
throat is severe or persists longer than the five to seven days
that is the usual duration of a cold or flu and is not caused by an
avoidable allergen or irritant. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Can hiccups
kill you? By C. Claiborne Ray.
</P>
