A4354 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LEWIS-JUDGE23-COX     02-22 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-JUDGE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge in Lewis case doesn't like verbosity
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The judge who will oversee the Ray Lewis murder trial
doesn't like lawyers who talk too much.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Superior Court Judge Alice D. Bonner, 59, gives
attorneys in her court a time limit and expects them to make their
points quickly and move on.
</P>
<P>
   But if Lewis' marathon bail hearing last week is an indication
of the trial to come, satisfying Bonner's requirements may be a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   In the hearing for the Baltimore Ravens football star, there was
only one defendant, but the proceeding lasted all day. When the
trial starts, there will be three defendants and three verbose
Atlanta lawyers on the defense side of the courtroom. Lewis' team
is headed by Ed Garland, probably the most talkative person so far
involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' fellow murder suspect, Joseph Sweeting, is represented by
Steve Sadow, who briefly gained the media spotlight as the Gold
Club's attorn the FBI raided the Atlanta nude bar looking
for mob ties. The third suspect, Reginald Oakley, is represented by
Bruce Harvey, Atlanta's best-known pony-tailed defense attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution is led by Clint Rucker, who repeated his name
over and over during Lewis' nationally televised bail hearing.
</P>
<P>
   All four lawyers will need to keep their tongues in check if
they want to stay on Bonner's good side.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't like lawyers to repeat themselves,'' said Carla
Friend, who has defended two murder suspects in Bonner's courtroom.
``That's something lawyers might find hard to do because we like to
talk so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Coleman, a prosecuting attorney who was assigned to
represent the state in Bonner's court for more than a year, knows
what it is like to anger her honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be making an argument and she will come out of left
field and nip at you and make snide comments,'' said Coleman, who
left the Fulton County District Attorney's Office to work for the
DA in Gwinnett County. ``She doesn't give a whole lot of respect to
the attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coleman said Bonner is fair: She is equally tough on defense
attorneys, prosecutors and lawyers in civil cases.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Bonner's desire to keep cases moving could come from
having too many open cases in her court.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Bonner had the most unresolved civil cases of all 17
Fulton County Superior Court judges, according to the Fulton County
Daily Report, a newspaper for lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that I work as hard as I can and get further and
further behind,'' Bonner told the legal paper last summer. The
judge declined a request for an interview for this story.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's background is in civil law. Before she became a State
Court judge in 1990, she was a law partner for six years with
attorney Mary Ann Oakley. Their firm, Oakley and Bonner,
specialized in employment law.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley said she hated to lose Bonner as a partner, but they are
still close friends. Oakley introduced Bonner during the
swearing-in ceremony when Bonner became a Superior Court judge in
1994. Both have season tickets to the Atlanta Braves _ their seats
are side by side _ and they attend five or six Atlanta Symphony
concerts together each year.
</P>
<P>
   When they talk business, Bonner usually tells Oakley about which
attorneys argued a good case and which ones didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't tolerate fools very well,'' Oakley said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who have pending cases in Bonner's court say she has a
reputation for being fair, as long as lawyers keep it brief and
honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice would be to be direct with her. If she asks a
question, she likes you to be up front,'' said public defender
Elizabeth Archer.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said she has respect for the judge, despite losing two
murder trials in Bonner's court. Bonner also denied Archer's
request that another murder suspect, William Harris, be given bail
while he awaits trial for a 1998 slaying.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how Bonner will handle the high-profile
Lewis case.
</P>
<P>
   Much of her criminal docket is filled with run-of-the-mill cases
such as drugs, credit card fraud and an occasional misdemeanor,
such as a trespassing case.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's no nonsense. She's very smart and she will play it by
the book,'' said Fulton County Superior Court Judge Philip
Etheridge. ``The fact that he's a big football player will make
absolutely no difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Her one previous highly publicized criminal case was in 1994.
Bonner sentenced R&AMP;B singer Lisa ``Left Eye'' Lopes of the trio TLC
to several months in a halfway house for burning down Atlanta
Falcons football player Andre Rison's $2 million home.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a big difference between an arson case and murder.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bonner accepted a plea agreement in a little-known
case against Terrance Gooden, who shot and killed a man who was
fighting in the street with Gooden's brother.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Lewis, Sweeting and Reginald Oakley also
stem from a street fight. Their fight, say police and prosecutors,
left two men stabbed to death in Atlanta hours after the Super Bowl
was played in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   In Gooden's case, he could have faced life in prison. But he
pleaded guilty to voluntary manslaughter. Bonner gave Gooden a
15-year prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The only notable aspect to the case came at sentencing, when
Bonner told Gooden he was a victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are just one more person who is a victim of the epidemic
of guns that we have in our society,'' Bonner said, ``and if your
family members learn nothing else from this experience it is that
no good comes from having a gun nearby.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
