<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-VIENNA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time, aid help heal wounds left by twisters
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As South Georgians begin recovering from devastating
tornadoes, people in other Georgia communities struck by similar
tragedies in recent years say patience is the best tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that's probably the last thing anybody wants to hear at
a time like this, but when you're dealing with local, state and
federal agencies and private organizations, contractors and
individuals, you've got to be patient,'' said Frank Daniell, deputy
director of the Gwinnett County office of emergency management.
``It just takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 450 homes were damaged or destroyed in Mitchell,
Grady, Colquitt and Tift counties late last Sunday and early
Monday, Feb. 13-14. Insured losses have been estimated at $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   State emergency officials listed 18 dead and more than a hundred
injured.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, tornadoes swept through the north Atlanta metro
area shortly after midnight, cutting a long corridor of destruction
through Gwinnett and DeKalb counties. One person was killed.
Property damage exceeded $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cleanup costs topped $25 million just in Gwinnett County,
Daniell said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the county is back to normal, except for repairing streets
and curbing damaged either by the storm or subsequent cleanup, he
said. And when Gwinnett got another presidential disaster
declaration this year after the recent ice storm, Daniell said
dealing with the bureaucracy was easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been through the learning process during the tornadoes,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Hall and White counties suffered at least $13 million
in damages and 13 deaths when they were hit by tornadoes that
leveled or severely damaged dozens of homes, chicken houses,
schools and other buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two years later, we're in good shape,'' said Elaine
Sexton, Hall County's emergency management director. ``Now, we have
10 new warning sirens in place. We're still working on getting
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year ago, a monster tornado cut through the Dooly
County city of Vienna in Middle Georgia, leaving 500 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency initially brought in 60
mobile homes as temporary housing. Now, only 11 families remain in
the government housing, said Kenny Calhoun, the county's emergency
management director.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado, which leveled two churches, knocked the police
station off its foundation and sucked the doors off the Fire
Department, was most destructive in Vienna's poorest neighborhoods.
Dozens of small frame houses and older mobile homes, many
uninsured, were ripped apart by winds.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of Vienna's destroyed or damaged dwellings have been
repaired or replaced by new houses, apartments and mobile homes,
Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actively seeking permanent solutions for the rest, some
of whom are still making repairs to their homes. It's been hard
because some of these people don't want to move outside the
community and our available rental property is saturated,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Without help, rebuilding would have been difficult for the
county, one of the poorest in Georgia. With $4 million in disaster
funds from FEMA and $500,000 more from the Red Cross, the community
is looking better than ever, Calhoun said. But it took more than
money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The will of the people has been to overcome this,'' he said.
``It's also been the will of the city and the county, from Day
One.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
