A4356 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-ALA-CORRUPTION23-COX     02-22 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-CORRUPTION23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Insult follows injury in Alabama town
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRICHARD, Ala. _ Forty years ago, so many shoppers came downtown
that their parked autos jammed an abandoned street car line in the
middle of Wilson Avenue. People could hardly find space to walk.
Bargain hunters browsed the sales at Kress department store.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday's shimmering sea of prosperity has gradually
turned into a turbulent tide of poverty. Today on Wilson Avenue,
black steel gates, chains and Masterlocks barricade nearly every
storefront. There are few shoppers. On New Year's Eve, looters
welcomed the millennium by smashing a van through the unguarded
doors of a pawn shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prichard just hasn't kept up,'' said Wayne Flynt, a history
professor at Auburn University.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the economic erosion and social shifts, city government
also is crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   A Mobile County grand jury has recommended the mayor, city
council and most of the water and sewer board be removed from
office for incompetence and neglect. A jury trial is scheduled
March 2.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury said there was ``substantial evidence'' of
corruption. The governor or attorney general would appoint
replacements if a jury decides to remove Prichard's officials.
</P>
<P>
   Prichard is $6 million in debt and declared bankruptcy in
October. According to the grand jury, the city wrote bad checks and
has underfunded its employee pension plan by $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Jesse Norwood and other city officials face criminal
charges. The city council president was arrested immediately after
a recent council meeting then released on bond. A circuit court
judge will hear motions on the cases today.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood, president of the National Conference of Black Mayors,
pleaded innocent. One of his family's businesses wrongly received a
$2,400 check from the city, according to the grand jury. He's also
charged with failing to report lease income from a city agency and
failing to disclose his interests in several businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now my job is just go back to work and continue to work for
the citizens of Prichard and see this thing through,'' Norwood said
outside the Mobile County jail Wednesday after being released on
$5,000 bond. ``I just hope people will continue to work with us and
continue to realize they shouldn't be so fast to judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day. Obviously, it's embarrassing. I'm
embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   So are Norwood's constituents.
</P>
<P>
   At the 8-Mile Fruit Stand, where fresh butternut squash is
stacked in wooden crates, Brenda Frazier shops inside, walking on
the store's unvarnished wooden planks. Her keys dangle from her
neck on a ribbon of cloth stamped W.W.J.D. (What would Jesus do).
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel hurt for the reason of trust,'' said Frazier, one of
Prichard's 33,000 residents. ``They didn't do the right thing. I'm
hurt especially because they grew up around here and they didn't do
anything to help make the place better.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the road at the Meat Block, where owner Mike Lee sells 48
rabbits a week along with cuts of pork and beef, customers stream
in steadily. Many are poor but loyal, several on welfare, Lee said.
Food World and others down the road have closed, pressed by a
Wal-Mart Supercenter outside the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a good business. We've been here 28 years,'' Lee said.
``What we do has made us successful, not anything that Prichard
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Prichard developed as a racially mixed but segregated town that
revolved in the political orbit of Mobile, which had struggled
itself as a backwater city on the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents are descended from African slaves who were
kidnapped in 1859 and shipped to the area by a Mobile businessman.
About a hundred blacks were loaded on the ship ``Clotilda,'' which
sailed into Mobile Bay under cover of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   But when authorities discovered the illegal plot, the delivery
was disrupted and the blacks scattered. After the Civil War, the
kidnapped blacks set up a settlement known as Africa Town east of
modern-day Prichard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are proud blacks there that aren't easily assimilated
into Mobile culture,'' Flynt said.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, Prichard and Mobile began going their
separate ways. An interstate highway came to Mobile but skirted
neighboring Prichard. After civil rights laws took effect, many
whites left Prichard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much here in Prichard to take care of the needs of
the working man,'' said Nick Solomon, a businessman on Wilson
Avenue. ``Prichard has never had a solid cash flow as long as I've
been living here. We just don't have a lot of industry in the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   The 64-year-old Solomon runs a combination television repair
shop, pool hall and arcade. Plywood fills in what used to be a
glass door at the front of the place. Inside, two men shoot pool on
one of Solomon's 10 tables. Stacks of television sets sit nearby.
The noon news drones in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Solomon opened his television showroom around 1975,
he found he couldn't compete with larger stores. So he concentrated
on making repairs. He put in a few arcade games to get kids off the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to survive as a business,'' Solomon said. ``You have
to work harder and longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon knew Norwood when the mayor was a child decades ago.
``We should keep an open mind,'' Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   As Solomon tells of taking Norwood and other Boy Scouts on
camping trips, the broadcaster on one of the TVs tells viewers the
mayor says he's innocent of any criminal acts. Said one of
Solomon's employees, ``I'm glad I live in Mobile.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
