<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stability control latest innovation from Mercedes
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A problem that has long existed in the automotive
industry is how to resolve the trade-off between ride comfort and
handling precision.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, large luxury cars have offered a sumptuous ride
but left a lot to be desired in the handling department.The other
side of the coin is that sports cars typically ride like wagons but
handle exceptionally well.
</P>
<P>
   At long last a solution has appeared on the automotive horizon,
and it is as simple as A-B-C. Active Body Control is the latest in
a string of technological automotive innovations brought to market
by Mercedes-Benz. It seems like a natural progression from
anti-lock brakes to traction control systems to a stability control
system.
</P>
<P>
   Active body control uses hydraulic, electronic and mechanical
components to reduce a vehicle's body roll compared with a
conventional suspension.
</P>
<P>
   What is body roll, and why should you care?
</P>
<P>
   Try to think of it this way: When a vehicle is traveling down a
perfectly flat stretch of road, the dashboard and bumper are
parallel to the road surface. When the vehicle starts to maneuver
through a corner or bend in the road, those angles change, and the
car tips, or rolls to one side. The greater the degree of change,
the more it affects the vehicle's handling performance because the
change in suspension geometry results in a shift of vehicle weight.
</P>
<P>
   In a corner, the inside tires carry much less of the weight than
the outside tires.
</P>
<P>
   This all sounds pretty complicated, but in reality it is simple.
Think of four equally husky guys carrying a heavy load. They would
be much more efficient if all four of them were carrying the same
amount of the weight. The same applies to a vehicle's tires. If all
don't support the same amount of weight, they do not perform as
efficiently. In simple terms, that means they don't provide equal
grip or traction.
</P>
<P>
   That's why more drivers lose control of a vehicle in a corner
than in a straight line.
</P>
<P>
   In back-to-back tests of a 1999 Mercedes CL and the 2000 CL 500,
I put both vehicles through a 35-mph straight line slalom. I
expected the results to be different, but not as different as they
were.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 CL could accomplish the maneuver, but only with much
effort on my part. It was not a comfortable or confident run. The
body felt like it had large parcels shifting inside as I fought my
way through the course.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the 2000 CL with advanced body control though the same
course was a piece of cake. It provided flat, precise cornering
that any reasonably skilled driver could accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Mercedes is offering ABC only on the CL 500 coupe. It
is expected on the S-Series sedans later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of ABC is the potential for the trickle-down
effect. Just as anti-lock brakes and traction control systems have
found their way into more mainstream vehicles, sometime in the
automotive future we probably will see ABC technology.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp, a training consultant to auto manufacturers, writes
for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
