<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2000 Avalon lives up to hype
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's time for an apology to the Toyota Avalon for
mocking those TV commercials showing the sedan floating dreamlike
through the clouds. It really is that smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Give it decent pavement and steady driving, and Toyota's
redesigned flagship is one of the most comfortable rides around. It
will give you some up-and-down movement when the suspension is
seriously worked but, for the most part, the Avalon is proof that
big cars no longer have to ride and drive like barges.
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeous, it isn't. Few reviews fail to join Car and Driver in
calling the 2000 Avalon ``slab-sided,'' which isn't necessarily a
bad thing (see the styling of Mercedes-Benz and BMW sedans). But
the styling _ from Toyota's studio in California _ also gives the
Avalon height (57.7 inches) and width (71.7 inches) to make the
bench-seat model a true six-adult sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Available in XL and XLS trim, the Avalon is such an Americanized
car that it comes off the assembly line at Georgetown, Ky.,
classified as a ``domestic'' vehicle, making it Toyota's first to
carry that tag. Base prices are $25,900 for the XL and $29,755 for
the XLS.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota, at last count, offers eight option packages for the
Avalon, introduced in '95 as a replacement for the Cressida. The
test XLS totaled $33,744, and it was optioned to the max, including
dealer-installed floor mats ($119).
</P>
<P>
   Strong points, in addition to the ride, include a sophisticated
V-6 engine that willingly churns out 210 horsepower with 220
pounds-feet of torque kicking in at 4,400 rpm, adding up to
zero-to-60 mph times in the 8- to 9-second range. That is adequate,
but not shocking, for a 3,500-pound sedan. Engine noise, along with
road noise, is pleasingly suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalon has good seats, lots of storage space _ including
flip-out boxes on the front door armrests _ and drink holders.
Visibility is good, but the front or ``A'' pillars can get in the
way, particularly during left turns. And while the windshield is
steeply raked, the instrument panel slopes away from the front
seats. The instrumentation includes a display showing direction of
travel, time, fuel economy and temperature at the top center of the
dash.
</P>
<P>
   The equipment, size and pricing of the Avalon mark it as
targeting older _ traditional, if you please _ buyers, which is not
what's generally been associated with Toyota. But then neither has
the idea of floating along like a cloud, so maybe it's time for a
change.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2000 Toyota Avalon XLS front-drive sedan
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $33,744 (base: $29,755, plus $485 delivery fee)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 3.0-liter V-6 engine with 24 valves (210
horsepower), four-speed automatic transmission with overdrive
lockout
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: Dual front air bags, dual seat-mounted front
air bags, power anti-lock disc brakes, height-adjustable front
shoulder belts, side-impact beams, optional skid and traction
control systems with brake-assist feature ($850)
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: Leather seating with driver's
seat memory, premium stereo with in-dash six-disc CD changer, dual
power heated mirrors with memory, 16-inch alloy wheels, keyless
entry system, $1,625; power moonroof, $910; floor mats, $119
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 21 mpg premium unleaded city, 29 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
