A4360 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-THE-MECHANIC23-COX     02-22 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mechanic's task ever more demanding
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How many of your cars are being fixed right the first
time _ or even the second time?
</P>
<P>
   Auto repairs are consistently among the top consumer complaints
nationwide. Yes, automakers are building better vehicles, but when
they break, it's a complicated and expensive proposition to fix
them.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of what I do _ train tomorrow's technicians in the
applications of electricity in the automobile. Hands-on testing
procedures are among the ways we instill in them the basic
necessary skills needed to begin diagnostic testing of the complex
electronic operating systems of today's vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Classroom projects serve as a steppingstone toward the ultimate
goal of graduating competent entry-level automotive diagnosticians
and repair mechanics who are so desperately needed in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, an associate's degree in automotive service technology
was a seven-quarter program, and cars were relatively simple
contraptions. High technology was limited to the alternator, power
windows, power seats and air conditioning available on really
deluxe models.
</P>
<P>
   I remember my own electronics class. I learned to fix toasters,
mixers and irons because their automotive counterparts were only an
engineer's concept.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of training, an automotive tech school graduate
embarked upon a career as a mechanic. He needed only adequate
knowledge of the righty-tighty/lefty-loosey rules of nuts and
bolts, a dose of hydraulic principles, some steering and suspension
geometry, and enough understanding of electricity to understand its
limited application to fix cars.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, most automobiles contained more electronics and
computer controls than the first moon-mission rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Today's futuristic vehicles boast navigational systems, infrared
sensors for night driving and multiple computer networks
controlling virtually every aspect of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The service and repair procedures needed to fix today's vehicles
comprise over a million pages of information. The knowledge and
techniques required to repair cars continue to climb exponentially.
However, today, an associate's degree in automotive service
technology is still a seven-quarter program.
</P>
<P>
   Humans certainly haven't been able to absorb and retain more
knowledge in less time. Yet we continue to attempt to cram more
information into the same amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   I think that just as a fuse blows from electrical overload,
future mechanics are on a similar course. In fact, I know several
good mechanics who have bailed out of the profession in the past
year because of the information overload and the paying public's
reaction to it. Or put another way: 1972 Nova expectations driving
2000 Mercedes-Benz technology.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer people are willing to take on the ever-tougher challenges
of repairing automobiles, and experienced mechanics who don't
update their training increasingly are finding themselves left with
professional frustration and unhappy customers.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 27 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
