<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4364 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEYTALK23-COX     02-22 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For some, Roths an easy decision
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For 32-year-old Waheed Malik, the decision between
traditional and Roth IRAs was a simple one.
</P>
<P>
   He put $2,000 apiece for himself and his wife into Roth
individual retirement accounts. That costs the dentist more in
taxes on his 1999 return, but it should save a lot more when he
retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 25 years, I don't have to pay tax on the money in that
account,'' he observed.
</P>
<P>
   His underlying strategy _ to tuck money away in retirement plans
_ is one many taxpayers could benefit from. The decision on which
kind of plan to use is a tactical one, requiring careful
consideration of individual circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   It's still a live decision for people preparing their 1999 tax
returns. IRA contributions for 1999 can be made until April 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional IRA is a baited hook,'' said Osmond Baptist, a
certified financial planner in Atlanta. ``The bait is the $2,000
tax deduction now and the tax deferral of earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hook is that maybe 30 years later, when the $2,000 has
grown, any money withdrawn is taxable as ordinary income, not
capital gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth IRAs, on the other hand, require you to pay income taxes
now on any contribution.
</P>
<P>
   As Baptist noted, $2,000 is the maximum contribution for any
year, either for a Roth or traditional IRA.
</P>
<P>
   The Roth's major benefit is any money your investments earn is
free from tax, assuming you abide by certain rules.
</P>
<P>
   Roth IRAs have other benefits. Unlike traditional IRAs, workers
can continue to contribute to a Roth at any age, and there are no
required withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   That makes them popular with people who are saving for their
estates rather than their retirements.
</P>
<P>
   For younger people who intend to invest for several decades,
such as Malik, selecting a Roth IRA is relatively easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a long-term horizon before you need that money _
at least 10 years _ and you expect to be in a higher tax bracket in
the future than now, then the Roth IRA can make more sense than a
traditional IRA,'' said Mark Watson, a partner in Washington with
the accounting firm of KPMG.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a closer call, he added, for people who expect to need
the money within 10 years and who expect to be in a lower tax
bracket when they retire.
</P>
<P>
   A major consideration is the income limits:
</P>
<P>
   _ For Roth IRAs, a full $2,000 contribution can be made if
adjusted gross income is less than $150,000 on a joint return or
less than $95,000 on a single return. Progressively smaller
contributions are allowed at higher incomes, up to $160,000 for
couples and $110,000 for singles.
</P>
<P>
   _ For traditional IRAs, there are limits on the tax deduction
available. Workers who have a 401(k) or other on-the-job retirement
plan will lose the tax deduction at higher income levels. At least
a partial deduction is available at adjusted gross incomes of less
than $61,000 on joint returns and $41,000 for single taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
