<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNKIN-DONUTS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Donut magnate pokes holes in negativism
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bill Rosenberg rises from his chair, a
large stogie dangling between his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The cigar seems a perfect excuse for sitting outdoors to talk
with a guest at his oceanside Delray Beach home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't smoke very much,'' he says, waving the cigar, ``not
since I had cancer of the lung in 1971 and they took out part of my
lung.''
</P>
<P>
   It's classic Rosenberg: to the point and unintimidated.
</P>
<P>
   At nearly 84, the founder of Dunkin' Donuts is nothing if not
blunt and comfortable with his approach to life.
</P>
<P>
   He's beaten cancer three times _ once miraculously, he says _
and is showing his gratitude by pumping money into cancer research.
He's donated over $2 million, so far, to the Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute in Boston and is being honored Friday at a black tie ball
at The Breakers in Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   He begins to run down the cancer checklist.
</P>
<P>
   1971: lung cancer discovered during a routine checkup.
</P>
<P>
   1977: cancer of the lymph glands and a sentence of only five
years to live. (That's the miracle part.)
</P>
<P>
   1990: cancer of the penis. A rare cancer that affects only about
1,300 men a year, it shows up as a sore on the penis, usually near
the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor said it was too much friction,'' he laughs, casting
a glance at Ann, his wife of 22 years who's 28 years younger than
he is.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't really a joke, Ann later explains. Friction from
tight clothing can irritate the penis, and sores can be very
serious. The cancer can also be caused by the human papillomavirus,
the same virus that causes cancer of the cervix in women. Part of
the reason the Rosenbergs are giving the interview is to call
attention to the various forms of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cancer, three hip replacements, and a list of
medical problems resulting in 18 operations, the man who left
school at 14 and became a business legend has a wry sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was basically recircumsized,'' he said of the penile
operation. ``The doctor said no sex for 3-4 weeks. I said, `Are you
kidding? Why don't you let me stop eating instead!'''
</P>
<P>
   He and Ann can laugh, now, but she says he has medical records
so thick, ``It's like reading `War and Peace'.''
</P>
<P>
   The most amazing recovery was from the lymphoma, which had been
diagnosed before his first hip operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my first hip was operated on, I got a call from the
doctor. He said, `I want to stop up and see you.' I said, `Why
can't you tell me on the phone?' He said he couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor came up and stood at the foot of my bed. My hip was
killing me, and I'm thinking that in three years I was going to die
anyway. `You know Bill,' he said, `your cancer is gone.' I said,
`What do you mean it's gone? In remission?' He said, `No, it's
gone. (We) can't find any signs of it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to peel me off the ceiling. It was like the governor
said you're not going to be electrocuted. I just felt like I was
reprieved from death.''
</P>
<P>
   To this day, he said, he has no explanation for what happened
beyond wearing the ``lucky'' crucifix a friend had given him.
</P>
<P>
   He and Clesson Blaisdell, who was president of the New Hampshire
Senate before his recent death, had exchanged religious jewelry
when Blaisdell found out about Rosenberg's cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Blaisdell gave him the cross his own mother had given him, and
Rosenberg responded by giving Blaisdell a chai, the Jewish symbol
for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He found out and he was all upset,'' Rosenberg recalled. ``He
was wearing this crucifix. He said, `this was given to me by my
mother and twice, it saved my life. I want you to put it on, it
will keep you from dying.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg lived to return the cross to Blaisdell, who buried it
with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   But if attitude has anything to do with recovery, Rosenberg
helped to cure himself.
</P>
<P>
   He lives his life dedicated to the principles with which he
started Dunkin' Donuts in a small shop in Massachusetts in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who have a positive mental attitude are result oriented.
That will help you in sickness, business, anything in life. The guy
who says it can't be done finds excuses. It's just a matter of
solving the problem. Just go on with life. Keep busy ... not dizzy,
busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he laughs at himself. He produces his ``attitude is
everything'' sheet with Positive Mental Attitude facing off against
Negative Mental Attitude, like two fighters in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   People with PMA are can do, will do, find solutions,
result-oriented problem solvers. It's that simple, he says. People
with NMA are can't do, won't do, find excuses, do-nothing failures.
</P>
<P>
   He sits back a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he is asked how it feels to be a legend, an icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``That and a dollar and a half will buy you a cup of coffee,''
he smiles.
</P>
<P>
   And a donut?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no. that's extra.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
