<HEADER>
A4371 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HIGHEND-DECOR0223-COX     02-22 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHEND-DECOR0223-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home designer shows soft spot for animal motifs
 &HT;    By Heather Graulich
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ John Landrum Bryant doesn't exactly look the
part of an artiste, and he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to West Palm Beach, the tall, dapper Bryant
oozed ``corporate attorney'' in a tailored navy blazer, crisp white
shirt and 18-karat gold cufflinks.
</P>
<P>
   But then you notice those cufflinks are miniature monkeys; the
clasp holding them on the cuff a perfect, tiny gold banana.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant designed them himself, and while he does actually hold a
law degree from Georgetown University, his heart and soul belong to
his new passion: designing high-end jewelry and home decor with
whimsical animal motifs. The decor line, called Jewelry for the
Home, includes sterling silver and bronze doorknobs, drawer pulls,
faucets, torchieres and tables _ all incorporating tigers,
elephants, monkeys or alligators.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who has a gallery in New York City, will show his work
at the Palm Beach Style Show being held this week at the
International Pavilion in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (people) like my work, they soon forget me,'' Bryant says
of his Savile Row image.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's foray into the art world is fairly recent, and it
surprises even himself, he admits. After getting his law degree, he
ended up as a businessman instead, helping lead nonprofit agencies
such as the National Park Foundation, where he served as president
for 17 years. He and his wife Patricia now run the Bauman
Foundation, a nonprofit group whose work includes supporting an
elephant sanctuary in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I was artistic,'' he says. ``But suddenly it
was like a volcano. I cannot stop designing.''
</P>
<P>
   It started about five years ago, when Bryant thought it would be
nice to have some custom jewelry made for Patricia.
</P>
<P>
   He doodled a few designs and took them to the New York City art
district, where he found silversmiths who helped him learn the
jewelry-making process.
</P>
<P>
   Although he can craft jewelry himself, eventually his level of
ability could not keep up with his increasingly intricate designs,
so he turned all the work over to a professional silversmith.
</P>
<P>
   For anniversaries, birthdays and holidays, he always surprises
his wife with his latest creations.
</P>
<P>
   And when the couple moved into a new apartment in New York's
Ritz Tower two years ago, he added home decor products to his
design repertoire. He wanted doorknobs and other fixtures that
would complement the apartment's lavish murals of exotic animals.
</P>
<P>
   His jewelry manufacturers figured out the complex means of
casting silver and bronze into elaborate fixtures that actually
work well, such as a solid sterling silver baby tiger that holds a
bathtub water spout between its paws.
</P>
<P>
   The line's prices range from $750 for a pair of bronze doorknobs
to $25,000 for the baby tiger faucet. Bryant prides himself on the
quality of the pieces, each of which are hand-cast and hand-carved.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are supposed to feel very nice in your hand,''
says Bryant, who hopes the added whimsy of the animals gives the
homeowner a chance to forget about the day's hassles. ``You turn on
the water and there are baby tigers, playing in the water. It can
be a nice diversion from life's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
