<HEADER>
A4372 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NUTSNBOLTS-COLUMN23-C     02-22 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTSNBOLTS-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some bath accessories are simple to attach to walls
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When working around my house, I always think
utility first and fashion second (or sometimes not at all).
</P>
<P>
   I love things that work well even if they're not glamorous,
which is why I love plastic hooks that glue to the backs of doors.
They're cheap, they're easy to install, and they give you a place
to toss your robe while you're in the shower.
</P>
<P>
   But most people demand something a little fancier. When they
want to hang something in the bathroom, they're likely to choose
some coordinated rack or fixture that attaches permanently to the
walls.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few tips on attaching things to your bathroom walls:
</P>
<P>
   _ Plain walls: If your bathroom walls are drywall or plaster,
hanging things from them is fairly simple. Attaching fasteners
through ceramic tile can be a bit trickier.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most common touch-up jobs for a bathroom is adding a
set with a coordinated toilet-tissue rack, towel racks or rings and
maybe a robe hook or two. Also available are decorative covers for
electrical switches in matching designs.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-inch metal towel rack costs about $12 to $15 for light
stainless steel or about $40 to $50 for brass. Wooden racks are a
little less expensive than brass.
</P>
<P>
   Ceramic fixtures come in a wide range of prices and two basic
types: surface mounted and recessed. Surface mounted ceramic towel
racks, soap dishes and so on are installed the same way as metal or
wood, while recessed ceramic fixtures are installed much like
ceramic tile.
</P>
<P>
   If you're just replacing existing fixtures with new fixtures in
the same positions, the job should go fairly quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the old hooks and racks by removing the screws that hold
them in place. In many cases, the screws are easy to see because
they were driven directly into the wall through the face of the
fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't see any screws, look on the bottom of the rack for
a rectangular opening that has been slid down over a metal bracket
that was screwed to the wall. Look for retaining screws holding the
fixture to the bracket.
</P>
<P>
   If you find retaining screws, remove them and lift up on the
fixture to slide it off the bracket. If there are no retaining
screws, simply lift the fixture off the bracket. Tapping lightly
with a hammer on the bottom of the fixture should loosen it if it's
stubborn.
</P>
<P>
   Recessed ceramic fixtures have no screws or brackets. They seem
to sit flat against the wall and have a ring of caulk around them
where the fixture meets the surrounding tile. We'll talk about
removing them later.
</P>
<P>
   After removing the screws holding your racks, hooks and brackets
in place, fill the screw holes with a little spackle or joint
compound. You can smooth the repair and paint to cover the little
blemish later or position the new fixture to cover the holes.
</P>
<P>
   Installation instructions and screws for your new fixture should
be included in the package in which they came. Following the
instructions should keep you out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Try to attach the brackets for holding your new accent pieces to
studs behind the wall when you can. However, towel racks and robe
hooks are light-duty fixtures, and anchors through the wallboard
should hold them securely enough.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing light-switch and outlet covers is a snap. Cut the
power to the outlet and remove the screw in the center of the old
cover. Pull the old cover free and put the newer cover in its place
with a new screw.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ceramic tile walls: All the metal, wooden and surface-mounted
ceramic fixtures that can be attached to a wall of drywall, plaster
or wood paneling can be attached to a wall of ceramic tile as well.
You just have to provide holes through the tile.
</P>
<P>
   To put anchors into ceramic tile to hold towel racks and similar
fixtures, place an X of masking tape over the spot in the tile
where you want to drill. Use a carbide drill bit and set your
variable-speed drill on low.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've drilled a hole, tap plastic anchors into the holes
carefully to avoid cracking the tile. The screws then will be held
in place by the plastic anchors squeezed against the surrounding
tile.
</P>
<P>
   Before driving screws into ceramic tile, apply a little glob of
silicone caulk to the tip of the screw. That helps make the
connection watertight.
</P>
<P>
   Recessed ceramic fixtures are usually designed to fit into
spaces left by removing one or two standard-size tiles. The
fixtures have a square or rectangular raised area in back, slightly
smaller than the tiles they replace.
</P>
<P>
   Work carefully to remove tiles to replace them with a fixture;
it's a time-consuming job. It might even be worthwhile to hire a
professional if you're not used to working with ceramic tile.
</P>
<P>
   Start by putting a drop cloth over any plumbing fixture under
your work area. Chips from the removed tiles can scratch and damage
surfaces if you accidentally put weight on them and grind them in.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the grout around the tiles you plan to remove. If you
fail to remove the grout, you're likely to crack the tiles around
the ones you want to remove.
</P>
<P>
   You can use a grout-removal tool, available where tile is sold,
or chip the grout away using a chisel, awl or screwdriver lightly
tapped with a hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Start removing grout at the center of the line you want to
remove. As you proceed, tap the chisel toward the area you've
already cleared of grout. If you chip outward from the cleared
area, you're likely to accidentally chip grout you don't want to
remove.
</P>
<P>
   Once the grout lines are removed, use a chisel and tap an X
across the face of tiles you want to remove. Keep tapping to break
the tile into four triangular sections then break up and remove the
tile a section at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Removing a damaged or unwanted recessed ceramic fixture is done
much the same way. Tap diagonally across the fixture to break it
into pieces; then break up and remove the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully scrape away adhesive on the wall behind the removed
tile using a utility knife or putty knife. Try not to damage the
wallboard under the adhesive or you'll have to patch it before you
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   To glue the new fixture in place you can use a ceramic-tile
adhesive applied with a trowel of the proper size and configuration
for the adhesive you have chosen. With ceramic-tile adhesive, using
the proper trowel is critical because applying too much glue is as
bad as not applying enough.
</P>
<P>
   You can also use a two-part epoxy adhesive to hold ceramic in
place.
</P>
<P>
   Press the new fixture firmly into place and apply strips of
masking tape to hold it in place. Different adhesives cure at
different rates, so you can expect to wait a day to a week before
putting any pressure on your new fixture.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
