r l BC-PSYCHOLOGY-COLUMN23-C     02-22 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHOLOGY-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting life in order can ease stress
 &HT;    By Hap LeCrone
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Do any of the following statements sound familiar
to you?
</P>
<P>
   _ I feel like I'm spinning my wheels most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   _ I feel like I'm going in circles half the time.
</P>
<P>
   _ I feel further behind at the end of the day than when I
started at the beginning. I can't ever seem to get caught up.
</P>
<P>
   _ The harder I work, the further behind I get.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 24-hour day just isn't long enough for me to get things
done.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel that you are always behind, use your time very
inefficiently, can never get caught up, waste too much of your time
or that you deserve a prize for the world's most inefficient
individual, then perhaps the following information could be of
assistance to you.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clutter, messiness, lost articles, etc., are all examples of
letting chaos control your time. Some individuals have things
categorized at home or work into ``piles'' or categories that
resemble a filing system. If this system truly keeps things in
order, then perhaps it works, but many individuals kid themselves
into believing that their system is helpful when, in fact, a more
traditional filing system or simply throwing things away would be
more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   For many individuals, a cluttered work place or home is simply a
reflection of a lifestyle lacking self-discipline and healthy
order. Check your home and work place to see if some filing,
throwing away, putting on hangers or re-shelving, etc. could
improve your ability to manage time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monitor your telephone and television time. How often do you
decide to a take a short break and call a friend or channel surf,
for a few minutes, only to find that an hour later you are still
taking your short break. Watching your favorite program as a way to
relax at the end of a long day beats staying glued to the boob tube
for long and unintended periods of time. Using e-mail, a fax, voice
mail or an answering machine to screen calls can also create more
time for necessary duties.
</P>
<P>
   _ Staying in good physical and mental shape increases efficiency
and reduces sluggishness, working in slow motion and efforts spent
sailing at half mast. Frequent worrying, poor sleep and depressive
states can also decrease efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   _ Uninvited drop-ins at the office or home can cause difficulty
in staying with a game plan, especially if your schedule is already
full. Let the unexpected ``guest'' know that you would like to
visit at another time when it's convenient for both of you. I'll
return to this important topic again in future columns.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hap LeCrone is a Waco clinical psychologist. His column
appears Sunday in the Waco Tribune-Herald. If you have questions or
topics you would like Dr. LeCrone to discuss, write him 4555 Lake
Shore Drive, Waco, TX 76710 or e-mail him at hlecrone(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
