<HEADER>
A4374 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WINTER-GARDEN23-COX     02-22 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-GARDEN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time arrives for lawn, garden work
 &HT;    By Christine Moran
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ It's still winter, but you don't have to wait
until the first day of spring to start your landscape and garden
work. In fact, if you wait until March 20, it may be too late. Some
projects need to be tackled early.
</P>
<P>
   But, you need to know what to do when, or your lawn and
landscaping can suffer, said Mike Wilder, agricultural extension
agent at the N.C. Cooperative Extension Service in Nashville, Tenn.
You have to know when to plant, when to fertilize and when to
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is crucial,'' Wilder said. ``A lot of people wait until
March or April before they start thinking about sculpting their
landscapes. In most cases, it's too late. There are certain steps
you should take in the fall and winter if you want your landscape
to look nice in the spring and summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer-flowering plants, such as crepe myrtles and butterfly
bushes, need to be pruned in late February, because their flowers
bloom on new growth. Wilder warns people not to prune
spring-flowering plants, such as dogwoods, spirea, azaleas and
forsythia, unless you want to lose the blooms for a season.
</P>
<P>
   He says prune evergreens in February if you want to encourage
new growth. Do it in June if you want to slow growth.
</P>
<P>
   Plant cool-season vegetables, such as asparagus crowns, carrots,
broccoli, cauliflower, head lettuce, onions, garden peas, Irish
potatoes, radishes, rutabagas, spinach and turnips, in February. If
cool, dry weather prevails, the vegetables can be harvested in late
March or early April.
</P>
<P>
   Prune fruit trees only after flower buds swell and show some
color. Even then, Wilder says, don't take too much away. Save some
pruning for May or June.
</P>
<P>
   Apply dormant oil on fruit trees to kill insect eggs before leaf
and flower buds begin to expand. If you wait until March, you'll
damage tender leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Plant trees and shrubs now, so root systems can develop before
hot weather causes them stress. Divide perennials, such as
daylilies, shasta daisies, gaillardias and peonies, when the ground
dries some.
</P>
<P>
   Fertilize spring-flowering bulbs as they emerge. Mid-February is
a good time to apply 3 to 4 inches of mulch along with a
pre-emergent herbicide to prevent summer annual weeds from
germinating. If you're not using herbicides, Wilder says, get ready
to pull weeds this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Fertilize cool-season lawns, such as fescue and bluegrass, in
mid-February. If you have a warm-season grass, such as Bermuda,
zoysia, centipede or St. Augustine, wait until May or June, when
the grass is actively growing.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing to do is to take a soil sample to know if
fertilizing is necessary and if you need lime to adjust the acidity
of your soil.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
