<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0223-CO     02-22 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0223-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Watch where you step at the Vatican's Jubilee celebration
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Rome is sprucing up for the Vatican's Jubilee
_ 12 months of celebration marking the 2,000 birthday of the
Christian era. According to Vatican estimates, as many as 25
million additional visitors are expected to hit the Eternal City
before the observance ends on Twelfth Night, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, municipal officials are eager to have their city put
its best (and cleanest) foot forward, but that could be a problem.
Over 200,000 dogs live in Rome, and for lack of back yards in which
to take care of business, they relieve themselves wherever they
can, thus transforming sidewalks and gutters into an urban
minefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoop or pay!'' owners have been warned, but so far, results
are scanty _ which is more than can be said for the doo droppings
all over town. City fathers now have taken matters into their own
hands, figuratively speaking of course, and ordered five
poop-scooping scooters (try repeating that a few times real fast)
to be placed into immediate service. Each scooter comes equipped
with a long vacuum nozzle and a tank mounted on the rear, as well
as a water spray for stubborn spots.
</P>
<P>
   Further description is probably unnecessary. You get the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Folks who've never lived in places like Rome or New York City,
might have difficulty imagining what life without grass is like for
doggies and their owners. Keep in mind that Rover can't just scoot
out the back door and head for a neighbor's flower bed whenever the
urge strikes. He has to be accompanied and cleaned up after.
</P>
<P>
   All of this leads me to believe that city dogs, over the years,
have probably become a bit uppity _ but for good reason. Put
yourself in Rover's place and see how humble you'd be if every time
you had to go, a guy in pinstripes and Gucci's trotted along behind
you with a Baggie and a shovel.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, New Yorkers didn't always scoop. When I lived there
in the '60s, signs everywhere warned owners: Curb your dog _ which
meant sidewalks were off limits and Spot had to be trained to use
the gutter. An improvement, but crossing streets got tricky.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-towners used to complain that New Yorkers were rude. Said
they never spoke to each other or even made eye contact. I hadn't
lived there two days before I figured out why. The natives were no
fools. They walked with their heads down because they were sick and
tired of scraping Dalmatian doo off their loafers.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, I lived in a small Georgia town with its very own
courthouse square, angle parking with a two-hour limit, and an
honest-to-goodness Barney Fife on patrol. Our deputy had a bit of
bad luck one night when the bank alarm went off. Seems he got so
excited that somehow he ended up speeding the wrong way down a
one-way street just in time to meet the sheriff's cruiser ... head
on.
</P>
<P>
   Barney was demoted to parking tickets and a Moto-Guzzi (a
3-wheeled Italian scooter), which he didn't seem to mind a whole
lot until one night some mean boys pushed his Guzzi up the
courthouse steps and turned it upside down on the stone table where
the old guys played checkers.
</P>
<P>
   That made Barney mad. So mad in fact, that he pulled out his gun
and threatened to shoot the miscreants. He didn't, of course, but
the sheriff wasn't any too happy to have his deputy standing on the
courthouse steps swearing and waving around his weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy was stripped of his pistol and put on foot patrol
around the square, armed only with a scoop and a broom. Business
was brisk since the town had no leash law.
</P>
<P>
   Barney still kept his badge shined up and walked with the same
old swagger, like his new job description didn't bother him a whole
lot, but we all knew he would have been much happier with something
to drive _ anything _ even an Italian poop-scooping scooter.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
