   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   NUTSNBOLTS-COLUMN _ Tips on attaching things to your bathroom
walls. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 24. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HIGHEND-DECOR _ John Landrum Bryant doesn't exactly look the
part of an artiste, and he knows it. On a recent visit to West Palm
Beach, the tall, dapper Bryant oozed ``corporate attorney'' in a
tailored navy blazer, crisp white shirt and 18-karat gold
cufflinks. But then you notice those cufflinks are miniature
monkeys; the clasp holding them on the cuff a perfect, tiny gold
banana. Bryant designed them himself, and while he does actually
hold a law degree from Georgetown University, his heart and soul
belong to his new passion: designing high-end jewelry and home
decor with whimsical animal motifs. The decor line, called Jewelry
for the Home, includes sterling silver and bronze doorknobs, drawer
pulls, faucets, torchieres and tables all incorporating tigers,
elephants, monkeys or alligators. (Graulich, Palm Beach Post). 28.
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WINTER-GARDEN _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ It's still winter, but you
don't have to wait until the first day of spring to start your
landscape and garden work. In fact, if you wait until March 20, it
may be too late. Some projects need to be tackled early. (Moran,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ Lee May's gardening column is not available
this week. (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TREE-PLANTING _ Three-part package on the life of a tree.
Background on trees and why they're so important to our
communities, types of trees for best suited for Georgia and a
six-step how-to guide for tree-planting. Roots are the most
important part of a tree because if something prevents them from
providing oxygen, water and food to the tree, it will suffer and
eventually die. In the suburbs, trees are falling victim to
developers' bulldozers; in the city, old age, cramped conditions,
and wear and tear are the culprits. Yet an equally big problem,
tree experts say, is homeowners who don't understand a tree's needs
and, as a result, buy the wrong kind or plant it incorrectly or in
the wrong place or at the wrong time.(Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
