<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4379 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POLITICS-HEALTHINS23-     02-22 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-HEALTHINS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family's insurance battle gets national, presidential candidates
attention
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The staffs of every major presidential candidate
have called 2-year-old Kaitlynn Bogan's parents in West Alexandria
after the family told Vice President Al Gore last week about its
battle over health insurance, Kaitlynn's mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a rare disease, Kaitlynn's diet is limited to an
expensive synthetic baby formula for which health plans rarely pay.
The Bogan Baby Bill, introduced by Ohio Rep. Gene Krebs (R-Camden)
as House Bill 218, would require private health plans to pay for
such medically necessary formulas.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore arrived for his Dayton campaign visit Feb. 9, ``he
came off the plane and came right up to us,'' mother Lydia Bogan
said. ``He said, `I know who you are.' (U.S. Rep.) Tony Hall
(D-Dayton) had given him information about us. We talked for
probably four minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the next few days, Bogan said, she talked to the
presidential campaign staffs of Republican candidates Texas Gov.
George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain, and played phone tag
with the representatives of former Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's chief
rival for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's people called me and asked for a picture of Kaitlynn to
put in his campaign headquarters in Nashville,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she said the television newsmagazine shows
``20/20'' and ``48 Hours'' accelerated their efforts to complete
stories about the Bogans and similar families.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 Ohio babies are born each year with disorders that
make all foods toxic, Krebs said, and state-funded health plans
cover the formula's $1,000-a-month cost for about 2,000 of them.
Nearly all babies outgrow the disorder after a year, but Kaitlynn
has not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting incredibly interesting,'' Bogan said, ``because
it's like a bidding war. The Republicans don't want the Democrats
to take it for their issue, and the Democrats don't want the
Republicans to take it. We're getting support from both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, however, the Bogan Baby Bill is stalled in the Rules
and Reference Committee, chaired by House Speaker Jo Ann Davidson
(R-Reynoldsburg). It has passed the Insurance Committee with some
of the House's most conservative Republicans joining the 14-4
majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not going to do anything in Ohio, we're going to
call in the national people,'' Bogan said. She said her recently
formed Mothers Aligned for Medical Advocacy (MAMA) has heard from
parents with similar stories across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was ``noncommittal'' about taking action on the issue,
Bogan said, ``but he said this is not just an Ohio problem. This is
a national problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on her conversations with lawmakers from both parties,
Bogan expects the subject will become part of ongoing congressional
discussions on patients' rights legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue's not going to go away,'' Bogan said of health
insurance reform. ``This is the heartbeat of the American people. A
lot of people are very upset about health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
