<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS     02-22 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THIS is rodeo week in Houston, the week of ill-tempered bulls and
bucking broncs and calves that don't wish to be roped, not to
forget sausage on a stick. This would have been a good week for
Giles Tippette, who was for greater or lesser periods of his life a
rodeo cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the author of 15 western novels, maybe more, and
briefly a mercenary pilot in Africa, a diamond courier, a private
eye, and a contributor to most of the country's magazines. It must
have been hell to be a writer who was nearly always more colorful
than the subjects of his stories.
</P>
<P>
   His hobby, he said, was recovering from the injuries he received
in the sports he took part in so he could write about them. If an
editor wanted a piece on a six-day sailing race in the Gulf of
Mexico, Giles joined the crew. Among other pursuits, he played
roller hockey and something called donkey baseball.
</P>
<P>
   As a competitor, an analyst and a spectator, he enjoyed all
sports except basketball. This was no reflection on the game. A
basketball player once stole his girl when he was on the football
team at John Tarleton Junior College. He never got over it.
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction to a piece on bull riding, Tippette once
observed that, ``Sometimes I think the worst thing about making
friends is the risk of losing them.''
</P>
<P>
   It hurts to reread those words now, but not nearly as much as it
did in October, when Giles died of a lung disease that had stolen
his sense of adventure a breath at a time. He was 63 going on 19,
Peter Pan's tall and rangy other brother. ``Dying is no big deal,''
Red Smith once wrote. ``The least of us will manage that. Living is
the trick.''
</P>
<P>
   In that respect Tippette was a genius, in a freestyle,
catch-as-catch-can way. It was a trial to keep up with him, but he
was the best kind of friend, truthful and generous, the kind who
gave you compliments so big they far outdistanced the insult he had
paid you earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In the days after his passing, other assignments interfered, and
the emotions of the moment went unsaid, a story or two untold. His
fans and readers, including a number of writers, will miss him. And
there will not be a better time to say so.
</P>
<P>
   There was an anecdote that defined Giles Tippette _ a wonderful
name; I wish I had thought of it _ about as well as anyone can.
This was the week of that annual bacchanal, the Houston Livestock
Show and Rodeo, and Giles had stopped for a refreshment in the bar
of a Houston hotel.
</P>
<P>
   He was dressed in the proper vestments _ the hat, the boots, the
belt buckle. He had been tagging along with a world-class cowboy,
Larry Mahan, researching a book that became The Brave Men.
</P>
<P>
   Two barstools over, a stranger sized him up. ``You in the
rodeo?'' asked the stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a writer,'' replied Tippette, not snobby, mind you, just
matter-of-fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you ride?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ride a typewriter.''
</P>
<P>
   No telling how far this conversation could have gone, except
that the stranger soon realized that they were not quite receiving
each other. When it became clear that Giles was a w-r-i-t-e-r, not
an r-i-d-e-r, the fellow introduced himself. He was Bill Peterson,
recently of Florida State, then the new Rice football coach. Out of
that encounter came another book, a season with the Owls called
Saturday's Children.
</P>
<P>
   Three things happened. Within weeks, the players thought Giles
was on the coaching staff. The book resulted in a lawsuit, and for
the only time in the school's history, Rice was investigated for
possible violations of NCAA rules. No penalty resulted, but the
probe was accepted as proof that the Owls, mired in a drought,
still had big-time football ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, Giles stumbled into more good stories than
most writers found on purpose. But he and Bill Peterson were both
correct. Tippette was a writer and a rider _ planes, trains, cars,
boats and bulls, hard landings and soft, a tale in every blessed
one.
</P>
<P>
   In his mid-30s, he felt an urge to return to the rodeo ring, and
he signed up to ride a bull at Fulshear. The public-address
announcer was reciting his literary credentials, and in the chute
the bull was going nuts, acting up and slinging strings of slobber
at him and looking back at him with an evil eye. ``Hell, don't tell
the crowd,'' yelled the author. ``Tell the bull. The bull ain't
impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   He rarely rewrote his copy, but what jumped off the page was
nearly always fresh and strong and nearly organic. He made it seem
easy. No writer worth his or her salt would admit, of course, that
the work was ever easy. But Giles made it seem so, and the answer
was in the attitude. He treated words as one would a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
