<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4406 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALOU-HNS &LR;      02-22 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALOU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Some of the toughest days are still ahead for
Moises Alou. Monday wasn't one of them.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Morning workouts had just started when Alou strolled into the
Astros' spring-training complex, put on his uniform, grabbed a
couple of bats and joined teammates on a nearby field. After some
brief stretching, Alou entered a batting cage and began swinging
away.
</P>
<P>
   His stroke was crisp. He smashed line drives in every direction.
And with one swing, Alou sent a pitch over a truck passing along a
street behind the wall in left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally a guy would be missing pitches and fouling off
pitches,'' Astros hitting instructor Tom McCraw said. ``He was
hitting line drives and hitting balls to all parts of the field.
It's like he never left.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou knows the truth. It has been 16 months since he last played
in a meaningful game. A freak treadmill accident crippled his left
knee and forced him to miss all of last season. It is time Alou can
never regain. But rather than dwell on the what-ifs, the
33-year-old left fielder is ready to put another chapter in an
injury-filled career behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very excited to get here,'' Alou said. ``That's why I'm
here a few days early. Maybe some of the guys will be a little bit
ahead of me, but in a couple of days I'll catch up. I felt good. I
worked hard for a year, and hopefully it will pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Alou was one of the best hitters in the game,
setting career highs with 38 homers and 124 RBIs in 1998. But last
year, with spring training only days away, everything changed.
</P>
<P>
   While preparing for the 1999 season, Alou fell off a treadmill
and tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee. Told he
would miss the entire campaign, Alou retreated to his offseason
home in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, he hoped to prove everybody wrong and return in
time to help the Astros during their September pennant run. Alou
was ready to play again in six months until he fell off a bicycle
in late August. His knee swollen, he had to start his
rehabilitation all over again, officially ending any hopes of
returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think watching was probably the hardest thing for me,'' Alou
said. ``It took a couple of months to realize I wasn't going to
play. Then there was the rehab. There are a lot of ups and downs
when you're coming off major surgery. There are a lot of days when
I felt great and a lot of days when I didn't feel that great.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the playoffs. Alou came under fire for not
accompanying the Astros to Atlanta for their Division Series
against the Braves. While Andres Galarraga and Javy Lopez, both on
the disabled list, sat on the Braves' bench, Astros management was
critical of Alou, and his name popped up in offseason trade rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Alou had several phone conversations with Astros general manager
Gerry Hunsicker over the winter, and the two sides claim
conciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten used to hearing my name (in trade speculation) all
the time,'' Alou said. ``I didn't worry about it, because I have a
no-trade clause in my contract, and I know most of the stuff was
just rumors. That was 1999. This is 2000. The injury is over, the
rumors are over, and I'm here with the Astros. That's all I have to
worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year is over,'' he said. ``We're starting a new chapter.
All families have squabbles, family feuds, from time to time. A lot
of what happened last year was wrapped up in frustration and
emotion on both sides. Nobody felt worse about Mo's year than Mo.
He is a great athlete and a very proud person. It was difficult for
him to sit and watch his teammates last year. He felt like he
needed to be out there. It's over. He's under contract for the next
two years, and I look forward to having him back in our lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   If he remains healthy, Alou sees no reason why he can't match
his 1998 run production. If not for the historic home-run duel
between Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa, Alou's numbers would have been
worthy of Most Valuable Player consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a player that likes to set any goals,'' Alou
said. ``But if I stay healthy, why not? I've done it before.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are counting on it. With the return of Alou and the
move to Enron Field, the team is hoping to improve an offense that
dropped off drastically last season as a result of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago he was our best hitter, the guy most likely to
get a big hit against a tough pitcher,'' manager Larry Dierker
said. ``He's just a big-game-type player.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker is mulling an outfield switch that would move Alou from
left field to right. He would in turn use a Richard Hidalgo-Daryle
Ward platoon in left, with Roger Cedeno, acquired in December from
the Mets, patrolling center. If the change occurs, Dierker would
prefer it happen during spring training, thus avoiding any
disruptions during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right field may be a little ambitious (for Alou) at this
point,'' Hunsicker said. ``I think coming off a knee injury, we
need to make sure he is healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou worked hard to get his knee in shape during the offseason.
The true test of whether it can withstand the strain will come when
he plays defense and starts running the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of doing some movement I haven't done in a
year,'' he said. ``I'll have to see how my knee feels. Right now I
feel good. I just have to be confident and lose a little bit of
fear I might have.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Astros have some concerns about Alou's knee that
can only be calmed as the season nears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you see the player physically get in the cage and swing
a bat and go through some baseball activities, you always have that
doubt in your mind,'' Hunsicker said. ``In 20 minutes of batting
practice, I don't think he hit one ball that wasn't on the sweet
spot of the bat. The ball coming off his bat just makes a different
sound than it does for the other guys. He's a special player, and
it's just great to see him back out there healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
