<HEADER>
A4407 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     02-22 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SARASOTA, Fla. _ The autograph hounds were up with the roosters,
and there were already several puddles of drool outside the gate at
Ed Smith Stadium by 9 a.m. when their man turned left in his shiny
new Mercedes and drove right on by.
</P>
<P>
   As he pulled into an open spot near the clubhouse, waves of
minicams washed over the blacktop as if somebody had opened a door
and let the tide in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I got him saying `hey' to me,'' shouted one of the
camera jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   Another one in the back of the throng proudly announced to his
peers, ``I got a great shot of all of you running after him.''
</P>
<P>
   While George W. Bush and John McCain are squabbling for the
right to run for the pedestrian office of president, Ken Griffey
Jr. came to the spring-training home of the Cincinnati Reds for a
well-oiled coronation as king of the National League, if not all of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Reds' publicity office, this would be the only
time all spring that Junior would meet with the media. There have
probably been papal visits that received less coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ESPNews and CNN/Sports Illustrated carried the news conference
live. Reporters filled about six rows of seats in three sections of
the stands. There was an unofficial master of ceremonies of sorts,
who called out the names and all of the accomplishments of the
individuals who arrived in a flotilla of golf carts down the
first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   First it was general manager Jim Bowden, then manager Jack
McKeon and finally Junior himself who took places before the
cameras in the row of folding chairs set up on the dugout roof amid
the tangle of microphone wires and TV lights. And from the look of
the entire overproduced, artificial setting, you were tempted to
jump in and start the questioning with: ``Bachelor No. 1, if you
could be a chest protector and ''
</P>
<P>
   This is baseball in the 21st century. Actually, it's all sports
in the age of a zillion cable channels with so much dead air to
fill when the Winter X Games and bass tournaments are over.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the way of the sports stars and sports franchises that
want to, quite literally, put your idols up on a pedestal without
letting you get close enough to touch. Just remember to buy those
tickets to help pay for a Junior Mint _ his almost $13 million
salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is back in Cincinnati,'' crowed Bowden, whose comment
must have come as a shock to McKeon and his other players, who
managed to win 96 games and push the Astros to the wire last
season. ``The Cincinnati Reds are excited that Ken Griffey Jr. will
begin taking the next steps in his Hall of Fame career and
hopefully wear his Reds uniform someday when he passes Henry
Aaron's career home-run record. There is just so much excitement in
the air in Cincinnati. We have installed 10 new telephone lines,
and now our ticket offices are open seven days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, indeed. Bowden also mentioned that he hoped Reds fans would
continue to support the team beyond this season to pay off
Griffey's contract, which guarantees him $116.5 million over the
next nine years.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably the most significant baseball acquisition since
the Red Sox sold Babe Ruth to the Yankees, and it has a
particularly warm and fuzzy feel since Griffey is returning to the
city where he grew up while his father played with Johnny Bench,
Pete Rose, Joe Morgan and Tony Perez on the Big Red Machine of the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In deference to Perez, whose number is retired, Junior will
trade in his No. 24 for No. 30, Griffey Sr.'s old number.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Petey Jr. and all of the kids of the old Reds have
done in the past _ worn their dad's number,'' Junior said.
</P>
<P>
   But what about his own dad, who is a coach for the Reds?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him, `Hey, pick a new number.'''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey chatted amiably, gave the usual lines about just trying
to be one of the boys in the clubhouse and denied there was any
pressure to make the Reds champions. But his right leg, which
rattled nervously the entire time he spoke, belied his emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there is pressure. There has to be pressure. His
grandmother and his cousins have been on the phone from Cincinnati
telling him that the town is going bonkers. Banners decorate office
buildings. Airplanes tow signs saying: ``Welcome home, Junior!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Uh-oh, here we go again,''' Griffey said. ``I just
figured I'd sneak in the locker room and nobody would notice me. I
didn't think there'd be all these cameras. I didn't want all
this.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``all this'' is what makes all that _ Junior's Mint _
possible. So he sits on a dugout roof, above the fray, or rides in
a shiny Mercedes, the tinted glass keeping the glare of the real
world outside.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
