<HEADER>
A4432 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CONNIE-NIELSEN-INTERV     02-22 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONNIE-NIELSEN-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIELSEN RATING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE showing Connie Nielsen in a scene from ``Mission
to Mars'' is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this
article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JESSICA KERWIN  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Someday soon, Connie Nielsen could be as big a star in New York
City, where she's been living for the past two years, as she is in
Elling, the small, small town in northern Denmark that the actress
left at age 18.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``all the way up there in gloom-and-doom country,''
Nielsen says, where she first performed in her mother's traditional
on-stage Danish review and variety show before continuing on to
Paris and Rome in pursuit of bigger and better roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so small it's not even on the map,'' she says of her old
hometown. ``There's not a lot going on there, but I got nature and
freedom _ and time to think.''
</P>
<P>
   If they were wowed by her past performances, just wait' til the
citizens of Elling get a load of Nielsen in two of her biggest
roles yet: she'll appear in ``Mission to Mars'' as an astronaut
along with Gary Sinise and Tim Robbins, and she stars in Ridley
Scott's epic ``Gladiator'' opposite Russell Crow and Joaquin
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen would be hard to miss in any crowd, but especially in
these ensembles _ she's the girl.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the first time that the actress has proven she can
hold her own in a macho movie. She camped it up as a temptress in
``The Devil's Advocate'' with Al Pacino and Keanu Reeves, played an
intergalactic babe opposite Kurt Russell in ``Soldier'' and buddied
up to Ben Stiller as a twisted German junkie in ``Permanent
Midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pure chance that I always end up being the girl with a
lot of guys around,'' she insists. ``It's not worth theorizing
about _ it's just like that. I try to look beyond the fact that
they are men and I'm a woman. I think that I'm part of an ensemble
and these are my co-workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen applies the same logic to her role in ``Mars.'' While
others might describe that character as a strong woman, ``I tend
not to look at it like that,'' she says. ``I look at the character
like a human being who has this kind of background with these kinds
of tasks in front of her.''
</P>
<P>
   During the filming of ``Gladiator,'' however, evenhandedness had
its limit. Nielsen won't be showing off any Zena-style moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't the one with the sword. I was the one scheming behind
the scenes and doing a lot of corridor-walking,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She may not have been battling barbarians on the film's
mega-sets, but working those period costumes did require a certain
athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trailing 12 meters of silk along behind me and trying
not to trip on it,'' she explains. ``It was part of the reason why
I cut off all my hair. When the next role came up, I said
`Astronaut? Sounds great!'''
</P>
<P>
   Little did Nielsen know that she'd be trading in that old corset
and train for a cumbersome 70-pound space suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was figuring on a T-shirt-and-pants sort of movie with short
hair and no makeup,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   That's just how the actress is dressed when she turns up for her
interview, and how she plans to attire herself after all the press
junkets and premieres are finished, when she can hang out with her
10-year-old son. She'll even pay a visit to Elling.
</P>
<P>
   After filming two huge movies in one year, Nielsen is also
hoping to scale things down a hit on-screen, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to do something intimate,'' she says. ``After the
huge canvasses of space and the Roman Empire, I'd like to do
something personal. I'm going to take my time.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's safe to say that Nielsen won't stay away from the set
too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your body is loose, but there's this tight energy, this
electrical thing that's inside you,'' she says of acting in
productions both big and small. ``It's always a rush.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jessica Kerwin is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
