<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4436 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     02-22 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, Feb. 22, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTION-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Anti-death activists are
appealing to presidential front-runner George W. Bush to spare
Betty Lou Beets, who will become the second woman to be executed in
modern times Thursday in Texas. Beets was convicted of murdering
her husband and was suspected of killing a previous husband. By
KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-TESTIMONY (San Antonio) _ Derek Lovelock, a member of
the Branch Davidians who was present at the 1993 U.S. raid on the
sect's compound near Waco, Texas, was back in the United States
last week for a Houston interview with attorneys for special
counsel John Danforth, who is investigating the Waco events for the
Justice Department. By DICK J. REAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-GOOKS (San Francisco)_ Long before he unapologetically
used the word ``gooks`` to describe his Vietnamese torturers, war
hero and presidential contender John McCain had uttered several
eyebrow-raising phrases. When he first ran for Congress in the
early 1980s, he referred to the senior community of Leisure World
as ``Seizure World.`` By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY-AMERICANS (Washington) _ The long-held view that the first
Americans arrived via land bridge from northern Asia 11,500 years
ago and quickly spread throughout the New World is giving way to
mounting evidence that migration instead came in multiple waves
beginning as long as 20,000 years ago. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   BIG-FOOT (Conroe, Texas) _ Jimmy Chilcutt, a fingerprint
specialist for the Conroe Police Department near Houston, has
developed techniques for lifting prints that are used by the FBI
and other law-enforcement agencies. He also has one of the few
archives of non-human, primate prints. His special expertise in
primate prints led him to examine casts of Big Foot footprints and
conclude that there is some sort of unexplained animal roaming
through U.S. forests. By HARVEY RICE (Photo available on NYT
database)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-MATADOR (Reynosa, Mexico) _ El Texano, the only gringo
ever to be confirmed as a matador in Mexico, retired here last
weekend after dedicating his last bull to his father and taking
home its ear. David Renk, 37, a McAllen, Texas, resident who has
spent the past two decades of his life fighting bulls, gave his
final performance as a professional matador to the strains of
``Golondrinas,'' the farewell song, in front of a crowd of about
500 in the Plaza Monumental de Toros. By ALISON GREGOR.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-FUJIMORI (Lima, Peru) _ Peru's democracy has been weakened
under Alberto Fujimori's 10-year rule, according to many analysts,
who say the president has a huge, unfair advantage in his
constitutionally dubious bid for a third term. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-SLUMS (Villa El Salvador, Peru) _ Government-sponsored
communal kitchens and day-care centers operating in the slums are
responsible for much of President Alberto Fujimori's popularity
among Peru's poor. Critics accuse the president of buying votes and
say the centers aren't part of a sustainable anti-poverty program.
By JOHN OTIS (Photo available on NYT database)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CURE (Undated) _ Robert Smith brings the Cure back to
familiar, and more successful themes, on the album
``Bloodflowers.'' By MICHAEL D. CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-AFFLECK-INTERVIEW (New York) _ Actor Ben Affleck has two
films coming out, ``Boiler Room'' and ``Reindeer Games.'' A look at
this ``regular guy'' who starts the spring film season with a bang.
By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-LETTERMAN (Undated) _ David Letterman is back and I couldn't
be happier. Not like, ``Hey, great, Letterman's back.`` But giddy
happy. ud happy. And this from somebody who usually has the cranky
pants pulled on pretty tight. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Amid the intense campaigning in an
election year, we reflect not on White House wannabes but on some
travel adventures _ and travel sites _ associated with past Chief
Executives. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-JARS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Europeans used orangeries _ glass
conservatories _ in the 16th century to protect plants and fruit
trees. Today, we have greenhouses. But if you don't have a lot of
space to start your plant or vegetable seedlings and cuttings, try
a glass bell jar or cloche (from the French word for bell). By
FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PALM-PILOT (San Francisco) _ Ever since the Palm Pilot debuted
with its little shades-of-gray face in 1996, its growing legions of
fans have been hoping for a color screen. This week those desires
come true. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-VALLEY-HOMES(Menlo Park, Calif.) _ The cars slow on
quiet Cloud Avenue so the occupants can roll down the window and
point. Undeterred by relentless rain, the drivers of a Mercedes,
then a Volvo pull to the curb. The object of their rubbernecking?
Not a crime scene or a fire. The focus of attention is an
unassuming four-bedroom house that inspired a 22-way bidding war
recently. The winner reportedly paid close to a million more than
the $1.25 million asking price. By KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-VALLEY-POLITICS (San Francisco) _ Silicon Valley isn't
shy anymore about its political agenda. It favors free trade with
China, looser accounting standards, an unlimited supply of
immigrant workers and a ban on Internet taxation. For the most
part, this year's leading presidential candidates have no problem
with those demands. In fact, they're working hard to make one or
more of those proposals a key part of their platforms. By ALAN T.
SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETING-SOUL (Troy, N.Y.) _ What do the Volkswagen Beetle,
Nike sneakers and Body Shop soap have in common? According to a
professor at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, they're all products
that have soul. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``S'' CATEGORY)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAIDERS (Oakland, Calif.) _ The headline in Saturday's
Oakland Tribune, the newspaper representing the community most in
touch with the travails of doing business with Al Davis, read
simply, ``Raiders Must Stay 11 Years.`` Now that's putting the best
face forward on it. Apparently, ``Parole Denied For Raiders,`` or
``Back To The Hoosegow For Al`` didn't fit the allotted space. By
RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Maybe flowers, trees and deer
can't predict the future, but from Monterey to the Oregon border,
nature seems to be forecasting a warm, early spring in Northern
California. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Columbia, S.C.) _ Presidential front-runner
George W.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is giving health care more attention as he campaigns
against rival
</P>
<P>
   John McCain. By CLAY ROBISON (Already filed)
</P>
</TEXT>
