<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4467 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GARDEN-JARS-HNS &LR;      02-22 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-JARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JARS GIVE SEEDLINGS AND EARLY START ON SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Growing and exhibiting plants dates back to
ancient times, but it was the Romans who first dedicated structures
to shield their plants from the elements.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans used orangeries _ glass conservatories _ in the 16th
century to protect plants and fruit trees.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we have greenhouses. But if you don't have a lot of space
to start your plant or vegetable seedlings and cuttings, try a
glass bell jar or cloche (from the French word for bell).
</P>
<P>
   Bell jars shield seedlings during the frosty cooler spring
months, while allowing light to filter through.
</P>
<P>
   They are also a good way to grow warm-weather vegetables in cold
gardens or to harden off plants prior to setting them out.
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners have long known that crops raised under glass mature
sooner than those left unprotected. Prior to bell jars, British
plantsmen used broken bottles to nurture seedlings, according to
the Country Living Gardener magazine. Today, a cloche is a term for
anything that is used to protect plants, from empty milk cartons to
a lead glass box. They are wedged open at the bottom for air
circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The French constructed cloches from a solid piece of clear or
green glass. Some were large enough to protect two plants at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   These handsome individual domed greenhouses come in a variety of
antique shapes and more contemporary styles.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden bases, with a groove, can also be found for many of the
domes. The groove keeps the bell jar from sliding off the base and
helps to seal out dust.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for bell jars start at $29.99 and go up to hundreds of
dollars for a vintage cloche.
</P>
<P>
   When not being used for growing purposes, bell jars can be
decorative accessories.
</P>
<P>
   The Victorians used them to keep dust off small figurines, dried
floral arrangements or nature studies of birds and other small
critters.
</P>
<P>
   Antique bell jars have also been converted into chandeliers,
sconces and lamps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
