<P>
   INTERNET POLITICS: As it decides what to do about taxing
Internet sales, Congress will be closely following how the issue
plays in the presidential campaign. Already, the topic has emerged
as a major point of dispute between the Republican front-runners,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: INTERNET TAXES: When the National Association of Governors
opens its annual meeting Sunday, Topic A will be what to do about
taxing sales on goods sold over the Internet. Most governors fear
that the growth of e-commerce will rob them of the money to hire
police officers and firefighters or to build roads. At the same
time, governors desperately want to appear friendly to tech
companies so they can attract New Economy jobs.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: INTERNET Q&AMP;A: Q&AMP;A on how sales taxes work on the Internet
under current law.
</P>
