<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4472 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-LETTERMAN-HNS &LR;      02-22 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LETTERMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WELCOME BACK, DAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Letterman is back and I couldn't be happier. Not like,
``Hey, great, Letterman's back.'' But giddy happy. Proud happy. And
this from somebody who usually has the cranky pants pulled on
pretty tight.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman was one of the first people who taught me, indirectly,
how stupid television really is, and how fun it can be once you
realize that and then exploit it. Long before I had any intention
of being the mockery of all my friends and family by reviewing
television for a living, I started watching ``The David Letterman
Show'' on NBC. That was 1980. Still in high school. Kind of
watching TV without understanding it. Then, this skinny guy popped
up on daytime television, probably when I was cutting class, and it
was the best lesson in irony, sarcasm and skewering pop-culture
that anyone could ever get.
</P>
<P>
   The show lasted four months and was akin to the Hindenburg.
</P>
<P>
   But, Lord that was funny stuff. It made absolutely no sense. And
it clearly sent all the daytime viewers scrambling for
alternatives. Soaps, game shows. Anything to get away from that
weird gap-toothed guy who was talking to the audience and acting in
a way that made his show seem like it was produced for eight bucks
and held together by gum and pipe dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, made it glorious viewing. And then there was
Edwin Newman, the most serious news man around, finally getting in
on the spirit of things after a couple of months and loosening up.
I miss Edwin Newman more than any other dead TV journalist
anywhere, and it's all because of Letterman's first show.
</P>
<P>
   All the hallmarks of Letterman's shtick were just coming to
light then. Talking to the audience. Getting them to do things that
made them uncomfortable _ which was riveting. And generally doing
cheap, dumb things that you could never see anywhere else at the
time. Maybe Letterman remembers it differently, but that was a
fascinating four months. Only Bugs Bunny cartoons were as cool at
that point. And that was kids stuff. Letterman's show was kind of
like anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, when ``Late Night With David Letterman'' began,
it was like finding out that other people actually listened to your
tiny little cult band. A late-night show with that Letterman guy?
You mean somebody else was watching and appreciated the whole
shtick? Of course, a good many people were already smitten by
Letterman and soon the entire country would begin to get a glimpse
of why he's now a legend.
</P>
<P>
   College kids really helped launch Letterman. They were the
target audience, and they were ready for his ludicrous, snide
approach, his belief that anybody could host a show with almost no
effort, and they loved the essential element of Letterman's
approach: That purposefully being unfunny was funny. That sending
up television was great art. That goofing on people and not taking
anything serious was the best way to host a show.
</P>
<P>
   I loved every minute of it. And I still do. Because I remember
when watching Letterman was as important as watching ``Twin Peaks''
or ``The Sopranos.'' You couldn't miss it. And man, if you got one
of those T-shirts _ that was like Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, by that time I was understanding just how
revolutionary Letterman's show was, even while it was winking at
and paying tribute to some of his own late-night heroes and
influences. But what Letterman did to late-night television was
make it essential. He took Johnny Carson a step further, by
deconstructing the genre, and his show became _ along with
``Saturday Night Live'' before it _ one of the defining elements of
late-night television history.
</P>
<P>
   There's no one like Letterman. No one as good. Neither Jay Leno
nor Conan O'Brien has ever been as funny or as innovative as
Letterman. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back, Dave.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
