<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4474 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-WONDER-REVIEW-LA     02-22 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WONDER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL DOUGLAS EXCEED EXPECTATIONS IN `WONDER BOYS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Curtis Hanson's quirky new movie, ``The Wonder Boys,'' suffers
from some of the same problems that afflict its main character, a
college professor undergoing a prolonged crisis of confidence. Like
this man, Grady Tripp, ``Wonder Boys'' is often aimless and
uncertain, not to mention fanciful in a rather forced fashion.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the movie _ and Grady _ bearable and ultimately
worthwhile is an expert performance from Michael Douglas, a gifted
comic actor who has rarely been afforded the opportunity to play a
likably loose character whose hair isn't always exactly in place.
The movie has other merits, too _ cinematographer Dante Spinotti's
work being chief among them _ but this really is Douglas' showcase,
and he puts on a teacher's clinic in acting.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas' Grady is a man watching his life unravel before his
eyes. One morning, his wife packs her bags and leaves him. Later
that evening, his lover Sara (Frances McDormand), the chancellor of
the Pittsburgh college where Grady teaches creative writing,
reveals that she's pregnant. To top it off, Sara is married to the
head of Grady's department, a Joe DiMaggio fanatic named Walter
(Richard Thomas).
</P>
<P>
   More complications: Grady's amoral book editor (Robert Downey
Jr. in an interesting bit of casting) has arrived from New York,
wanting to see the follow-up to the masterpiece that Grady wrote
seven years ago. It's not that Grady hasn't written anything. The
problem is he can't !ital!stop writing. The novel is at 1,200 pages
and counting.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all these dominoes falling, we're still not sure if
Grady's going to break out of his pot-induced haze and make some
hard choices. But when one of his best students, the devilishly
dour James Leer (Tobey Maguire), hooks up with Grady at a literary
party, events happen that force Grady's hand and threaten to end
his extended adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Grady's losing battle with past acclaim may certainly resonate
with director Hanson, who last directed the universally praised
``L.A. Confidential.'' With this offbeat follow-up, Hanson seems to
be trying a little too hard to soften expectations. To his credit,
he demonstrates a previously untapped capacity for rueful comedy,
even if he often relies on running jokes that grow a bit tired upon
repetition. You can only beat a dead horse so many times.
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter Steve Kloves (``The Fabulous Baker Boys'') does a
fine job in transferring the humanity of Michael Chabon's novel to
the screen, but one central problem remains. In frequent
voice-overs, Grady stresses the importance of his relationship with
Sara, yet their union is so underdeveloped that it's almost an
afterthought. McDormand pops up every 15 minutes or so, apparently
just to remind you that she's still in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   This flaw isn't fatal; the leisurely paced ``Wonder Boys'' has
too many subplots for that to happen. But it does render its
denouement a little less than wonderful. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Wonder Boys'' (R; language, extensive drug use). &QL; 
The stars: Michael Douglas, Tobey Maguire, Frances McDormand,
Robert Downey Jr. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Curtis Hanson. Screenplay by Steve
Kloves (based on Michael Chabon's novel). Released by Paramount
Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 52 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Citywide. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4476 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKS-POETRY-KANSAS-K     02-22 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-POETRY-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALEY, DICKINSON COLLECTIONS REFLECT TWO POETIC EVOLUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Poems of Emily Dickinson, edited by R.W. Franklin (692
pages; The Belknap Press of Harvard University Press; $29.95)
Begin Again: Collected Poems, by Grace Paley (178 pages; Farrar,
Straus and Giroux; $23)
</P>
<P>
   Movies are made, paintings finished, novels completed. Then they
make their way into the world to be watched, seen, read.
</P>
<P>
   Poetry, though ... poetry evolves. A single poem can take on
many forms. This was true even of the Romantics, who claimed their
work was more inspiration than perspiration. Samuel Taylor
Coleridge constructed seven versions of ``The Rime of the Ancient
Mariner.'' William Wordsworth revised The Prelude for 50 years.
John Keats asserted that if poetry did not come like the leaves to
the tree, ``it had better not come at all'' _ and yet he labored
over his verse.
</P>
<P>
   Two newly issued collections of poetry by female writes, one
living and one dead but both of whom have long inhabited the
literary canon, prove once again that versifiers must continually
be perused, analyzed, re-evaluated _ just as they must constantly
reinvent themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the more surprising of these volumes is R.W. Franklin's
edition of The Poems of Emily Dickinson. One would think that the
work of a poet who died in 1886 would be sufficiently codified by
now. But a century of readers' encounters with Dickinson have been
strangely vexing. Many have come to her through anthologies that
present only a fraction of her work. Others have sought out
complete editions, but the more academically inclined of those
volumes have presented multiple versions of each poem.
</P>
<P>
   Such a thing is fine for scholars, but readers have needed
exactly what Franklin has now provided: a comprehensive edition of
1,789 poems, with only a single version of each. And Franklin has
preserved Dickinson's oddities of spelling, punctuation and
capitalization, which allows readers to experience the artistry of
a fine writer but a true eccentric.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Dickinson can still be intimidating. How can that not be so,
of a woman who in one year of her life wrote nearly as many poems
as there were days in the calendar? The critic Harold Bloom, in The
Western Canon, correctly tagged Dickinson as one of the brainiest
of all poets; sometimes her verses, while powerfully felt, take
strangely cerebral and oblique turns, even as her language deceives
with its simplicity:
</P>
<P>
   When it comes, the Landscape listens _
</P>
<P>
   Shadows _ hold their breath _
</P>
<P>
   When it goes, 'tis like the Distance
</P>
<P>
   On the look of Death
</P>
<P>
   And Dickinson didn't care for titles. The Dickinson lover is
left to search, half-remembering those famous first lines: ``I like
a look of Agony'' ... ``A death blow is a life blow to some'' ...
``I died for beauty but was scarce//Adjusted in the tomb ...''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin does what he can: He provides a complete index of first
lines. Readers of Dickinson, though, still must be diligent and
devoted, giving more time to the object of their affection than
most other poetry readers are probably wont to do. Perhaps that is
as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Paley is high-maintenance, too. Like Dickinson's, her
poetry does not offer the ``easy read''; her subject matter can be
rather severe. Both Dickinson and Paley, for example, fixate on
death. Paley's Begin Again: Collected Poems, repeats and repeats
the motif of a watery demise, as in ``Drowning (II)'':
</P>
<P>
   This is how come I am drowned:
</P>
<P>
   First the sun shone on me
</P>
<P>
   Then the wind blew over me
</P>
<P>
   Then the sand polished me
</P>
<P>
   Then the sea touched me
</P>
<P>
   Then the tide came
</P>
<P>
   Again like Dickinson, Paley is blessed with an almost childlike
gift for language, but simple does not equal simplistic. ``Drowning
(II)'' is composed entirely of monosyllables except for
``polished,'' and yet it conveys, in six unadorned lines, the
great, human circle of life and death _ death physical, yes, but
also death metaphorical.
</P>
<P>
   In Paley's universe, death, real or imagined, is not really a
thing to be abhorred. Dickinson may get downright jolly about the
subject at times; Paley's tone toward the inevitable is more one of
quiet resignation. ``I wanted//to say last words,'' she writes in
``For My Daughter.'' ``... I wanted to say them now//in case I am
in//calm sleep when the last sleep strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a not-unexpected sentiment from a writer like Paley, who
always seems concerned with how her words are being constructed and
received. Begin Again, in fact, contains selections from her
previous volumes of poetry as well as new material.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Poem About Storytelling,'' Paley's narrator worries about
the ``listeners'' who are there _ or not there _ to hear the tales.
``What if they're all dead or//deadened by grief or in prison?''
she asks. ``Then there's no way out of it,'' for the artist, Paley
writes. ``She will listen//It's her work. She will be the
listener//in the story of the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Paley needn't worry, but it's nice she cares so much. ``A Poem
About Storytelling'' is not only an excellent piece of metafiction,
but also a shrewdly constructed meditation on the price of having
passion _ for life, or work or whatever one may hold dear. With
such work at hand, Paley can be sure she will never lack for
``listeners.'' Who else among modern poets can compare with
Dickinson, if not in sheer mass of work then at least in austere
elegance of diction and complexity of thought?
</P>
<P>
   These two collections show that the poets we think we know can
always have something else to tell us, if we only pay attention.
More than any other art form, poetry is not simply the craft of
invention but of re-invention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
