<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4480 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MOVIE-FRANKENHEIMER-K     02-22 1582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FRANKENHEIMER-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANKENHEIMER MAKES `REINDEER' WITH CARE, PASSION, GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gospel according to John Frankenheimer: ``You don't become a
better director by holding a lot of meetings. You do it on the
set.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankenheimer, 70, is a no-nonsense, old-school director who's
been doing it on the set for half a century.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City recently to talk up his new movie, the thriller
``Reindeer Games,'' Frankenheimer said he was inspired to go into
show business when in the late 1940s he saw an intense young Marlon
Brando on the Broadway stage in ``A Streetcar Named Desire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That experience changed my life more than anything else,''
Frankenheimer said on a visit to The Star. ``I was a 17-year-old,
undecided, searching for what to do with my life. After seeing
Brando, I realized I wanted to be part of something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankenheimer started out as an actor but found he didn't have
what it took to deal with the insecurities of that profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never comfortable as a performer _ I was always standing
outside myself, criticizing myself,'' he said. ``I couldn't make
the emotional connection between myself and the character. But it
turned out that I could help other people do just that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gravitating toward directing, Frankenheimer cut his teeth on the
live television dramas of the 1950s, and with only his fourth film
_ ``The Manchurian Candidate,'' starring Frank Sinatra, Laurence
Harvey and Angela Lansbury _ created a funny//creepy political
satire that has taken its place as one of the great American
movies.
</P>
<P>
   He also rejected an acting role that most certainly would have
turned him into a household name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was approached by Cubby Broccoli, the producer of the Bond
films, and offered the part of James Bond before it went to Sean
Connery. I turned it down. I've spent a few nights thinking about
that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Frankenheimer's directing credits are respected pictures
as varied as the racing film ``Grand Prix''; a World War II drama
with Burt Lancaster, ``The Train''; an eerie Rock Hudson thriller,
``Seconds''; ``The Birdman of Alcatraz'' (with Lancaster again);
``Seven Days in May,'' a political suspense film (with Lancaster
and Kirk Douglas); ``The French Connection 2'' with Gene Hackman's
second tour as Popeye Doyle; and the noirish ``52 Pick-Up'' with
Roy Scheider and Ann-Margret.
</P>
<P>
   But by the early '90s Frankenheimer was considered something of
a Hollywood has-been. He fought back by directing a string of
made-for-cable movies _ ``Against the Wall'' (about the Attica
prison riot), ``Andersonville'' (set in the notorious Civil War
prison), ``The Burning Season'' (a Brazilian activist opposes the
destruction of the rain forest) and ``George Wallace'' _ that
earned him four Emmy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   He made it back to the big screen when he was asked in
mid-production to take over the ``The Island of Dr. Moreau''
(notorious for the overacting of Marlon Brando and the on-set
tantrums of co-star Val Kilmer). He moved on to the contemporary
spy drama ``Ronin'' with Robert De Niro, and now ``Reindeer
Games,'' a densely plotted crime thriller with Ben Affleck,
Charlize Theron and Gary Sinise.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent far-reaching conversation, Frankenheimer talked
about his career and his art.
</P>
<P>
   - During the 1950s Frankenheimer directed live TV dramas on such
long-running series as ``Playhouse 90,'' ``Studio One'' and ``You
Are There.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I learned about what I do I got out of live TV. In
the '50s I directed 152 live dramatic shows. It was an incredible
education in working with actors _ I had 152 different casts. I
also had 152 scripts, and I developed a tremendous respect for the
writer. To this day, when I'm making a film I want to have the
writer with me on the set. When I was shooting `Ronin' I was
constantly on the phone with David Mamet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to leave TV. I loved being a TV director. But
live television dramas just ended about 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first film was `The Young Stranger,' which I made in '56
and which was based on a live TV show I'd done. It was a dreadful
experience. It got great notices, but I found moviemaking to be
such a constipating experience, so slow and frustrating compared to
the freedom of live television.
</P>
<P>
   ``With live TV you had several cameras shooting simultaneously,
and that provided a special kind of fluidity, both in camera
movement and in editing. Television is where I developed my visual
technique of using a wide-angle lens and lots of deep focus. I like
everything in focus _ the entire frame has to be clear and sharp.
It's become part of what I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, until I started doing my cable movies a few years ago, I
was really uncomfortable working in color. My best movies up until
that time had been in black and white. Color, I think, can be very
distracting. Black and white is much more dramatic, it gives a
piece a greater sense of mood, a much more serious emotional
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was shooting `Andersonville' I remembered what John
Huston did with his `Moby Dick.' He shot in color, but in the lab
he desaturated those colors, making them less intense. I started
doing that, too, not only in the lab but with the sets and
costumes. I didn't want any bright red or green cars on the street.
The extras were costumed in earth tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you see, everything that I think is good about my work came
out of live TV. Including my work ethic. You had three weeks
rehearsal and you were on the air. No wasted time. It got you ready
to work with Sinatra.''
</P>
<P>
   - Frankenheimer describes himself as a story-first director and
says he's appalled at the number of movies in which it's clear the
director came up with visual ideas first and worried about plot and
character later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so wrong when the shot takes precedence, when form
takes over content. I can't stand it. Show-off directing calls
attention to itself. A good film should look seamless. Whatever I
do is to put the audience into the picture. Anything I do to take
them out of the picture _ to remind the that it's only a movie _
then I'm not doing my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm especially frustrated with the way many directors now
shoot action scenes so that they don't make any sense. For an
action scene to satisfy you have to geographically know what you're
doing. You have to show where the characters are in relation to one
another and the location. The responsibility of a director is to
keep the audience oriented at all times. That's why I want
everything in focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's harder because you have to think ahead. You
have to make the picture on the set; you can't wait until you're in
the editing room. Again, it all goes back to live TV. We used to
come in and rehearse and block the scenes and by the time the cast
was ready to act in front of the cameras we had a pre-cut movie.
That's carried over into my films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing _ people ask why we don't have actors and stars
like Burt Lancaster or Lee Marvin any more. Well, Lancaster had
been a circus acrobat. Marvin had been a combat Marine. Charlie
Bronson was a coal miner.
</P>
<P>
   ``My point is that those guys had led real lives before they got
into movies. So many actors today go only to the gym and to acting
class. That's it. Their entire lives are based only in references
to other movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Considered a ``name'' director throughout the '60s and into the
'70s, Frankenheimer struggled through much of the '80s and early
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a couple of movies that didn't knock 'em dead at box
office. And the phones stopped ringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I was sitting there at home and I thought, `OK, you can be
just another promising youth who faded away. The world is full of
those people. They'll say that Frankenheimer made ``The Manchurian
Candidate'' and never lived up to his potential after that.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Or you can suck it in, stop thinking about the good old
days, go out and find material you know you can do that doesn't
have lots of fingerprints all over it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out that HBO had a script about the Attica prison
revolt. I read it, I said yes, and it turned me right around. HBO
took a big chance on me. Some people thought I was too expensive,
that my best days were behind me. In Hollywood if you're over 45
you're yesterday's news.
</P>
<P>
   ``But making films for cable saved me, really reinvented my
career. I won four straight Emmys. And that gave me the clout to
land `The Island of Dr. Moreau' with Marlon Brando. Of course, the
moment I arrived on the set in Australia I realized I was grossly
underpaid.''
</P>
<P>
   - The darkly humorous, fast-moving ``Reindeer Games'' certainly
doesn't seem like the work of a 70-year-old man. Frankenheimer said
his style is always dictated by the material, not by what other
directors are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imitate another director. You do a movie because you
know you can. I thought `Reindeer Games' had a terrifically smart
script (by Ehren Kruger). I never saw any of the twists and turns
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is playful, but you can never wink at your audience.
It has to be totally realistic. I never betray the audience by
getting cute or illogical. Once you do that, you never get them
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you do this, the more you realize it's all about
passion, dedication and really caring. I've got to find something
that really matters to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
