<HEADER>
A4482 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-MARKETING-SOUL-HNS &LR;      02-22 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETING-SOUL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROFESSOR SEES A CONNECTION BETWEEN `SOUL,' SALE  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ What do the Volkswagen Beetle, Nike sneakers and
Body Shop soap have in common? According to a professor at
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, they are all products that have
soul. Not in a Ray Charles or Aretha Franklin kind of way. Think
Plato. Think Aristotle.
</P>
<P>
   Think Buddha.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not New Age. I'm not sackcloth,'' insists Jeffrey Durgee,
a professor of marketing at RPI. But he is fascinated by the
connection between soul and sale.
</P>
<P>
   In an article titled ``Soul Branding: Thoughts on How to Do
It,'' to appear in a forthcoming edition of the Design Management
Journal, Durgee argues that more and more businesses are learning
that soulfulness is ``experienced in terms of warm, meaningful
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen, for example, draws on '60s nostalgia for the
traditional ``Bug'' by introducing the new New Beetle with the
slogan, ``If you were really good in a past life, you come back as
something better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike claims its products come ``straight from the soul of
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Durgee reserves his highest praise for those companies that
actually walk the walk by giving back to their employees, the
community or the environment. He noted the Body Shop, which
advocates non-animal testing and recycling. Or Volvo, which is
developing a car it claims will actually clean the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can people buy goodness?'' he asked. ``In these cases, the
employees feel good, the consumers feel good and the marketers feel
good. So in a way, I think you can.''
</P>
<P>
   To tap into what makes a product ``soulful,'' Durgee conducted
studies with more than 40 people and asked them to page through a
photo album of products in search of meaning.
</P>
<P>
   What he found is that soulful products allow consumers to relive
the past, particularly cherished childhood memories. Out of a
selection of briefcases, for example, most of those surveyed picked
a weatherbeaten leather item that looked like it came out of the
Truman administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said it looked like it lived another life,'' Durgee
said.
</P>
<P>
   People also found soulfulness in items that appealed to nature
or got the consumer involved, like home-brewed beer.
</P>
<P>
   As a marketing rather than a philosophy professor, Durgee
withheld judgment on the morality of most so-called soulful
appeals. However, he expressed doubts about some appeal-to-nature
claims, like ``mountain grown'' coffee and ``stonewashed'' jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Durgee links deeper products with a more communitarian
philosophy, but acknowledged that certain items seem to buck the
trend. Pan pizza begat personal pan pizza. Live conversation is
being eclipsed by ``chats'' on personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in products that bring people together,'' he
said. ``I like the tandem bicycle instead of the regular one, and
the hot tub instead of the bathtub.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
