<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS-SCHIFRIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LALO SCHIFRIN LIVES FOR MUSIC, NOT GRAMMYS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By MARLA MATZER ROSE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lalo Schifrin isn't surprised at the Latin explosion in popular
music: The Argentina-born composer has been breaking down musical
barriers himself for more than four decades. In fact, Schifrin's
longstanding practice of blending jazz and classical music with
Latin touches makes this year's Grammy favorite Carlos Santana look
like a newcomer and teen idol Ricky Martin look like ... well, a
mere teen idol.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing of boundaries ... I think the Berlin Wall fell,''
said Schifrin, who's nominated for an instrumental arranging Grammy
this year for his ``Latin Jazz Suite.'' He's been nominated 20
times before and has won four. Two of those were for his extremely
popular theme and score for the 1960s TV show ``Mission:
Impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office _ located in the guest house behind his
Beverly Hills manse _ Schifrin is surrounded by numerous awards and
dozens of pipes (``It's getting to be that a man can only smoke in
his own home,'' he sighs in his heavily accented but eloquent
English). ``Today, with the ways of communication that we have,''
added Schifrin, ``I think that the barriers are coming down fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Schifrin's world is full of juxtapositions of old and new. His
office is dark and European in feel; the only keyboard in sight is
a black Bosendorfer grand piano. ``I used to use electronic
keyboards more, but I'd find myself playing around all day ...
thinking, `Ah, listen to that sound!' so I got rid of most of
them,'' Schifrin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Schifrin's music remains vital and popular with younger
bands. His ``Mission: Impossible'' theme was redone once by U2 and
will be revamped again for ``Mission 2,'' possibly by Limp Bizkit.
Among the groups that have ``sampled'' Schifrin's music for new
songs are Britain's Portishead and the late rapper Big Pun.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of musical diversity is old news to Schifrin. He has
composed for Dizzy Gillespie, the Three Tenors and for soundtracks
featuring such tough guys as Bruce Lee (``Enter the Dragon''),
Clint Eastwood (``Dirty Harry'') and Steve McQueen (``Bullitt'').
One of his most recent projects is a series of concerts and CDs
titled ``Jazz Meets the Symphony,'' exploring the common ground
between jazz and ``serious'' music.
</P>
<P>
   The son of the concertmaster of the Buenos Aires Philharmonic,
Schifrin says his love of jazz rankled his father. ``My father used
to say, `If you can't read it or write it, it's not music.' He
couldn't understand the improvisation,'' recalled Schifrin. His
father also had other concerns: ``He was very concerned that I
would get playing jazz in nightclubs ... and nightclubs are
dangerous because, you know, the women of the night and the drugs
and the alcohol _ all the temptations,'' said Schifrin
matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I never had those problems,'' Schifrin said with a slight
smile, ``because my only obsession, my only passion was music.''
</P>
<P>
   Schifrin's wife, Donna, might dispute that statement somewhat,
but she readily admits Schifrin lives to compose. ``Oh, he's a
complete workaholic,'' said Donna Schifrin, who's been married to
Lalo for 26 years (both had been married previously). Said Donna,
``It's not that he doesn't know how to relax; I think he's just
really lucky that he still has a lot he wants to say musically.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade or so, Donna has also taken on being her
husband's personal manager and president of their own record label,
Aleph Records. Aleph releases Schifrin's music and maintains a Web
site (www.schifrin.com) offering recordings, T-shirts and even
autographed photos of Schifrin.
</P>
<P>
   Schifrin himself says he's aware he has a lot of fans but tries
not to be distracted by adulation and awards from both record
buyers and his peers. ``I don't have time for that,'' said
Schifrin.
</P>
<P>
   He calls the Grammys and numerous other awards, such as the
Chevalier de l'Ordre des Arts et Lettres from the French minister
of culture ``very good ego stimulators ... but on the other hand,
they can be dangerous. I know some of my colleagues who started
sleeping on the laurels of their glory, looking back at the past
and stopped working because they had awards. ... I have to keep
going.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4488 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-VICTIM-PROFILE-KANSAS     02-22 1585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICTIM-PROFILE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN NOT ONLY SURVIVED SHOOTING, BUT BETTERED HER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For weeks in the winter of 1992, Ann Whedon
lived with a feeling of impending doom.
</P>
<P>
   She took unusual routes to work. She parked blocks away.
Sometimes she wore a disguise.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't do any good. On a cold Thursday afternoon, the doom
enveloped her like a black cloud. After a sales meeting at the Silo
appliance store where she worked in Overland Park, Kan., she walked
to her truck. But when she opened the door, she saw a familiar pair
of brown cowboy boots in the back of the extended cab.
</P>
<P>
   It was Preston Collins, her former boyfriend. Weeks before, she
had left him, concerned about his increasingly irrational behavior.
Angry, he had kidnapped her at gunpoint. She escaped, and now he
was determined to exact his revenge.
</P>
<P>
   She screamed and ran. He ran faster.
</P>
<P>
   One hand squeezed her arm like a vise. The other brandished a
pistol-grip shotgun he had strapped to his body under an overcoat.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed the gun directly at her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going home now,'' he yelled.
</P>
<P>
   Then he fired.
</P>
<P>
   The force of the blast caused the gun to kick and the shot to
miss. It broke two car windows and blew out the front window of a
nearby carpet shop.
</P>
<P>
   It also knocked her to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Although she carried a small gun herself, she didn't know how to
use it.
</P>
<P>
   He reloaded and leveled the gun for another blast.
</P>
<P>
   Terrified, she covered her face and rolled into a ball as he
fired again.
</P>
<P>
   This time the shoJ bound its mark. It blew her right hand off,
took the thumb from her left hand and put a hole the size of a fist
in the back of her left leg, shattering the bone. In addition, the
blast left buckshot embedded in her muscles that would prove
impossible to fully remove.
</P>
<P>
   Lying in a pool of her blood, fighting to stay awake, she made a
silent vow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let you kill me,'' she said. ``I'm not going
to die.''
</P>
<P>
   `Changed my outlook'
</P>
<P>
   In the eight years since the shooting, that resolve has served
her well. By all rights the attack should have killed her, or at
least ruined her life.
</P>
<P>
   It did neither.
</P>
<P>
   While Collins was convicted of attempted murder and is now in
prison, Whedon has prospered. And while she wishes the attack had
never happened, it might have been the best thing that ever
happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   Today she walks with a limp, has a silver hook for a right hand
and pain as her constant companion. But she also has a whole new
life that is in many ways better than the one before. Since the
attack, Whedon, 55, has earned her social work degree at the
University of Kansas and started a new job helping disabled
workers. She even fell in love and got married.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed my perspective, changed my outlook, changed my
whole life,'' she said of the shooting. ``It left me alone with
nothing. You end up with a whole new start whether you want it or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't without difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Whedon spent three months in the hospital. Doctors gave her 50
pints of blood. The attack blew away her sciatic nerve and
destroyed the lymph nodes in her leg. She was even paralyzed for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, she has made the most of her new start.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the people in her classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Whedon is also now a teacher. But it's what she teaches
that often leaves people with their mouth hanging open. Every
Wednesday night the woman whose life was blown apart by an angry
boyfriend teaches batterers how to face up to, and conquer, their
anger control problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing story,'' said Johnson County District Attorney
Paul Morrison, who prosecuted Collins' case. ``She came out of (the
shooting) with a real good attitude. ... And now she has positively
affected the lives of other people.''
</P>
<P>
   William H. Reese, who administers the class Whedon teaches,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has survived and done some wondrous things,'' he said. ``I
am very, very, impressed by Ann's courage. She's a lesson for us
all on how to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Her brother, Chris Whedon, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my hero,'' he said. ``She has shown herself to be one of
the more remarkable human beings for what  come through. And
I do know that she has been inspirational to other people. Just
appearing before those people in the battering class and being a
true physical specter of the outcome of jealously and rage, how can
you not be inspired by that and want to calm down and control
yourself?''
</P>
<P>
   To the people in her batterer's class, Whedon is more than a
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's more like a mother to us,'' said Michael Woods, a
39-year-old Independence man who recently graduated from the
six-month court-mandated course. ``You can have any type of
problem. You can either save it till Wednesday night, or you can
call her at home or at work. She'll make time to talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewel Fleming, 32, of Overland Park said Whedon is uniquely
qualified to teach this subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been there,'' Fleming said. ``And you really don't know
what it's like unless you've been there.''
</P>
<P>
   But how can Whedon deal with abusers after what she's been
through?
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, going down there gives me an opportunity to help
someone else not turn into this guy,'' she said, referring to
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   `Get up and do'
</P>
<P>
   After such a brutal attack, no one could have blamed Whedon if
she gave up, withdrew from society or turned bitter.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, she didn't. Her mother, Annie Whedon of
Oskaloosa, Kan., said she didn't raise any of her nine children to
be quitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always said you either lie there and molt, or you get up
and do something,'' she said. ``And Ann has always gotten up and
done something. She was always a very determined girl. Maybe I
should say bullheaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Her upbringing helped her survive the attack. So did three
months of counseling, and a life that was rarely idyllic or pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Whedon is the first to admit she's not a perfect person. She's
used marijuana and twice tried cocaine. And when it comes to
picking partners, she doesn't have a very good history, having
divorced twice.
</P>
<P>
   It is the combination of all of this _ her imperfect past, her
current disabilities, combined with her bullheadedness and
commitment to helping others _ that have found expression in her
batterers intervention class. They're also invaluable in her new
full-time job at the Rehabilitation Institute in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   As the case manager in the institute's sheltered workshop,
Whedon hires, fires and assists physically disabled and mentally
challenged workers.
</P>
<P>
   Don Harkins, the institute's director, is thrilled with her
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a tremendous role model,'' he said. ``It would be easy
for someone who has gone through what she's been through to stop
trying and say `enough already,' '' Harkins said. ``But that's not
Ann Whedon. Ann approaches things as a challenge instead of an
obstacle. And she brings a tremendous amount of enthusiasm into the
workshop, and she communicates that through her words and
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those actions go beyond the workplace. In many cases,
Whedon has not only helped workers on the job, but in their
personal lives. She's helped them clean and organize their homes,
taken them to stores and kept them from getting evicted from their
homes. She inspired one client to go to college and start a career.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got an incredible heart,'' Harkins said ... ``She's been
an incredible addition to the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   `A true giver'
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Whedon has always been caring. But that's where
the similarities to her old life end. In almost every other way,
following the attack, her life has changed for the better.
</P>
<P>
   She says she improved her personal life when she met and married
Rick, a man in her apartment building touched by her tragic tale,
who has devoted his life to making hers better. He calls her
``Red'' and ``Tuffy.'' They've been married about a year and live
in an apartment in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of a person is his new wife?
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got it all when you say she has outflow for people,''
he said. ``Most people are inflow. You know, what's in it for me?
She doesn't care about that. ... She's a true giver.''
</P>
<P>
   As Whedon improved her personal life, she also expanded her
mind. Married and quickly pregnant out of high school, she never
went to college. But once there, she couldn't get enough.
</P>
<P>
   Before studying at KU, she enrolled in a Western civilization
class at Johnson County Community College that introduced her to a
whole new world. She began to appreciate history and culture and
books in a whole new light. Recently she read a book called The
Arcanum, a book about the discovery of making porcelain. She also
loves to listen to classical music.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, she has improved her career. Although she always
had jobs she enjoyed, including stints as a baker and a
salesperson, they never seemed to lead anywhere. Today she thinks
she is truly making a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother knows not everyone could do what her daughter has
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who have been traumatized crawl into their
little shell and feel sorry for themselves,'' Annie Whedon said.
``But you make your own future. ... You either lie there and wallow
in it, or get up and do something. And Ann is a hard charger. And
nothing's going to get to her. Nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
