<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4491 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-TELEVISION-TENTH-KANS     02-22 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEVISION-TENTH-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC HOPES THERE'S MAGIC IN MEGA MINISERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most ambitious TV miniseries in more than a decade begins
Sunday on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   And if the creators of this fairy-tale extravaganza could step
inside the magical world they've made, no doubt they'd find the
nearest genie and ask for a special stone with which to fell the
marauding game show giant that threatens their kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Into the teeth of what is turning out to be the TV story of the
year _ ABC's endless hit ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' _ flies
``The 10th Kingdom,'' which NBC optimistically calls ``the epic
event of the millennium.'' The 10-hour spectacular miniseries
begins tonight and continues for four of the next eight nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 10th Kingdom'' reunites the screenwriter, studio and
network that collaborated on the acclaimed 1996 miniseries
``Gulliver's Travels,'' the one that launched the recent craze in
Great Books-inspired TV blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   Since producing ``Gulliver's'' for NBC, the Hallmark
Entertainment father-son team of Robert Halmi Sr. and Robert Halmi
Jr. have virtually owned the miniseries field. Their special
effects-laden retellings include ``Moby Dick,'' ``The Odyssey'' and
``Animal Farm,'' as well as fanciful biographies of Cleopatra,
Merlin and Noah.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The 10th Kingdom'' tops them all, at least in size and
reach. Writer Simon Moore has spun a dense but linear tale about a
mythical world of nine kingdoms and the adventures of two seemingly
ordinary New Yorkers who stumble into it.
</P>
<P>
   His script cribs from nearly every well-known children's tale,
with glass menageries, magic spells, potent curses, poison apples,
mighty beanstalks, talking mice, worker-dwarves, Rapunzel's hair,
an evil queen and two icons of the genre, Cinderella and Snow
White.
</P>
<P>
   It will all end happily, not only for our heroes but for the
viewers who decide to invest a week's worth of TV time watching it.
But none of that becomes clear right away, and indeed for much of
the first two nights ``The 10th Kingdom'' really drags. John
Larroquette is the best thing in this miniseries, but he can't be
expected to carry the whole load even if a witch could turn him
into Richard Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be a grand finish by the time the final acts air
March 5 and 6 ... and by then the Nielsen ratings period will be
over, as will the threat from the kingdom of ABC. (Regis is the
Latin word for ``king'' _ coincidence?)
</P>
<P>
   Through the looking-glass
</P>
<P>
   ``The 10th Kingdom'' opens in a mythical realm where a
working-class stiff can have an apartment overlooking Central Park.
Larroquette plays Tony Lewis, an overworked building super with the
choice digs (it's a job perk, we're told). His 20-something
daughter, Virginia, played by Kimberly Williams, still lives with
him. Her mother mysteriously left them years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Larroquette has a talent for roles like these, which he
sharpened during his sitcom years on ``Night Court'' as well as an
even darker eponymous show for NBC and an underestimated turn in
last year's ``Fawlty Towers'' remake, ``Payne.'' He's wisely
avoided the feature film circuit, perhaps knowing that the same
qualities that make him so appealing here would look like shameless
mugging on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Larroquette gets no help from Williams, who is
called on to play a depressing and not very likable young woman
and, one must say, does all too well at it. Williams has been in
some pretty high-profile stuff, including the ``Father of the
Bride'' films (as the bride) and the ABC dating drama
``Relativity'' three years ago. But _ and perhaps this is faint
praise _ her best work has been done in large ensembles. For the
first two or three hours of ``The 10th Kingdom,'' Williams has a
heavier load to pull, and she clearly strains under the effort.
</P>
<P>
   To viewers who recall ``Gulliver's Travels'' (which pops up from
time to time on the Odyssey Network), the plot construction of
``The 10th Kingdom'' will seem familiar. Just as the scene kept
shifting between 18th-century English society and the exotic lands
where Gulliver roamed, so the action here switches from New York to
fairy-book-land and back again. Frankly, the two worlds can't
collide soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   And they do one night, when Virginia crashes her bike into a
golden retriever that is, in fact, a handsome prince. The dog has
come to her through a magic mirror, with a hunky werewolf and three
hideous trolls in hot pursuit. Soon Virginia, her dad and the dog
will be chased back through the looking-glass and into the fourth
kingdom, an empire founded by none other than the late Snow White
(who will reappear briefly from the dead in the program's eighth
hour as Camryn Manheim). Little mention is made of the other
kingdoms; they are apparently being saved for sequels.
</P>
<P>
   No kids' stuff
</P>
<P>
   The narcotic effect of magic is a recurring theme in ``The 10th
Kingdom,'' and it's one of several reasons why this miniseries,
like the original Grimm fairy tales, is not recommended for the
kiddies. Another reason is the language, and a third is the sadism
of the trolls, who in one scene brutally assault a young couple in
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's Part 2 continues the pursuit inside a ``disenchanted
forest,'' where we're introduced to another baddie called The
Huntsman, whose arrows weave through the trees like heat-seeking
missiles until they strike flesh. Rutger Hauer is the suitably
cold-blooded Huntsman; I suspect he got the part because he's a
ringer for Hannibal Lecter.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, things aren't always as grim as Grimm in ``The 10th
Kingdom,'' which delights in mocking many of the fairy-tale
conventions it uses. When Virginia saves the life of a talking
bird, the grateful critter flies back at key moments and sings,
``Because you have saved my life, I will help you.'' After a couple
of interventions, though, the bird adds, ``But this really has to
stop!''
</P>
<P>
   The best running gag is that after several generations, the
fairy kingdoms have sprouted their own bureaucracies. This is
nicely symbolized in the Snow White Memorial Prison, where much of
Part 1 takes place. As it turns out, the land of enchantment has
plenty of red tape to bog down a couple of impatient visitors. They
find their precious time being wasted by gatekeepers who speak in
riddles, ghosts that only speak in verse, disputes that must be
settled by a jury of sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Even a New Yorker can only take so much absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it with you people?'' Tony finally blurts out.'' And
later, ``Can we just stop with the rhyming (stuff)?''
</P>
<P>
   For all the twists and turns in ``The 10th Kingdom,'' the payoff
doesn't come until next weekend, when Virginia discovers that yes,
there is a Snow White. They meet at her icy estate in a scene
reminiscent of Marlon Brando's home in the first ``Superman''
movie. The casting of Manheim was inspired, and her speech even
galvanizes the lackluster Williams into a winning performance down
the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   A new set of NBC executives has replaced the ones that
green-lighted ``The 10th Kingdom,'' and they've stated their
displeasure with its running time. ``The 10th Kingdom'' has its
problems, but cutting it to the standard four-hour miniseries
length wouldn't have solved them. And it would have denied us the
distinct thrill of seeing an odyssey of this length reach its
satisfying conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, how many TV executives guessed that a revival of
``The $64,000 Question'' with a 64-year-old host would become a
prime-time sensation? Sometimes real life is stranger than fairy
tales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
