<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKS-LATINO-KANSAS-K     02-22 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-LATINO-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATINO CULTURE, AMERICAN CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 10 years' time, Latinos will be the largest minority in
America; in 50 years' time, one in four U.S. residents will be of
Latino origin, if current trends hold.
</P>
<P>
   And yet even as Latino culture saturates the airwaves in the
form of stars such as Jennifer Lopez and Marc Anthony, America at
large still hasn't quite figured out how to embrace it. The United
States continues to struggle with defining itself in terms of black
and white, much less black, white, brown and other colors.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez's Harvest of Empire, then, becomes almost required
reading, not simply for Latinos but for everyone who needs to
better understand the major contributions the culture has made as
far back as 1500.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's excellent opening section, ``Roots (Las Raices),''
notes how English and Spanish explorers and settlers subjugated
native American cultures, but of course the English conquest proved
the more widespread and enduring.
</P>
<P>
   Once the new nation called the United States was established,
however, its frontier expansion continued to carve away at Hispanic
culture. U.S. presidents from Jefferson to Theodore Roosevelt
consider the theft of Latin American land as just a piece in
America's ``Manifest Destiny'' geographical jigsaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``But along with the conquered lands,'' Gonzalez writes, ``came
unwanted peoples: Native Americans, who were pushed farther west,
then herded onto reservations, and several million Mexicans,
Cubans, Filipinos and Puerto Ricans, who were placed under U.S.
sovereignty. Even when Congress officially declared some of the
conquered peoples U.S. citizens, the newly arrived Anglo settlers
routinely seized their properties, and those seizures were then
upheld by the English-speaking courts the settlers installed. The
Mexican Americans of the Southwest became a foreign minority in the
land of their birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez also tackles a range of other subjects, from the
difficult questions posed by bilingualism to the hard-line
politicization of U.S.-Cuban relations, to a subject that most
Americans probably haven't even thought of: the rather sad status
of Puerto Rico, which most mainlanders consider only a vacation
destination, if they consider it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico is perhaps the richest ``colony'' America has ever
had, providing incredible wealth to the United States _ billions of
dollars in investment income, government-owned corporate revenue,
taxes and other resources. And yet Puerto Rican residents, while
considered U.S. citizens by birth, do not have the same rights;
they cannot, for example, vote in federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   So why not just make Puerto Rico the 51st state and correct such
inequities? ``With our government clamping down on the flood of
Latin American immigrants, it is almost unthinkable that a
congressional majority would be prepared to admit an entire state
whose people are racially mixed and who speak Spanish as their main
language.'' Even more unthinkable, of course, given Puerto Rico's
ongoing status as a treasure-trove for America, would be letting it
go its own way.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, however, is not simply a complainer or keeper of
historical facts that some Americans would probably just as soon
forget. He offers solutions in his epilogue _ sound thoughts on
making life for Latinos and, in fact, all Americans better _ such
as reinvesting in U.S. cities and public schools; ending
militaristic operations in Latin American countries; recognizing
``the rights of language minorities'' and promoting the study of
Spanish; and ending the decades-long economic blockade of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians, are you listening?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4514 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-AMERICAN-MATADOR-HNS &LR;      02-22 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-MATADOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POPULAR YANKEE BULLFIGHTER RETIRES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: For photos to accompany this story, call the San Antonio
Express-News at 210-250-3297.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALISON GREGOR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REYNOSA, Mexico _ El Texano, the only gringo ever to be
confirmed as a matador in Mexico, has retired after dedicating his
last bull to his father and taking home its ear.
</P>
<P>
   David Renk, 37, a resident of McAllen, Texas, who has spent the
past two decades of his life fighting bulls, gave his final
performance as a professional matador on Sunday to the strains of
``Golondrinas,'' the farewell song, in front of a crowd of about
500 in the Plaza Monumental de Toros.
</P>
<P>
   Renk performed his signature move, the mano latina, kneeling
before the horns of the first bull he fought, an 1,100-pound beast
that alarmed crowds when it leapt a wooden barricade and took a
turn around the exterior ring.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his second bull, fittingly named ``Bye Bye,'' that
moved the crowd when Renk dedicated the feisty animal to his
father, Fred Renk, an amateur matador who was his son's
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky enough to have the people behind me _ my dad and
my family _ that allowed me to do this,'' David Renk said before
the bullfight began on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He hugged and kissed his father before killing the bull with a
single sword thrust so clean and precise the judges awarded him the
bull's ear, bringing his collection to a career total of 99 such
ears and seven tails.
</P>
<P>
   Renk also has earned one indulto (pardon), the highest honor
that can be granted and another first for a Yankee matador.
</P>
<P>
   American bullfighters are sometimes caught between prejudice
against them in countries where the practice is popular, and
indifference or disgust in their own land, where bullfighting is
illegal and fans not numerous.
</P>
<P>
   Renk's career is all the more extraordinary because he overcame
a severe disability to become a matador.
</P>
<P>
   Renk didn't always have the supple grace of a Spanish dancer
that he demonstrated Sunday. He was born crippled by overly flat
arches, with his feet twisted inward. Walking was painful.
</P>
<P>
   Though doctors told him he would sooner or later be confined to
a wheelchair, Renk had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   He knew he would be a matador.
</P>
<P>
   Though he could hardly walk, Renk toted around a towel on a
stick, playing at mock bullfighting. At 9, medical science caught
up with his aspirations. He underwent an operation and spent a year
in a wheelchair wearing a series of corrective leg casts.
</P>
<P>
   During Easter weekend in 1971, still hobbled by casts, he
announced his career goals at a bullfight in Juarez fought by his
father's friend, retiring matador Pepe Luis Vasquez.
</P>
<P>
   As Renk sat in a wheelchair on the sidelines, Vasquez dedicated
his last bull to the slender boy and told him he could be anything.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a decade later _ also during an Easter weekend in the
border city of Juarez _ Renk became a matador, killing his first
full-grown bull with the help of Vasquez, who had become his
mentor.
</P>
<P>
   He was only the sixth, and at 18 the youngest, American in the
history of bullfighting to become a matador. Throughout Mexico,
Renk became known as ``El Texano,'' fighting his way to the top of
the profession with about 20 corridas, or bullfights, a year.
</P>
<P>
   Renk eventually returned to the United States, got a job in
water purification, married and had children. But he kept fighting.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday, Renk will no longer fight professionally in his
``suit of lights,'' though he will continue to fight smaller bulls
in traje corto, the suit used for festival fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll always be in my blood,'' he said, grinning. ``The gusano
(worm) gets in you. It will never leave you.''
</P>
<P>
   When Renk, now a wiry and sun-weathered man of 37, talks about
bullfighting, his quiet demeanor changes.
</P>
<P>
   He becomes the regal boy in the hundreds of photos and posters
that line the walls of what he affectionately calls his father's
``museum,'' the boy who bears no resemblance to the frail, crippled
youngster he had once been.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I put the suit on, and I tie that pigtail to the back of
my head, and put on those pink stockings, I can be arrogant as I
want to be,'' Renk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You become a different person. That's what I get out of it.
Just to even go to a bullfight, the whole thing, is very special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
