<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4516 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-HACKER-CYBER-ATTACK-N     02-22 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-CYBER-ATTACK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 GOOD and EVIL in CYBERSPACE  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax, By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   It happened almost overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Before people in the United States even began to realize it,
they were living via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic culture now has an impact _ and even greater
depth and speed _ comparable to that of the railroad and the
electric light in the 19th century and plastics and antibiotics
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The decade of the '90s was the most prosperous in U.S. history,
and the Internet is both a product and a beneficiary of that. It's
a gigantic virtual marketplace where people can find whatever they
dream of, from medical diagnoses to movie tickets to plane
reservations to at-home visitors supplied by erotic escort
services.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a day goes by when someone in the average American
middle-class family doesn't do an Internet transaction. Most of the
flowers and boxes of chocolates sent by people in love on
Valentine's Day were ordered from Yahoo.com and Altavista.com, two
favorite virtual ``sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Many bills that used to be paid by mail, from mortgages to
monthly cable-TV fees to private club dues, are now electronic,
click-of-a-mouse transactions. Perhaps the Internet is a good
explanation for the growing number of fat people in the United
States: If everything can be done within easy reach of the
keyboard, why move at all?
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand, then, the chaos that exploded during
the second week of February, when electronic pirates _ known as
``hackers'' _ attacked the Yahoo Internet site and created an
incredible bottleneck. The invasion, anonymous and impossible to
contain, was so well coordinated that separate parts of the plan
were able to evolve like clockwork. One by one, other major Web
sites were disrupted: Amazon, eBay, and buy.com.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has pinpointed a credible motive. Perhaps it was all
merely to show the world that the great Internet commercial sites
are actually very vulnerable to invasion and that, furthermore,
their weaknesses can be protected probably only by ``good'' hackers
whose skills are greater than those of the ``bad'' attackers.
</P>
<P>
   In the most authoritative newspaper columns,
information-technology analysts have likened what happened in
cyberspace to this scenario: a sale at a major department store for
which hundreds of thousands of customers arrive at the same time,
but only 10,000 were expected over the course of a week.
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, the February attack also bears the sinister feel
of the actions of a serial killer who strikes simply and solely
because he wants to, and nobody can guess who the next victim will
be.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time now I have wondered what makes a hacker, what
his moral code and his lifestyle might be. In the movies they've
been portrayed as gaunt young men who conspire in dark and dirty
basement rooms and grasp their computers as though they were
bloodthirsty knives.
</P>
<P>
   In real life, their image is different. At the university where
I work, the hackers describe themselves as ``white hats.'' They've
told me that their virtual universe has its own culture and
language, its own music and its own clear moral boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   I met some of these young men in mid-February, soon after the
attack on Yahoo. Far from gaunt and dirty, they were athletic, well
mannered and professionally employed in part-time mainstream jobs,
earning no less than $2,000 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them had positions in the information-security areas of
major high-tech corporations in the area of New Jersey between
Princeton and Edison: the home of medical laboratories, cell-phone
manufacturers and international hotel chains.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven I met, three were Indian, two were Korean, one was
Russian and the other was born in Kansas of Chinese parents.
</P>
<P>
   I learned that on Thursday and Saturday nights they meet at
Clyde's, a bar in New Brunswick that features 53 kinds of Martinis.
There they talk about their cybernetic adventures in a language no
ordinary non-''tekkie'' can put into normal written language: bits,
bytes and so on.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rajeev, one of the Indian computer experts, the
Yahoo invasion had all the earmarks of a program sent through the
Internet in November _ one that was signed by ``Mixter.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later I read in The New York Times that Mixter had
been found. He is, it seems, a 20-year-old German hacker who lives
near Hanover, N.J., and is believed to have created one of the most
damaging viruses of the '90s: the Magnolia Web.
</P>
<P>
   By the hackers' moral code, Rajeev told me, Mixter is a gray,
which means he's someone who hasn't yet crossed the boundary into
the territory of the white hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are something like a brotherhood and we have learned to
identify each other,'' Rajeev said. ``I'll bet you that Mixter is a
Prodigy fanatic and his favorite song is `Voodoo People.'
Everything he does has that techno trademark. As far as I'm
concerned he's too heavy. Those kids think they are gods.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoom, one of the Koreans, tried to sketch for me the evil ones,
the ``black hats.'' ``Even though nothing is hard and fast with
us,'' he told me, ``and any of us white hats might turn gray
tomorrow, for no particular reason, I can tell you that none of us
would become a black hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're despicable. You know what they're after? A power rush.
Adrenaline. ... I met a black hat in Nebraska. He lived alone. ...
His house smelled like a cave. This guy would pick some innocent
person who lived 1,000 miles away and access his e-mail _ it's so
easy _ and then destroy this person's life: read his mail and
sometimes answer it for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd use the victim's credit card. ... Once he even changed a
poor guy's blood analysis report _ the man was about to have
emergency surgery. Finally he got bored and found another human
target, but not before dispatching a virus that destroyed the other
computer memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this, and what for? Just to show that he was better, that
he knew more, that he had someone else's life in his hands. For a
black hat, there is no law besides vanity, no religion other than
ego.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the attack on Yahoo and other electronic business
centers has created an almost metaphysical panic in the American
economy _ panic in the face of an evil that nobody is able to
define or analyze or predict. What will happen, one wonders, if the
amoral black hats do infiltrate the crusading white hats, creating
inexplicable chaos?
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has created a new lifestyle and a new language, but
it is also creating new forms of evil and destruction. This century
is just beginning, and reality is already different.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the distinguished author of ``The Peron
Novel'' and ``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American
studies department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an
editor and journalist.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1307EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
