<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4518 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-VANISHING-VETERANS-CO     02-22 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANISHING-VETERANS-CONGRESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES MILITARY EXPERIENCE COUNT? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By JASON SHERMAN  
 c.2000 Armed Forces Journal International  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   __ A new study raises questions about the influence of
``vanishing veterans.'' __
</P>
<P>
   .....................................................
</P>
<P>
   Nestled within view of the Potomac River, the Pentagon is
flanked to the north and south by the Memorial and 14th Street
bridges, spans that connect the Defense Department with its
political patrons in Congress across the water on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Not marked on any map is another link that also provides an
important connection between the two institutions: military
service. Lawmakers who have donned a uniform, especially those who
served in combat, are widely regarded as providing an important
bridge of understanding between the world of professional
politicians and the professional military.
</P>
<P>
   During the last 30 years, lawmakers from the World War II
generation have moved on, and the abolition of conscription has
resulted in fewer lawmakers who span the political-military divide.
This trend has caused handwringing and analysis for a few years by
many observers concerned that, with fewer veterans, the federal
legislature may not adequately oversee and guide the U.S. armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Now a new study by William Bianco, a political science professor
at Pennsylvania State University, concludes that military service
does not have a notable impact on a legislator's voting behavior.
</P>
<P>
   If the decline of military veterans in Congress is leading to
significant changes in defense policy, Bianco found, its effects
are indirect and generally through changes in legislative agendas
or in the quantity and kinds of information available to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   And while the decline of lawmakers with military experience has
been much discussed, this study found that Congress now has an
unexpectedly low number of members who have served in the armed
forces compared to veterans in the general population.
</P>
<P>
   Does military experience matter? ``I think that's a fair
question,'' Bianco said, in a recent interview. ``If you look at
what a lot of veterans are saying, they are very concerned that a
Congress without veterans would behave differently than a Congress
with veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bianco examined the trends of military experience in the House
and Senate from 1789 to 1999, closely looking at partisan
differences in military experience during the last century. He also
analyzed the impact of veteran status on select military votes
during the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Bianco concluded, ``The gross effect that veterans are going to
vote differently on military-affairs issues, broadly defined, just
doesn't show up in the data.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, ``Vanishing Veterans: The Decline in Military
Experience in the U.S. Congress,'' found ``no evidence that the
absolute decline or emerging underrepresentation of veterans have,
by themselves, had a significant impact on the kinds of policies
emerging from Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper was co-authored with Air Force Lt. Jamie Markham, then
a Harvard undergraduate ROTC student, as part of a study conducted
by the Triangle Institute for Security Studies' ``Project on the
Gap Between the Military and Civilian Society.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran status, Bianco and Markham found, has ``at best a
modest'' impact on vote decisions and policy outcomes. This, the
authors argue, doesn't mean that the decline in the number of
lawmakers who have served in uniform has no impact on votes. ``What
it suggests is that this effect, if it exists, is primarily
indirect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bianco acknowledged that this argument implies that by the time
a bill gets to the House or Senate floor for a vote, veterans are
forced to go along with non-veterans. ``But if the agenda was truly
being skewed one way or the other, you could expect veterans to
break away from non-veterans on most votes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the only place you see that is on bills like the `don't
ask, don't tell' (policy on homosexuals in the military), and even
there the effect isn't shocking. It's not like all the veterans are
on one side of the issue and the non-veterans are on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The thinning of military veteran ranks in Congress has been
severe over the last 50 years. In 1971 more than 75 percent of
House members had military experience compared with 25 percent in
1999. The Senate has seen a similar decline, although it began
later and was a bit smaller.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in the House and Senate over the last generation has
been more or less evenly divided among Republicans and Democrats.
However, the decline of lawmaker veterans of the military has not
been as dramatic on the committees that deal with defense issues,
which ``continue to have a high percentage of veterans,
facilitating their role as information suppliers,'' according to
the paper.
</P>
<P>
   This includes lawmakers on the House Armed Services, House
Veterans Affairs, Senate Armed Services and Senate Veterans Affairs
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 100 years, the two party caucuses have had roughly
the same percentage of military veterans. While Republicans have
generally maintained a slight advantage _ a few percentage points _
the study noted: ``Surprisingly, the largest differences are
observed in the contemporary Senate, where Democrats have a better
than 10 percentage-point advantage over Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   The larger trend toward fewer lawmakers with military experience
may be viewed as a statistical correction, Bianco said, because for
decades during the Cold War, Congress had a higher percentage of
veterans when compared to the general population. And while Bianco
found that Congress today is underrepresented by those with
military experience compared to the general population, the
Congress of the early 1900s was even more so.
</P>
<P>
   With an all-volunteer, professional military, the number of
lawmakers who will have saluted a commander is expected to continue
to dwindle. Without universal conscription, Bianco found, an
individual with a high education level and high socioeconomic
status is less likely to serve in the military than one with less
education and lower income.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what's happening in Congress,'' the Penn State professor
said, ``is that it's been drawing from the same group over time _
that group is much less likely to have served (in the military) in
the past, and much less likely to have served relative to the whole
population.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers with military experience certainly bring a unique
perspective and familiarity with many defense issues that Congress
must address. However, these veterans by no means have a lock on
what is required to understand the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this very cherished belief about how military service
educates people,'' Bianco said. ``They learn about getting together
with a group of people that you don't necessarily like and learn
about patriotism and shared sacrifice. And while I'm certain the
military does that for some people _ and you can get it other ways
too _ it's not inevitable. People don't all come out of the
military as egalitarian internationalists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An Air Force colonel told me that his feeling on this was that
two years of flipping burgers at an air base in Texas doesn't teach
you much about national security. We all make a big deal about Bill
Clinton not being a veteran. But remember,'' Bianco said, ``that
Sam Nunn, one of the most respected defense influentials of the
last generation, is not a veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jason Sherman is senior editor at Armed Forces Journal
International, a McLean, Va.-based monthly magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
