<P>
   &UR; A WASTELAND of PSEUDO-WOMEN'S CULTURE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANCINE PROSE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; For immediate release &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   From Oxygen.com to TV, the entertainment industry is finally
creating culture that's ``for women, by women.'' But is this the
drivel we've been waiting for? As the executives see it,
``women's'' fare is only a step above ``young adult.'' And though
no one will admit it, the prevailing wisdom is that women are
stupid and narcissistic, desiring only mindless escapism.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Francine Prose is a fellow at the New York Public Library
Center for Scholars and Writers. Her new novel, ``Blue Angel,''
will be published in April. slugged: BC-OXYGEN-CENTERPIECE-NYTSF,
priority code s, category code c) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SECOND SEXUAL REVOLUTION &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JACK HITT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (For release: Feb. 20 or thereafter) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Viagra was just the beginning. Soon we'll all be medicated and
wired for high-performance romance. Though many of us think the
totality of sex is unknowable, maybe even divine, considering
today's enraged pace of daily life, who doubts that a drug-enhanced
four-minute sexual encounter among harried urbanites could become
the norm? (Jack Hitt is a contributing writer for The New York
Times Magazine. slugged: BC-SEX-CENTERPIECE-NYTSF, priority code s,
category code c) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ANTI-SADDAM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By JANINE di GIOVANNI &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (For release: Feb. 20 or thereafter) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Chalabi, 55, is the head of the Iraqi National Congress,
the once and, for now, future guiding body of the Iraqi opposition
to Saddam Hussein. As such, he is also the closest thing either the
Clinton administration or its Republican opponents have to a
strategy for replacing the failed U.S. policy of containing Iraq.
Aside from brutal in-fighting, though, the opposition has one major
problem. It still hasn't figured out a way to outsmart Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Janine di Giovanni is a correspondent with The Times of
London. slugged: BC-IRAQ-CENTERPIECE-NYTSF, priority code s,
category code c) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HIGH COST OF TV HAUNTS ALL POLITICS &LR;  &QL; 
