<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILICON-VALLEY-HOMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TODAY'S GOLD RUSH IS ALL ABOUT LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MENLO PARK, Calif. _ The cars slow on quiet Cloud Avenue so the
occupants can roll down the window and point. Undeterred by
relentless rain, the drivers of a Mercedes, then a Volvo pull to
the curb.
</P>
<P>
   The object of their rubbernecking? Not a crime scene or a fire.
Not a celebrity, unless the sheer act of buying a home here, the
center of the Silicon Valley real estate mosh pit, is worthy of
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of attention is an unassuming four-bedroom house that
inspired a 22-way bidding war recently. The winner paid close to $1
million more than the $1.25 million asking price.
</P>
<P>
   Word of such bidding battles has traveled like urban legend in
the heart of the valley, where a cozy home can cost as much as $1
million and there are plenty of newly minted millionaires _ by some
estimates 64 emerge each day _ to snap them up in record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The real estate rush has become a contemporary Gold Rush in
Northern California, fueled by the technology economy.
</P>
<P>
   There is the venture capitalist who offered to pay almost $4
million in cash for a Palo Alto house sight unseen, took one look
and handed over the money before the house hit the market. And the
high-tech entrepreneur who paid a million for a house in Monte
Sereno, between Saratoga and Los Gatos, plus $500,000 in stock
options. And the buyers who are offering sellers free rent, even a
Hawaiian vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beyond crazy. It's madness,'' said RoyAnne Florence, a
real estate agent with Coldwell Banker in Menlo Park who
represented the seller of the Cloud Avenue house. ``My whole belief
is that the market is being driven by Economics 101. There is a
short supply of houses. That's what's fueling the bizarre
beyond-belief market.''
</P>
<P>
   While the price of houses has skyrocketed around the San
Francisco Bay, nowhere is the market as turbo-powered as in parts
of Silicon Valley, according to real estate agents, developers and
those competing to buy.
</P>
<P>
   The market here changes almost hourly, with many homes selling
auction-style after offers and counter-offers, each pushing future
sale prices further skyward.
</P>
<P>
   With the median resale price of a home in Silicon Valley now
around $450,000, more than seven out of 10 people who do not own
already cannot afford to buy, according to Carl Guardino, president
of the Silicon Valley Manufacturing Group, a high-tech trade
organization working with public and private agencies to create
affordable housing in the valley.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in California are more million-dollar homes being sold
than in Saratoga, where the most expensive one went for $4.7
million, according to one real estate sales monitoring report. The
report by La Jolla-based Acxiom showed 241 such sales last year, up
from 139 the previous year. And four of the top 10 ZIP codes with
the highest sales in California were in the Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the buyers are undeterred by spiraling costs. Foiled in
their first few attempts to buy, they simply get more creative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people offer trips to Hawaii,'' said Jeff Barnett, a
vice president with Alain Pinel Realty in Los Gatos. ``It's no
different than throwing in $5,000 to $7,000. It's just being
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one couple looking to buy a home, and they saw in the
garage that the seller collected Porsches. They collected them,
too, so with their offer they sent pictures of them standing next
to their cars, just to show what kind of people they are.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Palo Alto, a widowed lawyer recently decided to sell the
Crescent Park house where he had raised his children and to look
for something smaller. He set the price at $2.7 million _ on a
house he bought more than 40 years ago for $75,000 _ because a
nearby house had just sold for $2.6 million. A venture capitalist
offered $4 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like hitting the lottery. It's just sheer luck,'' said
the lawyer, who asked that his name not be used because he is
hunting for a smaller house and did not want sellers to know how
much profit he made.
</P>
<P>
   With new houses in short supply, those who can't buy what they
want knock down existing homes and rebuild bigger ones.
</P>
<P>
   In some neighborhoods, ranch-style houses and cottages that have
served as family homes are referred to as ``tear downs.'' Many in
Palo Alto have sold for $700,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone to the extreme,'' said Christine Cummings, who
estimates that in the 13 years she has lived on Parkinson Avenue in
Palo Alto at least a dozen homes out of the 50 on her street have
been torn down or remodeled into what some now call ``monster
homes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody seems to care what's happening to the neighborhood,''
said Cummings, who supports a city measure to preserve older
houses. ``It's an emotional issue to me. I'm really ticked off that
people don't think houses have spirits to them.''
</P>
<P>
   What is happening in Silicon Valley is ``an anomaly,'' said
Penny Pompei, head of the Silicon Valley Realtors Association. But
rippling effects can be felt elsewhere as buyers find homes listed
for $300,000 are pushed up to $400,000 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came from out of state and we'd need a down payment that's
more than the total we've ever paid for a home,'' said Dana
Swenson, who's been frequenting open houses for the 18 months since
she and her husband moved to the Silicon Valley from Utah. ``It's
insanity to think of paying that much for a home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
