<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4577 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-JARRETT-BOS &LR;      02-22 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT'S DAYTONA EFFORT WAS FIT FOR A KING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ When Dale Jarrett pulled down pit road to
make his way toward Victory Lane after winning Sunday's Daytona
500, he was greeted by several well-wishers. But Jarrett was
startled when a familiar figure wearing a cowboy hat, sunglasses,
and a toothy grin came out to offer his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got involved in Winston Cup racing, I had the dream
that everybody else does of one day being in Victory Lane and
having a Daytona 500 trophy,'' said Jarrett, who claimed his third
such title, to go along with triumphs in 1993 and 1996. ``It's
always nice to come down pit road and get the congratulations of
other team members and your own team members.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the thing today was Richard Petty came out, made his way
across pit road, and shook my hand. That sent chills up my spine
that the King would make his way out there and congratulate me on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a career year in 1999 _ in which he won his first
NASCAR Winston Cup championship for the Robert Yates Racing team _
Jarrett may be embarking on another. He picked up a staggering
$2,277,975 in winnings Sunday, including a $1 million Winston No
Bull 5 bonus for his third Daytona 500 title. Jarrett joined Petty
(seven), Cale Yarborough (four), and Bobby Allison (three) as the
only drivers in NASCAR history to win three or more Daytona 500s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it just shows how special it is to get those three,''
said Jarrett, who was flanked by crew chief Todd Parrott in the
postrace press conference. ``It's very, very elite company and I
just have a lot of people to thank, mainly this guy sitting beside
me, for all those possibilities for it all happening.''
</P>
<P>
   While his first two Daytona 500s hold a special place in
Jarrett's treasure chest of memories, this trophy earned a coveted
spot because of the adversity his team had overcome to attain it.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment his red-white-and-blue rocketship was unloaded
from the hauler, Jarrett dominated Speedweeks 2000, winning the
pole position and the Bud Shootout, and finishing runner-up to Bill
Elliott in an impressive 1-2-3 Ford finish in the Gatorade Twin
125s.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it appeared he was in cruise control, though, Jarrett
was jarred by a Happy Hour accident Saturday afternoon that had his
team scrambling _ flying in fabricators Kevin Stimberis, Robby
Hancock, and Andrew Johnson from the team's shop in Charlotte,
N.C., that night _ to make emergency repairs to an out-of-joint
nose, a kink in the left corner of the hood, and dents on the front
and rear bumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like our great week had gone to pieces late Saturday
afternoon,'' Jarrett said. ``I spent about 2 1/2 hours after
practice was over with Todd and guys yesterday afternoon, and once
we went over everything, knowing the chassis was OK, then we talked
about what we needed to do to the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very confident when I left (the garage) that the car
would be back in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be good as new.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Jarrett enshrined his No. 88 Ford Quality Car Taurus at
the Daytona USA motorsports museum, where it will be on display
until next year's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an incredible race car,'' Jarrett said. ``It won
at Talladega in 1998 and won a million-dollar bonus there. It won
here in July last here and I think it finished second in both
Talladega races last year, then won some $2 million here, so this
is about a $4 million race car and I guess it deserves a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it really wouldn't be our choice. It really wasn't a
choice, sitting there in second, but it did cross my mind that,
hey, if I go on and win this Daytona 500, I've got to give up this
great-handling race car. But I know that he'll build some more
great ones, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
