<HEADLINE>
A SIGN OF SPRING: FLOWER SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring is near. Garden shows are under way. The Philadelphia
Flower Show, largest indoor flower show in the world and the oldest
in this country, runs March 5 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   This year's theme is ``Gardens for the New Millennium,''
celebrating how plants and flowers will enhance lives in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   If you're heading for this show, bring comfortable walking shoes
_ the exhibit area covers 10 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Should you be overwhelmed by the displays, take a break and
stroll eight of the most historical blocks in America. There are
guided trolly tours, a laser light show, world-class museums, and
dozens of events in conjunction with Flower Show Week, and all are
within walking distance of the show. And, should you take a walk,
there's free same-day readmission to return to smell the flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Flower Show Week includes hotel and day-trip packages, cultural
attractions, discounts, events, and restaurant offers. Pick up a
Bloomin' Fun Pass Book at the show, or call the Philadelphia
Visitors Center at 800-611-5960. Flower show information is also
available at www.philaflowershow.com.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is also big in the flower world. The New England Spring
Flower Show, March 11-19, is the third largest in the world. The
129th annual show will be held at the Bayside Expo Center with the
theme ``Symphony for the Senses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston show covers 5 1/2 acres and will have 50 garden
displays. Tickets for the Massachusetts Horticultural Society show
are $15 weekdays and $17 weekends for adults, and $6 for children
4-12. Discounted tickets are available at Stop &AMP; Shop. For show
information, call 617-536-9280 or visit www.masshort.org.
</P>
<P>
   There's still time to check out the Rhode Island Spring Flower &AMP;
Garden Show at the Rhode Island Convention Center in Providence.
The show is open from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. For information, call
800-766-1670 or visit www.flowershow.com.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for some gardens that are open to the public? ``The
Garden Conservancy's Open Days Directory: The Guide to Visiting
Hundreds of America's Best Private Gardens'' (Abrams, $14.95)
offers gardens that are open to the public on select weekend days
from March through October. This year 17 new cities were added to
the book, including destinations in New Hampshire and Long Island's
North Shore. The book can be ordered ($14.95 plus $3.50 shipping)
by writing to the Garden Conservancy, PO Box 219, Cold Spring, NY
10516 or calling 888-842-2442.
</P>
<P>
   Kona on the Big Island of Hawaii will feature its Kona Spring
Blossom Festival April 1 through 29. The festival features a farm
and field day, open houses in three villages, and Japanese heritage
events. The festival is planned to showcase the island's unique
agriculture that includes Kona coffee and macadamia nuts as well as
tropical fruits, nuts, flowers, vegetables, and specialty items
such as vanilla aand cocoa beans. For information on the festival,
call 808-323-3434 or visit www.agtourism.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spring break &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where is the college crowd heading for spring break this year?
Council Travel, which specializes in student trips, reports that
the five most popular destinations are: Panama City Beach, Fla.;
Cancun, Mexico; Daytona Beach, Fla.; South Padre Island, Texas; and
various Colorado ski resorts.
</P>
<P>
   For the majority of the expected 1.5 million undergraduate
students on spring break, warm weather, low prices, and
like-minded, party-hearty soulmates are the prime criteria.
Accessibility is also a prime factor. While students in the West
head to Mexico and Colorado, those in the East have made Caribbean
spots popular.
</P>
<P>
   While the often wild and uninhibited activities that
characterize spring break get a lot of media coverage, Council
Travel is finding a growing number of young adults are heading to
Europe for a different kind of trip. Last year more than 400,000
students traveled overseas, double the number that did so just
eight years ago, said Bill McGuinness of Council Travel. For
information, call 800-2COUNCIL or visit www.counciltravel.com.
</P>
<P>
   Offering a slightly different version of where the students are
going is a survey by PopWall.com, which bills itself as ``the Pulse
of the Net Generation.'' The on-line survey of 274 students reports
Mexico as the most popular with 14 percent of those surveyed, and
Florida a close second at 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also covered questions on drinking and sex.One
revelation was that 60 percent planned on paying for the vacation
themselves. If you want the answers to these and other questions,
check out PopWall.com.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica is expecting more students to select the island as their
destination of choice. The reason: MTV featured the island last
year. This year Ocho Rios is holding Spring Break Escape March
13-20 and to help boost it, the week is sponsored by Rolling Stone.
Negril is holding Tropical Insanity March 4-25. For information,
check out the Jamaica Web site at www.jamaicatravel.com.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Fort Lauderdale, where spring break became
defined by the 1960 film ``Where the Boys Are''? Well, the 23 miles
of beaches are still great, but a lot quieter since Fort Lauderdale
transformed itself from the host of 350,000 students to a diverse
and cosmopolitan destination.
</P>
<P>
   This year Fort Lauderdale reports the closest thing to a
bacchanalian rampage might be what happens on stage during the
Broadway show ``Titanic'' (March 7-19). Otherwise there are
concerts, great museums, antique shops, and great dining. Not your
typical spring-break fare. Want to know more? Call 800-22-SUNNY or
visit www.sunny.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate festival &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Touring inn to inn on cross-country skis or snowshoes and
indulging in chocolate dishes along the way _ that's what the 11th
annual Chocolate Festival at the Mount Washington Valley Ski
Touring and Snowshoe Center is all about. The festival is Feb. 27
from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. and includes eight inns with such treats as
chocolate fondue, fudges, chocolate chip cookies, chocolate mousse,
even maple-flavored chocolate business cards. Event passes are $14
for adults, $8 for juniors and seniors, and are available at
various locations in the area. For complete information, call
603-356-9920 or visit www.CrossCountrySkiNH.com. When calling, ask
about inns in the area that offer free skiing with a stay. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summer reading &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to spend your summer reading and discussing great
works of literature, philosophy, and the opera, take off for Santa
Fe. Each summer St. John's College, nationally recognized as the
great books school, offers a unique educational experience in a
small group, seminar-style setting. The Summer Classics is a series
of weeklong seminars, with participants choosing one seminar a week
for up to three weeks. Mornings are dedicated to the seminar, with
afternoons free for studying or participating in college-sponsored
excursions. For information, write to Summer Classics, St. John's
College, 1160 Camino Cruz Blanca, Santa Fe, NM 87501; telephone
505-984-6104; or visit www.sjcsf.edu.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ciboney Ocho Rios spa and beach resort in Jamaica has a
Diamond Package that for $99 a person above the standard provides
an upgrade to a Diamond Villa suite (all-inclusive rack rates begin
at $240 a person through March 31, and $205 April 1-Dec. 22). The
villa package includes an attendant to prepare breakfast, do light
washing and ironing, and to pack. The package also includes an
in-villa romantic dinner for two with a personal balladeer, and
five spa treatments a day per person. The nine-year-old resort is
undergoing a complete renovation, which ``will not disturb the
guest experience,'' said Peter Trench, co-general manager. For
information, call 800-CIBONEY.
</P>
