<HEADLINE>
KEN GRIFFEY IS SITTING PRETTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ At times Monday, Ken Griffey Jr. looked like a
rookie conductor facing a massive orchestra. He was nervous. His
right leg shook as he spoke at Ed Smith Stadium. Here he was,
running solo on the Hype Treadmill for the 11th day in a row.
</P>
<P>
   One day he is facing a staggering number of media. Another day
he is hearing the story of how, because of him, the Cincinnati
Reds' outdated phone system became so jammed that employees
couldn't check their voice mail. New day, new news: One of his
teammates, Sean Casey, stole Griffey's rookie card from a
department store when he was 13. Casey's father found out and sent
his son to the dictionary. He made him look up ``selfish,''
``greed,'' and ``thief.'' He made him return the card, too.
</P>
<P>
   On Day 11 in the buzzing Griffey Kingdom, a photographer even
accused the peaceful Holley Lama of intentionally obstructing his
view of the king. Man. I haven't been this insulted since Halle
Berry stopped taking my calls (I couldn't sell her on Halle
Holley). So I guess now would be a good time to explain why all
this spring training attention to Griffey is dangerous, overblown,
and unjustified.
</P>
<P>
   But I can't do it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I can't wait to see how teams are going to approach
this lineup; it is easily baseball's best. You'll find more power
in Cleveland. You'll find Nomar Garciaparra in Boston. You'll find
a balanced, patient crew in New York (in both Queens and the
Bronx). But over a full season, it's going to be impossible to
quiet the Reds. If I were one of their fans, I'd begin saving for
World Series tickets, too.
</P>
<P>
   Reds manager Jack McKeon was asked where Griffey will hit in the
lineup. ``Anywhere he wants,'' McKeon replied. He was joking. He
plans to put Griffey in the No. 3 spot, behind leadoff man Pokey
Reese and Barry Larkin and in front of cleanup hitter Dante
Bichette and Casey, who hit .332 last season.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, those five had 2,961 at-bats last season and
struck out only 418 times. Reese, Larkin, and Griffey all have
speed. They also have Gold Gloves, giving the Reds one of the most
devastating up-the-middle defenses in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey no longer will have the Ballpark in Arlington, Yankee
Stadium, and Edison Field to assault. But consider some of the NL
perks. He gains six extra games in the thin air of Coors Field. He
gains 81 games in the Queen City's Cinergy Field, where the ball
travels well. It's 307 feet to right in the new San Francisco park.
Dodger Stadium measures 330 down the right-field line. And there is
always Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   I know it's early. I know there could be an injury tomorrow. But
how do you pitch these guys? And receiving pitches from the Reds
may not be as inviting as you might think. They had the National
League's best bullpen last season. They don't have a 200-inning
pitcher in their rotation, but they expect Denny Neagle to reach
that this season.
</P>
<P>
   One thing all Reds fans should worry about is Junior adjusting
to NL pitching. He played in the American League for 11 seasons and
the new league is going to be very tough on him.
</P>
<P>
   Nah. Just kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, Larkin, Reese, McKeon, and Reds general manager Jim
Bowden were all smiling _ understandably _ this week. Larkin and
Griffey both grew up in Cincinnati and were friendly before the
Feb. 10 trade between the Mariners and Reds. Larkin said he has
seen the change in Griffey the past week. It used to be that Larkin
would leave a message and Griffey wouldn't return it for three
days. Now the center fielder is on the phone with the shortstop
several times a day, asking questions. Lots of questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Senior talked a lot,'' Larkin said of Griffey's father,
a Reds coach. ``But, my God, this guy . . .''
</P>
<P>
   If Griffey likes to talk as much as Larkin says he does, it's
another reason he will fit in Cincinnati. This team enjoyed talking
a lot last year, without Griffey. Now the Reds also may add Deion
Sanders, who signed a minor league contract.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey wasn't extremely talkative. Not only did he appear to be
uncomfortable, it seemed that he wasn't thrilled to be talking to
anyone. He arrived at his press conference Monday in a golf cart
and took a seat atop the first-base dugout. He scanned the crowd
and said, ``This is not normal.''
</P>
<P>
   He wore a shirt that could be described as ``Mariners blue.'' He
explained that he will have to get some new gear because, ``Most of
the things I own are blue.'' Although it didn't show, he said his
level of excitement rivaled his enthusiasm of 1995, when he scored
the winning run in Game 5 of a Division Series with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey insisted that he wanted to be traded so he could be
closer to his family. His wife and two children were here, waving
at a man in the Reds' offices. The man couldn't stop smiling. It
was Bowden, the GM who grew up in Massachusetts (Weston and
Wellesley).
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said he has dreamed of acquiring Griffey since 1992. The
Reds' new park, which will open in 2003, was designed with a
lefthanded power hitter in mind. Bowden knows he made a brilliant
trade, but he said with a straight face, ``The Mariners made a
better trade than people give them credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew that answer sounded more like Beacon Hill than Weston.
He made a great trade. This is one of the rare times that all the
hype is justified. Reds fans knew that in December when they heard
that their GM was pursuing Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would pick up my restaurant tabs without giving me a
chance to pay them,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what the fans will buy him before Game 1 of the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
