<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4638 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-MIRACLE-2TAKES-BO     02-22 1775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MIRACLE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUSTER HASN'T FADED FROM AMERICANS' SHINING MOMENT IN 1980 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The clock never moved. ``There were 10 minutes left when I
scored the goal,'' captain Mike Eruzione remembers. ``I went out
and played another shift and the clock said, like, 9:59. Then I
played another shift and it said 8:20.''
</P>
<P>
   Time didn't stand still when the US Olympic hockey team shocked
the Soviet Union and the world with its ``miracle on ice'' in Lake
Placid 20 years ago. It just seemed that way, as the Americans
strove desperately to hold off the Big Red Machine until the
buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many times when you play a game, you never want it to
end,'' says Eruzione, who never played another after he and his
teammates beat Finland for the Olympic gold medal two days later.
``That night, we couldn't wait for it to end.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, that game has never ended. Last week, when Eruzione
dropped the puck before a Penguins game in Pittsburgh, he got a
standing ovation from a crowd chanting, ``USA, USA.'' Millions of
Americans can tell you where they were and what they were doing
Feb. 22, 1980, when the Boys of Winter beat the unbeatable Soviets,
4-3, holding them scoreless for the final 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, it was a psychological turning point for the
American people,'' says Jack O'Callahan, the defenseman from
Charlestown, Mass., whose exultant, toothless grin graces the
famous celebratory photo snapped by The Boston Globe's Frank
O'Brien. ``Things were at a low point and the country was in a dark
state.''
</P>
<P>
   In February of 1980, both inflation and unemployment were
soaring, US citizens were being held hostage in Iran, the Red Army
was defiantly occupying Afghanistan, and President Jimmy Carter was
pushing for a boycott of the Summer Olympics in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without realizing it,'' muses O'Callahan, ``we became the dawn
of a new way of looking at things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, seeded seventh among the 12-team field, weren't
even supposed to win a medal on their home ice. They trailed in six
of their seven games. They trailed the Soviets three times. They
trailed the Finns with one period to play. They never trailed at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a thing that will never be forgotten in the history of
sport,'' says Vyacheslav Fetisov, a defenseman on that Soviet squad
who went on to win two Olympic gold medals and two Stanley Cups
with the Detroit Red Wings and is now an assistant coach with the
New Jersey Devils. ``It is a great example of how young kids can
get together with a big goal in their minds and make the impossible
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Boys of Winter (at an average age of 22, they were the
youngest US Olympic team ever) came from Massachusetts and the
Midwest, from the shadow of Bunker Hill to the Iron Range of
Minnesota. They were amateurs fresh out of college, most of them,
or still undergrads. They were selected and molded and goaded and
inspired by the mercurial, mystical Herb Brooks, the last player
cut from the 1960 team that defeated the Soviets at Squaw Valley.
And when they arrived in the Adirondacks, nobody had any idea how
they'd do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the kind of team where if we didn't play well, we could
lose to everybody in the tournament,'' says Jim Craig, the goalie
from North Easton, Mass., who played every minute of every game.
``And if we did play well, we could beat everybody in the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody, it seemed, except the guys in the red helmets. The
Soviets were undeniably the best team in the world. ``The best team
ever assembled, and I play for many teams,'' states Fetisov.
Vladislav Tretiak, Boris Mikhailov, Sergei Makharov, Valery
Kharlamov, Vladimir Petrov, Aleksandr Maltsev, Vladimir Krutov,
Valery Vasiliev _ a Hall of Fame on one bench.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, the Soviets had beaten the cream of the NHL in a
midseason best-of-three at Madison Square Garden, destroying the
pros, 6-0, in the finale. ``We played as good as we could,''
shrugged NHL captain Bobby Clarke, as his stunned mates blinked
back tears in the locker room. ``They are a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Olympians also played the Soviets in the Garden in a
tuneup the weekend before the Games and were demolished, 10-3.
``That was pretty good,'' Brooks cracked afterward, trying to
lighten the mood. ``That was fun to play them, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans didn't figure to face the CCCP again. They weren't
expected to make the Olympic medal round, not with Sweden and
Czechoslovakia in their group. But they came from behind twice in
the opener and tied the Swedes on Bill Baker's slapper (his only
tournament point) with 27 seconds left and the US cage empty.
</P>
<P>
   Then they routed the Czechs, 7-3, and suddenly, the award podium
seemed possible. ``We began thinking, hey, we could take a medal
out of this thing,'' says Dave Silk, who grew up in Scituate. ``But
none of us was so cavalier to think that it would beat the gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the loss at Squaw Valley, the Soviets had won the
gold at every Olympics since they first turned up in 1956. They
hadn't lost a game since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only team we were worried about was the Czechs,'' says
Fetisov. ``We weren't worried about anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Worry, in Russian, was a relative word. The Soviets had beaten
the Czechs, 11-1 and 6-1, at the 1979 world championships in
Moscow. In Lake Placid, they were running up fantastic numbers _
16-0 over Japan, 17-4 over the Netherlands, 8-1 over Poland. They
didn't need 60 minutes to beat you. The Soviets required only 60
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could score three goals in a minute and a half,'' says
Silk. ``They were deadly that way. Whenever the puck was in play,
there was danger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Finns had them on the ropes, down a goal with five minutes
to go. Then Krutov, Maltsev, and Mikhailov went bing-bing-bing in
79 seconds and it was 4-2 for the Soviets. The Canadians had them
down two goals in the final seconds of the second period and missed
a breakaway for three. The Soviets beat them, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   They may be winning, but the champs are off-form, Brooks told
his players. Bored, maybe. They'd won everything they could win.
``What do they have left?'' Brooks said. ``They're ripe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks could give the Big Red Machine a go _ if they ever got
to play them. After the Czech victory, the Americans seemed flat.
They had to rally to beat the Norwegians, a bunch of Oslo plumbers
and taxi drivers. They didn't shed the Romanians until midway
through the game. And they went two goals down to the Germans
before winning by two.
</P>
<P>
   But the Boys of Winter kept winning, somehow. And when they were
dressing for their medal-round date with the Soviets, they seemed
oddly relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had destroyed us before the Olympics,'' O'Callahan says.
``We knew they could kill us. So there was no need being tense
about it. We'd tried that two weeks before and it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans could never beat the Soviets in a best-of-three,
but they didn't have to. One night, one game, one chance. This is
no accident, Brooks told his players before they took the ice. This
was fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were born to be a player,'' he said. ``You were meant to
be here. This moment is yours.''
</P>
<P>
   This was no mere hockey game, the Americans realized, as soon as
they came out of their dressing room. It was, as Newsweek magazine
said, ``a morality play on ice.'' The Soviets were hooted at the
sight of their red helmets. The Americans were greeted like Daniel
Boone, Alvin York, John Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flags were everywhere and they weren't bought on the way
in,'' says Craig. ``They brought them out of attics and basements.
The patriotism at Lake Placid was real.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the gloom, the malaise, the anger, the frustration, the
helplessness that had been building for a year and more in America
had been given voice. People who didn't know whether a puck was
vulcanized or galvanized suddenly cared desperately about one
hockey game.
</P>
<P>
   Until they came through the gate in their red, white, and blue,
the US players hadn't sensed that. They had been sequestered in the
athletes' village out in Ray Brook for a fortnight, away from
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't read the papers,'' Eruzione says. ``We were in a
cocoon. We were clueless.''
</P>
<P>
   It was better that way, they concluded later. It was enough to
be playing against the best team in the world. Eruzione and his
mates didn't also need to be playing for truth, justice, and the
American Way.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to play out of your minds, Brooks told them. Just
play your game. It's been good enough so far. Stay poised, keep
possession and forecheck like hell.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets scored first, after nine minutes, but that was no
novelty. Everybody but the Romanians had scored first on the
Americans. Buzz Schneider, who had stung Tretiak for a hat trick at
the 1975 world championships, blasted a slapshot past him five
minutes later to tie it.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets grabbed the lead back within four minutes and set up
shop in the US end, peppering Craig with rubber. Then, one second
from the end of the first period, came the turning point. Dave
Christian had taken a long, what-the-hell slapper that bounced
harmlessly off Tretiak's pads. But Mark Johnson (``Magic'' to his
teammates) darted between a pair of Soviet defensemen and wristed
in the rebound just before the buzzer. 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets, who were already on their way to the locker room
and their intermission tea, didn't want to be bothered with a
meaningless faceoff. ``Drop the puck,'' O'Callahan shouted to the
referee, hoping that his teammates could get a gift goal into an
empty net. No such luck.
</P>
<P>
   The officials beckoned to coach Viktor Tikhonov to send out at
least a token group to take the draw. Instead of Tretiak, he
dispatched Vladimir Myshkin, the backup goalie. ``Does that mean
Tretiak can't come back?'' Eruzione asked Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knew what it meant. The Americans had heard that Tretiak,
arguably the world's best goaltender, had hurt his glove hand
before the game. Not so, Fetisov insists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no problem,'' Fetisov says. ``He was healthy. I think
the coach was a little bit panicking. Or maybe he was trying to
kill two birds with one arrow.''
</P>
<P>
   By yanking Tretiak, who considered himself indispensable,
Tikhonov might have been sending an intramural message. Myshkin,
after all, had shut out the NHL. The Americans, meanwhile, had
deciphered a message of their own. ``It was, `Hey, guys, we're not
playing very well and it's 2-2,' '' says Eruzione.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
