<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4640 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-MIRACLE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     02-22 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MIRACLE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... says Eruzione.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even after Maltsev put the Soviets ahead again on the power play
barely two minutes into the second period, their hosts sensed it
was a different game, a different night this time. The Americans
had been behind, 6-0, at Madison Square Garden. ``This thing's
special,'' Silk mused. ``This could be one of those nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Silk had been a fourth-line wing when the Games began.
Then he scored the first goal against the Swedes ``and it elevated
me.'' So Brooks had moved him to the first line with the aces and
was using him on the power play. Now, with the Americans a man up
with a dozen minutes to play, here came Silk down the left side,
looking to flip the puck over to Johnson before Vasiliev leveled
him.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, the red light was on. The puck had bounced off
defenseman Sergei Starikov's skate and onto the stick of Johnson,
who wristed a shot between Myshkin's legs from 5 feet away. It was
``the goal from nowhere'' and now, anything seemed possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were staying stride for stride with the Soviets,
banging and bollixing them. Now the ``Conehead Line'' _ Schneider,
Mark Pavelich, and John Harrington from the Iron Range _ was coming
up ice and Schneider, out of gas, was lifting his stick to come off
early.
</P>
<P>
   Over the dasher came Eruzione, just in time to collect a pass
from Pavelich, who was whacked in the corner just as he let it go.
Eruzione saw defenseman Vasily Pervukhin go to one knee to block
his shot, used the screen to wrist a 25-footer past Myshkin's
stick, and went dancing and screaming into the corner.
</P>
<P>
   The man who was almost cut a few months before the Games, the
man who wasn't supposed to be on the ice, had put his mates within
reach of the most astounding upset in hockey history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if I want to be real deep about it, I could think it was
destiny,'' Eruzione says. ``It was my time to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   All he and his teammates had to do now was shut down the world's
most prolific scoring machine for half a period.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can still score,'' Brooks reminded his charges as the
clock ticked down. ``They can score plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Finns had had the Soviets down with half as much time left
and lost by two goals. Ten minutes was half a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, if we need one goal we can get one goal,'' says
Fetisov. ``If we need two goals, we can get two.''
</P>
<P>
   Krutov thought he had one, but chinked the post _ and Maltsev
missed the rebound. Vladimir Golikov drove a shot off Craig's pads.
``If we're gonna lose, it's gonna be a good goal,'' Craig vowed to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes left now and Craig's mates were playing kamikaze
hockey, hurling themselves into the corners, dropping in front of
slapshots, happily taking pucks off legs and chests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do anything to win,'' thought O'Callahan. ``And they
won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks was rotating all four lines now, clocking the shifts with
a stopwatch. Tikhonov was staying with his gold-medal vets, the
Mikhailovs and Kharlamovs. ``What's going on?'' Petrov muttered
after seeing three US different faces across from him on the same
shift.
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes remaining, then three, then two, each one seeming
like five to the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd skate your shift and come back and look up at the
scoreboard and say, `They forgot to turn on the clock,' '' recalls
O'Callahan. ``You got so you didn't want to look at the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig kept screaming to his defensemen not to tie up the puck,
urging them to keep play going and the clock ticking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want the Soviets to get settled and set something
up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, everyone thought Tikhonov would pull Myshkin and
the Soviets would be skating six on five. But he never did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it,'' Brooks thought with 30 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty seconds now, with the Americans moving the puck around,
playing keepaway. ``We're going to win,'' wing Eric Strobel told
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe in miracles?'' ABC announcer Al Michaels asked
the nation, which was watching on tape delay because the
international federation refused to change the 5:30 p.m. start.
``Yes,'' he shouted, as the buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   Bedlam on the ice. Five teammates mobbed Craig, who had made 36
saves. The bench came dashing onto the ice, hugging anyone in a
white jersey. O'Callahan found Mike Ramsey, the 19-year-old
defenseman from Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was coming at me with his arms in the air,'' recalls
O'Callahan, who'd feared he'd never play after the Soviets caved in
his knee in the pre-Games tuneup in New York. ``He jumped on me and
I jumped on him and we just rolled around a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Then O'Callahan and Craig and Eruzione and Silk, the BU quartet,
went off to the side for a group hug. It was the Beanpot gone
global. Meanwhile, the vanquished champions waited patiently on
their blue line, stunned. They had never had a clock run out on
them at Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shock for everybody,'' remembers Fetisov. ``I knew we were
going to score a goal, even in the last second.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Soviets seemed amused, too, watching the star-spangled
celebration. Look at those wild kids, their expressions said.
``Nice game,'' Mikhailov told Johnson in the doping room.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the locker room, after President Carter had called
Brooks to congratulate him, the players began singing ``God Bless
America,'' until they realized they didn't know the words. So they
hummed instead.
</P>
<P>
   Within seconds, the result went around the world. The US
aircraft carrier Nimitz, cruising in the Mediterranean, flashed the
score to a nearby Soviet intelligence vessel. Above the Indian
Ocean, after American fighter jets had intercepted them near the
aircraft carrier Coral Sea, two Soviet pilots switched on their
radios. ``Congratulations,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `WE WON!'' headlines read across America the next morning. But
the players knew they'd won nothing yet. If they lost to the Finns
by two goals and the Soviets and Swedes tied, they would leave
without a medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not good enough for all this attention,'' Brooks told
them the next day, when he saw them scribbling autographs before
the workout. ``You're too young to win this thing. You haven't got
the talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Brooks skated them into the floor. ``He was yelling and
screaming at us,'' Eruzione recalls. ``I thought, what's he so
pissed off about? We just beat the Soviets. Then I realized he had
to bring us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't blow it, Brooks warned his squad Sunday morning, just
before the faceoff. You've been together too long and come too far
for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our last 60 minutes,'' he said. ``Our last will be our
best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans fell behind, as usual. They tied it up and fell
behind again. After two periods, the Finns led, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty minutes, gentlemen,'' Brooks told his players in the
locker room. ``If it's not 20, you'll never live it down. This will
haunt you the rest of your lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Phil Verchota, the burly teddy-bear forward from Duluth,
stood up. ``There's no (expletive) way the Finns are taking this
away from us,'' O'Callahan remembers him saying.
</P>
<P>
   No way, the Americans kept telling themselves when they returned
to the ice. No way. Verchota tied it up within three minutes, Rob
McClanahan scored the winner three minutes later and Johnson added
the coup de grace four minutes from the end.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much receiving the gold medals from Lord Killanin
that made the miracle real, Silk says. It was seeing the American
flag go up. Then Eruzione, who was on the podium as captain,
beckoned everyone else to join him. Twenty medals, one team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get in early,'' Brooks ordered his champions, who were due at
the White House the next morning. ``I'm not taking a bunch of
drunken hockey players to see the President of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   They were heroes now, deluged with telegrams and phone calls and
parades and luncheons and interviews and endorsement offers and
marriage proposals. All but Eruzione went on to play hockey
somewhere else. All are retired now. But two decades later, the
Boys of Winter are still playing one game _ and always will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still running into people who talk about it, who tell me
where they were when we beat the Russians,'' marvels Eruzione, who
still lives in Winthrop, Mass, just outside of Boston. ``It's like
Pearl Harbor and the Kennedy assassination and the Challenger. But
those were terrible tragedies. Ours was a hockey game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
