<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4643 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-INTERNET-TAX-BOS &LR;      02-22 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX DEBATE GROWS AS NET BOOM ROLLS ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER AND STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-commerce continues to boom as more consumers than ever click
on the ``buy'' buttons at Amazon.com and other online shops. But an
unresolved issue hangs over the emerging online marketplace:
whether cyberpurchases should be subject to the same sales taxes
levied on brick-and-mortar retailing.
</P>
<P>
   While a congressional commission has been examining the question
and hopes to issue recommendations this year, any chance of
reaching consensus in 2000 seems remote given the wide range of
views on how sales taxes would affect e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The basic positions on sales taxes are clear: Opponents fear a
tax would dramatically slow the spread of e-commerce, just as it is
on the verge of gaining a secure foothold among consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the increased acceptance of online retailing
could potentially produce sales-tax numbers that are too large to
ignore. And they say ``e-tailers'' will have a competitive
advantage over regular retailers unless they are also required to
collect sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Between these two poles, there is an array of opinions and
alliances, but even those whose allegiances are clearly on the side
of protecting e-commerce think sales taxes in some form are
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to see how the tax system would withstand the
Internet being tax-free,'' said Shikhar Ghosh, head of iBelong Inc.
and chair of the Massachusetts Software and Internet Council.
</P>
<P>
   For now, a federal moratorium on new Internet taxes is in place
at least through October 2001, with the result that the states are
becoming the battleground on the sales-tax issue.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, legislators plan to study how much sales-tax
revenue the state is losing on orders residents place over the Web.
Representative John H. Rogers (D-Norwood), cochair of the taxation
committee, said that the risk of doing nothing could be that ``this
technology would gradually make the sales tax obsolete'' as
ever-more shopping and purchasing moves online.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said a subcommittee will be formed to study the tax issue
in coming months, though an aide to Senator Marian Walsh, the other
cochair, said no action is expected before 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The mere formation of the subcommittee is controversial. Last
year, Governor Paul Cellucci, a staunch opponent of Internet sales
taxes, vetoed a budget item that would have created a commission to
study e-commerce taxes. Cellucci testified recently before Congress
against sales taxes, and on Wednesday he will take his antitax
message to a technology luncheon in Newton, appearing with Virgina
Governor James Gilmore, another sales-tax opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore, who also chairs the federal Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce that is studying Internet tax issues, faces
bills in the Virginia General Assembly to eliminate retail sales
taxes, on the grounds that if online retailers don't have to
collect a sales tax, neither should brick-and-mortar merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore said the bills are simply political posturing and have
no real chance of passing. Despite the ongoing debate, he believes
the federal moratorium on sales taxes could be extended several
years while the issue continues to be sorted out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a desire right now for a continued moratorium,''
Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   It is an open question whether the states are bound by the
moratorium, but so far most are following the federal government's
lead.
</P>
<P>
   In response, some state and local officials have argued that
they may be forced to raise other taxes to make up for lost revenue
if the emerging online marketplace continues to grow. Sales taxes
accounted for $3.3 billion of the $14.2 billion in taxes
Massachusetts collected last year.
</P>
<P>
   But these leaders have run into resistance from governors who
want to protect the booming technology sectors that have boosted
their states' economies.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lines have grown fuzzier _ and thornier _ over time.
Conservative Republicans are battling conservative Republicans.
Retailers are duking it out with retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Even traditional merchants aren't always on the same side.
Federated Department Stores Inc., an old-line merchant that has
planted solid roots online with macys.com, is conspicuously absent
from the parade of traditional merchants complaining that their
online rivals are being pampered.
</P>
<P>
   Technology firms also have developed different positions on the
tax issue. Internet gateways America Online Inc. and Lycos Inc. are
staunchly opposed to Internet commerce taxes. But a few high-tech
companies have said they would support some online taxes if the
tens of thousands of local and state tax systems _ each with its
own different regulations _ were somehow simplified.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over taxing so-called ``remote'' sellers such as
eToys Inc. is hardly new. The issue first emerged following the
explosion in catalog sales. It resurfaced several years ago when
tax collectors nationwide began suspecting that the online
marketplace would grow much, much larger.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Internet retail sales are fast gaining ground on catalog
sales. The Direct Marketing Association says online sales will
reach $31.1 billion in 2004 compared with $75.5 billion in catalog
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe Internet revenue will surpass catalog revenue by
2004. By then, Forrester Research estimates, online sales
nationwide could reach $184 billion, up from $20 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet and catalog transactions are already subject to
state sales taxes. But they go largely unpaid because most of these
retailers aren't required to collect those taxes unless they
actually have operations in the state where the purchase is made.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, consumers are supposd to be reporting their sales tax
obligations on many of their catalog and online purchases. But
these rules are rarely enforced by the states where they are in
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers have been further baffled by retailers' decisions to
tax or not to tax. Nordstrom Inc., for instance, charges online
sales taxes in states where it operates department stores. A Web
site co-owned by Barnes &AMP; Noble does not have widespread taxes
because the retailer considers its online store to be a separate
division. Also giving most consumers a tax-free shopping experience
are a host of retailers who exist only in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   On its own, Staples Inc. has figured out a way to collect sales
taxes from electronic customers in each of the 44 states in which
it operates retail stores. It wants its online rivals to figure it
out, too.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the company is looking for ``any state initiative
that levels the playing field,'' said Shannon Lapierre, a Staples
spokeswoman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
