<HEADLINE>
MORE HONEYMOON HORRORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether it's cow flop or cackling chickens, the unexpected can
get in the way of honeymoon bliss. Here are more terror tales from
entrants in Thrifty Car Rentals' sixth annual Honeymoon Disasters
Contest:
</P>
<P>
   --Alie and Ray Randlett of Cape Coral, Fla., decided to reenact
a love scene from a classic TV commercial by running through a
field of wildflowers in Virginia _ and ended up tromping through
cow patties. They also decided to jog along a mountain trail, but
the rains came, leaving them ankle deep in a rushing stream. Did we
mention the early-morning fire at their hotel?
</P>
<P>
   --Nancy and Paul Jack Davis of Phoenix were married secretly,
then ran off to a backwoods cabin to escape the bride's unhappy
family. But her dad and his cohorts found them, socked the groom in
the face, and dragged the bride off. A car chase followed, with the
groom ending up spending the weekend in jail. But love won out.
</P>
<P>
   --Ann Porter and Don Williamson of Tallahassee were going
camping in Montana, so they stored fuel in their backpacks, which
they brought aboard their plane. That fuel leaked from the overhead
bin, necessitating an emergency landing and a visit from the
hazardous materials crew. Add to that a $1,700 fine from the
Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   --Kristi and Robert Macarelli of Fort Myers, Fla., suffered
severe sunburn, had their luggage ransacked, shared a bus with live
chickens, were bumped from three flights, and endured unending
rain, insulting cabbies, and snakes. They got seasick on a cruise,
and on the plane home a fellow passenger suffered a heart attack.
And those are just the highlights _ make that lowlights.
</P>
<P>
   (If you'd like to enter the next Honeymoon Horrors contest for a
chance at winning a more sedate honeymoon, or just read more
disastrous stories, log on to www.thrifty.com and visit the
``Promotions'' section.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: On what Hawaiian island will you find the
southernmost point in the United States? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Hawaii is probably the best place to find the perfect
beach. It has the best beaches in the United States'' _ Stephen
Leatherman, a University of Maryland geology professor whose
extensive rating system for beaches has earned him the title Dr.
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a name: The town of Kamuela on the Big Island of Hawaii was
named for rancher Samuel Parker. ``Kamuela'' is the Hawaiian
approximation of Samuel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today's loopy law: Hawaii forbids placing coins in one's ears.
(With thanks to www.dumblaws.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's a lotta rain: The rain-forest mountain in the center of
the Hawaiian island of Kauai gets 460 inches of rain a year. That,
on average, is the rainiest place on earth. (With thanks to
www.daytips.com, via faithful contributor Mike Schuster of
Foxborough.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you guess it? On the Big Island of Hawaii. It's called South
Point.
</P>
