<HEADLINE>
BOSTON: IT'S CRUISE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's going to be a great cruise season for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   With 122 ship calls this season, business at the Black Falcon
Cruise Terminal has increased nearly tenfold since 1985 when only
13 ships called.
</P>
<P>
   The best news, though, is the number of ships that will depart
Boston on cruises to Canada, Bermuda, New England ports, England,
and nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Heading the list is the Norwegian Majesty's 27 weekly cruises to
Bermuda. Carnival Cruise Line's Carnival Destiny will offer two
four-day voyages, May 22 and 29, calling on Halifax, Nova Scotia,
and St. John, New Brunswick; and a three-day cruise, leaving May
26, to St. John. Premier Cruise Line is bringing in two ships: the
Seabreeze and the Big Red Boat. The Seabreeze will offer 36
embarkations alternating two-night cruises to nowhere and
five-night cruises to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Red Boat will only be calling on Boston during its New
England/Canada cruises out of New York. Premier soon will have four
Big Red Boats sailing out of New York, Florida, California, and
.....
</P>
<P>
   The Queen Elizabeth 2 will offer trans-Atlanic service from
Boston with four six-day cruises to Southampton, England, leaving
May 11, June 6, and Sept. 4 and 24. The QE2 recently underwent a
major renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean's Splendor of the Seas will make four
embarkations this fall on its New England/Canada itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Silverseas Cruise Line's Silver Wind arrives in Boston from
Dublin Sept. 22 for a Sept. 23 embarkation to New England/Canada
ports. The line's newest ship, the Silver Shadow, will visit Oct.
13.
</P>
<P>
   The 122 visits are expected to bring more than 200,000 cruise
ship passengers through the Black Falcon terminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cruise ship industry will bring jobs and increased
economic opportunity to the Boston area,'' said Virginia
Buckingham, Massachusetts Port Authority executive director.
Massport is now investing $10 million to expand and modernize the
terminal, added new gangways to accommodate larger ships (the
Destiny is one of the world's largest), and improving ticketing,
waiting, and baggage areas. ``This season alone we have 18 dates
with multiple embarkations,'' said Michael Leone, port director. On
Sept. 24, Black Falcon will have three embarkations _ the QE2,
Norwegian Majesty, and Seabreeze.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Health check &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported that Clipper Cruise Line's
102-passenger Nantucket Clipper voluntarily shut down in St. Thomas
because of the flu. The paper said that, according to Dave Forney
of the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, approximately
half the ship's passengers had become sick on two successive
cruises. (The CDC, which monitors conditions aboard ships that call
at American ports, becomes concerned when 4 percent of passengers
become ill, the report said).
</P>
<P>
   Following an inspection by epidemiologists, the ship has resumed
sailings.
</P>
<P>
   If you are concerned about a cruise ship's sanitation, call the
CDC's International Travelers Information line at 404-639-2573 or
visit www.cdc.gov/travel/cruiships.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skipper your boat &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelers looking for a different way to see Europe might
consider a Crown Blue Line cruise that allows them to be captain of
their own boat as they travel the waterways of Germany, France,
Ireland, Holland, and the line's newest destinations, Italy and
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   The line offers more than 500 self-skippered vessels, allowing
travelers to experience the character and charm of some of Europe's
most picturesque regions.
</P>
<P>
   Weekly prices begin at about $500 a person. For example, in
France, the four-person Tamarisi starts at $1,960 a week in low
season, and the luxurious 10-person Grand Classique is $4,980 per
week during July and August. Prices include fuel, a damage waiver,
Value Added Tax, and canal tolls.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call Crown Blue Line at 888-355-9491 or visit
www.crown-blueline.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Savings for 50 plus &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saga Holidays is offering travelers 50 and older deep discounts
on two ``Cruise and Stay'' holidays aboard the Saga Rose, the only
ship devoted to passengers 50 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at less than $80 a day, travelers can sail on the
69-night trip from Sydney, Australia, to Southampton, England, or
the 51-night trip from Beijing to Southampton.
</P>
<P>
   The 69-day cruise from Sydney includes a four-night stay in
Sydney's Darling Harbor. The cruise from China begins with an
eight-night stay in the Forbidden City of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly the cruise of a lifetime,'' said Frank Anthony,
president of the Boston-based Saga Holidays. ``And at these lower
rates, we're making it easier than ever for this dream to become a
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   For information, call 800-952-9590 or visit
www.sagaholidays.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Coastal sailings &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian Coastal Voyage is offering savings of $90 to $220
to passengers 67 and older on the 1,250-mile trip along Norway's
spectacular west coast. The 11-ship fleet sails daily year round
between Bergen in the south and Kirkenes in the north, above the
Arctic Circle. More than half the ships have been built since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Senior savings are available except from June 1 to July 15.
Fares, with the savings, begin at $1,075 a person.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian Coastal Voyage has been operating since 1893, its
ships doubling as cargo vessels and local transportation for
Norwegians. The ships call at 34 fishing villages, towns, and
cities, pausing only briefly at some places to pick up and unload
goods, and at others long enough for sightseeing and shopping.
Ports visited at night on the northbound voyage are called on in
the daytime during the southbound trip.
</P>
<P>
   For a brochure, call 800-666-2374. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foliage cruises &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may seem a bit early to think of foliage, but to see the
colorful scene from a riverboat, book now; these sailings sell out
fast.
</P>
<P>
   The authenic steam paddlewheelers Delta Queen, Mississippi
Queen, and American Queen will offer 14 foliage cruises leaving
from ports such as St. Louis, Cincinnati, and Nashville.
Itineraries range from three to seven nights. As with all cruises,
travel agents have details, or call the Delta Queen Steamboat Co.
at 800-543-1949.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whale watches &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Hawaii Cruises' seven-night ``Whales in the Wild''
Hawaiian cruises have become so popular that the line is now taking
requests for sailings next year from Maui each Saturday from Jan. 6
through March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers who book a cruise with a deposit at least six months
in advance can save $300 per person off the cruise fare, or can
purchase round-trip air fare (from 60 US cities) for $395 a person
(some restrictions apply).
</P>
<P>
   Each of the cruises aboard the SS Independence will visit five
ports on four islands. The first full day is spent at sea,
providing a close-up view of humpback whales.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free air &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holland America Line is offering free round-trip air fare from
New York on seven- and 14-day spring and summer sailings of the MS
Maasdam from Barcelona and Stockholm. The sailings begin at $1,599
a person (double occupancy) and include free air, port charges, and
taxes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Veterans' reunion &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A reunion of veterans who served in the Pacific islands is
planned for September. The 28-day voyage departs San Francisco
Sept. 24. The cruise begins at $4,795 a person and is not limited
to veterans. For information, write to Joan Irvine Travel, 1600
West Coast Highway, Newport Beach, CA 92663; or telephone
949-640-7402.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty discounts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new and innovative guest loyalty program for travelers who
sail on the six lines belonging to World's Leading Cruise Lines _
Carnival, Holland America, Windstar, Seabourn, Cunard, and Costa _
is now available.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called Vacation Interchange Privileges, provides
the same discount benefits accorded to members of each line's past
program.
</P>
<P>
   For example, guests who sail on Seabourn, Windstar, or Cunard
will not only have access to discounts offered through past-guest
programs of the Seabourn Club, Windstar Foremast Club, and Cunard
World Club, but also savings available through any of the six WLCL
member lines' repeat-passenger programs. All the cruise line
members of the WLCL are owned by Carnival.
</P>
<P>
   Savings of up to 50 percent are offered on select sailings of
Carnival, Costa, and Windstar. The discounts on Holland America are
up to 35 percent and those on Cunard, up to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the discount, a traveler simply books a cruise through any
travel agent, who then informs the cruise line reservations agent
of the past-guest status at the time of bookings and, with the
initial deposit, supplies proof of the prior WLCL cruise. Other
restrictions may apply.
</P>
<P>
   The World's Leading Cruise Lines has a Web site, www.
</P>
<P>
   leaderships.com, that provides information and a gateway to the
Web sites f the participating lines. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   World cruise &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Cruises has announced plans for its 2001 world cruise.
The Jan. 21 to April 27 sailing will boast more countries visited
than any previous Crystal cruise. The sixth world cruise of the
Crystal Symphony will visit 38 exotic ports of call in 31
countries, including rarely visited destinations in Southeast Asia,
India, the Middle East, Africa, and the Canary Islands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New canal boat &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Canal boating, long a favorite way to travel in France and
England, among other European countries, is coming to New England.
The Blackstone Valley Tourism Council's 40-foot canal boat, the
Samuel Slater, has arrived in Central Falls, R.I. The boat, built
in England to ensure authenticity, will be used for sightseeing and
overnight stays on the Blackstone River, which runs through the
Blackstone Valley region of Rhode Island and Massachusetts. Plans
are to use the boat for overnight stays at a cost of $125. The boat
is named for Samuel Slater, who began America's Industrial
Revolution at a mill in Pawtucket, R.I., that is now a museum to
that period.
</P>
<P>
   One of the country's earliest canals was along the Blackstone,
providing transportation of goods from the many mills that lined
its banks. The boat will not be sailing along the rivers of nearby
Providence because, according to a story in the Providence Journal,
those waters are considered navigable waterways, which under law
allow only US-built boats to carry cargo and passengers between US
destinations. The Blackstone is not considered a navigable
waterway.
</P>
<P>
   The council is seeking period furnishings for the boat, and
plans to put the vessel into service sometime this spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
