<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4648 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-PALM-PILOT-HNS &LR;      02-22 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALM-PILOT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PALM INTRODUCES ORGANIZER WITH COLOR SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT BEER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ever since the Palm Pilot was introduced in
1996, its fans have been hoping for a color screen. Now they have
it.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Inc., the spin-off division of 3Com that plans its own
initial public offering, unwrapped its Palm IIIc ('c' for color)
hand-held organizer on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The new Palm substantially raises the bar in the hand-held
computing world. The Palm already owns at least 70 percent of the
market against competitors Microsoft, Compaq, Hewlett-Packard and
others.
</P>
<P>
   The other hand-held color computers on the market, including
Compaq's Aero 2100, are heavy, the screens are somewhat dim, and
they're powered by Microsoft's Windows CE software, a woefully weak
platform when put up against the elegant, easy-to-use Palm OS.
</P>
<P>
   The new Palm IIIc beats the competition handily in both these
categories.
</P>
<P>
   The new device sports what is called an active matrix thin film
transistor display. It is the same kind of screen found in some
laptops. It is crisp, bright, and displays colors with as much
vibrancy as any laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Its color capabilities are driven by an internal lithium ion
battery. This power source is rechargeable through the included
desktop ``cradle,'' which also allows the Palm IIIc to be
synchronized with computer applications such as the Microsoft
Outlook or Palm's own personal information software.
</P>
<P>
   Palm is claiming the device will work for up to two weeks
between recharges, depending on how bright the screen is. If you
are on the road for longer periods of time, you may want to
consider the optional car/airplane or home charging cords. Or
simply pack the cradle.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm IIIc is packed in the classic III case. Apparently,
company engineers could not fit the battery needed for the color
display into the sleeker Palm V case. The battery also boosts the
weight of the Palm IIIc to 6.8 ounces, a smidgen over the Palm
III's 6 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good trade-off for the delight of having a bright, color
screen. There aren't that many color applications actually
available for the new color Palm. The device comes with a
backgammon and a full-color calculator. Considering the robust
40,000-plus developers' market for Palm software, you can expect
the color-based Palm software market to emerge simultaneously with
the IIIc.
</P>
<P>
   Also included with the Palm is the new Palm OS 3.5. It's a
tweaked version of the aforementioned operating system. Chief among
its new features are drop-down menus that appear with a title bar
tap, and a new view in the datebook which summarizes all
appointments and to-dos on one screen.
</P>
<P>
   There are some imperfections with the Palm IIIc: The screen is
nearly unreadable in bright light, a problem the gray-scale LCD
Palms don't have. You have to step into the shadows to see the
screen in those situations.
</P>
<P>
   And the price of this new Palm is a bit steep: $450 list, though
it is already being advertised at less than $400 on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   All-in-all, the new Palm IIIc is a more than worthy addition to
the Palm line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1400EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
