<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4649 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-STUDENTS-CITIZENSHIP-     02-22 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTS-CITIZENSHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES TARGET APATHY WITH INSTRUCTION IN CITIZENSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A professor tells of a college student who had volunteered, like
so many of his peers, in a soup kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   It was such a great experience, the student enthused, he hoped
his grandchildren would get the same opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   He did not seem to realize, the professor recalls with some
alarm, that this might be missing a point.
</P>
<P>
   When colleges began encouraging volunteerism a decade ago, it
was because they wanted students to become good citizens, to see
their responsibility for improving the nation's future.
</P>
<P>
   All they got, though, was good volunteers. Students are turning
out to build homes, tutor children, feed the poor, in record
numbers. But their voting participation rate is the lowest it has
been since 18-year-olds got the franchise. Discussion of politics
on campus, interest in social activism, and desire to ``be a
community leader'' have sunk.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the disconnect, higher education is taking a
more deliberate tack toward instruction in citizenship. The change
is not without critics, given how it departs from long-held notions
about what universities are and are not supposed to teach. But more
and more, college presidents are saying it is irresponsible for
higher education to default to apathy.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts leads the pack with the inauguration last month of its
University College of Citizenship and Public Service, which by 2002
will include courses across the catalog on everything from the
intricacies of political polling to the steps required to mount a
campaign for environmental cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Holyoke made the opening of its new Center for Leadership
and Public Advocacy the number one goal of its recent mission
statement. And over the past six months, scores of presidents
involved in Campus Compact, an organization founded in 1985 to try
to combat student apathy by encouraging community service, have
signed a pledge to increase voter registration on campus, engage in
their local communities, and create courses teaching ``the values
and skills of our democratic society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought that the way to get citizenship was to
just throw students out into service without challenging them to
think in a civic way, to think about the public issues that
underlie the very need for the service they're doing,'' said Rick
Battistoni, a political science professor at Providence College.
``A lot of service programs have worked hard to get students the
opportunity to do service, but they haven't challenged them to
think.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal, proponents of the curriculum say, is to make students
see the connection between, say, working in the soup kitchen and
understanding the conditions behind homelessness, being able to
evaluate policy changes that might alleviate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizenship has to become truly part of the fabric of the
university,'' said Tufts President John DiBiaggio. ``It doesn't
seem to me we can graduate students only with the ability to be
competitive for a job or admission to graduate or professional
school. We do that already. That's not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBiaggio, the head of Campus Compact, is such an enthusiastic
proponent of civic education that he is teaching the inaugural
seminar in the University College, a course called ``Leadership for
Active Citizenship'' that he sees as the first step ``to make
citizenship the defining signature strength of Tufts.''
</P>
<P>
   The first in an Italian immigrant family to go to college,
DiBiaggio recalled how the state of Michigan honored his father for
never failing to vote in any local, state, or national election.
Having left a country where elections didn't really mean choice,
the president recalled, his father got angry with anyone who had a
choice and didn't exercise it.
</P>
<P>
   These days, many students do not. While a record 75.3 percent of
college freshmen last fall did volunteer work in high school, only
15 percent of 18- to 24-year-olds voted in the 1998 election. This
year's annual freshmen survey by the University of Southern
California at Los Angeles found only 16.7 percent of students
interested in ``influencing the political structure,'' 26 percent
interested in keeping up with political affairs, and 28 percent in
``being a community leader.'' (By contrast, 73.4 percent of
students said they want to be well-off financially.)
</P>
<P>
   The Tufts trustees approved the University College in late 1998.
By 2002, it will include eight chaired professorships in each of
Tufts' schools, and offer a certificate program _ something less
than a minor _ for students who complete a certain number of
courses and service requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But the goal, DiBiaggio said, is to avoid making a separate
degree or specialty of citizenship and public service. Rather, in
the same way many schools have tried to include math or writing
``across the curriculum,'' the university wants to integrate
lessons of citizenship into courses in all departments. Ultimately,
officials say, it will be hard for any student to avoid exposure to
the how-to's of ``active citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This says this is critical enough, important enough, for us to
invest in,'' DiBiaggio said. ``We can say it's important, we can
have it as our vision statement, but this formalizes it. It's nice
to express a lot of platitudes, but it's another to convert it into
action.''
</P>
<P>
   The 50 students in his introductory course are an idealistic
lot. In their applications to be admitted to the class, they listed
experience working in community service projects in places like
Brownsville, Texas. One student said her goal was that ``every
child should have food or access to food.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBiaggio sees his task to take that inchoate idealism and turn
it into activism. He asks the students what makes a good leader. A
young woman in the front row quietly offers, ``To help change
others.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a dream, not a goal,'' DiBiaggio retorts. ``So, how are
you going to do it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To see that more people have opportunities?'' she offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just a dream, a wonderful dream,'' he says. ``But a
goal is something different. To address your dreams, that's why you
have goals, an action plan.''
</P>
<P>
   But to some other colleges, all the talk of teaching citizenship
sounds like a marketing gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   In their pitch to trustees, Tufts officials acknowledged the new
college will make the university more marketable among prospective
students, by defining a niche. They also say it will boost
fund-raising, and it has, with Democratic fund-raiser Alan
Solomont, a Tufts alumnus, leading the drive.
</P>
<P>
   And, as in the debate on teaching values, some question whether
you can teach, much less define, qualities like ``leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The probing analysis of these questions is why we have history
departments, women's studies departments, political science
departments,'' said Tom Gerety, president of Amherst College, who
still recounts his days as a campus activist at Yale. ``The
institution of protest is, I think, bogus, and instituting a
catechism of good citizenship is suspect. It exploits the deference
of our students to try to teach them these things. We should be
pushing them to be more challenging, but students have to find
their own way. And when they do, a goodly portion of them will be
sitting in my office calling me a bum.''
</P>
<P>
   Students in the Tufts course agree that you can't teach good
citizenship. But, said James Weinberg, a senior, ``You can teach
them ways to find an outlet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pose the questions,'' Battistoni agreed, ``I've found
young people really are interested in engaging with the larger
questions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
