<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO TRIAL ENTERS FINAL PHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Amadou Diallo trial is entering its final phase,
but the case surrounding it is not nearly over, nor are its
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo was the West African immigrant who, just over a year ago,
was gunned down by four white police officers who fired 41 bullets
as he stood, unarmed, in the doorway of his Bronx apartment
building.
</P>
<P>
   The killing unleashed pent-up racial tensions in this city, and
prompted weeks of protests against police abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers, who were members of the New York Police
Department's elite Street Crime Unit, were indicted on charges of
second-degree murder, the first time any officer here had been
charged with murder for something done while on the job.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after two weeks of testimony, many doubt that the
racially mixed jury will find the officers guilty. Certainly the
prosecutors have their doubts. Last week, they asked the judge to
let the jurors consider less serious charges, including
manslaughter and criminally negligent homicide. The judge agreed,
as did the officers' lawyers, with noticeable relief.
</P>
<P>
   While second-degree murder carries a jail term of 15 years to
life, manslaughter could result in as light a sentence as 18
months, while criminally negligent homicide can lead to mere
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Many took the move as a sign that the prosecutors
``overreached'' in seeking an indictment for murder. All along,
their lawyers have called the shooting ``a tragedy, not a crime,''
and last week the officers themselves _ Sean Carroll, Edward
McMellon, Richard Murphy, and Kenneth Boss _ finally took the stand
to tell their side of the story.
</P>
<P>
   They claimed Diallo was acting suspiciously in his doorway, and
that when they approached him, he pulled what they thought was a
gun from his pocket. One of them yelled ``Gun!'' and they all
fired. They also said Diallo was still standing, meaning he was
still seen as a threat, so they kept up the fire.
</P>
<P>
   After the smoke cleared, the officers said, they approached the
body and saw that the object Diallo had been grabbing was his
wallet, not a gun. They testified that they went into shock or
broke down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   One witness, called by the defense lawyers, confirmed she heard
an officer yell ``Gun!'' However, upon cross-examination, she also
testified that the police continued to fire after Diallo fell to
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers tried to discredit that part of her testimony,
noting she had earlier said Diallo stood during most of the
gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   However, a medical examiner, called by the prosecution,
testified that one bullet seemed to enter Diallo's foot and dart up
toward his knee, a trajectory suggesting shots were fired as Diallo
lay on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of this testimony, all of which was challenged,
lies in the two legal definitions for second-degree murder. One
involves an ``intent'' to commit murder, which does not fit this
case. The other involves a ``depraved indifference to life.'' The
prosecution argued, and will insist, again, in closing statements,
that by firing 41 bullets and continuing to fire after Diallo fell,
the officers displayed a ``depraved indifference'' to Diallo's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers think this is still far-fetched; that, however
trigger-happy or nervous or aggressive the officers may have been,
their behavior falls short of ``depraved.''
</P>
<P>
   In his instructions to the jury, Judge Joseph C. Teresi will say
citizens have the right to use force if they ``reasonably'' believe
it necessary to defend themselves. He will also say the law allows
police a particular benefit of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, director of the New York Civil Liberties Union,
who spoke at many of the protests against the officers last summer,
acknowledged in an interview last week, ``This kind of case is very
tough to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has been saying as much to several black leaders who
have been protesting during the trial, outside the Albany
courthouse, where the case was moved after a panel of judges ruled
that the officers could not get a fair trial in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privately, I think they see the point,'' Siegel said. ``But
publicly, they go back out there and say it's murder, pure and
simple.'' If the police are acquitted, or convicted of the lesser
crimes, Siegel said he thinks it may be necessary to ``walk the
streets'' to calm people's anger.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, who has been leading the protests from the
beginning, said Friday that demonstrations will continue if the
verdict falls short of murder, but he emphasized they will be
peaceful. ``We don't want Amadou's name tarnished with any
violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The major focus, he said, will be to push the US Justice
Department to bring a federal civil rights case against the four
officers. The lawyers for Diallo's parents will also file a civil
lawsuit against the city.
</P>
<P>
   There are several precedents for a federal case, notably in the
case of Los Angeles motorist Rodney King. A state court jury
acquitted the police officers who beat King on a highway, but
federal prosecutors later tried them for violating King's civil
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Questions also remain about the court order to move the trial to
Albany. Even if one accepts the argument that a Bronx jury could
not give white police a fair trial, and many do not accept that, it
seemed clear when the case began that the officers would request a
trial by judge.
</P>
<P>
   The judge chosen to hear the case was a black woman with a
liberal reputation. Sharpton and others suspect the case was moved
because the judge was black, another possible violation.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel regrets that the case was moved for another reason: ``If
the cops are acquitted,'' he said, ``it would have more legitimacy
in the community had that been decided by a local jury or by a
black judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, unless the upstate jury finds the officers guilty, he fears
that the doubts, distrust, and suspicion will linger, not only over
this case but between police and the city's citizens generally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
