<HEADER>
A4652 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-STARTUPS-COASTS-BOS &LR;      02-22 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARTUPS-COASTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX YEARS LATER, BOOK STILL IRKS MANY IN THE EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BERKELEY, Calif. _ There was a time when Silicon Valley and
Route 128 were mentioned in the same breath, as if the two regions
were exactly alike in their technological prowess, the only
difference being the weather.
</P>
<P>
   AnnaLee Saxenian, who grew up in Concord, Mass. and attended
graduate school in Berkeley, Calif. and Cambridge, Mass., knew
better. In 1991, she set out to prove what she intuitively knew _
that New England and Silicon Valley were fundamentally different in
their approaches to technology and that those differences would
lead one region to grow faster than the other.
</P>
<P>
   The results of her research were published in ``Regional
Advantage: Culture and Competition in Silicon Valley and Route
128.'' Though the book is now six years old, it still has the power
to evoke strong opinions and is frequently invoked in conversations
comparing the two regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people who would spit at the mention of her book,''
says Eric R. Giler, president and founder of Brooktrout Inc. in
Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, Saxenian's book traces the evolution of the two
regions and concludes that Boston was dominated by big companies
that were too rigid, closed, and hierarchical to adapt to
fast-changing technologies.
</P>
<P>
   As proof, Saxenian points to companies such as Digital Equipment
Corp., Data General Corp., and Wang Laboratories Inc., all of which
have withered. By contrast, Saxenian found Silicon Valley teeming
with smaller, fleet-footed companies that encouraged workers to
network, exchange ideas, and embrace risk.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed in Massachusetts since Saxenian published
her controversial book in 1994. The state is now home to hot
start-ups such as Akamai Technologies Inc. in Cambridge and
Sycamore Networks in Chelmsford, as well as fast-growing, large
companies such as EMC Corp. in Hopkinton.
</P>
<P>
   Software, the coin of the New Economy, is a vibrant industry in
Massachusetts, growing from 800 companies 10 years ago to more than
3,000 today. Saxenian's critics point out that her book chronicled
the decline of the area's hardware sector, without paying much heed
to the meteoric rise of the software sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``She missed the whole software revolution,'' says Joyce
Plotkin, president of the Massachusetts Software and Internet
Council. Plotkin pointed to a study released last July from the
Progressive Policy Institute in Boston that put Massachusetts at
the top of the list of states best positioned for innovation.
</P>
<P>
   But Saxenian, now 45, does not waver from her conclusions. In an
interview last Tuesday in her Berkeley home, she said: ``The
argument in `Regional Advantage' continues to apply. While Route
128 has been changing, it's a catch-up game now. The scale in
Silicon Valley is just much greater, and the infrastructure here is
far more developed. The center of gravity in terms of innovation is
still Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   That blunt, unapologetic stance may have earned Saxenian a
reputation in Massachusetts as the Camille Paglia of technology,
but Saxenian herself is surprisingly unassuming in appearance. With
her toothy grin, dark curly hair, and friendly, nervous manner, one
can easily mistake her for a graduate student.
</P>
<P>
   Saxenian began studying Silicon Valley in 1980 as a graduate
student at the University of California at Berkeley, where she is
now an associate professor. She was struck by how much people in
the region's semiconductor industry knew one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intuitively, I knew this place was different than what I had
grown up with around in Boston,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving her master's degree in regional planning at
Berkeley, she went to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology for
a doctorate in political science and began teaching at Berkeley in
1989, developing a reputation as an expert on Silicon Valley, just
as the region exploded in prominence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used Route 128 as a foil to contrast how one region was
following a model of big, vertically integrated companies, while
Silicon Valley was following a different model,'' Saxenian said.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the apparent hostility toward her book, technology
leaders in Boston agree that Route 128 needs to foster more Silicon
Valley-style tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California, Stanford University not only teaches students,
it provides a catalyst for people to network. Our universities here
need to take a much bigger role in doing that,'' says William J.
Warner, who founded Wildfire Communications Inc. in Lexington and
Avid Technology Inc. in Tewksbury.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, rare praise emerges from Saxenian's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard so many negative things about the book that I decided
to read it myself,'' Giler says. ``I found that the book is
completely accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can be
reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
