<SLUG> BC-INTERACTIVE-NET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVICE ADDS FACE VALUE TO INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If all the time we are spending on the Internet is turning us
into a nation of antisocial losers, as Stanford University
researchers reported last week, what about making our Internet
chatting something more like real human interaction?
</P>
<P>
   That's one big possibility for a newly launched version of a
service that allows you to see and hear people you are chatting
with on the Net, so you can have something a little more like a
face-to-face conversation thaembodied exchange of one-liners
in a chat room.
</P>
<P>
   The software, called CU-SeeMe World, developed at Cornell
University and licensed by White Pine Software of Nashua, has been
around for more than four years and now counts up to 4 million
users globally.
</P>
<P>
   What's new is that CU-SeeMe is quietly starting to offer a new
version of the system that can be quickly downloaded, for free,
from the Net instead of requiring you to spend $70 by mail order or
at CompUSA to install it in your machine.
</P>
<P>
   Through the cuseemeworld.com Web site, people who have paid $50
or $100 for a little camera to mount on top of their computer
monitor can set up video chat rooms ``on the fly.'' The idea of
giving it away is to attract more advertising to the site and spur
demand for premium versions of the service, including fully private
and lurker-proof chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Let's ignore the obvious possibilities for the Net's singles-bar
and trawling-for-sex chat rooms. What the new version of CU-SeeMe
makes eminently more doable are things like:
</P>
<P>
   --Sunday-afternoon conversations among far-flung family members
where you can see little Alice in her new dress and see how Uncle
Joe looks since he shaved off his nasty beard.
</P>
<P>
   --Nighttime get-togethers for eighth-grade girls plotting what
tomorrow's outfit must be.
</P>
<P>
   --A ``call'' to Grandma or to Dad on Army duty in Bosnia to show
how you are dressing your kid for Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one pervasive downside of Internet business has always
been the lack of contact with an actual human being,'' says Killko
Caballero, White Pine's president and chief executive. Everything
from call centers and help desks to chat rooms ``immediately become
more valuable entities with the enhancement of seeing who you are
talking to.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe adding some sexy technology could make talking to
family and friends more appealing for the 25 percent of hour-a-day
Internet users who, according to the Stanford study, admit they
spend less time talking to real people they know because they're
spending the time on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The new CU-SeeMe version is initially designed to support three
images at a time, but it can go up to 12 images at a time or more
or down to just one person for more face-to-face conversation.
While participating in a chat in the lower left corner, people can
click on a button to see the face of one of their chat
participants. They can also look up whatever information, or
fiction, fellow chatters offer about who they are. To avoid
cacophony and cross-talk, users can shut off the sound and just
enjoy text chatting.
</P>
<P>
   With three or more people on the screen, the pictures are not
necessarily terrific _ about the size of an image on a baseball
card. If you are using a 56k dial-up modem, expect to see some
choppiness in the video image, but with a broadband connection you
can see something as good as the 30-frames-per-second image quality
you would see on television. Broadband is also crucial to
supporting more than three people at a time in a visual chat.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more Americans get high-speed Net access _ nearly 14
million within four years _ using your computer as the videophone
that AT&AMP;T predicted in 1964 seems like an inescapable fad-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   Services like these are already making inroads at hundreds of
companies that use them as an alternative to scheduling
face-to-face meetings for far-flung employees. Microsoft, for
example, offers NetMeeting, often bundled with Windows, which
competes with a business-oriented product of White Pine's
MeetingPoint. Vocal Communications Ltd. of Fort Lee, N.J., which is
known mainly for voice calling over the Internet, offers a version
that can add video as well.
</P>
<P>
   Where White Pine thinks it has a big lead, for now, is in how
quickly and easily casual home users can try out its video
chatting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It enables you to be face to face with the click of a mouse,''
said Willy Wiegler, director and executive producer of CU-SeeMe
World. ``If you can get on the Net, you can use this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Peter J. Howe is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at howe(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
