<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4657 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CMGI-ENGAGE-ART-BOS &LR;      02-22 1567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-ENGAGE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ENGAGE TECHNOLOGIES: MATCHING ADS TO EYEBALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention the Internet company CMGI Inc., and people think first
of its sky-high stock price, or perhaps a string of glittering
acquisitions, such as the popular AltaVista Internet search
service. But for CMGI chief David Wetherell, the heart of the
business is Engage Technologies, Inc., a five-year-old firm that
has quietly collected a treasury of detailed information about
millions of Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think someday this will be the most valuable database in the
world,'' Wetherell said at CMGI's annual meeting last year.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Schaut, the man Wetherell chose to run Engage, puts it a
little differently: ``We're that secret sauce that allows CMGI to
do its thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Its thing'' is an effort to turn CMGI's huge Internet
investments into steady profits.
</P>
<P>
   Engage is vital to the plan. It exists to capture data on the
millions of visitors to CMGI's own sites, as well as to many other
Web locations. Using custom software, Engage figures out Web
surfers' tastes and interests. That information lets Engage target
them with advertising that's far more likely to attract eyeballs _
and dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most impressive thing about the Engage database is
what's not in it: personal information about Internet users. Engage
thinks it's found a way to reliably deliver personalized
information to Web surfers without knowing who they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no name and address data,'' Schaut says. ``There's no
e-mail address . . . no user-identifiable data.''
</P>
<P>
   This is made possible by the use of cookies _ little bits of
coded information that can be loaded onto a Web surfer's computer.
When you visit a particular Web site, such as Yahoo, the site's
computer can put a cookie onto your computer.
</P>
<P>
   And you can create a customized version of the Yahoo site, with
only those features you want to see. Whenever you return, the Yahoo
computer will read the cookie on your computer to recall the
features you asked for.
</P>
<P>
   All of this can be done without collecting any personal
information from the user. Cookies were invented to allow Web sites
to deliver personalized services without having to know anything
about the person.
</P>
<P>
   But cookies are used in a more controversial way by Emerge's
biggest rival, New York-based DoubleClick Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1996, DoubleClick also built its business plan around
anonymous tracking of Internet users. But late last year, it spent
$1.7 billion in stock to acquire Abacus Direct, which builds
databases of millions of names and addresses. The merged companies
have launched a program called Abacus Alliance, which will collect
names and addresses from Internet surfers. This data can be used to
target them for both online and postal advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Abacus Alliance has aroused a furor among groups concerned about
consumer privacy, though. A California woman has sued DoubleClick,
alleging it misappropriated personal information. The Federal Trade
Commission and Michigan's attorney general have launched
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Engage figures to avoid this sort of controversy _ and attract
customers who don't want to be accused of invading their customers'
privacy _ by refusing to add personal information to its database.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons it's so valuable is because it is
anonymous,'' says David Andonian, president of corporate
development at CMGI Inc., based in Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Engage has been toddling along quietly since 1995. That was when
Wetherell made the coup that launched him in the Internet business
_ the sale of an early Web browsing program to America Online for
$70 million. Much of that money went to establish CMGI's hugely
successful venture capital fund. But another chunk was used to
found Engage. The goal was to create a firm that would precisely
target Internet advertising to the most likely prospects, and to
measure the success of those ads.
</P>
<P>
   Only in July of 1999 did Engage begin selling its Engage
Knowledge profiling service. By then, the company had created a
network of popular Web sites where visitors receive cookies. Once
Engage attaches one of its cookies to someone's Web browser, the
company can track that person's travels to any other site in the
Engage network.
</P>
<P>
   The system tracks ``recency, frequency, and duration,'' says
Schaut. It determines how often a person visits, which pages on the
site he visits and how long he stays on those pages. A visitor to a
news site might spend most of his time reading news about the stock
market. This information is run through a sophisticated program
that assigns a numerical score to the user's interest in stocks,
and links it to the user's Engage Knowledge cookie. At least 35
million Internet surfers have been tracked by Engage, and each of
them has a profile that measures interest in 800 different
categories. ``We're selling a score,'' says Andonian, a set of
numbers that estimates your likely interests and tastes.
</P>
<P>
   This score is used to send targeted ads to the Web surfer. Visit
any Engage-linked Web site, and it'll use your cookie to look up an
anonymous but detailed personal profile. This profile determines
which ads you'll see.
</P>
<P>
   Show a customer an ad for a product that truly interests him and
it's much more likely he'll click on the ad for more information.
The number of these ``clickthroughs'' determines the price
advertisers are willing to pay Web sites, and anything that boosts
it is good news for both the site owner and the advertiser. Our
investor, for instance, may ignore most Web ads, but might start
clicking merrily away if he gets a steady stream of ads from
financial services firms.
</P>
<P>
   And this won't happen just when he's visiting a financial site.
Engage will display relevant ads, even when a Web user visits an
irrelevant Web site. For instance, a computer gaming Web site might
not seem the logical place for a financial-services ad. But Engage
might send just such an ad to our stock market watcher. Any Web
site that teams up with Engage will display ads based on visitor
profiles, no matter the purpose of the site itself.
</P>
<P>
   To make this part of the strategy work, Engage has built up a
network of Web sites that are visited by about 54 percent of
everybody on the Internet. These sites not only display ads sold
through Engage; they also provide more data that further enhances
the accuracy of the Engage Knowledge profiles. Every page you visit
on an Engage site provides the company with a little more
information about your tastes and interests.
</P>
<P>
   Engage recently paid $2.4 billion in stock to acquire two ad
network companies from its parent firm, CMGI. AdSmart and Flycast
sell advertising space on over 2,300 sites, ranging from big-name
sites such as Ameritrade and US News and World Report, to
lesser-known sites that serve small market niches. ``We like very
focused interest sites,'' Schaut says. ``That's good data.''
</P>
<P>
   Create Engage profiles of regular visitors to, say, a science
fiction site, and you'll likely have tapped into a group that'll be
interested in ads for the latest science fiction movies and TV
shows. But when our investment buff visits this site, he may still
get some financial services ads thrown in, because he brought his
Engage Knowledge profile with him.
</P>
<P>
   The entire Engage system seeks to develop a sort of virtuous
cycle. The more sites in the network, the more profiling data is
collected. The more data collected, the more accurate the profiles.
The more accurate the profiles, the more products purchased by
people viewing the ads, the more advertisers come knocking on
Engage's door, and the more sites want to join the network.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only about 500 customers have signed up for the Engage
service. But one of the early adopters, Philip Pennington,
president and chief executive of Image Networks Inc. in San
Antonio, Texas, is already in love. Image Networks sells ad space
on 13,000 sites and recently began using Engage's profiling data to
decide which sites should get which ads. ``We were able to see a 25
percent increase in the clickthrough rate in just a week,''
Pennington said.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the sort of response Schaut is counting on. He
sees Engage as a boon to thousands of small sites that can't sell
ad space in the traditional way because they attract relatively
small audiences. A leader like Yahoo can sell all the ad space it
wants. However, Schaut estimates that about 80 percent of ad space
on the Web goes unsold, because it's on less-popular sites.
</P>
<P>
   But because Engage aims its ads at the individual, not the Web
site, even the smallest sites can become viable advertising venues.
The Engage profiling system, says Schaut, ``gets the dollars
flowing where the eyeballs are going.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the dollars are barely trickling to Engage so far _ $8.3
million in sales for the quarter ended last December _ Engage has
attained a hefty share price, closing last Friday at $124 a share
on the Nasdaq exchange. Schaut and Wetherell, and quite a few
investors, are betting that the growth of the Internet will
eventually bring Engage and CMGI a torrent of profit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
