<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23     02-22 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Religion and our schools, again
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Cincinnati suburb of Blue Ash, the school board last week
overturned a two-year experiment that could have far-reaching
effects on schools everywhere. The board, faced with a lawsuit from
the American Civil Liberties Union, rescinded its two-year-old
policy of declaring their schools closed on two Jewish holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Through a smokescreen of absentee rate determination, the issue
decided was more about the separation of church and state; a
controversy that is nowhere near to closure and becoming more
complex with each day.
</P>
<P>
   What the suburban Ohio school board was doing _ as do so many
other school boards nationwide _ was closing the schools based on a
subterfuge. Calling them ``teacher work days'' or some derivative
thereof, the schools conveniently close on days of religious
holidays: Good Friday, Yom Kippur, etc.
</P>
<P>
   As others seek to impose prayer back into the public schools,
this decision would seem to widen the fracture. The area director
of the American Jewish Committee, in support of the decision,
asserted that schools should set their calendars for
administrative, not religious, reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Ohio school district, it appears, are many of Moslem,
Hindu and others non Judeo-Christian faiths. Shall ``teacher work
days'' be created for them as well? It gets a little clumsy.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming number of our school students are Christian;
the remainder are but small segments in the pie chart of religion
representation. Thus, it would appear to be academically
impractical to close schools for the holy days of those minorities.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea of how far the ACLU would have gone with its suit
had not the school board backed down but the challenge of Christmas
could have been on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the nation's constitutional foundation calling for a
separation of church and state, it doesn't live up to that. God can
be found on the dollar bill, in the Pledge of Allegiance and in
Christmas Day being declared a national holiday. Religious
movements want God back in the schools, as well.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mixed bag as to what the Ohio matter represents. The
original claim was that opening a school on a religious holy day
caused high absentee rates. In the school district that serves Blue
Ash, there was an average of 15 percent absenteeism on Jewish holy
days against a daily norm of 4 percent. That's what led to school
closing policy.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there were other minorities in the district that
felt excluded, they not getting their religious holidays off.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a school-age kid _ 1939-1951 _ schools did not close
either for Good Friday, Yom Kippur and varying religious holidays
other than Christmas week. If you were a practicing Catholic, you
simply took Good Friday off _ and the school understood. If you
were Jewish, you were absent on Jewish holy days and endured the
friendly chiding of Christian classmates who pronounced us lucky:
``Hey, you get your holidays off and Christmas, too. No fair!''
</P>
<P>
   Right! It wasn't fair but it was fun to go one-up on them.
</P>
<P>
   Today's environment is far more complicated. Closing the schools
on religious days, under any name other than religion, is
transparent. As minority religions continue to grow in the U.S.,
the need arises for inclusion as opposed to exclusion. To close the
schools for Jewish dates but not Moslem, or such, is wrong. Keep
them open and let the students (and their parents) determine the
breadth of their religious involvement.
</P>
<P>
   If the day is important to those of a particular faith, deal
with it the way it used to be: Take the day off but don't shut down
the entire school.
</P>
<P>
   This still doesn't explain Christmas Day, the dollar bill or the
Pledge of Allegiance but, as the unknown philosopher once warned
us: ``This is not a simple life, my friend, and there are no simple
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
