<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-22 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NECCO'S NUTTY WAR OF WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am sitting here with a Clark bar to my left and a Lewis &AMP;
Clark Bar to my right, conducting a taste test to determine what
has caused the otherwise nice people of the New England
Confectionery Company to act like unmitigated twits.
</P>
<P>
   And the answer may be in the chocolate. I take a bite of the
Clark bar _ brittle to the point of being unnatural, a relic of
times gone by. The butter crunch clings to my teeth.
</P>
<P>
   I take a bite of the Lewis &AMP; Clark Bar and immediately feel
myself ascending on the wings of angels, floating to a place so
creamy, chocolaty smooth that no mortal man has ever been there. I
am mesmerized by this cocoa concoction, struggling to keep my
clothes on in the presence of this wonderful bar.
</P>
<P>
   Ahem, some background: That's the New England Confectionery
Company, as in Necco, the nation's oldest candy manufacturer, which
still makes its namesake Necco wafers in its Cambridge, Mass.
plant. Last year, Necco bought the bankrupt Clark company, and with
it a candy bar that most chocolate aficionados believed had long
ago met with an unnoticed death.
</P>
<P>
   Time has not been kind to the Clark bar. The garish red wrapper
with the midnight blue lettering says stale, not fresh. The
Butterfinger has stolen its following. The Clark's coveted space
along the candy aisle has been squeezed out by what seems like nine
different variations of the M&AMP;M and Milky Way offerings, not to
mention Hershey bars so wide-ranging that one is even called the
Whatchamacallit.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, of the dozen markets I shopped Monday, not one carried
the Clark bar, including the convenience store adjacent to the
Necco manufacturing plant in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Now along comes Debbie Kruger of North Dakota to make matters
even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Kruger makes chocolate in the pharmacy on Main Street in Mandan
that she owns with her husband, Rusty _ a storefront complete with
an old-fashioned soda fountain and a collection of Coca-Cola
antiques.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, she began producing small batches of the
Lewis &AMP; Clark Bar, named for the adventurers who camped for the
winter of 1804-05 in her hometown, where there's now a Lewis &AMP;
Clark Bridge, a Lewis &AMP; Clark Street, and a Lewis &AMP; Clark School.
</P>
<P>
   Necco, flailing away without much notice in the much-heralded
chocolate wars, seemed to find an enemy it could defeat. So it went
after Kruger and her tiny Lindy Sue's Candies, firing off a letter
that threatened her with copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Necco executives and the lawyers who pull their
strings actually believe that the names of Meriwether Lewis and
William Clark, two of this nation's foremost explorers, fall within
the trademark of a candy bar that chocolate maker David Clark named
after himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very scared,'' Kruger says. ``I didn't want to go to
court and fight them because I didn't think I could win. They have
full-time lawyers. I couldn't afford a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for a moment, that the chocolate bars are nothing
alike. The Clark, in its most flattering portrayal, is butter
crunch, the Lewis &AMP; Clark a pure milk chocolate bar. The Clark is
covered by the aforementioned wrapper, the Lewis &AMP; Clark encased in
gold foil with a wrapper that depicts the explorers, two buffaloes,
and the Indian guide Sacagawea.
</P>
<P>
   So they talked on the telephone last week _ Kruger, Necco
president Domenic Antonellis, and North Dakota Senator Byron
Dorgan. Initially, Antonellis sounded apologetic, but when he
learned that Kruger was selling her bar all along the Lewis &AMP; Clark
trail, not just in North Dakota, he said he'd have to talk to his
lawyers again. The issue remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a big company muscling a small company,'' Dorgan
laments from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The entire episode is an embarrassing shame. Necco has always
been a proud, benevolent company, filled with characters like
Walter Marshall, who plans to retire soon from writing Valentine's
sayings on those candy hearts. But now the lawyers appear in firm
control, which is never good. Common sense is out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Necco fears that Kruger is plotting to sell the Lewis &AMP; Clark
name to Mars or Hershey _ a scenario that isn't so much unlikely as
absurd. Could it be they're really afraid that Kruger just makes a
better candy bar?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
