<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OLD _ AND FALSE _ TABOO ON PREPOSITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What kind of word should you never end a sentence with?
</P>
<P>
   Ha! you say _ a preposition, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Is that your final answer?
</P>
<P>
   Don't phone your local newspaper editor for help. Hostility
toward those terminal prepositions still runs strong among people
who not only aced sixth-grade grammar but went on to practice it
professionally. If you want to win the jackpot, consult your
sensible next-door neighbor, who hasn't thought about prepositions
since high school.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there's nothing wrong with a preposition at the end of
a sentence. What's more, those little last words are often not
prepositions at all, when you look closely. Yet editors tie
themselves in knots (and give writers fits) trying to get rid of
final prepositions.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary citizens apparently know better. Readers write to
complain about misuse of tenses, neglect of the subjunctive,
overuse of slang, and a thousand other ills the media are heir to,
but nobody's troubled, apparently, by late-breaking prepositions.
In fact, several correspondents have repeated the famous tale of
Winston Churchill's retort to someone's attempt to clean up a
sentence he had ended with a preposition: ``This is the kind of
bloody nonsense (or `arrant pedantry') up with which I will not
put.'' Others have sent variations on the sentence that aims for
the biggest pileup of terminal prepositions: ``What did you bring
that book that I don't want to be read to from up for?'' But the
mail has brought not a single protest about the final preposition.
</P>
<P>
   How did the people get so far ahead of the pros on this issue?
It's a mystery. Usage writers throughout the century have been
making fun of the fake ``rule'' about prepositions: In the 1926
edition of Modern English Usage, H. W. Fowler calls it a
``cherished superstition,'' and most usage guides since _
Bernstein's ``The Careful Writer'' (1965), Harper's usage
dictionary (1985), Oxford's Modern English Usage (1998) _ note that
constructions like ``Which shelf do the plates go on?'' and ``rules
to live by'' are good and idiomatic English.
</P>
<P>
   And Churchill's twist on put up with points to a larger issue:
Not all these little words are true prepositions. Many English
verbs, like those in its sister language, German, come in two
parts: When you put up string beans, run off with your sister's
boyfriend, drop in on a neighbor, buckle up or buckle down, you're
not using prepositions. Those are two-word verbs _ phrasal verbs,
they're sometimes called, or lexemes, in linguist lingo. But
they're units of meaning, not verbs with prepositions tacked on.
</P>
<P>
   The perpetrator of our prepositional muddle seems to be John
Dryden, the 17th-century English man of letters, who wrote in Latin
as well as English. Since prepositions can't come at the end of
Latin sentences, he probably reasoned, they shouldn't appear there
in English either. (Other scholars told us not to split
infinitives, on the same shaky grounds.) But unless you hope to
write prose like Dryden's _ and you probably don't _ there's no
reason to obey his syntactical strictures.
</P>
<P>
   Finish it off
</P>
<P>
   Bill Earls of Middletown, Conn., wrote last month to say he was
fed up with frisson and fin de siecle. Foreign words, to his ear,
are pretentious, meant mostly ``to establish the writer as a member
of an exclusive fraternity,'' and these two are among his least
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know whether frisson _ French for a shiver of excitement
or fear _ is headed for US citizenship. And fin de siecle still
means the end of the 19th century; it seems likely to fade as we
try to decide how to describe the end of the 20th. But I realized I
had probably added to Earls's distress with last week's column,
where I gave the number of Don Giovanni's conquests in Italian _
mille e tre _ instead of saying 1,003. Also, as Giovanni's many
fans know, that was just the tally in Spain; the Don had previously
done very well with the ladies of Italy, France, Germany, and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Pretentious and inaccurate, Earls is probably muttering. Still,
I hope he has some empathy for today's scribblers. Dryden's readers
would have understood every classical allusion and Latin catch
phrase; now, when so many smart and literate people have never
conjugated a Latin verb, a writer takes a risk even in offering a
simple mea culpa.
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
