<SLUG> BC-NO-CAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANDED IN MAINE WITHOUT A CAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHERMAN STATION, Maine _ Three years ago, her '84 Chevy gave its
final shudder and Ruby Perkins started to walk.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists have come to know her _ a blond-haired figure walking
the mile-and-a-half down Route 11 past barns and houses and scrubby
pine to the store, where she buys a carton of milk or a loaf of
bread, turns, and walks the mile-and-a-half home. Sometimes, she
bounces a grocery cart full of food the whole way along the road
shoulder. She has stopped being self-conscious about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk all the time,'' said Perkins, 33, a mother of two.
``People just look, and I say, `Hey, you do what you gotta do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though, the walking has taken on new proportions. Unable
to find a ride to her job training in Patten, 9 miles away, Perkins
sets out on foot every morning at 7:30, an hour-and-a-half before
she's due there, hoping someone will stop to pick her up. Most
often, someone does, which makes her think guiltily of her father,
who once said he would chop her thumbs off rather than see her
hitchhike.
</P>
<P>
   But she needs to get from one place to another. In rural Maine,
where public transportation is a concept as distant as the parking
meter, Perkins's dilemma is repeated daily by poor women who find
themselves stranded, unable to scrape up enough money to buy or
maintain cars. Pressed by welfare deadlines to seek employment
outside their homes, they are relying on bicycles, or squandering
their money on taxicabs, or walking for miles in the dead of
winter, or missing their appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how much I believe if we're talking about
employment we're really talking about transportation,'' said Jane
Gilbert, who, as human resources director for the Maine Department
of Transportation, has struggled to accommodate stranded women.
``When you're living in Macwahoc, Maine, unless you've got your own
car, you are sucking air. You don't have options.''
</P>
<P>
   North of Bangor, where distances between people begin to double
and triple, human life shapes itself around vehicles, and around
the lack of them. A generation ago, the stranded female was a
natural part of the social landscape; when Barbara Van Burgal moved
from Michigan to Van Buren, a small town on the Canadian border,
she was astonished to discover that while men were reliant on cars
and trucks, many of her female neighbors didn't even have a
driver's license _ and didn't want one. Lisa Daggett grew up in
Sherman, and remembers snow banks that climbed to the roofs of
houses, trapping women and children inside for days or weeks at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just an assumed way of life then,'' said Daggett, who
works at the Center for Women, Work and Community in Lewiston.
``Now I get a panic attack just thinking of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Maine, as in the rest of the country, new deadlines for
getting women off welfare have made the rural isolation a public
issue. In a 1997 survey of 112 Mainers who received Temporary Aid
for Needy Families, or TANF, 32 percent of respondents said they
could not work at a paid job because they could not get there, and
28 percent said they had gone without transportation for at least a
month over the past three years, according to the Maine Center for
Economic Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The same struggles are playing out in rural areas all over the
United States. After studying the problem, University of Iowa urban
planner Alan Peters concluded that money spent on job training for
poor people would be better spent buying them cars. Per capita
spending on transportation can run as low as $1.50 in rural areas
and as high as $300 in big cities, said Chris Bogren,
communications director at the Community Transport Association of
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to see in a city why you need to do this. There's
congestion, there's pollution. It's harder to see isolation,'' said
Bogren. ``I remember riding a bus in rural Missouri and sitting
next to a woman who said, `I left my house for the first time in
seven years when this bus started running.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's a familiar story to Nicole Martin, 21, who lives in a
70-foot trailer on Route 116, about 4 miles from the tiny downtown
of Medway, Maine. Even if she could afford a car _ a prospect so
outlandish to Martin that, thinking about it, she just laughs _ she
could not drive it because she does not have a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   So with snowbanks building up against the window sills, the
trailer's two rooms became her world: Friends occasionally drive
her 14 miles to the grocery store in Millinocket, but sometimes she
doesn't leave for weeks at a time, making her feel so ``ballistic''
that she blows off steam by playing Meat Loaf albums at full blast.
On her 21st birthday, she couldn't get a ride into town and
celebrated her first legal drink at the trailer's padded bar.
</P>
<P>
   But it was no mistake, coming here, she said. Some of the best
moments of her childhood were spent sitting on a hill with her
sister, as quiet as possible, waiting for moose to gather at a salt
pit. When she got pregnant with Garrett, who is now 18 months old,
she wanted to stay near her boyfriend and family. The $150 rent she
pays for her half of the trailer is as much as she can afford, and
transportation difficulties are just the price she has to pay.
</P>
<P>
   When she found out that a state welfare-to-work program required
her to attend job training in Millinocket every day, the news came
as a shock. She got a few rides from her roommate's sister-in-law,
Missy, until Missy's car broke down. Then she got a volunteer
driver, until the volunteer threw up her hands at driving 30 miles
out of her way every day. Finally, Martin acknowledged that she was
in a classic rural bind: Even after job training, the low-wage job
she could find in the countryside wouldn't pay for a car. Without a
car, she wouldn't be able to show up for that low-wage job. She's
packing up her baby and moving to Bangor.
</P>
<P>
   But she's already wondering when she can come back. ``Sometimes,
people who come from a country area want to stay in a country
area,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Women like Martin have been left behind as Maine reduced its
welfare rolls by 50 percent over the past eight years, and the
government is slowly assembling ``a patchwork quilt'' of
transportation options for isolated families, said Van Burgal, of
the state's Office of Family Independence, which provides support
services for families trying to get off state assistance. Van
Burgal's office will fund car repairs, reimburse for mileage, and
assist with insurance payments for families receiving TANF. And
Good Wheels, a new state program administered by Goodwill
Industries, has just begun to provide TANF recipients with
low-interest car loans and financial advice. Project director Ellen
Brangwynne said she hopes to supply poor families with 300 cars
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But state Senator Sharon Treat, a Gardiner Democrat who
sponsored a bill last year that would have created a committee to
study transportation and work patterns, said lawmakers are a long
way from seeing transportation as a service the state must provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough one to get other legislators to see as
important,'' said Treat. ``People thought, it's not food, it's not
medicine, it's not shelter. . . . There's a real fear of giving
something away for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Maine centers for Women, Work and Community, counselors
have begun to look at cars as the gateway to women's independence.
Last year, after their son died, a couple donated his car to the
organization, and administrators began to explore who among their
clients needed the car most.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, they had 20 applications from women in desperate
circumstances. In essays, the women explained how transportation
had come to dominate their lives: One woman in Waterville
hitchhiked with her elderly mother to chemotherapy sessions.
Another woman did all her shopping on a mountain bike. One woman in
Skowhegan was so reliant on her husband for transportation that she
couldn't begin to think of getting away from his beatings, said a
resource administrator, Wendy Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Poulin, 39, of Lisbon, a full-time college student and
single mother of two disabled children, ended up getting the car.
For four months after her 1985 Pontiac broke down, Poulin had to
drop out of classes and devote herself full time to the doctors'
appointments, grocery runs, and tasks that took half a day without
a car.
</P>
<P>
   The worst moments were so bad that she couldn't even think about
them until long after they were over. Late one night in November,
her heat went off, and she watched the needle on the thermostat
slide to 50, and then slide below it. She kept feeling her
children's faces for cold, and when their noses felt like they had
been playing outside, she called for help.
</P>
<P>
   She vows she won't ever be in that position again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pride comes into it,'' Poulin said. ``If I was this dependent
on someone before, then I damn sure don't want to be dependent
again. Then they have a huge piece of you, and when that's gone,
what are you left with?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
