<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-EGGERS-BOS &LR;      02-22 1677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-EGGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRENCHING TALE FOISTS STARDOM ON DAVE EGGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dave Eggers never had it in his head to become a
hot-new-thing literary-star, and now that he is one, he shows no
interest in taking to the role. He seems perpetually lackadaisical,
except when he's wryly bemused. He dresses shabbily, his Brooklyn
apartment is beyond unkempt, he wears a baseball cap to mash down
his Eraserhead hair (``I didn't have time to take a shower today,''
he says. ``Sorry.''), and he claims not even to own a copy of the
book that has made him suddenly famous.
</P>
<P>
   The book, published by Simon &AMP; Schuster, is called ``A
Heartbreaking Work of Staggering Genius,'' which sort of sums up
the sensibility involved here _ the fey irony that a) acknowledges
its pretentiousness, b) disarms criticism of its pretentiousness,
yet c) raises the possibility that, wait, maybe he's serious, maybe
the book really is all those things.
</P>
<P>
   Its subject-matter is no less disorienting than its title.
Almost a decade ago, when Eggers was 21, both his parents died of
cancer, within five weeks of each other, leaving him to look after
his 8-year-old brother, Toph. The book is about how they dealt with
it and how they pushed ahead with a life of joy, heartbreak, love,
bitterness, freedom, frustration _ all the usual stuff of life _ in
the aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   One hesitates before such a book. It could be maudlin. Since
much of it is ironic and self-indulgent and funny, it could be a
bit sicko. Eggers skates right up to the edge of these cliffs _
sometimes sails right over the top, plunges into the abyss _ but,
mostly, amazingly, it works.
</P>
<P>
   Michiko Kakutani, a New York Times book critic who generally has
little patience for playful post-modernism, hailed the book as ``a
virtuosic piece of writing, a big, daring, manic-depressive stew of
a book that noisily announces the debut of a talented _ yes,
staggeringly talented _ new writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Out for just a few weeks, the book is already in its fifth
edition, with 100,000 copies in print. Last week, 400 fans crammed
into a Manhattan Barnes &AMP; Noble for an Eggers reading, more than
the store had ever seen for a reading, while 100 more were turned
away for lack of space.
</P>
<P>
   Even McSweeney's, the year-old literary quarterly that Eggers
edits out of his home _ ``which,'' he admits, ``couldn't be
weirder'' _ is selling out soon after hitting newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   He seems genuinely bewildered by the opened floodgates. ``I have
no idea what's going on,'' he says, flatly. ``I'm the last guy to
ask. I've never been one to write things that appeal to a lot of
people. If I have 10 to 12 people paying attention, then I'm happy
as a clam.'' He pauses. ``We just sold publishing rights to
Finland. There's no way of processing such things. The only thing
you can do is just keep talking with your high-school friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York tabloids report that he's turned down offers of $2
million for film-rights from New Line and Miramax. ``I don't know
where these things come from,'' he deadpans. ``I haven't heard
about anything like that.'' Still, he concedes, he has no desire to
see his most wrenching life stories beamed up on the silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of these people who say, `I'll try anything, to
see what will happen,' '' he says, slowly. ``I never thought that a
movie would be such a hot idea. But, then I started thinking, `Wow,
if they're throwing around that kind of money, that would make all
the McSweeney's dreams come true.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Already, his foreign-rights sales have allowed him to start
paying his writers for the first time, and to start a McSweeney's
book-publishing house. ``We want to publish a lot of books, with
extravagant production,'' he says. ``We'll pay the writers, give
them 100 percent of the profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he's warming to the idea of a movie, after all. ``If
it were done in a very strange way,'' he muses, ``if somebody took
it to the limits, made it a corollary work of art instead of a
straight adaptation, just took the book as a starting-off point,
yeah, I could get into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then his brow furrows a bit again. ``But the movie thing,'' he
mumbles. ``It might be so painful.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an author, after all, who has not even read his book
since finishing it. ``And I won't,'' he insists. ``There are five
or six parts of the book _ the rough ones to write, the raw, more
emotional parts _ I don't know what's on those pages.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a particularly affecting chapter in which Eggers
recounts finding, quite by accident, his mother's cremated remains.
``The part about the cremains,'' he says, using funeral-parlor
parlance, ``I wrote that once and that's it. I just barely got it
down once. I didn't look at it again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The book is full of literary high jinks. The preface begins,
``There is no overwhelming need to read the preface. . . If you
have already read the preface and wish you had not, we apologize.
We should have told you sooner.'' A 21-page acknowledgements
section acknowledges, spells out, analyzes, puffs up, and debunks
every narrative trick he's about to pull.
</P>
<P>
   This is old-hat stuff by now; it should be tedious. It shouldn't
work. It shouldn't be funny or moving, much less hilarious and
gripping. And yet it is. It's a gravity-defying circus act, this
book. Eggers somehow balances the elements by keeping everything
continuously off-balance. He creates _ and, more dazzling, sustains
_ a tension between the tears and the laughter, the grimness, and
the weirdness.
</P>
<P>
   Eggers is fully aware of the traps that he laid for himself and
managed to elude at every turn. ``It's all in the material and the
subject matter,'' he says. ``I wanted to keep playing with form,
but, as the story went along, it became harder. The events
overwhelm the gimmickry, they burst through, they wash all over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   These ``events'' evolved into an obsession. For over a year, he
wrote the book nearly every night, from midnight to 4 a.m., after
his brother had gone to bed. ``I don't know why an idea so silly
came to me,'' he says of the whole concept of writing about dead
parents. ``But I couldn't shake it.''
</P>
<P>
   To the extent he wrote it as a catharsis, it did the job. ``For
years, I couldn't see past it,'' he says. ``Now I can. I've never
tried to write fiction. Now I find I have all these ideas for short
stories and novels. I feel like I can do that now. I couldn't have,
before doing this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working on'' _ he pauses _ ``a novel kind of thing. It
used to be I didn't think I was born with the right to do that.
When I was writing this book, I felt it really had to hurt. I had
this strange belief that if you're writing about anything that
isn't 19th-century steamships _ if you're writing about your own
heart _ you might as well put it in the first person and tell the
truth, or else it's sort of cowardly. I was being a little silly
then. It's incredibly liberating just to make things up, and not
have to type the word `I.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Eggers grew up in Lake Forest, Ill., the deceptively trim
Chicago suburb where ``Ordinary People,'' that nightmare vision of
suburbia, was filmed. He and his friends, many of whom are still
friends today, ``worshipped Monty Python,'' he recalls. ``We knew
every line by heart. We did talent-show acts that consisted of
Monty Python routines. I wrote a column in the school newspaper
that tried to make as little sense as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his early 20s, he fell for the short stories of Lorrie Moore.
``I thought she was the be-all and end-all,'' he says. ``It's that
combination of her subject matter _ the entire heartbreak of the
situations _ and how funny she is. I had a little bit of a crush on
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he discovered the surreal whimsy of Donald Barthelme and
John Barth. ``They opened me up to a different thing,'' he says.
``They completely kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   His favorite contemporary writer is George Saunders, author of
``CivilWarLand in Bad Decline,'' because ``anything can happen in
any sentence and he's in complete control _ a monkey might pop up
and he might start talking, but you never feel it's improbable, he
has such an assured voice. And his stories have such heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Put all these influences together, and you have as apt a
description as any of Eggers's own prose style: silly strangeness,
humor, heartbreak, heart.
</P>
<P>
   Eggers is more self-consciously literary, more deliberate, than
his insouciance might suggest. Before he wrote his book, he drew a
gigantic chart, outlining its entire structure. (He reproduces part
of it on page xxxiii of the acknowledgements, and notes that you
can order the full version for $5. ``You will not be
disappointed,'' he writes. ``Unless you are usually disappointed,
in which case this will be yet another disappointment.'')
</P>
<P>
   When writing, he used a word-processing program that let him see
how his prose would look in a book. ``I had to see it in the right
font,'' he says. ``I had to see how the paragraph breaks looked,
with the margins a certain way. I'm really reluctant to write for
something where I don't control the design.''
</P>
<P>
   He still lives with his brother, who is now 17, and whose
privacy Eggers avidly protects. There are two older siblings, a
brother and sister, but they took it for granted that Dave would
take custody. ``Toph and I had been inseparable since he was born,
we were completely attached,'' he says. ``None of us could imagine
its working any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   He hangs out with a few friends who make up a growing gang of
experimental writers in Brooklyn, many of whom he publishes in
McSweeney's. ``As long as we can play with the form of it and push
it _ and the next one we're pushing into the fourth dimension, and
that's all I can say right now'' _ he laughs _ ``as long as there
are experiments to do, we'll keep doing it. We just want to bring
odd, beautiful things into the world. It's just sort of fun to
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
