<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-CUCKOO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOOD TIME WITH `CUCKOO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At first, Arthur Laurents's ``The Time of the
Cuckoo'' seems like an odd play to revive. You might start out
wondering why a play that had received what some consider its
perfect incarnation as the David Lean film ``Summertime'' is doing
back on the stage, but then you realize it works much better
without all the distractions of what Laurents calls the travelogue
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   At times, you think it is stuck in the 1950s _ it was written in
1952 _ and then you remember the Puritanism of both the left and
the right when it came to l'affaire Lewinsky and it seems very much
of the moment. With a panel of historians recently rating Bill
Clinton's moral authority below that of Richard Nixon, who
dispensed with the Constitution, any time can be a time of the
cuckoo. And the theater can at least remind some of us there are
worse things in the world than extramarital sex. Still, ``The Time
of the Cuckoo'' is not a great play. It needs a first-rate staging
to work and that's what it gets at the Lincoln Center production,
which opened this week.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is a joy to watch _ particularly Debra Monk, Tom
Aldredge, and Polly Holliday as three of the American tourists, and
Cigdem Onat and Olek Krupa as the guiltless, if not entirely
guileless, Venetians. With the help of James Noone's gorgeous
garden piazza, which subtly hints at the romance outside the
pensione's gates, director Nicholas Martin focuses the forcefulness
of Laurents's rebellion against conventional morality. At the same
time, Martin gives each of the characters breathing room from what
could've been a claustrophobic setting.
</P>
<P>
   Monk takes what, alas, has to be called the Katharine Hepburn
role, given her star turn in ``Summertime.'' (In his upcoming
autobiography, Laurents writes that Hepburn advised Shirley Booth,
who pioneered the part, not to play Leona Samish in the film and
then took the role herself.) It is not an easy part to pull off
because most of the dated dialogue is centered in Leona's
wisecracks. In fact, the overall persona recalls the Eve Ardens,
Rosalind Russells, and other 50-somethings or 40-somethings of the
'50s who were making their way in TV and films without male
accompaniment. All of which means that Monk's generally successful
attempt in making Samish's self-destructiveness convincing 50 years
later is all the more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Samish is looking for love in all the accepted tall, dark,
handsome, and rich forms. That Krupa has more schlump in his
swagger than Rossano Brazzi did makes him all the more believable
as Renato Di Rossi. It falls to him and Signora Floria (Onat), the
owner of the pensione, to loosen up the moralism and monogamy of
the Americans. Life is imperfect, as are life's circumstances, so
gather ye rosebuds, love the one you're with, and find the best
happiness you can while you can.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Williams argued along the same lines more poetically
in ``The Rose Tattoo,'' although Laurents is more unconventional in
taking love's and lust's possibilities outside the marital arena.
Perhaps there is code at work in terms of tolerance for
homosexuality _ Laurents was accidentally outed by Frank Rich in
1995. But that's less central to the play than Laurents's ability
to dispense with romantic and sexual absolutes in a setting that
seemed to be crying out for traditional love. Samish wants life to
be a waltz. ``You should have gone to Vienna,'' says Signora
Floria.
</P>
<P>
   Laurents is perhaps better known for his screenplays (``The Way
We Were'') and musicals (the book for ``West Side Story''). So one
hopes for a revival of the musical based on this play, ``Do I Hear
a Waltz?,'' which he wrote with Richard Rodgers and Stephen
Sondheim. But then this production makes its own unexpectedly
resonant music under Martin's baton. There is more to running a
theater than one's ability as a director, but at least in that
capacity the Huntington has an obvious winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
