<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      02-22 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINDY BLACKMAN FINDS THE BEAT OF THE DRUM IRRESISTIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When she was a child, some folks would ask Cindy Blackman why
she didn't play the flute. They would fix their mouths in that
certain disapproving way, shake their heads, and wonder aloud why
that Blackman girl couldn't just play the clarinet, violin, or
something _ anything _ other than the instrument she had chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Girls weren't supposed to want to play the drums.
</P>
<P>
   But Blackman always loved the drums. Even before she was big
enough to see over a kit, she was fascinated by the way they
looked, was seduced by their urgent sound when she heard them on
records, or on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember just loving the role the drummer had in the band in
terms of the rhythm they created, and the way they carried the
rhythm. I always liked that,'' Blackman recalled. ``I liked what I
heard even when drums were treated more as a background instrument.
But when I heard them played in a way that put them more in the
foreground, that really got me.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, Blackman has been putting drums in the
foreground as the leader of her own jazz combo. She has released
several well-regarded albums, including her latest, ``Works on
Canvas,'' a challenging blend of original works and standards such
as ``April in Paris'' and ``Green Dolphin Street.'' Her best
compositions are reminiscent of her jazz heroes, especially the
late Tony Williams, who was a member of Miles Davis's influential
1960s quintet with Herbie Hancock, Wayne Shorter, and Ron Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and she has this other job, too. Since 1993, she's been the
sistah in the wraparound shades and the Cleopatra Jones 'fro
keeping the beat for Lenny Kravitz on such hits as ``Are You Gonna
Go My Way,'' ``Rock and Roll is Dead,'' ``Fly Away,'' and the
current single, ``I Belong to You.''
</P>
<P>
   With her jazz and rock credentials, these days Blackman is one
of the best-known women drummers around, a growing sorority that
includes all-around percussionist Sheila ``E'' Escovedo; Stefanie
Eulinberg, who plays with Kid Rock; Kate Schellenback of Luscious
Jackson; and Terri Lyne Carrington, who has played with everyone
from Dianne Reeves to Carlos Santana.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Yellow Springs, Ohio, and raised in Bristol,
Cromwell, and West Hartford, Conn., and her household percolated
with a heady brew of musical styles. Her mother, a violinist, loved
classical music; her father favored the jazz of Ahmad Jamal and
Miles Davis; her sister was into Jimi Hendrix, Sly and the Family
Stone, and the Beatles; and her brother was tuning his ear to John
Coltrane. As for Blackman, she was listening to the Jackson 5 and
the Sylvers, ``the teeny bop music of the time,'' she said, as well
as Kansas and Tower of Power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a collage of sounds,'' said Blackman, 40, during
an phone interview from her Brooklyn, N.Y., home. ``I feel blessed
to have been able to hear such a variety of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was 8, she was asking her parents for drums. But
it took her several years to convince her father to invest in a kit
for his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my dad and he said, `Well, we got you skis, and you
gave your skis away. So if we spend more money on these drums, are
you going to play them or give them away?' ''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Blackman ditched her skis after she saw a show
in which a woman was paralyzed after crashing during a race. ``I
didn't want anything to do with the skis after that _ I gave them
away the next day,'' she said with a laugh. ``The drums seemed a
lot safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackman's formal training began at age 13, and she would later
spend three semesters at the Berklee College of Music. She studied
with Lennie Nelson and Alan Dawson, who also taught Tony Williams.
During these years, she became intrigued by jazz drumming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so much more intricate,'' she said. ``The first time I
heard Max Roach, I was absolutely floored.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time she moved to New York in the early 1980s, she was
was a straight-up jazzhead, and was hanging out with her heroes
like Williams, whom she calls ``the most advanced drummer to have
graced this earth.'' And there was lots of time in the company of
such luminaries as Roach, Elvin Jones, Kenny Clarke, and the great
Art Blakey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught me a lot about drumming, about music, about life,''
she said of Blakey. ``He was the kind of guy you would go hang out
with, and you'd leave feeling like you were on top of the world. He
loved music and jazz so much, you couldn't be in his presence and
not carry that with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackman's jazz work is often characterized as hard bop. She
doesn't shun the label, but she maintains her influences are more
expansive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne Shorter referred to it as `creative music,' and that's
the term I use because that allows you to have total freedom in
terms of what elements you allow in the music,'' she said. ``If you
categorize it, it puts things in a box. Instead of saying it's this
kind of music, or that kind of music, how about saying it's just
music that's going to ignite thought and a creative spark?
</P>
<P>
   ``But whatever people call it, I feel really blessed to be able
to do what I love doing,'' Blackman said. ``To love music is a
blessing in itself. To play music and to play it for your career is
an extreme blessing. So, without sounding fanatical, I just thank
the Lord for allowing me to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham coves the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1418EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
