<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-CARAVAGGIO-BOS &LR;      02-22 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CARAVAGGIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUIRKY LIFE OF AN ARTIST AND HIS WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
M: THE MAN WHO BECAME CARAVAGGIO 
By Peter Robb. 
Henry Holt, 570pp., illustrated, $30.00. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Robb addresses ``M: The Man Who Became Caravaggio'' not to
the specialist but to the general reader who is interested in
Caravaggio, as everybody seems to be these days.
</P>
<P>
   Michelangelo Merisi da Caravaggio is now recognized as the
greatest artist active in Europe during the 15 or so great years of
his career; many in his own time thought so too. Caravaggio was
also the most notorious artist of his time, a rebel, a hothead,
wild, a criminal. He knew his way around the brawling streetlife in
Rome, repeatedly got into trouble with the law, did time in jail,
and killed a man in an argument after a tennis match. He enjoyed
the protection of wealthy and powerful men, most of them cardinals,
and was on easy terms with workers of both sexes from Rome's
professional sex industry.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the last years of his life condemned to death and on
the run; people always thought he was crazy, and by the end he may
well have been. Then, in 1610, when it seemed his pardon was
assured, he mysteriously disappeared (he was only 39), and nobody
knows what happened to him, although Robb presents a theory that
fits the known facts better than some of its predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   To some in the late 16th century, Caravaggio was a
counterculture hero, and over the last 50 years or so, he has
become a counterculture hero again. There have been novels about
him, stacks of biographies and studies, and even a movie. Robb's
bibliography runs to 15 pages of illegibly small type. But even in
this crowded company, his own book stands out for its thoroughness,
and fearless bravura.
</P>
<P>
   Robb, an Australian writer who has lived in Italy for 14 years,
received attention a couple of years ago with the international
publication of ``Midnight in Sicily,'' an extraordinary book about
the history of Sicily and the story of the Mafia in the last half
of the 20th century, intertwined with observations and reflections
about the literature, painting, and food of that amazing island _
where, incidentally, Caravaggio spent most of the last year of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   The strengths of Robb's new book are the strengths of its
predecessor _ it is not just about one thing, but about the way odd
things are connected in human and artistic realities. Robb writes
not only about the man Caravaggio, but also about the society of
the elite that supported him, about the repressive regime within
which he had to work, about the jealousy of some of his fellow
artists and the admiration of others, about his turbulent
relationships with young men and prominent female prostitutes,
about the politics of religion and of art, about the surprising
intersections of many different, coexisting worlds, and the way in
which the paintings of Caravaggio reflect his worlds.
</P>
<P>
   The established facts about Caravaggio's life would fill just a
few pages; Robb enthrallingly uses 570 not only to establish a
context and to speculate on what can't be known but also to study
the one thing no one can get to the bottom of, Caravaggio's
surviving paintings. Most of the book, and the best of it, lies in
Robb's close readings of the paintings. (It helps to have a good
book of Caravaggio reproductions at hand, because there aren't
enough of them here, and they're poorly reproduced and awkwardly
laid out for study.)
</P>
<P>
   It has been commonplace for a century and more to call
Caravaggio the first ``modern'' artist. What people mean by that is
that he put his own world, and his own psychology, into paintings
that were supposed to be on classical or biblical subjects. In the
single recorded remark Caravaggio made about art, which turned up
in a bit of police testimony, ``To me the term good man means
someone who knows how to do things well _ that is, knows how to do
his art well _ so in painting, a good man knows how to paint well
and imitate natural things well.''
</P>
<P>
   Caravaggio's success at imitating natural things well was fine
when he was painting water in a carafe or the blush on a grape, or
even a worm hole in an apple. But the Roman church was opposed to
nature in general and implacably opposed to human nature in
particular. Some of Caravaggio's greatest paintings were rejected
by the institutions that commissioned them. He became controversial
when he put human feelings and human realities into his works, not
to mention actual recognizable people from Rome's street life. Poor
pilgrims with tattered clothes and dirty feet kneel before the
Virgin Mary, and the model for the Virgin herself was a prominent
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Robb's method is unconventional. He writes in a mixture of
poetic evocation (``an embarrassment of frozen turmoil was now set
in a strangely elegiac early morning aspic'') and vulgar street
talk, striving to achieve a prose equivalent of Caravaggio's visual
daring. His work rests on a solid base of scholarship, and nearly
every paragraph has a word or an image in italics that comes from a
source contemporary to Caravaggio. But it is also freely
speculative, sexually partisan (Robb chooses not to be embarrassed
by Caravaggio's frank omnisexuality but to glory in it), and openly
anachronistic _ he devotes pages to comparing Caravaggio to the New
York photographer Weegee, who is quoted in the epigraph (``Crime
was my oyster'').
</P>
<P>
   There are some flaws in his work, which shows signs of
insufficiently rigorous editing _ Robb has an ear for talk like the
late George V. Higgins did, and writes in an oral tradition,
repeating himself more often than a reader needs. Much of what he
has said, he has said so well there's no danger anyone will forget.
It's clear that Caravaggio is Robb's oyster, and he makes him ours
too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1419EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-KNIGHT-BOS &LR;      02-22 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-KNIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT SINGS THE PRAISES OF HER `FEEL-GOOD' `CAFE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, Gladys Knight was honored with a Pioneer Award
from the Rhythm and Blues Foundation in New York. Stevie Wonder
stood at her side as she and her longtime group, the Pips, came up
to the podium. Tears flowed as they hugged one another _ and Knight
was particularly overcome. Although the public thinks of her as a
star, Knight, like many R &AMP; B pioneers, says she was cheated out of
royalties in the early days and has often struggled to have her
songs cross over from black radio stations to white Top 40 outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our ups and downs, and yes, we had to face racism,''
Knight says in a recent conversation from Chicago. ``You have to
realize that this is the 51st year for me in this business, and the
Pips and I were together for almost 40 years. So we went through
some times _ socially, as well as economically.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight, who was born in Atlanta, is 55, but she's been touring
since age 4, when she joined traveling church choirs in the South.
She has indeed seen some things, so you can excuse her if she's
trying to have some fun with her latest venture, ``Smokey Joe's
Cafe.''
</P>
<P>
   The musical is based on the songs of Jerry Leiber and Mike
Stoller, who wrote hits for Elvis Presley (``Hound Dog'' and
``Jailhouse Rock''), the Coasters (``Charlie Brown''), the
Drifters, Peggy Lee, and many others.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, whose career includes such hits as ``Midnight Train to
Georgia'' and ``I Heard It Through the Grapevine,'' starred in the
show on Broadway last year after being recruited by Leiber and
Stoller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful feel-good musical show,'' she says. ``Even if
you weren't born during the time when this music was popular, you'd
still have a sense of recognition because the things they have
written about are still so relevant today. Everybody knows a
Charlie Brown _ you know, that person who creates havoc and makes
mischief and keeps something going all the time. We've still got
those kind of people. And it makes for a really fun show. The music
is great and the way they've opted to present it is unique, fresh,
and uplifting.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight never met Leiber and Stoller in their heyday, but she
felt honored when they invited her to do the musical on Broadway.
``They came up with the idea of perking things up a bit, since they
had been on Broadway for about five years,'' she says. ``They
wanted to do a guest-star kind of thing, where they'd have a guest
star come in and maybe do a number for one week. So I came in and
did the week, and it worked out so well that they called me back to
do two weeks. And that worked out so well that they called me back
to do four weeks and it just went from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight is a diehard show-business trouper who opened shows for
Jackie Wilson and Sam Cooke before she was 13. She can still reel
off horror stories from the early days _ she and the Pips (who
included her cousin, James Wood, whose nickname was Pip) never got
any money from their first hit, ``Every Beat of My Heart,'' in
1961; and she still disdains most record company CEOs. ``Most of
them tell you what to sing and what not to sing, but they couldn't
carry a note or play a note if they needed to. They can count the
money, though. I give them credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Knight is looking ahead, not back. She won't let past
frustrations defeat her. She's on an upswing from a recent Grammy
nomination in the contemporary soul gospel category for her CD
``Many Different Roads.'' She's also doing a pop album for MCA
Records and hopes to get that out this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not frustrated, no,'' she says. ``Anything that the
heavenly father ordains, there's no way to stop it. It's his plan
anyway, and I'm just here to be his servant. He's going to see to
it that I'm successful in whatever arena I'm supposed to be
successful in.''
</P>
<P>
   Born a Southern Baptist, Knight is now a Mormon, and cites her
faith as a sustaining power. ``Whoever is not treating someone
fairly, they're going to have to answer for that. I don't even have
to worry about it. I don't have to spin my wheels dealing with it.
I just need to still make my music and he will grant me a way to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight is also about to release a physical fitness book, ``Body
Temples,'' with her fitness guru, Al Claiborne. She works out five
times a week and watches her sugar intake (she's a spokeswoman for
the American Diabetes Foundation); she says she's lost 40 pounds
and feels terrific. ``I'm just trying to get this body temple to
feel right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
