right. By Frank Bruni. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   ARIZ-PRIMARY (Phoenix) _ A separate on the results from
Arizona's GOP primary. By Todd S. Purdum. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   ARIZ-MCCAIN (Tuscon, Ariz.) _ Reaction and scene in Arizona. By
Alison Mitchell. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Washington) _ Bill Bradley's newly adopted
agressiveness is hardly surprising; he's got no choice. But why is
Vice President Al Gore continuing his relentless attacks against a
guy who would be lucky to win a single primary on March 7. A
political memo by Katharine Q. Seelye. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-NY (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ In a new approach, Bill Bradley
tries separate Al Gore from President Clinton. By James Dao. (1000
words)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-DEBATE (Washington) _ A folo: There were a lot of charges
and countercharges Monday night about the Gore and Bradley
legislative records. We try to get at the truth. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL-ERRORS (Washington) _ Hospitals, health companies,
Congress and others react to President Clinton's proposal for
mandatory reporting of medical errors. By Robert Pear. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ A roundup: The Supreme Court agrees to
take case challenging the use of checkpoints in Indianapolis, where
police used drug-sniffing dogs to check every car. Developments on
other cases, including one raising the issue of an athletic body
restricting communication from a high-school coach to a potential
recruit. By Linda Greenhouse. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   CIA-DEUTCH (Washington) _ John Deutch, the former director of
central intelligence accused of improperly handling secret files,
appears at a closed hearing before the Senate Intelligence
Committee. By Eric Schmitt. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RILEY-EDUC (New York) _ In his final State of American Education
speech, Richard W. Riley, the secretary of education says that
teachers should work year-round, spending the off-season in
professional development, in order to boost their pay and status.
We watch via satellite at Columbia Teachers' College here, where
the speech will be followed by a discussion among education
leaders. By Jodi Wilgoren. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Watching developments in a hearing to
determine whether a federal court has jurisdiction in the Elian
Gonzalez case. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Taipei) _ Reaction on Taiwan to China's report on
unification betrays little sense of crisis. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
