satellite, the Burundi peace talks led by Nelson Mandela, the
former South African president. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DRUGS-PRESCHOOLERS (Undated) _ A new study finds use of
psychotropic drugs, including stimulants and antidepressants, for
preschoolers increased in the early 1990s. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MIRCOSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Lawyers for the Justice
Department, 19 states and Microsoft present closing arguments
before Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson in the antitrust case. By Joel
Brinkley and Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-RESIGN (New York) _ Folo on the shakeup at Sotheby's
shakeup, in which its chariman and chief executive officer resigned
amid a federal anti-trust investigation. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   UNILEVER-CUTBACK (London) _ Unilever, the British-Dutch consumer
products giant, plans to cut 25,000 jobs, or 10 percent of its work
force, close 100 factories and focus on just 400 top brands like
Dove soap and Lipton tea. The remaining 1,200 products will be
folded into the leading brands, sold or eliminated. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   TI-CHIPS (Undated) _ Texas Instruments introduces new digital
signal processors, which the company says are the fastest and
lowest-power computer chips available.
</P>
<P>
   PAPER-MERGERS (Undated) _ Looking at the wave of consolidation
sweeping through the world paper industry after Stora Enso of
Finland says it has acquired Consolidated Papers of the United
States for $4 billion. The deal would vault Stora Enso to the
leading paper maker, over International Paper, and comes after the
No.3 paper maker, UPM-Kymmene agreed to acquire Champion
International of the United States for $6.4 billion. By Claudia H.
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-DEBT (Tokyo) _ Less than one week after Moody's Investors
Service warned that it was considering lowering its rating of
Japan's creditworthiness, the credit rating agency's chief rival,
Standard &AMP; Poor's reaffirmed its triple-A rating of the country's
sovereign debt. But Standard &AMP; Poor's also sharply criticized the
government's economic policies, which have depended largely on
public works spending aimed at avoiding the structural adjustments
many economists advocate. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   DOW-EXCITE (Undated) _ Dow Jones and Excite(at)Home form a joint
venture, which will develop a business portal. By Felicity
Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Nancy
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;  (3-column hole)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-RECRUIT (New York) _ Thanks to the growing economy,
consulting firms and investment banks keep expanding. But many of
their most prized recruits _ M.B.A.s at Harvard, Stanford, and the
like _ are shunning the traditional jobs for dot-com dreams. As a
result, some of the country's most prestigious firms are turning to
schools where they never before hired. The schools are gleeful. By
David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties'' and Pual Krugman's ``Reckonings.''
