<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROUGHT PUTS A NEW TEXAS CROP _ FRESH-WATER PEARLS _ ON HOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly half of all Texas counties are eligible for drought
relief now and the others are getting thirsty. Farmers are mowing
and bailing highway right-of-way to feed their livestock; stock
tanks are baked rock-hard dry.
</P>
<P>
   The hot, dusty winds continue to blow and there is a new victim
in this parched scenario: a new Texas crop that is failing, a new
industry that is being held in arid abeyance.
</P>
<P>
   Pearls.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have been working to establish a fresh-water pearl
industry in the state. The project is being conducted at Lake
Anahuac, near Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should just take a couple of years to get the first
pearls,'' said Dr. Leonard DiMichele, a fisheries researcher with
the Texas Agricultural Experiment Station. ``We've got the animals,
we've got the techniques, and usually we have the water. But this
is not a good year right now. We've had trouble with the drought
and growing conditions. We'll try to replant this spring.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMichele and other researchers thought that the Anahuac
location would be a good one because they are working with the
local water district that helps farmers flood rice fields every
year. That's a lot of water. Usually.
</P>
<P>
   But this year the rice fields are endangered and the anticipated
pearl industry is left unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Cultured pearls will remain in the grips of the Japanese and
other Asian markets for now, but researchers say that when the
rains do come, customers could end up with strings of purely Texas
pearls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a marketing and distribution infrastructure
right now,'' DiMichele said. ``But there are people watching our
research and they are ready to establish the systems when the time
comes.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason researchers believe Texas is fertile ground _ or
water _ for pearls is the presence of the Tampico pearly mussel
that produces pink to flame red pearls. It can be found all along
the Colorado River drainage basin and in Lake Buchanan, where
DiMichele has begun yet another research project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a bit of the pearls brought back to Spain by the
conquistadors came from those mussels,'' DiMichele said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the nuclei, or shell pieces that are introduced to
mussels or oysters to begin pearl formation, come from the United
State. The best of the nuclei come from the South, where the shells
are thick and strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like a thick, homogeneous shell,'' DiMichele said of the
Asian growers. ``The shells are cut into small cubes and rounded
out. The nuclei range from 5 to 10 millimeters in size. Actually,
when you buy the pearls, you're basically buying back the nuclei. A
cultured pearl has only a couple millimeters covering the nuclei.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMichele likens the current system to that of Colonial America.
``You produce the raw material and ship it overseas for the
manufacturing, and then it gets sold back to you,'' he said. ``That
is never as good an economic arrangement as doing the manufacturing
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 70 percent of the pearls sold worldwide are sold in the
United States, researchers believe U.S. pearl farms could become a
multimillion-dollar industry.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as it rains.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
