r l BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     02-22 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING HOME ALONE MEANS PEACE, QUIET AND BOREDOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have some bad news and some good news today.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that my husband left me. He took his clothes,
his car, and a big chunk of our checking account. He left before
dawn with barely a glance backward. The squeal of his tires on the
pavement was the most emotion displayed during his departure.
</P>
<P>
   He took the kids with him. Their clothes, CDs, Game Boys, and
their incessant noise _ all gone. Of course, they're coming back.
It's just a weekend trip. Kind of a last-minute deal. Regrettably,
I had prior commitments and could not accompany them. Oh, well.
Whatever will I do with myself for three, whole, entire,
uninterrupted, complete days alone?
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   After work, I'll go home and clean the house. I know that
doesn't sound appealing, but the idea that it will remain clean for
three days just gives me goosebumps. Then, I'll eat soup. I'll
probably cook it in a bowl since you shouldn't put cans in the
microwave. That's as close as I can come to not cooking at all. I
may even just drink my dinner.
</P>
<P>
   I've considered polishing my toenails because during dinner last
month, one of my girlfriends said, ``You can tell a lot about a
woman by her feet.'' Like what, for instance? What on earth can you
tell about someone by their feet? Big. Small. Wide. So what? That's
genetic stuff. OK, if they're dirty, you've got some ammunition,
but otherwise, I wouldn't exactly call a woman's feet a window to
her soul.
</P>
<P>
   But, just in case she's right, I might dig out that red polish
that I usually reserve for summer days at the beach. Nah, who's
gonna see my feet this weekend, anyway? If my friend drops by, I'll
just put on socks. That leaves me more time to read. I'll read a
good, trashy novel. That soup and the novel will get me through
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, I don't have to go to any sporting events. I won't
be asked to go for a bike ride or play badminton. The phone
probably won't ring. I won't even have to locate anyone's socks or
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Boy oh boy, I'm just gonna walk around the house in my socks and
... be bored out of my mind. What on earth was I thinking to let
them leave me here by myself? I don't even like soup that much!
</P>
<P>
   Well, the good news is that they're coming back on Sunday. The
bad news is, at this moment, it's only Friday morning, really early
on Friday morning. In consolation, I cling to one simple thought.
It is my beacon of hope and inspiration: Deep down inside I know
that no matter what else happens this weekend, no matter how
lonesome and bored I become, my feet are clean.
</P>
<P>
   They may not be decorated, but they are clean.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
