<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN, SHRUGGING OFF CHINA THREAT, REACHES FOR PRACTICAL
SOLUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ Unbowed by China's latest threat of force,
Taiwan on Tuesday called on the mainland to set aside fruitless
debates over sovereignty and resume talks over economic ties and
other practical matters to improve relations across the Taiwan
straits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call ourselves a sovereign country, and if they don't like
it, they'll have to live with it,'' said Su Chi, chairman of the
cabinet-level Mainland Affairs Council, in an interview. ``They
call us a province and we don't like it, but we live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Taiwan problem is not solvable by force or the threat of
force,'' Su said.
</P>
<P>
   Su spoke in response to a report issued by China on Monday that
repeated longstanding demands that Taiwan embrace the ``one China''
principle and warned of military action if the island endlessly
puts off talks on political unification.
</P>
<P>
   China's stern report came less than one month before
presidential elections here and appears designed to warn the
contenders and electorate that China's patience is running thin.
The report did not set down a timetable or ultimatum, but railed
against what it termed the separatist scheming of Taiwan's current
president, Lee Teng-hui and condemned American arms sales to the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Among members of the public here, reactions to China's latest
warning ranged from anger to indifference. But the prospect of new
tensions caused the Taiwan stock market to slump, dipping more than
4 percent at one point before intervention by a special stabilizing
fund held the day's loss to 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   China's report, and Taiwan's ripostes Tuesday, repeated familiar
arguments in which seemingly minor rhetorical differences reflect
crucial divisions over basic principle.
</P>
<P>
   For the Taiwanese, who are proud of the advanced economy and
democracy they have achieved, China's offered formula of ``one
country, two systems'' is embedded with an utterly unacceptable
assumption: that Beijing heads the true national government and
that Taiwan _ even if granted remarkable autonomy _ is merely one
of its provinces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot negotiate on the basis that theirs is a sovereign
country while ours is a province.'' Su said. ``We're not electing a
governor here,'' he said, referring to the March 18 elections.
``We're electing a president, and they have to face it.''
</P>
<P>
   Su repeated previous invitations to resume talks on trade and
communications links, on a treaty to prevent use of force and on
other practical issues, noting that a large majority in Taiwan is
not ready to take the political leap that China demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the People's Republic of China thinks the time is right to
reunify China, to bring Taiwan into its fold, they are
miscalculating,'' Su said. ``The Taiwanese people don't want to
declare independence, but they don't want unification now either,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of China's threats of war, all three major candidates in
the presidential election here have already declared their desire
to resume talks with the mainland and foster closer economic ties.
China angrily halted a tentative dialogue across the straits last
summer, when President Lee said Taiwan would meet only on a
``state-to-state'' basis _ a formulation that China considers
tantamount to declaring independence.
</P>
<P>
   China's new warnings seemed to cause few ripples in public
opinion here.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Taiwanese, we still control our own destinies. and we can
find our own directions,'' said Shi Tang-te, 31, an employee of a
Japanese trading firm here, as he shopped for computer software.
Shi said he still supports the opposition Democratic Progressive
Party, which has only recently tempered its calls for Taiwan's
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Lai Ching-chi, a 44-year-old sales manager for a printing firm,
was more distressed. ``When I heard the news yesterday, I felt
powerless,'' he said. ``I accept the idea that we are all Chinese,
but the mainland is too aggressive about this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwan is very small and the mainland sets the rules,'' said
Lai, a supporter of the Nationalist Party. ``I only hope there is
no war among the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
