<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4756 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-SILICON-VALLEY-POLITI     02-22 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILICON-VALLEY-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TECH COMPANIES TAKE ACTIVE INTEREST IN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Silicon Valley is no longer shy about its
political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   It favors free trade with China, an unlimited supply of
immigrant workers and a ban on Internet taxation.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, this year's leading presidential candidates
have no problem with those demands. In fact, they are working hard
to make one or more of those proposals a key part of their
platforms.
</P>
<P>
   All four of the leading candidates for the Republican and
Democratic party nominations have been vocal and visible in their
courtship of the technology sector. The extra attention is paying
off.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released last week by the Center for
Responsive Politics , a nonpartisan organization in Washington,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush has corralled the most donations from
Silicon Valley among the presidential hopefuls, with $698,033.
Former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey has pulled in $333,235;
Vice President Al Gore has raised $330,285; and Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., has attracted $140,536.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, President Clinton, as an incumbent, raised
$140,000 during his 1996 presidential campaign, said Holly Bailey,
a researcher who specializes in technology contributions for the
Center for Responsive Politics. And Sen. Bob Dole, the unsuccessful
Republican candidate for president in 1996, raised about $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The influence has grown tremendously, whether you look at
policy development, relationship building, being a player in the
state's capital or in Washington, D.C.,'' said Lezlee Westine,
general counsel and vice president of TechNet, a bipartisan Silicon
Valley organization that is generally recognized as the most
visible political organization representing technology interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people started out thinking Silicon Valley would only be
a major campaign contributor,'' Westine said. ``They've now evolved
into policy advisers and grass-roots campaign volunteers, as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Westine, who coordinates TechNet's relationship-building efforts
with the Republican Party, has witnessed the evolution firsthand,
coming aboard in 1997 after serving as an attorney and telecom
policymaker for California's governor at the time, Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The change in the Silicon Valley's political activism started
about four years ago. At the time, the industry was experiencing
some of its first success on the political front, succeeding in its
efforts to block a California ballot initiative that would have
made it easier for shareholders to sue public companies.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, a number of other issues emerged, among
them data encryption, Internet privacy and Internet taxation. While
those issues were important, many observers say it wasn't until
Microsoft Corp.'s antitrust case hit that the industry really took
notice of Washington's power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Microsoft antitrust case was a huge wake-up call,'' Bailey
said. ``That's when we saw campaign contributions step up, between
1997 and 1998. People were saying, 'Hey, this could happen to
us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the huge advance of technology stocks, the stage
was set for increased fund-raising activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unfortunate part of politics is money speaks,'' said Ted
Schlein, a general partner in the Menlo Park-based venture capital
firm Kleiner, Perkins, Caufield and Byers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of money here. Political power tends to focus,
then, on the money. Now that they're out here, the next question is
the ability to effect change.''
</P>
<P>
   To do so, the Silicon Valley is focusing on issues rather than
party affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think political parties mean less to people here,'' said
Schlein, who is actively supporting Bradley in the presidential
campaign. ``What we're used to here is anyone, regardless of race
or gender, has a chance to rise to the top. Anyone can start a
company. Anyone can be a CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude speaks volumes on the area's libertarian roots.
``Content is valued over branding,'' said Schlein, applying some
Internet speak to his political views.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's refreshing that this industry takes a truly bipartisan
approach,'' said Mark Albertson, senior vice president of the
American Electronics Association, a trade organization representing
more than 3,000 technology companies nationwide. ``It's a good,
constructive way to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   It also is a good way to leverage one's influence, Westine said.
With the presidential race heating up, she said, the Silicon Valley
is in an even better position to work with the candidates on
crucial policy positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition for Silicon Valley support has produced very
positive policies for the new economy,'' said Westine, whose
organization has grown to more than 180 chief executives from the
high-tech industry including hardware, software, biotech, and
content providers, as well as leading partners from venture capital
companies, investment banks and law firms.
</P>
<P>
   TechNet is based in Palo Alto. The organization recently opened
operations in Austin, Texas, and Orange County, Calif. The group
also plans to expand into Oregon, Washington, Colorado, New York
and Pennsylvania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
