<HEADLINE>
READERS REJOICE: HARRY POTTER'S BACK, AND SO IS KAY SCARPETTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At one time, publishers divided the book business into two
distinct seasons _ spring and fall _ with the idea being that the
best books were released just when consumers were most ready to buy
them for summer vacations or Christmas gifts.
</P>
<P>
   But the times, they are a changin', probably due to the advent
of customer-friendly mega-bookstore chains like Barnes &AMP; Noble and
Borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because bookstores have become a year 'round gathering place
with their coffee bars and reading areas, publishers have gotten
away from the idea of distinct time frames as (being) best for book
sales,'' says Kellie Lutz, a book industry analyst in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't just thinking about books as something they can
read on the beach or over the Christmas holidays. Now the so-called
big books by the best-known authors may come out any time from Jan.
1 to Dec. 31. I think it benefits the consumer, because you can
pretty much buy them on a steady pace throughout the year.''
</P>
<P>
   This new philosophy has never been more evident than in the
first months of 2000. Already, we've had fiction from Pulitzer
Prize-winner Robert Olen Butler (''Mr. Spaceman'') and perennial
bestseller John Grisham (''The Brethren'') as well as pointed
political commentary from Jeffrey Toobin (''A Vast Conspiracy'').
Also on store shelves are new novels by Carl Hiaasen (''Sick
Puppy''), John Updike (''Gertrude and Claudius'') and E.L. Doctorow
(''City of God'').
</P>
<P>
   From March through the beginning of next September, each month
promises to include publication of at least a few intriguing,
unmistakable bestselling titles. Attention from the media doesn't
guarantee success, as was demonstrated last year when ``Hannibal,''
Thomas Harris' sequel to ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' sold briskly
but was panned by critics and most readers. Edmund Morris'
semi-fictional ``Dutch,'' a long-awaited biography of Ronald
Reagan, earned comparable scorn, as did Susan Faludi's ``Stiffed.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a subjective Top 20 list of upcoming titles seems to
offer something for everyone, particularly in fiction. From Harry
Potter to Kay Scarpetta, with Jack Ryan in between, old favorites
return. Critical favorites Jane Smiley, Thomas Sanchez, Jeff Shaara
and Alice Hoffman have new titles, and Texas' own Stephen Harrigan
may eclipse them all with his monumental novel ``The Gates of the
Alamo.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, then, are the books of spring by month of publication:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``The Gates of the Alamo'' by Stephen Harrigan (March,
Knopf). The subject: Texas during the revolution, particularly the
famous siege in San Antonio. The buzz: Industry insiders have been
anticipating this one for years. The prediction: It's a
masterpiece. Give Harrigan all the awards for fiction now.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Ravelstein'' by Saul Bellow (March, Random House). The
subject: A colorful nonconformist takes on the world. The buzz:
It's Bellow, so it must be good. The prediction: It is, and how
well ``Ravelstein'' sells will tell us a lot about the modern
hunger (or lack thereof) for fine literary fiction.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``The Remorseful Day'' by Colin Dexter (March, Crown). The
subject: Prickly Inspector Morse solves his final case. The buzz:
Readers ought to flock to learn how a beloved curmudgeon closes out
his career. The prediction: It was time for the old drunk to go.
Less-than-anticipated sales will confirm this. Morse was always
much more popular in England than America.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Ordinary Resurrections: Children in Years of Hope'' by
Jonathan Kozol (April, Crown). The subject: America's favorite
``bleeding heart'' journalist takes readers to live with poor kids
in the South Bronx. The buzz: Kozol writes so wonderfully he makes
liberals feel proud of their social philosophies. The prediction: A
bestseller, with literary prizes to come.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Pontius Pilate'' by Anne Wroe (April, Random House). The
subject: A nonfiction investigation of a controversial, and largely
unknown, life. The buzz: The book won all sorts of awards in its
author's native England, and Random House is going to push it hard
in the United States. The prediction: It's superbly written and
should attract a wide audience.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Horse Heaven'' by Jane Smiley (April, Knopf). The subject:
Two years on a fictional horse-racing circuit. The buzz: ``Jane
Smiley always sells, even if she's not writing well.'' The
prediction: not this time. Critics always like to turn icons into
punching bags, and this could be Smiley's turn.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
