<HEADLINE>
S&AMP;P REAFFIRMS JAPAN'S TRIPLE-A RATING AFTER MOODY'S WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Less than one week after Moody's Investors Service
warned that it was considering lowering its rating of Japan's
creditworthiness, Standard &AMP; Poor's, the credit rating agency's
chief rival, reaffirmed its triple-A rating of the country's
sovereign debt.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's also said its outlook for Japan was stable,
citing the country's standing as the world's largest creditor
nation and the breadth of its economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency's assessment also carried a warning and an
implicit criticism of the current government's economic policies,
which have depended largely on pork barrel projects and other
spending aimed at avoiding the structural adjustments many
economists advocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, the government's failure to bolster economic
prospects _ by allowing the pace of structural reform to slip and
by faltering in its efforts to boost consumer confidence _ suggests
that the economic sluggishness could continue indefinitely, with
the government debt burden rising to levels inconsistent with a
triple-A rating,'' Standard &AMP; Poor's said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been troubled by the potential of an increased
discrepancy between Moody's and Standard &AMP; Poor's assessment of
Japan's ability to handle its mounting pile of debt, which
currently stands at 100 percent of its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inconsistent with a triple-A rating,'' said Robert Alan
Feldman, chief economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in Tokyo,
quoting the Standard &AMP; Poor's press release. ``That is a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   While the market has long been aware of Japan's debts, a recent,
subtle campaign by the Ministry of Finance to increase awareness of
the problem with politicians and the public has raised anew
questions about whether Japan has a strategy for pulling its
economy out of its decade-long slump.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Moody's raised the possibility that it would
downgrade Japan's credit rating yet again, having lowered it in
November 1998 to Aa1, one level below its top rating. It cited
Japan's rising debt as a major reason for its review.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things Moody's was talking about was a lack of
gross philosophy, meaning how Japan intends to get its economy
moving and deal with the fiscal issues it faces,'' Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa has warned repeatedly in recent
weeks that Japan cannot continue to expect to borrow at the low
interest rates it currently enjoys. Japanese government bonds with
a duration of 10 years have traded within a range of 1.6 percent to
2 percent interest for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Ministry officials have also quietly and persistently
made the point that tax revenues are falling dramatically as
companies lay off workers in an effort to overhaul their
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the ratings agencies would be too concerned if
Japan were spending money to boost structural change and promote
long-term growth,'' said Ron Bevacqua, chief economist at Commerz
Securities. ``But Japan is spending money in a way that delays the
need for structural adjustment, and in that case, the money is
wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand for 1.4 trillion yen of 10-year government bonds Tuesday
was the weakest since August of last year, even though the
government raised the coupon to 1.8 percent from 1.7 percent in the
last 10-year bond auction in January. Traders said investors were
seeking a 1.9 percent coupon, and that some investors were waiting
to invest in several private placements of municipal debt that are
coming up.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks, which are the major buyers of bonds here, have
bought heavily in recent months and may have lost some of their
appetite for bonds as the chance of a rise in long-term interest
rates increases, threatening their existing bond holdings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
