r w BC-EARLY-AMERICANS-HNS &LR;      02-22 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-AMERICANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RESEARCH SPARKS NEW THEORIES ON EARLY AMERICAN IMMIGRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The long-held view that the first Americans arrived
via a land bridge from northern Asia 11,500 years ago and quickly
spread throughout the New World is giving way to mounting evidence
that migration instead came in multiple waves beginning as many as
20,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Skeletal remains, new archaeological discoveries, genetic
sleuthing and language analyses are all tending to back that up,
showing the early Americas as a busy crossroads of various peoples,
according to scientists gathered here for the American Association
for the Advancement of Science meeting.
</P>
<P>
   While there was agreement about how the old view is being
discredited, scientists also acknowledged that evidence coming from
their various disciplines does not always point to identical
answers.
</P>
<P>
   One conclusion, however, was shared: ``There are at least two
major groups and they are not closely related to each other at
all,'' said C. Loring Brace, an anthropologist at the University of
Michigan who uses precise measurements of skulls to determine their
relationships to human sub-groups.
</P>
<P>
   Brace contends that American Indian populations that settled
around the U.S.-Mexico border and farther south into Latin America
were the first to arrive, and probably came from central China.
</P>
<P>
   Another group, more dominant in North America, appears to be
comprised of descendants of the Jomon people, the prehistoric
occupants of modern Japan.
</P>
<P>
   That group, Brace suspects, came down along the Pacific Coast
fewer than 20,000 years ago and a branch of them began migrating
East as the ice sheet covering much of Canada melted, creating
rivers so they could navigate inland.
</P>
<P>
   What could be another branch of the Jomon people, with some
ancestry from Mongolia, came later to what is now Alaska and are
the ancestors of the Eskimo and Aleut peoples, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Brace has not been able to measure the controversial
Kennewick Man, a skeleton dating back about 9,300 years found in
Washington state, his first reaction when he looked at it was, ``My
goodness, that comes straight out of Jomon, Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   The most startling evidence for archaeologists is the recent
discovery of a 12,500-year-old human settlement site in southern
Chile _ 10,000 miles from where scientists had thought the first
humans crossed over, and 1,000 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   David Meltzer, professor of anthropology at Southern Methodist
University in Dallas, said archaeologists are now focusing on
potential coastal routes that could explain how they managed to get
so far south while an ice sheet covered most of Canada. But they
are faced with a problem: when the ice melted about 12,000 years
ago, sea levels rose and the coastline became submerged.
</P>
<P>
   One researcher has been able to dredge up some archaeological
remains off the Pacific Coast, Meltzer said, but they have yet to
be dated.
</P>
<P>
   Meltzer and other scientists who spoke Friday at the scientific
conference tended to discount a recent hypothesis that some
precolonial early Americans came from Europe. The idea was based on
recent work that found a genetic marker found in European people _
but not Asians _ is also present in some American Indians.]
</P>
<P>
   Meltzer and Theodore Schurr of the Southwest Foundation for
Biomedical Research said they believe the more likely explanation
is that the marker was part of an ancient genetic code that died
out in Asian populations after the first immigrants came to the New
World.
</P>
<P>
   Schurr's work in genetics tends to suggest an earlier migration,
made up of multiple waves of people, some of whom are related to
the present-day occupants of parts of East Asia and Siberia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
