<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4778 &Cx1f; tab-z
r v BC-ESTHER-LOOKAHEAD-ADVI     02-22 0211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTHER-LOOKAHEAD-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Esther Dyson's ``Release 3.0'' column to be released Wednesday
notes that just as the Internet has empowered the individual, it
has also offered economies of scale to criminal elements.
</P>
<P>
   The recent denial-of-service attacks on Yahoo! and eBay are a
case in point -- the poor security of a large number of people was
used to mount an attack on a few.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson writes: ``We need to understand that electronic security
costs money, just like regular security (locks, guards, alarm
systems). Power implies responsibility; if you buy a computer that
can be used as a weapon, you need to make sure that it is designed
and installed safely.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she writes, ``the average computer user doesn't know
how to set up a safe system, but he needs to demand service from
someone who does.''
</P>
<P>
   She expects that in an increasingly decentralized world, the
best security solutions will evolve to match the evolving,
decentralized risks.
</P>
<P>
   For a look at Esther's next column, or to obtain more
information about Esther, call Bob Farnell at 1-800-535-4425, or
e-mail him at farnellb(at)nytimes.com.)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
