 ART ADV.: Photos with AUTHOR-PIERCE and CMGI-ENGAGE are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO (New York) _ Conviction will be a tricky matter when
the jury begins deliberating in the trial of police officers
accused of killing Amadou Diallo. By Fred Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   STUDENTS-CITIZENSHIP (Undated) _ Colleges are trying to make
students better citizens by briding the gap between volunteering
and good citizenship, where polls show students lag in voter
participation and interest in the political process. By Kate
Zernike. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   NO-CAR (Sherman Station, Maine.) _ For poor mothers in remote
Maine, having a car means the difference between subsistence and
independence. By Ellen Barry. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Grand Rapids, Mich.) _ John McCain's Michigan
gambit: Woo conservatives, but don't dismay moderates. By Thomas
Oliphant. &UR;  &LR; (w and k coding.)
</P>
<P>
   MCGRORY-COLUMN (Undated) _ I am sitting here with a Clark bar to
my left and a Lewis&AMP;Clark Bar to my right, conducting a taste test
to determine what has caused the New England Confectionery Company
to do this. By Brian McGrory.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE-COLUMN (Undated) -- Hostility toward ending sentences
with prepositions still runs deep among people who aced sixth-grade
grammar. In fact, there's nothing wrong with the practice. By Jan
Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH/SCIENCE (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FACE-RECOGNITION (Undated) _ Your face, whether you like it
or not, is likely on its way to becoming your password _ to ATM
machines, workplace check-ins, airline ticketing counters, even
your own computer. By Richard Saltus. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-EGGERS (New York) _ When his parents died within five
weeks of each other, David Eggers raised his 8-year-old brother,
setting up housekeeping as father and son. He has written ``A
Heartbreaking Work of Staggering Genius.'' By Fred Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-PIERCE (Newton, Mass.) _ Charlie Pierce, who writes for
GQ, Esquire and others, tells the story of the devastating swath
Alzheimer's has cut through his family. By Alison Bass. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-KNIGHT (Undated) _ Gladys Knight is feeling good about her
career again, which has taken off again with ``Smokey Joe's Cafe.''
By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   STAGE-CUCKOO (New York) _ At first, Arthur Laurent's ``The Time
of the Cuckoo'' seems like an odd play to revive. By Ed Siegel.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-CARAVAGGIO (Undated) _ Peter Robb addresses ``M: The Man
Who Became Caravaggio'' not to the specialist but to the general
reader who is interested in Caravaggio, as everybody seems to be
these days. By Richard Dyer. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMN-POP (Undated) _ Cindy Blackman, Lenny Kravitz's drummer,
is also a great jazz player/composer in the Tony Williams
tradition. By Renee Graham.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (t) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CRUISE (Undated) _ It's going to be a great cruise season
for Boston; checking on a cruise ship's sanitation. By Jerry
Morris. 1800 words.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN &UR;  &LR; (Undated) _ The Philadelphia Flower Show, largest
indoor flower show in the world and the oldest in this country,
runs March 5 to 12. By Jerry Morris. 1600 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES (Undated) _ Whether it's cow flop or cackling
chickens, the unexpected can get in the way of honeymoon bliss. By
Richard Carpenter.
</P>
