<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-SKREEN-SPI &LR;      02-22 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SKREEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BETTER OR WORSE, CONSULTANTS KNOW WHAT THE VIEWERS LIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 12 months have passed since our last trenchant
conversation with T.V. Skreen, Ph.D., eminent television industry
consultant and image-enhancement adviser to Ken Griffey Jr. In this
latest encounter, filmed entirely on location in the chat rooms of
my mind, Dr. Skreen touches on a recent development that has
unsettled some observers of the TV scene.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: So nice to see you again, Dr. Skreen. What have you been
up to lately?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: I sold the condo in Santa Monica and moved everything to
my new alpaca ranch in Idaho. It's on the Continental Divide, just
outside this lovely village with the most musical name. Say it with
me, would you? Lee-ah-dor-ay.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Lee-ah-dor-ay. Sounds nice. How do you spell that?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: L-E-A-D-O-R-E.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Forgive me, Doctor, but shouldn't that be pronounced Led
Orr? You know. Led, as in Led Zeppelin. Orr, as in Bobby Orr. Get
it? Lead Ore. I think it might have been a mining town.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Ugh. You critics are all so literal. Can't you ever
think outside the box, try to see things a little differently?
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: I do. I like to watch ``Baywatch'' and ``Baywatch
Hawaii'' with the sound off. It's easier to follow without the
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: That's not what I meant. Well, OK, maybe it is what I
meant. But you people don't seem to do it often enough.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Hey, it's not my fault that ``Baywatch'' is on only 12
times a week. I do what I can.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Perhaps, but you've been absolutely silent on some
cutting-edge TV that shouldn't go unnoticed by the poo-bahs of
punditry.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Like what?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Like ``Who Wants To Marry a Multi-Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: I wouldn't exactly say it went unnoticed. The show was
on in 23 million households. It gave Fox its biggest audience in
two years.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: But you didn't say a word.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Sometimes a critic serves best by saying nothing.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: What kind of copout is that?
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: I'm serious. Fox executives don't need me to tell them a
show like ``Who Wants To Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' is demeaning
to women, demeaning to rich people and demeaning to an industry
that already has more black eyes than a mascara test lab. They know
it all too well, but they also know America loves to watch people
lose their dignity. Whether it's ``Jerry Springer,'' ``Cops'' or
``America's Funniest Home Videos,'' millions will tune in to watch
misfortune befall other folks so they, the viewers, can feel
superior.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Hogwash! This is about dream fulfillment and making
people unafraid to aim high. From the moment I pitched the concept
to Fox, that was the premise.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: This was your idea?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: You betcha.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: But even Fox seems to be backing off now. It bagged a
rebroadcast of the show last night because there are now questions
surfacing about the multimillionaire's background. Seems he may not
be the tycoon of our dreams.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: No big deal. Once we've refined the vetting process to
weed out con-persons, contrarians and concubines, these shows will
be back, bigger than ever. Nobody will be able to resist the
sequels we've got planned, like ``Who Wants To Marry a Milliner?''
Can't you just picture 50 eligible guys vying to be the lifelong
partner of a hat designer?
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Um, actually ...
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: The beach-wear competition should be smashing! Speedos
in prime time! And then there's ``Who Wants To Marry a Barista?''
We're combing the espresso stands of Seattle right now. My own
favorite is probably ``Who Wants To Marry a Notary Public?''
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: A notary public?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Yup. Think of all the important documents you can have
notarized without leaving the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: You're missing the point.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: And that would be ...
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: That marriage is a serious, lifelong commitment between
two people, not a one-night game show pitting tux against tulle.
Anyone who would create such a show is disturbed and should
probably be put away for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Are you suggesting I'm a few tiles short of a successful
re-entry?
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: That's one way of putting it.
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: And that I should be institutionalized?
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: Well ...
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: You may have a future in this business after all.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: What do you mean?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Your mind works just like a TV consultant's. Who do yo
think suggested that Deborah Norville spend five days in a North
Carolina jail for ``Inside Edition''?
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: That was you?
</P>
<P>
   SKREEN: Bingo. Sometimes you have to go inside the box to get
outside the box.
</P>
<P>
   TV GUY: I see. Oh, God. Help me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1610EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4788 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-NEWBOOKS-2ndTake-TEX     02-22 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWBOOKS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Smiley's turn. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   7. ``The Borderland'' by Edwin ``Bud'' Shrake (April, Hyperion).
The plot: Veteran Texas writer pens novel of early Texas. The buzz:
Shrake's always been a good writer; maybe this one will establish
him nationally. The prediction: maybe, in any other year. But in
2000, Stephen Harrigan's the Lone Star novelist who gets rich and
famous.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``The Book of Honor'' by Ted Gup (May, Doubleday). The
subject: Investigative journalist reveals the secrets of the CIA.
The buzz: It's going to be controversial, which usually translates
into sales. The prediction: lots of media coverage, but most
readers will yawn.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Omerta'' by Mario Puzo (May, Random House). The subject:
The late author had one last Mafia yarn to spin. The buzz: Maybe
fans of ``The Godfather'' still buy books. The prediction: No, they
don't.
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Gone for Soldiers'' by Jeff Shaara (May, Ballantine). The
subject: More war fiction, this time pre-Civil War as the United
States takes on Mexico. The buzz: Shaara is a worthy successor to
father Michael, whose ``The Killer Angels'' launched this series.
The prediction: solid sales, but nothing spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   11. ``The Human Stain'' by Philip Roth (May, Houghton Mifflin).
The subject: A classics professor is forced to resign when he is
accused of racism. The buzz: Roth wants another Pulitzer for
fiction. The prediction: He stands a good chance of getting it.
</P>
<P>
   12. ``Day of the Bees'' by Thomas Sanchez (May, Knopf). The
subject: Details of a 50-year-old love affair stagger a scholar.
The buzz: Sanchez proves again he's one of our most talented
novelists. The prediction: Sanchez remains a critic's darling whose
books just don't sell much.
</P>
<P>
   13. ``The River King'' by Alice Hoffman (June, Putnam). The
subject: Small-town turmoil in Massachusetts. The buzz: Hoffman is
such a fine novelist that this time she'll sell a million copies.
The prediction: Kudos to Putnam for giving Hoffman time to ``grow''
a wider readership; ``The River King'' ought to be her breakout
book.
</P>
<P>
   14. ``Papal Sin: Structures of Deceit'' by Garry Wills (June,
Doubleday). The subject: Popes aren't saints, at least in the
author's opinion. The buzz: Had Wills written a similar book about
the the Ayatollah, he'd have been sentenced to death a la Salman
Rushdie. The prediction: a bestseller, and the most discussed
nonfiction of the year.
</P>
<P>
   15. ``In a Sunburned Country'' by Bill Bryson (June, Broadway).
The subject: Acerbic world traveler finds new annoyances in
Australia. The buzz: Bryson is gradually winning the travel book
audience from Paul Theroux. The prediction: another bestseller.
Bryson may be the funniest author currently at work.
</P>
<P>
   16. ``Harry Potter and the Doomspell Tournament'' by J.K.
Rowling (July, Levine/Scholastic). The subject: Everybody's
favorite wizard-in-training tries to lead his team to victory in an
oddball sport. The buzz: All three of Rowling's previous ``Harry''
titles remain bestsellers. Love the series or hate it, but don't
deny its sales dominance. The prediction: Harrymania continues.
</P>
<P>
   17. ``The Last Precinct'' by Patricia Cornwell (July, Putnam).
The subject: Kay Scarpetta and the usual cast get involved in
murders present and past _ in Jamestown, of all places. The buzz:
Readers can't get enough of Scarpetta's morbid adventures. The
prediction: no end in sight for Cornwell's popularity and
megasales.
</P>
<P>
   18. ``Hot Six'' by Janet Evanovich (July, St. Martin's). The
plot: No specifics from the publisher as yet, but we can be certain
diminutive bounty hunter Stephanie Plum will be bumbling her way
through another slapstick case. The buzz: Evanovich has made it to
the top sales tier. The prediction: bestseller. Readers love
Evanovich's breezy style.
</P>
<P>
   19. ``The Bear and the Dragon'' by Tom Clancy (August, Putnam).
The subject: President Jack Ryan battles liberals and foreign foes
to save America from disaster. The buzz: Clancy's Ryan backlist
isn't selling ``quite'' as briskly. It's being whispered that even
his staunchest fans may be sick of 700-page tomes that could be
edited to a brisker 400 pages. The prediction: another No. 1
bestseller, but its stay atop the list will be brief.
</P>
<P>
   20. ``Robert Kennedy: His Life'' by Evan Thomas (September,
Simon &AMP; Schuster). The subject: The first full-blown biography of
RFK since the '70s. The buzz: It's good, it's really good.
Prediction: short-listed for a Pulitzer.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
