<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-McCAIN (Detroit) _ Michigan and Arizona Republicans hold
primaries that will likely determine whether John McCain's quest
for the GOP nomination is realistic or quixotic against George W.
Bush, who regained momentum with his victory in the South Caroline
primary. By CRAGG HINES and R.G.RATCLIFFE..
</P>
<P>
   GOP-McCAIN (Phoenix) _ Sen. John McCain says his presidential
race is much like his life _ a ``high wire act'' that, win or lose,
is made to order for a risk-taker. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-WHITEWATER (Washington) _ Whitewater prosecutors urge the
Supreme Court not to throw out the guilty plea of President
Clinton's friend Webster Hubbell to a misdemeanor tax charge.
Hubbell's attorney argues that incriminating documents used against
his client were obtained illegally. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SLAVERY-SEX (Washington) _ International trafficking in young
women and girls for the purposes of prostitution is ``slavery pure
and simple,'' a State Department official tells a Senate panel.
About one million women are forced into the sex trade against their
will each year, and 50,000 are brought to the United States. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-HOLT (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ Houston Astros pitcher Chris Holt
tries to overcome injuries and return to his promising form of two
seasons ago. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ One of the saddest sights in
politics is a formerly important public figure refusing to concede
that his or her time has passed. We see that now in Ralph Nader,
the consumer advocate whose crusades have faded and who no longer
attracts attention. He just announced his candidacy for the White
House on the Green Party ticket, a losing cause if there ever was
one. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
