<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZINFANDELS PLAY THE CLOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everybody knows that wine is a serious, dignified
business. The fear of using the wrong word or the wrong glass or
even of liking the wrong wine has stifled the pleasure of more than
a few would-be wine lovers. Words like funny, silly, informal and
relaxed do not come to mind in a world of Chateau Grand Mal de
Tete, right?
</P>
<P>
   Yet, more than a few California wine producers have been joking
around with their wines for years, coming up with names and labels
that, if not exactly funny, are at least silly and occasionally
even ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   The comic turn is mostly applied to zinfandels. Robert Sin-skey
Vineyards of Napa Valley, for example, refrains from yuk-king it up
with its chardonnays, merlots and pinot noirs, but its zinfandel is
another matter.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``The Adventures of Zin-skey,'' and offers up the
winemaker as pulp superhero: ``Commander Zinskey must find and save
the exploited zinfandel vines before the White Zin Supremacists
subvert the world!''
</P>
<P>
   Commander Zinskey stands tall among his fellow zinfandel
infidels, including Cardinal Zin from Bonny Doon Vineyards, whose
owner, Randall Grahm, is an inveterate punster; Zebra Zin from
Harrison Winery; Grandmere Zin from Renwood; Gnarly Vine from Louis
M. Martini; and Mother Clone from Pedroncelli.
</P>
<P>
   Why zinfandel as an object of jest? Maybe it's the letter ``z,''
which seems inherently comical, or maybe it's the fact that
zinfandel is produced only in the United States, permitting
winemakers to behave subversively, making up for a perhaps overly
respectful attitude toward European wines like cabernet sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the silly names, the wines themselves are serious,
well-made and surprisingly good. Most cost $20 to $30, but the
nonvintage Barefoot Zin at $7 easily holds its own with the more
expensive bottles. These six bottles are listed in order of
preference. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COSENTINO WINERY, THE ZIN, CALIFORNIA, 1997 $23 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rich, ripe and fruity with a tannic finish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HARRISON WINERY, ZEBRA ZIN, NAPA VALLEY, 1998 $25 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ul and robust, with invitingly sweet berry flavors; tannic
finish. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BAREFOOT ZIN, CALIFORNIA, NV $7 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peppery, minty aromas, raspberry-cherry flavors, light bodied. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BONNY DOON VINEYARD, CARDINAL ZIN, GNARLY OLD VINES, &QL; 
CALIFORNIA, 1998 $23 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Herbal aromas, sweet berry and chocolate flavors, firmly
tannic. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LORENZA-LAKE WINERY, BLOCKHEADIA RINGNOSII, CALIFORNIA, 1998
$20 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cherry-mint aromas, blackberry and chocolate flavors. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT SINSKEY VINEYARDS, THE ADVENTURES OF ZINSKEY, 1996
$19.50 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spicy aromas but light bodied, pleasant but unconcentrated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prices are those paid in various Manhattan wine shops. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
