<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4799 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-MCCAIN-GOOKS-HNS &LR;      02-22 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-GOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN'S TONGUE GOT HIM IN TROUBLE BEFORE `GOOKS' REMARK  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Long before he unapologetically used the word
``gooks'' to describe his Vietnamese torturers, Sen. John McCain
had uttered several eyebrow-raising phrases.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the senior senator from Arizona who is seeking the
Republican presidential nomination, was a veteran Navy pilot who
was shot down and held captive during the Vietnam war. He also is
know for these remarks:
</P>
<P>
   _ When he first ran for Congress in the early 1980s, he referred
to the Leisure World community for senior citizens as ``Seizure
World.''
</P>
<P>
   _ He once said the nice thing about getting Alzheimer's disease
``is that you get to hide your own Easter eggs.'' Last year, he
said his party was about as popular as Jeffrey Dahmer, the
cannibalistic mass murderer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last summer in Washington, he asked fellow Republicans at a
fund-raiser if they knew why Chelsea Clinton was so ugly. ``Because
Janet Reno is her father,'' McCain said, referring to Attorney
General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   McCain certainly isn't the first politician to utter a mistake
of the mouth. But analysts say a pattern of off-color remarks may
cause voters to question a candidate's judgment and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all make mistakes and if we were judged by every single
slight, we'd all be in trouble. But what you look for is a pattern
of behavior,'' said Michael Genovese, an author on the presidency
and a professor at Loyola Marymount University in Los Angeles. ``He
is often indelicate in his language and it goes beyond political
correctness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the race) is a character test, then verbal references have
to become an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of McCain's remarks, including his reference to ``gooks''
nearly five months ago, had been widely reported in the mainstream
media. But last week, when McCain defended his use of the ethnic
slur to the large campaign press corps covering the South Carolina
primary, the issue hit the front pages.
</P>
<P>
   Republican analyst Tony Quinn of Sacramento, who served in
Vietnam, said that the word ``gooks'' has always been an
unmistakable ethnic slur and McCain's use of it may offend more
people in California, with its growing Asian population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was perfectly clear that the phrase was used by GIs to
refer to all Vietnamese. It applies not just to bad guys and
communists but it's generic and derogatory. When he comes to
California, he's going to have to be a lot more sensitive to
that,'' Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Although unapologetic for his use of the word, McCain said he
was describing his captors during five years of imprisonment.
McCain spokesman Dan Schnur said the senator would no longer use
the word.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``it's beyond the pale,'' said Elaine Kim, a professor of
Asian-American studies at the University of California at Berkeley.
``To be mean-spirited and express misogynistic and racist views and
then people say, `Oh, the poor guy, don't take it too seriously.'
It's very low class and crummy. He stands for the dominant theory
that people in power can say whatever they feel like.''
</P>
<P>
   Schnur said that much of McCain's appeal is his willingness to
be candid and not to work from a script. ``Most voters would prefer
a candidate like John McCain who talks straight to them even if he
sometimes offends them,'' Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara O'Connor, a communications professor at California State
University in Sacramento, said ``the average person'' would not
hold the ``gooks'' remark against the senator. ``He's an
iconoclast, and he's quick at labeling; he's lively, but I think
that's what people like about him.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Conner said voter should delve more into McCain's record on
Vietnam, which has shown him to be at the forefront of normalizing
relations with the former enemy. But if McCain's main opponent for
the Republican nomination, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, makes it a
larger issue, she said, the context might be overshadowed by the
more immediate blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Margita Thompson said the issue hasn't been
raised in the Bush camp. But she gave McCain a slight jab, saying,
``We're focused on bringing people under the tent and not using
language that leaves them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Schnur defended McCain's past off-color remarks as joking and
said the senator uses the Alzheimer's remark on himself when he
forgets a point he wanted to make. And Schnur said McCain
apologized profusely for the Chelsea Clinton joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apology unaccepted,'' said Helen Grieco, president of the
California National Organization for Women.
</P>
<P>
   Grieco said calling Vietnamese ``gooks,'' then bragging about
normalizing relations is ``talking out of two sides of his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't support issues and have a `slip of the tongue' and
degrade people you purport to respect. This questions his
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is not alone among politicians:
</P>
<P>
   _ Jesse Jackson, a Democratic presidential hopeful, was roundly
denounced in 1984 for his use of the word ``hymies'' to describe
Jews in a private conversation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ronald Reagan was famous for telling off-color jokes as
California governor, and it never touched him. ``It was like,
`There goes ol Uncle Ron again,'' Genovese said.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1988, George Bush referred to his own Hispanic
grandchildren as ``the little brown ones.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Agriculture Secretary Earl Butz in 1976 resigned after saying
a black man was uninterested in the political process as long as he
had ``good sex, loose shoes and a warm place to s---.'' Butz said
the remark ``in no way reflects my real attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether McCain's language becomes an issue with voters is
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Zia of Oakland, Calif., the author of a book on
Asian-Americans, said McCain's joke about Chelsea Clinton was
unpresidential and cruel.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Zia said it could hurt the Arizona senator among women
voters, who made up 41 percent of his votes in his remarkable New
Hampshire primary victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he seems to not care about civility or courtesy and
respect for what his constituents might feel, then you have to
start wondering,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
