<P>
   NY-DIALLO-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Amadou Diallo gave four police
officers no choice but to fire 41 bullets at him when he refused to
stop for questioning and drew what appeared to be a gun, defense
attorneys argued Tuesday. ``That's not unreasonable behavior on
their part,'' attorney John Patten said in closing arguments at the
officers' murder trial. ``That's unreasonable on his part.'' The
black object in the unarmed Bronx man's hand turned out to be a
wallet. But when he pulled it out, ``that was it,'' Patten told
jurors. ``You can't expect (the officers) to stand there and get
blasted away.'' (Summary from wires) By Jane Fritsch.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT11,12.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOMELESS (New York) _ A state court said Tuesday that the
Giuliani administration cannot bar single adults from shelters if
they fail to meet work requirements and other welfare rules. The
court said that the rules _ a centerpiece of the Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani's policies on the homeless _ violate a 19-year-old court
decree guaranteeing homeless people the right to shelter. While
yesterday's decision applied only to single adults, advocates for
the homeless said they would argue that the ruling could also
prevent the city from ejecting homeless parents from shelters _ and
putting their children in foster care _ if they fail to meet the
stringent welfare requirements. By Nina Bernstein.
</P>
