<HEADER>
A4811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANARCHY-BOOK-REVIEW-N     02-22 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANARCHY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE COMING ANARCHY': DASHING HOPES OF GLOBAL HARMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How long do eras last? To the people of the Tang dynasty in
China during the eighth century or those of the Ottoman Empire a
millennium later and probably to most Americans today, they might
seem to last forever. They don't, of course, or at least they
haven't. Yet it is difficult to imagine how, for example, the
stable, prosperous and powerful United States might turn into
something very different from what it is today. Might it defy the
historical rule and last forever?
</P>
<P>
   That is not exactly the question that Robert D. Kaplan addresses
in ``The Coming Anarchy,'' his analytically daring collection of
essays on the face of global things to come, but it lurks
nonetheless. Kaplan, a frequent commentator on foreign affairs and
the author of ``Balkan Ghosts'' and ``The Ends of the Earth,''
seeks to create ``an unrelenting record of uncomfortable truths, of
the kind that many of us implicitly acknowledge but will not
publicly accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among these ``uncomfortable truths'' is that a new kind of
global anarchy instigated by poverty, swelling populations and a
culture of militarized gangsterism and transnational corporations
is taking shape under our very noses. It is likely to change
forever the world of stable nation-states with stable borders that
most of us have come to see as pretty much permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan is a knowledgeable and forceful polemicist who mixes the
attributes of journalist and visionary. These terse, confident
essays (most of which have been published previously in magazines)
are often conceptually brilliant even if they are too fragmentary
and diverse to add up to a fully formulated defense of the author's
main postulate. Tossed into the mix, for example, is an essay on
Henry A. Kissinger's 1957 book on the Austrian diplomat Metternich
and another on Joseph Conrad's literary depiction of the third
world. While very worthwhile in themselves, the essays glance
tangentially on Kaplan's central theme. He ends with a bravura,
counterintuitive chapter called ``The Dangers of Peace,'' which
argues that a little bit of anarchy is a very good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Here and there one wants to argue. Kaplan's title essay focuses
on the deterioration of life in West Africa and South Asia, where
pressure on land and resources, environmental degradation and the
availability of rootless young men to serve in private armies will
lead to a ``withering away of central governments, the rise of
tribal and regional domains, the unchecked spread of disease and
the growing pervasiveness of war.''
</P>
<P>
   This will affect the United States in many ways, he says, not
least because its government may feel obligated to police the
coming anarchy. The collapse of West Africa will also intensify
racial stereotypes in the United States, he argues, and increase
domestic political conflict. More generally, other forces will
``make the United States less of a nation than it is today,''
Kaplan says.
</P>
<P>
   Canada will eventually dissolve, he predicts, and the United
States will pick up some of its territory. Meanwhile, he asserts,
``many future regimes, ours especially, could resemble the
oligarchies of ancient Athens and Sparta more than they do the
current government in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Assertions like that are so sweepingly speculative that they are
both irrefutable and unprovable. The dire conclusion about coming
anarchy seems overdrawn. West African states may indeed face ``an
anarchic implosion of criminal violence,'' but it does not
necessarily follow that West Africa will prove a paradigm for
``most of the rest of the world'' or that its collapse would
profoundly shake the foundations of European and American
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ome of Kaplan's remarks are infused with such pleasure at the
force of his ideas that they acquire lives of their own. The notion
that ``the recently expanded NATO'' is ``a variation of the Western
Holy Roman Empire,'' illustrating how the world is ``awash in
dangerous new alliances,'' is one example. What new alliances
Kaplan does not exactly specify, though he does talk in other
essays of a looming clash of civilizations identified in 1993 by
Samuel Huntington, a political scientist at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kaplan's bold assertions do concentrate the mind. ``The
Coming Anarchy'' is informed by a rock-solid, unwavering realism
and an utter absence of sentimentality. One essay, ``Was Democracy
Just a Moment?,'' which enumerates the problems of a foreign policy
shaped by a yearning to spread American values, is a model of
clearheadedness.
</P>
<P>
   The book also conveys a historically informed tragic sense in
recognizing humankind's tendency toward a kind of slipshod, gooey,
utopian and ultimately dangerous optimism. This is most on display
in the final essay, on the dangers of peace. Several themes are
blended here, but Kaplan mainly warns against the rhapsodic notion
that we may one day live in a conflict-free world benignly governed
by some supranational U.N.-like body. This, he eloquently argues,
would not be the happy future so many envision but a dark one. A
society whose overriding goal is peace is a society unaware that it
must fight and make sacrifices for some principles and interests,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avoiding tragedy requires a sense of it,'' Kaplan writes. ``In
an era of extended domestic peace, those who deliver up pleasures
are the power brokers. Because pleasure is inseparable from
convenience, convenience becomes the vital element in society.''
</P>
<P>
   I cannot imagine a more succinct identification of the
underlying cause of so many broader cultural trends of American
life, from the substitution of documentary-style entertainment for
the broadcast news, to the high-altitude strategy of NATO's war in
Kosovo, to the loss of historical memory. ``Permanent peace, with
its worship of entertainment and convenience, will produce ever
shallower leaders,'' Kaplan contends. It is a disturbing thought,
like many of his thoughts, and it just might be true.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE COMING ANARCHY'
</P>
<P>
   Shattering the Dreams of the Post-Cold-War
</P>
<P>
   By Robert D. Kaplan
</P>
<P>
   198 pages. Random House. $21.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
