<SLUG> BC-BOURBON-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE MEALS THESE DAYS ARE BEING ACCOMPANIED BY COCKTAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So many wine snobs, so little patience. That's why
one of my favorite drinking buddies is Al Hirschfeld, the
96-year-old artist, who can't be bothered with sermons on grassy
undertones. He's a Jack Daniel's man. And when we go out together,
he prefers to keep drinking it past cocktails and through the meal,
which, by the way, he prefers to be steak.
</P>
<P>
   I love a guy who breaks the rules, almost as much as I love
breaking them myself. Because my dirty little secret is, I'm
drinking right along with him _ Maker's Mark bourbon. And while I'm
not as enamored of steak, I am enamored of sitting down to dinner
after a hard day's work and doing exactly as I please, which some
nights means having a drink. And another.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I would ever do so at a place like Montrachet, where
the food is perfectly paired with the wine. That would be
foolishness. But like many New Yorkers who dine out frequently
during the week, sometimes the last thing I have energy for is a
correct dinner with wine. Sticking with a cocktail constitutes a
break, a vacation from the conventions of dining. A few Maker's
Marks and a meatloaf sandwich at Joe Allen is my equivalent of
Linus' blanket. On those nights, it beats foie gras and Sauternes
every time.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, admitting this in today's superserious world of food
and wine is nothing short of treason. And doing it as a woman has a
double whammy attached: Slugging booze instead of sipping wine has
always been barmaid behavior, pure and simple. At least Hirschfeld
has an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got used to drinking hard liquor during Prohibition,'' he
says. ``There were Virginia Dare stores, very popular in the city,
where you could buy an essence of gin, vodka, Scotch or bourbon,
then go to the drugstore with a prescription from the doctor for
alcohol. You poured the essence into it. The other kind of alcohol
was wood alcohol, which blinded you. Virginia Dare sold wine
essence too, but that was a more complicated process.''
</P>
<P>
   While I certainly can't plead Prohibition, as it happens, I have
increasingly more company in my wicked, wicked ways. As highly
spiced fusion and pan-Latino cuisines become more popular, spirits
are finally staying up past the cocktail hour and sitting down to
dinner. It only makes sense, really, that as traditions about food
bend and break, drink would follow. In polite society, it used to
be the mark of a heathen to sit at table with a cocktail, even
though that heathen had been a gentleman a scant half-hour earlier
in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinking vodka or gin through the meal was the sign of a real
drunk,'' says Letitia Baldrige, the etiquette expert, who was
Jacqueline Kennedy's social secretary at the White House. ``It was
very frowned upon. Cocktails kill the taste of the food. You cannot
enjoy the subtleties of good food if you are deadening your tongue
while eating it.'' She sighed heartily. ``This is a new
affectation. That must be New York. Quelle horreur.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale DeGroff doesn't think so. The bartender extraordinaire,
late of the Rainbow Room and Blackbird, now consulting to Windows
on the World, introduced cocktail dinners at the Rainbow Room in
1994, matching a juniper-roasted venison chop and black olive
mashed potatoes with a Blood and Sand cocktail made of J&AMP;B Select
Scotch, Cherry Heering, sweet vermouth and orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you see spice, the more you see spirits,'' he says.
``It's a coming thing. The rules are breaking down a little bit.
Thai, Chinese, Mexican, Ethiopian and Latin American food all go
well with spirits. In Mexico, tequila is a table beverage; in
Russia, vodka is a table beverage. They are meant to be paired with
food, in little tiny shots. In this country you're seeing it more
and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Immer, the corporate director of beverage programs for
Starwood Hotels, agrees. ``Pan-Latino is taking off, and that food
has a vibrant cocktail culture attached, with caipirinhas and
mojitos,'' she says. ``With Mexican food, people have been
automatically programmed to cocktails _ margaritas and daiquiris.
Where restaurants have really fused Asian foods, they've found that
cocktails are automatic connectors. The big thing with Generation X
has been sake martinis, which are lighter than traditional
martinis, with less alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's usually easier for a restaurant to pull off cocktails
than an interesting program of wines by the glass,'' she goes on.
``Thai or Chinese cuisine needs something like a Gewuerztraminer,
and the average person doesn't relate to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sticking with cocktails is also a way to keep the party going
through the night. And if the partyers are older than 25, there is
a nod to hangover prevention by avoiding the mix of liquor with
wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a second martini, you're inclined to have red
wine, then you're inclined to Cognac, then you're inclined to
morning pain,'' says Clark Wolf, a food and restaurant consultant
based in Manhattan. ``I'm a firm believer in drinking Scotch
through the meal, as long as you choose food that goes well with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He considers these to be smoked salmon, steak, hamburgers and
wild mushrooms. As for drinking martinis through the meal, Wolf
says gin martinis are too complex to mix well with food, but vodka
martinis ``with vestigial vermouth'' go well with light fish like
sole. With steak, he says, vodka martinis taste better with a bit
more vermouth and ``dirty olives,'' meaning a bit of the brine is
added to the drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not to diminish the great pleasures of a meal with
wine,'' he continues, ``but we all eat out so often, we don't want
an epiphany five nights in a row. Look at people's faces when they
receive a cocktail. It's like the Yanks have landed.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
