<HEADER>
A4814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-BOURBON-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      02-22 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOURBON-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: have landed.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At some places, like Lot 61, which is part restaurant, part
club, 61 is the number of flavors the martinis come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to sip martinis with dinner,'' says its owner, Amy
Sacco. ``I've even seen people having vanilla martinis with their
dinner. A great wine really embraces a meal, more so than a
martini. But to each his own. What I always say is anytime is a
good time for one if you feel like it _ with lunch, through dinner;
there are no rules. In fashion and art and family life, the molds
have all been broken. Look at fusion cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   She gets no argument from Drew Nieporent, an owner of the Myriad
Restaurant Group, which includes Layla, the Middle Eastern
restaurant with belly-dancing floor shows, and Icon, at the W Court
Hotel. ``At Layla, liquor sales have skyrocketed since we started a
pomegranate margarita,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There are other considerations, too, when it comes to sticking
with cocktails. Though no one would be quoted about it, there was a
consensus that the Wall Streeters with new money would rather play
it safe with mixed drinks than risk the humiliation of ordering the
wrong bottle of wine. And many women, myself included, prefer to
skip the experience of ordering wine by the bottle when a man is
not at the table; more often than not, the condescension of the
server still leaves a rotten taste. Cocktails make the evening
easier. And, I must say, I have never encountered a raised eyebrow
from a server by ordering cocktails in place of wine; no one is a
snob when the tip escalates with each additional drink.
</P>
<P>
   On the home entertaining front, Marian McEvoy, the editor of
Elle Decor, says she has noticed a marked decline in her male
guests' consumption of wine with dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``More men have been going through the meal with their Scotch
and soda or vodka,'' she says. ``Maybe they never did like wine,
and they've decided they're not going to pretend anymore to know
about it or to like it.''
</P>
