   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McEvoy, who lived in Paris for 15 years, says the furthest the
French might go in deviating from wine with dinner is to start with
Champagne, then carry it through, a practice she does not follow.
``That's how to turn off a table of men,'' she says. ``Serve
Champagne.''
</P>
<P>
   You actually can order Champagne at Charlie Trotter's, the
celebrated restaurant in Chicago, but no mixed drinks of any kind.
``We don't have spirits in the house,'' said the reservationist who
answered the phone. ``They don't go with the food. And we've spent
a lot of money on our wine program, so we concentrate on that.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in New York, thankfully, is nearly that rigid, though
more than a few restaurateurs bristled when I asked if they've
noticed an increase in cocktail drinking through dinner. They
seemed to perceive the question as an insult to their winehood.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Snyder, the restaurant manager at the ``21'' Club,
lectured me on his extensive cellar, and Michael Cetta, the owner
of Sparks Steakhouse, which has one of the most impressive wine
lists in the city, protested: ``Drinking martinis during dinner?
That's uncivilized.'' Julian Niccolini, an owner of the Four
Seasons restaurant, says he has noticed an increase in hard liquor
sales before dinner, but is selling more red wine tableside than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, cocktail dinners, whether comfort inspired, fusion
inspired or gourmet inspired, go forward, like them or not.
Wednesday night, for instance, the authors Gary Regan and Mardee
Haidin Regan, whose four books include ``The Book of Bourbon''
(Chapters) and ``The Martini Companion'' (Running Press), are
teaming up for one with Donna Hammond, the chef at Painter's Tavern
in Cornwall-on-Hudson, N.Y. They are beginning with a martini circa
1900, Regan says, which means ``50-50 vermouth and gin.''
</P>
<P>
   Though my husband the martini purist winced when I told him
this, the idea of it didn't bother me much. I never drink martinis
_ to me they smell like the doctor's office right before you get a
shot. And Regan was philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a martini as we would recognize it today,'' he said,
``but out of context as another drink, it works well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With it, as an appetizer, we're having tapenade,'' he added,
``because what goes better with a martini than olives?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
