<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING TO SONOMA FOR CABERNETS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Sonoma County winemakers have nothing better to do, they
like to needle the folks over the mountain in Napa County,
particularly if there's a gullible audience. To hear the Sonoma
crowd tell it, Napa people are social-climbing pseudo-sophisticates
who wear designer clothes and get their cars washed.
</P>
<P>
   Sonomans, they will insist, are simple country folk,
warm-hearted, generous and close to the soil. Napa people make
elegant cabernet sauvignon, while Sonomans prefer earthier, more
accessible wines like pinot noir and zinfandel.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma's wineries do indeed make some of the finest zinfandels
and pinot noirs, but they make terrific cabernets, too. As a group,
Sonoma cabernets tend to be overlooked _ an indignity, and it needs
to go.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma County itself can be deceptive. It looks rural and open,
but its population is three times larger than Napa's. Napa is
neatly arranged: almost all the towns and wineries are distributed
along two parallel roads, Highway 29 and the Silverado Trail.
</P>
<P>
   From the city of Napa at the south end to Calistoga in the north
is a 30-minute drive when traffic is light.
</P>
<P>
   In Sonoma County, distances are great. From the town of Sonoma
north to Cloverdale is more than 50 miles; the western border of
the Sonoma coast region starts at San Pablo Bay and runs more than
70 miles, most of it along the Pacific Ocean, to the Mendocino
County line.
</P>
<P>
   The variety of soils and climates in this big county is
enormous, and winemakers are only beginning to learn how to exploit
such diversity. But there are patterns.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to generalize when so many variables are in play,
but as a rule, Sonoma cabernets are rounder and fleshier than the
Napa cabernets.
</P>
<P>
   If any comparison can be drawn, it should be between the wines
of the Medoc _ Pauillac and Margaux _ and the wines of St.-Emilion
and Pomerol. They are all Bordeaux wines, but traditionally, the
St.-Emilions and Pomerols are more approachable, less austere.
</P>
<P>
   Good cabernets are produced all over Sonoma County, but some of
the best are in the Sonoma Valley, north of the town of Sonoma but
still in the southern half of the county. Sebastiani, Buena Vista,
Gundlach-Bund-schu, Carmenet, Arrowood, Chateau St.-Jean, St.
Francis and Kenwood are among the best cabernet makers.
</P>
<P>
   In the north, centered on the town of Healdsburg, are three
famous cabernet-producing viticultural regions: Dry Creek, Chalk
Hill and the Alexander Valley. Simi, Chalk Hill, Rodney Strong,
Ferrari-Carano, Jordan, Bellerose and Gallo Sonoma are a few of the
wineries to look for.
</P>
<P>
   Benziger Winery, in the Sonoma Valley, once noted for its
inexpensive Glen Ellen label, has become an important name among
Sonoma's fine wines. The 1995 Cabernet Sauvignon shows why. With
merlot and cabernet franc to smooth it, this is a large-scale wine
with, it would seem, good staying power. It is rich, nicely
structured and worth its $35 price.
</P>
<P>
   In the same general region, but up on the western slope of the
Mayacamas range, Carmenet Vineyard, part of the Chalone group of
wineries, is dedicated to making Bordeaux-style wines. Theirs are
more concentrated and less opulent than some of their Sonoma
neighbors', but they are more approachable than most Bordeaux. Look
for the 1996 Moon Mountain Reserve, at about $40.
</P>
<P>
   B.R. Cohn is another Sonoma Valley winery skilled in fine cabs.
The Olive Hill Estate 1996, about $35, is loaded with intense fruit
flavor. Kenwood Vineyards draws on grapes from the nearby Jack
London Vineyard for its best cabernet (London lived and wrote in
the Sonoma Valley). The wine, about $30, has good body and an
intriguing bouquet of fruits and berries.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Vineyards may be the best-known Alexander Valley winery.
Its 1995 cabernet, about $35, is a typical Jordan wine: smooth,
velvety and easy to drink.
</P>
<P>
   Much more imposing is a wine from Kendall-Jackson's impressive
Single Vineyard Series, the 1996 Buckeye Vineyard cabernet
sauvignon. This is a big, elegant wine with layers of flavors and a
lovely, long finish. At $65, it's a wine for dedicated cabernet
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Benziger, using grapes from Ash Creek Vineyard, in the Alexander
Valley, produced a full-bodied 1996 cabernet in a slightly
different style (about $30).
</P>
<P>
   Simi Winery has a long, distinguished history in Healdsburg. It
is no longer owned by Moet-Hennessy, but its wines are still
notable, particularly the 1994 Reserve Sonoma County cabernet, with
immense character (about $40). It has a smoky quality, something
like a great Burgundy, although it most assuredly tastes like
cabernet and not like pinot noir.
</P>
<P>
   A unique entry on this list is the Herzog 1996 Alexander Valley
Special Reserve cabernet, at about $26. It is a kosher wine,
meaning it's pasteurized. Even so, it will easily hold its own with
nonkosher wines at higher prices, and the string of awards garnered
by Herzog wines in recent years is proof.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Strong's Northern Sonoma Reserve 1995 cabernet is another
fine issue from this well-known winery, with lots of fruit in a
medium-bodied concentrated wine. It sells for about $40, but the
winery also has a velvety 1996 cabernet with a Sonoma County
appellation that's a true bargain at about $16.
</P>
<P>
   Knights Valley, in northeastern Sonoma, is sandwiched between
the northern Napa Valley and the Alexander Valley _ and most of it
is planted by Beringer Vineyards. Beringer is one of the leaders in
offering genuine values in fine wine, and its Knights Valley
cabernet is a good example.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 sells for about $25 and is the equivalent of many wines
at $15 or $20 more. What's more, Beringer makes quite a bit of it.
It should be relatively easy to find.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
