<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RILEY SUGGESTS YEAR-ROUND JOBS FOR TEACHERS
 &HT;    320&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ School systems should consider hiring teachers to
work a full year instead of nine or 10 months, Education Secretary
Richard Riley suggested Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In his seventh annual ``State of American Education'' address,
Riley said the United States has outgrown two assumptions:
</P>
<P>
   ``One assumption was that the job of a teacher lasted nine
months,'' he said. The other was that the nation ``would always
have a ready supply of dedicated teachers, mostly women, who for
relatively low wages would teach our children their lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said working year-round would raise teachers' annual
income and give them more time to plan courses, improve their
skills, and provide some students extra help.
</P>
<P>
   Riley did not propose a federal role in establishing or
financing a longer work year for teachers, and added, ``I am not
proposing year-round schooling for all children. These decisions
about school schedules are best left up to each individual school
district.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech at Southern High School here, Riley also called
for more federal aid for education in return for a ``mid-course''
review of school reforms by the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no slowdown, no moratorium when it comes to
putting high standards in place,'' Riley said. ``At the same time,
we must not make the mistake of reducing our effort to raise
standards to a 'blame and shame' game _ blaming schools for not
doing enough, and shaming students, teachers and parents for a lack
of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   He announced new grants of $30 million from the Mott Foundation
for after-school programs and another $30 million by the GE Fund to
help high school students qualify for college.
</P>
<P>
   He also outlined President Clinton's plan for a 12 percent
increase in spending by Riley's department, which would be the
biggest in history and include $1 billion for programs to improve
teacher quality.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   His detailed list of proposals was quickly attacked by House
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, in the first formal response
ever by Republicans to the annual addresses that Riley inaugurated
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Washington provides less than 10 percent of the money
for schools, it creates 80 percent of the paperwork,'' Riley said
in a speech at a charter school in Pasadena, Calif. Demonstrators
outside Riley's speech in Durham held aloft ``school choice'' signs
and distributed copies of Armey's speech.
</P>
<P>
   Armey called for consolidating federal education spending into
block grants and using some of the funds to finance vouchers, which
would help parents of children in failing public schools to pay for
their children's tuition at private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's create more choices for parents and teachers to do what
they find works with the children whose names they know,'' Armey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Armey's suggestions had been brushed aside by Riley in
his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no accountability when it comes to block grants and
vouchers,'' Riley said. ``I travel all over the country visiting
with teachers and parents, and I have never heard one parent tell
me, 'Go back to Washington and support block grants.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
