u i BC-IRAN-ELECT-NYT &LR;      02-22 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORMERS APPEAR TO BE THE BIG WINNERS IN IRAN'S ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Many of the conservative parliamentarians who led
the opposition to President Mohammad Khatami's reform program
apparently were soundly defeated in voting on Friday, according to
independent analysts who tallied up the hardliners' losses Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Vote-counting was nearly complete in the major cities, including
the capital, Tehran, although no official results will be announced
until the end of the week, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But preliminary results in Tehran, plus the decided races in
provincial areas, already indicate that the conservatives have lost
most of their senior representatives in the Parliament, analysts
for several foreign embassies and Iranian political parties said.
</P>
<P>
   A runoff election will be needed to decide the winner of some 60
to 65 seats in the 290-member Parliament, they added. The runoff
has tentatively been set for sometime in April.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most closely watched races, the former president
of Iran, Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, was barely holding on to
30th, or last, place in Tehran, which accounts for 30 seats in the
Parliament. It was not clear whether he would even get the minimum
number of votes _ 25 percent of those cast in the capital _ to
claim a seat in the first round, or whether he would be forced into
a runoff election.
</P>
<P>
   The top 29 vote-getters in the capital appear to be from the
reform camp that supports Khatami and advocates cultural freedoms,
including liberating the press from clerical censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami's brother, Mohammad Reza Khatami, has held onto his lead
as the top vote-getter in the capital since the counting started.
Most analysts, including those for the reformers, give the
pro-Khatami forces about 70 percent of the seats in the first round
and the conservatives about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The tallies differ according to the analyst, however, because
some independent candidates are claimed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the elections, a spokesman for the
defeated conservatives admitted publicly Tuesday that they have
suffered a damaging blow.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, Mohammad Reza Bahonar, one of the most prominent
ideologues of the conservative side, suggested in an interview with
a Tehran newspaper that hard-liners have some soul-searching to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not change our principles and positions, but it is
natural that we should reconsider our policies and methods,'' he
was quoted as saying in the newspaper Iran Vig. Bahonar also lost
his parliamentary seat in Tehran, according to unofficial results.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference Tuesday to proclaim victory in the
parliamentary poll, the reformers pledged to push for legalizing
satellite dishes and allowing a free public debate of religious and
social issues that hard-liners had tried to suppress.
</P>
<P>
   But the younger Khatami warned that normalization of relations
with the United States _ an issue that some of his allies have
suggested should be put to a public vote _ would depend on action
by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States supported the totalitarian regime of the
shah,'' he said. ``And now that Iran has become one of the most
free nations, it continues its policy of sanctions and continues
its baseless claims against Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States cut off relations with Iran during the 1979
revolution, after students seized its embassy in Tehran and held 52
diplomats captive. It also has classified Iran as a state that
sponsors terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the paradoxes of Iran's budding reform movement, some
of its most prominent advocates for opening the country to the
outside world and institutionalizing democratic values were either
hostage-takers or supporters of the seizure.
</P>
<P>
   The poor showing by Rafsanjani, a veteran political operator who
has held high government positions since the Islamic revolution 21
years ago, surprised even his reformist critics.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to the Feb. 18 elections, most
commentators considered Rafsanjani a shoo-in not only for a
Parliament seat, but also for the post of speaker.
</P>
<P>
   He was described as a man who could provide balance in the
Parliament between the up-and-coming leftists and their adversaries
on the right. Many analysts had assumed that most Tehran voters,
who could choose 30 candidates, would include Rafsanjani as a
stabilizing factor.
</P>
<P>
   Rafsanjani had long been considered outside Iran as a political
moderate who allowed the publication of independent newspapers and
took steps to liberalize the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, some of the pro-Khatami activists have
openly accused him of steering government contracts to family
members during his presidency and failing to support the cause of
reformers jailed over the past two years for expressing their
political views.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1659EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
