<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADICCHIO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADICCHIO AND ENDIVE FREE OF THE SALAD BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By JACK BISHOP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ American cooks have adopted radicchio and endive as
their own. Just try to find a restaurant that doesn't serve one or
both of these bitter ``lettuces,'' considered exotic just 10 years
ago and impossible to find in many parts of the country. Now, even
mini-marts carry bagged tricolor salad mixes with radicchio, endive
and some sort of greenery.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the radicchio revolution seems to have stopped at
the salad bar. That's a shame, because many cooks are missing out
on the best way to enjoy the delightfully distinctive flavors of
radicchio and endive _ by cooking them.
</P>
<P>
   Once you think of radicchio and endive as vegetables, and not
just salad greens, the possibilities are almost endless. Roasted
radicchio is smoky and crisp, but wilt it with pancetta and onions,
and radicchio becomes soft and even a tad sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Cider-braised endive is creamy and sweet, but bake it under a
blanket of cream and Parmesan and the result is a nutty rich dish
worthy of the finest prime rib or beef tenderloin.
</P>
<P>
   The directions for roasting, grilling and pan-searing radicchio
are basically the same: oil the wedges well to keep the leaves from
drying out, then cook, turning once, until lightly browned. Timing
is the only difference. In the oven, radicchio needs about 20
minutes to brown and soften. Over coals or in a hot skillet,
cooking time will be five minutes or less.
</P>
<P>
   Although grilling and pan-searing are quicker than roasting, you
must be vigilant, since radicchio can turn to ashes rather quickly.
Roasting is still relatively quick and goof-proof.
</P>
<P>
   The brash flavor of radicchio doesn't change much when cooked.
If anything, it is even more assertive, with smoky overtones from
the light charring that occurs. Don't try to compete with this
flavor. Some good olive oil, salt, pepper and maybe a drizzle of
balsamic vinegar just before serving are sufficient seasonings.
Beef is the ideal partner for crisp, lightly browned radicchio.
</P>
<P>
   When slicing radicchio into wedges, keep the core or stem end _
normally cut off when making salads _ to ensure that the layers of
leaves stay together when cooked. Start by cutting each head of
radicchio in half through the core end. Lay the halves cut side
down, and then cut each into two wedges for small to medium
radicchio, or three wedges for larger heads.
</P>
<P>
   These directions assume you have purchased the widely available
rossa di Verona variety, which is round and looks like a miniature
red cabbage. At specialty stores or farmers' markets you may see an
elongated variety (it looks like purple endive) called rossa di
Treviso. It should be sliced in half lengthwise through the stem
end, just like endive.
</P>
<P>
   For those who do want to tone down the bitter flavor of
radicchio, there is one option: treat it as if it were red cabbage.
Shred or coarsely chop it, then wilt it in a covered casserole with
some chopped onions, pancetta (or bacon, prosciutto or sausage) and
garlic.
</P>
<P>
   It will take about 10 minutes for the radicchio to collapse into
a soft mass. Add some wine or broth if the radicchio starts to
scorch, but as long as there are a couple of tablespoons of fat in
the pan and the heat is not too strong, the radicchio should wilt
on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Wilted radicchio can be served with roast pork or duck, or
simmered with cream and used as a sauce for fresh fettuccine.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to build a risotto on top of wilted radicchio.
After 20 minutes of simmering with the rice and stock, the
radicchio will almost melt into the rice. But there is no missing
the effect of the radicchio _ the risotto will be mauve, and the
flavor will be rich and smoky but not bitter.
</P>
<P>
   If radicchio is almost always loud and brash, endive is more of
a chameleon. When cooked, its texture changes from crisp to creamy
and its bitterness mellows considerably. In fact, cooked endive can
taste sweet, making it an appropriate vehicle for a variety of
seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Endive can be braised in white wine, chicken stock, cider, heavy
cream or orange juice, and will soak up flavors from the cooking
liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet and creamy cider-braised endive is the perfect partner for
pork or poultry. Grilled endive with a simple orange-honey glaze
pairs nicely with chicken, duck or even salmon. To change
directions completely, dot endive with butter, dust it lightly with
Gruyere and roast it until lightly browned. Gratineed endive takes
roasted chicken to new heights of luxury.
</P>
<P>
   At the market, choose endive with leaves that are mostly or all
white. Some yellow around the edges is fine, but avoid endive with
green edges, which indicates exposure to light and signals that the
endive will be especially bitter.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   To prepare endive for cooking, remove any limp outer leaves, and
then slice the endive in half lengthwise through the core or stem
end. Because the leaves are still attached to the core, the endive
can be cooked without the individual leaves separating. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED ENDIVE WITH GRUYERE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   4 medium Belgian endive, halved lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded Gruyere (about 2 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Grease a 13-by-9-inch baking
dish with { tablespoon butter. Place endive, cut sides down, in
dish. Cut remaining butter into small bits, and scatter over
endive. Sprinkle with salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   2. Roast endive for 20 minutes. Turn endive cut sides up and
sprinkle evenly with cheese. Continue cooking until endive is
tender and cheese is lightly browned, about 15 minutes. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CIDER-BRAISED ENDIVE WITH MUSTARD AND THYME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 medium Belgian endive, halved lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup apple cider
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh thyme leaves &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Melt butter in a saute pan large enough to hold endive in a
single layer. When butter is hot, add endive, cut sides down. Cook,
turning once, over medium heat until lightly browned, about 8
minutes. Season with salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   2. Turn endive cut sides down, and add cider to pan. Reduce heat
to medium-low, cover and simmer until endive is tender, about 15
minutes. Use slotted spoon to transfer endive to serving platter.
</P>
<P>
   3. Raise heat to high, and simmer liquid in pan until it
thickens and reduces to a couple of tablespoons, 1 to 2 minutes.
Remove from heat, and whisk in mustard and thyme. Adjust seasonings
and drizzle over endive.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 to 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED RADICCHIO WITH BALSAMIC VINEGAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 medium heads radicchio, cut into quarters through core
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon aged balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Place radicchio in a
13-by-9-inch baking dish. Drizzle oil over radicchio, and gently
toss to coat evenly. Sprinkle with salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   2. Roast, turning once with tongs, until radicchio is lightly
browned and tender, about 20 minutes. Drizzle with vinegar, and
serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RISOTTO WITH RADICCHIO AND SAUSAGE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 links sweet Italian sausage (about 6 ounces), casings
discarded, meat crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped fine
</P>
<P>
   2 medium heads radicchio, cored and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   { cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   6 cups chicken or vegetable stock, warmed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   { cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oil in a large saucepan over medium heat. Add sausage
and onion, and saute, breaking up sausage pieces with wooden spoon,
until sausage loses its raw color, about 5 minutes. Add radicchio,
and cook, stirring often, until partially wilted, about 2 minutes.
Add wine, and cook until wine evaporates and radicchio is
completely wilted, about 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add rice, and cook, stirring, for 2 minutes. Ladle 1{ cups of
warm stock into pot. Cook, stirring frequently, until rice absorbs
stock. Continue adding stock in {-cup increments, stirring often,
until rice is creamy and soft but still a bit al dente, 20 to 25
minutes. (Add hot water if you run out of stock.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Off the heat, vigorously beat in butter and cheese with a
wooden spoon. Adjust seasonings, adding salt as necessary, and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 first-course servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
