<HEADER>
A4830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-OAXACA-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     02-22 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAXACA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEASONS OF MY HEART: A CULINARY JOURNEY THROUGH OAXACA, MEXICO':
HOW OAXACA COOKS NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Seasons of My Heart: A Culinary Journey Through Oaxaca,
Mexico,'' Susana Trilling includes a recipe for coctel de camaron,
a pungent shrimp cocktail. The backbone of the dish is an intense
shrimp stock flavored with chilies, but it gains its sweet
undertone from orange soda and its satiny texture from ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   This type of dish illustrates the essence _ and integrity _ of
Trilling's recipes in ``Seasons'' (Ballantine Books, $25).
</P>
<P>
   She does not hesitate to show the true nature of the modern
Oaxacan kitchen. These are the dishes that her neighbors in Oaxaca
make, the dishes that she teaches at her cooking school (also
called Seasons of My Heart) near the city of Oaxaca, and they are
at once intriguing and transporting. Any seemingly out-of-place
ingredients these recipes occasionally call for are just as
authentic as the guajillo chilies, ground shrimp and dried avocado
leaves also used in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Trilling, an American chef whose grandmother was Mexican, was
captivated by the food of Oaxaca while traveling there in 1983.
Several years later she and her husband established a commercial
farm, a bed and breakfast and the cooking school. The book expands
on recipes first presented on Trilling's public television series.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes give a very real portrait of contemporary Oaxacan
cooking, a melding of pre-Hispanic and Spanish influences with a
few modern conveniences. Many Oaxacan cooks today use animal
crackers to thicken moles, as an alternative to more traditional
plantains, nuts, tortillas and fresh masa.
</P>
<P>
   But Trilling only suggests substitutes like crackers and ketchup
when they are used by Oaxacan cooks, not to spare Americans from
searching for obscure ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   And so amassing the ingredients to cook just some of her recipes
meant shopping at three specialty stores. Worse, some techniques
were time-consuming and laborious, even when a blender was
substituted for a metate, the Mexican mortar and pestle.
</P>
<P>
   The mole coloradito took me about four and a half hours. But the
results were unlike anything I had ever cooked, layered with fiery,
fruity, smoky and herbal tastes. Other recipes I tried were equally
enticing, including a salad of grilled cactus paddles, baked sea
bass with olive, caper and tomato salsa, and corn croquettes
stuffed with dried shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   But there were missteps, too. Cilantro rice was mushy and bland.
The sour-cream pound cake recipe was missing half its ingredients,
including flour and sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Trilling gives a vivid picture of Mexican culture,
underscored by the candid photographs that are much more engaging
than heavily styled beauty shots. They take readers right into
Trilling's community and, along with her headnotes and chapter
introductions, give a compelling sense of a way of life at once
ancient and modern. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED POBLANO CHILI BISQUE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Seasons of My Heart: A Culinary Journey Through
Oaxaca, Mexico'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7 poblano chilies
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   2 medium white onions, thickly sliced
</P>
<P>
   7 cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs fresh epazote or 1{ teaspoons dried (available at
specialty spice stores or Mexican markets)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 quart chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces requeson (about one-third cup) or ricotta or farmer
cheese (with salt)
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups milk
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons Mexican fresh crema, heavy cream or creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   4 corn tortillas, 8 inches in diameter, cut into strips and
fried
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large skillet or over a gas flame, roast chilies until
blistered and blackened, turning to roast all sides. Place in a
plastic bag, and set aside until cool enough to handle. Peel
chilies, and remove stems and seeds. Cut flesh into strips 1 inch
wide; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a heavy 4-quart pot, melt butter over medium heat. Saute
onion until transparent, about 5 minutes. Add garlic, and cook
about 5 minutes, stirring so garlic does not brown. Add chili
strips, and cook 20 minutes, stirring occasionally. Add the
epazote, salt and pepper, and stir well. Pour in the stock, cover,
and simmer 15 minutes over low heat.
</P>
<P>
   3. Puree with requeson in a blender or food processor until very
smooth. Return to pot, and add milk. Gently reheat; adjust
seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, divide soup among 6 bowls, and top each with a bit
of crema. Garnish with tortilla strips, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
