<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4832 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV22-     02-22 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV22-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE SIDEWALK TO THE SUBURBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday Feb. 22) 
By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago I met Susan, a one-eyed red-haired homeless woman
with a yellow dog who stood almost daily outside a Trader Joe's
store asking for money.
</P>
<P>
   She did very well on that piece of sidewalk. People would drive
out of the parking lot and read her cardboard sign and pass over
some money, a bag of trail mix, an umbrella, some dog food. The
sign explained she couldn't work because of her missing eye but
didn't qualify for disability benefits because she wasn't blind
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Many were kind to Susan. Some were cruel, like the ones who
yelled at her to get a job or sell her dog.
</P>
<P>
   Susan always maintained that she would eventually get back to a
normal life, but she didn't know how long it would take. ``When you
get down to begging, the way back is real hard,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Susan is back to where she began. She's a ``homed'' person.
She is, in fact, virtually mainstream, a suburbanite, living in a
house with a swimming pool on a cul-de-sac in Hacienda Heights near
Los Angeles. It is not only a roof but almost a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   Susan once said that after you stop being homeless the next
worry is finding a place and keeping it. This is the house Susan
grew up in, now owned by her sisters who inherited it when their
mother died. Susan and her boyfriend pay nominal rent and Susan
sleeps in the same bedroom she had as a girl.
</P>
<P>
   When I first started writing about Susan some people were
suspect. How did I know that she really used the $5 and $10 bills
people gave her to get a motel room? Maybe she bought liquor or
drugs. Maybe she wasn't really a former office manager,
housecleaner and landscaper with two grown kids.
</P>
<P>
   They're the ``free ride'' cynics, who when someone asks for a
handout want to know if the person really needs it, as if asking
for a handout wasn't proof enough of a need.
</P>
<P>
   What I liked about Susan was she had pluck. She knew she would
get off the sidewalk. ``I feel like I snowballed to the bottom and
now I'm going to snowball to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't feel sorry for herself, but neither did she apologize
for asking for help. This was only temporary.
</P>
<P>
   People like Susan often make the comfortable feel uncomfortable.
They try to rationalize the Susans away, make them someone they
would never be. They can't imagine that some Susans were once like
them, with a checkbook and a warm car to drive home.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Susan's one of them now. She started to pull her life
together while she was in Sonoma County with the help of others.
Someone helped her get an eye prosthesis, job training, first and
last months rent and a car that ran. Susan got a part-time job,
relinquished her spot on the sidewalk and moved into an apartment
with her dog and her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Her boyfriend came and went in her life and had his problems
too, working odd jobs. Susan never offered many details about him
but talked like they were a couple.
</P>
<P>
   Now they live together like Mr. and Ms. Hacienda Heights with
cable and a lawn mower bought for $2 at a yard sale. Susan's son,
who is a mailman, lives with them.
</P>
<P>
   Susan works for an agency that provides in-home care and her
last job was with a couple in their 80s named Slim and Marie.
They'd talk about their plumbing business and Susan told them about
all her lives, including the homeless chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Susan has found her own Susan, a woman who goes by the name of
Scotch and lives under the freeway. Susan gives her clothes and
spare change.
</P>
<P>
   Susan said to tell everyone at Trader Joe's hello for her. She
said the one near her neighborhood closed which is too bad because
she always wanted to shop in one.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
