<HEADER>
A4837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-VEGETABLE-SPROUTS-2TA     02-22 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGETABLE-SPROUTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WHISPER OF SPRING IN A SPROUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: recipe in 2nd take)  
 (bl)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine if you took a beet, put it through a juicer,
then reduced its juice until all that was left was the pure sweet
essence of the vegetable. And then you found a way to inject that
essence into a frail little leaf, no longer than a blade of grass.
</P>
<P>
   What you would have would not be a clever invention. It would be
a beet sprout.
</P>
<P>
   What would be clever is if you took that sprout and placed it on
top of a pile of roasted baby beets in the center of a beet and
ginger soup, so that with each bite you would get three different
variations of beet flavor.
</P>
<P>
   That's just what Franklin Becker, the chef at Local, does. And
it is just that little sprout, bright with intense beet flavor,
that makes the dish shine.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, as winter lies in a deep, grey lull, months before
kohlrabi, beets, mustard, kale and daikon radishes start showing up
in the Greenmarkets, the sprouts of these vegetables are already
being harvested. In fact, they are about all that is green at the
markets these days. For chefs, they mean a whole new medium to work
with, and one that more and more are taking advantage of.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable sprouts _ sometimes called microgreens or shoots
depending on the variety _ are simply the vegetables in their early
stages of growth, when they are just a few inches long and the
first few leaves have formed. Frail as they may appear, their
flavor is powerful, and they often contain hints of sweetness,
acidity and grassiness not present in the vegetables themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At 71 Clinton Fresh Food, the chef Wylie Dufresne props beet
sprouts and shungiku, a mild Asian green related to chrysanthemum,
like a tumbleweed on top of a tall, tightly stacked root vegetable
``lasagna.'' They're bouncy and light and come across like a whiff
of optimism between bites of the delicious, though by now too
common, parsnips, potato, celery root and carrots that are in the
dish.
</P>
<P>
   Other chefs use vegetable sprouts as variations on a theme. At
Union Pacific, Rocco Dispirito serves mackerel with celery root
puree and celery oil, with celery sprouts laid over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really just accent the celery message that I'm trying to
deliver with that dish,'' he said. It works. You don't finish
wondering what the secret ingredient is. Celery is practically
ringing in your ears.
</P>
<P>
   There's the same layering of flavors in the crab cakes at Local.
The cakes themselves are textured with kernels of corn, the sauce
tastes of roasted corn and springing forth from the dish are what
look to be thin rods of pale yellow silk. They are corn sprouts,
and they taste like sweet corn dew, if there is such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   The corn sprout echoes the other flavors of corn and gives the
dish dimension, not just novelty. Unlike the ill-used parsley
sprig, vegetable sprouts have purpose. The corn sprout, Becker
said, re-enforces the corn as the core ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   These sprouts are different from alfalfa and bean sprouts, which
are typically cultivated in the dark in water so that both the
roots and tops can be eaten. Most other vegetable sprouts are grown
in soil, and only the part that grows above the soil is eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Growing techniques vary, but many involve seeding a plot
densely, so that the vegetable grows in patches like grass. Most
can be harvested in 4 to 6 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Jones, an owner of the Chef's Garden in Huron, Ohio, which
sells vegetables to chefs like Thomas Keller, Charlie Trotter and
Jean-Georges Vongerichten, grows his vegetable sprouts in compost
at low temperatures. The slower the sprouts grow, Jones said, the
better their flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The harvesting is the real backbreaker. Most farmers harvest the
sprouts by bending over and cutting them by hand. Jones harvests
his to order, using shears and packing them in individual
containers. For that, they cost just a small fortune. Jones sells
his for $48 to $120 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   At the Union Square Greenmarket, pints, or a few handfuls, are
about $3 at Windfall Farms and Hudson Valley Organic Gardens. They
may also be ordered by mail from Indian Rock Produce in Quakertown,
Pa., (800) 882-0512.
</P>
<P>
   Varieties differ from farm to farm, but some of the more common
choices include bull's blood beets, pink chard, radish, ruby chard,
corn shoots, broccoli, celery and red Russian kale.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a certain kind of farmer to harvest a vegetable when
it's hardly begun growing. Jones remembered the day his father,
also a farmer, came into the office when they were tasting corn
sprouts. ``He just shook his head and walked out,'' Jones said. Of
course, had he tasted them, he might have stayed.
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable sprouts are interesting to use, but challenging.
Because they lie somewhere between a vegetable and an herb, it is
not obvious which way to treat them. It's best not to be too
ambitious. A dish like the seared scallops, roasted fingerling
potatoes and braised leeks at the Grocery in Brooklyn is a good
choice. Charles Kiely and Sharon Pachter, the chefs, finish the
dish with a large pinch of purple broccoli sprouts. The tiny
broccoli leaves have a peppery kick, and they are meant to work as
a bright counterpoint to the mild, earthiness of the potatoes and
the sweetness of the scallops.
</P>
<P>
   At Nicole's, the chef Annie Wayte uses beet sprouts with deep
fuchsia-trimmed leaves alongside a crab salad. The color is
striking, the flavor supportive to the crab.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Palmer, the chef at Aureole, places daikon radish
sprouts on tuna tartare with a citrus dressing. That would be
difficult to make any simpler.
</P>
<P>
   At home, you could place a fluff of sprouts on top of grilled
fish, or mix something like sharply flavored curly cress or red
Russian kale into a salad, so that it acts like an herb.
</P>
<P>
   Some sprouts, like pea shoots, are much larger and meatier.
Rather than placing them on top of a dish suggestively, they can be
treated more like a full-grown green. At 71 Clinton Fresh Food,
they are scattered below a roasted chicken breast. They catch the
juices, stopping them from diluting a hazelnut sauce, and they wilt
a little, so you get some bites that crunch with fresh pea flavor
and others that are soaked with warm chicken juices.
</P>
<P>
   It's a delicious dish, and a spoil at this time of year. Peas in
the pod won't be around for another month or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could probably get sugar snap peas from Peru now, but
that's not the point,'' said Dufresne, the chef. ``It's guilt-free,
because it's local, and I don't feel it's some sort of
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, it's a compliment. Now, perhaps parsley can
redeem itself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPES IN 2nd TAKE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   SEARED SEA SCALLOPS WITH BROCCOLI SPROUTS AND BROWN BUTTER
VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from  &UR; the Grocery &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 50 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 fingerling potatoes, cut in half lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 medium leeks, white and light green part only, each trimmed to
4-inches
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white wine
</P>
<P>
   8 large sea scallops
</P>
<P>
   1 handful broccoli sprouts
</P>
<P>
   1. Place a small roasting pan in oven and preheat to 350
degrees. In a medium bowl, combine potatoes with 2 tablespoons
olive oil, and season with salt and pepper to taste. Place potatoes
in roasting pan cut side down, and roast until bottoms are golden
brown, about 10 minutes. Turn potatoes over, and sprinkle with
lemon juice. Continue to roast until potatoes are tender, about 10
minutes more. Remove from oven and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large pan over high heat, combine 2 tablespoons butter
with 1 cup water. Bring to a boil. Split leeks lengthwise, and
season with salt and pepper to taste. Place leek halves cut side
down in pan, and simmer until tender, 6 to 8 minutes. Keeping leek
halves intact, transfer them to a plate, and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a small pan, combine remaining 2 tablespoons of butter and
cream. Place over medium heat, and cook at a lively simmer until
milk solids become nutty and brown, and clear, clarified butter
rises to top. Immediately remove from heat, and pour off and
discard clarified butter. Add vinegar and wine, scraping bottom of
pan to incorporate browned milk solids into sauce. Bring to a boil,
and season to taste with salt and pepper. Remove from heat, and
keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   4. Season scallops with salt and pepper to taste. In a
well-seasoned cast-iron skillet over high heat, heat remaining 2
tablespoons of olive oil. When pan is smoking, add scallops, and
sear until springy to the touch and browned on both sides. Transfer
to a plate.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, on each of four plates place a piece of leek with a
potato half on each side. Place 2 scallops on each plate, with a
bouquet of broccoli sprouts between scallops. Spoon a little sauce
over potatoes, leeks and scallops, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
