<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-CITRUS-EATING-WELL-AR     02-22 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITRUS-EATING-WELL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE WILDER SHORES OF CITRUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the '40s and '50s, a sure sign that company was
coming to dinner was the sight of my mother carefully sectioning
white grapefruit halves with a serrated knife, a bottle of
maraschino cherries at the ready for topping. If grapefruits
weren't exactly exotic back then, they were certainly for special
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   I still have the serrated knife, and it got a workout last week
sampling more than two dozen varieties of unusual citrus that have
been making their ways to specialty markets and restaurant kitchens
over the last year or two. Finally, winter fruit is getting
interesting. Not to mention confusing.
</P>
<P>
   There are pear-shaped pomelos that look like misshapen
grapefruits. And pomelos that look like well-formed grapefruits _
not surprisingly, since the pomelo is one of the grapefruit's
ancestors. There is also the limequat, a cross between lime and
kumquat that is yellow or green instead of orange, and there are
yellow lemons with green stripes and pink flesh.
</P>
<P>
   All of them offer not just pleasurable eating, but also
significant levels of vitamin C, folic acid and potassium. Like all
citrus fruits, exotic or common, these fascinating new varieties
have high levels of the components called phytochemicals, which are
believed to be effective in reducing risks of certain types of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The botany and plant sciences department at the University of
California at Riverside has a collection of more than 900 different
kinds of citrus fruit from all over the world. But until recently,
said Ottillia Bier, a staff research associate, no one was paying
much attention to them. ``We have had things in our collection for
30, 40, 50 years, but in the past, farmers were just looking for
things they could plant 10,000 acres of and sell it,'' she
continued. ``Now, we've started showing them things that are a
little different, and they are interested. I think the interest is
consumer driven. It starts with the chefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmers' markets and the influx of Asian populations are also
responsible, said David Karp, a California writer and expert on
citrus. Asian farmers grow pomelos for their fellow immigrants and
sell them at farmers' markets in California, where non-Asian
shoppers see them.
</P>
<P>
   And want them. It takes longer for these specialty items to
arrive in New York. But each year, Gourmet Garage has more _ most
domestic, some imported _ and Dean &AMP; Deluca and Eli's carry some.
Frieda's, which supplies exotic produce to supermarkets nationally,
is a good source by mail (800-241-1771 or www.friedas.com).
</P>
<P>
   Not all of these oddities are worth the time it takes to cut
them open, especially some of the pomelos. Others are so
interesting they make me wonder why it took so long for them to get
here. But the biggest surprise is that even though the textures and
flavors of these exotic citrus varieties are so different, all of
them descended thousands of years ago from three species: pomelo,
mandarin orange and citron.
</P>
<P>
   Today's grapefruit is the result of the crossbreeding of a
pomelo and a sweet orange. The flesh of pomelos can be white,
ivory, pale green, light red or intense pink. They all have the
same yellow to yellowish-green skin as a grapefruit, but they
generally have more seeds and thicker albedos, as the pith is
properly called. They frequently have flesh that is too dry for the
American palate, though it is much beloved in China.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most delicious exotic citrus I tried were the
Oroblanco, a cross between a pomelo and a grapefruit, and the
Sarawak pomelo. The former does not look much different from an
ordinary white grapefruit but has a superb balance of acidity and
sweetness. Sometimes it is extremely juicy, but even when it is
not, the flavor is much more complex than grapefruit's.
</P>
<P>
   The Sarawak pomelo, with pale lime-green flesh and luscious
tropical taste, has less sugar than the Oroblanco and a higher acid
content that makes the flavor intense and intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   Melogold, another cross between a pomelo and a grapefruit, has
the same parents as the Oroblanco, but it is sweeter and less acid.
</P>
<P>
   Cocktail grapefruits, with a canary yellow skin and a deep
yellow flesh, are really sweet, very close in taste to oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Blood oranges no longer quite qualify as exotics in New York,
and of the three I tried, my choice would be the ones labeled
Moros, from Sunkist. They have a lovely balance of flavor and a
hint of flower.
</P>
<P>
   Seville oranges are also relatively common this time of year. If
you are into making your own marmalade, they offer an opportunity
to have it more bitter than the commercial kind. You certainly
wouldn't want to eat them out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Kumquats actually belong to the genus Fortunella, not Citrus,
but they are usually lumped in with oranges. The Meiwa kumquat has
a rounder shape and a much sweeter skin than the ordinary kumquat,
making it quite pleasing to eat in thin slices. (In both varieties,
and in limequats, the flesh is very sour.)
</P>
<P>
   Lemons with green stripes are called Variegated Pink Lemonade
lemons and are marginally sweeter than yellow lemons. A few wedges
of them alongside a piece of fish add a jaunty look to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   All these new citrus are for more than breakfast or a snack. At
Chicama, Douglas Rodriguez and his ceviche chef, Adrian Leon, use
them in superbly flavored ceviches. ``The fruits have very specific
qualities that enhance the flavor of the fish,'' Rodriguez said.
The bitterness of kumquats brings out the perfume of salmon; a
sweet pomelo enhances the sweetness of scallops; Seville oranges
provide the perfect counterpoint to the richness of cooked duck.
</P>
<P>
   If my mother had had Oroblancos, she would never have bothered
with maraschino cherries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
