improvement retailer said Tuesday that net income rose to $578
million, or 25 cents a share, from $418 million, or 18 cents a
share, in the year-ago period. Sales rose 26 percent to $9.17
billion from $7.26 billion. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DOW _ Stocks continued the slide that began last Friday, but the
selling momentum slowed on Monday as analysts detected investor
sentiment to get back in the market when an opportunity occurs. But
some analysts, including Ralph Acampora of Prudential Securities,
looks for further weakness, especially in blue chips, before the
end of what he calls a bull market correction. Federal Reserve Alan
Greenspan makes another appearance before Congress this week _ the
Senate on Wednesday _ but is not expected to say anything different
from his House testimony last week, when he as much as promised
that the Fed would continue to raise interest rates until the
economy is safe from inflation. The good news for stocks is the
continued drop in 30-year Treasuryyields and a decline in oil
prices. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-BIZ _Women-owned businesses have increased by 103 percent
duringthe past decade. According to a report released Tuesday in
Atlanta, annual sales have jumped 436 percent. Georgia is among the
top 10 states in the nation for number of companies owned by
females. (Harte, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LODIGAN _ Atlanta-based Lodgian sells two hotels in Florida and
South Carloina. The company plans to use the proceeds, nearly $20
million, to pay down debt. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
