<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4844 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-22 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A RUNNER WHO OUTRAN HIS FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the saddest sights in politics is a fading
public figure who refuses to concede that his or her time has
passed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest egotist to ignore reality is Ralph Nader, the aging
consumer advocate whose crusades stalled and popularity sagged long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   He announced Monday that he will seek the presidential
nomination of the Green Party. The cheering was muted. It will be
his second try. He ran for the White House on that party ticket in
1996 and attracted a whopping 1 percent of the total votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   As a political force, the Green Party isn't much. It champions
environmental protection and has a small presence in California and
other western states.
</P>
<P>
   But Nader, 66, hasn't gotten over his earlier decades of fame as
the chief advocate of auto safety and other good causes and as the
relentless scourge of big business. He has settled into a role as
the ghost of causes past.
</P>
<P>
   These days he hangs around the fringes of what remains of the
old political left, trying to regenerate some of his former
publicity magic. Through a group called Global Trade Watch, he
helped plan the demonstrations in Seattle against the World Trade
Organization. He demands changes aimed at emasculating the
organization so it will be helpless to influence international
trade decisions.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the Nader of old, whose causes defied the vested
interests on behalf of the little guy for the broad public good.
Global protectionism does not fit there. Although Nader once
crusaded for all sorts of financial disclosure and openness in
government, his GTW does not reveal the names of its donors. One
financial backer is reported to be the protectionist U.S. textile
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Nader achieved folk-hero status in 1965 after General Motors
hired private detectives to discredit him and his book ``Unsafe at
Any Speed,'' which criticized GM for shoddy car construction.
</P>
<P>
   But he began to lose moral authority in 1972 when he abandoned
his nonpartisan aura to endorse the politically doomed Sen. George
McGovern for president. Nader grew preachy and prickly. He lobbied
for a dizzying array of causes, some of which he won, some of which
he lost and some of which were tailored to his own individual
interests.
</P>
<P>
   About to be ejected by a rent increase from his downtown office
quarters, Nader even proposed a taxpayers' subsidy to provide
housing for nonprofit, volunteer citizens' public interest groups _
like his own. It went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Even liberals felt that his 1978 campaign to establish a
Cabinet-level Consumer Protection Agency was too much bureaucracy
for too little gain. After the measure was defeated in Congress,
his relations with Capitol Hill and the media soured. By 1982 a
Gallup Poll found that fewer than 40 per of those surveyed admired
Nader, a dramatic fall from a decade earlier, when he ranked among
the 10 most admired Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Nader is in the great tradition of political die-hards who
stubbornly hope against hope that they can keep the reporters and
speaking fees coming despite all the derisive laughter. It's a
shame, but it's human nature.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Stassen, of course, takes the grand prize. A former
Minnesota governor, he first ran for the Republican presidential
nomination in 1948 _ and then ran and ran and ran every four years
until 1992, when he was 84 and finally gave up the gig.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative commentator Patrick Buchanan is working toward that
record, making his third presidential run. This time he is moving
in on the chaotic Reform Party, with which he has no prior history
or even common policy goals. No popular groundswell for this
candidacy was detected, except in Buchanan's shaving mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes is in the mold as well, refusing to drop out of this
year's Republican primaries despite pitiful showings at the polls.
He's a broadcaster like Buchanan _ anything to maintain the buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the ostrich-head-in-the-sand routine takes the form of
holding an opponent hostage after an election has been lost. Recent
examples of sour grapes were Republican Ellen Saurbrey, who was
defeated by Democrat Parris Glendening for governor of Maryland in
1994 and Republican Rep. Michael Huffington, defeated for the
California Senate seat in 1996 by incumbent Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Saurbrey challenged the election outcome for two months although
the margin of victory was nearly 6,000 votes. She ran against
Governor Glendening again last year and deservedly lost again.
</P>
<P>
   Although Huffington was defeated by 165,562 votes, he did not
issue the pro-forma congratulation to Feinstein for three months.
Both losers charged that old standby, voter fraud, which when
examined almost never turns out to have been so one-sided as to
have changed an election outcome.
</P>
<P>
   But back to Nader. He was once so good. Why can't he leave it at
that?
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1714EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOYS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-22 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WONDER BOYS': MARIJUANA, MANUSCRIPT AND MARRIAGE EQUAL A MESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Chabon's 1995 novel, ``Wonder Boys,'' chronicles a
hectic weekend in the life of Grady Tripp, a frustrated,
concupiscent college teacher mired in at least three ill-starred
relationships: to marijuana, to his elephantine unfinished
manuscript and to the wife of his department chairman. More Anne
Tyler than John Updike, the book plays Grady's dilemma for gentle
comedy and lingers fondly over the quirky geography of a proud,
battered American industrial city, in this case Pittsburgh.
``Wonder Boys'' is intoxicated by its setting and enchanted by
writing: by the sweet, fizzy soda pop of its own style and also by
some unabashedly romantic notions of the literary life. Chabon's
characters tap out their manuscripts on old typewriters, are
reckless in love and loyal in friendship and suffer from the
creative agitation Grady calls ``the midnight disease.''
</P>
<P>
   In bringing ``Wonder Boys'' to the screen, Steve Kloves and
Curtis Hanson have tried to be faithful both to its spirit of
bittersweet farce and to its beguiling profusion of detail. Hanson
and his production crew have assiduously rounded up a Citroen
(though not, as in the book, a convertible) and a vintage Ford
Galaxie, an IBM Selectric and a pair of red cowboy boots. They
built themselves a Pittsburgh dive, complete with neon signs and
Naugahyde banquettes. And to their great credit, they allowed
Pittsburgh to play itself, a picturesque late-19th-century city of
red brick factories and dark, wainscoted interiors, whose weather
seems to consist of variations on snow, rain and wind.
</P>
<P>
   While Chabon's convoluted narrative has been streamlined and
some of its charming shaggy-dog tangents sheered away, the heart of
the novel _ a cat's cradle of comic entanglements involving Grady's
collapsing marriage, his monstrous manuscript and his duty to help
a troubled fledgling writer _ has been carefully preserved. Kloves
has lifted chunks of dialogue from the pages of the book and placed
them in the competent mouths of a cast that includes Michael
Douglas as Grady, Frances McDormand as his paramour, a college
administrator named Sara Gaskell, and Tobey Maguire as James Leer,
Grady's wayward prize student. And yet the words that seem so
artful and lively in print have a way of becoming lifeless and
artificial when uttered aloud. Hannah Green, a student who rents a
room in Grady's house and has a half-requited crush on him, gushes
to him, ``It's like all your sentences seem as if they've always
existed, waiting up there in Style Heaven or wherever, for you to
fetch them down.'' Reading this may elicit a smile. Hearing it,
even as uttered by the charming Katie Holmes in her
character-defining red cowboy boots, is more likely to produce a
wince.
</P>
<P>
   This, in a nutshell, is the mystery of ``Wonder Boys.'' It
boasts a first-rate cast, a credible literary source and a director
whose last film, ``L.A. Confidential,'' showed a prodigious ability
to capture both the headlong rhythms of a complex plot and the
particularities of a motley assortment of characters. With so much
going for it, how could the movie be such a dud? There's no
shortage of screwball material _ a dead dog, an errant tuba and a
very tall drag queen, for starters _ but Hanson, perhaps aiming for
wry understatement, has smothered whatever antic rhythm the story
might have had. ``Wonder Boys'' is like a George Cukor movie with a
bad head cold _ slow, muffled and vague.
</P>
<P>
   The same three words might describe Douglas' performance. To be
fair, he is playing a pothead, a merciful change of pace for an
actor who typically performs as if he is coming off a three-day
Viagra binge. But Douglas seems not to be enacting the hazy
confusion that is Grady's dominant trait; he seems to have
succumbed to it. His scenes with McDormand, whose character
kick-starts the plot by telling Grady she's pregnant with his
child, lack the erotic heat, the sense of longing, that might lend
pathos to their predicament. You never quite shake the sense that
you are watching movie actors freshly arrived in a strange city and
awaiting further instructions.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of ``Wonder Boys'' _ as phony and conventional here as
it was in the book _ is rescue. And just as the book was saved from
banality by its author's mordant whimsy, the film is rescued from
complete dullness by the manic insouciance of Robert Downey Jr. He
plays Grady's editor, Terry Crabtree, who blows into Pittsburgh to
participate in a college-sponsored event called WordFest and sets
about seducing James Leer. Downey and Maguire, whose improvisatory,
ironical acting styles seem to belong in a different movie, might
have found some real chemistry, but they don't get much time
together on screen. What occupies the screen is a well-intentioned
muddle. The problem with ``Wonder Boys'' is not that it's a bad
movie, though if it had risked becoming one it might have been a
lot more. The problem is that everyone involved seems to have
agreed that it was a great idea for a movie and pretty much left it
at that.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Wonder Boys'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It contains some sexual
situations, clouds of marijuana smoke and the the senseless killing
of a blind dog.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   WONDER BOYS
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Curtis Hanson; written by Steve Kloves, based on the
novel by Michael Chabon; director of photography, Dante Spinotti;
edited by Dede Allen; music by Christopher Young, with the song
``Things Have Changed'' written and performed by Bob Dylan;
production designer, Jeannine Oppewall; produced by Scott Rudin and
Hanson; released by Paramount Pictures. Running time: 112 minutes.
This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Michael Douglas (Grady Tripp), Tobey Maguire (James Leer),
Frances McDormand (Sara Gaskell), Robert Downey Jr. (Terry
Crabtree), Katie Holmes (Hannah Green), Rip Torn (Q), Richard Knox
(Vernon Hardapple) and Jane Adams (Oola).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1715EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4846 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NAZITORAH-AZR &LR;      02-22 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZITORAH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGREGATION EAGERLY AWAITS RESTORED TORAH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Torah in the Phoenix synagogue's lobby is
displayed exactly the way Hitler would have wanted _ in a museum
case, behind glass.
</P>
<P>
   For years, this bothered many at Beth El Congregation. But the
Torah, once stolen for Hitler's planned museum of artifacts from
``a liquidated race,'' could not be used in worship because of its
deteriorated state.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the congregation's restoration project will be complete,
and this sacred text of the Jewish people will never be behind
glass again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Torah, like the people it represents, was programmed to
die and it refused to die, the same way we refused to die. Hitler
is dead. I am alive, and the Torah is alive,'' said Helen Handler,
a Beth El congregant and the only member of her family to survive
Nazi death camps.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Nazis destroyed thousands of Torahs
publicly to demoralize the Jewish community, said Rabbi Rick
Sherwin, spiritual leader of the 850 families at Beth El.
</P>
<P>
   Many others were stolen for Hitler's planned museum.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, the Beth El Torah and about 1,500 others
were left for two decades in a neglected synagogue outside Prague
in what is now the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   An English businessman and philanthropist discovered them, and
the Torahs were rescued, although many were beyond repair. Beth El
was one of the congregations around the world to receive one in
fair condition.
</P>
<P>
   A Torah is written in Hebrew and contains the first five books
of the Old Testament. The books were given to Moses on Mount Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish law prescribes that only a perfect Torah may be used in
worship. The Beth El parchment scroll was brittle, yellowed and
torn, its Hebrew letters no longer crisp and black. The
congregation preserved the Torah behind glass as a memorial to
Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it in my stomach. It bothered a number of people,''
Sherwin said. ``With the help of Cathy Wolf and Jody Jones, we
devised a plan to get the Torah out of that case and into the hands
of a scribe to fix it, letter by letter, and bring it back to the
synagogue so we can use it.''
</P>
<P>
   The scroll spent a year and a half in Brooklyn, N.Y., at Klein
Bros. where the two sibling rabbis restore and write Torahs
following strict religious guidelines. They spent about 1,500 hours
on the project.
</P>
<P>
   The Torah is estimated to be between 200 and 400 years old. The
parchment was softened and reinforced, then each letter redrawn,
following its original style, a task more difficult and expensive
than writing a new one.
</P>
<P>
   There is also more joy, said one of the brothers, Rabbi Moshe
Klein.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is one of the most important things that a Jewish
congregation can do,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Handler and more than 300 members of Beth El greeted
the nearly restored Torah with great anticipation. Handler was one
of the first to hold the Torah, wrapped in a prayer shawl, and she
smiled as she clasped it. Then she couldn't stop crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides my son, it is the most precious thing I have ever held
in my arms. I have nothing from my background, not even a picture,
to pass on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Torah could have returned completed, but the synagogue has
dedicated this year to understanding the Torah's history, studying
it more deeply, and seeking inspiration from its message.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Wolf, members of Beth El, have worked with the
synagogue in the restoration project and in the educational
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The programs will continue through May when Klein will come to
the congregation, and the rabbi and congregation will complete the
Torah together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is bringing in the congregation, from the youngest
kids. It's hard not to feel the joy and the spirit and the energy
that surrounds this,'' said Wolf, program manager for the Downtown
Neighborhood Learning Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Handler, now a retired owner of a Phoenix drapery shop, was born
in the former Czechoslovakia, the country where the Torah was
found. At 15, she was separated from her family at Auschwitz, where
10,000 were gassed every 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, the Nazi women would make them stand in line for
two or three hours, barely clothed in the cold, waiting to see who
would die that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stood in front of us in their fresh crisp uniforms. I
could smell the toothpaste in their mouths,'' Handler said. ``We
were standing absolutely dying in front of them, and they were
talking about their dates from the night before. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I picture them, the SS men and women in front of us
and try to figure out if they hated us. But they didn't see us. We
didn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Torah behind glass exists as proof of the generations
who prayed and celebrated births and bar mitzvahs and weddings with
the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that their spirits stay around this Torah and they
rejoice with us as we bring it back,'' Handler said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Kelly. &QL; 
Ettenborough(at)ArizonaRepublic.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
