<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE PUDDING WITH A JAPANESE TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is the eighth of eight columns by Tadashi Ono, the chef at
Sono in Manhattan. They are written with Mark Bittman.)  
(lh) 
 By TADASHI ONO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many people are surprised to find rice pudding, a
classic American comfort food, on my menu. But to me, it seems a
natural choice. Rice is tremendously important in Japanese cuisine,
and I knew we could create a rice pudding that departed from the
ordinary. What Christine Chang, our pastry chef, and I came up with
follows the typical technique, which is to simmer rice in sweetened
milk until it is soft and creamy. But the result has a flavor and
texture that are completely unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   My simmering liquid is half coconut milk, which is richer than
milk and adds its own flavor. I use short-grain sushi rice, which
becomes softer and creamier than long-grain rice and, because of
its high gluten content, has a chewier texture. I cook the rice
until it can hold a shape. The result is less like American rice
pudding than a creamy version of Asian sticky rice.
</P>
<P>
   It's best to simmer the rice in a wide-bottomed pot so that the
liquid can evaporate quickly; this keeps the rice from becoming too
mushy, and it leaves the core of each grain distinct as the entire
mixture becomes creamy. The technique is very much like that for
risotto _ the pudding requires near-constant stirring, too _ and in
fact the results are not dissimilar.
</P>
<P>
   At the restaurant, we lay shallow 5-inch rings on a no-stick
surface and pack the pudding into the rings, smoothing the top. At
home, it's probably easier to spoon the pudding into custard cups
or ramekins. They can sit at room temperature for a few hours, or
be refrigerated for up to a day.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, we grate a layer of palm sugar on top and
caramelize it with a propane torch; at home, brown sugar can
substitute. Caramelize it under the broiler (set the rack as close
to the heat source as you can and watch carefully).
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, rice pudding is topped with whipped cream, but
instead of adding more creaminess and sweetness I created a tart,
bright-green syrup with lime juice and zest that adds a spark of
color and cleanses the palate of the pudding's richness.
</P>
<P>
   COCONUT RICE PUDDING WITH LIME SYRUP
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 1 hour  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 limes
</P>
<P>
   3 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   3 cups canned coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean
</P>
<P>
   } cup short-grain (sushi) rice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   6 teaspoons palm or brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1. Set a small pot of water to boil. In a separate pot, combine
{ cup sugar and { cup water and bring to a boil. Cook for a few
seconds, until sugar dissolves. Zest the limes and place zest in
boiling water for 10 seconds, no more; drain through a strainer and
plunge into ice water to chill. Set aside. Juice limes, and add
them to sugar syrup; cook over medium heat, stirring only
occasionally, until it darkens and thickens, about 20 minutes.
Cool, then stir in lime zest and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Put the rice in a deep bowl, and run cold water on it,
stirring with your hand. Drain and repeat until excess starch is
removed and water runs clear. Combine milk and coconut milk in a
wide, deep, heavy bottomed saucepan, and turn heat to medium-high.
Split vanilla bean lengthwise and scrape out seeds; add them to the
mix, along with the rice, 1 cup sugar and salt. When liquid begins
to boil, adjust heat so that it bubbles steadily but not
vigorously; if at any point the mixture browns, turn heat down a
little more. Stir occasionally at first, then more and more
frequently, until mixture becomes thick and much like oatmeal,
about 25 minutes total.
</P>
<P>
   3. Spoon rice pudding into six ramekins, and cool to room
temperature (you can refrigerate for up to a day, but these are
best at room temperature). Before serving, sprinkle top of each
pudding with palm or brown sugar and use a propane torch or run
under broiler until sugar bubbles and begins to burn. Serve,
drizzled with lime syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: six servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
