<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE DEER POINT TO AN EARLY SPRING IN NORTHERN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Maybe flowers, trees and deer can't predict the
future, but from Monterey to the Oregon border, nature seems to be
forecasting a warm, early spring in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cannonade procession of storms the past month, the
temperatures have been extremely mild. In the Bay Area, it has the
foothills turning green, spring fruit trees blooming and the
magnolias on the Peninsula ready to pop their purple blooms any
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Valley is also greening up, and in the mountain
foothills at elevations up to 2,500 feet, sprouting tulips and
gladiola are already 5 inches tall, another anomaly for
mid-February. In the north state, at the town of Mount Shasta
(3,400 feet), there is no snow on the ground, a
once-in-a-hundred-year aberration.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to my wilderness cabin this past week on the flank of
Shasta, I saw sprouting tulips, vegetation and a dozen deer
browsing, unheard of for what is usually peak winter. What are the
deer doing here? Looking for food, that's what, and finding it.
</P>
<P>
   On the north coast, Humboldt County might have been deluged with
rain, but there are apricot and plum trees that are green.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with nature, you never know what will happen next:
The polar jet stream could suddenly dip down and deliver a
procession of Arctic storms that turns Northern California into an
ice box. Or a massive high pressure system could take hold, force
the jet streams into Canada, with 70-degree temperatures arriving
in March.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that the deer are betting on the latter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOOR NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   Record trout: A 17-pound rainbow trout, a new lake record for
Shadow Cliffs Lake in Pleasanton, was caught Thursday by Gene
O'Connor of San Leandro. The trout measured 30 inches long.
</P>
<P>
   One way to solve it: In the Salt Lake City area, some parks have
solved hiker vs. biker trail conflicts by reserving days where
trails are for the exclusive use of hikers, as well as others for
the exclusive use of bikers. Sounds good on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   This just in: A landmark funding bill for wildlife and wild
places, H.R. 701, won congressional committee approval last week
with 294 co-sponsors from both parties, which virtually assures its
future passage. The bill, co-authored by Rep. George Miller,
D-Martinez, would provide $2.8 billion per year for 15 years for
on-the-ground restoration and enhancement projects for wildlife
across America.
</P>
<P>
   Bonus salmon: Shasta Lake near Redding has received a bonus of
100,000 king salmon stocked since last November, providing the
opportunity to expand a new trophy fishery at California's biggest
reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Great freebie: Cal/North, a directory of sources for boating,
fishing and diving, is available for free by writing Cal North
Marine, P.O. Box 410483, San Francisco, CA 94141-0483, or phoning
(415)243-0426.
</P>
<P>
   Live animal sales: Eric Mills has emerged as the leader to
promote and enforce laws to prohibit the inhumane treatment of
wildlife in live animal markets. He can be reached at P.O. Box
20184, Oakland, CA 94620.
</P>
<P>
   Learning from California's mistakes: After studying California's
live fish markets, now legal in San Francisco and Oakland
Chinatowns, the Washington Fish and Wildlife Commission voted
unanimously to ban the sale of live fish.
</P>
<P>
   Guinness world record: On a single gallon of fuel, a light
trimaran-type skiff traveled 67.27 miles powered by a Yamaha
4-horsepower, 4-cycle outboard, a new fuel economy record for
boating.
</P>
<P>
   Learn-to-fish clinics: Beginner clinics are set for Saturday and
March 11 at Shadow Cliffs Lake in Pleasanton, limited to 13 people,
$5, advance registration required at (510) 636-1684.
</P>
<P>
   There they go again: Two wild parrots flew over my parents'
house on the Peninsula, then an hour later, there went 16 more,
beautiful and powerful, like a squadron of fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   Now full: Lakes filling and spilling this past week in Marin
were Lagunitas, Bon Tempe and Alpine lakes, all set in a row on the
flank of Mount Tamalpais, and in Santa Clara County, Uvas, Vasona,
Guadalupe and Almaden, with Calero and Stevens Creek likely to fill
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Trees don't lie: Hydrologists are privately stunned that
according to tree ring studies, Northern California hasn't had six
straight years of above-normal precipitation since the 1500s _ yet
with another month of average rain, they point out that is exactly
what will have occurred since the winter of 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   And that means: California's 383 lakes you can drive to and 483
significant lakes you can hike to will be full again this spring
and summer, making for a banner nine-month season for camping,
hiking, boating and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Circle this date: Audubon Canyon Ranch near Bolinas Lagoon will
open on March 11, providing an extraordinary view of herons and
egrets courting, mating, nesting and raising their young.
(415)868-9244.
</P>
<P>
   Why sport anglers protest: In 1996, the total landings of marlin
in the Atlantic was 38.2 tons, while the total discard of dead
marlin by commercial fishermen was 335.7 tons, according to the
International Game Fish Association.
</P>
<P>
   Closings &AMP; openings: The fishing season for rockfish off the Bay
Area coast will be closed in March and April. The sport salmon
season opens April 1 in Monterey Bay and Santa Cruz, and April 15
out of the Bay Area ports.
</P>
</TEXT>
