<HEADLINE>
UNDER HOUSE ARREST, KHOMEINI'S BETRAYED SUCCESSOR SPEAKS OF IRAN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EXCLUSIVE...Note 2 trims, totaling 400. Uncut is 1,275)   (This EXCLUSIVE ``separate-buy'' article _ the first interview
given by the imprisoned ``mouthpiece of the Iranian revolution,''
Ayatollah Hossein Ali Montazeri _ is from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper
in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS TWO EDITOR-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 400 WORDS.
TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,275.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QOM, IRAN _ The voice was friendly, elderly, avuncular, so close
to me _ Ayatollah Hossein Ali Montazeri was just three meters (10
feet) away, behind a dividing wall _ that I not only heard his
words through the interphone but the murmur of his actual voice
from the next room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the mouthpieces of the revolution,'' he said.
``But when they treat me, me, like this, how must they be treating
the others?''
</P>
<P>
   It was an eerie experience. To interview the man whom Ayatollah
Khomeini once anointed as his chosen successor is one thing. To
talk to him through a wall after he has spent more than two years
under house arrest in this gold-domed holy city _ two Revolutionary
Guards watching his front door and his every visitor _ was
positively surreal.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the parliamentary elections that have handed
Iran's revolution back to its people, the stubborn old cleric was
still patiently awaiting his freedom _ and condemning the elderly
Islamic clergymen who put him there, who ``did not keep the promise
of the revolution,'' who refuse to yield political power to the
president of Iran.
</P>
<P>
   This was his first interview in captivity _ house arrest was
meant to shut him up.
</P>
<P>
   We had to walk quickly through the back door of the house of
Ayatollah Montazeri's son Ahmed and persuade him to let us talk to
his father through the white cord telephone attached to an inner
wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to my home,'' the Ayatollah growled at me in English.
It was one of the few kind things he said. Because the reasons for
Montazeri's house imprisonment _ and the contents of his
extraordinary interview Sunday _ go to the very heart of the crisis
behind last week's parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Ayatollah believes that the Supreme Leader of Iran, the
unelected Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, should not hold political power,
should not be able to hinder the reformist movement of President
Mohamed Khatami _ who appears to have received an overwhelming vote
of support in last week's poll.
</P>
<P>
   Did he still believe that the velayat e-faqih _ the institution
of religious guide created by Khomeini and once awarded to him _
had been misused? The voice growled again, this time in Farsi.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an Arabic expression that says: `There's a limit to
all things _ and everything that passes its limit destroys itself.'
If the institution of the Supreme Guide was one of an observer, it
would remain. But if there is dictatorship, it cannot continue...
</P>
<P>
   ``People like me and Mr. (Mohsen) Kadivar (a `reformist' cleric
in Tehran) are sent to prison because these people cannot tolerate
criticism. Yet the Imam Ali always said: `You should criticize me.'
These gentlemen should behave the same way (as the Imam).''
</P>
<P>
   All the while we were speaking to each other through that
whitewashed wall in Qom Sunday, the Ayatollah's son Ahmed stood
beside us, bearded and turbaned, turning at one point to mutter
that ``this is the first time he has given such an interview.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Montazeri expect now to be freed, in the aftermath of
last week's election, to be spared the Ayatollah Khamenei's charge
of ``treason against the revolution?''
</P>
<P>
   Back came the disembodied voice. ``All my hope is in God. But
these people (the conservative clergy) should take note that
keeping me in prison is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a Husseiniya (religious teaching school) class next to
my home where I have many Korans and books _ and they took them
from me. I have 3,000 cassettes and audio-equipment and they took
all of it. Even if a person is convicted, they're not allowed to
confiscate his belongings...
</P>
<P>
   ``Our revolution was Islamic and (came about) through the will
of the people. And we asked for independence, for freedom and for
an Islamic Republic. It seems that they (the clergy) have forgotten
freedom. They did not keep the promise of the revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   It was his habit of speaking out which lost Ayatollah Montazeri
the favor of Imam Khomeini. Once described by Khomeini as ``the
fruit of my life,'' he dared to write a letter to the founder of
the Islamic Revolution after the end of the Iran-Iraq War,
condemning the hanging of thousands of young Iranian men and women
accused _ often without proof or fair trials _ of joining the
violent pro-Iraqi ``mujahedin'' opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Khomeini, whose son Ahmed _ also now dead _ is said to have
intercepted the letter, allowed the executions to continue and
dismissed Montazeri as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Ayatollah Khamanei, the man who now holds the job Montazeri was
destined for, was enraged by the latter's subsequent criticism of
his powers.
</P>
<P>
   Our talk Sunday in a tiny apartment off an alleyway in the
suburbs of Qom, suggested that the voice will not be stilled. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 300 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 825) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have another expression in Persian that says: `Rights are
something you must seize _ they're not given to you.' The people
had to elect good representatives and oblige them to work in the
people's interest. Violence brings negative results. But they (the
conservative clergy) have created what are called `force groups'
who used violence and attacked people when they wanted to speak
publicly. And they attacked me too. These kinds of action make
people hate religion. But you can never serve the interests of
religion through violence.''
</P>
<P>
   And had he changed his views on the ``velayat e-faqih,'' the
all-powerful institution of the nation's Islamic Guide?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote four books about this,'' came the voice down the
interphone. ``But right now it's not (about) what I wrote in my
books. In our constitutional law, the executive power is separate
from the institution of the Supreme Leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things now are not according to constitutional law here. The
president is supposed to be responsible but the tools of power are
in other people's hands. According to Islam, they should be
separate.''
</P>
<P>
   And he began to talk about issues he had not chosen to address
so far, the 100 intellectuals and writers, for example, who were
``disappeared'' under the presidency of Ali Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani in the decade up to 1998, the authorities' attack on
Tehran University dormitories last year that led to student riots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election should be enough to stop the bad things they have
been doing in the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's said that they have killed 100 innocent people. The
judiciary must follow this up. And when they invaded the
university, they did nothing about those who violated the campus.
But they arrested some of the students. So people should ask for
justice. Our constitution says so.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he agreed, Iranians were happy after their election. ``They
really did their duty and they went to take hold of their destiny.
But if they want to do this, they shouldn't let others decide for
them. Thank God, the people participated well in this election _ I
wish them all success.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 1,175, OR CONTINUE TO 1,275) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   In the meeting room across the tiny hallway, there were
photographs of Montazeri with the murdered Iranian Justice Minister
Ayatollah Behesti _ killed by a ``mujahedin'' bomb after the
revolution _ and of Montazeri's son Mohamed who died in the same
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The voice down the telephone was a lonely one and we gently
offered the only surviving son, Ahmed, the hope that our next
interview would be conducted in a more civilized way. He smiled but
remained silent. I could see why. The family's future depends on
those elections. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
