<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0223-COX     02-22 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0223-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW JUDGE ASSIGNED IN ELIAN CASE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A new judge was assigned the case of 6-year-old Cuban
rafter Elian Gonzalez Tuesday after his predecessor fell ill, a
move that will likely delay for two weeks a crucial hearing that
could determine the boy's fate.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Michael Moore was randomly assigned the case
by computer after Judge William Hoeveler suffered a stroke over the
weekend. Hoeveler, 77, was scheduled to preside over a hearing
Tuesday on jurisdictional issues, but Chief Judge Edward Davis told
attorneys that Judge Moore will be taking the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Moore assured me he would be able to meet the deadline
Judge Hoeveler set,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   That deadline calls for a final hearing on the matter to be held
the week of March 6. But Moore could decide _ or could be asked by
attorneys _ to hold a hearing earlier than March 6 to consider the
question of whether the federal courts have jurisdiction over
immigration matters, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The court proceedings came as the furor over the boy continued
on both sides of the Florida Straits _ in Miami and Havana _ with
charges of spying, secret desires to defect and family intrigue
swirling around a custody battle that has become a nasty
international tug-of-war.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was found floating in an inner tube off Fort Lauderdale on
Thanksgiving Day, after his mother and 10 other people died when
their boat sank as they attempted to flee Cuba for the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The boy has been living in Miami since then with the family of
his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez. Federal immigration officials
have ruled that Elian should be returned to his father in Cuba, but
his Miami relatives have gone to court to try to keep the boy in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father, Cuban tourism worker Juan Miguel Gonzalez, has
repeatedly demanded that the U.S. government return his son. But he
has refused to come to the United States country to claim him,
saying he fears for his safety in Miami's volatile exile community.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez has also asked U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno to move the boy to the Miami home of Manuel Gonzalez, a
relative who favors returning Elian to Cuba. Immigration officials
have denied the request, saying it would be too disruptive for the
boy.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Gonzalez appeared in court Tuesday with lawyers who filed
a motion on his behalf asking for custody of Elian. As he left the
federal courthouse, Manuel Gonzalez was rushed by several dozen
angry, flag-waving Cuban exiles shouting ``traitor,'' and
``communista.''
</P>
<P>
   He met with his brother, Lazaro Gonzalez, to discuss the case
Monday night. But neither side would say what happened during the
family conference. After the meeting, Manuel Gonzalez, a bus
mechanic for the Miami-Dade School System, suffered heart
palpitations and was taken to a hospital. He was later released.
</P>
<P>
   In another legal move in the case, the American Civil Liberties
Union filed a friend-of-the-court brief Tuesday, asking the court
to reject arguments on both sides and to respect the principle that
parents have a constitutional right to custody of their children.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives' lawyers wished Hoeveler a speedy recovery
and welcomed Moore to the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tries a lot of cases. He moves very firmly and
decisively,'' Kendall Coffey, a member of their legal team, told
Reuters of Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Cuban officials denied stunning allegations
leveled by a Miami nun, Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin, who hosted a
high-profile reunion between Elian and his grandmothers in late
January. O'Laughlin told the Miami Herald that she believes Elian
should stay in the United States because one of his grandmothers
wants to defect, and because his father allegedly physically abused
the boy's mother. She also says the Cuban family knew of Elian's
mother's plans to flee the island.
</P>
<P>
   O'Laughlin has refused to say where she learned the information,
but has given a sworn affidavit to the Miami family's attorneys
that reveals her sources. Since hosting the reunion as a ``neutral
observer,'' O'Laughlin has become a strong advocate of keeping
Elian in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Cuban Interests Section in Washington denied
O'Laughlin's charges. The official also said there was no
connection between the Elian case and a Cuban diplomat who was
given seven days to leave the country last Saturday, because of his
alleged involvement with a federal immigration official arrested
two days before in Miami and charged with spying for Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The wild gyrations in the case have become almost routine, as
Elian has come to symbolize the deep hatred between Cuba's
communist government and Miami's Cuban exiles.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials decried the arrest of the immigration official
and the expulsion order for the diplomat, saying the moves were
part of a plot to keep Elian in the United States. The unnamed
diplomat has been the ``victim of a brutal provocation and a vile
calumny,'' said a statement issued by the Cuban government, which
has refused to call him home.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
