<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OSCARS-TV-2TAKES-TRIM     02-22 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-TV-2TAKES-TRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING UP BABY VERY CAREFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The four-hour Academy Award show is tedious. The
jokes often fall flat. The musical numbers can be _ let's face it _
embarrassing. The scripted patter between movie stars is silly. And
the plethora of awards leaves television viewers _ especially on
the East Coast _ numb and sleepy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet who doesn't endure the Oscar show?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a show that everyone has an opinion about,'' said Richard
D. Zanuck, the new co-producer of the 72nd annual Academy Awards
which will be televised on March 26 on ABC. ``We're putting
ourselves on the line on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   His co-producer and wife, Lili Fini Zanuck, was blunter. ``It's
a thankless job. It's like we had a baby and everyone was giving us
advice on how to raise it.'' She laughed. ``The day after the
Oscars we may just go flee to the Antarctic. Or start making movies
in Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful that the Zanucks _ who won an Academy Award
themselves for producing the 1989 film ``Driving Daisy'' _ will
wind up in Antarctica or Hong Kong. But they are aware that as a
television production, the Oscar show, while still very successful,
has suffered audience erosion in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Oscar broadcast saw a significant ratings drop
over 1998, drawing at least 10 percent fewer viewers. The numbers
were still huge _ by ABC's own estimate the number of viewers who
watched at least some part of the show was 78 million. But this was
down from 87 million a year before. Even more worrisome to ABC and
the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, which presents the
Oscars, was that the telecast _ the longest on record at four hours
and five minutes _ was the lowest rated Oscar show since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   To Oscar aficionados, the show is essentially an extravaganza of
glitz, drama, bad jokes, tackiness and genuine emotion. ``The
patter between stars is always horrible _ and those dance
numbers!'' said Damien Bona, co-author with Mason Wiley of ``Inside
Oscar: The Unofficial History of the Academy Awards.''
</P>
<P>
   Bona added: ``But people love watching the show because it's a
contest _like the Super Bowl or `Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'
There's still suspense. And as jaded as people may be, you can't
deny the glamour of it. It's a chance to see famous movie stars
more or less be themselves, and there's always the possibility that
someone will make a fool of themselves. That's always fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In taking over the show from Gil Cates, who produced the last
three Oscar presentations _ and a total of nine in the last 15
years _ the Zanucks made it plain that this year's program at the
Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles will seek to be, first and
foremost, shorter. The goal is three and a half hours, not four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually watch the show at home with friends, and we're
using that as a barometer for the decisions we're making,'' said
Zanuck. ``We're saying, `Is this the place we would have gotten up
to get some food?' When did we start talking during the show? When
did we lose interest? When did interest peak?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've changed everything to some degree,'' Zanuck added.
``We've put some spin on every aspect of the show. And the pacing
will be much closer to what the audience today expects.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is that the Zanucks cut out all the dance numbers
_choreographed in recent years by Debbie Allen _ that exasperated
many viewers. There have been such blunders as a kind of
jitterbugging Daisy (as in ``Driving Daisy'') and a singing Telly
Savalas. In 1986 Frank Sinatra and Dean Martin were asked to sing a
version of Frank Loesser's ``Fugue for Tinhorns from ``Guys and
Dolls.'' After being rejected by the crooners, the Academy was left
with an incongruous trio: Dom De Luise, Pat Morita and, once more,
Telly Savalas.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most famous, or infamous, dance number was on the
1989 show, produced by Allan Carr, the impresario whose earlier
projects included ``Grease'' and the Broadway msical ``La Cage aux
Folles'' and who died last year. The opening sequence, borrowed
from a campy San Francisco musical called ``Beach Blanket
Babylon,'' saw an actress playing Snow White alongside a singing
and dancing Rob Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the worst,'' said Robert Osborne, author of ``70
Years of the Oscar: The Official History of the Academy Awards,''
``Rob Lowe said he looked out at the audience and saw Meryl Streep
making a face.''
</P>
<P>
   Even worse for Carr, he produced an elaborate nightclub sequence
designed to show great elderly movie stars. But the only stars he
managed to snare were Roy Rogers, Dale Evans, Vincent Price, Coral
Browne, Tony Martin, Alice Faye, Cyd Charisse and a few others.
``That show was a train wreck,'' said Osborne. ``Poor Allan Carr.
He never got over it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With Carr's disaster very much in their minds the Zanucks
resolved not only to eliminate all dance numbers (unhappy
choreographers have sent protest letters to the academy as well as
to the Zanucks) but to simplify the musical selections for the five
nominated songs. The performers from the soundtracks _ such as Phil
Collins singing ``You'll Be in My Heart,'' from ``Tarzan,'' or
Aimee Mann singing ``Save Me,'' from ``Magnolia,'' will perform.
The new music directors will be the Oscar-winning Burt Bacharach
and Grammy-winning Don Was.
</P>
<P>
   Zanuck spoke diplomatically about the issue. ``We just don't
think dance is part of the vocabulary of motion pictures today,''
she said. ``It works for the Tony Awards, which honors Broadway
shows. It works for the MTV awards. It's organic to their process.
It's no longer organic to the filmmaking process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zanucks have also decreed that there will not be any
politicians or government officials at the show: last year, Gen.
Colin L. Powell and Sen. John Glenn made separate appearances, and
both men _ as well as the audience _ seemed a little perplexed
about why they were there. Billy Crystal will return for a seventh
stint as the Oscar host, a relief to the Zanucks after last year
when the host, Whoopi Goldberg, was criticized by newspaper
reviewers for her sometimes raunchy jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Zanuck, who is 65, said he had probably been present at more
Academy Award shows than anyone else. He began attending them at
age 7, riding in a limousine with his father, Darryl F. Zanuck, the
legendary producer and chairman of 20th Century Fox. He recalled
that his father won three Irving Thalberg awards, was nominated
numerous times for top awards and won the Oscar three times. As a
studio chairman himself, the younger Zanuck won best picture awards
for ``The Sound of Music,'' ``Patton'' and ``The French
Connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Zanuck said there will be no written dialogue for the presenters
_ critics often said the patter was lame and unfunny. And to speed
up the proceedings, presenters will have three ways of entering the
stage: quickly, not-so-quickly and slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly will be for glamour queens, divas and most popular
younger female stars like Gwyneth Paltrow. Audiences want to see
what these actresses are wearing. Quickly, will be for those
presenters (picture, say, an older actor or a director) whose black
tie outfit may not be a source of fascination but whose comments
may be. At this point, no one is quite sure what types of
presenters will fall into the middle category.
</P>
<P>
   Most certainly, a highlight _ and almost guaranteed to produce a
standing ovation _ will be the appearance of Jane Fonda, who
retired from acting years ago. Fonda won best actress Academy
Awards for ``Klute'' in 1971 and ``Coming Home'' in 1978. She has
not made an appearance on the show since 1992. After her recent
separation from her husband, Ted Turner, she agreed to attend the
ceremonies in what some Hollywood producers see as, perhaps, an
attempt to return to movies. Zanuck said she asked Paula Weinstein,
a producer and friend of Fonda's, to invite the actress. Fonda will
present an honorary Oscar to the Polish filmmaker Andrzej Wajda,
whose films include ``Ashes and Diamonds'' and ``Kanal.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Zanucks seek is, of course, drama and surprise on the
part of the winners. ``It's those moments you remember _ Charlie
Chaplin coming back, last year when Sophia Loren appeared, the year
the streaker showed up onstage, Cuba Gooding winning, Jack Palance
doing his pushups,'' said Zanuck. ``Those are the great moments of
the Oscars.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's the not-so-great moments the producers worry about.
``Allan Carr never got over it,'' said Zanuck. ``People were so
mean. You can fail in such a public way. And that's a little
frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1725EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0226 </DOCNO>
