   O'Laughlin has refused to say where she learned the information,
but has given a sworn affidavit to the Miami family's attorneys
that reveals her sources. Since hosting the reunion as a ``neutral
observer,'' O'Laughlin has become a strong advocate of keeping
Elian in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Cuban Interests Section in Washington denied
O'Laughlin's charges. The official also said there was no
connection between the Elian case and a Cuban diplomat who was
given seven days to leave the country last Saturday, because of his
alleged involvement with a federal immigration official arrested
two days before in Miami and charged with spying for Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The wild gyrations in the case have become almost routine, as
Elian has come to symbolize the deep hatred between Cuba's
communist government and Miami's Cuban exiles.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials decried the arrest of the immigration official
and the expulsion order for the diplomat, saying the moves were
part of a plot to keep Elian in the United States. The unnamed
diplomat has been the ``victim of a brutal provocation and a vile
calumny,'' said a statement issued by the Cuban government, which
has refused to call him home.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
