<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Two Brands of Spinach Leave Others Behind   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  After mashed potatoes and macaroni and cheese,
there may be no more comforting food than creamed spinach. Thanks
to companies making convenience products, it's possible to have
creamed spinach any time in a matter of minutes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted five brands of creamed spinach from the
freezer section. All were cooked in the microwave according to
package directions. All of the products can also be boiled in their
bags or baked in a conventional oven.
</P>
<P>
   Two brands ranked quite well, but the others fell seriously
short. The biggest complaint was the texture of the spinach, which
many panelists found tough and stringy. The panel also thought many
of the products were too salty _ sodium content ranged from 270 mg
to a whopping 1,170 mg, which is almost half of the recommended
daily allowance of sodium.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stouffer's &LR;  (nine ounces, $2.69 at Andronico's) was the panel's
favorite. Four panelists particularly liked the flavor, two of them
also commenting on the nice texture. But one panelist thought there
was too much sauce in proportion to the spinach, and another
thought the spinach tasted old. Four would buy it; one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Another popular brand among panelists was  &UR; Seabrook Farms &LR;  (nine
ounces, $1.55 at Safeway). Two panelists thought it had the most
true spinach taste and was nicely seasoned, but one described it as
bland. Others detected a metallic finish. Three would buy it, one
might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Scores dropped by more than thirty points to third place which
went to  &UR; Green Giant &LR;  (10 ounces, $1.89-$2.19 at many
supermarkets). Some panelists liked the larger leaves, but others
found them cumbersome. Tasters also complained about the chemical
butter flavor. One pointed out that some of the spinach leaves were
flecked with brown, as though they were old. One might buy it; four
would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Boston Market &LR;  (10 ounces, $1.89-$2.09 at many supermarkets)
came in fourth. Panelists disliked the heavy garlic flavor and the
saltiness (this brand had the highest sodium content). Some also
complained that the spinach tasted undercooked and stringy. One
might buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists also tasted Tabatchnick but it scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Lynne Bennett, California Culinary Academy
graduate; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Marc Halperin, culinary
director, Center for Culinary Development; Kim Severson, Chronicle
staff writer; Roland Passot, chef-owner of La Folie in San
Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo ParkKirk Webber,
chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are tasted
blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
