<SLUG> BC-BAKEOFF-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Chefs Flock to San Francisco to Vie for $1 Million Prize
in  Pillsbury's 50th Bake-Off   By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Forget the World Series, the Super Bowl and the
Final Four. The mother of all competitions hits San Francisco
Monday when 100 home cooks from across the country go
spatula-to-spatula in the Pillsbury Bake-Off.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's battle for kitchen bragging rights promises to be
bigger and better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the prize money: A cool million bucks for the
kitchen gladiator whose dish beats out 99 other casseroles, cakes
and canapes, plus $54,000 in prize money for the runners-up.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it's the 50th anniversary of the contest, which has been
growing in popularity and prize money ever since Eleanor Roosevelt
handed out the first check in 1949. To commemorate a half-century
of Poppin' Fresh Barbecups and Tunnel of Fudge cakes, Pillsbury has
created a Hall of Fame featuring the all-time 10 most popular
Bake-Off recipes and donated a package of memorabilia to the
Smithsonian's National Museum of American History.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pillsbury Bake-Off contest reflects changing tastes and
lifestyles in the United States over the last three generations,''
says Fath Davis Ruffins, Smithsonian museum historian.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes reveal America's moves into convenience food in the
'60s, into health food in the '70s and into microwave cooking and
more ethnic ingredients in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   This year's entries show that American cooks have fully embraced
cooking styles and ingredients already common in many Bay Area
kitchens. Roasted vegetables are popular. Portobello mushrooms,
which barely registered a blip among the tens of thousands of
recipes submitted to the Bake-Off two years ago, are prominent.
Butter, after taking a back seat to margarine, is back. And
desserts have gone through a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like after going through the death-by-chocolate '80s
and early '90s, we're seeing a lot of fruit everywhere,'' says
Pillsbury spokeswoman Marlene Johnson, a 20-year veteran of the
Bake-Off. ``Chocolate is number one but, boy, is there a lot of
fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Most striking, however, is that middle America's home cooks are
wading into the world of fusion and ethnic flavors. Mexican and
Latin American flavors show up in force, although that could be in
part because eight of the 29 official ingredients contestants had
to pick from were Old El Paso brands. (Pillsbury flour _ the
product the Bake-Off was invented to promote _ is not among the
official qualifying ingredients.) Salsas and chutneys abound, and
recipes use ingredients such as coconut milk, tamarind and lemon
grass.
</P>
<P>
   Bake-Off recipes, which are usually more suited for Women's Day
than Gourmet, are the most sophisticated and diverse ever. Gone are
the days when cheddar and Swiss were the most exotic cheeses. This
year, Asiago, feta and Gorgonzola are in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the recipes reflect what happens when fusion meets the
heartland. Consider Mandarin Chicken Salad Pizza from a Kansas
contestant or Thai Chicken Crescent Potsticker Sandwiches from a
Michigan finalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting boldness and authenticity from ethnic
ingredients and they aren't afraid to mix and match styles,''
Johnson says.
</P>
<P>
   A supper recipe submitted by one of the 11 California finalists
reflects that boldness, Johnson says. Julie Stutzman, 41, from
Martinez, the only finalist from the Bay Area, hopes her
Turkey-Mango Picadillo Wraps will catch the judge's fancy. She's
competing in the ``Easy Weeknight Meals'' category.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping the mango-raisin combination is innovative enough,
but I don't know,'' she says. ``It's a little unique in that it's
not casserole-y. It's a lot lighter.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Stutzman's first venture in the world of cooking contests,
but she's been around them all her life. Her mother, 72-year-old
Barbara Morgan of Concord, is a two-time Pillsbury Bake-Off
finalist and a winner of several other, smaller competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Mother told daughter that becoming one of a hundred finalists
among tens of thousands of entries is really the prize. And
already, Stutzman, executive development director of the non-profit
Ruth Bancroft Garden in Walnut Creek, received $100 and a new
General Electric Advantium oven that's supposed to cook food in a
quarter of the time a conventional oven does.
</P>
<P>
   She is looking forward to four days of being pampered and
catered to in her free room at the Marriott Hotel, the event's
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're treated like royalty,` Stutzman says.
</P>
<P>
   The contestants spend Monday cooking in fully stocked,
individual kitchenettes built around new stoves trucked in by GE
especially for the contest. Each will be calibrated and leveled, so
no one can complain about having bad equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury staffers buy enough ingredients so each finalist can
make as many as three batches before selecting one for the judges _
12 food writers and editors _ who are sequestered nearby.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the winner will be announced on national television.
The show airs live at 11 a.m. on the East Coast and is tape-delayed
to be shown at 10 a.m. on the West Coaston KPIX (Channel 5).
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically we pre-empt half of `The Price is Right,''' Johnson
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
BAKE-OFF EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   The Pillsbury Bake-Off is generally for the participants and
judges only, but the public can attend the following two events
and, of course, watch the announcement of the winner on television.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Viewing &LR; . Competition begins at 8 a.m. Monday. Dishes must be
submitted to the judges by 1 p.m. The public may view entries and
other Pillsbury displays in the halls of the San Francisco
Marriott, 55 Fourth St. (at Mission Street).
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Kids Bake-Off. &LR;  Sunday, 8 a.m.-5 p.m. at the Marriott's
Golden Gate Hall. Sixty cooks ages 9 through 13 will compete for
grocery gift certificates and a $1,000 savings bond.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; TV coverage. &LR;  The winner will be announced during a live
television broadcast at 8 a.m. Tuesday and televised on the East
Coast. A tape-delayed broadcast on KPIX (Channel 5) will air at 10
a.m. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A Snapshot of the Pillsbury Bake-Off Through the Years
</P>
<P>
   YEAR HOST GENDER BREAKDOWN POPULAR INGREDIENTS WINNING RECIPE
TOTAL PRIZE MONEY TRENDS
</P>
<P>
   1949, New York Art Linkletter 3 men, 97 women Flour, buttermilk,
whipping cream and baking extracts like vanilla and lemon.
Water-Rising Twists, yeast-based sweet roll raised while submerged
in a bucket of water. $70,000 The first bake-off was designed to
celebrate women returning to the kitchen after WWII. Eleanor
Roosevelt was the guest of honor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
1966, San Francisco Pat Boone 3 men, 97 women Self-rising flour,
mashed potato flakes, frosting and pudding mixes. Golden Gate Snack
Bread made with cheese spread and onion soup mix. $40,000 The theme
`'Busy Lady'' was a nod to the growing need for convenience
cooking. The popularity of time-saving recipes prompts the Bake-Off
to add categories for refrigerated dough and baking mixes the
following year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
1978, New Orleans Bob Barker 4 men, 96 women Crescent rolls and
refrigerator biscuits; whole wheat flour, bran and raisins;
vegetables suchas broccoli and asparagus. Two awarded:
Chik-N-Broccoli Pot Pies made with Hungry Jack biscuits and Nutty
Graham Picnic Cake flavored with orange juice and brown sugar.
$79,000 Ingredients in several prize winners reflect a growing
interest in nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
2000, San Francisco Phylicia Rashad 8 men, 92 women Mixes and
refrigerated dough; a variety of cheeses like feta and Asiago and
bold flavors such as sun-dried tomatoes, cilantro and ginger. To be
announced on Tuesday $1.054 million, including $1 million for the
winner Fusions of various ethnic cuisines and an emphasis on
Mexican and Latin dishes prominent; fruit emerges as a popular item
in desserts, rivaling chocolate.
</P>
