 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Creamy Lemon Pasta Dances on Your Tongue   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  I'm in love with the Linguine with Lemon Cream at
Mescolanza, a charming neighborhood Italian restaurant in the
Richmond District.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's so simple _ only six ingredients, counting the pasta _ but
the end result is extraordinary. The flavors of cream, butter and
Parmesan cheese set off the fresh lemon. And the amazing thing is,
the dish has an intense taste without having to add lemon zest: the
flavor comes from the juice alone.
</P>
<P>
   In the restaurant, the dish is served without any garnish. At
home, this pasta can become the base for many versions. I love it
with fresh lemon thyme or tarragon sprinkled on top. It's also
exceptional with sauteed shrimp or broccoli rabe.
</P>
<P>
   Mescolanza opened in 1987, but was purchased in 1998 by Maria
and Ruben Macedo, who had been cooking at the restaurant since it
opened.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are reasonable _ most items are less than $12 _ and the
recently redone interior makes this restaurant a cut above the
typical neighborhood trattoria.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Mescolanza, 2221 Clement St. (between 23rd and 24th &LR; 
 &LR; streets), San Francisco; (415) 668-2221. Dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Lots of lemon. &LR;  The juice of five lemons seems like a lot,
but this amount gives the sauce a fresh intensity without having to
grate or chop the zest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ The utter simplicity. &LR;  The play between the cream, butter,
Parmesan and lemon juice is invigorating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LINGUINE WITH LEMON CREAM
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried linguine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt + salt for cooking pasta
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 5 lemons
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter, cut into pieces
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Cook the linguine in a large pot of generously salted water
until tender but still firm to the bite, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, combine the cream, lemon juice and 1/2 teaspoon salt
in a large saucepan over medium-high heat. Bring to a boil. Add the
cheese and butter. Stir constantly until the sauce thickens, about
5 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the pasta. Transfer to a large serving bowl. Pour sauce
over; toss to coat. Season with white pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 830 calories, &LR;   &LR; 17 g protein, 63 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 57 g fat (35 g saturated), 188 mg cholesterol, 597
mg sodium, 0 &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
