<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE SHOW, TIME TO PARTY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: FIXES bad slug) 
 
 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With nearly 100 categories, there will be plenty of winners at
tonight's Grammy Awards. With nearly 1,000 nominees, there will be
plenty of losers, too.
</P>
<P>
   For both, the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences,
which sponsors the Grammys, is putting on one big party down the
street so nominees can either a) celebrate their victories or b)
drown their sorrows.
</P>
<P>
   The post-Grammy party, produced by veteran entertainment
industry party-giver Mary Micucci of Along Comes Mary Productions,
will take over the Biltmore Hotel in downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It will feature performances by several nominees, including
trad-country stalwarts Asleep at the Wheel with Dwight Yoakam;
jazzbos Manhattan Transfer with Marty Stuart; revived '60s rockers
Eric Burdon &AMP; the New Animals with Spencer Davis and John Mayall;
r&AMP;b classicists the Bar-Kays; Latin jazzers the Pete Escovedo
Orchestra, Poncho Sanchez and Tito Puente; and other jazz, techno,
zydeco and chamber-music artists.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrants will be dining on some of the area's top food,
too, with a spread presided over by the Biltmore's executive chef,
Roger Pigozzi.
</P>
<P>
   They include Southwestern chefs (and radio hosts) Mary Sue
Milliken and Susan Feniger of Border Grill and Ciudad; postmodern
sushi star Nobu Matsuhisa of Matsuhisa; Takashi ``Fred'' Iwasaki of
Wolfgang Puck's Chinois on Main; Euro-eclecticist Hans Rockenwagner
of Rockenwagner and Rock; Cuban-Asian experimentalist Xiomara
Ardolina of Pasadena's Xiomara; Angelo Auriana of the Italianate
heaven Valentino and the chefs of two of Joachim Splichal's
sterling restaurant group, Walter Manzke of Patina and Joseph
Gillard of Nick &AMP; Stef's Steakhouse. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
