 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: What's Best to Drink With A Grilled Cheese 
 Sandwich?  By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; When I was a young boy, one of my fondest food
memories was my mother fixing me a grilled cheese sandwich for
lunch. If I was lucky, and we had butter in the house, she would
spread it liberally on one side of a piece of white bread, place
the bread, buttered-side down in a cast-iron frying pan, top it
with two thick slices of American cheese, then complete the
sandwich with another slice of bread, buttered-side up.
<P>
   A tall glass of cold milk was my beverage of choice in those
days, but today I'd be happy to savor my grilled cheese sandwich
with a tall glass of cold ale or lager, an aromatic dry white wine
or a glass of light red wine.
</P>
<P>
   Just about any lager or ale will do, but I like Anchor Steam,
Sierra Nevada Pale Ale and Red Hook Old India Pale Ale. The buttery
richness of melted cheese is a good match with a dry Riesling or
Chenin Blanc, a light red Beaujolais-Villages or Napa Gamay or even
a dry Tavel Ros &LR; e &LR;  from the Rhone Valley of France.
</P>
<P>
   Matching wine with cheese is not difficult, and melted or not
makes little difference. Just follow the same basic rule as you
would with wine and other foods; the seasonings and sauces are more
important than the type of meat or fish.
</P>
<P>
   Since cheese usually is not sauced or seasoned, simply remember:
The fresher and drier the cheese, the lighter, less complicated the
wine. Herbed goat cheese is great with a nonoaked Sauvignon Blanc,
but a creamy Camembert cries out for a bigger more complex Cabernet
Sauvignon, especially if the cheese is just starting to ``melt''
out of the rind.
</P>
<P>
   European cousins of the American grilled cheese sandwich include
fondue and raclette. Fondue, traditionally made in Switzerland with
Emmentaler, calls for a light red like Chianti, a Swiss Dole (Pinot
Noir and Gamay), or even a light-medium Zinfandel. Raclette, made
in Switzerland with a mild rustic cheese called raclette, works
nicely with a light Swiss white like Chasselas, an Italian Pinot
Grigio, or a dry California Sauvignon Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh Rarebit, an English cheddar-based dipping sauce made with
a hearty beer is best with beer, not wine.
</P>
<P>
   Italian melting cheeses that are favorites among Americans
include mozzarella and provolone. Slices of nutty flavorful
provolone melted in a casserole or open-face sandwich marry nicely
with a medium to full-bodied red like California Sangiovese,
Italian Chianti and Gattinara or a Mourvedre from the south of
France.
</P>
<P>
   Mozzarella, of course, means pizza, although the cheese is much
more versatile. Personally, I prefer a crisp lager with pizza, but
a light-medium red like Chianti or a California Nebbiolo is a nice
match with a cheese-y pizza.
</P>
<P>
   For all dishes with melted cheese, the bottom wine-line is: Stay
with light and dry, whether red or white, or opt for a hearty lager
or ale, and you can't go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Events &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Wine as Rare as the Place is the theme for the Year 2000 Tour
of the Napa Valley Vintners Association. The vintners will hold a
special tasting to benefit the Arthritis Foundation, March 13, 7-9
p.m., at the Hyatt Regency, 5 Embarcadero Center, San Francisco.
Tickets are $50 per person in advance and $55 at the door. To order
tickets, and for more information, contact the Arthritis Foundation
at (800) 464-6240.
</P>
<P>
   _ Welcome spring this year with a visit to the colorful gardens
of Ferrari-Carano Winery and the Villa Fiore Hospitality Center,
8761 Dry Creek Road, Healdsburg, Sonoma County. On April 8, 11 a.m.
to 4 p.m., Ferrari-Carano will hold the 10th Annual Taste of
Spring, a preview of a fresh, new season. Included will be
Ferrari-Carano's new wines and springtime foods from winery chef
Joseph Costanzo. A $10 per person fee includes a complimentary
glass. For more information, call the winery at (707) 433-6700.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WineScore &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Working on the theory that everything is easier with a computer,
there's now software called WineScore that claims to take the
guessing out of which wine to choose when you're in a store or
restaurant. Designed for Palm computing devices, WineScore rates
more than 5,300cq &LR;  wines on a scale of 1 to 10, using the input
from major wine reviewers and medals won in 1998 and 1999 wine
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   WineScore software is priced at $24.95 and is marketed through
the Internet at  &LR; www.winescore.com &LR;  and various other software
e-commerce Web sites. For more information call (877) 845-9990 or
e-mail:  &LR; info &LR; winescore.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh  &LR; Stimson Lane Goes Aussie
</P>
<P>
   In a move that reflects the importance of the global wine
market, Stimson Lane Vineyard &AMP; Estates, parent company of
Washington's Chateau Ste. Michelle and Columbia Crest, has
announced a joint venture with Australian Brian Crosner, of
Petaluma Vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   The new venture will produce a line of super-premium Australian
wines that will be marketed under the Petaluma name in North
America. The first vintages are expected to be released this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Crosner, who received his winemaking degree from the University
of California at Davis, liked the name of the town Petaluma
(California) so much, he named his winery in South Australia after
it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Has American-made Viognier hit its peak? Could be that
Viognier's 15 minutes of fame are up, and it's time to step aside
for the next hot white wine, like Pinot Gris. Viognier is native to
the Northern Rhone where it stars in the lively wines of Condrieu.
Rarer still is the Viognier from the seven-acre estate of
Chateau-Grillet. So famous is Grillet, that it has its own
appellation, one of the smallest in France.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you recently won the lottery and have connections, pass
on the ultra-expensive Chateau-Grillet and opt for a less-expensive
Condrieu.
</P>
</TEXT>
