 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: `Pot Pies' Promises More Than It Delivers  &HT;       
 By David A. Steinberg  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Most people would agree that the lowly potpie is a
quintessential part of the American culinary landscape. Long before
Julia Child taught Middle America how to stop worrying and learn to
love French cuisine, there were potpies.
<P>
   Though often dismissed as a catch-all way of reinventing
leftovers, most of us when we were growing up couldn't wait for
those wintry days when mom would either make one from scratch or
(as in my case) heat one up courtesy of Safeway's freezer section.
Potpies are the very definition of comfort food.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine my surprise when I discovered that Diane Phillips'
``Pot Pies: Comfort Food Under Cover'' not only stretched the
definition of a potpie, but also failed to deliver anything
remotely resembling the classic potpie we have grown to know and
love.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Phillips extrapolates the concept of a potpie past
recognition. It seems like a case of false advertising. Maybe I'm
reacting to some sort of existential loss of childhood, but then
again, if someone labels a cookbook ``pot pies'' I think it is not
unreasonable to expect some of the classics to appear out of
courtesy, if nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the recipes were, indeed, imaginative and edible. The
Portobello Mushroom Pie was oddly interesting, though the recipe
was time consuming and labor intensive. The result, however, was
far more like a phyllo-wrapped calzone than a potpie, especially
considering there was nary a pot to be found anywhere in the
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   The promising sound of Old-Fashioned Chicken Pot Pie with Chive
Mashed Potato Crust ended up being more recognizable as a
shepherd's pie, but even with a change in nomenclature, the recipe
was adequate at best in the end.
</P>
<P>
   One bright spot was the Pot Roasted Lamb with Rosemary White
Bean Crust. With a more-than-passing resemblance to cassoulet, the
result was every inch comfort food: hearty, rich and satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   While this cookbook is far from a failure, the overall effect is
that it promises more than it delivers. Many recipes appear to
resemble other types of comfort foods such as casseroles, stews and
that tried-and-true staple of Midwestern potlucks _ the hot dish.
</P>
<P>
   While trying to shoehorn everything under the potpie rubric,
Phillips ends up muddling the flavors and textures. The results
vary from good to extremely disappointing. My recommendation is to
get the recipe from your mom if you want a truly heart-warming
potpie, or at least pick up a Marie Callender's at Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Pot Pies: Comfort Food Under Cover,'' by Diane Phillips &LR; 
 &LR; (Doubleday; 214 pages; hardcover; $24.95). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
POT ROASTED LAMB WITH ROSEMARY WHITE BEAN CRUST
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds boneless lamb, cut into 11/2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups finely chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 cups beef broth
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cooked white beans
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 375 degrees. Heat the oil in a 5-quart Dutch
oven. Sprinkle the lamb with the salt and pepper, and brown it in
the hot oil a few pieces at a time, removing the pieces from the
pan as they are done, about 6-8 minutes. Add the garlic, onions,
carrots, celery and 2 teaspoons of the rosemary to the pan, and
saute for 3 minutes, until the vegetables begin to soften. Stir in
the flour and cook for 3 minutes, until the flour begins to bubble,
then gradually whisk in the broths, bringing the liquid to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Return the lamb to the pan and simmer for 10 minutes. Float the
beans on top of the pie.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the breadcrumbs, the remaining teaspoon of rosemary and
the parsley and sprinkle the mixture on top of the beans. Bake the
pie for 45 minutes, until the crust is browned and the meat is
tender.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 630 calories, &LR;   &LR; 61 g protein, 49 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 20 g fat (7 g saturated), 154 mg cholesterol, 854
mg sodium, 10 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
