<HEADLINE>
MOUNSEY TEARS KNEE LIGAMENT, OUT FOR SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tara Mounsey, a defenseman on the 1998 women's Olympic ice
hockey team that won the gold medal in Nagano and now a captain for
Brown University, will miss the rest of the season after tearing
the anterior cruciate ligament in her right knee during a loss to
Harvard Saturday. She is scheduled to undergo surgery March 8.
</P>
<P>
   A junior from Concord, N.H., and the Bears' leading scorer this
season with 14 goals and 10 assists, Mounsey said Tuesday she was
fighting off a Harvard defender midway through the second period
when ``I felt it go.'' She crumpled to the ice and was helped off.
An MRI on Monday confirmed the tear.
</P>
<P>
   Mounsey is no stranger to the injury: She missed her junior
season at Concord High School while recovered from a torn ACL in
her left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to know how much therapy I have that lies ahead of
me,'' she said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As for this season, ``I was feeling so good and getting ready
for the playoffs,'' said a subdued Mounsey, who missed the first
four games of the ice hockey season while she was leading Brown's
field hockey team to the NCAA tournament and being named an
All-American. ``I guess life isn't always simple. I'll get through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury is a blow to Brown, which lost Saturday, 2-1, for the
first time in 16 games. It clings to first place in the ECAC by
just a point over Dartmouth with four games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll definitely miss Tara, but I think the other kids can
pick up the slack,'' said coach Digit Murphy, who added that she
was encouraged by the Bears' 4-0 victory in a nonconference game
against Providence the next day.
</P>
<P>
   With an average recovery time of 4-6 months, the injury
shouldn't severely handicap Mounsey's chances of making the 2002
Olympic squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to take it one day at a time and maybe I'll be
able to go to camp this summer,'' she said, referring to a festival
Aug. 13-22 during which evaluations will be made for a pre-Olympic
touring team. ``I want to get back 100 percent and be ready to
go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
