<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Feb. 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, temperatures soared to 70 degrees as far north as
St. Louis, as gusty breezes from the south imported unseasonably
warm air north into much of the central states. During Wednesday,
the axis of warmth will shift eastward. Indeed, amid partial
sunshine afternoon readings will reach the 60s from the Ohio Valley
to the southern Middle Atlantic states. Sunshine and very mild
conditions will also cover the Northeast, though clouds will
prevail from the eastern Great Lakes to the mountains of New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered strong to severe thunderstorms will erupt across the
lower Mississippi Valley as a flow of humid air from the Gulf of
Mexico intercepts a jet stream disturbance passing overhead. A few
of the storms could be severe, replete with hail and damaging
winds. These storms will spread east into the Tennessee Valley by
evening. Showers will also dampen portions of the central Plains
and upper Mississippi Valley Wednesday as moist air is drawn into
the circulation of low pressure over Kansas. Farther south, morning
showers and thunderstorms will yield to afternoon sunshine across
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A plume of moist air will take aim on portions of the West Coast
Wednesday, bringing heavy rain to much of western California from
near Los Angeles to the Oregon border. As the damp air ascends the
higher terrain of the interior mountains, it will cool setting the
stage for heavy snow across the Sierra. Lighter showers and
mountain snow will also occur in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Rainy California
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, record daily rainfalls were measured from Los Angeles
to San Diego. As it does nearly every year, the heart of the rainy
season has arrived in California. Weather stations from Arcata in
the north to San Diego in the south report their greatest average
rainfall in January and February with a sharp decline in wet
weather thereafter. Early in the cool season, the jet stream
typically sends Pacific storms toward the Northwest coast. At this
time of year, the jet stream has reached its southernmost position
of the winter, directing the parade of Pacific storms toward
California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
