<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIAN-TESTIMONY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DAVIDIAN FOLLOWER DISCUSSES EVENTS IN WACO SIEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DICK J. REAVIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a fall afternoon in 1993, Derek Lovelock, a 38-year-old
Briton, suddenly found himself standing on the sidewalks of Waco,
three hours before the flight that would take him home.
</P>
<P>
   He was wearing a secondhand T-shirt, jeans whose origin were a
mystery to him _ and rubbery jail sandals. His own clothing had
been taken, presumably as evidence, when he was jailed seven months
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Lovelock had never been charged with a crime. Federal
authorities had held him, without bond, as a material witness to
the 1993 gunfight and fire at David Koresh's Branch Davidian
compound near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The British Consulate in Houston intervened to obtain Lovelock's
release from jail, because his father had died.
</P>
<P>
   Once back in Manchester, he was not recalled, either by
prosecutors in the 1994 San Antonio trial of 11 other survivors,
nor in 1995, when Congress investigated the federal siege of
Koresh's religious compound.
</P>
<P>
   Lovelock was in Houston last week for an interview with lawyers
for special counsel John Danforth, the former U.S. senator from
Missouri who is investigating the Waco events for the Justice
Department. Lovelock also returned to Texas to be deposed in a
wrongful death lawsuit, slated for trial in May, that other
survivors of the Branch Davidian attack filed against the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   In his sworn statements and in an interview, the British witness
gave an account of his time at the Branch Davidian compound that
challenges several points of the official version of the Waco
events _ and also debunks some claims that conspiracy theorists and
government critics have raised.
</P>
<P>
   Like most survivors of the siege, whenever the chance presents
itself, Lovelock also sought to reaffirm his faith in the religious
message that first brought him to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   During the late 1980s, Lovelock, a member of a Seventh-day
Adventist Church, ran across a publication that warned about
Koresh, who had gone to the United Kingdom to recruit Adventists
for his flock. Lovelock was intrigued, despite the church's
warning.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he went to the Koresh compound, where, he said, ``From
the Scriptures, David showed me things that no man had shown me.''
</P>
<P>
   Some two years later, he took up residence at the compound
again, even though there were aspects of its life that displeased
him _ first among them, guns. When other males volunteered for
lessons in weaponry, he stayed away. ``I just don't like guns,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He insists that he didn't take up a weapon, as others did, on
the morning of Feb. 28, 1993, when some 75 agents of the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms raided the property in search of a
cache of weapons. Lovelock said he was in the building's cafeteria
when ``I heard the helicopters. They got louder and louder, almost
as if they were landing on the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleadings in the wrongful death suit allege that federal agents
in the aircraft fired upon the Branch Davidian compound. Lovelock
did not see bullets strike where he was, nor did any shots come
through the walls of the bedroom in which he took cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran to the room and threw myself on the floor,'' he said,
not looking up until the shooting stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Four ATF agents and six followers of the Branch Davidian
religious cult died in the Feb. 28 gun battle. Koresh and more than
70 Branch Davidians, including some 21 children, died during the
inferno that ended the siege on April 19. (What caused the deadly
fire continues to be a source of speculation and investigation.)
</P>
<P>
   ATF agents who testified in the 1994 criminal trial denied that
they fired at unseen targets, and the House of Representatives,
during 1995 queries into the events at Waco, looked into charges
that shots were fired from the helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   While the House found no evidence to substantiate allegations
about helicopter gunfire, its report noted that ``there is
insufficient evidence to determine with certainty as to who fired
the shots'' that witnesses say left holes in the roof of the
Davidian complex.
</P>
<P>
   Lovelock said what he saw in the aftermath of the gun battle
convinced him that the helicopters fired at the building and that
ATF raiders fired through its doors.
</P>
<P>
   He drew these conclusions partly from viewing the body of
Winston Blake, a fellow Briton who had been his roommate. Blake was
shot dead, his autopsy and an ATF report say, by a bullet fired at
close range.
</P>
<P>
   Lovelock contests that finding. He believes Blake was felled by
shots fired from the helicopters toward vinyl water storage tanks
that stood in front of a window in the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the bullet holes in the tanks,'' Lovelock said. ``There
were three of them, in a straight line. There was water coming into
the room.''
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department's 1993 report on the Waco incident lists
Perry Jones, 64, as a second murder or suicide victim. The official
view is supported by a coroner's report, noting only one wound in
Jones' body _ in the roof of his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Davidians who witnessed the raid admit that one of their number,
now dead, killed Jones, but they insist that his killing was an act
of mercy. Jones, they say, had been wounded by ATF fire as he stood
at the front door of the Branch Davidian building in the early
minutes of the raid. He begged to be put out of his misery, they
have testified.
</P>
<P>
   Lovelock said he saw Jones before his death, ``lying on his bed,
blood on his abdomen. He had been shot by the ATF.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Feb. 28 raid was over, Lovelock did not seriously
consider coming out, he said, because ``my fear of God was greater
than my fear of man. God is in control of my destiny, not man, and
I could have lost my soul eternally.''
</P>
<P>
   He presumed Koresh would eventually arrange an exit with the
FBI, which took over the siege shortly after the members of the
religious cult repelled the ATF.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it would end up like it did,'' he said, ``and I
didn't think that I would be put in jail, because I hadn't done
anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The seven years since have not been kind ones, the survivor
says. A cook before he joined Koresh, Lovelock has not resumed life
in the workaday world. He is undergoing counseling and treatment
for depression, and flashbacks beset him, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I see something on TV, like a policeman dressed like
the ATF, it all comes back to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even on better days, he says, he is not up to par. ``I've lost
my get-up-and-go, my concentration and my confidence,'' he said.
Today, Lovelock lives on public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   If there is light in his life, it antedates the events of 1993.
Lovelock, like others who survived the Waco ordeal, is steadfast in
his faith that Koresh was a prophet.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Waco messiah's scriptural interpretations, much on
Lovelock's mind during the 51-day siege, remains fresh in his mind
today.
</P>
<P>
   Koresh told his flock that what lay ahead was foretold in the
Bible's Book of Nahum, a book that many scholars think is
historical, not predictive, describing events in the seventh
century B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The text the Davidian preacher cited says ``The chariots shall
rage in the streets ... they shall seem like torches, they shall
run like the lightnings.'' Koresh told his followers that those
``chariots'' would be military tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the wicked fulfill prophecy,'' Lovelock said. ``As David
said to the FBI, `You guys made Nahum come true.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
