<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News has moved the following feature
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients on Wednesday, Feb.
23, 2000 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please
contact Steven Rosenberg at the Daily News, (818) 713-3752.
</P>
<P>
   GRAMMYS-PRODUCER _ Superproducer Walter Afanasieff, at 41, is at
the top of his game. He's got records by Mariah Carey, Celine Dion,
Michael Bolton, Kenny G, Ricky Martin, Whitney Houston, Babyface,
Marc Anthony, Barbara Streisand and more under his belt. Last
year's Grammy-winning ``My Heart Will Go On''? Yep, that's him.
He's competing for the highly regarded producer of the year Grammy.
By Fred Shuster (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   GRAMMYS-SCHIFRIN _ For Mr. ``Mission: Impossible'' Lalo
Schifrin, it's the music that matters. Sure, he's been nominated
for 20 Grammys over the years, winning four, but he'd rather be in
the guest house behind his Beverly Hills home plinking away on the
Bosendorfer piano. And what about this Latin explosion thing? He's
been blazing a trail for those kinds of sounds _ and an advocate
for blending jazz and classical music _ for decades now. By Marla
Matzer Rose (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   GRAMMYS-PARTY _ After the show at the Staples Center ends, the
partying begins at the Biltmore Hotel with performances by Asleep
at the Wheel, Dwight Yoakam, Manhattan Transfer, Eric Burdon,
Poncho Sanchez, Tito Puente and more. The food will be provided by
many of L.A.'s top chefs, including Mary Sue Millikan and Susan
Feniger, Nobu Matsuhisa and Hans Rockenwagner. By David Bloom
(moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WONDER-REVIEW _ Review of ``The Wonder Boys,'' starring
Michael Douglas as a more-than-slightly disheveled
writer/professor, Tobey Maguire as the new wunderkind on the block
and Robert Downey Jr. as an amoral book editor. By Glenn Whipp
(moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
</TEXT>
