<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT23-COX     02-22 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT WARNS JUDGE IN FINAL ROUND OF TRIAL
 &HT;    480&AMP;add. Moving in the (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Microsoft Corp. lawyer Tuesday urged U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson to consider the harm a
sweeping guilty verdict in the high-profile antitrust case could
cause to the most dynamic sector of the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Jackson issued ``findings of fact'' that that
Microsoft does have an operating system monopoly, and has leveraged
that monopoly to stifle competition and harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   With that ruling having all but sealed the outcome of the trial,
Microsoft sought to persuade the judge to look beyond the narrower
legal issues and focus on the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   Lead attorney John Warden, citing Microsoft's all-but-universal
operating system for personal computers, said: ``I find the
government's assaults on Windows to be truly remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a critical element to the PC,'' Warden said. ``It is the
modern paradigm of a product that not only promotes commerce but
creates wealth. It is the engine that has driven our economy to new
heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden's appeal came toward the close of nearly five hours of
oral arguments over how Jackson should apply the antitrust laws as
they relate to the already established facts in the case.
</P>
<P>
   His position was promptly countered by David Boies, the chief
government litigator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an attack on success,'' Boies informed Jackson.
``It is an attack on practices that have no other purpose but
anti-competitive, monopolistic behavior. You have been told that
you ought to give the (Microsoft) PC operating system a pass
because it is a creative engine. But I think the contrary is true.
If the heavy hand of monopoly were lifted, this industry would
thrive and prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden, however, insisted on having the last word.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of nothing doesn't add up to something,'' he boomed.
``The government is stuck with a chain of suppositions. We've heard
about a miscellaneous ragtag of acts. That's not proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling a halt to proceedings. Jackson said: ``Gentlemen, after
two and a half years, it's still a pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   He then summoned the litigants _ including Joel Klein, chief of
the Justice Department's antitrust division, and four attorneys
general representing the 19 states that are also parties to the
case _ to his chambers.
</P>
<P>
   For some months, at Jackson's behest, a federal mediator in
Chicago has been seeking to broker an out-of-court settlement that
would absolve Jackson of having to issue a final ruling and impose
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was called to assess how well Richard Posner, the
presiding chief of the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals, was doing in
cutting a deal. If Jackson believes there's a good chance for an
accord, he might be inclined to delay his ruling, which is
otherwise expected in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Deal or no deal, Boies dwelled at length on a litany of U.S.
Supreme Court rulings that he maintained fit the facts in the
Microsoft trial. These cases could leave Jackson with the
reasonable prospect that he would not be reversed were he to drop a
legal hammer on the company, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson gave Microsoft a small glimmer of hope when he pressed
the opposing attorneys on how he might fit to the facts of this
case a previous setback by a federal appeals court. In 1998, the
higher court rejected Jackson's finding that Microsoft had
illegally tied its Internet Explorer Web browser to the Windows 95
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   While the appeals' panel ruled for Microsoft largely on
technical grounds, it also stated that the union of Windows 95 and
Explorer was a legal ``genuine integration'' because it was done
for efficiency's sake and had positive consequences. That is not
now the government's view.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson's overall skepticism as to the worthiness of
Microsoft's claims was display when he likened Microsoft's actions
to the classic Standard Oil monopoly, which the Supreme Court
dissolved nearly 90 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Rockefeller had fee simple (absolute) control over his
oil,'' Jackson told Warden. ``I don't really see a distinction
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
