<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER23-COX     02-22 1649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Big clash in Michigan
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain, seeking to bounce back from a staggering weekend
defeat in South Carolina, clashed Tuesday with George W. Bush in
primaries in Michigan and Arizona. ``Every day is do or die,''
McCain said. Heading into a high-stakes run of 16 primaries and
caucuses in 14 days, Bush and McCain agreed that Michigan's voting
was pivotal. ``That's why I'm still here in the state working to
turn out the vote,'' Bush told a suburban Detroit crowd.
</P>
<P>
   KEEP THOSE BALLOTS ROLLING
</P>
<P>
   In some areas of southwest Michigan, they were having to print
more ballots because of the heavy turnout in Tuesday's GOP primary.
Earlier, though, turnout was said to be light in much of the state.
There are 58 delegates at stake in Michigan _ where the primary
isn't limited to Republican voters _ and another 30 in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   THIS TIME HE COULD EVEN VOTE
</P>
<P>
   John McCain was in Phoenix on Tuesday with one primary-day
advantage over George W. Bush: He got to cast a vote. ``I think
that it's kind of nice to be the first presidential candidate in
this campaign to vote for himself,'' McCain said after he and wife
Cindy cast ballots at the Arizona Veterans Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   NEXT UP AFTER TODAY
</P>
<P>
   With Michigan and Arizona behind them, the Republicans will now
square off next Tuesday in Virginia, North Dakota and Washington
state. The Democrats will also compete in Washington. George W.
Bush has his eye on Virginia, politically similar to South
Carolina, where he beat John McCain decisively. At stake in
Virginia are 56 delegates, winner take all. McCain has his sights
on Washington, an independent-minded state that will allocate 12 of
its 37 delegates by percentage of ballots. For the Democrats, the
Washington primary is a ``beauty contest''; all of its 75 delegates
will be assigned during a March 7 caucus. North Dakota Republicans,
with 19 delegates at stake, are shifting from a primary to a caucus
this year.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING THE DOZENS IN HARLEM
</P>
<P>
   The race for the Democratic presidential nomination has become
very angry, with the two candidates slamming each other
continually. In their debate Monday night at Harlem's Apollo
Theater, Al Gore and Bill Bradley attacked each other relentlessly
on racial and urban affairs issues and challenged each other's
commitment to racial justice. In their ninth face-to-face meeting,
each attempted to knock out the other and portray himself as the
candidate best equipped to bridge racial divides and champion
federal programs that are important to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   SHOWTIME AT THE APOLLO
</P>
<P>
   The red velvet seats in the orchestra section and two mezzanines
of the Apollo Theater were dotted with celebrities _ and celebrity
attorneys _ for the big debate between Al Gore and Bill Bradley. As
movie director Spike Lee was being interviewed, the Rev. Al
Sharpton waited for a photo-op with Lee. Whoopi Goldberg held Lee's
leather jacket and waited for her turn with the press. Also there
were Dallas Cowboys veteran Calvin Hill and Los Angeles Lakers
coach Phil Jackson, both Bradley supporters. Gore acknowledged
Martin Luther King III of Atlanta midway through. There also was
O.J. Simpson defense lawyer, Johnnie Cochran. His favorite was
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   PREACHING VIA TELEPHONE
</P>
<P>
   Religious broadcaster Pat Robertson is using a recorded
telephone message to attack John McCain's national campaign chief,
former Sen. Warren Rudman (R-N.H.), as ``a vicious bigot who wrote
that conservative Christians in politics are anti-abortion zealots,
homophobes and would-be censors.'' ``John McCain refused to
repudiate these words,'' Robertson added in the message that was
taped Monday by a Michigan man and shared with the McCain campaign.
Rudman angered leaders of the religious right in 1995 by defending
retired Gen. Colin Powell against their attacks over abortion.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON RIPS BUSH ON REBEL FLAG
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson excoriated George W. Bush, warning that his
stances on important racial issues _ particularly the question of
whether South Carolina should fly the Confederate flag over the
state Capitol _ has reframed the primary season as ``not Bush vs.
McCain, but Bush vs. the history of our nation.'' Jackson said he
was not prepared to endorse a Democrat, but he criticized Bill
Bradley for ``offering no leadership in a crunch time'' when the
issue of racial profiling surfaced in his home state of New Jersey
last year.
</P>
<P>
   AND FLOAT LIKE A BUTTERFLY
</P>
<P>
   Film director Spike Lee will be in a TV ad aimed at helping Bill
Bradley make a comeback in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just got to take the gloves off,'' Lee said.
``It's for real now. Bill will come out smoking.'' The ad has not
yet been filmed, he said. Lee said he's concerned that black voters
are blindly supporting Al Gore. ``Right or wrong, black people
think President Clinton can do no wrong. But I don't think that
means we should automatically transfer that allegiance from Clinton
to Al Gore,'' Lee said. Basketball legend Michael Jordan already
stars in a Bradley ad.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR A BIG TRUMP CARD
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Jordan now on TV for Bill Bradley's team, Al Gore
wants to trump that with, well, Trump.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and The Donald _ New York developer Donald Trump _ talked
by telephone last weekend, and Gore asked for his endorsement,
according to The Associated Press. Trump, who recently decided not
to run himself as a Reform Party candidate, was said to be
considering the request. Gore's spokesman Chris Lehane confirmed
that the pair had talked.
</P>
<P>
   THAT'S THE WASHINGTON WITHOUT THE BELTWAY
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley is shifting his insurgent's campaign to Washington
state in hopes that it's independent-minded voters will give him a
lift in next week's nonbinding Democratic ``beauty contest''
primary. Starting Wednesday, Bradley plans to spend six days in the
state with the West's second-largest bloc of national convention
delegates, after California. Backers say the Feb. 29 showdown could
give Bradley a boost heading into the pivotal round of
coast-to-coast contests a week later.
</P>
<P>
   S O WHERE'S THE HOME-COURT ADVANTAGE?
</P>
<P>
   Even in his home state, Missouri, Bill Bradley appears to face
daunting odds against Al Gore. Bradley trailed Gore 48 percent to
31 percent in Missouri, according to a St. Louis Post-Dispatch poll
published Sunday. The outlook was even worse across the Mississippi
River in Illinois, where Gore was holding a 59 percent to 24
percent lead. Among Republican voters in Missouri, George W. Bush
held a 55 percent to 26 percent lead over John McCain. The poll did
not include Republicans in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   A BIGGER RUN ON DONUTS EVERY FOUR YEARS
</P>
<P>
   The Gore-Bradley debate produced one quick benefit for Harlem: a
big boost for donut sales across the street from the Apollo
Theater. The customers were security police. But the manager of the
Krispy Kreme shop wasn't all that impressed with the Democratic
contenders in the neighborhood. ``Parachuting in and out is not the
way to get the black vote,'' said Tyrone Grant. ``They should spend
more than a few hours here, and come more often than every four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   YOU GOTTA HIT THE OPEN MAN
</P>
<P>
   The Harlem neighborhood is sprinkled with big corporate chains,
many of them new arrivals in a boom economy: Duane Reade.
Starbucks. McDonald's. Blimpie's. But Bill Bradley's foray into the
crowd opposite the Apollo Theater on 125th Street lost him at least
one vote: He missed a computer software store under construction
alongside the Apollo. ``At first, I was for Bradley. But just now
he passed us, didn't even look our way,'' said store worker Philip
Reed. Meanwhile, Gore walked into the store ``and he shook hands
with all of us. I'll probably vote for him. I like being
acknowledged.''
</P>
<P>
   RACE ISSUE OF A DIFFERENT KIND
</P>
<P>
   On a routine flight with John McCain between campaign stops in
Michigan, the staff passed out a form to the media types asking
such things as name, birth date, Social Security number, etc. But
the form also asked ``race,'' with most members filling in
``white'' or ``Caucasian.'' When a few reporters questioned the
appropriateness of that, according to the Washington Times,
campaign staff sheepishly explained that they meant only to ask in
which state the reporter was covering the Republican primary race.
</P>
<P>
   A LORAL MISSILE OF HIS OWN
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's campaign accused Rudy Giuliani of having
``cornered the market on hypocrisy'' after records showed his
Senate campaign took money from a source he criticized Clinton for
tapping. A PAC linked to Loral Space and Communications Ltd.
donated $750 in September to Giuliani. After a reporter questioned
the donation, Giuliani spokeswoman Kim Serafin said the money would
be returned. Loral is under Justice Department investigation for
allegedly providing China with information that could help make its
nuclear missiles more reliable.
</P>
<P>
   TRYING NOT TO LET THE WOMEN GET AWAY
</P>
<P>
   It is not the problem that she or anyone else expected. A year
ago, Hillary Clinton's most enthusiastic supporters were women who
sympathized with her marital plight. Democratic, independent and
even Republican women also shared her concerns about education,
health care and children. Today, her support among these women,
even some of the Democrats, has dropped, forcing her Senate
campaign to make a priority of bringing them back. Her advisers
insist that she will.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
