<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4914 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GRAMMY-ATLANTA-COX     02-22 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMY-ATLANTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Local music gurus weigh in on who's Grammy worthy
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's music's biggest night tonight as the recording
industry hands out the 42nd annual Grammy Awards, recognizing the
best music in the past year. The three-hour show, broadcast live
from Los Angeles, is shaping up to be a lively cross-mix of sounds
and stars.
</P>
<P>
   Sixties guitar legend Carlos Santana leads the nominations with
10, followed by Atlanta-based TLC with seven. But it's likely to be
some of the live performances that scorch the tube, from the
outrageous Kid Rock to the smooth Afro-Cuban jazz of Buena Vista
Social Club to the Backstreet Boys performing with Elton John.
</P>
<P>
   Only professionals were allowed to cast votes. But we asked a
cross section of metro Atlanta music experts, none of them actual
Grammy voters, to pick their winners:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rob Perkins, owner of Spin Street music store: ``I have a
special place in my heart for Santana, because I grew up with him,
and his latest album is just remarkable. As far as new artists, I
hope to see Macy Gray win this year. She has a smooth blues sound
in her music that's appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Steve Goss, program director at WPCH-FM : ``By far the best
rock album was `Dosage' by Collective Soul. The Sarah McLachlan is
pretty good, and the Backstreet Boys album is better than a lot of
people think.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Camille Love, director of the city of Atlanta's Bureau of
Cultural Affairs: ``My favorite album last year and right now is
the Isley Brothers' compilation, `It's Your Thing: The Story of the
Isley Brothers.' I grew up on their sweet sounds and the loving
messages, and to me it was black men speaking to black women and I
just loved it!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Leslie Fram, program director of new rock station 99X: ``I
think R.E.M. should get an award for `The Great Beyond' from the
`Man on the Moon' soundtrack. It's the first R.E.M. song in a very
long time that has evoked so much emotion from an audience. I think
the song was overlooked, and it deserves recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Michael Krohngold, co-owner of Deux Plex, Mumbo Jumbo, Tongue
and Groove, and Fusebox: ``Beck's `Midnite Vultures,' because of
the diversity in the music. He's kind of a chameleon of sorts and
on some of the songs he sounds a little bit like Prince.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frank Ski, morning announcer on WVEE-FM (103.3): ``Santana's
album. First of all because he did it and I'm such a fan. But also
I just thought it was a great thing to come back with that album,
and with artists like Lauryn Hill and Wyclef Jean.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Speech, of Arrested Development: ``I want to see people like
Santana, TLC and Will Smith win. (Will is) a musical legend of his
own, but what's kind of wack is that America is just now giving him
his props when he's been making great music for decades.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jason Orr, creator of FunkJazz Kafe: ``Outside of reissues, I
wasn't too impressed with 1999. But if I had to pick, Meshell
(Ndegeocello's) `Bitter,' without a doubt. ... It was just an
emotional record.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rhubarb Jones, Y-106.7 morning man: ``I think Martina McBride
put out the best album of the year, in any category. It's an album
that shows the real, honest, beautiful clarity this woman has. When
she hits those notes, she's singing from her heart and not her
larynx.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Russ DeVault, Shane Harrison, Ryon Horne and Sonia
Murray contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Various Atlanta performers have been nominated for Grammy
Awards this year: www.ajc.com/links
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chat with the winners backstage at the Grammys:
www.accessatlanta.
</P>
<P>
   com/shared/community/chat/
</P>
<P>
   musicchats.htmlgrammys
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
