<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4915 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TREE-PLANTING24-COX     02-22 1893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREE-PLANTING24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't be left there when selecting, planting and maintaining
trees
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Feb. 24.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine how it would feel to have a set of weights fall on your
chest. Or a towel crammed down your throat. Or how about a garden
tiller roll over your feet?
</P>
<P>
   It may seem like scenes from a bad horror flick, but trees
experience those sensations every day, all at the hands of humans
either ignorant or insensitive to their needs. Roots are the most
important part of a tree, because if something prevents them from
providing oxygen, water and food to the tree, it will suffer and
eventually die.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing so many trees because they are so easy to
harm,'' said Melissa Merlino, newly named ``treekeeper'' in
Atlanta's Ansley Park neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburbs, they're falling victim to developers'
bulldozers; in the city, old age, cramped conditions and wear and
tear are the culprits.
</P>
<P>
   Now is the perfect time to replace trees, which seem to make the
news every day, especially in Atlanta, a city known as much for its
canopy as its sprawl. In the suburbs, local governments are beefing
up ordinances to protect trees from development. In the city, power
companies are struggling to explain the dilemma of burying utility
lines _ and uprooting older trees _ in the aftermath of storms that
blew limbs onto wires, leaving residents in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   An equally big problem, tree experts say, is that homeowners
don't understand a tree's needs and buy the wrong kind. Or they
plant it incorrectly. Or they plant it in the wrong place or at the
wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two big areas where homeowners miss the boat:
inappropriate tree selection and maintaining, preserving and
protecting our existing tree canopy,'' said Merlino.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburbs, new homeowners rush out to buy mature,
fast-growing varieties for the instant gratification of providing
beauty or shade to barren lots. But in less than 20 years, many of
those trees will deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   In town, the opposite is occurring. Trees planted 50 to 100
years ago have outgrown their space, their roots spilling onto
streets and sidewalks. In popular neighborhoods, they're suffering
from vehicles and construction equipment that come with traffic
congestion and home renovations.
</P>
<P>
   If you own a home _ regardless of where _ here's how you can
help:
</P>
<P>
   KNOW WHY YOU'RE PLANTING
</P>
<P>
   First, understand how a tree grows. Its most important roots are
within the top 6 to 8 inches of the ground, extending outward from
the trunk to about the width of its canopy. The tree gets its
nutrients from those roots, so if something damages or obstructs
them _ vehicles, cement, mounded soil _ it can spell disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Before hitting the nursery, know the reason you're planting.
Trees serve many purposes _ providing shade, focal points, screens
_ so learn which varieties will accomplish your goals. If seasonal
interest is important, choose accordingly instead of opting for all
evergreens.
</P>
<P>
   Trees require different temperatures, soil types and amounts of
sunlight, depending on their variety. Ask your nursery if your
choice will grow in this area. If the nursery doesn't carry it, ask
that it be ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more diversity in our trees, and the only way that's
going to happen is if customers demand it of their nurseries,''
said Jane Bath of Land Arts, a Monroe nursery.
</P>
<P>
   CHOOSE A TREE FOR THE SITE
</P>
<P>
   When choosing a tree, consider its ultimate height and shape in
relation to nearby structures or utility lines.
</P>
<P>
   For height, power companies classify trees as small, medium and
large.
</P>
<P>
   Small trees generally grow to less than 25 feet and are best
planted 15 to 20 feet from a house, in narrow planting strips (less
than 4 feet) between sidewalks and streets, and on power company
rights of way.
</P>
<P>
   Medium trees typically are 25 to 50 feet when mature. They are
best planted 20 to 25 feet from the house, in medium strips (4 to 8
feet wide) and at least 30 feet from power lines.
</P>
<P>
   Large trees generally grow to more than 50 feet and are best
planted 30 to 35 feet from a house, in strips wider than 8 feet and
at least 40 feet from power lines.
</P>
<P>
   Choose a shape _ columnar, conical, spreading or weeping _
appropriate for your space and purpose. In the tight quarters of an
intown garden, columnar varieties may be more suitable, while on
large suburban lawns, spreading canopies have plenty of room to
grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one looks up to see what's overhead anymore,'' Bath said,
noting the mistakes consumers make.
</P>
<P>
   One reason homeowners in new subdivisions plant so many common
varieties, such as Bradford pears, red maples and willow oaks, is
they want fast-growing trees. So most nurseries cater to the demand
by offering only the mainstays that can be grown on site, Bath
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell maybe 300 crapes myrtles to every oak,'' she said.
``That's pathetic, a tragedy, that people are ignoring the need for
diversity. We have to encourage them to experiment'' _ and to plant
young trees.
</P>
<P>
   She cited the allure of stately old trees that shade magnificent
estates. ``What people don't realize is that those trees were
planted small, not dropped in there by a bird. The point is we need
to think more about the future and less about the present.''
</P>
<P>
   PROTECT MATURE TREES
</P>
<P>
   For neighborhoods with mature trees, the ``present'' means
battling two enemies: tight spaces and home improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Oaks, hickories and other hardwoods, planted after the turn of
the century to create the shaded streets sought by home buyers,
have come of age. Their knees _ those shallow roots _ are buckling
sidewalks and hugging curbs because they've outgrown the narrow
planting strip between the sidewalk and street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have a wide root area so with being shallow,
there's not a lot of room to go,'' Merlino said.
</P>
<P>
   Paving over or piling dirt on roots stifles their oxygen supply.
Combine that with the weight of vehicles and a location typically
dry from the heat of pavement, and the trees have a struggle at
best.
</P>
<P>
   In neighborhoods buzzing with remodeling, construction is
another problem. Trucks, building materials and portable toilets
compact the soil, further harming roots, said Merlino, who has a
degree in horticulture and is charged with teaching homeowners how
to select and protect trees.
</P>
<P>
   It could prove a big job. Neighbors recently halted a homeowner
from cutting down a century-old red oak to make way for a home
renovation because the owner had not secured a city tree permit.
(In Atlanta, trees larger than 6 inches in diameter require
approval for cutting.) And during last month's ice storm, another
80-year-old oak, planted in the sidewalk strip, heaved, knocking
out power to much of the Ansley Park neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to discourage any kind of tree planting, but if
people can plant the trees in their front yards so that they shade
the sidewalk, instead of the strip by the street, it's such a
better option,'' Merlino said.
</P>
<P>
   Trees Atlanta, a nonprofit organization that donates some 1,300
young trees annually to residential neighborhoods and commercial
thoroughfares, will plant in sidewalk strips and medians. But the
area has to be at least 2 feet wide and planted with only small
appropriate varieties, such as redbud, Trident maples, Florida
maples, serviceberry and yaupon hollies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be the ideal situation, but a treeless street is
even less ideal,'' said Greg Levine of Trees Atlanta. ``Those trees
will bring benefit for about 80 years, though environmental
stresses will kill the majority of them before they fall on their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S SO GREAT ABOUT TREES?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  They provide shelter and shade.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Add form, height and structure to gardens.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Encourage wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Create focal points and screen out bad views.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Require little attention once established.
</P>
<P>
   Source: American Horticutural Society
</P>
<P>
   THE RIGHT WAY TO PLANT IN SIX EASY STEPS
</P>
<P>
   Trees Atlanta isn't just a nonprofit organization that donates
and plants trees along neighborhood streets and at commercial
intersections. Part of its mission is educating people about the
importance of trees, said Marcia Bansley, its executive director.
</P>
<P>
   One important lesson is the proper way to plant, and the group
begins each of its Saturday plantings with one for its volunteers
and neighborhood residents.
</P>
<P>
   In this climate, the best time to plant trees is between
November and March, cold months when the trees aren't faced with
the stresses of heat, insects and disease. ``Spring is the worst
time to plant because trees are real active then in sending out
sugar,'' said Greg Levine, program coordinator for Trees Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The group's step-by-step recommendations are sure to get your
trees off to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   _ Danny C. Flanders
</P>
<P>
   STEP ONE: Using a spade, dig a hole at least twice the size of
the tree's rootball. Slant the sides of the hole inward and make
sure the bottom is flat. The hole should be deep enough so that
when the rootball is placed in it, the top of the ball is about
1/4-inch above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   STEP TWO: To measure the depth of the rootball, hold the
shovel's handle against it, then place the handle upright in the
hole to determine if the hole is deep enough.
</P>
<P>
   STEP THREE: Place tree in the hole, lifting the tree by its
rootball, as are Greg Levine (right) and volunteer Brian Harris.
</P>
<P>
   STEP FOUR: Remove any grass from the remaining soil, then fill
in the hole. (Though some experts recommend adding soil amendments,
Trees Atlanta says trees need to adapt to existing conditions
instead of being ``teased'' by amendments.) Break up any clumps of
soil, being careful to avoid damaging the rootball.
</P>
<P>
   STEP FIVE: Build a ``dirt doughnut'' around the tree, about the
diameter of its top, to prevent runoff. (Once the tree is
established, remove that barrier for proper drainage.)
</P>
<P>
   STEP SIX: Add several inches of mulch, such as pine bark or
straw, to help the soil retain moisture. But keep the mulch at
least 3 inches away from the trunk because mulch can spread
insects, fungus and disease. Depending on conditions, give new
trees at least 10 gallons of water every few days until
established.
</P>
<P>
   4 SEASONS OF BRIGHT IDEAS
</P>
<P>
   Here are some recommendations for trees that yield seasonal
interest in Georgia:
</P>
<P>
   FALL COLOR
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red maple: Acer rubrum `October Glory'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Japanese maple: Acer palmatum
</P>
<P>
   `Bloodgood'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gingko: Gingko biloba `Autumn Gold'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Scarlet oak: Quercus coccinea `Splendens'
</P>
<P>
   WINTER INTEREST
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Serviceberry: Amelanchier arborea
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  River birch:
</P>
<P>
   Betula nigra
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Star magnolia: Magnolia stellata
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Magnolia: Magnolia grandiflora `Little Gem'
</P>
<P>
   SPRING COLOR
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Crab apple: Malus niedzwetskyana
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pink dogwood: Cornus florida `Cherokee Chief'
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Japanese white dogwood: Cornus kousa
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cherry: Prunus `Okame'
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER SHADE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Styrax: Styrax japonicus
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Star magnolia: Magnolia -- soulangeana
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Golden-rain tree: Koelreuteria paniculata
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lacebark elm: Ulmus parvifolia
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
