the number of preschoolers taking stimulants, antidepressants and
other psychiatric drugs rose ``dramatically'' between 1991 and
1995. Prescriptions for stimulants _ most commonly methylphenidate,
the generic form of Ritalin _ increased two to three-fold among
children, ages 2 to 5, enrolled in two state Medicaid programs and
one northwestern HMO, the researchers found. Prescriptions for
antidepressants doubled in the Medicaid programs. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Amadou Diallo gave four police
