<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4921 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-INTERNET-PLAYERS-$ADV     02-22 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PLAYERS-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEADERS IN THE INTERNET TAX DEBATE
 &HT;    With INTERNET-TAXES. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The battle over Internet taxation is being fought
by political leaders at both the state and federal levels. These
are some of the dominant voices in the debate:
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEADERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Gov. James Gilmore, R-Va., chairman of the congressionally
appointed Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce. Unlike most
governors, he believes Congress should protect online retailers
from new taxes. He points to his state's healthy coffers to show
that online companies, such as home-grown America Online Inc., can
create enough prosperity to compensate for any lost sales tax
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gov. Michael Leavitt, R-Utah, chairman of the National
Governors' Association and a member of the Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce. He believes that unless online sales are
taxed, many states soon could face a revenue crisis. He has been
quietly pursuing a compromise that would extend the current tax
moratorium until 2003, giving states a chance to develop new
software and computer networks to help businesses collect taxes on
remote sales.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE LEADERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Goodlatte, R-VA., co-sponsor of the Internet
Non-Discrimination Act, a bill introduced in February to block new
Internet taxes. As chairman of the Congressional Internet Caucus,
he is widely recognized as a champion of high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Christopher Cox, R-Calif., a longtime advocate of curbing
federal regulation of the Internet. He says that California's sales
tax revenues have skyrocketed because of the prosperity generated
by the growth of mostly tax-free online commerce. He wants to
convert the current moratorium on new Internet taxes into a
permanent ban.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE LEADERS
</P>
<P>
   _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., sponsor of the Internet Tax Freedom
Act of 1998, which put a three-year moratorium on new Internet
taxes. As a presidential candidate, he continues to push for a
permanent ban all Internet-related taxes, even on in-state
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., sponsor of the Internet
Non-Discrimination Act. He has long been a leader in the effort to
ban taxes on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1826EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4922 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-INTERNET-Q&AMP;A-$ADV27-C     02-22 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-Q&AMP;A-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS ABOUT INTERNET TAXES
 &HT;    With INTERNET-TAXES. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. In terms of taxes, do online companies follow the same rules
as other retailers?
</P>
<P>
   A. Rather than collect sales taxes as traditional local
retailers are obligated to do when customers make purchases, online
merchants follow the laws that govern catalog companies and other
direct marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the sales tax rules for direct marketers?
</P>
<P>
   A. Ordinarily, mail-order and online companies in one state do
not collect taxes on merchandise shipped to another state. But if a
merchant has a physical presence in your state, then it will
collect sales tax. If you buy an item from the Sears' Web site, you
mostly likely would have to pay tax on the sale, because Sears has
stores all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does that mean customers have no tax obligations when they
buy online from an out-of-state company?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. Internet and catalog customers are supposed to pay state
sales taxes, even if the taxes aren't collected at the point of
sale. In most states, you are supposed to fulfill your obligation
by calling your state tax authority and requesting a tax form. In
reality, virtually no one does this, and few states even try to
collect the sales taxes they should be getting.
</P>
<P>
   Q. It seems a little crazy to think people would voluntarily
mail in sales taxes. Why are the rules like that?
</P>
<P>
   A. The tax obligations of direct marketers and their customers
were spelled out by the U.S. Supreme Court in a 1992 case called
Quill Corp. v. North Dakota. The court held that imposing a tax
collection obligation on an out-of-state vendor with no physical
presence in North Dakota was unconstitutional because the high cost
of complying with the myriad rules and rates of different states
put an undue burden on interstate commerce. Back in 1992,
electronic commerce was virtually unknown, and mail-order sales
were only a small part of the retail world, so not many people took
much notice of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Q. If catalog companies have been getting along under the Quill
ruling for years, and most states are reaping record sales tax
revenues, why bother changing anything?
</P>
<P>
   A. States didn't worry much about catalog companies because
those transactions didn't put a significant dent in state budgets.
But with the Internet growing so quickly, no one can safely predict
the impact on state revenues. For example, this past holiday
season, online sales surpassed $7 billion, more than doubling the
previous year's results. If that growth rate were to continue,
sales tax revenues could plummet. A recent study by economists at
the Univeristy of Tennessee predicted that electronic commerce
would cost states about $10.8 billion in lost revenues by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   It's also possible that traditional retailers could use the
Internet to escape sales taxes. For example, they could let a
customer view merchandise in the store, then go to a computer
kiosks to purchase it online _ tax-free _ from a separate, but
affiliated, company in a different state.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Given that states are facing the prospect of dramatic
declines in revenues, what are they doing?
</P>
<P>
   A. So far, most state and local leaders are just fretting. But
in a few places, lawmakers are debating solutions. In Texas, Lt.
Gov. Rick Perry has created the Advisory Council on the Digital
Economy, a group of business leaders and state senators that will
recommend tax changes to the Legislature by January. Some
legislators in Virginia say the state should eliminate the state's
4.5 percent sales tax to help attract Internet retailers who
otherwise might be reluctant to lose taxable sales from its 7
million residents.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is Congress saying about the issue?
</P>
<P>
   A. In 1998, Congress passed a moratorium on new state or local
taxes on Internet sales through October 2001. But the political
pressure from governors and mayors is growing. Given what a hot
topic this is becoming, Congress soon may consider Internet tax
bills being floated by a number of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is Congress getting any input from business leaders?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. The 1998 law also created the federal Advisory
Commission on Electronic Commerce. The 19-member committee, with
representatives drawn from industry and government, will have its
final meeting March 20 and 21 in Dallas. The group is supposed to
make recommendations to Congress by April 21.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What action might Congress take?
</P>
<P>
   A. One possibility is a national sales tax on remote sales. In
this scenario, the Internal Revenue Service would receive tax
revenues collected by online retailers, and then Congress would
appropriate the money back to the state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one idea; there are lots of others. For example, the
six companies whose representatives make up the ``business caucus''
of the federal advisory committee recently suggested that Congress
exempt books, music, records and other information and
entertainment products from all sales taxes, both in stores and on
the Internet. In exchange for this exemption and a new tax break
for telecommunications companies, state governments would gain the
authority to collect other sales taxes from direct marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Q. But that possible solution still would have online retailers
collecting sales taxes. Isn't that supposed to be too complicated
for them?
</P>
<P>
   A. Some experts believe that a combination of streamlined tax
rates and better software could solve revenue collection problems.
They say new software could match each ZIP code with its sales tax
rate and rules, making it easier for businesses to collect the
right taxes from each customer. Other experts suggest creating new
firms, licensed by the states and dedicated to administering tax
software and handling the revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
