<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-ELIAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES DECIDE TO STAY OUT OF DISPUTE OVER CUBAN BOY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday opted to stay out of
the international dispute over whether 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez
must be returned from Miami to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, without comment, rejected the unusual appeal of an
Arizona man who had urged them to order that Elian be sent home.
Robert Hirschfeld, a disbarred Phoenix lawyer, bypassed lower
federal courts in directly urging the justices to ``cut short'' the
political dispute that has swirled around Elian ever since he was
plucked from the Atlantic Ocean after a desperate voyage from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The legal dispute over Elian began Nov. 25, when fishermen found
the boy clinging to an inner tube off the Florida coast. His mother
and 10 other people had drowned during the voyage from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service has ordered Elian to
be returned to his father, Juan Gonzalez, who was divorced from the
boy's mother. But Elian's great uncle and other relatives in Miami,
with whom the boy has been living, are seeking a court order to
have him stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Michael Moore in Miami said he will hold a
hearing on the family's lawsuit the week of March 6. Moore was
assigned to the case by random computer selection Tuesday after the
original judge, William Hoeveler, suffered a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld, the self-proclaimed founder of the National Congress
for Fathers and Children, argued to the justices in vain that their
early intervention was needed to preserve the father-child bond.
</P>
<P>
   In other high court action, the justices agreed to decide
whether the Constitution permits police, in their zeal to catch
drunken drivers and drug traffickers, to stop all motorists and
check for narcotics in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision, expected in July 2001, will have no effect
on Texas. The state Court of Criminal Appeals in 1994 ruled that
police could not establish so-called sobriety checkpoints until the
Texas Legislature passes a law allowing the practice, a move
lawmakers have not made.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's decision to hear the case from Indianapolis
brings into question the legality of roadside checkpoints, a common
law-enforcement tactic against drunken driving and the drug trade.
As part of the practice, officers stop motorists and conduct quick
visual examinations of whether the driver is impaired or is
carrying illegal narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis, whose police have conducted the checkpoints since
August 1998, told the justices that the checks only briefly delay
law-abiding motorists and are necessary to keep roads safe and
discourage drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The city is pressing the justices to overturn a 7th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals decision that the checkpoints are
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the high court refused without comment to hear a
condemned Alabama man's challenge to the constitutionality of the
state's exclusive use of the electric chair for executions.
</P>
<P>
   The court's conservative and liberal wings were divided over the
decision of whether to hear murderer Robert Lee Tarver Jr.'s
argument that the electric chair is cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Anthony M.
Kennedy, Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas
refused to hear the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Stephen G. Breyer, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, David H. Souter
and John Paul Stevens and voted to consider the case. But under
Supreme Court rules, a majority of five justices must agree to
accept a death-row appeal before the case will be heard.
</P>
<P>
   In his unsuccessful appeal to the justices, Tarver's attorney,
Bryan Stevenson, called the electric chair ``antiquated'' and said
it can cause ``excessive burning, disfigurement and ... pain and
suffering'' before death. Alabama countered that the electric chair
administers an almost painless and instantaneous death.
</P>
<P>
   The court's refusal to hear the case sets no binding legal
precedent as to the constitutionality of executions in Alabama,
Georgia and Nebraska, the states that use the electric chair as the
exclusive means of capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Texas relies solely on lethal injection for executions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The court's refusal, however, allows Alabama officials to set a
new execution date for Tarver, who had been scheduled to be put to
death earlier this month until the Supreme Court granted a stay
pending its consideration of his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
