<HEADER>
A4929 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-INTERNET-POLITICS-$AD     02-22 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLITICS-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET TAXES: WHERE DO THE WHITE HOUSE RIVALS STAND?
 &HT;    With INTERNET-TAXES. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Congress tries to make up its mind what to do
about taxing Internet sales, little guidance is coming from this
year's presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   While the candidates _ especially the Republicans _ do have
different approaches, the debate is muted because all of them
oppose any early action to alter current law.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona takes the most forthright approach
toward the application of sales and use taxes to sales across state
borders: He's against them.
</P>
<P>
   As the New Hampshire primary approached, the McCain camp posted
a ``Just Say No to Internet Taxes'' banner ad on the Slate Web
site. The idea was to embarrass Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who
had called for a three- to five-year moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was the chief sponsor of the current three-year
moratorium on Internet taxation, which expires in October 2001. In
the Senate, he has fought for a permanent ban.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, McCain signed an ``E-Freedom Declaration,''
saying, ``I support a permanent ban on Internet taxes because the
Internet is the greatest economic engine the world has ever seen.
As president, I will not let the Internet become a tax collection
machine for politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain assailed Bush for failing to take same pledge. By not
doing so, the senator charged, Bush ``is endorsing a tax increase
that could total over $160 billion by 2003.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, as governor of a state that collects more than half its
revenues from sales taxes, cannot easily afford to ignore the
rapidly growing online market. Sheltering those sales from taxes
could pose a serious revenue problem to many Texas communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the current moratorium on Internet sales taxes and
would extend it for several more years to determine the full impact
of e-commerce on our society,'' Bush says.
</P>
<P>
   The no-tax pledge is the handiwork of a lobbying group known as
the E-Freedom Coalition, closely aligned to the Americans for Tax
Reform.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bush nor the two Democratic presidential contenders,
former Sen. Bill Bradley and Vice President Al Gore, have taken the
pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by the Associated Press where he stood on the issue of
Internet taxes, Gore responded: ``I supported the (1998) Internet
Tax Freedom Act, which President Clinton signed into law.'' Bradley
noted that he also backs that three-year moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic candidates cited the ongoing work of a
congressional advisory panel known as the Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he backs the panel's ``efforts to develop a tax
policy which encourages the astonishing growth of the Internet and
electronic commerce, but is fair to bricks-and-mortar companies and
doesn't erode the state and local revenue stream.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Gore said while he did not want to prejudge the
panel's conclusions, ``I will tell you that I am committed to
finding a solution to this issue that will allow the Internet and
e-commerce to flourish, but without stripping states and localities
of the revenue they need to educate our children and fight crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
