A4934 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-INTERNET-TIMELINE-$AD     02-22 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TIMELINE-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With INTERNET-TAXES. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Important events in the development of the current sales tax
system:
</P>
<P>
   1932 _ Mississippi becomes the first state to adopt a modern
retail sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   1935 _ California and Washington enact statutes imposing a
``use'' tax on goods that are purchased outside the state but
brought into the state for use there.
</P>
<P>
   1937 _ The U.S. Supreme Court upholds the Washington use tax in
Henneford v. Silas Mason Co.
</P>
<P>
   1967 _ The U.S. Supreme Court, in National Bellas Hess Inc. v.
Illinois, rules that for a state to require a mail-order company to
collect sales and use taxes on its behalf, the company must have a
substantial physical presence in that state.
</P>
<P>
   1992 _ The Supreme Court, in Quill Corp. v. North Dakota, rules
that a company whose only contacts with a state are directed
through the mail or a common carrier would not have sufficient
contact in the state to be subject to sales and use tax collection.
</P>
<P>
   1993 _ The staff at the National Center for Supercomputing at
the University of Illinois in Urbana-Champaign develops the Mosaic
browser, which allows people to easily view the graphical portion
of the Internet. Mosaic later becomes the Netscape browser.
</P>
<P>
   1995 _ Amazon.com begins selling books over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   1998 _ Congress passes the Internet Tax Freedom Act, which
imposes a three-year moratorium on new Internet taxation.
</P>
<P>
   1999 _ The Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce, appointed
by Congress to study Internet taxation and issue recommendations,
holds its first meeting in Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   2000 _ The advisory commission will hold its final meeting March
20-21 in Dallas and must give its report to Congress no later than
April 21.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Deloitte &AMP; Touche E-Business Tax Services Group
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
