<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCSORLEY'S SHAMELESS ACT OF ASSAULT UP FOR REVIEW BY NHL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever it was that got into Marty McSorley's head, and
ultimately into his arms and stick, he will have a chance to
explain Wednesday when he sits before National Hockey League
disciplinarian Colin Campbell at league headquarters in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley can talk. He can justify. He can apologize. He can
invoke the devil-made-me-do-it defense. Maybe he'll say he was
still feeling the drain of jet leg, the long haul from Boston to
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever he says, or how he says it, it just won't be good
enough. There is nothing he can say. The days when violence was an
accepted part of hockey, thankfully, are long gone. If only it
could be eradicated, too.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley lifted his stick, clearly intent on hurting Donald
Brashear, and if not for his helmet, the Canucks' 28-year-old
forward could have been paralyzed or killed. The replay, shown
thousands of times across North America Tuesday, showed Brashear's
head bouncing off the ice Monday night like a hard rubber ball, the
end result of McSorley chopping at his temple and knocking him
backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in shock,'' McSorley said immediately following the
incident, sounding as if some demon had leased his soul. ``I have
to come to terms with what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   In short order, Campbell will do that for him. Based on the Dale
Hunter decision of '93, McSorley will have to be hit with no less
than a 21-game suspension. Hunter, a Washington thug, ambushed
Pierre Turgeon from behind, some three seconds after Turgeon, arms
up and rejoicing, scored a playoff goal for the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   NHL commissioner Gary Bettman handled the Hunter-Turgeon case
personally, and in truth, he let Hunter off lightly. It was nothing
less than a street mugging and Hunter, no stranger to the dark side
of the game, should have been turfed for at least half a season.
Personally, I would have benched Hunter for a year and then allowed
him to apply for reinstatement, subject to the review of a panel
that included league and union employees, and a group of his
playing peers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, what of McSorley? Frankly, I think the Hunter mugging was
worse. No one knows what either individual truly was thinking, but
Hunter's hit _ a crash from behind _ looked more aggravated.
Nonetheless, McSorley's two-hander falls into the same family of
heinous misbehavior, because he was clearly headhunting and he
clearly connected. Brashear was down, bleeding and twitching. The
end result looked far worse than the crumpled deck of cards that
was Turgeon the day he was crushed by Hunter (who, by the way, in
his Quebec days, delivered a pitchfork-like spear directly to Terry
O'Reilly's groin).
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (thankfully) have but 23 games remaining in what has
turned out to be a season worse than even their dead-last campaign
of 1996-97. If the league does the right thing _ and I am certain
it will _ McSorley's suspension will encompass at least the rest of
the regular season and all of the playoffs (increasingly a moot
point here in the Hub).
</P>
<P>
   Boston fans have seen worse over the decades. McSorley's chop
doesn't come close to the paralyzing crackdown Oakland's Jack Tatum
delivered to the Patriots' Darryl Stingley in a 1978 exhibition
game. Who could forget the look in Ted Green's eyes, caught by
camera, as Wayne Maki sliced into his skull with a two-hander in a
1969 Bruins-Blues exhibition game? Compared with those incidents,
McSorley's swing looks like a love tap.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when McSorley's conduct was du rigueur on the
rink. Vivid in my mind is an afternoon game in the '60s, televised
by CBS, when Boston's Wayne Cashman (we give you loose cannon,
Exhibit A) barreled into a mid-ice scrum, and came ripping down
with a wild-swinging two-hander aimed at some faceless Flyer.
Cashman missed the guy's skull by a couple of inches and cracked
him across the collarbone. It was frightening. Two inches from a
certain homicide. Remember, those were the days before the helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday night, the worst thing McSorley ever did with a
stick was carry an illegal blade into the 1993 Stanely Cup finals.
Keen-eyed Montreal coach Jacques Demers called for a measurement
that night at the old Forum, and the minor penalty against McSorley
cost the Kings the game _ and, in the view of many, the Stanley
Cup. It was McSorley's 15 seconds of Buckneresque infamy.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cashman days, McSorley's misdeed probably wouldn't have
drawn more than a five-minute major. In fact, if Brashear had been
the only guy with a helmet, the referee might have been willing to
let the final three seconds burn off the clock and sweep the whole
thing under the Zamboni. Quotes the next day would have referenced
the perils of playing in a man's game with, of all things, head
protection.
</P>
<P>
   But here in February 2000 we all expect better. That especially
includes the players, even the game's tough guys like McSorley and
Brashear, who have to be assured they can play an inherently
dangerous game without the threat of someone turning it into an
open audition for ``NYPD Blue'' shooting at Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds as if McSorley is ashamed of what he did. At least he
has that much right. It is the second ridiculous, inexcusable act
by a Bruin this season. The other was Joe Murphy leaving the bench
in St. Louis to corral, mug, and pummel Blues forward Tyson Nash.
This is some disciplined bunch, isn't it? No wonder they're sitting
in Edmonton with 18 wins, dressed in black, veiled in shame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
