<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-ORANGES-ART-3TAKES-NY     02-22 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORANGES-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUEEZING GOLD FROM THE GROVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURNDALE, Fla. _ ``You want to look at oranges?'' Jim Walker
asked. ``Well, let's go look at oranges.'' Walker, lean and fit at
70, jumped into his red minivan. I joined him, and minutes later we
were deep into Walker Groves, a 70-acre spread of citrus trees
midway between Tampa and Orlando that his family has cultivated for
more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   Here in central Florida, the citrus groves form a sea of dark
green foliage stretching to the horizon. Unfortunately, the horizon
is limited; the land is so flat that there are hardly any places
high enough to see more than a mile or two. The growers and the
bureaucrats who watch over the crop use helicopters to keep an eye
on the groves and, in fact, to count the oranges. Not one by one,
of course, but by using educated guesses about how much fruit a
tree will produce. The crop for the growing season from fall 1997
through late spring 1998, the most recent count available, came to
about 48 billion oranges, according to the Florida Citrus
Department.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, we bumped along past rows of 12-to-15-foot-high
trees thick with glossy, dark green leaves but bereft of fruit.
``Early varieties,'' Walker said, ``all picked.'' Abruptly, we came
upon row after row of trees laden with fat orange fruit.
``Valencias,'' my host remarked, ``not quite ready yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I had recognized them. In fact, it was their imminent
arrival in my local supermarket that lured me down here last week
in the first place. I am, I must confess, an orange-juice addict.
Only two or three fresh-squeezed oranges a day will do it for me,
and Valencias are my orange of choice. I await their annual debut
the way some people yearn for the start of spring training. In
fact, the ballplayers and the Valencias turn up around here every
year at about this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best juice oranges in the world,'' Walker agreed.
</P>
<P>
   You might not know it by looking at them. These happen to be
pretty good looking oranges, but not all Valencias are. Valencias
are thin skinned, making them susceptible to nicks and bruises.
When they are ripe, they may be a brilliant orange or tinged with
yellow or even green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Color has nothing to do with ripeness,'' Walker said. ``A
green orange can be fully ripe and an orange one far from ready to
be picked. What makes an orange orange is cold weather. When it
gets a little warmer around here in a few weeks, these Valencias
could turn green again. But they'll be ripe.''
</P>
<P>
   But they are heavy with juice. They have been bred that way,
although the Florida weather helps. California oranges, navels
mostly, develop thick skins because they are grown in a dry
climate. They are light in weight and drier in texture. Florida
oranges are juicier because Florida is wetter. The water table is
high, and the rainfall is one of the heaviest in the United States.
In Florida, water is everywhere, even in the oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it's the navel that is considered the eating orange, by
growers and consumers alike, because it peels so easily and looks
so much more attractive in the produce bin. It's too bad; a
Valencia sliced into wedges or circles is a fine thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Valencia was once known as the Rivers Late, after the
Englishman who first shipped the seeds here in the 19th century. It
came to be known as the Valencia when, it is said, a Spanish grower
saw some Rivers Late trees in this country and claimed them to be
his country's Valencias. (The navel orange has a less romantic
history: it is known formally as the Washington Navel, not for the
state but for Washington, D.C., where it was propagated by the
Agriculture Department after arriving from Brazil in the 1870s.)
</P>
<P>
   Today, Valencias are the world's most popular orange, and they
grow in every part of the world where oranges thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Orange trees have a lot in common with grapevines. With wine
grapes, the noble European vinifera vines _ cabernet sauvignon,
chardonnay and others _ are grafted onto disease-resistant American
roots that, left on their own, would produce relatively useless
grapes. Similarly, fruit-bearing citrus branches are grafted onto
rootstock derived from, among others, the Rough Lemon tree. On its
own, the Rough Lemon will produce unusable fruit. Paired with good
plant material, it produces high-quality fruit: oranges, lemons,
grapefruit or limes.
</P>
<P>
   A grafted orange tree comes into maturity in five years; a tree
grown from seeds takes at least 15 years. Seedling trees are rare
in Florida these days. Growing lemon tree rootstock is itself a
major business. Much of Florida's citrus is grown in sand, which
contributes little or nothing to the tree's well-being. Most of its
nutrition, aside from what it gets from sun and water, comes from
hefty doses of manufactured nutritives.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy tree can be economically viable for 50 years, a Citrus
Department spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida a century ago, the groves began much farther north,
not all that far from the Georgia border. Frequent devastating
frosts prompted the industry to move farther and farther south.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are fewer frost problems,'' the spokesman told me. ``But
lots of the groves are in hurricane territory now, and a hurricane
can be just as deadly as a bad frost.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in an ideal season, there is a long period, from late
summer through winter, when there are no Valencias to be found.
Since oranges, including Valencias, are grown all over the world,
they are always in season somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In northern European cities, it's not uncommon to find oranges
from all over the world in the markets. Why don't we see oranges
from Morocco or Uruguay or South Africa or Brazil in this country?
Spanish clementines do show up, but other foreign oranges are
scarce because they compete with the domestic product. French
supermarkets may put on a dazzling display of imported oranges, but
there are no domestic growers to complain.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, tariffs protect Florida Valencias;
California navels, which ripen in the early fall; and other
varieties that ripen between those two main seasons. The only times
we are short of oranges in this country is when Florida is hit by a
bad freeze, as happened in 1990, when more than a third of the crop
was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The juice business also has had a profound effect. The
year-round availability of good _ and infinitely cheaper _ frozen
and bottled juice has all but squeezed out the fresh-orange
business. Sales of fresh citrus fruit are almost an afterthought in
the orange-juice business, a $3 billion-a-year industry. Oranges
are counted in 90-pound boxes, the way they are picked in the
groves. In 1997-98, more than 230 million boxes of Florida oranges
went into pasteurized, chilled juice, most of it from reconstituted
frozen concentrate, according to the Citrus Department. Fewer than
9 million boxes were sold as fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh grapefruit fared better. From the same harvest, some 28
million 85-pound boxes went into chilled juice, and 20 million were
shipped as fresh fruit, the department says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, when John McPhee wrote a monumental two-part essay on
oranges for The New Yorker magazine, he was surprised to discover
how difficult it was to get fresh orange juice in Florida.
State-run tourist offices offered every sun-starved visitor a cup
of juice, McPhee reported, but it was all made from concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has changed. Tourists arriving at the portals of the
Sunshine State are still offered free orange juice, and it still
isn't fresh squeezed, even though an orange, presumably a fresh
one, is featured prominently on the state license plate. Some
Florida hotels offer fresh juice, at a price, but rarely does
anyplace else. At both the Florida Citrus Department in Lakeland
and at Tropicana Products' vast headquarters and bottling plant in
Bradenton, cordial receptionists offered me orange juice, but none
of it fresh squeezed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' Walker said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Oranges have been grown in Florida since the 16th century.
Columbus took citrus seeds on his first voyage and spread them
around the Caribbean. Ponce de Leon is supposed to have taken them
from Spain to Florida. ``He came looking for the Fountain of
Youth,'' the juice people like to say, ``but in fact he brought it
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Four hundred years later, some Florida scientists invented
frozen concentrate. By the time McPhee wrote his essay, the
changeover from fresh fruit to frozen concentrate was almost
complete. The 6- and 12-ounce cans whose contents were diluted with
three equal amounts of water were in millions of home freezers.
Minute Maid, a pioneer in the concentrate business, became the
country's largest producer of processed orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, however, consumers began to move away from
frozen concentrate toward chilled juice, both pasteurized
not-from-concentrate and reconstituted concentrate. Chilled-juice
sales passed frozen concentrate in 1986, and the gap has continued
to widen. Chilled juice now accounts for more than 60 percent of
all orange-juice sales, the department says.
</P>
<P>
   Tropicana, which produces chilled juice, both from fresh fruit
and from concentrate, is now first in the industry, with between 37
percent and 38 percent of the market, said Jim Dwyer, Tropicana's
senior vice president for North American operations. Florida is the
nation's largest producer of oranges, and each year Tropicana buys
about 25 percent of the state's orange crop. In the 1998-99 season,
the company produced some 320 million gallons of orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast is the United States' biggest orange-juice market,
consuming some 40 percent of all the orange juice the country
makes. The New York metropolitan area alone consumes about 17
percent of the national output. Just to serve the metropolitan
market, Tropicana dispatches five full trainloads of orange juice
each week to its bottling plant in Jersey City, N.J. Each train
carries more than 5.2 million gallons of juice. Tropicana also has
production plants in France, Britain and China.
</P>
<P>
   The Tropicana plant in Bradenton is a technological marvel.
Twenty-four hours a day, seven days a week, millions of oranges are
squeezed, turned into rivers of juice and bottled, some with no
pulp, some with a bit of pulp and some with a lot of pulp. ``Kids
hate pulp,'' said Steven Lezman, a Tropicana executive, who showed
me around.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he didn't just say it; he shouted it, the only way to
be heard over the ceaseless, ear-splitting roar of the plant
machinery. Like all dedicated Tropicana people, Lezman is immune to
the lure of fresh juice, even though he has his own private orange
tree in his backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep two kinds of Tropicana juice in the refrigerator at
home,'' Lezman said. ``No pulp for the kids and pulp for the
adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Auburndale, where the only noise is an occasional
blackbird and where hawks wheel lazily in the warm, late winter
air, Walker squeezes his juice in a stainless-steel machine about
half the size of a player piano. It's in a back room of the little
shop on Route 599, where he welcomes tourists who are loyal fans,
newcomers lured by his billboards out on the Interstate and a
surprising number of Floridians who refused to take the dearth of
fresh juice in their state lying down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got people coming all the way up from Hollywood,'' he
said, chuckling. ``They want a few gallons of the real stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Walker is no stranger to the more commercial side of the
business. What he doesn't sell at his shop, or ship around the
country in gift packages, he sells to local processors to be turned
into pasteurized juice or concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just so I can keep this way of life going for a while,'' he
said, as we walked among his fruit-laden trees. ``My grandfather
came down here from Tennessee in 1884. He was 30 years old and
suffering from what they used to call consumption. They'd told him
he wasn't going to live long in any case but that he might live a
little longer in Florida. Well, this life must have agreed with
him; he lived to be 87.''
</P>
<P>
   I returned to my car and headed for Tampa, pulling on a quart
bottle of Walker juice and thinking about that old man. Could it
have been the orange juice? It seemed distinctly possible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPES FOLLOW)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
