<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE RICH ARE DIFFERENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; John Loring &LR; , design director of Tiffany &AMP; Co., is in San
Francisco this week with his new book, ``Tiffany Jewels'' (Abrams;
$60).
</P>
<P>
   Are the rich of today different from the tiara-wearing rich of
yesteryear? ``There are a lot of young people all over the world
who have been remarkably successful,'' he said, ``especially in
technology. We have a very large population of very young people
who have the means to have whatever they want. They can be very
lavish, and buy perfectly wonderful gemstones at prices not
available to everyone, but they want to wear these things in their
own way.''
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, says Loring, he gives a ``big lunch party for the
Save Venice charities. I will tell you right now that the very
aristocratic Venetian woman wears denims and a white T-shirt and a
magnificent string of pearls. The clothing will be absolute
minimum, but she'll be wearing a breathtaking string of pearls or
jeweled pin at the waistline.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident that the clothes are simple, the jewelry
expensive. Tiffany sales over the holidays were ``stupendous,''
said Loring, ``absolutely astonishing. ... It was partly due to the
fact that ready-to-wear fashion has become so exorbitantly
expensive that women think, look, for that amount of money I could
buy a beautiful piece of jewelry. We've been helped by the fact
that ready-to-wear fashion has priced itself out of the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. ``In this era of luxe,'' writes Vogue magazine columnist
 &UR; Camilla Nickerson &LR; , ``affordable clothes have sort of been
forgotten.'' And so the latest issue of the magazine launches ``The
Look for Less,'' a column that spotlights ``stylish clothing that
can be found for under $2,001.'' The debut spread includes bargain
trench coats for just under $900.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. A Town &AMP; Country spread on San Francisco Arts Commission
head  &UR; Stanlee Gatti &LR; , who's in the party-creating business, says
that his low price for a wedding nowadays is $50,000, and the price
for the most fancy ``has blasted to an outrageous $7 million.''
</P>
<P>
   DO have a cascading bridal bouquet, advises Gatti; DON'T have
too many glasses and too much silverware on the table. ``There's a
part of me,'' says this renegade, ``that loves to see one glass on
the table, one knife and fork, and silverware served before each
course.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. Socialite  &UR; Nan Kempner  &LR; told the New York Daily News how
she broke her shoulder. During one of her dinner parties, she
tripped on a phone cord, ``lassoed my foot and went forward. I fell
on my shoulder to avoid falling face first.'' That was a considered
decision, she said, because she had just gotten a face-lift.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile,  &UR; Fran Lebowitz &LR;  gave the online magazine Senses her
own opinion of women who try to turn back the clock with surgery.
``What's the goal here?'' she asked, in comments quoted in the New
York Post. ``To get invited to the prom? It's a crazy thing to do
in middle age. If you're in your 40s or 50s and you think your life
will change because of a nose job, you are a moron.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEN THE WIND BLOWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tom Geller &LR; , whose office is on the Embarcadero in San
Francisco, at the foot of Howard Street, poses a science (?)
question.
</P>
<P>
   Geller, who works for GCI Group, and his office mate have a
glass door that opens toward the Bay Bridge. They often leave the
door open to get some fresh air. Somehow, the building's position
allows papers to remain on their desks, undisturbed by gusts of
wind. ``Except,'' writes Geller, ``every day, at precisely 5:06
p.m., a wind whips up for about 30 seconds and scatters the
detritus from our desks.''
</P>
<P>
   The instant wind doesn't seem to be the result of cooling caused
by the sun going down, says Geller. The time never changes, even as
the days grow longer.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone have any idea as to what causes this?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIGNED ON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight year, Yahoo magazine has named San
Francisco the ``most wired'' city in the country, based on numbers
of computer users at home and work, domain density (the numbers of
domain names divided by the numbers of businesses), the numbers of
computers per capita hooked up to the Net, density of Web sites
devoted to the city and quality of content on local sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason this show works has very little to do with the fact
that it's about gangsters. It's about a guy with two families, one
at home and one at work. Guess what, everybothat. The drama
and contrast are heightened by the work, of course, but everyone
can relate.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Steven Van Zandt, the rock 'n' roller who plays a hit man on
``The Sopranos,'' in Rolling Stone.
</P>
</TEXT>
