<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-BRAUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE SEEKS SALE OF BRAUN DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Gillette Co. has hired J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. to explore a
possible sale of a portion of its Braun division.
</P>
<P>
   The review will focus on Braun's household appliance and home
diagnostics business. Braun also makes electric shavers and
power-assisted oral-care products. Those businesses will not be
part of the review.
</P>
<P>
   The move, announced Tuesday, was not unexpected. In the fall,
Boston-based Gillette had said it would consider several options,
including a possible sale, for business lines that were not
performing as well as its razors and battery divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gillette said it had hired Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. to
conduct a similar review of its stationery business.
</P>
<P>
   Challenged by economic troubles in some of its key overseas
markets, Gillette has been under pressure from Wall Street
investors to sell some of its noncore product lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the decision is made to divest the businesses, we will not
sell at fire-sale prices,'' said Gillette spokesman Eric A. Kraus.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette bought Braun in 1967 for $68 million.
</P>
<P>
   With razors and blades, Gillette has perfected a winning
strategy. It uses innovative technology to differentiate its razors
from the competition. Then it relies on big marketing campaigns to
convince consumers that a razor is not a commodity product and that
a Gillette razor is well worth a premium price.
</P>
<P>
   Through a series of acquisitions, Gillette has looked to apply
that strategy to other consumer product categories.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has worked for Gillette's Duracell battery
division, as well as for Braun razors and oral-care products. But
Gillette has had a harder time trying to introduce technological
innovations to low profit-margin categories with products such as
Paper Mate pens, Braun blenders, and Braun ear thermometers.
</P>
<P>
   These product lines, while of high quality, don't have ``a
synergistic fit'' with Gillette's core categories of razors,
batteries, and oral care, said Fredric E. Russell of Fredric E.
Russell Investment Management Co., a Gillette investor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I applaud the decision'' to hire J.P. Morgan to review options
for Braun's underperforming business lines, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Braun accounted for $1.58 billion of Gillette's total
sales of $9.9 billion. The portions of the Braun business that are
subject to review accounted for about $500 million in 1999 sales.
</P>
<P>
   If Gillette were to sell the underperforming Braun product lines
and its stationery business, it could reduce overall sales by just
over $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, shares of Gillette fell 7/16 to
close at 37 1/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1840EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
