u f BC-SBC-STERLING-NYT &LR;      02-22 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SBC-STERLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL PHONE COMPANY TO ENTER E-COMMERCE VIA MAJOR ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (bl)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the biggest move by a major local phone company into the
torrid electronic commerce business, SBC Communications said
Tuesday that it had agreed to acquire Sterling Commerce for almost
$3.9 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   As competition increases in every sector of the communications
industry, established companies like SBC and AT&AMP;T are trying to
de-emphasize the sale of raw communications pipes and offer instead
more complex services that can carry richer profits.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling, based in Dallas, is a leader in developing systems
that link businesses to one another so that they can electronically
exchange information. In the last year, the so-called
business-to-business part of e-commerce has become a newly popular
and heavily traveled stomping ground for both public investors and
private institutions like venture capital firms.
</P>
<P>
   SBC, based in San Antonio, is the No. 1 local phone company (at
least until Bell Atlantic completes its pending acquisition of
GTE). It is spending billions of dollars to enhance systems that
deliver Internet data to customers at high speeds. But the company
also wants to sell and profit from the software applications that
can ride on top of its Internet infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling, which has as its clients large corporations like ,
including Johnson &AMP; Johnson and Wal-Mart Stores, would give SBC an
advantage in that area.
</P>
<P>
   ``This instantly gives SBC the skill sets, software, products
and services needed to take the lead in one of the most rapidly
growing segments of the e-commerce market,'' Edward E. Whitacre,
SBC's chairman, said in a statement. ``Sterling Commerce's highly
skilled information technology teams also will help us in the
future, as we continue to capitalize on Internet-driven
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Sterling's shareholders would receive $44.25 in
cash for each of their Sterling shares, a 40 percent premium over
Sterling's closing share price Friday of $31.5625.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling's shareholders were obviously pleased Tuesday as the
company's shares rose $12, to $43.5625. But SBC's shareholders had
doubts about the deal, sending SBC's shares down $2.25, to $36,
despite the company's assurances that the acquisition would not
dilute SBC earnings.
</P>
<P>
   To their chagrin, the big local phone companies are generally
valued by investors on their per-share earnings growth and dividend
payments. At this moment of sky-high Internet valuations, that can
sometimes make it difficult for the old-line local phone giants to
pull off big acquisitions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1845EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SF-JEWISH-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      02-22 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-JEWISH-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH MUSEUMS FROM BERLIN TO THE BAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: In lead, Jewish Museum San Francisco is the official title of
the museum. No words are missing.) 
jt) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Jewish Museum San Francisco has unveiled a design by the
Berlin-based architect Daniel Libeskind _ his first project in the
United States _ to be built in the Yerba Buena cultural district
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is scheduled to reopen in a renovated power
substation in 2002. The $60 million project will include more than
100,000 square feet of space for a core exhibition, temporary
shows, offices, a theater, media lab, bookstore and cafe. The
museum has been designed in association with Gordon H. Chong &AMP;
Partners, architects in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Libeskind is best known for the new Jewish Museum in Berlin,
which is widely judged the most important of the many buildings
that have risen in the German capital since the destruction of the
Berlin Wall. A dramatic composition of zinc-clad, zigzag-shaped
wings, the Berlin Jewish Museum has brought wide public attention
to the work of an architect previously known for theoretical
projects. For the Berlin museum, Libeskind's floor plans
incorporated shapes that evoke lightning bolts, surgical sutures
and the Star of David. The museum's interior and outdoor garden are
so powerfully expressive that the building began to draw crowds
long before any art had been installed.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco design is a parabuilding, or an addition that
radically transforms a structure. An angular construction of
complex geometric forms, clad in metal, will be inserted inside the
Jessie Street substation, built in 1907 and vacant for two decades.
The addition will straddle the building's roof and clamp onto the
red brick facades at either end, inserting a highly visible
architectural identity into the cityscape.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a classical musician before he came to the United
States to study architecture, Libeskind has often used musical
motifs in his unbuilt works. In 1988 the Museum of Modern Art
included his projects in its show on deconstructionist
architecture, whose curator was Philip Johnson. Titled ``City
Edge,'' the project featured a gigantic concrete slab, tilted on
one end, that rose 10 stories to peer over the Berlin Wall. In 1998
Libeskind won a competition to design an addition to the Victoria
and Albert Museum in London. Titled ``The Spiral Extension,'' the
project is scheduled for completion in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco visitors will pass through the power station's
imposing entrance to arrive in a soaring lobby dominated by large
metal renderings of the two letters that form the Hebrew word chai,
or life. Libeskind has also used the two letters to create
three-dimensional spaces inside the substation. Galleries derived
from the letter chet will contain the museum's core exhibition.
Spaces based on the letter yud will provide vertical and horizontal
circulation throughout the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Libeskind was born in Lodz, Poland, in 1946. Jewish and
cabalaistic themes have figured in his previous work. In a design
statement Libeskind writes: ``In the Jewish tradition, letters are
not mere signs, but are substantial participants in the story they
create. Thus the spatiality of chai _ a fundamental emblem of
Jewish life _ will be experienced as a full dynamic movement
responding to the many levels of interpretation this word
possesses.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the Yerba Buena area has become a major focus
for the ethnically diverse cultural life of San Francisco. It is
already home to several institutions designed by distinguished
architects. They include the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art,
designed by Mario Botta; the Yerba Buena Center for the Arts, by
Fumihiko Maki; and the Center for the Arts Theater, by James
Stewart Polshek &AMP; Partners. A Mexican Museum is planned for a site
next to the new Jewish Museum, which will be at 701 Mission Street
and Third Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
