<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4965 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-RAIDERS-HNS &LR;      02-22 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RAIDERS ARE IN OAKLAND TO STAY (FOR NOW) 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAT RATTO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The headline in Saturday's Oakland Tribune,
the newspaper representing the community most in touch with the
travails of doing business with Al Davis, read simply, ``Raiders
Must Stay 11 Years.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's putting the best face forward on it. Apparently,
``Parole Denied For Raiders,'' or ``Back To The Hoosegow For Al''
didn't fit the allotted space.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to question the Tribune's headline writing skills _
to the contrary, those five words captured the facts and the mood
from both plaintiff and defendant in the Raiders' attempt to break
their lease with Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the owner of the Oakland Raiders can't go to Los
Angeles, no matter how much he claims he was hoodwinked by those
Machiavellian slyboots in the Oakland political establishment, no
matter how many spoons he sharpens to dig to freedom, no matter
whether he holds his breath until Carmen Policy turns blue.
</P>
<P>
   He's just going to have to be a man about it and take his
regular checks from the taxpayers until his claim that he was duped
by the Oakland politicians into returning to his vision of hell is
adjudicated.
</P>
<P>
   No, we're still not done yet. Davis gets to press his claim for
nearly a billion scoots in damages based on the hilarious notion
that the pols tricked him. This is not exactly the same thing as
Stephen Hawking being bamboozled by a flock of geese, but it comes
close enough.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, emitted by Superior Court Judge Joe S. Gray, a man
with a rich if slightly perverse sense of humor, was preliminary,
but unless he rescinds his ruling, the Raiders really will remain
in Oakland for 11 more fun-filled seasons.
</P>
<P>
   So we are back where we began, with Davis fuming over his
reception in Oakland, the politicians fuming over his obstinate
Al-ness, and the rest of us sick to death of the whole ghoulish
mess.
</P>
<P>
   Only now, the argument has reverted to money. Davis, never a man
to misunderstand the value of a dollar, is asking for $800 million
from the city and Alameda County to soothe his hurt feelings at
being lured from Los Angeles _ although ``lured'' isn't entirely
accurate. Davis has never been lured anywhere he didn't want to go,
as long as the money was right.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' chief defenders claim he has never been motivated by
money. This is, of course, monumental nonsense, because everybody
is motivated by money. Maybe Davis' chief interest is still winning
football games, but money has always been 1-A.
</P>
<P>
   How else did he deduce years before anyone else that the NFL TV
contract would be worth billions? How else has he been able to get
top buck and a dime beyond out of every negotiation he ever
entered? How has he taken a minority stake in a football team and
become one of the most influential men in the entire NFL? Well,
money. He knows how to make it, how to use it and how to replace it
with even more money. This trait does not make him a bad person; in
fact, it makes him a smart person. A very smart person.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes his claim that he was buffaloed into coming back an
interesting one, to put it kindly. Unless, of course, he wants to
make the case that spending all that time with the Oakland pols
eroded his brainpower, which would be a matter not only for a jury
but for a neurologist.
</P>
<P>
   And the number $800 million is interesting as well, since there
seems no way for Oakland to come up with that kind of scratch save
selling off Piedmont for the parts _ or, say, nullifying the lease
the city just won the right to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   The trial for that little argument is tentatively scheduled for
April 24, although Davis might want to challenge Gray's ruling,
call other witnesses or see how Policy is coming with that turning
blue business.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, your hope of making the sniveling stop is doomed.
Davis has just lost a round in a fight that has already gone longer
than Jack Johnson's last bout, and he takes losing in court about
as well as losing to Mike Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   At least with Shanahan, though, Davis is up against an equal, at
least on the football plane. Here, he is trying to outwit people by
claiming they outwitted him, a legal triple Salchow that would put
Michelle Kwan into a full body cramp only gallons of hot water and
a crowbar could cure.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, though, has tackled bigger and more fearsome game, and
among the things he doesn't take is no for an answer. He has
nothing but time, and plenty of geese to get in his sights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
