<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4968 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-TAXI-DROUGHT-2TAKE     02-22 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXI-DROUGHT-2TAKES(1000)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVERS AND RIDERS SEE NO RELIEF FOR THE GREAT TAXI DROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is as inexorable as the tides, as reliable as the
setting sun. And it happens every weekday afternoon around 5, just
as office buildings are beginning to empty out, just as hundreds of
hands are being raised into the air on hundreds of crowded
Manhattan street corners: the Great Taxi Drought begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, guy!'' yelled Don Ciliotta, waving, leaning into traffic,
trying to catch the eyes of a cabbie tearing down Ninth Avenue.
``Guy! Hey guy!''
</P>
<P>
   The driver waved back, which was nice of him, considering that
more than a dozen taxis had simply roared past Ciliotta, a tile
importer from Long Island, suffering for more than 20 minutes in a
subfreezing wind with his brother and their wives.
</P>
<P>
   Atop each passing cab glared the familiar amber off-duty light,
as forlorn as a no-vacancy sign buzzing in the dead of night.
</P>
<P>
   The Ciliottas, far from alone, were caught in the gears of the
dreaded taxi shift change. It happens when daytime drivers end
their 12-hour work day and hit their off-duty lights to give
themselves time to gas up and return to their garages to hand the
cab to the night drivers, who are anxious to start their own
12-hour shifts to catch as much of the evening rush as possible.
</P>
<P>
   As New York phenomena go, the changeover approaches a kind of
natural law, and one that seems to have been handed down from God,
like alternate-side-of-the-street parking rules and 20 percent
tips.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it has been around so long and has become so ingrained
in most taxi drivers' lives that explaining it seems, to them, as
unnecessary as explaining why their cars have tires. ``It's been
around, like, forever, for eons,'' said Mike Higgins, a longtime
cabbie who publishes the trade newspaper Taxi Talk. ``It's just a
traditional thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But to the cab-hailing public, it is a natural law that makes
about as much sense as the one that compels salmon to swim
upstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't follow any kind of supply and demand laws,'' said
Nathana Josephs, a public relations consultant who practically
lives in taxis and has, in desperation, talked police officers and
once even firefighters into giving her rides when she could not
find a cab during a shift change.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 53rd and Fifth Avenue to 57th and Fifth, you could die
before you get a cab at 5 o'clock,'' said Josephs. ``Or you could
get killed because of the competition to get the ones out there
that are on duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Taxi industry historians say that the weekday late-afternoon
shift change _ or at least the version that has become so
noticeable and roundly reviled _ started happening in the early
1980s, when the large taxi fleets began leasing cabs to drivers
instead of hiring the drivers as employees and paying them on
commission.
</P>
<P>
   The change, the result of a taxi industry policy adopted in
1979, made drivers into independent contractors who generally
worked longer hours _ 12-hour shifts instead of 9-hour shifts, to
make more money _ but who had more control over when they worked.
</P>
<P>
   In order to keep the cabs occupied with drivers, fleets and
other companies that leased taxis needed to divide the two 12-hour
shifts so that there would always be a roughly equal number of
drivers to fill day and night shifts.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that if the day drivers started their shifts
when they really wanted to _ at around 7 a.m. or even 8, when the
streets begin to fill with people _ they would hand off to the
night drivers too late for those drivers to reap the busiest time
of their shift, when people left work. This would mean fewer
drivers willing to take on night shifts.
</P>
<P>
   So widespread shift changing around 4:30 or 5 o'clock began to
evolve, giving both groups of drivers the benefit of a rush hour.
And to make sure that the system was fair to night drivers, fleets
also began to assess late fees from day drivers who stayed out too
long and cut into night drivers' business.
</P>
<P>
   But, in truth, night drivers are always complaining that day
drivers should start earlier and hand off earlier because so many
of their precious evening fares are simply evaporating, into the
subways or into private car services, while the handoff takes
place.
</P>
<P>
   Day drivers, who hate starting as early as they do, are not
budging.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Sherman, president of the Midtown Operating Corp., one of
the city's largest fleets, with about 200 cars, recalled a heroic
effort a few years back to move the shifts so that more of his
drivers would change over earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it made sense and we'd give it a try,'' he said. The
result? ``We completely lost our whole day line.'' He said that
about 70 percent of his drivers now change at 4:30 p.m. and others
work out changes among themselves that are earlier or later.
</P>
<P>
   There is not much he can do, he added, because the healthy
economy has prompted many taxi drivers to leave for more lucrative
work at private livery companies and has increased competition
among taxi fleets for drivers. So the drivers who lease his cabs,
Sherman said, pretty much ``do what they want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really no different from Hertz or Avis,'' he said. ``I
can't tell you when to come in and rent a car from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman's drivers insist that, sure, they feel for the stranded
pedestrian with a late afternoon meeting or a plane to catch or a
child waiting at day care. But there is really not much they can
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's rough out there, and of course everybody wants
to go home, but I want to go home, too,'' said Anthony Tilelli, 58,
who stood in Sherman's Long Island City garage last week after his
day shift, while restless night drivers played ``Ms. Pac-Man'' in
the waiting room behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Tilelli, a 20-year taxi veteran, said that when he is off duty
and angry pedestrians begin knocking on his window at a stop light,
threatening to report him to the Taxi and Limousine Commission for
refusing service, he generally rolls down his window and spells his
name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them to make sure and get it right,'' he said. ``I
don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While the commission has no exact figures to show exactly how
many cabs are changing shifts around 5 p.m., the indications are
that more are doing so than several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This is because the number of taxis being driven by individual
owner-drivers _ those who work for themselves and tend to drive
from the morning rush through the evening rush, filling in the gap
_ is dropping, said Bruce Schaller, a transportation consultant who
studies the taxi industry. From 1994 to 1998, the proportion of all
taxis driven by owner-drivers fell from about 28 percent to 18
percent, and the percentage is believed to be lower now.
</P>
<P>
   That, combined with the fact that more discretionary income
means more people competing for the fraction of the 12,187 cabs
remaining on duty, means one thing: some very mean streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't really a lot we can do about it,'' said Diane
McGrath-McKechnie, the chairwoman of the Taxi and Limousine
Commission. ``Except make it very hurtful for the drivers, and
we're not going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the ugliest manifestation of the increase, said Higgins,
the Taxi Talk publisher, is the rising occurrence of what he calls
``the big double cross,'' when an off-duty driver, motivated by
both commercial and humanitarian impulses, decides to pick up a
passenger who swears his destination is in the direction of the
driver's garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `Yeah, I'm going to 49th Street. This works out
great!' And then they get in and say, `OK buddy, take me to
Brooklyn Heights,' and what are you going to do because they're
already in the cab?''
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, Higgins says, he doesn't take the risk
anymore. He does exactly what all those cab drivers who whooshed
past the poor Ciliottas on Ninth Avenue did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if it's Jesus Christ or a little old lady,'' he
said. ``I've got to get to the garage on time.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And what about the Ciliottas, who had a dinner reservation in
the West Village? When a reporter left them, they were still
waiting, and beginning to shiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we going to do?'' Ciliotta said. ``We're not going to
 &UR; walk &LR;  40 blocks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
