u i BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-U.S.-NYT     02-22 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AND THE WHITE HOUSE CRITICIZE CHINA'S THREAT ON TAIWAN
</HEADLINE>
  (With CHINA-TAIWAN) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration and Congress on Tuesday
sharply criticized a threat by China to forcibly reunify Taiwan
with the mainland if Beijing determines that negotiations between
the two are dragging on too long.
</P>
<P>
   Senior lawmakers said the official Chinese statement released on
Monday could increase the chances that Congress would approve
legislation expanding ties between the U.S. military and Taiwan,
despite President Clinton's threatened veto of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The House overwhelmingly passed the measure, called the Taiwan
Security Enhancement Act, earlier this month, but the Senate has up
to now viewed the measure more skeptically. China's report could
also imperil the administration's effort in Congress, especially in
the House, to win permanent trading status for China.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who want to kill this trade deal with China,
and China is playing right into their hands,'' said Sen. Gordon
Smith, R-Ore., who supports normal trading relations with China.
``This is tugging our loyalties to trade and to Taiwan in opposite
directions.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House on Tuesday urged China and Taiwan to resolve
their differences over unification without resorting to force, and
issued a veiled warning to Beijing to temper its bellicose
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have repeated, in I think both actions and words, that we
view any threat to Taiwan with grave concern,'' said the White
House spokesman, Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   The United States officially supports the concept of ``one
China,'' but under the 1979 Taiwan Relations Act is also committed
to providing Taiwan with means to defend itself.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., who heads the Armed Services Committee,
said he had summoned top Pentagon experts to testify about China in
a closed session on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Warner said it was ``a slap in face'' for China to issue its
provocative 11,000-word report just after a high-level American
delegation, led by Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, had
left China. The delegation, Warner said, had been ``trying to calm
the waters.''
</P>
<P>
   But some other leading Republicans cautioned against reading too
much into the report. ``It's bad judgment to put out that statement
at this time,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi. ``But we'll factor that in to all our thinking. It's
not determinative.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other administration officials contrasted China's
statements with its even more menacing actions in 1996, when it
fired missiles off Taiwanese waters in the run-up to the island's
first direct presidential elections. The United States responded by
sending two aircraft carrier battle groups near the Taiwan Straits
to show support for Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   ``One should be careful not to exaggerate the significance of
this,'' a State Department spokesman, James Rubin, told reporters.
``We've had much worse periods on this question in the past. This
is a new formulation. We find the formulation troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said Beijing's words do not alter the administration's
continuing review of Taiwan's request for sophisticated weaponry.
``The decision about arms sales is a complicated calculation, and
isn't necessarily affected by any one statement on paper,'' Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
   But across Capitol Hill, Republicans and Democrats urged the
administration to send a tougher message to Beijing, and assailed
China's statements as unduly provocative.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's white paper communications are unacceptable,'' said
Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., on the Foreign Relations Committee.
``There's no other way to put it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
