<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4973 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-QUEBEC-NAMES-ART-2TAK     02-22 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEBEC-NAMES-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ITALIAN NAME FOR A QUEBEC BRIDGE? QUELLE SCANDAL! 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: a  map  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ To Quebec nationalists, the proposal seemed
suspicious from the start: to rename one of the 15 highway bridges
leading into this city after an Italian.
</P>
<P>
   But after two years of petitions from representatives of some of
Montreal's 200,000 people of Italian background, Quebec's official
place names commission voted two months ago to take a walk on the
ethnic wild side. They renamed a 32-year-old suspension bridge
after Pietro Rizzuto, a Sicilian who arrived here penniless in
1955, made a fortune in road construction, and died three years
ago, a federal senator in his adopted land.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the commissioners reasoned, of the city's other
bridges, 12 carry French names, one carries the name of a pope,
and, in deference to Montreal's dwindling English-speaking
minority, one is called Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   Giuseppe Sciortino, a lawyer here, promoted the name change as a
way to bridge the gap, symbolically and literally, between
Montreal, an increasingly ethnically diverse city, and Laval, a
northern suburb with a strongly separatist largely homogeneous
French Canadian population. In 1968, Rizzuto's construction company
built and paved the access lanes to the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The commission apparently did not expect much of a reaction to
removing the bridge's old name, Papineau-Leblanc. In the ethnic
coding here, these family names are ``pure laine,'' literally
``pure wool,'' or old stock Quebecois families that go back before
the time of the British conquest of 1759.
</P>
<P>
   The Leblancs were pioneers, settling Laval in 1666. The
Papineaus were political nationalists of the first hour, arguing
for French language rights as early as 1793. But, with ``Je me
souviens,'' or ``I remember,'' on their license plates, modern
Quebecers are driving into the 21st century, still smarting over
events in the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really mad,'' said Gilles Leblanc, a Laval
businessman who is descended from the first settlers. After
delivering a protest petition with 4,000 signatures to the
commission in January, he warned them: ``Don't step on the
ancestors. You don't touch that.''
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls of complaint were so numerous that the Laval
City Council, which had unanimously supported the name change,
reversed itself and voted unanimously against it. Laval's four
representatives to the provincial assembly, all members of the
separatist Parti Quebecois, denounced the name change.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the commission, one representative, David Clichi,
noted that the six-lane highway bridge carried the names of
``illustrious families'' and suggested something ``more
appropriate'' for the Sicilian.
</P>
<P>
   Getting down to specifics, the Societe Saint-Jean-Baptiste de
Montreal, a nationalist group here, proposed that an appropriate
memorial for Rizzuto, a federalist, would be a subway stop in
Saint-Michel, an Italian part of town.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Montreal's ethnic and linguistic minorities,
supporting the name change, asked for tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``History evolves,'' argued Anna Mancuso, Quebec president of
the National Congress of Italian Canadians, a national group based
here. ``Senator Rizzuto also influenced Quebec society.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Robinson, a columnist for The Gazette, an English
language newspaper that carries little weight with separatists,
noted that, in Quebec, Papineau is used 106 times to name streets,
parks, boulevards and creeks and that Leblanc is similarly used 179
times. Rizzuto is nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Don Macpherson, another Gazette columnist, wrote that the
commission approves about 100 name changes a year, almost all in
``the `right' direction, in favor of the old-stock
French-Canadians'' whose interests the Party Quebecois ``has
consistently favored.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely controlled by nationalists, the place name commission
has ignored English complaints and purged dozens of historic
English place names from English-speaking areas. It changed the
name of Montreal's central boulevard from Dorchester, the name of
an early British governor, to Rene Levesque, the name of the man
who founded the Parti Quebecois in 1968. Two years ago, the
commission overruled Cree Indian objections and gave Quebecois
names to 101 deserted islands that the Cree said already had Indian
names.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On the editorial page of Le Devoir, a separatist newspaper,
Michel Venne argued that nationalism should no longer be synonymous
with ethnicity, asking if ``a symbol of recognition for New
Quebecers is going to be become a symbol of our being closed to
others?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We often discuss the integration of immigrants and the
pluralistic nature of Quebec society theoretically,'' said Venne,
who recently organized a well-attended round table here to spin an
inclusive, multi-cultural vision of an independent Quebec.
Referring to the name change, he added: ``We have before our very
eyes a concrete case of an attempt to include and to recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   But such pleas fell on deaf ears.
</P>
<P>
   Lysiane Gagnon, a columnist for La Presse, a newspaper that
favors Quebec staying within Canada, wrote that ``it is normal and
legitimate to cherish the memory of a history which goes back close
to 400 years,'' and urged readers to ignore ``those who profit from
this false debate to start circulating again these tiresome
insinuations about the congenital xenophobia of the `French
Canadians.'''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By the end of January, the controversy had become so bitter that
the Rizzuto family asked the commission to cancel the name change.
The commission complied immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But if Quebecois nativists have trouble digesting European
ethnic groups that have been here for over 30 years, such as
Italians, Greeks and Portuguese, they are in for a real demographic
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   In central Montreal, home to 1 million people, almost one third
of children under 15 are what Canadian census takers officially
classify as ``visible minorities'' _ Arabs, Asians, Blacks and
Latin Americans. This portion will rise to one half of school age
children in about a decade, predicts Jack Jedwab, executive
director of the Association for Canadian Studies.
</P>
<P>
   In a turnaround, the majority of these children of immigrants
now attend French language schools instead of English-language
schools. But a CROP poll taken last fall of 2,000 Canadian adults
found more Quebecois respondents _ 51 percent _ favored more limits
on immigration than other Canadians _ 44 percent. In Montreal,
members of minority groups increasingly complain about
discrimination over skin color or their accent when they speak
French.
</P>
<P>
   Nadia Zouaoui, an Algerian immigrant who is a free-lance
reporter, complained recently that she was turned down for a job at
a Montreal television station because her accent ``was not Quebec
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a kind of racism that's hard to denounce,'' Zouaoui
said last month at the start here of a privately funded campaign
called United Against Racism. ``In France, there is racism, but
people say it out loud. Here, people don't talk about it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While the bridge debate highlighted unspoken divisions, some
analysts suspect that, in the Machiavellian world of Quebec
politics, the controversy also represented payback time.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Sciortino was the token ``ethnic'' on the
executive board of the Parti Quebecois. In November, 1995, Jacques
Parizeau, Quebec's premier, blamed his razor thin loss in a
referendum on whether Quebec should separate from Canada on ``the
ethnic vote,'' and vowed, ``We will have our revenge.'' After a
general outcry, alarmed party leaders accepted Parizeau's
resignation and propelled Sciortino before television cameras to
say, in lightly accented French, that ethnic minorities were
welcome in the separatist movement.
</P>
<P>
   But when Sciortino tried to win his party's nomination for a
legislative Assembly seat, he lost out to a ``pure laine''
Quebecer, Robert Perrault. During the nomination debate, one
delegate suggested that Sciortino might feel more comfortable
``among his own people, in Little Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after trying to run the Parti Quebecois operation for
Montreal Island, the city core, Sciortino tired of constant
challenges to his leadership. He resigned from the party, charging
in an essay in La Presse, that the separatists were not welcoming
to ``New Quebecers.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the emotions bared over the bridge dispute, Jim Duff,
an analyst for The West Island Suburban, an English weekly, wrote
recently, ``If I was a conspiracy buff, I'd say Giuseppe set out to
deal a masterful slap to the faces'' of his former party
colleagues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
