<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO MAKE SENSE OF A CHANGE OF HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  (Lessons Column) 
(jt) 
 By ALISON LEIGH COWAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike most of the Ivy League, Brown University has not added a
business school to its campus, despite the obvious perk: wealthy
alumni. No matter. Brown's students and faculty got a lesson from
the business world this month. The school's barely broken-in
president, E. Gordon Gee, stunned the community when he announced
that after just two years in office, he had accepted an offer to
run Vanderbilt University.
</P>
<P>
   Only last month, he was telling The Chronicle of Higher
Education that it takes two years for schools to warm to him, but
that he had the vision and passion to carry the institution
forward. There was another interview earlier about how this was the
summit of his career, his last college presidency. He had made an
8-to-10-year commitment.
</P>
<P>
   So clearly not just Brown, but all of academia, was at a loss.
Gee explained. But the more he explained, the more the world seemed
to spin.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he said, there was always a question of fit. He never
felt quite at home in Providence. He liked his residences, a
historic home in town and an $850,000 country house that he would
sorely miss in the coming months, he said. It was the job that was
vexing. ``There were days I'd wake up and not feel as committed or
as passionate as I should,'' he told the student paper. Vanderbilt
was a bigger canvas than Brown, more like what he had grown used to
in the years he ran West Virginia University, then the University
of Colorado and finally Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   The money was also about two to three times the $300,000 a year
he made at Brown. Not that he cared, but Brown refused to match it.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was his wife, Constance. She had been given a
teaching position at Brown, but it was not a tenured position, like
the one Vanderbilt had offered. She looked happy when her husband
first ascended at Brown and introduced her as one of the ``biggest
assets we had at Ohio State'' and ``an equal partner'' at Brown.
Visitors to Brown's Web site are still greeted with a color photo
of the beaming couple, holding hands.
</P>
<P>
   Gee also took pains to explain how much he struggled over his
dilemma. When he first told a member of Brown's board that
Vanderbilt had approached, he was advised that the conversations
were inappropriate. But Vanderbilt kept coming. Before long, Gee
(the ``g'' is hard) was furtively visiting the Nashville campus,
and consulting an ethicist to help him weigh his choices. It must
have worked. By the time the parting was official, he was saying it
took ``courage'' to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter? Martha Ingram, the businesswoman who helped
recruit Gee to Vanderbilt, says she does not see what all the fuss
is about. ``People take people from my company all the time,'' said
Ingram, who runs a powerful wholesale book business.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it isn't any different. Sports, entertainment and business
personalities job-hop all the time. Character seems not to be what
people expect from their leaders anymore. Maybe prosperity has
changed the rules for universities too. Gordon Gekko, Hollywood's
notion of the consummate corporate raider, certainly would applaud
Gordon Gee.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of imprint will it leave on those who graduate from
Brown this year, with an interim president as master of ceremonies?
What does it say to them about honoring one's obligations, choosing
meaning over money, being satisfied when life is sweet enough?
</P>
<P>
   Gee delivered ably on his promise to throw himself into the
business of the institution, chiefly fund-raising and recruiting.
He was the very definition of a professional president. With no
previous ties to Brown, he amassed college trophies for his office
the way investment bankers collect tombstones from deals they've
closed.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say people ought to feel trapped in ill-fitting
jobs. A long time ago, I landed what seemed like a dream job out of
college in advertising. But a year into it, I started fretting. It
was not for me. So I tiptoed into my boss' imposing corner office
to let him know I would be taking a job as a copy girl at The New
York Times, a job that paid about $4,000 less than the $17,000 I
was making on Madison Avenue. He led me to believe I was letting
him down. Loyalty and all. Then, a few weeks later, he quit for a
better job in advertising. I made a note to myself that loyalty is
a concept business likes to toss around, but seems to vanish the
moment the proverbial better offer comes along.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad college presidents don't come with money-back guarantees
or employment contracts. Then Brown could do one thing companies
and consumers do all the time when feeling burned: claim a refund
or sue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
