<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-POOR-MORPHINE-AR     02-22 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-POOR-MORPHINE-ART-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. AGENCY CITES SHORTAGE OF PAIN KILLERS IN POOR COUNTRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ An international narcotics control agency that
is better known for raising alarms about the narcotics trade and
drug abuse has turned its attention this year to a severe shortage
of morphine and other pain killers in poor countries, where many
are left to die in agony from cancer and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The International Narcotics Control Board, a U.N. agency based
in Vienna, said in a report to be published Wednesday that it has
been tracking the rising but uneven use of morphine and other
natural or synthetic drugs with similar structures and effects for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   The board and the World Health Organization encourage the use of
morphine, which is derived from opium, or similar drugs to relieve
cancer-related pain. The board said there is no evidence that these
drugs are widely diverted for illicit use, and therefore no reason
to caution against increased production.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the 26-member board made up of experts and
diplomats found great disparities in access to strong pain killers
among countries and also within them _ usually for economic
reasons, but not always. Cultural or social attitudes and medical
philosophies also play a part. Treating pain has gained more
attention in the United States and Europe in recent years, but for
other countries, morphine may still be an unaffordable luxury,
experts said. ``The 10 largest consumer countries accounted for as
much as 80 percent of analgesic morphine consumption,'' the report
found. In those countries, all richer nations, the annual average
consumption of such drugs was 31 grams for each 1,000 people. At
the other end of the scale, in 120 mostly poor countries, there was
little or no consumption of these painkillers, called opiods.
Eighty other countries fell somewhere between these extremes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a large proportion of the countries and territories of the
world,'' the report said, ``insignificant amounts of these
medicines are available for medical purposes and it is generally
agreed that the treatment of chronic or acute pain caused by cancer
is still inadequate. Only about 10 to 30 percent of patients
suffering from severe cancer-related pain may be receiving adequate
treatment, even in many technologically advanced countries.''
</P>
<P>
   But the situation is often starkest in the poorest countries,
the report found. ``In developing countries, the relief of pain and
suffering is given much lower priority than other, more urgent,
health and social problems,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization, which is represented on the
narcotics board, predicts that by 2015, two-thirds of an estimated
15 million new cancer cases each year will be in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Like calls made by others for cheaper and more readily available
drugs for HIV-AIDS in the Third World, the narcotics board report
recommends making more painkillers accessible.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The use of morphine for medical purposes was relatively low and
stable until 1984, the report said. In the last 15 years, it has
risen tenfold.
</P>
<P>
   The country with the highest consumption of morphine for medical
use in 1998 was Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the narcotics control board also surveyed the use
of legal mind-altering drugs and found that Europe far outstripped
America and all other regions in the medical use of hypnotics and
sedatives. Americans, on the other hand, continued to lead the
world in the use of amphetamines, which act as stimulants, and, in
fact, increased their intake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last few decades, accepted therapeutic uses of
amphetamines have become rare and as a result almost all countries
in the world report declining medical use of such substances,'' the
report found. ``Not so the United States.'' U.S. consumption of
amphetamines for medical use is ten times higher than in any
European country, the narcotics board said.
</P>
<P>
   The board said the issue of possible oversupply and
overmedication with these drugs will be the focus of next year's
annual report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
