<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SEC BRINGS CASES AGAINST THREE INVESTMENT FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The nation's top securities regulator brought civil
cases against two stock day-trading firms Tuesday and turned a hat
trick by also accusing an unregistered hedge fund manager of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission found that all three
investment firms violated regulations designed to protect investors
in some of the financial markets' most speculative arenas.
</P>
<P>
   All-Tech Direct Inc., one of the leading providers of rapid-fire
daytrading services, was accused of violating regulations governing
the practice of lending money to customers to buy stocks. A second,
smaller daytrading firm, Investment Street Co., was accused of
similar loan violations, indicating that the practices of such
firms remain under close scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In the third case, the SEC contended that David M. Mobley Sr.,
manager of Maricopa Investment Fund Ltd., and three related hedge
funds, defrauded investors of at least $59 million. While Mobley,
43, of Naples, Fla., claimed to be producing returns of 51 percent
a year he diverted investor funds to buy a $98,000 Porsche, a
$864,000 home in Naples and a $2 million vacation home in Vail,
Colo., the regulators said. The money he did invest for his clients
since 1993 went into his own ill-fated business ventures, including
a cigar lounge, a country club development and a stadium on a golf
course.
</P>
<P>
   In the day-trading actions, All-Tech Direct, of Montvale, N.J.,
its president and six of the firm's managers were charged with
making 103 loans exceeding $3.6 million to customers throughout
1998 in violation of federal rules. Regulators also contend that
All-Tech management failed to advise its customers of the loan
terms.
</P>
<P>
   Investment Street Co. of Miami and two of its principals
extended $250,000 in credit improperly to customers, the SEC
contended, and allowed people to conduct business as registered
stockbrokers even though they were not registered.
</P>
<P>
   All-Tech is fighting the regulatory action. Investment Street
and its principals settled the SEC matter without admitting or
denying guilt. The firm and the individuals paid $36,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say both firms made the loans to keep their customers
trading stocks even when the value of their accounts fell below
required levels. This allowed both All-Tech and Investment Street
to continue generating commissions as their customers traded on
what is called margin. All-Tech generally charges $25 a trade,
although active traders receive discounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Margin magnifies both the risks and costs of daytrading,''
said Richard H. Walker, director of enforcement at the SEC. ``We
will not allow daytrading firms to overextend margin and keep
customers afloat so the firms may continue to generate
commissions.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's regulatory actions are an outgrowth of a broad,
18-month investigation by the SEC into the practices at daytrading
firms. Many of the firms have seemed to operate by their own rules,
and regulators are working to rein them in.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on lending coincides with increased concern among
regulators that investors are borrowing too heavily to buy stocks
and may not understand the risks inherent in the practice. Last
month, Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve Board,
asked the SEC to study a troubling spike in the amount of debt
accumulated by investors in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who borrow money to buy stocks must meet two separate
requirements, one set by the Federal Reserve, the other by the
brokerage firm where they do business. The Federal Reserve requires
that investors put up 50 percent of a stock's initial cost.
According to the SEC, both All-Tech and Investment Street lent
money to their customers to meet this initial requirement.
</P>
<P>
   All-Tech's founder took issue with the regulatory complaint.
``The SEC has spent many hours investigating everything they can
think of and came up with something that is not true,'' said Harvey
Houtkin, All-Tech's founder. ``They're trying to twist and turn
things to come up with something to justify their investigation. We
believe the charges are baseless, and we believe we will be
exonerated when the facts will come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Those named in the complaint were Mark Shefts, 42, All-Tech's
president; Harry Lefkowitz, 43, vice president of the firm's
operations; Lisa Esposito, 34, head of All-Tech's margin loan
department; Ralph Zulferino, 40, manager of the firm's Edison,
N.J., branch office; David Waldman, 58, an All-Tech employee; Adam
Leeds 31, a broker in All-Tech's San Diego office, and Barry
Parish, 46, manager of the San Diego branch.
</P>
<P>
   All-Tech Direct, with 22 offices where traders furiously buy and
sell stocks many times during the day, is one of the better-known
daytrading firms. The firm made headlines last summer when a
disgruntled investor opened fire in its Atlanta office, killing
five people. Houtkin, who considers himself the father of
electronic daytrading and a champion of the individual investor,
was not named in the SEC's complaint Tuesday. The SEC said that its
investigation into the firm's practices is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, which breathlessly pitched daytrading as an investment
strategy almost anyone could succeed at, has softened its message
somewhat. For example, though securities regulators estimate that
nine out of 10 daytraders lose money, All-Tech's Web site once
answered a question about losses this way: ``If you are disciplined
in following the techniques you will be taught, losses can and
should be kept to a minimum.'' Now the site says: ``Active
electronic stock trading is risky and not for everyone. Because of
the use of margin, losses may exceed the amount invested.''
</P>
<P>
   In the civil case against the hedge fund manager, the SEC and
the Commodity Futures Trading Commission contend that Mobley had
conducted an elaborate seven-year fraud in which he told investors
that he managed $450 million of clients' funds and made bets on
which direction the stock market would take using computer trading
models that he had developed.
</P>
<P>
   According to regulators, more than 170 investors, most of them
wealthy, gave Mobley $140 million to manage. He attracted clients
with a promotional brochure that shows monthly returns on a
hypothetical investment in his funds. The returns were ``plucked
out of thin air,'' according to the regulators' complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Although he returned approximately $48 million to some
investors, the bulk of the $59 million in losses came from
investments in Mobley's failed business ventures. He also paid
himself well _ a $1 million annual salary and a $2 million bonus
last month. Mobley also gave approximately $3.5 million of
investors' funds to charity, according to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley, who by early evening Tuesday did not have a lawyer,
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mutual fund managers, hedge fund managers are not
required to register with regulators or to file financial
information because their wealthy investors are considered to be
sophisticated and capable of evaluating risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action demonstrates the importance of investors assuring
themselves that their investments are being handled by responsible
persons and being appropriately managed,'' said Phyllis J. Cela,
acting director of the enforcement division at the CFTC. ``People
obviously thought their money was in good hands and clearly had not
done enough checking to be sure of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
