u w BC-SCOTUS-RDP-NYT     02-22 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT REJECTS CHALLENGE TO ALABAMA'S ELECTRIC CHAIR 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ala., Tenn., Fla., Pa., Ariz.) (With SCOTUS) 
(nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court justices returned from a
mid-winter recess on Tuesday and disposed of hundreds of cases.
Because the argument calendar for the current term is now full, the
cases granted Tuesday and for the next four months will be argued
after the new term begins next October.
</P>
<P>
   The court took the following action on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   Sports Rule Makers
</P>
<P>
   The court agreed to decide whether the statewide athletic
associations that in many states regulate interscholastic sports at
the high school level should be considered ``state actors,'' even
though they are nominally private organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The practical significance of the public-private distinction is
that if the organizations are deemed to be public, they will be
governed by the same constitutional constraints that apply to
government agencies; the Constitution places limits on government,
but not on private, behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The justices accepted an appeal by the Brentwood Academy, a
private school in Brentwood, Tenn., that ran afoul of the Tennessee
Secondary School Athletic Association's restrictions on recruiting.
The school sued the association on the ground that the rule against
coaches' communicating with prospective student athletes violated
the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The school won in federal District Court in Nashville, but the
6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Cincinnati, overturned that
ruling on the ground that as a private organization, the athletic
association was not bound by the First Amendment. The same question
has come up in six other federal appellate circuits, with all the
other courts finding that the statewide athletic associations were
state actors.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Secondary School Athletic Association, founded in
1925, has 290 public and 55 private schools as its members. Nine
public high school officials constitute its rule-making legislative
council. For years, its role in governing interscholastic sports in
the state was officially designated by the state board of
education; its role became unofficial in 1995, as the state action
issue began to be litigated around the country.
</P>
<P>
   One issue the court may address in this case, Brentwood Academy
vs. Tennessee Secondary School Athletic Assoc., No. 99-901, is the
extent to which the secondary school athletic associations differ
from the National Collegiate Athletic Association. The court ruled
in a 1988 case that the NCAA, as a national organization not
confined to any one state, was not a state actor, at least in the
context of a disciplinary action against a state university, in
that case, the University of Nevada at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   A new challenge to the NCAA, concerning its academic
prerequisites for freshman eligibility, is likely to reach the
Supreme Court soon. The federal appeals court in Philadelphia ruled
two months ago, in dismissing a case brought by four black
athletes, that because the NCAA was not a direct recipient of
federal money, it was not bound by the provision of the Civil
Rights Act of 1964 that bars racial discrimination in schools and
colleges that receive federal money.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Electric Chair
</P>
<P>
   Without explanation, the court lifted the stay of execution it
had granted on Feb. 4 to an Alabama death row inmate, Robert L.
Tarver Jr., who challenged the state's use of the electric chair as
cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The court had granted the stay, hours before Tarver's scheduled
execution, in order to decide whether to hear his case on the
merits. Earlier this term, the court agreed to hear, and then
dismissed, a challenge to Florida's use of the electric chair after
the state passed a new law to make lethal injection the preferred
method of execution. Similar legislation is moving through the
Alabama Legislature but has not yet passed either house.
</P>
<P>
   Four justices _ John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer _ voted to hear the Alabama inmate's
case. Ordinary, four votes are all that are required for the court
to hear a case. But Tarver's case was procedurally unusual, seeking
a writ of habeas corpus directly from the Supreme Court rather than
as an appeal from a lower court. Although the Supreme Court has not
disclosed its internal rules for acting on habeas corpus petitions,
and did not do so Tuesday, the court evidently regards five votes
rather than four as necessary to grant such a petition. The case
was In re Tarver, No. 99-8044.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
