<SLUG> BC-L.A.-POLICE-240&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SLAP AT LAPD, OFFICERS' UNION SEEKS INDEPENDENT PROBE OF
BRUTALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In an extraordinary step that reflected the
plummeting public confidence in the Los Angeles Police department
over a growing corruption scandal, the union representing police
officers undercut the department's chief Tuesday and demanded an
independent investigation of the growing evidence of police
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   The union noted that, since its creation in 1925, it had never
advocated the creation of an outside body to investigate the
department. But it said such a step was needed now because the
scandal had so tainted the department, as reports emerge that
corrupt officers framed perhaps several hundred people, and in at
least two instances shot unarmed suspects and then planted guns on
them.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was also a political shot at the chief of
police, Bernard C. Parks, who has staunchly fought any outside
interference but is now clearly losing the confidence of his
uniformed officers, some of whom have said they fear the chief may
make some of the wrongdoers scapegoats and not thoroughly
investigate the department's senior officers.
</P>
<P>
   The police department has established an internal Board of
Inquiry, composed of top officers, that has been investigating the
scandal for several months separately from the criminal
investigation at the district attorney's office. The Board of
Inquiry is expected to deliver its report to the police commission,
a civilian oversight body, on March 1.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Parks did not comment on the announcement and Commander David
Kalish, the department spokesman, did not return calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents a great leap forward for the police union and
it's also the first step in reinforcing to the public that
restoring the credibility of the police department is our single
biggest priority,'' said Ted Hunt, the president of the Los Angeles
Police Protective League, which represents about 9,500 officers.
</P>
<P>
   The call for an investigation outside the board of inquiry's was
also considered Tuesday by the City Council. Joel Wachs, a city
councilman who is also running for mayor, proposed that the city
consider such a body to ensure that the police brutality was being
thoroughly investigated, particularly accusations of culpability by
the department's top officers.
</P>
<P>
   His motion was voted down, 8-6, but several other members of the
council said that over the past week a more militant mood had
developed, as confidence in the police chief tumbled and concern
grew over the extent of the brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could this go on so long and be so bad and nobody at the
top knew about it?'' asked Wachs in an interview. ``It just doesn't
pass the smell test to do something from within.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the scandal ``a moral and a financial crisis,'' and
said that what had sobered politicians and the public were the
reports that the civil suits by those unjustly imprisoned could
cost the city $200 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   The new mood marks a major shift, since politicians, especially
the mayor, had generally watched quietly since the first reports of
corruption emerged last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those whose views are evolving, particularly in the
last week or so,'' said Laura Chick, a member of the City Council
who voted for Wachs' motion. She said she now believes that
restoring public confidence in the tarnished police department
cannot be achieved by the police commission alone.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal began last September when a former officer, Rafael
Perez, had agreed to disclose evidence of the corruption in return
for a lighter sentence in a case in which he admitted to stealing
about 8 pounds of cocaine from the department. He told how the
police had framed scores of innocent people, many of them gang
members, lied in court and, in at least two instances, shot unarmed
gang members, one of them while he was handcuffed, and then had
them framed on trumped-up charges.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the scandal was focused on his old inner-city
station, the Rampart Division, but evidence is emerging that the
brutality may have been more widespread.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 criminal cases have been overturned so far, with
the police saying that at least 99 have been tainted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
