testified that a North Hollywood bank robber wanted to bleed to
death, and his efforts to get medical aid came too late. But former
Detective James Vojtecky said he wanted Emil Matasareanu to live so
he ``could get him in court.'' By Jesse Hiestand.
</P>
<P>
   (Will run on the ``a'' national and ``n'' state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-TIGHTEN (Los Angeles) _ With cockroach-ridden restaurants
receiving A grades, Los Angeles County public health officials said
they are pushing to tighten requirements so critical food-safety
violations count for more during inspections. The recommendation
came after the county restaurant trade group noticed that
establishments with gross violations were receiving A grades, while
others with minor, structural problems got Bs and Cs. By Troy
Anderson. (Will run on the ``n'' state news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ABSENT-VOTE (Los Angeles) _ With all signs pointing to
California's March 7 presidential primary as a key battleground,
all sides are pouring on the effort to get out the vote, including
absentee ballots to make sure their supporters don't get
sidetracked on election day. We're checking on the volume of
absentee ballot requests in Los Angeles County, and whether a
record might be set in this election. By Lee Condon. (Will run on
the ``a'' national and ``n'' state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LOCA-EXPO (Los Angeles) _ Locations Expo at the L.A. Convention
Center this weekend will feature a protest over runaway production
in addition to pitches from film commissions from other countries
like Canada. L.A.'s own entertainment
</P>
<P>
   Industry Development Corp. will snub the event again, too.
</P>
<P>
   The group's president calls it ``a glorified junket for film
commissioners.'' By Marla Matzer Rose. (Will run on the ``f''
financial news files.)
</P>
<P>
   THQFOLO-GAME (Calabasas, Calif.) _ On the eve of its earnings
report, Calabasas-based video game maker THQ is besieged with
lawsuits. By Jason Cohen. (Will run on the ``f'' financial news
files.)
</P>
