<SLUG> BC-BOX-RUIZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUIZ-HOLYFIELD IS SET FOR MAY 27 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ May 27 is the time. Las Vegas is the place. The only
question is, will it be John Ruiz's time when he's in that place?
</P>
<P>
   That's because Don King said Tuesday he has finalized a deal for
Ruiz to fight Evander Holyfield at Caesars Palace for either a
vacant World Boxing Association title or the right to be considered
the true No. 1 contender in heavyweight boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz was recently elevated to the No. 1 spot by the WBA, making
him the top contender both in that organization and the World
Boxing Council. Both Holyfield and undisputed heavyweight champion
Lennox Lewis had agreed prior to their rematch to fight the WBA's
leading contender or its highest-rated available opponent if then
top-rated Henry Akinwande was unavailable. With Akinwande dropping
to No. 4 because of inactivity due to health problems, Ruiz was
elevated, and King now will push the WBA to declare its title
vacant because of Lewis's decision to fight Michael Grant April 29
instead of Ruiz despite the prior agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the rematch, both fighters agreed the winner was to
fight Akinwande or the leading available contender,'' King said
while watching welterweight champion Felix Trinidad work out at the
Church Street gym in lower Manhattan Tuesday. ``Now they come up
with some b.s. not to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't be selective with the rules when they become
inconvenient. John Ruiz has been put where he rightfully belongs.
He deserves the opportunity to fight for the WBA title. Both guys
agreed to fight the leading contender with no intervening bouts. If
they don't do it, they're working with two sets of rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Failing that, however, King said he would still stage
Ruiz-Holyfield as a 12-round fight in a so-called title eliminator
to make one the undisputed contender. Although International Boxing
Federation No. 1 David Tua might dispute that pronouncement, King
did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the WBA refuses, I don't care,'' King said. ``We fight them
12 rounds anyway. But just because you're the undisputed champion,
it doesn't give you the right to abuse the law. The undisputed
champion should uphold the law. You can't destroy the rules so a
Boston kid can't get his opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the fight seems assured, and the Chelsea, Mass.,
heavyweight who has seldom gotten his due in local circles is
finally on the cusp of boxing's big reward _ the million dollar
payday and a shot at the big-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bringing big-time boxing back to Caesars Palace,'' King
said. ``We're going to do that with Felix Trinidad on March 5 (vs.
WBA super welterweight champion David Reid) and we're doing it with
Johnny Ruiz on May 27.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
