<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: MEDICAL REPORT CHALLENGED
</P>
<P>
   Belgium, France, Switzerland and Spain registered formal
challenges to a British report suggesting that Gen. Augusto
Pinochet, 84, is medically unfit for extradition to Spain to stand
trial on torture charges. Jack Straw, the home secretary, promised
a response ``as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: CAR BOMB KILLS 2
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Buesa, a leader of the opposition Socialist Party, and
his bodyguard died when a car bomb exploded as they walked in the
Basque regional capital of Vitoria. The government blamed the
Basque separatist group ETA, and Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar
vowed to resist the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: TRIAL ON TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   Several media companies, including the BBC, CNN, ABC and CBS,
asked a Scottish court to allow them to televise the trial of two
Libyan men accused of blowing up Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie,
Scotland, in 1988. Although English law bans cameras from the
courtroom, Scottish law allows trials to be broadcast after they
are over.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: CLASHES IN KURDISH REGION
</P>
<P>
   Police forces battled demonstrators in the Kurdish city of
Diyarbakir who were protesting the arrest of three Kurdish mayors
charged with aiding Kurdish terrorists. The clash reflects the
sudden worsening of relations between Kurdish politicians and the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: GENERAL FACES QUESTIONING
</P>
<P>
   Parliament plans to question Gen. Wiranto about the killings and
destruction in East Timor last year. The general was suspended from
his cabinet post this month so that he could concentrate on
investigations into the atrocities and on a criminal investigation
by the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: GUN LAW CHALLENGED
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court heard a challenge to a law that would require
all Canadians to obtain licenses by the end of the year and
register all their guns by the end of 2001. The challenge,
initiated by six provinces, asserts that the federal government is
invading their right to regulate private property. Since the new
law went into effect 15 months ago, roughly 5 percent of Canada's
estimated 3 million gun owners have applied for licenses. A ruling
is expected this spring.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: SUSPECTED KIDNAPPER HELD
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities arrested Nicolas Caletri Lopez, 44, whom
they described as one of Mexico's most prolific kidnappers, and
said they were seeking to identify government officials who may
have protected him. Authorities attributed the abduction of at
least seven industrialists to Caletri.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SECURITY SPENDING SLASHED
</P>
<P>
   Israel cut its budget for security for the 170,000 Jewish
settlers in the West Bank and Gaza, slashing such funding from
$34.5 million to $6.2 million in line with overall cuts in the
Defense Ministry budget, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: WITHDRAWAL FROM LEBANON
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Giora Eiland, the Israeli army's chief of operations,
told reporters that he expected Israeli troops to leave Lebanon by
year's end, but expressed doubt about Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
July 7 deadline for a withdrawal. The July date is based on the
uncertain prospects for a peace pact with Syria, he said, adding
that without such an agreement there could still be ``some
formula'' for a withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA: U.N. SEEKS REVERSAL
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. war crimes prosecutor argued for the reversal of a
decision that could free a top suspect in the 1994 genocide that
took the lives of at least 500,000 ethnic Tutsi and moderate Hutu
in Rwanda. The prosecutor, Carla Del Ponte, said new evidence
proves that it was not the fault of prosecutors that the suspect,
Jean-Bosco Barayagwiza, a former Hutu government official, was not
charged for the crimes in a timely manner. But Barayagwiza's
lawyers said that the evidence was not new and that Barayagwiza
should be released, as ordered by an appeals court late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: MUGABE FACES SUIT
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled that human rights lawyers may sue
President Robert Mugabe to force him to release the findings of two
inquiries into alleged atrocities by troops trying to stop a
rebellion in Matabeleland in the 1980s. Mugabe commissioned the
inquiries but the results have never been made public.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: SUBPOENAS WITHDRAWN
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to pressure from the media, the Human Rights Commission
has agreed to invite _ not subpoena _ dozens of editors and news
directors to defend themselves against charges of racism. The panel
agreed to withdraw its subpoenas provided that the news
organizations agreed to participate in the hearings on racism in
the media, which are scheduled for next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
