<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES REJECT NEWEST CHINA THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Taiwan responded defiantly to China's latest threat
to invade, with Taiwan's top presidential candidates declaring
Tuesday they would not be bullied by Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, meanwhile _ eager to avert a military
confrontation that would destabilize Asia and almost certainly rope
in the United States _ also chided China for its belligerent
statement, which raised tensions three weeks before Taiwanese
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The latest dustup could alter the course of reunification talks
with Beijing and the prospects for a stable regional environment
for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   China, after its absorption of Hong Kong in 1997 and Macao in
December, is determined to speed up talks about unifying Taiwan
with China.
</P>
<P>
   The US government recognizes Beijing as the only ``one China,''
and wants to protect its delicate relations with the communist
leadership and promote trade with China _ while at the same time
defending its longtime friends in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reject any use of force or any threat of force in this
situation,'' Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart said in Washington.
``We have repeated, I think, in both actions and words that we view
any threat to Taiwan with grave concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has considered Taiwan a renegade province ever since the
Nationalist Party retreated to the island and set up a government
in exile following the 1949 civil war. China has long threatened
war if the island declares independence or if a third country
intervenes, but Monday was the first time it threatened attack over
delays in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan says it favors eventual reunification, but only when
China is a democratic, capitalist nation. Until then, Taiwan's
leaders say the two should be regarded as separate states.
</P>
<P>
   When Taiwan held its first presidential elections in 1996 _ a
move that underscored the island's de facto independence _ an
infuriated China conducted war games and fired two nuclear-capable
missiles across the 100-mile-wide Taiwan Strait to intimidate
voters from supporting independence-minded candidates. Washington
sent two aircraft carriers and other battleships to nearby waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will remember that in 1996 we responded appropriately to
what was viewed as a threat,'' Lockhart told reporters. ``That
should give you some indication of how we view this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Beijing has not resorted to military muscle-flexing,
but some Taiwan analysts say the latest rhetoric from China's
cabinet could be just as damaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a paper missile,'' said Andrew Nien-dzu Yang,
secretary-general of the Chinese Council of Advanced Policy Studies
in Taipei. ``Beijing wants to send a very strong message to the
international community that Taiwan is part of China.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Hong Kong Tuesday, Yang said the panic in
Taiwan over the 1996 missile tests subsided after a few weeks,
while this ``well-calcuated policy of hard-line approach could be
sustained for much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Yang said China's military is ``sharpening their
knives and at the same time, updating missile systems ... China
wants to show that the next time (the United States) wants to come
to Taiwan's rescue, it won't be so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Chao Chien-min, of the Sun Yat-sen Graduate Institute for Social
Sciences and Humanities at National Chengchi University in Taipei,
agreed the message was directed as much at the US as at Taiwan.
``Beijing is trying to circumvent Taiwan and negotiate with
Washington directly. The white paper was meant for Washington's
ears, and probably for (China's) own people's ears...to appease
hard-liners in Beijing.''
</P>
<P>
   Chao also warned that the white paper, compared to earlier
policy statements from Beijing, ``abandoned good will. In the past,
maybe there was a group'' of leaders who were ``softer'' on Taiwan,
but apparently not now.
</P>
<P>
   China this month sailed its newly-purchased Russian destroyer
through the Taiwan Strait, and Chinese President Jiang Zemin last
weekend toured military bases in southern China that would be key
in any invasion of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's government, meanwhile, Tuesday accused Beijing of
stalling unification talks itself by insisting that Taiwan is not a
sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1949, the two sides of the Taiwan Strait have been under
separate rule, neither subordinate to the other,'' said Lin
Chong-pin, of Taiwan's Mainland Affairs Council. ``The Chinese
Communists' continued denial of the existence of (Taiwan's
government) can only bring more trouble to cross-strait relations
and deepen tension.''
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's top presidential contenders _ who had all proposed
plans to improve ties with China _ reacted Tuesday by distancing
themselves from Beijing and denouncing the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not go to China to negotiate terms for our
surrender,'' declared independent candidate James Soong, a former
Nationalist leader. ``We will not be intimidated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
