<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RILEY-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION SECRETARY PROPOSES TEACHERS WORK YEAR-ROUND TO BUILD PAY,
STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JODI WILGOREN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying public schools are plagued by ``an old agrarian schedule,
an outdated factory model and an antiquated wage system,''
Education Secretary Richard W. Riley proposed Tuesday that teachers
work year-round to boost their pay and their status.
</P>
<P>
   In his seventh annual address on the state of American
education, Riley also called for a review of the standards movement
that has swept the nation over the past decade, suggesting that
states use a range of assessments rather than a single
multiple-choice test, and that high achievement goals required for
promotion or graduation be phased in slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers need extra time for professional development to master
the ambitious new standards and integrate technology into the
curriculum, Riley said in proposing the extended calendar. He said
he would leave it up to school districts and states to decide
whether students should spend additional days in class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never really improve American education until we
elevate the teaching profession and come to grips with the issue of
teacher compensation,'' Riley told a crowd of 1,500, mostly adults
in suits, packed into a high school gymnasium in Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that experienced teachers with master's degrees earn an
average of $32,000 a year less than their counterparts in other
fields, he called for a ``dramatic overhaul of how we recruit,
prepare, induct and retain good teachers,'' adding that, ``With
knowledge all around us, available anytime and anywhere, the role
of the teacher is going to be fundamentally transformed in the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   In an hour-long speech that touched on many policies outside his
purview, from paid maternity leave to gun control, the secretary
named the persistent achievement gap between white and minority
students as one of the nation's profound problems, and worried that
a ``growing digital divide'' is widening the gulf. He renewed his
call for universal preschool, urging parents to read daily to their
babies. He reiterated his position that vouchers, publicly funded
coupons that students can take to private schools, ``are simply a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   His boldest proposal, to extend teachers' calendars, was hailed
by the nation's two teachers unions as a long overdue remedy for
two of their chief complaints _ low salaries and lack of time for
professional development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demands are such that we need more time than you can fit
in the normal school year,'' said Donna Fowler, a spokeswoman for
the American Federation of Teachers. Asked whether it might deter
people attracted by teaching's schedule, Fowler said many teachers
take second jobs because they cannot afford summers off. ``I'm sure
they would rather spend that time doing what they do during the
year and getting paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley's comments on standards were more vague. He declared
himself a supporter of high-stakes tests, yet said states should
``incorporate multiple ways of measuring learning,'' including
portfolios of student work. He said it is ``far better to ratchet
up standards a step at a time than to try to make one huge leap all
at once.'' He added that ``promotion standards must be phased in
sensibly, not rushed,'' a nod to the backlash against the new
emphasis on testing in several states where hundreds of thousands
of students are facing failure.
</P>
<P>
   Robert B. Schwartz, president of Achieve, a nonprofit group
monitoring the standards movement, said it is difficult to quibble
with the suggestion for review, but that the 50 states cannot all
be helped with the same remedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``While on the one hand you may have places that seem to be
marching rapidly to the edge of the cliff at breakneck speed,
you've got other places that are proceeding pretty carefully, and
other places that have barely started,'' he said. ``It's hard to
make a general statement that everybody needs to stop where they
are and have a mid-course correction.''
</P>
<P>
   Chester E. Finn Jr., a leading conservative on education, said
Riley ``would have done standards-based reform more good if he had
advised state officials to be steadfast and resolute and to
persevere and not be deterred by the forces of resistance to
accountability and standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, one of three Clinton Cabinet members to have survived
from the first days of the administration, initiated the annual
education speech. Tuesday, he was welcomed to Souther High School
by a chorus of teen-agers in glittery silver vests singing, ``I
believe I can fly,'' but most students watched the speech on
television from their classrooms, as the gym was filled with
guests.
</P>
<P>
   Each year at his speech, Riley has held up a photograph of one
of his newly born grandchildren, effectively dedicating his speech
to students of the future. The tradition remained unbroken, thanks
to the birth this weekend in Sacramento, Calif., of William Daniel
Riley, who weighed 8 pounds, 9 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
