<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-AMERICAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALAND ON A ROMP _ AGAINST A FASTER BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ When the Italian team sailed Luna Rossa
into the middle of an America's Cup nightmare Monday, there was an
unavoidable sense that New Zealand was on a romp.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just a step ahead in every department,'' said Peter
Gilmour, the Australian who skippered the Nippon Challenge for
Japan. ``From their design to the techniques they have worked out
for sailing their yacht, the Kiwis are on a new standard.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians may indeed be in full retreat. Or, after they
licked their many wounds on the second layday Tuesday, perhaps they
will come out fighting as they did against AmericaOne to take the
Louis Vuitton Cup from Paul Cayard.
</P>
<P>
   There is little empirical evidence that New Zealand is a faster
boat than Luna Rossa.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes after a slam-dunk start by skipper Russell Coutts
in Race 2, one that stuffed Prada back 18 seconds off the line,
Italy skipper Francesco de Angelis had Luna Rossa perking along on
the first beat and closing the distance. And that was with a
plastic bag hanging on the keel, creating troublesome drag and
attendant problems.
</P>
<P>
   On the third leg, after smoothing out the boat-handling horrors,
Prada was cooking again, and in fact sailed a faster leg than New
Zealand by an average speed of 9.5 to 9.2 knots _ a huge
difference, though the two boats had such separation they could
have been sailing in different wind.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with a 2-0 lead in the best-of-nine finals, Team New
Zealand is creating the impression that it is the varsity
scrimmaging the JVs. Several challengers for the 2003 Cup have
already called New Zealand authorities to reserve dock space along
Viaduct Basin.
</P>
<P>
   If NZL 60 is a breakthrough boat, it is not because of any one
design feature, said Gilmour, but ``a whole lot of details outside
the box.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime yacht designer David Pedrick, who has been analyzing
the boats here, agreed. NZL 60 certainly looks different, because
of its ``spoon'' bow. Rather than the long fine entry into the
water that Luna Rossa has, NZL 60's bow angles down into a chunky
chin that looks in profile like the front of a barge.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be pretty, but many designers agree with Pedrick that
the ``knuckle bow'' is just one innovation that translates into
boatspeed.
</P>
<P>
   The bow has the trademark of its designer, Laurie Davidson, who
is known to use the design to gain waterline length without paying
the measurement price. In fact, as measured, NZL 60 has at least 1
foot more effective sailing length than did NZL 32, the Kiwi Cup
winner of 1995. This is enough to account for significant
differences around an 18-mile course, said Pedrick.
</P>
<P>
   The slightest speed advantage becomes magnified, not necessarily
in straight-line drag races, but in allowing match-racers to gain
controlling positions.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, New Zealand's chief designer last time was Doug
Peterson, who was hired to design Prada's Luna Rossa, along with
German Frers and his son, Mani.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the ``knuckle'' bow, the Kiwi boat also has
shallow stern overhangs and several anti-drag measures. For
example, when it occurred to someone that on upwind legs, the
topmast backstay _ the steel rod that holds the mast up against
sail pressure downwind _ was simply hanging limp, creating some
drag, the Kiwis decided to detach it and drop it on deck.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gilmour, Japanese analysts ran computer tests and
found the dropped backstay to be a factor of 4 kilograms of drag in
a total 350 kilograms of total drag created by these rigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real percentage,'' said Gilmour.
</P>
<P>
   With these innovations, and the ``millennium rig'' _ a stiff
mast given superior bend control by three sets of stays rather than
five _ the Kiwis have broken through into what Gilmour calls
``tomorrowland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, everyone has just caught up with where the Kiwis
were in '95,'' said Gilmour. ``So by the next Cup, if all we've
done is catch up to where the Kiwis are now, it won't be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kiwis look like they've raised the design game in several
ways. We're all chasing this little isolated country out here in
the Pacific.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
