<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5027 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SLAVERY-SEX-HNS &LR;      02-22 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVERY-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SMUGGLING FOR PROSTITUTION IS CALLED `SLAVERY' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A million women and girls a year are smuggled
across international borders and forced into prostitution, the
State Department told a Senate subcommittee Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, about 50,000 enter the United States annually from
Asia, Latin America and Eastern Europe, said Frank Loy,
undersecretary of state for global affairs. Most of the females are
lured by false promises of legitimate work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Loy and other officials said gangs of smugglers linked to
organized crime keep the girls and women in their control through
beatings, rape, psychological intimidation, confiscation of
passports and threats to relatives back home. Often the victims
contract sexually transmitted diseases including HIV, the virus
that causes AIDS, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Such exploitation represents ``one of the most egregious human
rights abuses right now,'' Loy declared. ``It is slavery pure and
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Lederer, director of the smuggler-monitoring Protection
Project at Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government, said
the traffickers seem to operate with impunity in such nations as
India, Thailand, Brazil and the former Soviet republics of Ukraine
and Moldova.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kansas, chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations subcommittee on Near Eastern and South Asian Affairs,
said of the trafficking: ``This is one of the most shocking and
rampant human rights abuses worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman who called herself Inez from Veracruz, Mexico, testified
about being trapped for several months in a prostitution ring. She
wore sunglasses and a scarf around her head to disguise her
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   She told the senators that in 1997, when she was a lemon
harvester in Veracruz, a friend told her about an opportunity to
work in a U.S. restaurant for good pay. Inez said she jumped at the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   A smuggling gang spirited her across the border in Brownsville,
Texas, took her to Houston and from there transported her to a
trailer in Avon Park, Fla., which turned out to be a brothel.
</P>
<P>
   There she was told she had accumulated a $2,500 debt for
transportation to the United States and that she would have to pay
it off by selling her body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was horrified,'' Inez said. ``I asked my friend what this
was all about. She said she had already worked in the brothels, and
it did me no good to complain.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Inez said, she plunged into the terrifying world of forced
prostitution. Condoms with torn wrappers were sent back to the
smugglers and served as tickets for $25 deductions from the
smuggling debt.
</P>
<P>
   Inez and the other women and girls _ some as young as 14 _
worked six days a week, 12 hours a day, and were ferried from place
to place, she said. Beatings and rapes by the smugglers were
commonplace. Those who became pregnant were forced to get
abortions, with the abortion fee added to the smuggling debt, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   After a few months police and FBI and Immigration and
Naturalization Service agents raided the brothel. Inez said that
after spending several more months in a detention center, she was
released to a women's domestic violence center where she received
comprehensive gynecological examinations and mental health
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony helped put several of the smuggling crew in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``No woman or child would want to be a sex slave and endure the
evil that I have gone through,'' Inez told the Senate panel.
``Please help us. Please do not let this happen to anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate and House are considering legislation to beef up
criminal penalties for prostitute-smuggling gangs and to provide
social services and visas for immigrant females forced into
prostitution. The legislation would also allow the administration
to impose sanctions against foreign nations involved in
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version would authorize $86 million over two years
for the federal effort; the House would authorize $78 million.
</P>
<P>
   Loy said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright often brings the
issue up in talks with foreign ministers. He added that the United
States is promoting a plan to attach a measure forbidding such
trafficking to the United Nations Convention on Transnational
Organized Crime.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
