<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, Feb. 23. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead stories:
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-PRIMARIES (Detroit) _ Ledeall on Tuesday's Republican
primaries in Michigan, where the polls close at 8 p.m. EST, and
Arizona, with a poll-closing of 8 p.m. EST. By Richard L. Berke.
(We plan to move the story by 9:15 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   The stories run under a 4-column, 2-line hed.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1-7.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ASSESS (Detroit) _ A news analysis on the Republican
contest. By R.W. Apple Jr. (Scheduled to move by 10 p.m. ET in
``p'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis runs under a 3-column photo.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ With raised voices and
emotional appeals, lawyers for the four New York City police
officers charged with the murder of Amadou Diallo plead with jurors
to see his shooting as a tragic mistake brought on by Diallo's
actions. The lawyers' summations come after three weeks of a trial
that was, at times, racially charged. By Jane Fritsch. (Scheduled
to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT11,12.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Microsoft Corp. gets its last
chance in federal court to persuade the trial judge not to issue a
stinging antitrust verdict against the company. But the judge,
Thomas Penfield Jackson, gave Microsoft little comfort. At one
point in the final arguments, he dismissed a key Microsoft defense
by comparing the company to John D. Rockefeller's Standard Oil
monopoly. By Joel Brinkley and Steve Lohr. (Eds.: an early version
of this story has moved; the 1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move
by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-VOTE (Gadzhiyevo, Russia) _ On March 26, the day Russians
vote for a new president, the people of this city, whose population
is an official secret, will be engaged in a battle they feel far
more intensely than the lop-sided presidential contest that Acting
President Vladimir Putin is expected to win. The citizens of this
closed military city, which hides one of Russia's nuclear submarine
bases above the Arctic Circle, are staging an extraordinary civic
revolt. In a referendum on whether the fleet can put a nuclear
waste dump at the city limits, they are taking on the navy they
have long served. By Patrick E. Tyler. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m.
ET in ``i'' news file.) 2,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Washington) _ New assessments by NATO say that
Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, is stepping up his
campaign to interfere with U.N. peacekeeping in Kosovo. By Jane
Perlez. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   See also KOSOVO-MITROVICA, inside story.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DRUGS-PRESCHOOLERS (Undated) _ In a finding that medical
experts call ``troubling'' and ``very surprising,'' researchers
report that the number of preschoolers taking stimulants,
antidepressants and other psychiatric drugs rose dramatically from
1991 to 1995. By Erica Goode. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.) 1,300 words.
