<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KING-EXILE23-COX     02-22 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-EXILE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expatriate's pardon came down to the wire
 &HT;    By Colin Campbell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Preston King _ who's expected back in America today for
the first time in nearly nearly 40 years _ didn't know until the
last minute whether he would return home a free man or end up in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   After his eldest brother died Feb. 12, in Miami, King's
sister-in-law in Albany, Ga., Carol King, postponed the funeral so
King's lawyers in Washington could once again press the government
to let him fly from England, where he's a professor of political
theory, to attend the funeral in Albany without fear of being
arrested. King has been a fugitive since his 1961 conviction for
draft evasion.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and others in the administration were believed
to sympathize with King, since even the judge who sentenced him has
said that the case would never have come to trial if King _ an
educated young black man in Jim Crow Georgia _ hadn't demanded to
be addressed politely by his white draft board.
</P>
<P>
   King's hopes had been raised before _ only to be crushed by
apparent political questions at the White House about pardoning a
``draft dodger.''
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, with his lawyers in Washington still negotiating with
the government over the terms of his possible return, King had
grown so frustrated that he had determined to fly to Atlanta on
Wednesday no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've basically decided,'' the 63-year-old King said Monday,
``that I've got to come home for this funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   King had refused to risk imprisonment earlier by returning for
the funerals of his parents and three other brothers, but, now that
his 79-year-old brother Clennon W. King Jr. was dead, he had had
enough. ``It was Gordian-knot time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers had been discussing legal options as diverse as a
full presidential pardon, commutation of his sentence, or some
temporary deal whereby he'd be allowed to enter the country for the
funeral and then leave again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as you know,'' King said Sunday afternoon, 24 hours before
the pardon was issued, ``this has been going on for over a
generation, and its latest resuscitation has been going on for over
a year.''
</P>
<P>
   King decided he would take the last train to London on Monday
night and catch a Delta flight to Atlanta today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we must just go ahead,'' he said shortly before
leaving for the station. ``The whole question is, What are the
intentions of the American government? ... I'm going to try to get
a visa first thing in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if the U.S. Embassy in London looked him up, discovered
that he was a U.S. fugitive and refused to stamp a visa in his
Australian passport?
</P>
<P>
   ``They would look me up in their computers to clap me in
irons,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   But, King said, ``I got off the train about midnight, in
London.'' The train was an hour late, but a camera crew from NBC
News was waiting for him, looking serious. ``And then they said,
`You got a pardon!''' His reaction was numbness, and relief.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, instead of a visa, he picked up his new blue U.S.
passport, which expires Feb. 21, 2010. He was, officially, a
native-born citizen again. ``Isn't that wild?'' he said. King's
last U.S. passport expired in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The pardon ``was really unexpected,'' said his lawyer, Liz
Holtzman, by telephone from New York. King's formal petition for a
pardon was submitted _ seemingly with Clinton's blessing _ on Dec.
21. But weeks passed and nothing happened. ``I could see this was
an endless process,'' Holtzman said.
</P>
<P>
   When King's brother Clennon died earlier this month, King told
Holtzman almost despondently that he would never be allowed to
return for the funeral. ``I felt a kind of futility creeping over
me,'' King recalled. Holtzman left a message at the Justice
Department asking that King be allowed to return for the funeral,
if only for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   A government lawyer returned Holtzman's call and asked if
Clennon's funeral had happened. It hadn't yet. It was scheduled to
take place last Saturday. Holtzman and Carol King agreed to
postpone the funeral until this Thursday to give the government
more time. ``I could see that they were really trying,'' Holtzman
said. ``Somebody was moved by the fact of the funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtzman said: ``I give the president enormous credit. It took
courage _ it's not necessarily a risk-free pardon, but it's the
right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank him,'' King said of Clinton on the eve of his
departure for America, ``and I applaud him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
