<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HDEPOT-EARNINGS23-COX     02-22 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDEPOT-EARNINGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot's earnings take another step up
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot's profit continues to surge as consumers
spend more on remodeling and housing supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company said fourth-quarter earnings rose 38
percent to $578 million, or 25 cents a share, from $418 million, or
18 cents a share, in the year-ago period. Home Depot beat analysts'
expectations by a penny, according to a survey by First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 26 percent to $9.17 billion from $7.26 billion. The
company opened stores at a brisk pace and concentrated on
higher-ticket merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot customers continued to spend more on average for each
purchase. In the fourth quarter, the average transaction was
$46.61, against $44.46 a year ago. Some of the increase was caused
by price hikes in commodities such as lumber and building
materials, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're demonstrating to the customer the benefits of products
that are one step up in price,'' said analyst Doug Gordon at Banc
of America Securities, who rates the shares ``strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's stock closed Tuesday at $53.87 1/2, up 12 1/2
cents. The retailer's shares have fallen more than 20 percent this
year on concern that rising interest rates could curb consumer
spending and hurt profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Arthur Blank told analysts in a conference call
Tuesday that he was ``optimistic'' about housing growth trends.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Home Depot's long-term growth initiatives already have
paid off in recent earnings results, analysts said. For example,
the company is aggressively expanding its selection of decor,
flooring, appliances and other pricier goods. And it's adding
installation services for products such as roofing, water heaters
and siding. Those goods and services generally are more profitable
than Home Depot's commodity items, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Depot has put a lot of energy into notching up the
quality of its product assortment,'' analyst Ursula Moran at
Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. told Bloomberg News. She rates the stock
``outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, competitor Lowe's Cos. reported a 51 percent increase
in fiscal fourth-quarter profit. Lowe's also benefited from sales
of items with higher profit margins, such as kitchen cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot said its profit got a boost because it offered fewer
markdowns and got suppliers to bear more costs. Gross margin, which
measures the profit from each sale, widened to 31.9 percent from
30.3 percent a year earlier. Blank said he expects margins to
improve further this year.
</P>
<P>
   At stores open at least a year, sales rose 9 percent. The
retailer said it maintained ``same-store'' sales increases of 10
percent until the last two weeks of the quarter. Same-store sales
are a key indicator of a retailer's business because they exclude
sales from new and closed stores.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot operated 930 stores at the end of its fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   North Wilkesboro, N.C.-based Lowe's reported that sales at
stores open at least a year rose 6.2 percent. Same-store sales were
hurt by cold weather, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot anticipates comparable sales increases in the ``upper
end of the mid-single digits'' for the first quarter, said Marshall
Day, senior vice president of finance and accounting.
</P>
<P>
   For the year ended Jan. 30, Home Depot said sales rose 27
percent to $38.43 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A replay of the company's conference call with analysts is
available for five days at www.homedepot.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
