<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-ART-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE LAWYERS ASK JURY TO SEE DIALLO SLAYING AS TRAGIC ERROR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT11-12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JANE FRITSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With raised voices and emotional appeals, lawyers
for the four New York City police officers charged with the murder
of Amadou Diallo pleaded with jurors Tuesday to see his shooting as
a tragic mistake brought on by Diallo's actions.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Eric Warner, responded with an equally
impassioned argument. ``Amadou Diallo never had a chance,'' Warner
said. ``In the mind-set they had, that man was doomed from the
minute they saw him.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' summations came after three weeks of a trial that
was, at times, racially charged. The four officers, who are white,
fired 41 shots at Diallo, a black man who was standing, unarmed, in
the vestibule of his apartment building in the Bronx on Feb. 4,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   In their arguments Tuesday, the defense lawyers stressed the
state of mind of the officers, who they said shot Diallo out of
fear. They believed Diallo was pulling a gun out if his pocket and
intended to shoot them, the lawyers said. The officers, who
happened to be driving down the street where Diallo lived, said
they approached him because they thought he might have been a
rapist or a robber.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner argued that the officers thought the worst of Diallo
for no good reason and that their judgment was flawed from the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were willing to write him off on such flimsy
suspicions,'' Warner said. ``He was one of the people they were
supposed to protect,'' he added, but the officers ``took a dim view
of that block and everything went downhill from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury of four black women, two white women and six white men
is to begin deliberating Wednesday, after hearing instructions on
the law from Justice Joseph C. Teresi of the Supreme Court. The
officers could be convicted of second-degree murder, first-degree
manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide in relation to
Diallo, and reckless endangerment of bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants _ Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Richard Murphy
and Kenneth Boss _ all pleaded innocent to the two counts of
second-degree murder that each is charged with in the killing of
Diallo, a 22-year-old immigrant from Guinea. The first count is for
Diallo's death and the second for depraved indifference to human
life.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Much of the attention over the case has centered around the
issue of race and the violent circumstances of Diallo's death. The
four policemen fired 41 bullets at Diallo. Nineteen of those shots
hit the victim.
</P>
<P>
   The officers testified that at the time of the shooting, they
believed Diallo had a gun and was threatening them. It turned out
that Diallo was holding his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, who were members of the police department's Street
Crime Unit and were dressed in plainclothes, said they were on
patrol looking for a rape suspect and had gotten out of their car
to question Diallo because they thought his actions were
suspicious. They said Diallo did not follow their instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors argued that the officers acted hastily after
cornering Diallo, fired too many shots, and did not try to
determine whether Diallo was hearing impaired or could understand
English.
</P>
<P>
   Although the officers were charged with second-degree murder,
the judge ruled the jurors would be permitted to consider the
lesser charges of first- and second-degree manslaughter and
criminally negligent homicide in their deliberations. Minimum
penalties for convictions range from 15 years to life for
second-degree murder to probation for criminally negligent
homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi's instructions to the jury, which he outlined on Friday,
pleased the defense but left prosecutors disgruntled.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said his instructions would include presenting jurors
with two statutes from New York penal law that outline when the use
of deadly force is justified. One statute, Section 35.30, says that
a police officer is justified in using deadly force to defend
himself or herself or a third person if he or she is making an
arrest or preventing an escape from custody.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution argued that such a statute does not apply to the
four officers in the current trial because the policemen said that
they planned to question Diallo, not arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also said he would instruct jurors on Section 35.15,
which says any citizen may use deadly force if he or she
``reasonably believes'' the action is needed to defend against an
attack. Part of the statute also allows the use of deadly force if
a citizen believes another person is in the process of committing a
crime like rape or robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors tried to bar those parts of the statute. Carroll had
testified that he believed Diallo was either a robber or a rapist
when he and the other officers tried to question him.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi said he would also explain to the jurors a state law that
allows police officers to approach citizens and to question them.
The defense lawyers hoped that a reading of the law would make it
clear that the police officers had the authority to question
Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   The closing arguments Tuesday concluded an intense and highly
emotional phase of the trial in which witnesses and the police
officers recounted, sometimes in tears, the night of the shooting.
Carroll said that after discovering that Diallo was unarmed and had
only been clutching a wallet, he wept over the body and begged
Diallo to stay alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1954EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0329 </DOCNO>
