<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5035 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FOOTBALL-PLEA-KAN &LR;      02-22 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-PLEA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL PLAYER PLEADS GUILTY TO CHARGES INVOLVING STOLEN VEHICLE
SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With his guilty plea to a federal felony
Tuesday, Kansas City Chief Tamarick Vanover joined a long line of
cooperating witnesses in a drug probe that has stretched over 27
months and touched at least four states.
</P>
<P>
   Vanover, a wide receiver and kick returner, is the
highest-profile figure yet snared in an investigation that has led
to convictions against seven men in California and Missouri and
pending criminal charges against seven others.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded guilty to aiding and abetting the sale of a stolen
vehicle that had crossed state lines. Vanover appeared before U.S.
District Judge Gary A. Fenner and was released after he promised to
appear at future court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Vanover could face from four to 14 months in prison, according
to a preliminary estimate included in the plea agreement.
Prosecutors could ask the judge to sentence him to less than that
if they find his cooperation substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Following the court appearance, U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill
said the plea was a positive step.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has agreed to cooperate with an ongoing investigation by
the FBI and the Internal Revenue Service,'' Hill said. ``This is a
helpful development.''
</P>
<P>
   Such cooperation often involves extensive interviews with
federal agents, appearances before grand juries and, occasionally,
testimony at trials.
</P>
<P>
   Hill declined to discuss whether other Chiefs players had come
under scrutiny in the probe.
</P>
<P>
   After his plea, Vanover declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Michael T. Yonke, emphasized that Vanover is fully
cooperating with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tamarick understands what he has done is wrong and there is a
price to be paid for his actions,'' Yonke said. ``He is willing to
pay that price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tamarick is sorry for the embarrassment he has caused his
family and his employer. I am confident that this will be the last
involvement Tamarick Vanover will ever have with the criminal
justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanover acknowledged in court that he helped transport a stolen
Ford Expedition from Missouri to Florida in March 1999. For that,
Vanover later received a $10,000 check from a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the stolen sport utility vehicle first emerged
earlier this month, with the release of court records charging
Vanover's personal assistant, Gregory E. Burns, with federal
cocaine and marijuana violations. Burns has pleaded not guilty to
those charges.
</P>
<P>
   Court records linked Burns to a ``large-scale, organized and
structured'' cocaine smuggling operation based in Fresno, Calif.,
with ties to Missouri, Kansas and Tennessee. The conspiracy once
resulted in more than 200 pounds of cocaine being transported to
Kansas City every month, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Vanover came to federal authorities' attention when cooperating
witnesses identified him as an associate of Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Even with his guilty plea, Vanover will be allowed to travel to
play football. But Vanover's future with the Chiefs was uncertain
even before his legal problems surfaced recently.
</P>
<P>
   He remained under contract with the team as of Tuesday. He has a
$750,000 bonus due from the Chiefs on March 1 if he remains on the
roster. Should he be released before March 1, the Chiefs would
neither be responsible for the bonus nor Vanover's base salary of
$850,000.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued Tuesday by Bob Moore, the Chiefs public
relations director, did not suggest his role with the team would
change because of his guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``As is the case with any employer, we believe in the sanctity
of the legal system,'' Moore said. ``The legal system has run its
course in this matter. The issue has been addressed to the
requirements of the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
