<HEADER>
A5041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW23-COX     02-22 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tale of two markets
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a twofold message to investors in the stock
market's behavior, according to analysts: Technology is here to
stay, and the first half of 2000 will be more painful than the
second.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the message is based on the idea that a giant
shift is under way in the economy, which is reflected on Wall
Street by a move out of Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stocks and into
Nasdaq composite stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The second message is that the Federal Reserve's strategy of
raising interest rates to slow the economy is having little impact
on ``new economy'' stocks of the technology sector, while hurting
``old economy'' stocks. That threatens to deepen the correction in
blue chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which fell 295 points Friday
ahead of the three-day holiday weekend, recaptured some of that
loss in a late rally Tuesday, rising 0.8 percent. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 also benefited from bargain hunting to rise 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite, which traded at a record 4,548.92 on
Thursday, fell Friday and again Tuesday, although it too was rising
at the end of the trading day.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts saw no fundamental change in the trading pattern
and expect the Nasdaq to go on leading the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a market that wants to participate in the most dynamic
growth sector in my 40 years in the business,'' said Alfred
Goldman, strategist for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons.
</P>
<P>
   At Robinson-Humphrey in Atlanta, senior strategist Robert S.
Robbins increased the recommended portfolio weighting of technology
stocks to 42 percent from 38 percent of total stock holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth stocks in general and technology stocks in particular
remain the overwhelming stock market leaders short term and long
term, in our opinion,'' said Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Fed's strategy of raising interest rates to slow the
economy, analysts say it is having little impact on the technology
sector while hurting the blue chip sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed is raising rates and slowing the segment of the
economy that is already slowing,'' said Goldman. He explained that
technology companies do not borrow as much as traditional cyclical
and interest-sensitive firms included in the Dow and S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stocks that have been such powerful drivers of this market
have gotten tired,'' George Cohen, a principal at Cohen
Klingenstein &AMP; Marks, told Dow Jones News Service, referring to
blue chips. ``Whether this is the moment for a true correction or
not, I don't think anybody can say. But many of these stocks have
gotten stretched.''
</P>
<P>
   At Prudential Securities, technical analyst Ralph Acampora noted
that his morning conference calls with company offices have dealt
in the recent weeks with ``the split between the `old economy'
stocks and the `new economy' stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' he said, ``many of the suspicious `old
economy' stocks reside in the Dow average _ thus the Dow is apt to
do worse than some of the `new economy'-laden indices such as the
Russell 2000 and the Nasdaq composite.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Acampora, the market is oversold on a near-term
basis and due for a ``technical rally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the problem still remains: Is any rally from current
levels sustainable? We don't think so. Therefore, a retest of the
recent lows and even lower levels can be expected for the Dow,'' he
said. ``We leave the door wide open for the Dow to retest its
October 1999 low of 9,976.02.''
</P>
<P>
   But Acampora also said a setback of that size would be
``positive for the longer-term market'' since it would ``wash out
the excesses and set the stage for a longer-term upside move'' in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, yields on the 30-year Treasury bond continued to fall
as demand remains strong in the face of the government's promise to
reduce new debt in a period of budget surplus. The yield on Tuesday
fell to the lowest point in 3 1/2 months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
