<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-CORRECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRECTION IS OFFICIAL; DOW, NASDAQ INDEXES DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's official. The stocks that make up the Old Economy are in
the midst of a correction.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery is whether New Economy stocks will follow.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq index, which represents a spectrum of technology
companies, dipped 29.62 Tuesday, closing at 4382.12. It was an
insignificant second consecutive day's decline, a blip in an index
whose all-time high was achieved only last week.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dow Jones industrial index, despite a small rally
Tuesday, has tumbled 12 percent from a record of 11,722.9 on Jan.
14. A correction occurs when stocks decline 10 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The glare from the Nasdaq has truly masked the poor
performance of some very critical sectors of our old economy,''
said Ned Riley, chief investment strategist for State Street Global
Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which is composed of heavy-hitting stocks such as J.P.
Morgan and Wal-Mart Stores Inc., closed at 10,304.84, up 85.32
points (less than 1 percent). But the index did not leave
correction territory, which it entered on Friday during a 295-point
free fall that wiped out 2.8 percent of its value in a day.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's dive was a delayed reaction to hints by Federal
Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan that the wealth being generated by
a rising stock market is causing the economy to overheat.
Inflation, the Fed fears, may be ignited if it does not act
decisively.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, though, has faltered repeatedly since Fed interest-rate
hikes began in June. Some industries represented in the Dow _
including home building and some financial companies _ began to
reveal cracks months ago. Not even the addition of Microsoft Corp.
last year to the Dow's roster of 30 stocks was protection against
flagging investor sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Market strategists say the Dow is hurting because some investors
have become increasingly convinced that an economic slowdown is
coming _ and they want out before it occurs. The Nasdaq has not
been fazed by higher rates because there is plenty of equity
funding _ from venture capitalists and other stock investors _ and
less need for loans, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greenspan's diagnosis was pretty clear,'' said Allen Sinai,
president of Primark Decision Economics, a Boston consulting firm.
The economy is experiencing ``a boom with a bunch of imbalances,
and the only way the central bank can deal with it is to raise
interest rates. But implicit in his comments about rate hikes to
come is (that) some damage to growth has to happen,'' Sinai said.
The companies in the Dow ``are cyclically sensitive to Fed
tightening,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the chemicals giant E.I. DuPont DeNemours was
trading at about $65 a share at the end of last year. It closed at
54 3/16, up 2 1/12.
</P>
<P>
   Interest-rate-sensitive financial companies are suffering from
higher rates. American Express Co., at 173 a share last year,
closed at 139 1/8, up 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   And retail companies are being hit by anticipation of a softer
economy and slower sales. Wal-Mart Stores Inc., for example, closed
at 48 3/16 up 7/16, from levels of more than 69 a share in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvester Marquardt, research director for John Hancock Funds,
sees a ``significant change from the period of September to
November, when estimates of economic activity were still rising.''
</P>
<P>
   Although economists have not yet revised their growth forecasts,
``investors are acting as if the economy will slow.''
</P>
<P>
   The advent of an official correction has elicited a full range
of forecasts by experts about the future of the Dow _ and of the
red-hot Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point there has to be some profit-taking in these
things, but every time you throw in the towel, they go up,'' said a
trader at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``These stocks could turn up on a dime.
We have a little rational selling right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts for the Dow run the gamut, from fears a correction
could turn into a bear market to a belief that the index will again
recover, as it showed signs of doing Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's less there than meets the eye,'' said Larry Wachtel, a
market analyst for Prudential Securities Inc. in New York. The
simple reason the Dow came back Tuesday he said, was ``it got a
little oversold last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Primark predicted the markets will be up this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Minervini of Quantech Research Group in Connecticut is
not optimistic. He has put out memos to staff saying the Dow may
even be headed below 10,000 as cylical stocks suffer from the rate
increases and an outflow of money from Dow stocks to Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Minervini also said he believes the Nasdaq will not repeat its
86 percent rise of 1999 and could fall sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't count on the Nasdaq holding up this well forever,''
he said. With the Dow off so much, ``We think the Nasdaq is going
to play some catch-up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
