<HEADER>
A5043 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-BIGDIG-BOS &LR;      02-22 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BIGDIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX GROUP SAYS `BIG DIG' SHORTFALL SHORT BY $1B 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL REZENDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A respected fiscal watchdog group delivered bad news
Tuesday to officials struggling to come up with $1.4 billion to
cover a ``Big Dig'' cost overrun: you need another billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Taxpayers Foundation warned that the Central
Artery project, now pegged at $12.2 billion, could climb even
higher.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, a business-backed independent group, recommended
state officials agree to a plan to generate $2.5 billion. The group
suggested the state consider turning Interstate 93 into a toll
road, re-imposing fees on car registration, tapping this year's
budget surplus, and dedicating a portion of the gas tax to help
finance the project.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Widmer, president of the group, said it is essential the
state build in a cushion to guard against future funding shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems we have now is that we've had no
contingency plans and no margin for error,'' Widmer said. ``If
three years ago we'd put a contingency plan in place that dealt
with the inevitable cost overruns, things would be a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation by the MTF could complicate an already
challenging effort under way on Beacon Hill to come up with money
to solve the Big Dig cost crisis. It drew a frosty reaction from
Cellucci, who stood by Massachusetts Turnpike Authority's estimated
$1.4 billion cost overrun on the $12.2 billion project as a ``worst
case scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran said legislators may
embrace a plan that would prepare now for cost overruns beyond the
$12.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to go about this by coming up with piecemeal
suggestions every six months,'' Finneran said. ``To come back in
another year to the taxpayers and motorists of Massachusetts and
say, `Oops, we missed it in the year 2000, this time we think we're
closer to the mark,' that doesn't add any credibility to the
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran said MTF is known for its ``credible and responsible
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the foundation's suggestion that drivers traveling on
Interstate 93 pay tolls would likely be a tough sell politically.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and the Legislature are under intense pressure to
devise a plan to find a way to cover the $1.4 billion overrun by
March 15. US Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater has threatened
to cut off future federal funds if the state fails to put forth a
credible plan.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven auditors from the Federal Highway Administration are
expected to arrive in Boston Thursday to examine the progress of
the project, scrutinize contract increases and determine whether
$12.2 billion is a realistic final price tag.
</P>
<P>
   They are expected to remain here for two weeks. The team is
expected to include Highway Administrator Ken Wykle, who will
return to Washington after a day; Deputy Highway Administrator
Walter Sutton, and representatives from the office of the Inspector
General of the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The audit was spurred by Turnpike Authority Chairman James J.
Kerasiotes' admission earlier this month that the cost of the Big
Dig would soar by $1.4 billion, despite earlier assurances that the
project was proceding ``on time and budget.'' Kerasiotes has been
criticizing for failing to tell the public last year _ when the
cost increases were discovered _ that the project could not be
completed for $10.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Widmer said because the state is enjoying strong
revenues and a robust economy now, it would be prudent to develop a
plan that could cover more than the $1.4 billion gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a manageable problem now,'' Widmer said, ``but if
we're faced with other problems like this two years from now in the
middle of an economic recession it becomes a crisis. Let's deal
with the problem now while we have the resources to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Widmer said the surplus for this fiscal year, expected to bet
between $200 million and $600 million, could be applied to the Big
Dig. In addition, he said, the state could borrow about $2 billion
by issuing bonds, then repay them with revenue from four separate
sources.
</P>
<P>
   The sources, Widmer said, could include 4 cents of the existing
21-cent state gasoline tax, which would raise $120 million
annually; the restoration of recently elminated auto registration
fees, raising $55 million; maintaining driver's license fees, as
Cellucci has proposed; raising $45 million; and new tolls directed
at drivers north and south of Boston, raising $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit of agreeing to the larger sum, Widmer said, is
that local officials would be assured that other transportation
projects could proceed without the Big Dig interfering with their
projects or siphoning off funds they are anticipating.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci worried that pushing up the price tag to cover
additional, unforeseen costs might be an invitation to project
managers to spend more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not put more money on the table so that the people who
are building this thing can find other ways to spend it,'' Cellucci
said. ``Let's not try to create something that's not going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran, for his part, said he isn't prepared to say how much
state officials should be prepared to raise to cover Artery cost
overruns.
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that some artery officials, including the top
management consultant overseeing the project, have said overruns
could exceed the current $1.4 billion gap.
</P>
<P>
   He also said legislative leaders, including Senate President
Thomas F. Birmingham, should be willing to consider an array of
revenue sources, including the gas tax, tolls, and auto
registration and license fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll consider anything at this point,'' Finneran said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
