A5044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SEC-HOOPS23-COX     02-22 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-HOOPS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The race to the SEC title
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Winning the SEC regular-season championship guarantees
a team absolutely nothing in basketball's big picture _ the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But the title isn't meaningless to Kentucky coach Tubby Smith,
whose team is one of six still with a chance with two weeks left in
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the SEC championship and before the season started,
that was everyone's goal,'' said Smith, whose Wildcats (19-7, 9-3
SEC) play at Tennessee (21-4, 9-3) tonight in one of the key games
down the stretch. ``Winning the conference is always special. As
tough as the league has been this year, it will mean even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the SEC is split into divisions, the team with the
best record in either division is declared the regular-season
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose going to win this thing? It's anybody's guess,'' said
Florida coach Billy Donovan, whose team plays tonight at Georgia.
``But if I had to guess, it would be the team with the easiest road
schedule. It's been really tough to win on the road this season.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at the six SEC teams still in the race for the title, as
the end of the regular season draws near:
</P>
<P>
   _ Auburn: The Tigers appeared to be in trouble after an 83-68
loss at LSU on Feb. 9, but followed it up with an impressive 86-80
win at Vanderbilt. Beginning with Tuesday night's game at Alabama,
Auburn will play three of its last four games on the road. Games at
Florida on Sunday and at home next Wednesday with LSU will be
difficult. ``We're just going to try to be the same, no matter what
the circumstances are,'' coach Cliff Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida: The Gators, who lost a tough one in overtime (76-73)
at Tennessee on Feb. 12, must win tonight at Georgia and then get
ready for Sunday's nationally televised game with Auburn in
Gainesville. Depending on what happens this week, the March 4 trip
to Kentucky for the last regular-season game could loom large.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kentucky: After consecutive road losses at Florida (90-73) and
LSU (70-57), the Wildcats looked like they would sag down the
stretch. But if the Wildcats can win tonight in Thompson-Boling
Arena, they could be in position to win the championship when they
host Florida on Feb. 4. ``We know we've got our work cut out for us
because Tennessee is a tough place to play,'' Smith said. ``But I
still think we have a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LSU: The Tigers have been the surprise team of the SEC. They
have won eight of their last nine, including a pair of victories
over Auburn and Kentucky. Three of LSU's final four games are
against noncontenders _ South Carolina, Mississippi State and Ole
Miss. The other, a March 1 trip to Auburn, could be critical.
``When you look at their schedule, I like their chances a lot,''
Alabama coach Mark Gottfried said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tennessee: Coach Jerry Green has made no secret of the fact
that he was not happy with his team's performance in Saturday's
85-72 loss at Vanderbilt. Green said Monday that his team had lost
patience and was shooting too fast at Vandy. The main offender was
guard Tony Harris, who was 1 of 14 from the field. The Vols must
correct that problem, Green said, tonight against Kentucky and in
the last three games, against Alabama, Arkansas and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vanderbilt: The Commodores' only shot is to win their final
four games against non-contenders and hope the others stumble. ``I
think you have to include Vandy in the mix,'' Auburn's Ellis said.
``The way this league has been going this year, anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
