<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5047 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-VOTE-ART-2TAKE     02-22 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-VOTE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RUSSIA'S NORTH, POLITICS AND NUCLEAR JUNK ARE HOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GADZHIYEVO, Russia _ The citizens of this closed military city
that hides one of Russia's nuclear submarine bases above the Arctic
Circle are staging an extraordinary civic revolt, taking on the
navy they have long served in a referendum on whether the fleet can
put a nuclear waste dump just outside the city limits.
</P>
<P>
   On March 26, the day Russians vote for a new president, the
people of this city, whose population is an official secret, will
be engaged in a battle they feel far more intensely than the
lop-sided presidential contest that Acting President Vladimir Putin
is expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   Sentiment is running high against the waste dump. Elsewhere in
post-Soviet Russia, unpaid shipyard workers have blocked roads and
even threatened to take ships hostage to draw attention to
grievances, but this seems to be the first time an entire town has
challenged the authority of the Russian military.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most surprising, the revolt is being led by former
high-ranking submarine officers who openly distrust the navy's
ability to look out for their interests and protect the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of political and economic mudslides, Russians who
have built some basics of democracy but whose freedoms seem ever
tenuous _ threatened by corruption, lawlessness and economic decay
_ are acting as if this election is a referendum on what is
important in their lives, whether that is the war in Chechnya, the
future of economic reform, even whether there is too much sex on
television or, here in Gadzhiyevo, whether the navy can store
radioactive waste near a town without consulting its residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just know from our experience what can happen,'' said
Vladimir Musatyan, 53, who has served on both ballistic missile and
attack submarines over two decades. Speaking in an interview on a
deserted stretch of road north of Murmansk, he said, ``I can tell
you that when we are loading rockets into our submarines, somebody
always drops one.''
</P>
<P>
   His longtime colleague, Yevgeny Burakov, 58, could only agree.
``We are on a base where there are significantly more frightening
weapons than this radioactive waste,'' Burakov said. ``But those
weapons are for the defense of the country and this waste site has
nothing to do with protecting the country, and that is why it
should be placed as far away as possible from any populated area.''
</P>
<P>
   All across Russia, from the rocky fjords here on the edge of the
Barents Sea to smokestack urban centers and snowy plains in the
farm belt, the country's political parties are trying to mobilize
voters for the presidential contest _ a task made more difficult by
the still vivid memory of the tough, mudslinging campaign for
parliamentary elections in December.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to tell how much success the parties will have
in mobilizing their footsoldiers. But it is also hard to find a
Russian who does not have an opinion about what this election
represents.
</P>
<P>
   In the little town of Bolshaya Glushitsa near the Volga River,
Anna Chechenkova, 67, is voting for Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist
Party candidate for president, because there are too many
``cheats'' in government, and too much sex and too many commercials
on television.
</P>
<P>
   Many of her neighbors in the snow-covered village are leaning
toward voting for Putin, because he is young and energetic. But
some _ especially those with draft-age sons _ are nervous about his
war policy in Chechnya, even those who support his fight against
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Others have a sense of dread about Putin's assertion that Russia
needs a ``dictatorship of law.'' They worry that the ``law'' part
of that equation might get overtaken by the ``dictatorship'' part
after he gets into office.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That is certainly one of the concerns of Boris Fursov, 58, a
retired military officer and engineer who spent his career building
infrastructure for the Soviet military in far off places like
Somalia. He lives in Samara, an industrial center on the Volga, and
says he is voting for the Yabloko Party candidate Grigory Yavlinsky
because he best embodies the democratic principles of the late
Andrei Sakharov.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in Russia's Northwest and in the Volga River
industrial region around Samara, voters and party workers expressed
strong views that Putin's lock on the election might not be as
strong as his advisers think, or as the polls reflect. Many people
seemed to be searching for the best means to influence Putin's
policies by orchestrating a strong turnout for opposition
candidates, and the ideologies they represent.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason the popular and strongly reformist governor of
the Samara region, Konstantin Titov, is running as a maverick
candidate for president, hoping that a strong showing by a
pro-democracy, market-oriented regional leader will force Putin to
ally himself with the more progressive voices promoting a
capitalist, democratic model for Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to consolidate the true democratic forces in society,''
said Titov in an interview, adding that if Putin announces
progressive policies, the governor might yet line up behind the
acting president. ``If Putin conducts a policy of reform, why
shouldn't I support him? I am not simply looking for a
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Titov, too, sees the election as a kind of referendum, one that
can be used to shape Putin himself, who continues to withhold any
detailed description of the course that he would chart for Russia
after being elected.
</P>
<P>
   But among others, the sense of inevitability is overpowering,
underscored by Putin's own maneuvering to cultivate better ties
with the West _ officially repairing relations with NATO and
reaching agreement with some of Russia's foreign creditors _ and to
proceed in Chechnya, even if that means virtually obliterating
Grozny and riding roughshod on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can compare Putin to a cannonball that was fired on Dec.
31,'' the day Boris Yeltsin resigned, said Vladimir Shaganov,
editor of the Evening Murmansk, a daily newspaper for the largest
city above the Arctic Circle. ``And this cannonball is going to
land in the president's seat on March 26. Everyone understands
this, despite some politicians who have wind blowing in their
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
