u a BC-ASBESTOS-GRACE-BOS &LR;      02-22 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASBESTOS-GRACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
W.R. GRACE SUED OVER ASBESTOS-TAINTED INSULATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ W.R. Grace Co. was hit with three class-action lawsuits
Tuesday, one filed in Boston on behalf of homeowners nationwide who
have asbestos-tainted Zonolite Attic Insulation in their homes, and
the other two in Montana, where the company operated a mine and
mill.
</P>
<P>
   The suit filed in US District Court in Boston by Edward M.
Lindholm accuses Grace of fraud, deception and enriching itself at
homeowners' expense for failing to warn the public that the
Zonolite insulation it sold from 1963 through 1984 contained
tremolite asbestos. Grace's Cambridge, Mass. Costruction Products
Division oversaw its Attic Insulation line.
</P>
<P>
   Two class-action suits filed Tuesday in federal court in
Missoula, Mont., seek damages for all property owners in Libby,
where Grace operated a mine and mill until 1990, and damages for
all residents exposed to tremolite asbestos. Grace got its
vermiculite, the mineral that was the main ingredient in its Attic
Insulation, from its Libby mine. Asbestos was naturally occurring
in the Libby vermiculite.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is asbestos contamination in settled dust throughout
Libby in homes and areas outside,'' said Edward Westbrook, a
Charlestown, S.C., attorney with one of the five firms that filed
the Montana cases.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Attorney Kenneth Gilman, who represents Lindholm and
filed the suit in US District Court in Boston, is urging a judge to
order Grace to notify homeowners of the dangers of living with
Zonolite in their houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``All class members should be given an opportunity to inspect
repair and remove Zonolite and to attempt to prevent personal
injury,'' the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gilman nor Lindholm, who is described only as the owner
of a home in Essex County, could be reached Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is seeking punitive and compensatory damages from Grace
and wants the company to foot the bill for Zonolite removal and
attorneys fees for Lindholm and other homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   William Corcoran, a spokesman for Grace, said, ``We believe our
Attic Insulation is a safe product and the lawsuit is without
merit. We've been very open with the governmental agencies and with
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported last week that Zonolite, a type of loose-fill
insulation, contains asbestos, but Grace officials fought to keep
warning labels off the product.
</P>
<P>
   Grace, which discontinued its Attic Insulation in 1984, knew as
far back as 1963 about the asbestos, but feared public disclosure
would hurt sales, according to memos from high-ranking Grace
officials.
</P>
<P>
   An internal Grace memo dated May 24, 1977 and obtained by the
Globe, revealed that the company was concerned by an in-house study
that revealed mortality rates were five times the national rate
among ex-employees at the Libby plant.
</P>
<P>
   But the memo reaffirmed Grace's opposition to warning labels on
Zonolite, saying, ``We believe that a decision to affix asbestos
warning labels to our products would result in substantial sales
losses.''
</P>
<P>
   W.R. Grace, today worth $1.5 billion, has paid out $1 billion as
a result of asbestos claims and expects to pay $1 billion more,
according to Corcoran. Many of Grace's claims are due to its past
manufacture of Monokote Fireproofing, a spray insulation that
contained asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Correspondent Adrianne Appel contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5049 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DINO23-COX     02-22 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINO23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fernbank scientist marvels at Giganotosaurus
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLAZA HUINCUL, Argentina _ Gazing up at the biggest meat-eating
dinosaur skeleton ever assembled, Christine Bean, a petite
scientist from Atlanta's Fernbank Museum of Natural History, was
awestruck, almost speechless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, wow! That's so cool,'' Bean whispered.
</P>
<P>
   She was gaping at an artificial cast of a Giganotosaurus at the
Museum Municipal de Carman Funes. She had come to this tiny museum
in this remote, windswept region of western Argentina to help
figure out how to squeeze a skeleton like this one, and that of the
even larger, plant-eating Argentinosaurus, into the Fernbank's
now-empty Great Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we have plenty of room,'' she quipped.
</P>
<P>
   She'd also come to learn more about the dinos, whose fossilized
bones were discovered near here, and to hear about a remarkable new
discovery: fossils from a ``herd'' of giant meat-eaters. It appears
the new dinosaurs were part of a social group _ which contradicts
conventional wisdom about how the carnivores behaved.
</P>
<P>
   First for Bean was the gee-whiz reaction, which Fernbank
visitors are likely to share. Reaching up to touch the
Giganotosaurus skeleton, she remarked: ``My whole body could fit
inside its mouth! The head is gigantic, just unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   She was just as startled upon entering an adjacent room, where a
dozen 2-ton vertebrae of the Argentinosaurus lay stretched out.
Longer than four school buses, the huge plant-eater weighed 100
tons. If the Fernbank's skeleton were posed on its hind legs as if
it were eating leaves out of the tops of ancient conifer trees, its
head would jut through the ceiling of the 72-foot-high Great Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just unbelievable!'' exclaimed Marissa Vivona, a public
relations staffer from Fernbank, who made the journey with Bean.
</P>
<P>
   The fossils of both dinosaurs will be cast in fiberglass-like
material, and the casts will be shipped to Atlanta, where they will
be assembled. (Almost all big dino-skeleton displays are casts,
rather than actual fossils. Large fossils are impractical to mount
due to their weight and the potential for damage.) ``People will
have a chance to walk under and around these great animals,'' Bean
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the fossilized bones that will be used for the Fernbank
casts are housed at the Museum Municipal de Carman Funes. The
museum's sun-baked curator, world-famous paleontologist Rodolfo
Coria, discovered both the Giganotosaurus and the Argentinosaurus
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Bean and Coria _ along with Philip Currie, a paleontologist with
the Royal Tyrrell Museum in Canada, and Don Lessem, head of the
company producing the reconstructions _ are trying to settle on a
design for the Fernbank that will depict what happened in real life
_ a hungry Giganotosaurus chasing the bigger plant-eater. Coria
speculates the Giganotosaurus, which had teeth like steak knives,
would jump repeatedly onto the Argentinosaurus, chewing, slashing
and bleeding it to death.
</P>
<P>
   The Fernbank's Giganotosaurus cast is due to be displayed by
June. Fossils of the Argentinosaurus are still being excavated, so
its skeleton won't be on exhibit until December.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Coria and Currie announced a discovery that will
likely shake up the world's dinosaur experts. Paleontologists in
Argentina have found the fossil bones of a new, yet-unnamed species
of meat eater, which is even bigger than the Giganotosaurus.
</P>
<P>
   The find suggests that giant meat eaters, including the famous
Tyrannosaurus Rex of ``Jurassic Park'' fame, weren't as dumb as
previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists stumbled upon a rare ``herd'' of the new species
of meat eaters. The group appears to have been a hunting pack, and
it may have been a family, Currie said.
</P>
<P>
   The dinosaurs perished together, probably in a flash flood,
Currie said. ``Some were large adults and some were babies,'' he
said. The discovery indicates there may have been some sort of
family life among the great meat eaters, Currie said.
</P>
<P>
   Until this and similar recent finds, meat-eating dinosaurs had
been considered solitary creatures not capable of much social
interaction.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted at the University of Maryland, paleontologist Thomas
Holtz, one of the world's top experts on meat-eating dinos, said
the discovery of the fossil herd was ``very exciting and
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stunning,'' Holtz said. ``By working as a team, these
predators would be able to eat even a giant plant eater.''
</P>
<P>
   Digs have revealed the fossilized bones of at least seven of the
meat eaters, and possibly a dozen or more. Some of the fossils have
been brought to Coria's museum here.
</P>
<P>
   After their announcement, Coria and Currie headed back to the
plains of western Patagonia late Tuesday to look for more fossils
and to show Bean where the Fernbank's Giganotosaurus and
Argentinosaurus had been found.
</P>
<P>
   Bean toured the museum, taking photographs and videotapes of the
bones. She'll use those in the classes she teaches to thousands of
Atlanta-area schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is that these gigantic dinosaur skeletons will fuel
the imagination of kids and adults alike,'' she said. ``It will be
a heart-pounding, awesome experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
