<HEADER>
A5051 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-VOTE-ART-2NDTA     02-22 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-VOTE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 GADZHIYEVO, Russia: their heads.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And the Kremlin is using all of its muscle to reinforce Putin's
``positives.'' Shaganov says he was offered a handsome political
payoff from the Putin organization if he agreed to publish a series
of articles that would help create a favorable image of Putin in
Russia's Northwestern region _ an offer hastily withdrawn when the
Putin people realized they already had a great deal of regional
press loyalty and did not need to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Putin headquarters invited the Murmansk newspaper
to send one of its columnists to Moscow for an ``exclusive
interview'' with Putin along with other regional newspaper
columnists.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   So many Russians have lost faith in the ability of the central
government to solve the country's problems that nearly 2 million
Russian voters marked ``none of the above'' on their ballots in the
December parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``none of the above'' dramatically out-polled 20 of the
26 parties listed on the ballot. Now, campaign organizers are at a
loss over how best to approach a testy and mercurial electorate. In
Murmansk, Yabloko leader Igor Lebedev said people in the Northwest
are ``tired'' of politics and don't even read national newspapers
anymore, either because they cost too much or people are just fed
up with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Titov, the Samara governor, thinks people are tired of the same
old opposition candidates. ``Zyuganov and Yavlinsky have been
around a long time,'' he said. ``Newer faces should appear, or
people will get sick of going to the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Bolshaya Glushitsa, party workers like Liliya
Murza, 32, who runs the local children's center and who built an
eight-member team to campaign door-to-door last fall for the
reform-oriented Union of Right Forces party, say they have no time
to do it again for the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Energizing voters who struggle to make ends meet can also be a
daunting task. And yet, there are exceptions, like 77-year-old
Konstantin Mokshin, a feisty beekeeper who sells honey in the local
market. He shocked the whole town with his bold financial
intervention into last fall's campaign. Mokshin stands on one good
leg like a soldier for the local Communist Party committee and he
shares his house with Anna Chechenkova.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of the ferocious Battle of Stalingrad in World War II,
he was disabled by the bullet that took his left leg shortly after.
The couple was not happy with the era of Boris Yeltsin, not just
because there is a lot of sex on television _ a particular peeve
shared by many used to the public puritanism of Soviet times _ but
really because they haven't seen a leader they admired since the
days of Roosevelt and Stalin.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the local school, they used to hang pictures of the heroes
of the Great Patriotic War,'' Mokshin said, gesturing with still
powerful hands over a dinner table laid with homemade butter, fresh
baked bread and honey from the hives stored under the house for
winter. ``My picture was among those at the school,'' he says.
``Now they have pulled them all down. They don't respect the heroes
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Chechenkova, alluding to the blatant corruption of the Yeltsin
era, said: ``I heard in other countries when people do something
wrong in office, they resign and go away. But here they stay in
office and just keep stealing.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Mokshin got so enthusiastic about the local Communist
candidate for parliament that he marched down to the village bank
and withdrew most of his life savings, the equivalent of about
$425, and donated it to the man to help him fight the ``cheaters''
and ``crooks.''
</P>
<P>
   The teller at the bank thought Mokshin had gone crazy _ and said
so _ and then talked him into withdrawing only two-thirds of his
money. And though his life savings is now less than $200, a sum he
and Chechenkova would like to hold on to, Mokshin seems likely to
impulsively throw his money behind the Communists once more. ``I am
going to vote for Zyuganov,'' he declared, ``because he is trying
to protect ordinary people.'' Putin, he adds scornfully, ``is just
``the lowest card from Yeltsin's deck.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gadzhiyevo, the retired submarine officers who have mobilized
the city against the navy, Musatyan and Burakov, are the only two
Communist Party members of the nine-member city council, where the
referendum on the radioactive waste dump has majority support.
</P>
<P>
   The navy has not disclosed how large the dump site would be, or
how many of the 100 nuclear submarines presently mothballed in the
fleet might end up there waiting, perhaps for decades, for
decommissioning and final disposal of the highly radioactive spent
fuel inside their reactors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are an American, would you allow a radioactive burial site
in your town?'' Burakov asked a foreign visitor.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the glory days of the Soviet fleet, Musatyan and Burakov were
no ordinary officers aboard the nuclear submarines that sailed _
and still sail _ from here. They were Zampolit officers, or
political commissars, in charge of maintaining strict Communist
Party discipline among the crews, whose task it might be to fire
nuclear warheads against U.S. cities or military targets.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of nuclear war, they were said to share the
responsibility with the captain to authorize the launch of the
nuclear-tipped ballistic missiles from the steel tubes welded into
the belly of the Soviet ``boomers.''
</P>
<P>
   In taking on the navy, the city elders have taken some risks, as
was evident when an officer of the Federal Security Service
unsuccessfully sought to prevent a meeting between city council
members and a foreign reporter to discuss the referendum outside
the city gates.
</P>
<P>
   The security officer declared that not only was the city closed
to foreigners, but the road leading to it from Murmansk, the
provincial capital, was also closed. As a result, the former
submarine officers and several of their supporters drove five miles
outside the city and stopped along an empty stretch of highway
where they explained their opposition to the navy's plans in a
roadside interview.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I have heard of people from the naval
community actually challenging the fleet,'' said Thomas Nilsen, a
senior researcher with the Bellona Foundation in Norway, an
environmental group that is now working with Russia to solve
nuclear waste problems. ``The whole history of the last decade has
been that the people living in these closed cities just take orders
from the navy,'' he continued. ``I think this is extremely
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   It is far from clear whether the navy will pay attention to the
March 26 referendum, but the civilian challenge has already forced
provincial leaders in Murmansk to organize the first environmental
impact studies on the proposed radioactive storage site.
</P>
<P>
   As Communists, Musatyan and Burakov see no irony in the
democratic tactics they have employed to rally the voters here.
Indeed, their remarks convey a sense of dragging communism back to
its activist roots, before power ossified both the ideology and
many of those who professed to act in its name. ``Do you think that
Communists don't care about people?'' Musatyan asked. ``We are
Communists,'' added Burakov. ``In fact, I am the secretary of the
local Communist Party committee, but we are not doing this because
we are Communists, we are doing it because it is the best thing for
the future of our town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
