<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NY-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVOKING CLINTON, BRADLEY BRANDS GORE A FOLLOWER, NOT A LEADER
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ In a nod to President Clinton's continuing
popularity among Democratic voters, former Sen. Bill Bradley
asserted Tuesday that Vice President Al Gore had adopted many core
Democratic principles only after becoming Clinton's ``No. 2,'' and
he suggested that the vice president could not be counted on to
defend those principles on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has criticized Clinton's ethics in the past, the
former senator from New Jersey twice wrapped himself in the
president's mantle Tuesday, saying that he and Clinton shared
common views on universal health care, and contending that Gore had
forsaken that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was running for vice president in 1992, he took Bill
Clinton's views on health care and said we needed health insurance
for everyone,'' Bradley told more than 250 people here at Adelphi
University. ``Now that he's on his own running for president, he
says health insurance for all Americans is too expensive and we
can't do it, even though we have a giant budget surplus and 8
million more uninsured than seven years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley went on to argue that in 1993 Clinton supported
replacing Medicaid, the government health care program for the
poor, with a new program that was similar to what Bradley has
called for in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bill Clinton wanted to reform Medicaid to end the
two-tiered system in our country, Al Gore supported it,'' Bradley
said. ``Now that he's running for president, he attacks me for
wanting to do the same thing that Bill Clinton wanted to do, and
that he used to support.''
</P>
<P>
   In evoking Clinton Tuesday, Bradley _ who is trailing Gore by
double digits in public opinion polls in most states _ was trying
to show that Gore was a follower and not a leader in the Clinton
administration, his aides said. Bradley sought to underscore that
theme by calling Gore ``a loyal No. 2.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley also seemed intent on trying to separate Gore
somewhat from Clinton, who remains very popular among voters in
Democratic primaries. A CBS-New York Times poll conducted last
week, for example, found that 70 percent of Democratic voters view
Clinton favorably.
</P>
<P>
   And by mentioning the president twice _ he usually does not
mention Clinton at all in his speeches _ Bradley wanted to show
that he strongly supported some of the president's major
initiatives, Bradley's aides said.
</P>
<P>
   That acknowledgment represents a subtle shift for Bradley, whose
campaign was once strongly premised on the idea that Democrats
would be ready to throw Gore out of office because of weariness
with the Democrats' fund-raising abuses in 1996 and questions about
Clinton's ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying desperately to create phony distinctions, because
he loses when voters focus on the real differences in this
campaign,'' said Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for Gore. ``He's
repackaged the same old line of attack he has used since losing
Iowa and New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming just two weeks before the March 7 ``Super Tuesday''
primaries, Bradley's 20-minute speech Tuesday was one of his most
forceful and clearly articulated explanations yet for why Democrats
should choose him over a sitting vice president when the nation, by
many measures, is in very good health.
</P>
<P>
   It also picked up on a theme he began sounding during the
Democrats' debate in Harlem on Monday night, when Bradley asserted
that Gore was a conservative congressman and senator whose views
turned left when he joined the administration in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   By having shifted ground on abortion, gun control, tobacco
regulations, health care and other issues, Gore had showed himself
to have no clear ideological core, Bradley said. ``What does he
really believe?'' the former senator asked, repeating the question
later for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   But Hattaway said, ``Senator Bradley knows very well that Al
Gore is pro-choice and supports gun control.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bradley, who has been criticized by some Democrats for having a
low-keyed stump style, also urged voters not to be taken in by
Gore's more forceful manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strength is not about shouting or pounding a table, it's about
knowing what you believe and acting on those beliefs no matter what
those around you are doing,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not flashy,'' he added. ``Never have been, either on the
floor of Madison Square Garden or in the United States Senate. My
passion for these things is deep in my heart. And it's deep in my
soul. I show them not by shouting or making a fist, but by the
consistency of my beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his speech Tuesday, Bradley stopped in the Astoria
section of Queens, where he shook hands with voters and dropped by
a Greek delicatessen where he ate feta cheese and baklava, bought a
spinach-and-cheese pie and did his version of a Greek folk dance
for the amused clientele.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bradley will give a speech on economics at
Columbia University before flying to Washington state, where he
intends to spend almost all of the week campaigning in preparation
for its nonbinding primary on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is staking much time and money on Washington, hoping to
jump-start his struggling campaign for the stretch run to March 7,
when 16 states will hold primaries or caucuses that will select
nearly a third of the Democratic delegates.
</P>
<P>
   His plan to focus on Washington poses something of a gamble,
since it will reduce the time he spends in the major states that
vote on March 7, including California, New York and Ohio. But
Bradley's advisers say they believe he needs some kind of public
relations victory to build momentum before the March 7 contests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
