<SLUG> BC-RATHEYON-EARNINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC SEEKS EARNINGS STATEMENT FACTS, RAYTHEON SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. said federal regulators are questioning its recent
earnings restatements.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing to the Securities and Exchange Commission late
Tuesday, the Lexington, Mass. defense contractor said it received
``an informal inquiry'' from the SEC's Division of Enforcement
following Raytheon's announcement last month that it planned to
restate financial results back to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Such requests by the agency are considered less intrusive than
formal investigations, which involve subpoena powers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the probe adds more uncertainty to the financial outlook
for Raytheon, whose shares have fallen severely in recent months as
it has reduced its profit outlook and warned of slowing sales
overseas. In response the company has begun another restructuring
program that includes hundreds of local layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Of interest to the SEC are restated results at Raytheon's
Wichita, Kan. aircraft division, which once booked revenue on some
planes after manufacturing was complete and titles passed to
customers. Under new accounting rules adopted by the SEC in
December, Raytheon said, it now recognizes revenue only after
planes are delivered.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing, Raytheon said it is ``in the process of
responding to this inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Company spokesman David Polk declined to describe the SEC's
specific interests. ``The SEC customarily makes inquiries whenever
a company restates its financial results, so we're not surprised''
by the current action, Polk said.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also provide certain documents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a spokesman for the commission declined to
discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon disclosed the inquiry as part of an amended filing to
sell up to $3 billion worth of securities, which it said may
include debt, warrants, or preferred stock. The registration dates
to last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Raytheon said its Engineering and Construction unit
received a contract to provide management services for the
expansion of two optical-fiber manufacturing plants in North
Carolina, though it didn't disclose terms.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also said it has reached agreements to sell the South
Korean Navy a guided missile system to help defend a new class of
destroyers. Terms also were not disclosed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2015EST &QL; 
