A5055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-DEBATE-NYT &LR;      02-22 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE AT THE APOLLO RAISED SOME OLD ISSUES FOR BRADLEY AND GORE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Did not! Did so!
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only players who came out ahead in Monday night's
fractious Democratic debate were the opposition research teams for
the Gore and Bradley campaigns, gnomes who puzzle over 20-year-old
votes and speeches that drew only minimal attention when they were
given.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, though, Bill Bradley was right on Monday night
at the Apollo Theater when he said that Al Gore voted to curb
Internal Revenue Service efforts to develop rules that would end
tax exemptions for segregated private schools.
</P>
<P>
   And the vice president was right when he said that Bradley voted
to end a tax break that encouraged minority purchases of
broadcasting stations.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest charges that Gore and the former senator from New
Jersey leveled in Monday night's Democratic presidential debate in
New York turn out to be completely accurate. But the conclusions
that Gore and Bradley drew about what these old votes reveal about
their opponent's commitment to racial justice may have been
strained.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Bradley said Gore ``voted five times over
three years for a tax exemption for schools to discriminate on the
basis of race,'' he was drawing the worst possible conclusion about
his opponent's votes. The Gore campaign issued a statement on
Tuesday saying that the votes only concerned stopping the IRS from
taking a broad, rather than a case-by-case, approach, and that Gore
was trying to protect ``legitimate, nondiscriminating religious
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   That was an expansion of the vice president's claim, defending
his challenged votes from 1979, 1980 and 1981, that all he was
doing was opposing ``quotas.'' He said they had been against
quotas, the traditional attack against affirmative action programs
of all sorts. He was straining, using the argument offered by the
most conservative proponents of the restriction.
</P>
<P>
   On five occasions Gore voted for measures intended to keep the
revenue agency and the courts from developing rules and procedures
to enforce a Nixon-era prohibition on tax exemptions for the
segregation academies that sprung up in the South after the Supreme
Court outlawed segregated pubic schools. None of them simply
directed the IRS not to use numerical quotas. They prohibited any
new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's allies said the IRS wanted to impose racial quotas on
private schools, which until then could qualify for tax-exemption
if they simply stated they were not discriminating.
(Time-consuming, difficult cases could be built against schools
that were obviously lying.)
</P>
<P>
   Numerical yardsticks were indeed one of several ways a school
could defend itself, but there were others, like hiring minority
teachers or running joint programs with integrated schools.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps learning from Gore's mistake, Bradley offered no
explanation at all for his 1995 vote _ unique among Finance
Committee Democrats _ to make the repeal of the provision on
minority ownership retroactive and thereby block a pending $2.3
billion sale by Viacom to minority interests that depended on the
tax break to work. On Tuesday his spokesman, Eric Hauser, said
Bradley had felt ``This was not the most efficient way to help
minority broadcasters.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Viacom deal had given the minority preference a bad
odor, and when Newt Gingrich's new House majority seized on the
issue as an example of the failure of affirmative action,
relatively few white Democrats stood up to fight to preserve the
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The issue had been debated harshly in the House. One Democratic
representative, Bill Richardson of New Mexico, who is now energy
secretary, called the measure ``the opening salvo of the Contract
with America's war on minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, like Rep. Henry Bonilla of Texas, scorned Democrats
for ``using the race card.'' The bill passed in the House with only
44 no votes, after a compromise effort had been defeated, 234-191.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate Finance Committee, Carol Mosely Braun of Illinois
fought hardest to preserve the tax benefit, first generally and
then for Viacom.
</P>
<P>
   The savings from ending the program, however, were transferred
to a popular program to extend tax deductions to self-employed
individuals who buy health insurance. And when the bill came to the
floor, the health insurance provision dominated the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that he thought the minority broadcast provision
``is not appropriate tax policy.'' He said ``I have consistently
opposed the special interest loopholes.'' But he said he was
unhappy ``that the issue of affirmative action has been interjected
into this underlying issue'' of tax deductions for health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore said nothing on the House floor, and little on Monday
night, about the IRS measures which all passed by overwhelming
votes, he did offer a comment on gun control that could be a useful
standard for talking about old votes.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by CNN after the debate, he was asked about
Bradley's claim that the vide president had altered his views on
gun control so often that it was hard to believe him.
</P>
<P>
   Gore confessed to changing his mind, saying he saw the gun
problem differently when he represented Tennessee with all its
urban areas in the Senate than when he represented a rural House
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that all of us grow and learn as we encounter people
who have real experiences in life. And, you know, theory collides
with reality and you begin to see better solutions for problems.
So, sure, I've changed my mind on some things and I think it's a
good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's apparently easier to admit to changed views on guns
than on race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
