<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UNILEVER-CUTBACK-ART-     02-22 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNILEVER-CUTBACK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNILEVER TO ELIMINATE 25,000 JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Unilever PLC, the world's leading maker of consumer
goods that include supermarket mainstays like Dove soap, Ragu
spaghetti sauce and Lipton tea, said Tuesday it would embark on a
severe corporate cutback plans, eliminating 25,000 jobs over five
years, closing 100 factories and possibly jettisoning up to 75
percent of its products.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the Anglo-Dutch conglomerate, surprising in
its severity and scope, reflected a growing trend by European
companies to emulate the cutbacks made by big U.S. companies like
General Motors, IBM and AT&AMP;T in the 1990s to become more efficient
and more profitable. Company officials announced the restructuring
plan as Unilever reported profits last year fell 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe hasn't gone through the mega-downsizings we've seen in
the United States,'' said John Challenger, chief executive officer
of Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas, a Chicago-based job-placement
company that tracks U.S. layoff trends. The Europeans, Challenger
said, ``are kind of following the same path as we move into the
global marketplace. They've got to compete against U.S. companies
that have made these changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Unilever job cuts amount to 10 percent of the company's
global work force, and the cost of the cuts in employment and
factory closings will total $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the job reductions will be made in Europe and North and
South America, but company officials declined to specify how many
would come from layoffs and which countries would be most affected.
Also left unclear was what specific brands might be sold or
discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   In absolute terms, the job cuts rank among the biggest by a
European company, though they are by no means the biggest ever.
Former state-owned monopolies like British Telecommunications and
Deutsche Telekom of Germany cut far more jobs after they were
privatized, for example. Some leading European banks have also cut
many thousands of overlapping jobs after mergers.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain in particular, job losses have become synonymous with
restructuring in sectors from oil to insurance to utilities. In the
past year, companies from BP Amoco to Barclays PLC have announced
payroll cuts amounting to 10 percent of their work forces and the
trend has seeped slowly into Continental nations, like Germany and
France, where reducing staff is both more difficult and more
expensive. Even Deutsche Bank AG has broken its staid mold with a
program of job cuts since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts said that the pressures on Unilever are
broader, reflecting a global duel with more profitable rivals _
most notably Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., the biggest household products
manufacturer in the United States _ in markets as disparate as
continental Europe and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Unilever, we have to appreciate that this is a global
company,'' said Susanne Seibel, an analyst with Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
in London. ``And it's competing against global peers.''
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the restructuring, Unilever said, was to use the
savings gained to sharpen the marketing of the top 400 among its
1,600 brands _ leaving less profitable product lines to be
reorganized, discontinued or sold off.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever officials had said last year they wanted to winnow the
company's lineup of brands, but the announcement Tuesday showed how
Unilever intends to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program is all about accelerating the rate of growth at
Unilever,'' said Antony Burgmans, Unilever's co-chairman. The
changes, he said, would ``dramatically improve our ability to
market our leading brands.''
</P>
<P>
   The Unilever name is not widely recognized by consumers, but it
is the corporate parent behind a vast array of everyday beauty,
home-care and food staples. Some of the best-known products include
Wish-Bone salad dressings, Imperial margarine, Good Humor ice
cream, Wisk detergent, Vaseline skin lotion, Q-tips cotton swabs,
Brut deodorant, Suave shampoo, and Calvin Klein and Elizabeth Arden
fragrances.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Unilever is playing catch-up with P&AMP;G and Danone SA
of France, which both have higher profit margins. The quest for
investor returns has been all the more cutthroat as markets have
generally been leery of food and consumer-goods stocks, preferring
high-growth sectors like telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Unilever's stock declined by 35 percent and
underperformed European rivals by 50 percent, while shares of P&AMP;G,
which itself began a program to cut 15,000 jobs last June, has
generally held steady.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement cheered investors somewhat. In Amsterdam,
Unilever shares rose 3.6 percent, to 47.66 euros, or about $47.66.
In London, the shares rose 1.3 percent to 391 pence, or about
$6.25. Unilever's U.S. depositary receipts rose $1 to $25.75.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its measures would deliver annual savings of
$1.5 billion by 2004, which would largely be invested in enhancing
top brands, including Elizabeth Arden cosmetics and fragrances.
</P>
<P>
   Of its 380 manufacturing sites, Unilever said it will focus
investment on 150 principal plants, closing 100 and leaving the
other 130 as support units.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will probably be about 100 sites surplus to requirements
which we will dispose of,'' said Niall Fitzgerald, the company's
other co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Unilever's weaker profits, rivals have posted
rising earnings. P&AMP;G has said its profits rose by 11 percent in the
fourth quarter of last year. And P&AMP;G's operating margins grew to
16.4 percent last year, compared to 11.1 percent at Unilever. And
Danone said its profits in the second half of 1999 were up by 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement was taken by some analysts as a further
sign of a shifting corporate culture at Unilever, once viewed as a
slow-moving dinosaur with little appetite for radical change. The
shift reflects the ambitions of a new management, which has said it
is committed to a leaner organization focused on a tighter product
range.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two co-chairmen, Fitzgerald took over the top slot in
Britain in 1996 and accelerated the streamlining of its British
operations. Burgman's arrival last year as the Dutch co-chairman
led to the decision to focus on the top 400 brands.
</P>
<P>
   Burgmans said that the thrust of investment in top brands would
be in North and South America. By contrast, a European bakery
division will be sold off if it fails to grow faster this year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, though, remained skeptical about the impact of
the changes. ``It remains to be seen if it's enough,'' Riet Vijgen,
a Belgian analyst, said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
