<SLUG> BC-GI-JFK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASBRO PLANS JFK ACTION FIGURE TO JOIN GI JOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Action figure GI Joe could soon have a new comrade in arms _
former president and war hero John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to what may be an unprecedented agreement between the
Kennedy Library Foundation and toymaker Hasbro Inc., consumers
willing to pay $30 may be able to buy an action figure of JFK in
PT-109 fatigues this fall.
</P>
<P>
   On display at last week's American International Toy Fair in New
York, the planned JFK action figure is part of a GI Joe collector's
series that celebrates American military heroes and famous battles.
</P>
<P>
   The JFK figure ``will be the first of a number of Kennedy
products'' that will be made under an agreement between the Kennedy
Library Foundation and Hasbro, the maker of GI Joe, said Hasbro
spokesman Wayne Charness.
</P>
<P>
   Charness declined to elaborate on what those products might be,
but Tom McNaught, a Kennedy Library Foundation spokesman, said one
action figure under discussion might have JFK resplendent in a
naval officer's dress whites.
</P>
<P>
   In the PT-109 edition, the Kennedy figure wears fatigues as he
uses a knife to carve a message into a coconut shell. The figure
reenacts a scene from World War II that Kennedy made famous in his
political campaigns. After their boat was sunk by a Japanese
warship, Kennedy and his crew swam to the safety of a nearby
island. The message on the coconut was entrusted to friendly
islanders who brought it to Kennedy's rescuers.
</P>
<P>
   Because JFK is a public figure, Hasbro probably could have made
the action figure without the Kennedy family's permission, McNaught
said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Cape Cod gift shops are full of Camelot-era
knick-knacks, from Jackie Kennedy dolls to postcards of the late
president sailing in nearby waters. Such products rarely have the
Kennedy family's permission, nor does the law require it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If images are in the public domain, they belong to
everybody,'' McNaught said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Hasbro needed the foundation's permission to make the
action figure is ``a dicey area'' of the law, said Bill Hartglass,
team leader of GI Joe product development for Hasbro.
</P>
<P>
   But he stressed that making an action figure without a family's
permission is ``not the way we do business.''
</P>
<P>
   According to McNaught, Hasbro first broached the idea around the
time of a Kennedy Library event last fall that featured retired
General Colin Powell as a speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Powell was immortalized in the GI Joe heroes line. In
return for his approval of the action figure, Hasbro made a
donation to Powell's favorite charity, the Boys and Girls Clubs of
America. The Powell figure was a smash hit, Hartglass said.
</P>
<P>
   Pledging to treat JFK's image with respect, Hasbro made a
similar proposal, offering to donate royalties to the Kennedy
Library Foundation. Neither Hasbro nor the foundation would comment
on dollar amounts, but McNaught said the money the foundation could
receive was ``significant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To the best of my knowledge, this is the first time something
like this has been done,'' McNaught said of the agreement between
Hasbro and the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   JFK and GI Joe may have an earlier connection, according to one
man. A few years ago, a self-styled GI Joe historian and author
named Hal Fowler offered the theory that the facial features of GI
Joe may have been partly modeled after Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler told a California newspaper that he had reached this
conclusion because the face of the original GI Joe doll bore a
striking resemblance to that of JFK. GI Joe was introduced in 1964,
a year after Kennedy's assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes criticized for glorifying war and promoting
inappropriate play, GI Joe debuted as a line of action figures for
boys. During the Vietnam era when soldiers were out of favor, GI
Joe evolved into a generic adventurer and, for several years, was
discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   GI Joe's revival has been partly helped by a trend sweeping the
toy industry _ the advent of the adult collector. In the last few
years, adult collectors have crowded into toy stores, hoarding
everything from Beanie Babies to Barbie dolls.
</P>
<P>
   GI Joe has been no exception, and now many GI Joe products
target such collectors.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, GI Joe enthusiasts could buy figures modeled
after such famous US generals as Dwight D. Eisenhower and George S.
Patton, for which agreements were made with their families,
according to Hasbro. Generic figures also commemorate such famous
battles as D-Day and the invasion of Inchon.
</P>
<P>
   Because the JFK figure that was exhibited at the GI Joe display
duy Fair was a prototype, Hasbro would not allow it to be
photographed. The annual Toy Fair trade show is sponsored by the
Toy Manufacturers of America Inc., and draws 2,000 toy makers,
distributors, and importers.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts estimate GI Joe accounts for only a
fraction of Hasbro's business _ maybe $50 million out of total
sales of about $4.23 billion. Hasbro does not issue specific sales
figures for toy lines. But thanks partly to collectors, Hasbro did
say GI Joe sales last year rose by nearly a third.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro has high hopes for the JFK in its GI Joe line.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hartglass, ``The Kennedys have a special place in American
history and a special place in America's heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
