A5061 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-1STLD     02-22 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-ERRORS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBTS CAST ON CLINTON'S PROPOSALS CONCERNING MEDICAL ERRORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for new lead, rewriting throughout)  
(HLW) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The official leading federal efforts to reduce
medical errors told Congress on Tuesday that he had no firm
evidence that mandatory reporting of such errors, as proposed by
President Clinton, increased the safety of patients or reduced the
number of mistakes in states where it had been tried.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Dr. John M. Eisenberg, director of the Agency for
Health Care Research and Quality, said that some of the criticism
of the president's proposals was ``on target.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we know if these programs work?'' Eisenberg said at a
Senate hearing. ``No, we don't. We don't know how well they work,
and when they work best.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg was responding to comments made on Monday by Dr. Nancy
W. Dickey, former president of the American Medical Association,
who said, ``A number of states have mandatory reporting, and
there's no evidence that they have greater safety or fewer
errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Several states require hospitals to report certain kinds of
mistakes and ``adverse events.'' Clinton wants all states to
require such reports.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg said ``there's been very little analysis'' of states'
experience with mandatory reporting. He said that one bit of
evidence, from New York state, suggested that such reports could
improve the quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals in New York have been required to report medical
mistakes and other unexpected occurrences to the state Health
Department since 1985. Under a separate program, the agency
collects information on every patient undergoing heart bypass
surgery in New York, regardless of whether there was an error. The
state publishes death rates for all hospitals that perform the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The death rate for bypass surgery has dropped by more than 30
percent since New York first published such data in 1989. The
figures are adjusted to take account of each patient's medical
history and other ``risk factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg said the federal government would develop a research
agenda to identify the best methods of mandatory reporting. As a
condition of getting Medicare money, he said, hospitals will have
to comply with reporting requirements in their states. In addition,
Medicare officials will choose up to 100 hospitals to test the
value of mandatory reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey said: ``The president has the cart before the horse. He'd
put in place mandatory reporting, then study it and do something
different if it doesn't improve patient safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. J. Richard Gaintner, chief executive of Shands Health Care,
which operates seven hospitals in and around Gainesville, Fla.,
said he feared that the reporting of medical errors would feed the
appetite of lawyers eager to sue hospitals for malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take medical errors very seriously,'' Gaintner said in an
interview. ``But the incredible litigiousness in the health care
field is a great concern to us. I have been in this business for 30
years and have sat on the boards of several insurance companies.
I've seen too many examples of information that gets out and is
used in ways that are not good for patients or patient care.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's proposal, the names of hospitals reporting
serious errors would be ``made public without identifying patients
or individual health care professionals.'' The president said that
the results of a hospital's internal investigation and analysis of
its errors should not be available to patients, their lawyers or
the courts.
</P>
<P>
   But Eisenberg said the Clinton administration had not
recommended any specific penalties for the improper disclosure of
such information.
</P>
<P>
   New York hospitals have been required to report errors and
mishaps to the state Health Department since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Spencer Foreman, president of Montefiore Medical Center in
the Bronx, said: ``These requirements compel hospitals to look at
errors and examine them, to find out what caused them and to take
reasonable steps to correct them. Even states with a long history
of incident reporting, like New York, don't have a model program to
ensure that problems, once identified, are corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators of both parties said Clinton was apparently trying to
impose a new mandate on the states without offering them any money
to carry out the task of tabulating and analyzing thousands of
error reports from hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, the Pennsylvania Republican who heads the
Appropriations subcommittee for health care, said he supported
mandatory reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Without a federal law, he said, hospitals will not acknowledge
their errors, and he cited his state's experience to prove his
point. Under state law, he said, hospitals are supposed to report
medical errors, but 35 Philadelphia hospitals reported only one
medical mistake in the year that ended in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   David L. Bernd, chief executive of Sentara Health Care, a large
nonprofit health care system in Virginia, said: ``We support
efforts to deal with medical errors. They can be tragic. But if the
information is used to browbeat providers who report errors, they
won't report. The problem will get worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2019EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5062 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-1     02-22 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-435(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSING ARGUMENTS UNDERSCORE GAP BETWEEN MICROSOFT AND GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs to rewrite lede grafs and add about 800 words to provide
better focus and additional details; story is now 2 takes)  
(bl) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY and STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. got its last chance in federal
court Tuesday to persuade the trial judge not to issue a stinging
antitrust verdict against the company.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge, Thomas Penfield Jackson, gave Microsoft little
comfort. At one point in Tuesday's final arguments, he dismissed a
key Microsoft defense by comparing the company to John D.
Rockefeller's Standard Oil monopoly, the subject of the first major
antitrust case, in 1906, that resulted in a breakup of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really see a distinction,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The government, in its final argument, said it was ``simply
impossible to imagine'' that the company will not be found to have
violated the nation's antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, for its part, argued that it was impossible to see
how the company could be found guilty. ``A lot of nothing doesn't
add up to something,'' said John Warden, the company's lead lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   And so the trial drew to close on exactly the same notes that
carried it through 16 months of testimony and argument. The
government pressed hard on its broad points, while Microsoft
refused to concede even a nit. Tuesday's arguments on the relevant
points of law bearing on the case were the last act before a
verdict, which will probably be issued in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The court is likely to hold separate hearings on remedies if, as
expected, Jackson rules that Microsoft violated antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   A strong verdict against Microsoft could well lead to harsh
sanctions against the company, including breaking it up. If,
however, Jackson agrees with some of the government's legal
allegations but rejects others, the sanctions against Microsoft
could be less severe, prohibiting it from some practices but
leaving the company intact.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Justice Department and state attorneys general
pressing the case insist they will not settle for a mild sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remedies have to be drastic and far reaching,'' Richard
Blumenthal, the attorney general of Connecticut and one of the
plaintiffs, said this evening.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Microsoft and the government concluded this phase of
the trial, their representatives are continuing to meet in Chicago
in search of a settlement, in mediation talks overseen by Richard
A. Posner, chief judge of the 7th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals.
The two sides reportedly remain far apart, but government officials
note that the fact they are still meeting at this late date
suggests a willingness on both sides to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to work hard with Judge Posner,'' said
William H. Neukom, Micrsoft's general counsel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The debate in court Tuesday was over how legal precedents from
industries ranging from ski slopes in Colorado to newspapers in
Ohio apply to the facts in the Microsoft case. The government said
Microsoft is an old-fashioned monopolist in high-tech clothes.
Microsoft responded that computer software _ a fast-changing,
dynamic, fiercely competitive industry _ does indeed have
distinctive characteristics, and the courts should tread carefully.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard Oil analogy was just one of several skeptical
questions and remarks Jackson aimed at Microsoft's lawyer in court
Tuesday. Warden was making the argument that the Windows operating
system was protected by a copyright, and therefore was protected
against some of the government's charges, when Jackson spoke up to
say he had a problem with that defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What exactly is covered by copyright?'' the judge asked. Was
it ``fee simple'' or absolute ``control over code? Rockefeller had
fee simple control over his oil. I don't really see a
distinction.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warden responded that the laws were different then, adding that
he did not think copyright law was more powerful than antitrust
law.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's presentations were the final attempt by both sides to
try to influence Jackson's thinking. At one point, David Boies, the
Justice Department's lead trial lawyer, said Microsoft's business
strategy was based on trying to `bribe and coerce'' other companies
in the computer industry. Warden dismissed one of Boies' arguments
as ``entirely wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The government, according to most antitrust experts, is sitting
on a big lead, while Microsoft is trying to limit its losses in
Jackson's court while hoping to fare better on appeal. But at one
point, Boies appeared to be trying to embolden Jackson not to worry
about appeals by saying: ``Try to imagine the Supreme Court ruling
that these acts do not violate the antitrust laws. It is simply
impossible to imagine that.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, on the other hand, seemed to be employing elements of
a loss-limitation strategy. Warden began by saying that Microsoft
``respectfully disagreed'' with much of the Jackson's findings of
fact, issued in November. They strongly favored the government's
case.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Warden then went on to tell Jackson that his ruling may well
shape the ground rules for competition in the entire high-tech
economy. And he lambasted the government for its ``assault on
Windows, which promotes and creates commerce for the citizens of
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft case, Warden noted, focuses on the company's
``fights with competitors in a highly competitive, fast-moving
industry.'' And antitrust law, he observed, encourages competition
even when that rough-and-tumble competition hurts a company's
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law should not be rewritten to prevent Microsoft, or any
other company, from competing aggressively,'' Warden said.
</P>
<P>
   In the government's view, Microsoft is trying to change the
subject with arguments like these. ``We don't say competition is a
violation of the antitrust laws,'' Boies said. ``Our allegations
here deal with the means by which they compete. They are seriously
anti-competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the voluminous court record _ including thousands
of e-mails, internal Microsoft documents and months of witness
testimony _ show Microsoft to have been an arm-twisting monopolist,
whose corporate behavior stifled competition and harmed consumers.
Jackson's factual findings agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Boies opened his remarks by emphasizing that the Supreme Court
has long recognized that antitrust cases are ``especially
fact-based cases.'' And throughout his presentation, he repeatedly
made reference to the judge's findings of fact.
</P>
<P>
   But at one point, Jackson asked hard questions of Boies, too.
Antitrust experts say that the Government charge that is most
vulnerable is the allegation that Microsoft illegally tied its
Internet browser to a separate product, its industry-standard
Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson questioned Boies closely on the tying issue. Boies
argued that Microsoft's decision was not really a product design
decision, but more a mere ``bolting'' together of the browser and
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Boies was trying to recast the tying charge as a
contract restriction _ that is, PC makers who wanted Windows had to
take its Internet Explorer browsing software whether they wanted it
or not.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jackson appeared to be skeptical. What about the benefit,
he asked Boies, of the increased distribution of browser technology
resulting from Microsoft's decision to fold its browser into
Windows? ``I can't offset that _ one plausible benefit,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kevin O'Connor, an assistant attorney general for
Wisconsin, who represented the states, declared that ``Microsoft
has used virtually every tool of the monopolist's trade _ attempted
collusion, exclusionary contracts, tying, predation _ in a
coordinated scheme to eliminate threats to its monopoly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
