<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5064 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-JUDGE-MICROSOFT-BOS &LR;      02-22 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-MICROSOFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE QUESTIONS KEY MICROSOFT DEFENSE IN ANTITRUST SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Appearing before the same federal judge who branded
it a fierce monopolist, Microsoft Corp. returned to its antitrust
trial Tuesday to argue that it is a vigorous competitor in the
software market but that it never broke antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Federal District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who was
mainly silent during the 76 days of testimony in the case last
year, repeatedly challenged one of Microsoft's key defenses -- that
copyright law gives the company wide discretion in how it designs
and distributes software. He also questioned the degree to which he
was bound by an earlier appeals court ruling that was favorable to
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   And at another point, Jackson compared Microsoft's control of
the computer operating system market to John D. Rockefeller's grip
on the late 19th century oil market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't see a distinction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While such comments are not a reliable guide to a judge's
thinking, the analogy could not have cheered Microsoft. Rockefeller
was considered a ruthless monoplist, and the Supreme Court split
his Standard Oil Co. into more than 30 companies in 1911.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments Tuesday marked the opening of the second phase of
the government's antitrust case against Microsoft, which has the
potential to reset the competitive landscape for a variety of
technology markets for years to come. The trial is proceeding even
as the two sides are working with a mediator chosen by Jackson in
an effort to settle the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson on Nov. 5 issued ``findings of fact'' that said
Microsoft, the world's dominant software company and an engine of
the new economy, used its Windows monopoly to throttle competitors
and rob consumers of the benefits of competition, such as a wide
choice of products. Now, the court must rule on whether those
actions violated antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson finds that Microsoft acted unlawfully, he could
impose a range of penalities on the company, the most severe being
its breakup into separate units. His decision is almost certain to
be appealed, no matter how he rules.
</P>
<P>
   It is not illegal to operate a monopoly, but federal law bars a
company from using its monopoly powers to defend the monopoly or to
extend it into new markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 19 states say that Microsoft
threatened to withhold access to its Windows software from
companies that declined to hurt a Microsoft rival, Netscape
Communications Corp. The government says Microsoft wanted to crush
Netscape's Web browser and Sun Microsystem's Java product, both of
which had the potential to develop into rivals to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The government also says Microsoft adopted predatory pricing --
giving away its own browser for free -- in an attempt to crush
Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft lawyer John Warden Tuesday said the company's actions
were lawful, and that they were taken at a time when Netscape, not
Microsoft, was the dominant maker of Web browsers. Microsoft only
enhanced competition by offering consumers an alternative to
Netscape, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the debate Tuesday turned on whether Jackson, whose
harsh ``findings of fact'' suggest that he believes Microsoft acted
illegally, would be on sound legal footing to rule that the company
broke antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The government's lead lawyer, David Boies, listed the
anticompetitive actions that Jackson already detailed in his
``findings of fact.'' He then asked Jackson to ``try to imagine the
Supreme Court not finding a violation of antitrust law on these
facts. . . I think it is virtually impossible to imagine that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson, in questions to the lawyers, suggested that he is
wrestling with the degree to which a 1998 appeals court ruling
forces him to side with Microsoft on one key point.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends that in addition to charging nothing for
its browser, Microsoft built its browser into the Windows operating
system merely to drive Netscape out of business. The appeals court
for the District of Columbia, overturning Jackson in an earlier
Microsoft case, said in 1998 that a company could merge two
software products into one if it benefited consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Warden said the appeals court gave Microsoft a right to fold its
Web browser into Windows, because consumers find the combined
software easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   Boies replied that the appellate court itself ``recognized the
fragile and incomplete record it was working with,'' and that it
might rule differently in light of the expansive testimony laid out
in the current case.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson treated one of Microsoft's other defenses with
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   The company argued that Microsoft has rights under copyright law
to control the way computer makers use Windows. One issue in the
trial is whether Microsoft can control the first screen that users
see when they turn on a computer, and the icons that are initially
displayed on that screen.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson suggested that copyright law does not allow
Microsoft to dictate these features if its true goal is to keep a
competitor, such as Netscape, from appearing on the computer
screen. ``Copyright does not protect the conduct with which your
client is charged,'' Jackson said, but it was unclear if he meant
the comment as a definitive finding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
