<HEADER>
A5065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS23-COX     02-22 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis' ties to co-defendants stronger than first admitted
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In his only statement to police, Ray Lewis said the
other men in his limousine the morning after the Super Bowl were
``club people'' _ people he didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   He told police he had met co-defendant Reginald Oakley _ whom he
identified as A.J. Johnson _ at a club the night of the Super Bowl,
and that he didn't know the names of the other two men in the
limousine.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis was pals with Joseph Sweeting, the third defendant
charged with murder in the stabbings of two men.
</P>
<P>
   Sunseria Keith, Lewis' mother, knew it. So did Lewis' former
college teammate and fellow NFL All-Pro Warren Sapp.
</P>
<P>
   Both testified at a bond hearing for Lewis last week of a
long-standing relationship between Lewis and Sweeting.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, who often bragged about knowing Lewis, also had been a
roommate of another of Lewis' friends.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether Lewis had a personal relationship with
Sweeting and Oakley, both of whom have lengthy criminal records,
could be pivotal to the criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County, Ga., prosecutors have already started trying to
establish a connection between Lewis and his two co-defendants
indicted on murder and assault charges in the Jan. 31 double
slaying. Discrepancies between what Lewis originally told police
and testimony from various witnesses at last week's bond hearing
could provide a challenge for Lewis' attorneys as they try to
distance Lewis from Sweeting and Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   At a bond hearing for Lewis last week, prosecutors introduced as
evidence a framed photo of Lewis, Sweeting (whose nickname is
''Oomph'') and Yuille Garfield, a friend and former roommate of
Oakley's. The orange-framed photo was retrieved by investigators
from Lewis' $900,000 home in suburban Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' mother was shown the photo and testified to knowing
Sweeting as ''Oomph'' and said she'd seen him with her son,
specifically at Ravens home games.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Clint Rucker further pressed the
issue, asking Ravens owner, Art Modell if Sweeting, 34, frequently
had sideline passes. ''So would you be surprised to know that
Joseph Sweeting ... has been to Ravens home football games, has
stood on the sidelines, and has mingled with players, staff and
coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Modell said he had no knowledge of Sweeting, nor how he
maneuvered to get on the sidelines. Rucker did not offer evidence
that Sweeting had access to sideline passes for Ravens games.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp, NFL defensive player of the year, testified that Sweeting
and a frequent sidekick of his in South Florida, Toby Baine, were
often seen at University of Miami football practices while he and
Lewis were there, and that Sweeting was familiar to Miami players.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was always there,'' Sapp said. ''I mean, everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Shown the photo of Sweeting with an arm draped around the
shoulder of Lewis and Garfield, Sapp said: ''Looks like three guys
having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rucker asked Sapp if he was aware Sweeting had purchased three
knives the day before the murder.
</P>
<P>
   No, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rucker also portrayed the co-defendants as drug dealers, asking
Sapp: ''So you would be surprised if you knew that Ray Lewis
associated with drug dealers, wouldn't you? Wouldn't sound like
your running partner, would it?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Sapp what was meant by ``associated,'' Rucker replied:
''I mean flying them into Atlanta to celebrate the Super Bowl,
allow them to stay in his hotel room, ride around town for a week
in his limousine, attend autograph signings with him while he's
here in town, go to clubs, sit at the table, buy drinks for him, go
to strip clubs and buy table dances for him. That kind of friend.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, it would'' surprise me, Sapp said.
</P>
<P>
   At Garfield's Phase II Beauty Salon in Baltimore, Oakley was
known to brag about the celebrities he knew, dropping the names of
Lewis, movie star Denzel Washington and members of the R&AMP;B group
Dru Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts suggest that Lewis' attorneys will attempt to
distance him from the other defendants as the case unfolds,
possibly seeking a separate trial for Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Greta Van Susteren, co-host of CNN's show ``Burden of Proof,''
said she believes Lewis will act as though he has a distant
relationship with the two other defendants. The two others look
more ``rugged,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, whom Lewis originally identified as A.J. Johnson, had
his ''head busted'' during the fracas, Lewis told police.
</P>
<P>
   When news spread that Oakley was wanted on charges of murder, he
called his grandmother and father to tell them his version of what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he got hit upside his head with a champagne
bottle,'' said John Oakley. ``He said he didn't know what happened
after that. He said he wasn't guilty, he wouldn't do nothing like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Testimony at last week's bond hearing underscored the
substantial number of witnesses both sides may eventually bring
into court.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors brought up the name of Jaye Roberson, whom they
described as Lewis' girlfriend, and three other women who were in
the limo during the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness, Keith Ponder, who had shot footage of
celebrities at a club prior to the incident, testified to arriving
upon an argument between Lewis' friends and another group. He
described Lewis as a ''peacemaker,'' but Ponder acknowledged the
two victims hadn't been stabbed when he left the scene. Ponder
testified to there being ''at least 50'' people within 30 feet of
Lewis' limousine when he left.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Keeler, whose second-floor apartment overlooks the crime
scene, said she witnessed the victims being beaten by four or five
men, adding there were ''tons of people all around.''
</P>
<P>
   One witness, in particular, Keeler said, interceded and tried to
help the victims. Police interviewed the man, described as black,
about 6-foot-5 and 300 pounds and driving a mid-1980s Honda, at the
crime scene but he was not called to appear at the bond hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and the co-defendants are charged in the stabbing deaths
of Jacinth Baker, 21, and Richard Lollar, 24, after a night of
post-Super Bowl partying in Buckhead, Atlanta's entertainment
district. Lewis, 24, is free on $1 million bond. Initially, Lewis
told police his ''homeboy'' Kwame King, a friend from Lakeland,
Fla., was among the group. Then he said King had left earlier, and
that he had given the clothes he was wearing that night to King,
who apparently had taken them with him.
</P>
<P>
   King refused to comment on what happened to the clothes when
contacted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
