<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MALAYSIA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA AIRLINES MAY PICK AIRBUS OVER BOEING FOR $1 BILLION
ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Long-time Boeing customer Malaysia Airlines Wednesday
may announce an order for more than $1 billion worth of airplanes
from Airbus Industrie.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing Co. has been pushing hard to sell Malaysia's national
airline its next generation 737, but the carrier has apparently
decided instead to buy upwards of 30 Airbus A320s, according to
people familiar with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   European governments have lobbed the airline hard in recent
weeks to go with Airbus over Boeing as it seeks to replace about 40
older model 737s in its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia Airlines is also talking with Airbus about buying its
A340-500 and A340-600 long-haul widebody jets that are now in
development.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has been counting on Malaysia Airlines to buy its planned
777X, which will compete against the two planes from Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Airbus for the single-aisle planes could hurt
Boeing's chances of selling the airline its 777X, industry analysts
said. Increasingly, airlines like to stick with one manufacturer
for both their widebody and single-aisle fleet needs because it
saves them money in maintenance and pilot training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would would be quite a blow for Boeing if they decided not
to go with the 777X,'' said Paul Nisbet, analyst with JSA Research
in Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Asian carrier has a memorandum of understanding
with Boeing to buy the 777X, it apparently has grown impatient with
Boeing's repeated delays in launching the longer-range version of
its 777, Nisbet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their original preference was to go with Boeing,'' Nisbet
said.
</P>
<P>
   The respected industry publication Flight International recently
reported that Malaysia Airlines is also upset that Boeing chose
General Electric as the sole supplier of engines for the 777X. The
airline now operates nine 777s, all of which are powered by
Rolls-Royce engines.
</P>
<P>
   The A340-500/600 planes will be powered by Rolls-Royce engines.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine said Malaysia Airlines could order as many as 10 of
the A340-500/600 jets from Airbus. They would replace older Boeing
747s and would be used to open new non-stop transpacific routes to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how close Airbus and Malaysia Airlines may be to
reaching any agreement on a widebody order.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus has scheduled a news conference Wednesday at the Asian
aerospace air show in Singapore, apparently to announce the order
for the single-aisle planes. The show runs throughout this week.
Bloomberg News reported the order is for 30 jets worth $1.4 billion
at list prices. Airlines are almost always able to get better than
list prices, especially for such large orders.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia Airlines now has mostly Boeing jets in its fleet of
about 90 planes, including the 747, 777, 737 and the MD-10. But it
also operates 10 A330-300 widebody jets, according to the airline's
web site.
</P>
<P>
   This would be the first big airplane order that either Boeing or
Airbus has announced in 2000. Last year, Airbus significantly beat
Boeing for the first time ever in landing new airplane orders.
</P>
<P>
   The order reflects the upturn in Asia's economic climate. A
financial crisis that swept through Asia two years ago crippled
many airlines in that region, forcing them to cancel or delay
orders with both Boeing and Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing postponed the launch of its 777X because of the sagging
fortunes of Asia airlines, which are the principal customers for
the new plane on long routes across the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Asian economies are improving, Boeing has stepped up
efforts to sign launch customers for the 777X. It reported has more
than two dozen commitments, but has not yet announced a launch
date. It could get approval to do so at a meeting of the Boeing
board of directors that is set for Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Potential customers for the 777X include Japan Air Lines, Cathay
Pacific, Singapore Airlines and leasing giant International Lease
Finance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan-based Eva Airways said last week that it will buy several
of the 777X jets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
