<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5067 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JEWS-IN-PALESTINE-FIL     02-22 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWS-IN-PALESTINE-FILM-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CZARIST RUSSIA'S JEWS, A LOOK AT A PROMISED LAND 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27)
</HEADLINE>
   (af) 
 J. Hoberman is the senior film critic for The Village Voice and the
author of ``Bridge of Light: Yiddish Film Between Two Worlds.'' 
By J. HOBERMAN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several empires back, on the eve of World War I, the ghettos and
market towns of the Russian Pale were transfixed by a sensational
new motion picture attraction. The feature-length documentary ``The
Life of the Jews in Palestine'' was, according to the future
Israeli film exhibitor Yaacov Davidon, then a young man, received
with ``indescribable enthusiasm.'' He said, ``Tears of happiness
gleamed in the eyes of Jewish audiences, thirsty for redemption.''
</P>
<P>
   In another sort of redemption, ``The Life of the Jews in
Palestine'' _ which was produced in 1913 by the Odessa-based
Mizrakh Company and presumed to be lost for some 80 years _ has
resurfaced in New York. Showing on March 6 and 7, in an excellent
new print with English intertitles at the Museum of Modern Art,
Noah Sokolovsky's 78-minute silent film is quite likely the rarest
of the rarities featured in the museum's 10-program tribute to
France's national film archives, the Centre Nationale de la
Cinematographie.
</P>
<P>
   For its producer as well as its original audiences, ``The Life
of the Jews in Palestine'' was something of a celluloid aliya, or
pilgrimage. In April 1913, the Mizrakh crew boarded a ship in
Odessa harbor and steamed through the Black Sea and the Bosporus to
the port of Jaffa, in what was then the Ottoman Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   After creating some panoramic views of the brand-new Tel Aviv _
an impressive grid of houses and boulevards whose construction had
begun only four years before _ the filmmakers spent the next six
weeks touring the Jewish settlements of Judea, Carmel and the
Galilee, documenting cooperatively managed orange groves and
vineyards, as well as portraying a number of local heroes _ Tel
Aviv's first mayor, Meir Dizengoff, presiding over the City
Council; Joseph Trumpeldor (a founder of the World War I Jewish
Legion), plowing his fields with his one remaining arm; the
middle-aged Biluim of Gedera (student radicals of the 1880s)
celebrating their village's 30th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   As suggested by the rubric Mizrakh (the Hebrew word for east),
Sokolovsky was an active Zionist, and his film _ at once
straightforward travelogue and homespun pageant of parading
schoolchildren and athletic contests _ is a vision of Jewish
productivity. Populated by industrious workers and fit, healthy
farmers, by Ashkenazic pioneers laboring beside their Sephardic
co-religionists, the Land of Milk and Honey has been reclaimed by
the presence of Jewish dairies and beekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation is overwhelmingly secular; not until the
filmmakers reach the northern town of Tiberius do they show a
traditional yeshiva. Still, the landmarks of Jerusalem, like Jaffa
Gate, David's Tower, the Western Wall (with worshiping Hasidim
ducking away from the camera), as well as other biblical sites like
Rachel's Tomb, the Cave of the Patriarchs, the Dead Sea and the
River Jordan, must have appeared as little short of miraculous to
the Russian Jews who thronged to see ``The Life of the Jews in
Palestine.''
</P>
<P>
   Sokolovsky's documentary was considered newsworthy within the
Yishuv (the Jewish settlements in Palestine), and some of the
scenes were proudly staged for the cameras. Reporting on the
harvest filmed at the venerable Rishon le Zion settlement, a local
journalist wrote that ``when its turn came to appear before the
great Hebrew public outside the borders of the country, the
settlement stripped itself of its weekday clothes and all became
extremely national _ not one outside laborer was filmed!''
</P>
<P>
   The journalist observed that the mandate for self-employment was
heeded; farmers' daughters, for example, became grape pickers:
``Their fingers that are used to drum upon the piano keys were this
time skilled in passing with swift movements among the grape
clusters and almond boughs,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Life of the Jews in Palestine'' had its world premiere
late in the summer of 1913 as a special event at the 11th Zionist
Congress in Vienna. Within six months, the movie played more than
30 separate engagements throughout Europe and Russia. In Ukraine,
the enthusiastic crowds became the subject of secret police
reports; in Galicia, special screenings were organized for
ultra-Orthodox audiences under rabbinical supervision. Sokolovsky's
documentary was exhibited in New York as well, opening in early
1914 as ``Life in the Holy Land.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's showings in the Yishuv proved the most controversial.
Although ``The Life of the Jews in Palestine'' was praised by
right-wing Zionists, it was criticized by the Zionist left for
idealizing pioneer life while ignoring the presence of the local
Arabs (who are shown, in supporting roles, in only a few shots).
</P>
<P>
   Despite some scraps of badly decomposed nitrate footage found in
the possession of a Bronx film collector, ``The Life of the Jews in
Palestine'' was scarcely more than a memory when an unmarked but
nearly complete print was discovered (without intertitles) three
years ago in the French center's vaults by the archivist Eric Le
Roy. ( Le Roy is scheduled to introduce the Museum of Modern Art's
screenings.)
</P>
<P>
   The film's survival in France was less a factor of exhibition
patterns than of Russian underdevelopment _ the original negative
had been shipped by Mizrakh from Odessa to Paris to be processed by
the Gaumont film laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Le Roy's find was identified by the Israeli film historian and
filmmaker Yaakov Gross and restored in time to be shown in 1998 by
the Jerusalem Film Archives on the 50th anniversary of Israeli
statehood. Gross, who had previously tracked ``The Life of the Jews
in Palestine'' to the Soviet documentary film archives in
Krasnogorsk only to discover the film cans empty (``even though
they were registered in the most official manner and were under the
watchful eyes of Lenin, whose portraits were still on the walls''),
regards the existence of the French archive material as nearly
miraculous. ``It was like finding documentation of Moses; almost
like images of Moses descending Mount Sinai,'' he told a French
journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Sokolovsky's international hit _ which inspired a similar Polish
production, still lost _ was not his last production. Mizrakh soon
after released a topical four-reel drama, ``War and the Jews,''
featuring the ``heroic act'' of a Jewish double agent. Over the
18-month period following the fall of the czar in February 1917,
the Odessa studio produced a number of literary movies on the
subject of pre-revolutionary Jewish life. These adaptations by the
Yiddish writers Sholom Aleichem and I.L. Peretz have yet to be
rediscovered; if they were, they might seem even more exotic than
``The Life of the Jews in Palestine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
