<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5068 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ASBESTOS-GRACE-BOS &LR;      02-22 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASBESTOS-GRACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
W.R. GRACE SUED OVER ASBESTOS-TAINTED INSULATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ W.R. Grace Co. was hit with three class-action lawsuits
Tuesday, one filed in Boston on behalf of homeowners nationwide who
have asbestos-tainted Zonolite Attic Insulation in their homes, and
the other two in Montana, where the company operated a mine and
mill.
</P>
<P>
   The suit filed in US District Court in Boston by Edward M.
Lindholm accuses Grace of fraud, deception and enriching itself at
homeowners' expense for failing to warn the public that the
Zonolite insulation it sold from 1963 through 1984 contained
tremolite asbestos. Grace's Cambridge, Mass. Costruction Products
Division oversaw its Attic Insulation line.
</P>
<P>
   Two class-action suits filed Tuesday in federal court in
Missoula, Mont., seek damages for all property owners in Libby,
where Grace operated a mine and mill until 1990, and damages for
all residents exposed to tremolite asbestos. Grace got its
vermiculite, the mineral that was the main ingredient in its Attic
Insulation, from its Libby mine. Asbestos was naturally occurring
in the Libby vermiculite.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is asbestos contamination in settled dust throughout
Libby in homes and areas outside,'' said Edward Westbrook, a
Charlestown, S.C., attorney with one of the five firms that filed
the Montana cases.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Attorney Kenneth Gilman, who represents Lindholm and
filed the suit in US District Court in Boston, is urging a judge to
order Grace to notify homeowners of the dangers of living with
Zonolite in their houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``All class members should be given an opportunity to inspect
repair and remove Zonolite and to attempt to prevent personal
injury,'' the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gilman nor Lindholm, who is described only as the owner
of a home in Essex County, could be reached Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is seeking punitive and compensatory damages from Grace
and wants the company to foot the bill for Zonolite removal and
attorneys fees for Lindholm and other homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   William Corcoran, a spokesman for Grace, said, ``We believe our
Attic Insulation is a safe product and the lawsuit is without
merit. We've been very open with the governmental agencies and with
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported last week that Zonolite, a type of loose-fill
insulation, contains asbestos, but Grace officials fought to keep
warning labels off the product.
</P>
<P>
   Grace, which discontinued its Attic Insulation in 1984, knew as
far back as 1963 about the asbestos, but feared public disclosure
would hurt sales, according to memos from high-ranking Grace
officials.
</P>
<P>
   An internal Grace memo dated May 24, 1977 and obtained by the
Globe, revealed that the company was concerned by an in-house study
that revealed mortality rates were five times the national rate
among ex-employees at the Libby plant.
</P>
<P>
   But the memo reaffirmed Grace's opposition to warning labels on
Zonolite, saying, ``We believe that a decision to affix asbestos
warning labels to our products would result in substantial sales
losses.''
</P>
<P>
   W.R. Grace, today worth $1.5 billion, has paid out $1 billion as
a result of asbestos claims and expects to pay $1 billion more,
according to Corcoran. Many of Grace's claims are due to its past
manufacture of Monokote Fireproofing, a spray insulation that
contained asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Correspondent Adrianne Appel contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
