<HEADLINE>
IN IRAN, THEY'RE ALL REFORMERS NOW _ EVEN THE HANGMEN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: A post-Iranian election analysis)   (This compelling 875-word (trimmed) ``separate-buy'' article _ ``a
Persian tale of love and hope'' _ is from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper
in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A 300-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 675. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,175
WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN _ This is a Persian tale, of hope and love and
generosity. It is also, like all Persian stories, not as simple as
it seems; a trifle opaque perhaps, elliptical, full of heroes who
might not all really be heroes. And it may yet prove to have an
unhappy, tragic ending.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, like the French Revolution and the Russian
Revolution, the Iranian Revolution finally fell under the control
of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Could any election have been more historic in the Middle East,
that dark terrain of dictatorships and torture chambers and secret
policemen? Could any people have broken free of their chains more
gently, more elegantly, and with so much trust?
</P>
<P>
   How else could one interpret the tens of thousands who queued
for hours outside the Husseiniya Ershad mosque _ in which Dr.
Shariati and his friends once protested the Shah's autocratic rule
_ to vote for the friends and supporters of the man they all
adored, President Mohamed Khatami?
</P>
<P>
   And when I talked to them, they all spoke of integrity and
democracy and the mistakes of the past, the men in their jeans and
cheap coats, the women in their ``Hejab'' covering, showing
infinite courtesy to the foreigner who had come to ask his usual
blundering, foolish questions.
</P>
<P>
   I even asked Hojatolislam Seyed Abdulwahed Moussavi Lari, the
Iranian interior minister watching the voters fill in their forms
in the mosque, what historians would write about the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will say...that the people came to vote because they
wanted freedom and to determine their own destiny,'' he announced.
</P>
<P>
   The West has always consistently and willfully misunderstood
Iran and we were at it again Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government and, of course, the American press and CNN
and all the usual suspects were billing the elections as a crucial
struggle between ``reformers'' and ``hard-liners,'' the poll which
could give President Khatami, elected with 70 percent of the vote
last May, a parliament that would at last break the power of the
``conservatives,'' the ``radicals,'' the ``extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   America, of course, says it would like Khatami's supporters to
win _ although I am not sure this is true because America likes
dictatorships in the Middle East and, with one exception, fears
real democracy in the region.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, as usual, the world is being presented with a
partial, skewed version of events here.
</P>
<P>
   Which is where this Persian tale becomes opaque. For look at
some of the men who now say they are supporting Khatami, who are
now calling themselves ``reformers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafsanjani, Mohtashemi, Karroubi: the list is endless, all men
from the past, a few of them _ Mohtashemi comes to mind _ with
blood on their hands and a number of ``pro-Khatamists'' (not,
mercifully, candidates) with blood all over them.
</P>
<P>
   Why, wasn't that friendly Ayatollah Khalkhali advocating reform
this month the very same Ayatollah Khalkhali whom I interviewed in
Qom all of 20 years ago, after he had hanged men like thrushes in
Evin Prison, including a 14-year-old old boy for whom, he said, he
had no conscience because he had ``sent him to heaven?''
</P>
<P>
   And what of those stories now moving through the bazaars? In the
decade up to 1998, so they say, up to 100 dissidents were
``disappeared'' in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Akbar Gangi, probably the finest Iranian investigative
journalist _ there are precious few around _ is demanding a truth
commission to find out who ordered their murders.
</P>
<P>
   How high did their death warrant go? Wasn't Ali Akbar Mohtashemi
an interior minister after the revolution? Wasn't Ali Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani the president when all those men were put to death?
</P>
<P>
   And isn't that the same Rafsanjani who is now a pro-Khatami
``reformist,'' aching, no doubt, to become speaker of the new
pro-Khatami parliament?
</P>
<P>
   So what is this new parliament going to look like? It may call
itself ``reformist'' but _ like a cup of tea that is steadily mixed
with coffee _ it may not taste like tea when it is drunk. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (300-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 675) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I put this point to the men waiting to vote outside the mosque
in the Seyed Khandan district. Wasn't there a danger, I asked, that
the parliament's 290 members would look rather similar to the
gentlemen who filled the previous anti-Khatami assembly?
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't the ``reformist'' movement being diluted? Weren't there
one or two men who might be seeking to avoid retribution and keep
their profits by joining the winning team?
</P>
<P>
   One of the men told me to read a copy of Thursday's ``Asre
Azadegam'' which had listed all the ``bad events'' since the
revolution, and another said _ using the same words as a woman
candidate I had met earlier _ that ``there was a kind of change in
these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Some had admitted their mistakes, he said. And no one had to
vote for them. Had not one ``reformist'' party refused to put
Rafsanjani on their list because he was not ``Shafafiyat'' _ a
lovely new Iranian word that means ``straight-talking?''
</P>
<P>
   A publisher of political works and modern Iranian literature,
this bespectacled voter _ note that they haven't yet reached the
point of wanting their names printed _ insisted kindly that the
``men of the past'' had changed their attitude towards society.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference from the first period of the
revolution,'' he said. ``These men have learned to pay attention to
what we say and what we want.
</P>
<P>
   ``In its initial stage, our revolution was like the French and
Russian revolutions. At first they thought they had to be radical
but little by little they understood that radicalism isn't good in
any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Such trust he reposed in the men he was electing, such
simplicity. But it was moving all the same. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF 300-WORD TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,175) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People laugh in Tehran again now. Their jokes have become
powerful, daring.
</P>
<P>
   One of the pro-Khatami parties has a slogan _ ``Ei Iran, Ei
marze, pourgohar'' _ which means ``Oh Iran, the precious
homeland.'' Note the lack of the world ``Islamic.'' And note _ much
more to the point _ that this was the title of a popular song
during the reign of the Shah.
</P>
<P>
   Was this really the same Tehran I remember 21 years ago? The
same people? The same proud, stubborn, brave, single-minded race
that walked in their tens of thousands into the Shah's guns?
</P>
<P>
   I watched that extraordinary revolution and the world seemed to
have changed. America was no longer able to maintain its power
throughout the Middle East. A dynasty had been swept away in
Robespierre blood and fury. But yesterday Friday, instead of
shouting ``Death to America,'' they queued for hours to vote for a
new, gentler revolution that would belong to them.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could share all their faith but like all Persian tales,
I think this needs a familiar sign off: To Be Continued. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
