A5076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WOMEN-BIZ23-COX     02-22 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-BIZ23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Female business owners pump profit into Georgia economy
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia's female-owned businesses are a powerful
economic engine, according to a study released Tuesday at the state
Capitol by the Center for Policy Alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   These companies' annual revenue in Georgia tops $182 billion,
giving the state a sixth-place ranking in the nation. Female-owned
firms also employ more than 1 million people, the Washington,
D.C.-based nonprofit group reports.
</P>
<P>
   Since the state now boasts nearly 250,000 companies owned by
women, CPA President Linda Tarr-Whelan says it's time to take the
next steps _ collect data, open up business procurement processes
and address the benefits and retirement issues that this powerful
new segment of the economy will need.
</P>
<P>
   Female-owned companies employ one-quarter of U.S. workers and
generate $3.6 trillion in annual sales, she said. Yet, Tarr-Whelan
noted, only 18 states currently collect any data about female-owned
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But today's business climate for women is still a far cry from
the old days when it was tough for a woman in the Peach State to
get her own credit card, much less the capital to start her own
business.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Hanenkrat, president of JSH Building Services, a
25-year-old commercial cleaning firm, said that now ``a great new
generation is out there doing great things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A new cycle has begun, as some women my age are retiring or
selling their companies, merging into larger firms or even
investing in other people's start-ups,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She recalls the mid-1980s when a handful of women started Women
Business Owners of Atlanta. It joined the National Association of
Women Business Owners in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's chapter of NAWBO now has 130 members, said Dale
Miller, corporate partners chair and owner of Corporate Promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Members' businesses include computer companies, construction
firms, employment services, health-care companies, and advertising
companies.
</P>
<P>
   One of her group's goals is keeping the pipeline open for new
female entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numbers draw more numbers, and (that will help us) have a
voice with the state Legislature,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
