<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-2TAKES-N     02-22 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CAMP SEES FEW RISKS IN STAYING ON THE OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take to move by 9 p.m. ET)  
(nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Anyone tuning in to the Democratic debate Monday
night saw two extremely aggressive candidates going full tilt at
each other. Bill Bradley, who trails in all the polls behind Vice
President Al Gore, had obvious reasons to try to make his mark. But
Gore's nostril-flaring performance, and his combative campaigning
over the last few weeks, have raised questions about why, when he
appears to be so far ahead in the race for the party's presidential
nomination, he feels the need to be so pugnacious.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers say that the vice president has several reasons to
keep the heat on Bradley and that there are few risks in doing so.
</P>
<P>
   The central fact is that Bradley, whose campaign has seemed
desultory and dispirited since he lost the New Hampshire primary
three weeks ago, has needed to change the dynamic of the race. The
debate Monday night in Harlem presented him with an opportunity.
The Gore camp anticipated that Bradley would intensify his
criticisms of the vice president, and Gore was fully prepared, even
boning up with his usual Bradley stand-in, Tom Downey, the former
congressman, playing his role with a new militancy.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's posture in the debate only mirrors his posture in the
campaign at large. Gore wants the world to know he is a fighter _ a
quality that he needs to assert now to prod core Democrats to the
primaries and a reputation he needs to build to woo independents in
November.
</P>
<P>
   He is constantly growling to his audiences, ``I want to fight
for you!'' He is running a television commercial that shows him, in
fast clips with a driving beat, as a fighter _ against pollution
and drug companies and for Medicare and Medicaid. At a Democratic
party speech in San Jose earlier this month, he questioned
Bradley's loyalty to the party and his commitment to the cause. He
told reporters last week that his job was to ``pour on the gas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy is to campaign very hard, prosecute this case
very vigorously,'' said Bob Shrum, a top Gore adviser. ``Gore is
going to go out and make his case all over the country in a
national primary, which is what this is.''
</P>
<P>
   This is reflected in Gore's relentless campaign schedule, which
often includes four or five events a day and has him traveling in
the wee hours. Tuesday was a rare day off in a campaign that has
been crisscrossing the country and all time zones. On Wednesday he
heads to Florida, South Carolina and New York, and this weekend he
begins a West Coast swing. He is keeping up a pace more often seen
in a general election in the fall than in the winter primaries.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is the simple fact that Gore does not yet have the
nomination. Although he has pulled away from Bradley in the polls,
his campaign believes he cannot let up until he has locked up the
nomination. And yet, while Gore's standing in the polls is
improving, surveys show that voters still have a lingering doubt
about his capacity as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that, Gore has found success as a combatant,
particularly in debate formats. He came to the presidential
campaign with a history as a fierce debater. Remember Ross Perot?
And in his previous match-ups against Bradley, Gore has found an
easy foil, someone who, despite his years in competitive
basketball, has not been quick to respond or defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley was given a chance in Monday's encounter at the
Apollo Theater to say that Gore did not have the character to be
president, he offered a typically ambivalent response. On the one
hand, Bradley said, ``If Al were the nominee I would support him.''
But he then delivered the heart of his newly packaged criticism of
Gore, branding him a ``conservative,'' and adding that he ``did not
support national health insurance, had an 84 percent right-to-life
voting record, and was the poster boy for the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, wagging his finger constantly, laced his comments with
derision and sarcasm and kept accusing Bradley of false charges.
</P>
<P>
   He called Bradley ``desperate'' and in a few rehearsed zingers
said he was ``the only Democrat in America who misses Ken Starr''
and nearly accused him of initiating racial profiling, saying:
``Racial profiling practically began in New Jersey, senator.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley camp says Gore is especially fired up these days
because he is worried that Bradley could still turn the race
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore knows that his support is very soft,'' said Cornel West,
a top Bradley adviser. West also said that Gore should be concerned
about the Republican contest, where Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
who has strong backing from independents, is battling Gov. George
Bush of Texas. ``If McCain gets pushed out, independents begin to
look toward Bradley,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
