<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PAPER-MERGERS-NYT &LR;      02-22 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPER-MERGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINNISH PAPER GIANT STORA ENSO TO BUY CONSOLIDATED PAPERS, INC. 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that marks the fourth major paper-industry merger or
acquisition in less than two weeks, the big Finnish paper company
Stora Enso said Tuesday that it would acquire Consolidated Papers
Inc., based in Wisconsin Rapids, Wis. The deal is valued at $3.9
billion, plus the assumption of $900 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The merged company's combined sales of $13.2 billion in 1999
place it a distant second in revenue to the International Paper
Co., which sells a bigger proportion of high-priced stock, and had
$25 billion in sales. The new company, though, will probably be the
world's largest producer in terms of paper tonnage.
</P>
<P>
   Stora Enso is paying $44 a share for Consolidated, a rich
premium over the company's preannouncement closing price of $26.
Investors thought Consolidated got the better deal: its stock
jumped $10 on Tuesday to $36, while Stora Enso's shares lost 2
euros, to 11.10 euros, in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts hailed the merger as another sign that the
fragmented paper industry was building a global business. ``This
sea change that we've been expecting is finally happening,'' said
Kathryn F. McAuley, a Brown Brothers Harriman analyst, ``and we're
seeing real globalization of the industry,
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, UPM-Kymmene, also of Finland, bought
Champion International, creating a behemoth in coated papers;
Abitibi-Consolidated bought Donohue Inc., creating a leader in
newsprint, and International Paper, which bought Union Camp last
year, said it would acquire Shorewood Packaging, which had been
embroiled in a takeover battle with the Chesapeake Corp. when
International Paper made its offer.
</P>
<P>
   More deals are in the works. The New Zealand conglomerate
Fletcher Challenge has said it wants to sell its newsprint
operations. Norske Skog is said to be looking for a North American
acquisition. And on Friday, St. Laurent Paperboard of Canada said
it was in merger talks. It did not specify with whom, but the name
swirling around Wall Street was that of Smurfit-Stone Container,
the world's biggest corrugated-box maker _ itself formed when
Jefferson Smurfit gobbled up the Stone Container Corp. in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the mergers, paper remains a highly fragmented
industry. ``You can still find 30 or 40 publicly traded paper
companies in the U.S., and probably another 15 in Canada,'' said
Mark Wilde of Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown, noting that even
International Paper, the industry leader, accounts for only about 5
percent of the 300 million tons of paper produced worldwide each
year.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of cohesion has cost the industry dearly. Most
companies expanded wildly when paper prices started to soar in the
mid-'90s. When economic troubles overseas put the brakes on demand,
the industry found itself drowning in capacity. Prices and profit
plummeted late in 1995, and did not recover until last year.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, industries like publishing and manufacturing, which
are prime customers for paper, have been consolidating into global
powerhouses that want to deal with global suppliers. ``They want to
deal with the same supplier all over the world,'' McAuley said,
``but they don't want their paper shipped to Chicago from
Finland.''
</P>
<P>
   In such an environment, consolidation may have been inevitable.
The European paper companies began merging several years ago and
the resulting big producers, like Stora Enso, are now looking to
North America for merger partners. North American companies,
though, are still joining mainly with each other. ``The American
companies may be missing chances to expand into higher-growth
markets,'' Wilde said.
</P>
<P>
   And the industry has returned to good times. After a dismal 1997
and 1998, most companies were profitable last year, and McAuley,
for one, predicts that profits will remain robust through 2002.
Consolidation can only improve the profit picture, as merged
companies close older plants and eliminate administrators.
</P>
<P>
   The result has not yet translated to higher prices. ``We may see
more pricing power but we're far from being an oligopoly yet,''
McAuley said.
</P>
<P>
   The deals may help smooth out some of the wild swings that have
characterized paper pricing. And they are likely to buoy profit.
``It doesn't mean anything for prices,'' said John V. Faraci,
International Paper's chief financial officer, ``but it's enabling
all of us to get costs out and to put more money into product
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say stockholders will settle for nothing less.
``Shareholders have made it clear they want financial returns
improved,'' Wilde said, ``that they want CEO's to stop building
plants and start rationalizing their businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-AVERY23-COX     02-22 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-AVERY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Avery's a Brave again
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ All it took was some small talk during
spring-training stretching, and look who's back.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves signed Steve Avery to a minor-league contract
Tuesday, giving him a chance to return to the rotation he once
helped to headline. Avery was MVP of the 1991 National League
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   It happened because Braves manager Bobby Cox and John Smoltz
were shooting the breeze before the workout for pitchers and
catchers at the Disney complex Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avery's name came up, and I asked who he was with, and Smoltz
said nobody,'' Cox said. ``I said, `Give me his number. We'll call
him.'''
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, Avery was throwing his first side session with
the Braves since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been dying to get down here,'' said Avery, who is coming
off Aug. 5 shoulder surgery. ``I'm sitting (at home in Michigan) in
the snow, watching all the spring-training highlights on TV, and
... it's driving me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery, the third pick overall of the 1988 draft, spent the first
seven years of his 10-year career with the Braves but hasn't been
himself since the mid-'90s. He had a losing record in four of the
past five years, and his ERA hasn't been below 4.00 since 1993. The
speed on Avery's fastball had dipped to the upper-70s. He finally
underwent arthroscopic surgery to repair a frayed rotator cuff,
remove a bone spur and reattach his labrum to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not completely recovered,'' general manager John
Schuerholz said, ``but we think we can help him in his
rehabilitation right here, and it gives us an opportunity to look
at another real quality, still very young pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery has been throwing off the mound since January and said he
thinks he'll be ready for the start of the season. After watching
him throw in January, Reds assistant general manager Doc Rodgers
said, ``Wow, that's the old Steve Avery.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of a mix-up over Avery's free-agency status, the Reds
apparently didn't realize they wouldn't be able to sign him until
May 1, which left Avery thinking about going elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   He will compete with Bruce Chen to become the fifth starter.
Terry Mulholland is another option, although the Braves would like
to have him in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Avery) is 29, smart as the dickens about how to pitch and
stubborn, too,'' Cox said. ``I look at it as drafting somebody out
of high school. It's a risk, but ...I like his chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Reds management reportedly suspected that Avery hid injuries so
contract bonuses would kick in for innings pitched and appearances.
Avery denies it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have said, `I can still go out there. I can handle a
little bit of pain,''' Avery said. ``This year, I made a pact to
myself that, if I felt like I did last year, to stop. It's one
thing not to go out there 100 percent, but there were times when I
was 50 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
