<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5088 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JAPANESE-EDO-PAINTING     02-22 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-EDO-PAINTINGS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JAPANESE TREASURE MOVES TO THE MIDWEST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS, Ind. _ Over 20 years, Alan Strassman, a Boston
investment manager, collected 95 Japanese paintings from the Edo
period (1615-1848).
</P>
<P>
   Twenty were gloriously painted screens that included depictions
of a field of tall grasses glowing gold in the moonlight, corpulent
gods wrestling, evocative scenes from ``The Tales of Genji,'' wild
dancing in the streets near a tea house and a Noh theater
performance in an aristocrat's courtyard. His collection became one
of the largest and finest of its kind in private hands.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, when he bought his first scroll painting _ which
showed a tiger gazing at the moon (prompting him later to call his
Edo works the Tiger Collection) _ Strassman was dazzled by, as he
put it, the ``unique flat perspective'' in Japanese art. ``It was
striking and beautiful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was also impressed by the history and stories depicted in
these works on paper and silk, and soon assembled a library of
1,400 books on the subject. ``Much of Edo painting has roots in
mythology, roots in history, roots in some kind of narrative that
is deep in the Japanese psyche,'' he said. ``There is something
literary that lies behind each image, making these paintings
especially meaningful.''
</P>
<P>
   As the collection grew, he enjoyed planning exhibitions of the
works in his home, frequently changing them to avoid overexposure
to light and moisture. He even had a vault built there to store
them. Their fragility and his space limitations made it impossible
to view all of his collection at one time.
</P>
<P>
   But Strassman will finally be able to see most of these Edo
paintings when they go on view in ``300 Years of Japanese Painting:
New Treasures for Indianapolis,'' an exhibition that opens at the
Indianapolis Museum of Art on May 20 and remains until Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the museum acquired 70 works from the Tiger
Collection, including the 20 screens. The museum paid more than $7
million, and Strassman donated five screens and his library.
</P>
<P>
   The show will not include 25 scrolls that Strassman still owns;
he plans to give them to the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston, where
he is a trustee and was board president from 1993 to 1997. But the
exhibition will also include five Edo scrolls that were bought by
the Indianapolis museum from Leighton Longhi, the New York dealer
from whom Strassman acquired most of his Edo art.
</P>
<P>
   ``These works strengthen the collection at key points,'' said
James Robinson, the museum's curator of Asian art.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisitions, with a total value of $10 million, represent
the largest purchase of Japanese art by an American museum, and are
the Indianapolis Museum of Art's second-largest purchase, exceeded
only by the $30 million it paid in 1998 for 101 paintings and
prints by Paul Gauguin and his Pont-Aven followers.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's Japanese additions complement these works as well
as works by other early modernists of the late 19th century, most
of whom were influenced by Edo paintings. The acquisition more than
doubled the museum's Japanese art holdings; its Edo collection now
ranks with those of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Museum of
Fine Arts in Boston, the Smithsonian's Freer Gallery and the Los
Angeles County Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``These works, which are in immaculate condition, are of a
quality and rarity no longer available in the art market at any
price,'' said Bret Waller, the Indianapolis museum's director.
``The weakness of the economy in Asia in recent years became a
major factor in making this purchase possible. And we were lucky:
the prices for Japanese art had not escalated as swiftly as those
paid for other artworks.''
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is part of the museum's $160 million development
plan, which will include an expansion of the Asian art galleries to
accommodate the Japanese acquisitions. Until now, such holdings
were overshadowed by the museum's substantial Chinese art
collection, the core of which was donated by Eli Lilly, the
pharmaceutical magnate, who was the museum's largest benefactor
until his death in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion also reflects the museum's awareness of the
growing Japanese presence in Indiana. Today, there are some 200
Japanese companies, including Toyota, Subaru and Isuzu, in the
state, employing more than 40,000 workers. Since 1993, Indiana has
led the nation in attracting new Japanese investment and now ranks
third, after California and Ohio, in the total amount invested: $8
billion plus.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's search for Japanese art began in 1997, when
Robinson alerted dealers in this country and abroad that the museum
was interested in acquiring a major holding. But he never expected
that he would luck into anything like the Tiger Collection, which
includes all the major traditions of Edo painting.
</P>
<P>
   The screens are the stars of the exhibition, revealing the
virtuosity that the Japanese achieved in this art form during the
Edo period, a level of screenmaking unmatched anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all the scrolls and screens are exhibited together, I
hope that the extraordinary density will give people a sense of the
opulence of this collection,'' Robinson said. ``It cuts a broad
swath through Edo painting, something that should knock your socks
off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
