<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5091 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MORRISSEY-FILMS-2TAKE     02-22 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORRISSEY-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE BARD OF THE DEMIMONDE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 David Bahr's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about Tim
Roth and his film, ``The War Zone.''  
 By DAVID BAHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paul Morrissey disdains rock music, abhors
recreational drugs and thinks even less of liberal politics. When
asked his views on sex, he pauses for a moment, looks his
inquisitor in the eye and says: ``I'm Catholic. I'm with Rome 100
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments may seem surprising coming from a director whose
films luxuriate in the libertine lives of heroin users,
masturbating transvestites and polymorphous-perverse male
prostitutes. Yet Morrissey _ who from 1966 to 1972 directed more
than half a dozen movies produced by Andy Warhol, discovered the
avant-garde rock band the Velvet Underground and once saw a court
label his work ``obscene, vulgar and profane'' _ believes he's
misunderstood, to say nothing of misrepresented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every movie I've ever made says the same thing,'' said the
dapper, Morrissey, 61, recently over tea and cookies at Manhattan's
Carlyle Hotel. Presumably, that includes ``Trash,'' which will be
shown at the New York Underground Film Festival at Anthology Film
Archives on Friday and open in New York and Los Angeles on March 17
to mark its 30th anniversary. ``They all find comedy in people
trying to live their lives without any rules,'' he said. ``They are
a record of the period, but without any overt messages. And I think
that confuses people.''
</P>
<P>
   Conceived, directed and photographed by Morrissey, ``Trash''
chronicles the debauched behavior of a group of affable human
oddities living in lower Manhattan during the late 1960s. The
second work in the trilogy that includes ``Flesh'' (1968) and
``Heat'' (1971), it attempted to capture, as Morrissey put it,
``the dead-end existence of sex, drugs and rock 'n' roll.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also the second Warhol-produced film, after ``Flesh,'' in
which Morrissey had total creative control, though the trilogy
remains commonly identified with, and filed in video shops under,
the Warhol name _ which does not particularly please the director.
``How many films written, directed and photographed by one person
are given co-authorship with their presenter?'' asked a riled
Morrissey. ``I don't know any. But because Andy is a celebrity,
people have to think of him before they think of the movies, which
is grotesque.''
</P>
<P>
   For those familiar with Warhol's numerous films, including
``Sleep'' (1963), which depicts a man sleeping, and ``Couch''
(1964), which shows a series of people conversing on a couch,
Morrissey's movies offer something Warhol's never did: plots. They
also demonstrate Morrissey's unmistakable flair for quirky casting.
In the trilogy, the director follows a colorful collection of
lovable deadbeats, focusing primarily on the quietly charismatic
and usually naked Joe Dallesandro (simply ``Joe'' in the films) as
he evolves from a male hustler in ``Flesh'' to a junkie in
``Trash'' to a washed-up child actor turned aspiring rock singer in
``Heat.'' Employing improvised dialogue delivered mostly by
nonactors, the idiosyncratic films are cinematic exercises in the
mundane, at times tremendously poignant and unexpectedly funny.
</P>
<P>
   Of all his movies, ``Trash'' remains Morrissey's biggest
commercial hit and, arguably, his most emotionally satisfying work.
(After making more than a dozen films over three decades, he gave
up directing in 1988, after his personal favorite, ``Spike of
Bensonhurst,'' was released.) Made for a mere $3,000 and shot on
16-millimeter film, ``Trash'' is a sympathetic portrait of the
chemically anesthetized Joe and his garbage-collecting girlfriend,
Holly (played by the transvestite performer Holly Woodlawn), and
her desperate attempt to attain respectability by getting on the
welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Structurally slack and digressive, the film exhibits a seemingly
aimless humor and directorial imprecision that actually appear
sharper and more effective after repeated viewings. Yet despite its
enduring cult following and an accumulation of positive reviews
since its initial release, ``Trash'' is still dismissed as
amateurish by some film authorities and ignored by others, along
with the rest of Morrissey's work. Ephraim Katz's ``Film
Encyclopedia'' defines Morrissey's movies as ``mediocre''; Leonard
Maltin's latest guide to 20,000 films lists neither ``Flesh'' nor
``Trash''; and ``The St. James Film Directors Encyclopedia,''
edited by the venerable Andrew Sarris, does not mention Morrissey
and his films at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul's work has always been in a category of its own,'' says
the avant-garde filmmaker Jonas Mekas, a Village Voice film critic
from 1958-75 and founder of Anthology Film Archives, a showcase for
experimental cinema. ``Those in the avant-garde didn't really get
them. And those who were in Hollywood thought them a little too
loose and amateurish. Like Norman Mailer did in his early films,
Paul used nonactors who improvised. Until then, there were really
only traditionally scripted narratives or documentary-style cinema
verite, which filmed people in real situations, avoiding any
artificial dramatization. Morrissey and Mailer pushed it further by
having nonactors improvise.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``Trash'' achieves an engaging sense of reality
from the uninhibited expression of its nonprofessional actors, many
of whom knew firsthand the counterculture lives they were
portraying. ``There was no script,'' recalled Ms. Woodlawn in a
phone interview from her home in West Hollywood. ``We showed up. He
threw out ideas and rolled the film. There were some retakes but
most of it was done in one shot. The character I was playing was
fictional, but her personality was basically me.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrissey believes that strong personalities, not acting
credentials, make for good screen stars. That is the reason, he
said, that he so frequently cast transvestites. ``Actors should be
instinctive and spontaneous,'' he said. ``If you think about
acting, you're not going to be good. I am the first to use
transvestites that didn't play transvestites, and no one has done
it since. I think the artifice of using a man as a woman makes it
more of a movie. And movies are great because they create
artificial situations, and only through artificial situations does
the real truth sneak out.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrissey's aesthetic of artificiality extends to rawly
simulated depictions of sex and drug use in his films. One
prolonged shot in ``Trash'' shows Dallesandro inserting a
hypodermic needle into his arm and drawing blood as if he were
mainlining heroin. ``So much of the culture glamorized drugs at the
time,'' Dallesandro said in a phone interview from his home in Los
Angeles. ``Paul wanted to show the seedier side, where it all led
to.'' Although the actor, who was 21 at the time, was not told by
Morrissey to puncture his skin, Dallesandro wanted to lend
credibility to the scene. ``I was not some naive kid,'' he said
when asked how he came up with the idea. ``I was already
streetwise.''
</P>
<P>
   It does not seem strange to Morrissey, who professes to being a
political conservative and a devout Catholic, that he would make
affectionate, playful films about unrestrained carnality. ``You
don't put your personal viewpoints in a good movie,'' he said. ``A
movie should only be concerned with characters, not some big moral,
although it's always underneath. I just thought the idea of people
doing whatever they want was a great subject for films. The
characters may be losers, but they're all kind of likable. I can't
imagine putting unlikable characters in a movie. As to why their
lives are so messed up, well, that's for the audience to figure
out.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Woodlawn, it was Morrissey's determination to avoid
moralizing in his films that made them so popular, particularly
among audiences who do not share the filmmaker's political or
religious views. ``Paul is very straight and narrow,'' she said.
``But he's not moralistic. That's why we got along so well. And
that's why his fans run the gamut from A to Z, from old ladies to
gay liberals.''
</P>
<P>
   So what can a conservative like Morrissey possibly make of his
loving, liberal fan base? ``My films show very human characters,''
he said, a faint curmudgeon's smile slowly turning the corners of
his mouth. ``And liberals tend to go to movies, while conservatives
tend to resent anything that rocks the boat.'' He paused, now
grinning widely. ``Of course, not a good conservative. A good
conservative is someone with an open mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
