<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-RIGHT-ART-NYT     02-22 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RIGHT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TRIES TO REASSURE MICHIGAN'S CATHOLICS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT1-4 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROMULUS, Mich. _ Even as Michigan residents cast their votes and
time ticked away before the polls here closed, Gov. George W.
Bush's campaign officials worked Tuesday to assure the state's
Roman Catholics that Bush was a friend who deserved their support.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute effort was a response both to negative telephone
calls about Bush that some Michigan Catholics said they had
received and to speculation by some political analysts that Bush's
alliances with Christian conservatives _ and, especially, his visit
earlier this month to Bob Jones University in Greenville, S.C. _
had upset Catholic voters.
</P>
<P>
   The effort also reflected the fact that the race here, unlike
the New Hampshire or South Carolina primaries, was much too close
to call and involved a number of factors that could determine the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Bush began his day by railing against the phone calls, which
portrayed him as anti-Catholic and which he attributed to the
campaign of Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign has said that it did not authorize the phone
calls but allowed for the possiblity that they may have been made
by over-exhuberant volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, John McCain, he's a man who's called me an
anti-Catholic bigot, and I don't appreciate it,'' Bush said during
a visit to a restaurant in nearby Royal Oak on Tuesday morning.
``That's shameful politics.''
</P>
<P>
   To pound home the Texas governor's message, the Bush campaign
electronically mailed, in the span of just 42 minutes after 1 p.m.,
nine different news releases containing statements from nine
Republican governors, all of whom denounced the telephone calls.
Many of the governors are Catholic, and many assumed the McCain
campaign was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Michael O. Leavitt of Utah called McCain's tactics
``shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts labeled McCain a ``typical
Washington politician who says one thing then does another,''
echoing some of Bush's attack ads, and said, ``He should be
ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also released a similar statement from Tom
Monaghan, the founder of Domino's Pizza and an active benefactor of
Catholic causes in the Detroit area.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Roman Catholic,'' Monaghan said, ``I am offended that my
faith is being used as a negative smear tactic to divide people in
a political campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a script of the telephone call that the Bush
campaign released Tuesday, a recorded message notes that Bush
visited Bob Jones University, whose officers in the past have made
anti-Catholic statements. Bush has said repeatedly over the last
few days that he does not agree with those statements and has noted
that his brother Jeb, the governor of Florida, is Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   The script provided by the Bush campaign reads: ``Governor
George Bush has campaigned against Senator John McCain by seeking
the support of Southern fundamentalists who have expressed
anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Jones has made strong anti-Catholic statements, including
calling the pope anti-Christ, the Catholic church a satanic cult,''
according to the script. ``Governor Bush has stayed silent.''
</P>
<P>
   By releasing the script and the blizzard of statements, the Bush
campaign was perhaps doing more than assuring Catholics that they
had nothing to fear from the governor.
</P>
<P>
   It may also have been diverting attention from reports that the
evangelist Pat Robertson, a supporter of Bush, had recorded and
sent an incendiary telephone message branding McCain a foe of
conservative Christians and an insufficient opponent of abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Several political analysts said that the Robertson call,
emblematic of the tough politics that Bush's allies on the
religious right used to guarantee Bush's victory in the South
Carolina primary, could hurt Bush with moderate voters if he does
not quickly establish some distance from Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to be put back into the bottle,'' Scott Reed, who ran
Bob Dole's 1996 presidential campaign, said of Robertson.
``Somebody should pick up the phone and tell him to stop. He is way
over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Tuesday that Robertson had made the calls
independently of his campaign, an assertion that Robertson
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   As early surveys of voters leaving the polls Tuesday afternoon
gave a slight edge to McCain, the Bush campaign stepped up efforts
behind the scenes, turning to an army of volunteers much bigger
than the Arizona senator's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call longer, call louder,'' said a senior adviser to Bush
about the message the campaign was sending into the field.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also enjoyed an advantage over McCain in terms of radio and
television advertising. Bush's advisers estimated that the Bush
campaign bought $2.6 million worth of advertising in Michigan,
while the McCain campaign spent $2 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
