<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BUSH HITS A POTHOLE IN MICHIGAN
</HEADLINE>
   (With REPUBS-PRIMARIES) 
(sw) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ This road is nothing but bumps.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire knocked Gov. George W. Bush's bandwagon off the
highway. Then, last Saturday, South Carolina derailed Sen. John
McCain's Straight Talk Express. On Tuesday, after a meager two-day
campaign, Bush hit a sizable pothole in Michigan, right in the
middle of his turnpike to victory.
</P>
<P>
   So McCain lives to fight another day, and Bush, with his cloak
of inevitability further frayed, must find somewhere else to drive
the Arizonan from the contest. Bush tried to look past McCain in
his speeches here, concentrating his fire on President Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore, the most likely Democratic nominee. That
proved premature.
</P>
<P>
   Although it sounded at the time like wishful thinking, McCain
prophesied on Sunday that Michigan would differ from South
Carolina. In South Carolina, he said, ``it was very clear that we
were wiped out by the so-called Christian right, and that's where a
lot of this hate stuff was directed'' _ implying that Republican
conservatives would count for less on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Because he has more money, more prominent backers and two
powerful geographic bases _ Florida, where his brother Jeb is
governor, and his own state of Texas _ Bush must still be counted
the front-runner. On the other hand, McCain can now entertain
legitimate hopes of rekindling the widespread enthusiasm he
generated in the campaign's early weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The results in Michigan, much the most representative state to
vote so far this year, also contained dire warnings for both of the
candidates. This is the eighth largest state, with a highly
competitive two-party system, a downsizing government, prosperous
farms and a growing, highly innovative economy: the kind of state
all presidential candidates shoot for.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was outpolled 60-40 by McCain among moderate voters here.
Such voters usually hold the key to presidential elections. Having
allied himself firmly with the far right in South Carolina, Bush
apparently suffered for that in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Although the poll of voters conducted by the television networks
and The Associated Press contained no denominational questions,
many politicians suggested that the governor's visit two weeks ago
to Bob Jones University, which is often accused of
anti-Catholicism, had hurt him among Roman Catholic voters in the
blue-collar suburbs of Detroit and other big cities.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father, George Bush, lost centrist voters to Bill
Clinton, and with them the election of 1992, and then Bob Dole did
the same thing in 1996. This year, the Republican leaders who
flocked to the Texas governor did so in large part because they
thought he would have broader appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Delighted though he was to do so well here, McCain must worry
about the uncomfortable degree to which his victory depended upon
Democrats and independents. Bush took two-thirds of the Republican
vote, and only the fact that Democrats and independents accounted
for an astounding 50 percent of Tuesday's electorate pulled the
Arizona senator through.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that the non-Republican turnout reached record
proportions for a Republican primary, partly because of local
ballot issues in some communities. There were hints that at least a
few Democrats had deliberately voted in the Republican primary to
foul up the other party's process.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Flashner, 31, a Democratic sales representative in the
Detroit suburbs, backed McCain. Asked why, he replied: ``To tell
the truth, I'd like to see the process go on as long as it can,
because the more they beat each other up, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability to attract voters across party lines augurs well for
McCain's chances this fall, should he be nominated, but it will not
help him in many of the primaries that take place later this month.
Virginia's voting next Tuesday and Georgia's and Ohio's on March 7
are open to all registered voters, but only registered Republicans
can vote in primaries in Washington state next Tuesday and in New
York on March 7. In California, which also holds its primary on
March 7, non-Republicans can cast ballots, but their votes will not
count in awarding delegates.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, the electorate was much more balanced than in South
Carolina, from a number of points of view. Half the voters here
described themselves as conservatives; 60 percent did so in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, 34 percent called themselves Christian
conservatives. Fewer than 3 voters in 10 here said they identified
with the religious right, a decline from 1988, when Pat Robertson
ran strongly here, and 1996, when Pat Buchanan took 34 percent of
the total in giving Dole a tough fight.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson recorded telephone messages to Michigan voters this
year urging them to turn out in support of Bush, accusing McCain of
having chosen, in former Sen. Warren E. Rudman of New Hampshire, a
``vicious bigot'' as national chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Because the voting here followed almost immediately on the heels
of that in South Carolina, the results there may not have had time
to sink in and generate a surge for Bush. Not until election day
itself, the exit poll indicated, did a small swing to the Texas
governor get under way.
</P>
<P>
   Michiganders, subjected for a much shorter period to bombardment
by the artillery of radio and television ads, took a different view
of the candidates on important points. In South Carolina, McCain
was seen as the less fair of the two contenders; in Michigan, Bush
was, although McCain took a more caustic tone in his personal
appearances. In South Carolina, Bush and McCain were seen as
equally likely to say what they believed rather than what people
wanted to hear; in Michigan, McCain had an advantage on that score.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Breadon, a United Auto Workers member who works on a
Chrysler production line, said in explaining his vote for McCain:
``I really don't care for George Bush. He seems like a daddy's boy.
He seems like a weasel.'' An independent, Breadon voted in Royal
Oak, north of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, McCain seemed to have gone some way towards
reclaiming his identity as a reformer, for which Bush successfully
challenged him in the last few weeks with the slogan proclaiming
himself a ``reformer with results.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, McCain did much less well than he had hoped among
two groups he has targeted. A Vietnam veteran who spent years as a
prisoner of war, he got the votes of only a few more veterans than
Bush. And he did less well than his rival among young voters,
especially under 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
