<HEADLINE>
SAILING BECOMES A CONTACT SPORT IN THE HAURAKI GULF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ In hockey and football and all the other
contests where contact is a ritual of the game, the vision of a
bloodied combatant translates to business as usual. But when it
comes to sailboat racing, the sight of deep crimson flowing freely
from a battered competitor, though not unheard of, is rare indeed.
</P>
<P>
   So it is likely that the image that will be remembered from
Tuesday's Race 2 of the America's Cup match between Italy's Prada
Challenge and Team New Zealand will be that of the Italian crewman
Max Sirena reeling from a head wound that left a smudged red stain
along the aft quarter of Luna Rossa's otherwise gleaming silver
topsides. Never mind that Team New Zealand convincingly defeated
Prada to take a 2-0 lead in the five-of-nine race finals, which
resume after Wednesday's lay day, or day off; cut away from the
chase.
</P>
<P>
   When serious injuries occur aboard racing boats, they generally
result from a head-first encounter with an untamed mainsail boom or
spinnaker pole, or from a finger or hand that gets wound into a
line under load. So what happened to Sirena has to go under the
category of freak accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Midway up the first windward leg, with Prada's crew regaining
its composure after a harsh lesson in starting-line tactics by the
clinical Kiwis, the Italians' charge came to a crashing halt when
they hooked a big piece of plastic, with a long length of rope
attached, to the blunt, leading edge of their keel bulb some 12
feet below the waterline.
</P>
<P>
   The resultant drag was deadly, and the junk had to be removed.
Sirena, the bowman, was dispatched below deck to retrieve the long,
carbon-fiber pole that each boat carries to floss the keel clean
when debris is snagged on the bulb or winglets.
</P>
<P>
   The poles, also called kelp sticks, came into vogue during the
last cup regatta off San Diego in 1995, where they were regularly
employed to free the long strands of seaweed routinely encountered
off the Southern California coast. But in the pristine waters of
the Hauraki Gulf, they have rarely been needed.
</P>
<P>
   Any sailor who has ever snared a lobster pot or other flotsam on
his keel or rudder knows what it does to boat speed and handling.
But it's one thing to be inconvenienced on a cruise along the Maine
coast, and quite another to be tripped up in a crucial race for the
America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   So Sirena was moving quickly, which may have contributed to his
mishap. As he passed the back end of the pole topside, and turned
his attention to other tasks, he was stunned when the business end
of the pole _ equipped with a sharp, plastic hook _ raked him
across the top of his scalp.
</P>
<P>
   Sirena sports a haircut like Michael Jordan's; in other words,
he's as bald as a cue ball. A wide gash that would later require
seven stitches pierced his temple.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Sirena's cut looked worse than it was. Alessandra
Ghezzi, a Prada spokeswoman, said Wednesday that the sailor was
``still a bit dazed and quite a bit swollen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's OK and should be sailing tomorrow,'' Ghezzi said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the blow to Sirena was not the only one suffered by the
Prada crew. By the time they freed the plastic and regained
control, Team New Zealand had built an insurmountable lead. Now the
Italians find themselves down two races to a Kiwi crew that is
proving to be far more formidable than anyone Luna Rossa
encountered in the four-month-long challenger's trials.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, after the 2-minute-26-second Race 2 thrashing, the
New Zealand helmsman Russell Coutts found fault with his squad's
performance. ``Our spinnaker pole almost went over the side and
almost broke going upwind one time,'' he said. ``There were a
couple of other mistakes. It wasn't a great day.''
</P>
<P>
   Those remarks begged a question: What will happen if the Kiwis
put together a race that satisfies Coutts?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Italians remain resolute. ``We were feeling pretty
good, and then that thing happened with the keel,'' said the Prada
tactician, Torben Grael. ``It was very unfortunate. We are very
happy with the performance of the boat, and we're looking forward
to the next race.''
</P>
<P>
   Prada's problems, unfortunately, have thus far had nothing to do
with its boat. Had the crews swapped weapons before the series,
with the Kiwis aboard the Italian boat and vice versa, the results
Wednesday would still be the same. The Prada crew has been
outsailed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, it will become clear if a good, sharp crack on the
bean has brought them around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
