<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-KOSOVO-MITROVICA-NY     02-22 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-MITROVICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS LINGER IN MITROVICA ON DAY AFTER MASSIVE DEMONSTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (See also KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT13, 14, 15 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ Ethnic Serbs living on the
north side of this divided city were edgy Tuesday, a day after the
massive show of force by thousands of Albanian protesters. The city
was calm, slumped in a ``morning-after'' state, with mud and debris
on the streets the only sign left of the disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of young Serb men gathered by the main bridge that
connects the Serb north and Albanian southern district, and
suddenly erupted and attacked a German armored vehicle, pelting it
with stones as it swung by them in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It was a small incident, over as quickly as it blew up, but a
sign of the anxieties and aggression that lie very near the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Serbs had gathered Monday to defend their district
on the north side of the, as tens of thousands of Albanians
streamed into Mitrovica from all over the country. ``We were
worried, because of the huge number of Albanians and of course we
did not expect anything good of it,'' said Oliver Ivanovic, the
self-styled leader of the Serb community in Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting violence, they had evacuated some women and children
and had organized their own protest of 800 people by the bridge and
2,000 more further up the main street, he said. ``It was a clear
intention to show us they have a big number of people and that they
will one day come over the bridge,'' Ivanovic said. ``It was also a
message for us that we are not welcome here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although peacekeeping commanders were congratulating their
soldiers for containing the demonstration and preventing clashes
between the two ethnic communities, the Serbs complained that the
huge demonstration right on the bridge only proved that the
peacekeepers were doing little to protect the Serb community.
</P>
<P>
   With only some 10,000 Serbs on the north side of the city and
some 90,000 Albanians living on the south of the river, the sheer
demographics explain their fears. There are some 100,000 Serbs left
in Kosovo, more than half of them in the north around Mitrovica,
among a population of nearly 2 million Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the mood was muted on both sides. Some Albanian miners
made a brief protest on the south side of the bridge in the
morning. Some Serbs stood around, playing nationalist music on loud
speakers and lobbed a few stones at U.S. paratroopers who deployed
on the main bridge overnight. The Americans had arrived to
reinforce British troops, who had borne the brunt of the turbulent
demonstrations and had ten soldiers slightly injured.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Nick Carter of the Royal Green Jackets, whose men had
the job of preventing the demonstrators breaking through to the
bridge, said he expected a week or two of calm now, at least on the
Albanian side of the city. The demonstration had been generally
good humored and only a hardcore of 2,000 had been intent on
pushing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made their point, to show the massive feeling that there
is among Albanians that Mitrovica cannot remain divided. The
international community has bought two weeks and now has to produce
some results,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the Serbs, it was a more intractable problem and was a
question of their viewpoint. ``I personally don't think they will
feel secure while looking over a river,'' he said, comparing the
River Ibar with the Berlin Wall. In Pristina, where the Royal Green
Jackets have been guarding a small Serb community, there is no
dividing line between the ethnic communities and that has helped
the beginnings of normality.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he has been able to reduce the static guards on
houses as slowly the violence has been reduced and Albanians have
taken on the responsibility of ensuring the security of the Serbs.
But he admits, ``It's going very very slowly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
