<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-AFFIRMACT23-COX     02-22 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-AFFIRMACT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida Cabinet approves end to racial preferences in college
admissions
 &HT;    By Marcia Gelbart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ It's official: Race will no longer help
students get into Florida's 10 public universities.
</P>
<P>
   The state Cabinet, sitting as the Board of Education, voted 4 to
2 Tuesday to approve Gov. Jeb Bush's One Florida plan, eliminating
affirmative action in college admissions but guaranteeing a
university seat this fall to the top 20 percent of students in
every high school graduating class. Attorney General Bob
Butterworth and Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson, both Democrats,
opposed the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to the Legislature to ensure that One Florida,
encoded in law, can work in reality. Come the session that opens
March 7, that means supporting Bush's request to add $20 million in
need-based financial aid, and to set aside other funds to teach
Advanced Placement courses in school districts where they're not
now available.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he has the support of the House and Senate Republican
leaders. But as critics of the plan pointed out, little is certain
when it comes to budget matters, especially in an election year and
especially with dozens of lawmakers scheming to score their last
hurrahs as they wrap up their legislative careers because of term
limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not adequately funded, it's not going to make it,''
Butterworth said.
</P>
<P>
   There was also more talk Tuesday of the looming repercussions of
the Cabinet's vote: a possible economic boycott of Florida, as
suggested Sunday by NAACP leader Kweisi Mfume. That could mean a
boycott of orange juice, the tourism industry or canceled Florida
convention meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called the possible action ``inappropriate.'' Also, several
black lawmakers, including House Minority Leader Les Miller of
Tampa and the head of the legislative black caucus, Democratic
Miami Sen. Daryl Jones, were reluctant to immediately embrace the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sen. Kendrick Meek (D-Miami) said, ``This doesn't end
here. That's not a threat, it's a promise.'' It was Meek who
sparked the fierce opposition to One Florida after staging the
January Capitol sit-in with another black lawmaker, Rep. Tony Hill
(D-Jacksonville).
</P>
<P>
   The hostility between Meek and Bush was unmistakable Tuesday as
Meek urged the Cabinet to slow the governor's plan by not adopting
it in its entirety. He explained to Bush how the One Florida plan
is contributing to the building of two Floridas by offering some
words from one of many letters he has received: ``Why don't you go
back to Africa where all your people belong?''
</P>
<P>
   And at one point, as Bush sat behind the dais with a smirk on
his face, Meek said, ``I'm glad this is amusing for you governor,
because it's not for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 30 people who signed up to speak to the Cabinet in
favor of the plan were affiliated with the Florida university
system. But emotional talk of racism elicited personal stories from
opponents and supporters alike.
</P>
<P>
   Regent Steve Uhlfelder, who grew up in Palm Beach County,
recalled being angry that blacks had to ride in the backs of buses.
He also spoke of the grandparents and other family he lost because
of the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should never treat people like they treated us in
Germany,'' he said. ``In my heart and soul, if I thought this would
hurt African-Americans, I would not (support it).''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Betty Holzendorf (D-Jacksonville) _ who when asked about
the possible boycott said, ``Why not?''_ recounted her youth in
explaining her opposition. ``In 1954, when I was in the 10th grade
and they announced the (U.S. Supreme Court) Brown (v. Board of
Education) decision, we jumped and cheered, and to have to stand
here at the podium today is painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Bush remained stern. ``We're not moving one step
back in the fight against racism,'' he said. ``Perceptions are
important in politics, boy are they. But I'm focused on reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ONE FLORIDA PRICE TAG
</P>
<P>
   Several provisions of Gov. Jeb Bush's One Florida plan need
approval from the Legislature, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ $20 million in need-based financial aid for college students.
</P>
<P>
   _ Money to encourage low-performing schools to teach Advanced
Placement classes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Money to make PSAT tests available to all 10th graders.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moving procurement decisions from the Department of Labor to
the Department of Management Services.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increased penalties for companies that discriminate on the
basis of race or gender.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
