<SLUG> BC-TRUCKER-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUCKERS JAM NATION'S CAPITAL TO PROTEST RISING FUEL PRICES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PHILIP CAUTHON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hundreds of truckers wheeled their rigs through the
nation's capital Tuesday, blasting their horns and protesting
skyrocketing fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   Adorned with U.S. flags, the trucks filled Washington's
already-congested streets. The drivers pleaded for government help
in dealing with unbearable operating costs, including steep diesel
prices, which have increased by as much as 55 percent since Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a crossroads here,'' said John Medaglia, a driver for
more than 30 years from Langhorn, Pa., who parked his truck for the
first time last week. ``Do I go back to work and take a loss every
day or do I go out of business. I'm 55 years old. What else am I
going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The high price of fuel adds to &UR;  &LR; truckers' long-standing
complaints that freight rates are too low to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Many drivers lease their services to motor carriers, because in
addition to providing insurance and operating permits the carriers
are better equipped to reach clients. Those carriers, in turn, keep
rates low for independent drivers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the ability to pass these costs on to clients,''
said Medaglia. ``The carriers don't feel the cost because the
burden is on us. And they're refusing to raise freight rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Shouting over incessant horns on Capitol Hill, rally organizers
demanded that Congress suspend the diesel excise tax, now at 24
cents per gallon, and allow states to rebate an additional 15 cents
per gallon to drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to let the government know that this is an
emergency,'' said Joe Smith, a driver from Camden, N.J. ``We need
some help until the price of fuel comes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and others expressed concern that summer demand for fuel
by travelers would boost already excessive costs. The current spike
in diesel prices was fueled by high demand for heating oil in the
Northeast and the rising cost of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart said
that it would be difficult to repeal a tax that builds the very
roads the trucks depend on. He said that the administration does
not want ``to intervene in a way that manipulates the price'' of
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves truck drivers to wrestle with prices that can
fluctuate radically and vary from region to region.
</P>
<P>
   For example, John Garcia, a 27-year-old driver from Denmark,
Wis., recalled paying $2.30 per gallon in Connecticut on Monday,
compared to the $1.45 he paid when he left home. He said that, this
time last year, a gallon of diesel cost around 99 cents in most
states.
</P>
<P>
   New England states have been the hardest hit, with diesel prices
rising 55 percent last month and nearly doubling over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Texas' diesel prices are among the lowest, rising just 9 percent
last month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys can't afford to fill up,'' said Garcia, who
learned about the rally from drivers in New Jersey. ``I'm doing
alright now but everybody's got to stick together.''
</P>
<P>
   Speakers at the rally also want the government to create
regional fuel reserves to cushion future price shocks and
investigate whether the current spike in prices was orchestrated by
oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the protest was without incident. Traffic was
relatively unimpeded, given that hundreds of trucks flooded the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Ed ``Firecracker'' Amaroso of Baltimore said he hoped the rally
would bring relief. He said that despite a fuel surcharge he
received from his contractor, he was paying about $1,200 a month
more in operating costs than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fortunate,'' Amaroso said. ``But you know, $300 a week,
that's a truck payment or mortgage. And a lot of guys are getting
hit a lot worse. It's really getting tough out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
