<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-SPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBA REFUSES TO WITHDRAW U.S. DIPLOMAT
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cuba will not withdraw the diplomat linked to an
espionage investigation, despite an order from the United States
that he leave the country, Cuban officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat, identified as Jose Imperatori, had been linked to
an American immigration official charged with espionage last week.
The American charged with spying, Mariano M. Faget, was arrested
late Thursday after he was caught passing to a Cuban-born New York
businessman false information that American officials had fed him
about a Cuban intelligence agent's plan to defect to the United
States, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Faget is a senior official in the Miami office of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Cuban Special Interests section, Luis
Fernandez, confirmed that the Cuban government would not withdraw
the official. He said the diplomat would remain to testify and
prove the espionage accusation to be false.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said that Imperatori and another Cuban official, Luis
Molina, had met with Faget in Miami on separate occasions. He said
the two had spoken to Faget on immigration issues and Faget's
desire to someday visit Cuba. But Fernandez said that Imperatori
had never tried to recruit Faget or to get sensitive information
from him. ``The contacts with this man were public and completely
open,'' Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Rubin, the spokesman for the State Department, said
that the expelled Cuban diplomat had been ``declared persona non
grata,'' and must depart the country by 1:30 p.m. on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be highly unusual for a state to refuse to remove a
diplomat under these circumstances,'' Rubin said. ``Under the
Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations, Cuba must either recall
the diplomat in question or terminate his functions.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the diplomat not leave the country, Rubin said, he would
lose diplomatic privileges and immunities, and would become subject
to the laws of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Cuba do not have formal diplomatic
relations; they are represented in each other's country by an
interests section, under the flag of Switzerland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5111 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     02-22 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ CARRIED TOO MUCH CONTRACT BAGGAGE FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Associates of Juan Gonzalez, trying to
tailor Igor's baggy-pants reputation, are saying this spring that
something else didn't fit in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The word from the Detroit camp, where Juan is now the Tigers'
leading man, says the Rangers purposely allowed the big fellow to
stew in his own public-relations mess last season.
</P>
<P>
   If the club had no plans to sign Gonzalez to a long-term
contract, and if a trade in the winter was a given kept secret,
then Juan did play right into the Rangers' scheme.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was his snub last summer of the All-Star Game,
followed by Gonzalez' refusal to even suit up for the Hall of Fame
exhibition game in Cooperstown. Juan said his uniform pants were
too baggy in the butt.
</P>
<P>
   What followed both incidents was the obvious _ a large load of
local and national Juan-bashing in the media, plus Gonzalez was
also roasted throughout baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that criticism, the Gonzalez camp is now claiming, could
have been avoided if the Rangers had been willing to spin-doctor
the news, like many teams will attempt to do in those ugly
situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's spreading that stuff, but it's wrong,''
general manager Doug Melvin said yesterday. ``I know I personally
went to Juan and asked him to back off his stance on the All-Star
Game, and to apologize for what he said. I told him he needed to
restore his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan's answer to me was that he was comfortable with how he
had handled it, and what he had said was how he wanted to leave
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, Juan would be leaving Arlington less than a
month after the season was over, the No. 1 reason being because the
Rangers had no desire to play contractual roulette with Gonzalez
when he became a free agent for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers took that gamble, and even with a staggering $140
million, eight-year offer currently on the table, will probably
enter this season with no long-term commitment from Juan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Rangers received almost no fan backlash from
dealing the two-time American League MVP to Detroit. That alone is
rather amazing, and definitely appears to relate to the incidents
from last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, Gonzalez is gone because a free-agency
``cycle'' is at work in baseball for all clubs not named the
Yankees. Win three world championships in four years and it's
different, but for basically all other teams, the ``cycle'' goes
like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at our '96 team,'' Melvin said. ``We won the first
divisional title in franchise history \Rending a 25-year wait\S. It
has been three years since the end of that season. How many players
do we have left from that team?''
</P>
<P>
   For those of us caught trying to do a quick count, Melvin had a
ready answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two,'' he said. ``Pudge \RRodriguez\S and Rusty \RGreer\S have
been with us the whole time. That kind of turnover in three seasons
is a perfect example of how the system now works. Due to a lot of
considerations, most of it having to do with how you choose to
spend your money, and how much you choose to spend, a team will
turn over its roster every two to three years.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting infield for the '96 AL West winners was Will Clark,
Mark McLemore, Kevin Elster and Dean Palmer. Greer was in left,
Darryl Hamilton in center and Juan in right. Pudge was the catcher
and Mickey Tettleton the DH.
</P>
<P>
   The starting rotation was Roger Pavlik, Bobby Witt, Ken Hill,
Darren Oliver (who is back this season) and Kevin Gross. John
Burkett took Gross' spot in August of that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on his numbers, Juan certainly figured as a career
Ranger,'' Melvin said. ``But based on his free agency, it came down
to another set of numbers. How much money would it take to make him
a career Ranger? That's the telling part.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, the ``cycle'' goes the other way for the Rangers. ``Our
nucleus is in place this spring to keep this current group together
for three seasons,'' Melvin said. ``We have every player except two
tied up for at least two years, and most of them three and
beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland and first baseman-DH Lee Stevens are in
free agency seasons. At a contract of $3.5 million, Stevens is
almost certainly gone after 2000. Wetteland, due to his value, is
iffy, some of it depending on how young newcomer Francisco Cordero
develops this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In negotiations, I keep hearing players ask for a no-trade
clause,'' Melvin said. ``My answer is for them to sign a reasonable
contract and a no-trade is almost guaranteed. Rusty is a prime
example _ his contract is reasonable and he produces on the field.
As far as I'm concerned, Rusty will be here forever. But about 70
percent of trades these days are an attempt to either move or avoid
bad contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan, I think he meant you. \Ntagtop:Randy Galloway's ``Sports
at Six'' can be heard weeknights, 6-8 p.m., on WBAP NewsTalk 820.
\Ntagbottom:rgalloway\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
