<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5114 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-WORLDMATCH23-COX     02-22 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WORLDMATCH23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Campbell not just Tiger bait
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Michael Campbell remembers sitting on the
edge of his hotel bed after failing to break 80 in the 1997 French
Open and seriously pondering a career change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going, `What can I do?''' Campbell said Tuesday.
``I couldn't even hit the golf ball. I couldn't putt. I couldn't
chip. I was shanking my chips.''
</P>
<P>
   First, it was tendinitis in his left wrist that derailed a guy
who almost won the 1995 British Open. Now it had become, well,
cancer of the golf swing, as Chip Beck once called his own disease.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell lost his European Tour and Australian Tour card,
missing cuts on a weekly basis. He wondered about his old job with
the New Zealand phone company. He figured he could always sell golf
balls and give lessons to amateurs with swings even more crooked
than is.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about turnarounds. One day on the scrap heap, the next at
the focal point of the golf world. Three years ago Michael Campbell
might not have beaten Earl Woods. Now today, in the first round of
the $5 million Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship,
Campbell has the opportunity to knock off the world's No. 1 player,
Tiger Woods, at the La Costa Resort and Spa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to win, not make up the field,'' Campbell said. ``I
believe the way I'm thinking, when I'm in that zone and being
focused, I have a very good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell needs a little more luck than he has been getting
lately. During the six-tournament PGA Tour winning streak that
Woods assembled, Campbell's exploits on the other side of the world
became muted. Not only did Campbell, who will turn 31 today, win
three of the last four events in Australia, he beat Woods last
November in the Johnnie Walker Classic in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   For all of this success, by all logic Campbell should have
ascended higher than 65th, from 67th, for his last Australian win
and missed Woods in the first round. Instead, Campbell secured the
last spot in the field, the 64th, when Japan's Jumbo Ozaki
withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   But, then again, any position in a field where the world's best
play for $1 million is enough reward, considering Campbell's
difficult journey. In the summer of '95 in the New Zealand Open, he
thumped a driver into the hard ground and ruptured a sheath in his
wrist, setting off an agonizing, three-year nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating Tiger at the Johnnie Walker in Taiwan in November I
think was the kick-start to my career,'' Campbell said. ``Everybody
expected Tiger to win that week. All the attention was on Tiger.
All I did was just play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   For Woods, the event's obvious favorite, the first-round pairing
is particularly dangerous. But with La Costa still soggy despite
sunny weather Tuesday _ another Pacific storm is to hit today _
Woods' length should provide a significant advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing well; he obviously has a lot of confidence,''
said Woods, who lost in the quarterfinals last year to eventual
champion Jeff Maggert, ``and it's definitely a match I'm looking
forward to playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Campbell feel like an underdog? Of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most common thing we have is we're the same color,''
Campbell said of Woods. ``We're sponsored by the same brand, wear
the same golf shoes, wear the same socks, different clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Campbell fully realizes where the best players
reside every week. It's on the PGA Tour, where he eventually wants
to play as soon as a few unspecified goals are fulfilled in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at my fields I've beaten the last few months
compared to Tiger's fields,'' Campbell said. ``It's not as strong.
I think what Tiger has done is phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   If Woods is to win, Campbell pledges that it won't be through
intimidation. In a regular stroke-play event, he feels too many
players defeat themselves at the sight of Woods' name on the
leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's guys out there subconsciously going, `Oh, my God, he's
coming again,''' Campbell said. ```Here he comes. Oh, he's past me.
Oh, he's won.' That's where I think guys waste energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell is intent on not wasting the trip. While wife Julie has
accompanied him to La Costa, 18-month-old son Thomas remained in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves me whether I win or lose tomorrow,'' Campbell said.
``He's an inspiration to me. He was born in August of '98, and ever
since then my whole golf game has turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
