<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-MCSORELY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCSORELY FACES NHL HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ After a nightmarish evening in Vancouver
that was a metaphor for this baffling, tumultuous year, the Bruins
arrived here Tuesday missing three players, one of whom is likely
gone permanently.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, defenseman Marty McSorley will learn the fate of
his season, which is almost certainly over. McSorley flew to New
York for a 10 a.m. hearing at NHL headquarters that will determine
his punishment for a despicable two-handed baseball swing to the
head of Vancouver Canucks forward Donald Brashear with less than
three seconds remaining in a game Monday night that ostensibly was
over in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley, who was assessed a match penalty for deliberate
attempt to injure, was suspended indefinitely pending the hearing.
He is no stranger to supplementary discipline. This marks the
seventh time in his 17-year NHL career that he has been suspended
and the fifth time he's been banished for a stick infraction.
Chances are, though, this will be a suspension of epic proportions.
</P>
<P>
   There are 23 games remaining in Boston's season, and it seems a
fait accompli that McSorley will be ineligible to play in any of
them. A suspension of that magnitude would break the record for
on-ice violence held by Dale Hunter, who was banished for 21 games
at the start of the 1993-94 season for a blindside hit on Islanders
forward Pierre Turgeon in the 1993 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Brashear, whom McSorley struck in the right temple, was
diagnosed Tuesday with a Grade 3 concussion; he lost consciousness
when his head struck the ice. He was held in the hospital overnight
for observation and released Tuesday morning. He was told that he
can participate in no hockey activity for at least 2-3 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty has said it publicly, he's ashamed and has asked for
pardon from everybody,'' said coach Pat Burns, who held a team
meeting Tuesday to try to purge the poison from the dressing room.
``There's nothing more that I can add.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all in a state of shock. I certainly don't condone that
sort of play at any time and I don't think anybody should. Marty
has said that what he did was wrong and that's a step in the right
direction. Now it's up to the National Hockey League to decide what
they want to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explained to the players, that's not the way the game should
be played. These young players, they have to learn that and they
certainly got a good dose of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The disgraceful mess began only 2:09 into the contest, when
McSorley and Brashear squared off. Brashear pounded the aging
veteran, embarrassing him in the bout. At 12:22, McSorley tried for
a rematch but wound up with a double minor for roughing and
cross-checking while Brashear received no penalty. When McSorley
protested to officials, he was hit with a 10-misconduct and
banished to the dressing room for the rest of the period.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for the nasty end of the game, which Boston
wound up losing, 5-2. Had the game officials done their jobs
correctly, both players would've been assessed game misconducts and
tossed out prior to the situation deteriorating to overt violence,
which has prompted a police inquiry in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley was shaken after the game and seemed in shock himself
at what he had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very stupid play,'' said McSorley. ``I went up to him
to fight, as I'd done earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I embarrassed my hockey team. I apologize to Donald Brashear
and the fans who had to watch that. I guess I'm trying to write
checks my body can't cash and I got way carried away. I wanted to
go over and fight him like I'd done with so many guys at so many
different times. Why that happened, I don't know. No excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still kind of in shock at what I did. It was just stupid.
That's not the way I want to be known as a hockey player. The
repercussions are the last thing I'm thinking about. I've got to
reflect about what I did. I've played too many years and played too
honest. I've got to come to terms with what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   McSorley clearly isn't the player he used to be. Besides the
eroding skills, he hasn't been healthy, battling through a shoulder
injury and a bad wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as healthy as I was,'' he said. ``You square up and
fight anybody at any given time and I think I've done that for
years and years and years. You just get frustrated with yourself.
But I'm not making any excuses. It was so stupid, I can't believe I
did that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, across the board, were ashamed to be in the league.
Captain Ray Bourque said it wasn't a good night to be a hockey
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't justify that,'' said Bourque, who seemed more
distraught than ever. ``I have never witnessed anything like that.
I don't know what happened there. It was a shocker. It's a game of
respect where you go out and play hard and you battle. I can't
justify that. It blew me away. That's the first time I've witnessed
something like that. It's not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That takes the cake,'' added defenseman Kyle McLaren. ``I
don't know what to say. Something like that shouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But it did, and McSorley will pay dearly for it.
</P>
<P>
   The other two Bruins who were lost are Byron Dafoe and Anson
Carter. Dafoe, who suffered a knee injury, and Carter, who suffered
a shoulder injury, flew to Boston for medical examinations. Forward
Antti Laaksonen was recalled from Providence.
</P>
</TEXT>
