<HEADLINE>
KEYES' EVEN SPLIT; MISSOURI'S TIGHT RACE; GRAMS' RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Mo., Minn.)  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR KEYES, AN EVEN SPLIT
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes may be the first black candidate in a contest of
national importance whose support among whites and blacks was just
about the same. Keyes, an outspoken conservative, won the votes of
about 7 percent of the blacks who voted in the Michigan primary
Tuesday. His support among voters overall was not much less than
that.
</P>
<P>
   TIGHT RACE IN MISSOURI
</P>
<P>
   The Senate race in Missouri is a topsy-turvy one if the polls
are any indication. A poll released Tuesday by the National
Republican Senatorial Committee showed the Republican incumbent,
Sen. John D. Ashcroft, ahead of Gov. Mel Carnahan, a Democrat, 53
percent to 43 percent. A Zogby poll last week showed Carnahan ahead
47 percent to 45 percent. A Democratic poll last month showed
Ashcroft ahead 41 percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING ONE MORE TIME
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn., announced Monday that he was running
for re-election. He also said it would be his last such
announcement. Grams has said he believed that senators should serve
only two terms. He was first elected in 1994. ``He believes
individuals should be citizen legislators, and should return to
private business,'' Grams' press secretary, Steve Behm, said
Tuesday.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
