<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN WANTS TO FINISH JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Anaheim Angels position players reported to camp
Tuesday, checking in and getting physicals in preparation for
today's first full-squad workout. Among them was Mo Vaughn, who
greeted teammates before making it clear to reporters he isn't
going anywhere, despite the offseason rumors he would be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read all this about me wanting to get traded,'' said Vaughn,
who appeared to bulk up his upper body and shoulders. ``First of
all, nothing I've ever started did I not finish. I'm not about to
jump ship when things don't go the way they're supposed to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always believe my choice to come here was the right
choice. This organization took care of me, gave me an opportunity.
Things don't always happen right away. Last year was a bad year,
but we're in a different situation now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might say that situation is one of rebuilding and cutting
payroll. Although this year's payroll is roughly the same as last
season, it was money that kept the Angels from bringing back
pitcher Chuck Finley, causing many Angels players to question the
team's direction.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, though, said he can't concern himself with the
organization's direction, whatever it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter, I'm not the GM,'' he said. ``We're out here
to play the game the way it's supposed to be played and that's
it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Taking it personally: For the first time in years, pitcher
Brian Cooper didn't play winter ball. Instead, he stayed at home in
Glendora, got married and worked out in preparation for the season.
</P>
<P>
   But not playing winter ball also provided something Cooper he
could have done without.
</P>
<P>
   Angels bashing was popular this offseason, particularly as time
passed and the Angels roster didn't change much. The Angels' lack
of pitching is the heart of the criticism and that struck Cooper
personally.
</P>
<P>
   Angels general manager Bill Stoneman has said he's content to go
with the pitchers he has, even if that means giving the young guys
like Cooper, Ramon Ortiz and Jarrod Washburn a shot at spots in the
starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, when I heard my name mentioned for the starting
rotation, it didn't matter what people were saying,'' Cooper said.
``It didn't bother me too much except that people didn't give us
credit. Whether we got here this year or next year didn't make a
difference. It's a credit to our coaches that they got us here.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Signings: Pitcher Matt Wise and catcher Jason Dewey were
signed for the 2000 season. Wise likely will pitch at Triple-A
Edmonton this season. He was 8-5 with a 3.77 ERA last season at
Double-A Erie.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey split time last season between Single-A Lake Elsinore and
Erie.
</P>
</TEXT>
