<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5126 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-REPUBS-PRIMARIES-ART-     02-22 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PRIMARIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN SEEN AS WINNING BOTH ARIZONA AND MICHIGAN  
 (Eds.: early story)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT1-7 are being sent to NYT photo clients. A poll
graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Sen. John McCain scrambled back into contention in the
Republican Presidential race on Tuesday, capitalizing on his
home-state advantage to easily defeat Gov. George W. Bush in
Arizona and riding a wave of independents and Democrats to gain a
narrow edge on Bush in Michigan, polls of voters show.
</P>
<P>
   The voting in Michigan has been watched most closely not only
because the campaign here was marked by bitter accusations of
unscrupulous campaign tactics on both sides, but, more importantly,
because it is the first large-state showdown of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain regained some of the footing he lost on Saturday in the
South Carolina primary by running well ahead of Bush among
independents and Democrats here _ as well as many people who had
not before voted in a Republican primary. Those voters poured to
the polls, swelling turnout estimates to at least one million, more
than double the figure in primaries here four and eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bush drew his strength from a vastly different pool of voters:
he drew far higher proportions of conservatives and Republican
loyalists than McCain. But those voters helped Bush more in South
Carolina than here in the Midwest, where the electorate is far less
Republican _ and far less conservative.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 percent of Michigan's precincts reporting, McCain had 49
percent of the vote while Bush had 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The two contests on Tuesday were especially critical for McCain
because after Bush's victory in South Carolina, he has sought to
demonstrate that he is not a one-state wonder who could only win
the primary in the tiny state of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Bush's advisers had hoped that they could
effectively knock off McCain after Tuesday's voting. And even
McCain's aides had acknowledged that a lopsided defeat in Michigan
would shatter their chances for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the voting on Tuesday assures that what McCain called ``a
wonderful, wonderful ride'' after his defeat in South Carolina will
not be over. It means that a Republican nominee will probably not
emerge at least until after the candidates sprint through 16
primaries and caucuses over the next 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the outcome on Tuesday will intensify the focus on
the races next week in Virginia, Washington state and North Dakota.
But the most important voting will be on March 7, which is
something of a national primary, with voters going to the polls in
New York, California, Ohio, Missouri, Georgia and several other
states.
</P>
<P>
   After the South Carolina voting, Bush and McCain rushed to
Michigan to concentrate their stumping because the outcome here is
far more important. There are 58 delegates at stake in Michigan; 30
in Arizona. McCain was also widely expected to win in Arizona
because he is the favorite son there who has served three terms in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bush's defeat in Arizona, according to the polls,
underscores how the primary season has been far rockier than he or
his advisers had anticipated. Bush enjoyed the energetic backing of
the Republican governor, Jane Dee Hull. For a time last year,
surveys in Arizona showed Bush ahead of McCain. That led some of
the governor's advisers to happily predict that they would
humiliate Mr. McCain in his own state.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush's advisers now insist they never intended to win
in Arizona, they poured as much as $2 million into smothering the
state's Republicans in television commercials and direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   The see-saw nature of the Republican competition - while McCain
has won New Hampshire, Bush was victorious in South Carolina and
Delaware _ leaves Bush appearing far less invincible than he seemed
throughout last year when polls showed, month after month, that he
towered over the Republican field and could easily defeat a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the McCain campaign has fastened onto the theme that Bush
is such a weak candidate that he could lose a general election.
</P>
<P>
   But the voting in Michigan pointed to larger difficulties for
both Bush and McCain. Bush's constituency is drawn most from his
party's conservative wing, according to the surveys of voters,
conducted by a consortium of the television networks and Associated
Press. If he is the Republican nominee, it might be difficult for
him to attract Republican moderates, independents and Democrats in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for McCain, the surveys showed, is that he
encountered difficulty attracting members of his own party. That
could be perilous for the senator because many of the upcoming
primary contests are in states like New York and Ohio, where _
unlike Michigan _ only registered Republicans can participate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
