<HEADLINE>
CHECHNYA'S NEIGHBORING PROVINCE UNDEREQUIPPED FOR SURGE IN
REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs to add about 800 words at end; in 2nd graf, `altogether' is
cut; in 5th graf, `gerrymander-shaped' is changed to
`irregularly-shaped'; in 9th graf, two semicolons become commas;
story is now 2 takes)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARABULAK, Russia _ By any reasonable judgment, life is
unspeakable for the 6,000 or so denizens of the Solglacia refugee
camp, a network of 250 tents and a strand of rail cars set along
the sinuous main road to Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   There is one water spigot. Electricity was spotty until January.
Hot meals ceased three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But all it takes to abandon reason is a brief drive a couple of
miles toward Grozny, to Mukharbek Hashtyrov's abandoned pig farm.
And suddenly, life in a green tent with any water at all begins to
look luxurious.
</P>
<P>
   Solglacia and the Hashtyrov pig farm are bookends in Chechnya's
lesser-noticed tragedy: the endless stream of war refugees westward
into the overwhelmed province of Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
   This irregularly-shaped state of barely 300,000 souls has now
absorbed more than 210,000 war victims, and with the Russian
government's seizure and purging of Chechnya's capital, Grozny, the
tide is again rising, by 300 a day at mid-month.
</P>
<P>
   As in the war, the hardest-hit are innocents who happen to be in
the wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   The lucky ones _ 20,000 or so at most _ wind up at two model
refugee camps just across the border from Chechnya with the odd
nicknames of Solglacia (or in English, Agreement) and Sputnik. In
both government-run camps, families live in hundreds of green and
tan tents staked out on grids of bulldozed roads.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more live in long strands of passenger rail cars on
abandoned tracks next to each camp. The less fortunate _ now up to
190,000 people _ sometimes find a way to share private homes. The
unluckiest of all are cast into small encampments; some are
semi-organized, but all too many are squatters' outposts like the
Hashtyrov pig farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stay in cattle farms, in mosques, in former factories,''
said Alexander Petrov, the deputy director of the Moscow office of
Human Rights Watch, who is in Ingushetia monitoring the refugee
situation. ``There are hundreds of such places.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But there are surely few that are more demeaning than the
Hashtyrov place, a crumbling collection of 19 narrow, long-deserted
brick sheds set on a landscape of abandoned machinery and tall
grass.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in buildings filled with trash, dirt and hundreds of
rusted sties, nearly 380 refugees from the Chechen war have staked
out claims on the meanest of spaces. Eight and ten at a time, they
squat in concrete storage rooms at each end of the pig sheds, all
devoid of water or toilets. Each is by rubber hoses that feed
stolen gas into jury-rigged space heaters.
</P>
<P>
   In one 7-by-19-foot room, beneath a single light bulb, beside
the blanket-covered planks that serve as the family bed,
39-year-old Roza Murdolova gathered her seven children around her
Thursday afternoon. Her husband, 43-year-old Supyan, is an invalid.
</P>
<P>
   A single plate of orange tea soup sat on a stone ledge. A
plastic wash basin sat on the floor, by all indications unused.
</P>
<P>
   The family fled its home in Urus-Martan in November, she said,
after Russian troops besieged and then flattened the village in one
of the critical early battles of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nowhere to go,'' she said. ``My house is destroyed.
Everything is destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   A few sheds away, Zulay Takhaeva, 48, and his 35-year-old wife,
Rasol, refugees from Grozny, care for their two children and a
brother's five orphans in a single room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state brings us bread,'' Rasol said. ``Sometimes, it's
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly, the Ingushetia government and international
agencies do reach refugees here and in other similar spots, though
often with hardly enough aid for them to survive. War victims who
obtain a pass from the Ingush migration service, a bureaucratic
trial requiring valid documents and other evidence of refugee
status, can now get half a loaf daily.
</P>
<P>
   The Danish Refugee Council, one of the most active charities
serving refugees, has delivered sugar, flour and cereals _ pearl
barley and buckwheat _ which have been a staple for some families
at the farm. The state brings water twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third turn as a refugee camp for the Hashtyrov farm,
once a bright spot in Russia's early-1990s march to capitalism. The
farm's 57-year-old owner, Mukharbek Hashtyrov, bought the property
in 1992 with the hope of converting it to a chicken farm, only to
be overwhelmed by regional wars.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But a war between Chechnya and Ingushetia quickly flooded it
with migrants who took beds, refrigerators, tables and other items
from the main office. ``They looted this place,'' he said in an
interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A second effort fell apart in 1994, when the first Chechen war
against Russia flooded the farm with still more refugees, many of
whom remained until the war ended in 1996. This time, Hashtyrov
said, the migrants stripped away door frames, gas stoves, and
windows.
</P>
<P>
   The farm sat idle until last year when the second Chechen war
brought refugees back. This time, he said, they have illegally
tapped electricity and gas for which the state is billing him.
``It's all on my neck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
