<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD     02-22 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 KARABULAK: neck,'' he said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life in the tent cities and railway cars, with their organized
food handouts and conveniences like running water, offers
advantages to refugees, at least compared to places like the
Hashtyrov farm.
</P>
<P>
   At both Solglacia and the more sprawling Sputnick camp, a daily
hot lunch was suspended early this month after the Russian
government's Emergency Ministry ran out of money. Residents get
bread and intermittent food from charities like the Agency for
Rehabilitation and Development, a Dutch organization.
</P>
<P>
   In tent 36 at Solglacia, a 15-by-15-foot, 10-window affair with
a hole in its peaked roof for a gas-stove chimney, Zenap
Hadjimurtova sat with her 12 relatives and ticked off that day's
rare handout: ``Ten cans of tinned meat or four kilograms, five
kilos of rice, five bars of soap, four bottles of oil, 20 kilos of
flour, one tube of toothpaste _ the first in five months! _ and two
packages of washing powder.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been no butter this month, she said, and there was
great disappointment not long ago when a donation of tinned meat
turned out to be pork, an inopportune choice for a camp of Muslim
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hadjimurtova and her clan _ a husband, two sisters, many
children, grandchildren and in-laws _ fled Grozny in September and
October and lived months in Solglacia before gas heat and plank
floors were installed this year. When regular electricity became
available in January, they and a few dozen other fortunates planted
poles, tree limbs or two by fours outside their doors and topped
them with antennas made of scrap wire and other stray metal. Now a
19-inch television blares Russian movies from one corner of the
tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to go to work,'' Ms. Hadjimurtova joked. ``When
there is a film on TV, we watch it. If not for television, we'd all
go mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hardship _ among other things, she said, the family
can only wash once a week, and men must leave the tent when women
dress and bathe _ the family realizes it is lucky.
</P>
<P>
   When she first moved to Solglacia in September, into a camp that
had barely erected its first tents, hundreds of others filled a
waiting list, many of them living in cars and trucks until new
tents were erected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were jealous of us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as one daughter, Sveta, was concerned, all the
handouts in the world are nothing compared with what they have
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can give us nothing,'' she said flatly, ``if only we
could just go home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
