<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-PRIM-MCCAIN23-COX     02-22 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIM-MCCAIN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain's next battle: Proving to GOP he's a `true conservative'
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sooner rather than later, John McCain has to
impress Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain continued in Michigan to rack up overwhelming numbers
among the independents and Democrats who voted in the Republican
primary.
</P>
<P>
   But exit polls in Michigan indicated that George W. Bush beat
McCain 2 to 1 among Republicans, roughly the same picture that
emerged from the South Carolina primary Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The peril for the Arizona senator is that upcoming primaries in
Washington state next week, then California and New York on March 7
count only Republican votes for the purposes of allocating
delegates to the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   There is no path to the GOP nomination that does not include
winning key states on the basis of Republican _ not independent or
Democratic _ support. Ultimately, the race will become a battle for
the 1,033 delegates that are needed to secure the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's results ensure that McCain will remain a viable
candidate until the California primary, said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe,
a political scientist at Claremont Graduate University in suburban
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had hoped to crush McCain's campaign in Michigan, building
upon his 11 percentage point win in South Carolina on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's performance Tuesday pokes another hole in the Bush
campaign's argument that their man is best suited to take on the
Democrats in the general election, Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's opportunity is to take advantage of some nervousness
that might exist on the part of California Republicans that perhaps
Bush isn't what they thought he was going to be, that he is not the
stronger candidate against Gore or Bradley,'' Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain spent two rare nights in his own bed this week, as he
stopped in Arizona to vote in the primary there. But when he
returns to the campaign trail today in Washington, then in
California for two days after that, McCain will be stressing his
ability to beat the Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with inevitability is that you're only inevitable
until you aren't,'' said Dan Schnur, McCain's communications
director and a veteran California operative.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, national polls show that McCain performs much better
thaagainst Vice President Al Gore. Oddly, McCain increased
his lead over Gore in the Gallup Poll that followed Saturday's
South Carolina primary, while Bush's narrow advantage over Gore
remained steady.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffe said McCain also has to repair his image among
Republicans in California, by toning down his reform message and
turning away from his campaign rhetoric that he is an outsider.
``He has to show Republicans that he is a true conservative,''
Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   That task may be harder after the campaigns in Michigan and
South Carolina. In both states, McCain was practically in open
warfare with the Republican establishment, which was strongly
supportive of Bush in both states, and with religious
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But Californians probably will see McCain TV ads that link
McCain with Ronald Reagan, a California Republican icon. And in
California, core Republicans who watched Democrats take over all
but two statewide offices might be prepared to vote for a candidate
they think can win, even if they find him occasionally irritating.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will be trying to walk a fine line in coming weeks,
seeking more Republican votes without weakening himself among
independents.
</P>
<P>
   In several states, including Virginia next week, the Republican
primaries are open to independents, and in some cases, Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The cluster of March 7 primaries includes Georgia, where the
primary is open to all voters, and much of New England, where
independents can vote in the GOP contests.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
