<SLUG> BC-PRIMARY-ARIZONA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN SAVORS BIG WIN IN HOME STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ He was supposed to be home, taking a nap. But John
McCain can't stand to be alone, and besides, as he excitedly told
the advisers he kept calling on the telephone, his ``do or die''
presidential campaign appeared to be close to doing it Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   By lunchtime here, McCain advisers were excited. Exit polls
showed McCain ahead of Texas Governor George W. Bush in the
critical Michigan primary, that he would score a big win here in
the Arizona primary, and, most important to McCain, that he could
prevail without big-name endorsements or crawling into the
negative-campaign gutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day is do or die, we're a high-wire act, an insurgency
campaign, and we've had a great, great ride, and we're proud of the
positive campaign we've been running,'' the Arizona senator told
reporters after voting for himself at Phoenix's Veterans Memorial
Coliseum. ``We believe that is the way the voters will finally come
down.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory in Arizona was expected but still sweet for the
three-term senator. Several prominent GOP officeholders, including
Governor Jane Hull, were working against McCain, whose relationship
with Hull has been stormy. She showed up at the coliseum before
McCain, voted for Bush, and told reporters, ``It's an exciting day
for Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's advisers, however, were far more focused on Michigan,
where a defeat could cripple a campaign that had soared high after
thumping Bush in the New Hampshire primary and then was badly stung
in Saturday's bruising South Carolina primary. They had not had
much time to recover from South Carolina, so their best hope was
that Michigan voters would reject the anti-McCain barrage and
ignore Governor John Engler's endorsement of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michigan was the jury, and it voted against Bush's negative
tactics in South Carolina,'' said Michael Murphy, one of McCain's
top strategists. ``And more importantly, it has shown that McCain
is a far stronger candidate against Al Gore than George W. Bush,
because he has shown power in Michigan, a state that really counts
in the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Davis, McCain's campaign manager, said the exit polls
showed ``a total repudiation'' of the value of negative
campaigning, which tarnished McCain more than Bush in South
Carolina. McCain vowed to end his negative attacks, and he angrily
accused Bush of ``character assassination'' when he and others
allied with Bush, like evangelist Pat Robertson, did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``What changed from South Carolina was that the people of
Michigan weren't inundated with negative attack ads by the Bush
campaign and its surrogates,'' Davis said. ``So they were able to
see the campaign in a relatively clear prism. We've always felt
that given that opportunity, people would choose John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   If McCain calls himself a high-wire aerialist, it's his campaign
that often seems to be flying without a net. Tuesday, encouraged by
the reports from Michigan, advisers hastily plotted a course that
would take McCain to Washington state _ political director John
Weaver called the McCain camp bullish on its Tuesday primary _ and
to the big March 7 contests in New York, California, and New
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll run full bore,'' said Weaver, who thinks McCain can stay
competitive because both campaigns have war chests of about $15
million. ``John is doing very well in New England, particularly in
Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut, and Vermont, and
naturally, all eyes will be on California.''
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls in Michigan showed that McCain was doing very
well among cross-over Democratic and independent voters. Bruce
Merrill, a professor of mass communications at Arizona State
University and a longtime McCain-watcher, said that may be a risky
strategy as the campaign heads into primaries open only to
Republicans. ``Even if he wins narrowly in Michigan, I don't see
how he survives for long,'' Merrill said.
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain is clearly exhausted from nonstop campaigning,
aides tentatively scheduled a predawn departure for Washington
state this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Cindy McCain had ordered her husband to spend a quiet
day at their sprawling home on Phoenix's Central Avenue. But when
he wasn't on the phone, or meeting with advisers, McCain was at his
son's school, attending the practice of his championship lacrosse
team. Tuesday night, the McCains planned a small party at their
home for family and friends before attending a larger victory rally
at a nearby resort.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, an estimated 4,000 people, mostly students, turned
out at a McCain welcome-home at the University of Arizona in
Tucson. Aides said it was the largest single crowd he has attracted
in his 22-year political career here. Deb Gullet, the senator's
state campaign manager, said he was ``tired and upbeat and
enthusiastic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think its kind of nice to be the first presidential
candidate in this campaign to vote for himself _ it's a unique
experience.'' McCain said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
