<SLUG> BC-EXECUTION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PAROLE BOARD DENIES REPRIEVE FOR WOMAN SCHEDULED TO DIE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state Board of Pardons and Paroles ruled
Tuesday that there is no compelling reason to delay Thursday's
scheduled execution of condemned murderer Betty Lou Beets.
</P>
<P>
   On a 13-5 vote, the board refused to recommend to Gov. George W.
Bush a 180-day reprieve for Beets, and it unanimously rejected
commutation of her death sentence to a term of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to save her life, Beets' daughters pleaded for a
review of the case based on a relatively new claim that Beets was a
physically and emotionally battered wife.
</P>
<P>
   But parole board Chairman Gerald Garrett said Beets wasn't
eligible for a special clemency review that was authorized by state
lawmakers in 1991. The review, reserved for inmates whose crimes
may have resulted from overlooked domestic violence, doesn't apply
to Beets because she murdered ``for financial gain'' and has shown
no remorse, Garrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has never accepted guilt for the offense for which she was
sentenced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beets, 62, of Gun Barrel City in northeast Texas, is set to be
executed for the 1983 shooting death of her fifth husband, Dallas
fire Capt. Jimmy Don Beets. His body was found buried outside
Beets' home about two years after he was reported missing while on
a fishing trip.
</P>
<P>
   Beets would be only the second woman executed in Texas since the
Civil War and the fourth in the nation since the U.S. Supreme Court
allowed capital punishment to resume in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Appellate attorney Joe Margulies said Beets' trial lawyer knew
about a pattern of spousal abuse, but failed to raise it as a
mitigating factor. Backed by the Texas Council on Family Violence,
Margulies displayed photographs that he said came from the trial
lawyer's files and corroborated her abuse claim, along with her
daughters' sworn affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   One of her daughters said the photos were taken a week after she
was severely beaten by her fourth husband, Doyle Wayne Barker.
Barker's body likewise was found buried near Beets' home, and
although she was indicted in his 1981 shooting death, she was never
tried on that charge.
</P>
<P>
   Urging Bush to reduce Beets' punishment to a life term because
of her victimization, her daughter, Faye Lane, tearfully said,
``I've seen it with my own eyes ... All my mama's life she's been
abused. I've seen her beaten up by her husbands so many times I
can't remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could only have done something like this if she had been
very scared or threatened ... The jury never heard any reason to
have compassion about my mama, and when I told her lawyer, he
wouldn't listen,'' Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who don't live with it just don't understand what it
does to you, how hopeless, vulnerable and ashamed it makes you
feel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That contention was backed up by University of Texas law
professor Sarah Buel, an expert on domestic violence. She contended
the state does not have the right ``to execute a battered woman who
has been denied due process, who has been denied effective
assistance of counsel.'' Buel said Beets endured ``horrific abuse''
and was ``only trying to figure out how to stay alive'' when she
took her final husband's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, as her community, we have to take some
responsibility for failing to protect her at many, many possible
points of intervention,'' Buel said.
</P>
<P>
   Beets was condemned based on a Henderson County jury's finding
that the murder was motivated by her desire to cash in on her
husband's insurance and pension benefits. But her trial lawyer has
sworn that Beets knew nothing about those benefits until he told
her about them a year after the murder.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate lawsuit seeking the special review that was denied
Tuesday, Beets said she was raped at age 5, first married at age
15, and was abused by all but her third husband. Her ``lifetime of
abuse'' resulted in brain damage, post-traumatic stress disorder,
battered women's syndrome and rape-trauma syndrome, Margulies said.
</P>
<P>
