<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WORDS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW OPERA: AT NOT LOSS FOR WORDS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Words have been much on music's mind lately, and the two have
been as much opponents as colleagues. Watching important literary
properties (``The Great Gatsby,'' ``A Streetcar Named Desire'')
being wrestled to the ground musically has become a sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, words seem to be coming out on top. New
operas have to have selling points, and music is not first among
them.
</P>
<P>
   Manifestos are easier than the great books. Social and racial
justice are can't-miss categories (``Harvey Milk,'' ``Marilyn,''
``Malcolm X''). Narrate the thundering international incident
(``The Death of Klinghoffer''); add music to the popular movie
(Jake Heggie's soon-to-be ``Dead Man Walking'').
</P>
<P>
   F. Scott Fitzgerald and Tennessee Williams have more cachet, but
any topical news item or publicity-drenched cause will do. First
the sexy idea, then how to illustrate it with a lot of loud
singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gatsby'' and ``Streetcar'' have had the tougher problem. Their
newsy companions, with no texts set in stone, have enjoyed free
rides into mediocrity. How were John Harbison and Andre Previn to
get away with ``Gatsby'' and ``Streetcar'' with the authors looking
over their shoulders?
</P>
<P>
   Harbison may have looked back too often, thus becalming his new
piece with an undue reverence for the original. Previn's opera
moved gingerly through its minefield of famous scenes and
much-quoted lines. In ``The Festival of Regrets,'' part of the New
York City Opera's recent triptych, ``Central Park,'' Deborah
Drattell treated Wendy Wasserstein's clever libretto with such
open-mouthed awe that her music dwindled to near-invisibility.
</P>
<P>
   Cole Porter's ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' currently running wild on
Broadway, may have a better idea. Its center is Shakespeare's
``Taming of the Shrew,'' and bits of that hallowed text run through
the evening. But Shakespeare's plot is hollowed out. Broad outlines
are left standing; virtually everything else is trashed and hauled
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss Me, Kate'' ignores the play's maze of exchanged and
hidden identities. Some of the clever wordplay and punning
survives, but most of it gives way to songs like ``So in Love'' and
``From This Moment On'' and Porter's fiendishly clever lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Music can't emulate Shakespeare or Fitzgerald or Williams, but
what it can do is leave the walls of their writing untouched and
build something entirely new inside. An architect friend of mine
calls it ``adaptive use.'' We see examples all over Lower
Manhattan; and for urban renewers across the land, the idea is a
form of daily bread.
</P>
<P>
   What to do with a handsome loft building in SoHo once floor upon
floor of small manufacturers have disappeared? An earlier
generation would have torn it down and begun all over again. The
present one preserves the facade and puts behind it overpriced
living spaces, art galleries and clothing shops with Italian names.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss Me, Kate'' proudly advertises its lack of fidelity by
offering a play within a play, the backstage drama emanating from
and sometimes bleeding into what happens before the footlights.
Another thing that gives this revival at the Martin Beck Theater
such a healthy look is its commercialism. It is trying to make
money by making audiences happy; and so there has been some inner
as well as outer adaptive use going on.
</P>
<P>
   The 1948 original pretty much went along with the Elizabethan
idea of womanly subservience. In the year 2000, delicate revision
allows Kate's elaborate postlude on wifely virtues to be delivered
with a smirk or two. Happily, Shakespeare's urtext has an
incorruptible life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Public reverence and public subsidy make sure that ``Kiss Me,
Kate'' can't touch it. The inviolability of the Fitzgerald and
Williams originals is equally assured, but that fact needn't stop
opera composers from ripping out any walls they want. It certainly
didn't stop Verdi, who used the bare bones of his beloved
Shakespearean plays and reconstituted them with powerful Italian
melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   This is one neighborhood zoned for anti-authenticity. If our
SoHo loft building really hewed to contextual accuracy, it would
recreate the old lost companies within its spruced-up walls and set
them to making parts for machines now extinct. Maybe these
operations could get a grant from the National Endowment for the
Arts or gifts from the French and German ministries of culture. I
can't think of anyone who would pay them money otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss Me, Kate'' bears a resemblance to one of those railroad
stations turned shopping center. Some trains may go in and out just
to keep the original atmosphere alive, but the waiting rooms and
all the attendant dramas of travel are pushed pretty much to the
side.
</P>
<P>
   Opera composers often begin with other people's words; the
question is, who will be boss? The horrifying drabness of most
music on Broadway suggests composers dedicated to making sure that
we understand every overamplified line. Visits to four musicals in
quick succession a year or so ago found the same semichanted,
run-on, through-composed music, replete with phony climaxes,
running from one show into the next. No one with eyes shut could
have told one event from another.
</P>
<P>
   There is a case for blaming the tyranny of words and stories for
the uniformity of Broadway musicals and the pervasive drabness of
new American opera, but maybe we are looking at the wrong end of
this argument. Maybe the true culprit is a lack of original music
in the first place. Storytelling has simply rushed in to fill the
vacuum. Perhaps, the only thing to put great literature in its
operatic place is better composers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
