<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5136 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AUDRA-MCDONALD-MUSIC-     02-22 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDRA-MCDONALD-MUSIC-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOFTY VISION OF A BETTER MUSICAL THEATER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Audra McDonald, the theatrical mezzo-soprano who has drawn the
kind of acclaim on which legends are built, is a singer of such
impeccable taste that she can turn the most rough-and-tumble
Broadway showstopper into a concert gem.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to her exquisitely phrased, finely shaded performances
of a program of mostly show tunes on her second solo album, ``How
Glory Goes,'' you come away captivated by as lofty a vision of
nonclassical American theater music as any singer has dared put
forth.
</P>
<P>
   Although the collection of 14 songs tilts more toward Broadway
than did McDonald's 1998 debut album, ``Way Back From Paradise,''
which consisted mostly of theatrical art songs written by obscure
younger composers, its musical point of view is just as elevated.
Classic show tunes like ``Bill'' (from ``Show Boat''), ``A Sleepin'
Bee'' (from ``House of Flowers'') and even Judy Garland's signature
tearjerker ``The Man That Got Away'' (from the movie ``A Star Is
Born'') coincide comfortably with gorgeous, little-known theater
songs by Jeanine Tesori, Adam Guettel and other lesser-known
contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   What holds the program together are passionate vocal
performances that glide so seamlessly between a semi-operatic
lyricism and a pop-blues gutsiness that the normal dividing line
separating classical formality from pop self-expression completely
dissolves. At the same time, the prim twittering arrangements for a
woodwind-heavy orchestra blur the distinctions between a theatrical
pit band and a classical ensemble. There's not a musical moment on
this predominantly contemplative album that could be described as
blaring or bumping-and-grinding.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably no accident that the collection's most heavily
represented composer is Harold Arlen, with five songs: ``Any Place
I Hang My Hat Is Home,'' ``I Had Myself a True Love,'' ``A Sleepin'
Bee,'' ``I Never Has Seen Snow'' and ``The Man That Got Away.'' And
it is also probably no accident that all five have previously been
recorded by Barbra Streisand, whose 1963 debut album marked a
historical musical moment that is comparable to McDonald's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Arlen's belting pop-blues show stoppers for Lena Horne, Garland
and Streisand established him as the most diva-friendly composer of
his generation. And McDonald, for all her classical restraint, also
projects an expansive, larger-than-life theatricality.
</P>
<P>
   In ``How Glory Goes,'' she seems to be staking her own claim to
this tradition and doing so on her own noncompetitive terms. The
album's opening cut, a joyous, beautifully articulated ``Any Place
I Hang My Hat Is Home,'' from the 1946 show ``St. Louis Woman,''
can be taken as a statement of musical intention.
</P>
<P>
   But McDonald's approach to Arlen is pointedly different from,
and in some ways opposite, that of Streisand, who recorded three of
these numbers on her first three albums. Those still-thrilling
early '60s performances blew the roof off the songs with a tornadic
intensity of will and the jaw-dropping bravado of a budding
superstar determined to conquer the world.
</P>
<P>
   If McDonald's singing does not convey the same raw excitement
and personal ambition, in its own discreet way it is as emotionally
charged. Interpreting Arlen's classic torch songs, ``I Had Myself a
True Love'' and ``The Man That Got Away,'' McDonald goes against
custom by making each an expression of private sorrow instead of
public kvetching.
</P>
<P>
   So many singers have used these songs to parade their
heartbreak, building them into crowd-pleasing athletic
demonstrations, that to hear McDonald's anguished interior
monologues is to hear them subtly reinvented. The mood of
introspection is mirrored by arrangements that refuse to nudge the
singer toward the footlights.
</P>
<P>
   Cut by cut, ``How Glory Goes'' (Nonesuch 79580-2) purposefully
builds to a quietly shattering climax that segues ``Somewhere''
from ``West Side Story'' into ``How Glory Goes'' from Guettel's
1994 Off-Broadway show ``Floyd Collins.''
</P>
<P>
   The first song's aching romantic cry for a mythical lovers'
refuge deepens in Guettel's song into a wider spiritual inquiry
about death, eternity and the possibilities of an afterlife. The
album fades out on Tesori's and Brian Crawley's tender lullaby,
``Lay Down Your Head,'' from the 1997 musical ``Violet.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this kind of cerebral contemplation has had an honored
place in the Broadway musical at least since Rodgers and
Hammerstein's ``Carousel,'' that place has never been large. Which
raises the delicate question of how much impact McDonald's
brilliant but comparatively introverted albums can have on the
gaudy landscape of show business.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Streisand stormed onto the scene nearly 40 years
ago, she was viewed as a savior by aging composers like Arlen and
Jule Styne, who embraced this talent with the force to stir up
their creative juices. Since then, of course, many Broadway stars
have risen and fallen, but until now none has offered the almost
unlimited promise of McDonald, who in addition to having a major
voice is blessed with beauty, intelligence, taste and formidable
acting ability.
</P>
<P>
   In championing composers like Guettel and Tesori and placing
their songs alongside those of Kern, Arlen and Bernstein, McDonald
has made a bold and powerful statement about the future. Now it is
up to the composers and their collaborators to deliver the shows
from which she can spin her magic.
</P>
<P>
   But will they? Already one has come and gone, Michael John
LaChiusa's promising but flawed ``Marie Christine,'' which was
custom made for her.
</P>
<P>
   As for the public, beyond a coterie, does a mass music-theater
audience schooled in its taste by Andrew Lloyd Webber, Frank
Wildhorn and Boublil and Schonberg expect or even want a musical
theater as refined as the ideal envisioned by McDonald's albums?
Rude rabble-rousing pop fantasies have always been the bedrock of
the Broadway musical.
</P>
<P>
   It may well be that her vision of a higher and better popular
musical theater will turn out to be a pipe dream. If so, McDonald
will at least have dreamed as large as a singer who fuses the best
of two musical worlds could.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
