A5141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-HAWKS-RIDER23-COX     02-22 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-RIDER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rider may be moved by Hawks
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ It hasn't even been seven months since the
Atlanta Hawks acquired Isaiah Rider. But they are so weary of his
actions off the court and his moodiness on it that they might waive
him if they can't trade him. A trade appears to be the first
option. With the NBA trading deadline Thursday at 6 p.m., several
teams, including Miami and Chicago, are interested in acquiring
Rider. Tonight's game against the Sacramento Kings could be his
final game in a Hawks' uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only tell you I'm talking to teams around the league
about a lot of different things,'' Hawks general manager Pete
Babcock said. Babcock added that no deal would take place before
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If no deal is made, a decision to waive Rider and pay off his
contract is a possibility. When asked about his reaction to the
possibility that he might be waived, Rider responded, ``That's
cool. I'll get my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider's $5.4 million contract for this season is fully
guaranteed. He makes $65,853.66 per game. If the Hawks were unable
to trade him and elected to waive him before Friday's game in
Seattle, they would be obligated to pay another $1.975 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now 28-years-old, Rider gives this assessment of life in the
NBA: ``It's all about having fun and playing basketball and getting
paid,'' he said. ``If they aren't going to do that, then I'll get
paid and be at it next year. Somebody wants the talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there has been less fun and less money.
</P>
<P>
   Rider has paid about $200,000 in fines and suspensions this
season to the charitable Hawks Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons that he does not share, Rider is noticeably moody
these days. His game suffered the past four weeks, as his shooting
and per-game scoring plummeted to season lows of .416 and 21.4,
respectively. Monday night, however, Rider apparently enjoyed a
renewed rivalry with Utah fans. Last spring, they suffered when
Portland and Rider eliminated the Jazz in the playoffs. He hit his
first four shots and finished with 22 points in the Hawks' 96-94
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the showing will encourage suitors around the league who
have some interest in Rider's offensive potential.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is one of them. The Heat is believed to be offering guard
Voshon Lenard, whose contract runs through 2002 with a total
obligation of about $9 million, and forward Mark Strickland, signed
through next season at about $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   One rumor to disregard involving the Heat is the widely reported
Rider-Alan Henderson-Bimbo Coles for P.J. Brown-Lenard deal. Brown
is not available, and Henderson is a base-year player under the
salary cap, which means that the Hawks cannot take back the full
value of his contract in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock might be able to deal Rider to the Bulls, who are trying
to clear maximum cap room for the summer. Chicago is offering
veteran guard Hersey Hawkins, who is signed through next season at
a salary of $4.1 million, and perhaps a second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   It would be cheaper for the Hawks either to waive Rider or to
suffer through the rest of the season and hope they can peddle him
in a sign-and-trade deal over the summer, when Rider becomes a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Hawks avidly protect their ability to go well
under the cap in 2001, they also want to remain flexible this
summer, when Henderson, for example, loses his base-year
designation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably can't have cap room,'' Babcock said, ``but we
would not discount the possibility of being able to work a
sign-and-trade that would allow us to sign a free agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
