<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5145 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-RUBELLS-ART-2TAKES-$A     02-22 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBELLS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SCENE HEATS UP UNDER THE MIAMI SUN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 David Hay is a playwright and journalist who writes about the
arts.  
 By DAVID HAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The talk was fast and furious on a January evening that
was distinctly chilly by Miami standards. ``Did you know this
building used to be a cocaine factory?'' asked one of the guests at
the opening of a new exhibition at the Rubell Family Collection's
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   A mile and a half northwest of downtown, the 40,000-square-foot
warehouse once served, in fact, as a storage facility for
contraband seized by the Drug Enforcement Administration. But on
this night, when many new acquisitions by the New York and Miami
collectors Donald and Mera Rubell were on display for the first
time, most of the comments centered on how the Miami art scene was
coming of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite something, isn't it?'' said Bonnie Clearwater, the
director of the Museum of Contemporary Art in North Miami, looking
at the crowd. More than 500 guests attended the opening, a
testament to the enthusiasm that has been generated in the last
year by the emergence of new artists and unusual gallery spaces in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Clearwater, who like everyone else was dressed in
standard black, was another star of the evening: an untitled
diptych painted last year by Chris Ofili, the young British artist
whose ``Holy Virgin Mary'' was at the center of the public debate
over the Brooklyn Museum of Art's recent ``Sensation'' exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   In his new work, Ofili juxtaposed two richly textured portraits
of a man and a woman, turning their noble poses into something more
flirtatious. The work rested on the floor supported by two hard
lumps of dung.
</P>
<P>
   Running through June, the exhibition, curated by Bill Begert,
29, demonstrated how thoroughly the Rubells have scoured the
contemporary art market. Only 105 pieces from a collection of more
than 1,100 works were on display; the contributions by Cindy
Sherman (a self-portrait from 1978), Damien Hirst, Charles Ray,
Rosemarie Trockel and the photographer Thomas Struth were
particularly strong.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Rubells' latest acquisitions were 16 paintings done on
such found wooden objects as the back of a high chair by the
Miami-born Purvis Young. (The Rubells bought 3,000 of Young's
paintings in one day last May.) A long, thin gallery was devoted to
photographs of performance pieces by the Chinese artist Zhang Haan.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that same night, much of the city's art establishment
trekked through the deserted Espirito Santo Bank building on
Miami's fashionable Brickell Avenue. A nine-story dark-tinted glass
box, it was about to be demolished to make way for the 36-story
Espirito Santo Plaza, designed by Kohn Pedersen Fox.
</P>
<P>
   But on this evening _ inspired by William Ross, the president of
Group Espirito Santo's United States development company _ the
empty building became the site of an extraordinary exhibition,
``Departing Perspectives.'' Forty-four artists, ranging from the
well-known Haitian-born Edward Duval Carrie to students from the
New World College of the Arts, had spent four days making
installations in the staircases, offices and even vaults of the
empty building. Open to the public for one weekend, the show would
disappear with the arrival of the wrecking ball.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of imminent destruction proved irresistible. In one
corner office, Carol K. Brown opted to build tiny wood stairways
leading to miniature doorways carved into the wall. Behind each
door the artist glued a sentence typical of any good domestic
argument _ ``You'll Never Amount to Anything,'' ``You Always
Embarrass Me.''
</P>
<P>
   On another floor, Annie Wharton transformed a bleakly
utilitarian office into a showcase for beauty by covering the walls
and pillars with soft, circular plastic molds, each in a creamy
pastel shade. On the third floor, Julian Picaza, 22, Jay Hines, 22,
and Bhakti Baxter, 20, tore down walls to erect a moving, womblike
walk-through structure made of cream-colored paper, onto which a
video of ocean currents was projected. In a closet on the seventh
floor, Baxter had installed huge, almost grotesque ivy vines that
burst from the walls, symbolizing nature's attempt to take back the
doomed building.
</P>
<P>
   Many patrons commented on how strong the younger artists' work
was. Born and schooled in this city, a new generation is serving
notice that the Miami art world is no longer the exclusive preserve
of emigre artists from Cuba or Haiti or even New York.
</P>
<P>
   This meeting of the old and the new was on display earlier in
the day at the Fredric Snitzer Gallery in Coconut Grove.
</P>
<P>
   Attending a lunch for the Cuban-born artist Jose Bedia were
members of a collector's circle from the Birmingham Museum of Art
in Alabama. (They timed their visit to coincide with Art Miami, an
international art fair held in the Miami Beach Convention Center in
late January.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With his paintings on the gallery walls around him, the
long-haired Bedia talked eloquently of his desire to fuse the
symbolism of the Afro-Cuban religious system known as Palo Monte
with that of the American Indian. Bedia, who has been based in
Miami for six years, also spoke of the symbols he used to evoke the
forced journey of migration.
</P>
<P>
   Listening attentively was a 23-year-old Miami-born artist, Naomi
Fisher. Wearing a pale pink Lacoste cardigan, her black hair
falling gently about her face, the soft-spoken Fisher confessed to
being ``so comfortable in this city, I don't see any reason to
move.'' An exhibition of her large color photographic studies of
women imperiled by nature _ in one, the artist has buried her face
into the ground at the base of a tree, while in another she appears
to have been impaled by a coconut palm _ opened earlier this month
at the Snitzer Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   This burgeoning new talent has not gone unnoticed by the city's
major institutions. Later this year, the Miami Art Museum begins
its ``New Work: Miami'' project, a series of four exhibitions each
featuring commissioned works from two local artists.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, however, the Miami Art Museum and the Museum of
Contemporary Art are provoking a different kind of discussion. By
sponsoring major exhibitions of, respectively, Brice Marden and
Frank Stella, they are asking Miamians to examine the direction
abstract art took in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Marden exhibition differs slightly from its first showing,
at the Hirshhorn Museum in Washington. An earlier work, ``Cold
Mountain No. 1,'' as well as two new paintings that continue the
artist's recent confident embrace of color, have been added.
</P>
<P>
   While some have noted how seductive Marden's work has become in
the 1990s, Peter Boswell, the senior curator at the Miami Art
Museum, argued that ``it would be a mistake to assume that the new
work is less subtle than the black-and-white images from the Cold
Mountain series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, it's more subtle,'' he said. ``The interplay of
colors is complex and there's a lot more change and working over of
the painting than is evident at first glance.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions of subtlety _ and, surprisingly, even lyricism _ hang
over Frank Stella's exhibit at Charles Gwathmey's handsome but
modest Museum of Contemporary Art.
</P>
<P>
   Wedged between city hall and the North Miami police station, the
museum has devoted its two galleries, one expansive and the other
small, to the first major exhibition of new work from Stella in the
United States since his 1987 show at the Museum of Modern Art in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The artist has moved from basing his work on geometric and
engineering templates to extrapolating from three-dimensional
computerized images of blown smoke rings. It's a multidimensional
template that allows Stella the freedom to construct even wilder
collages of forms, colors and objects. But the result of this
chaos, especially with the large canvases, is a gentle lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do have an ease about them,'' Stella admitted in a
telephone interview. ``They float above the ground.'' Between the
huge canvases are heavy, swirling sculptures Stella made in his
workshop near Newburgh, N.Y., combining preciously forged steel
with other metal objects from everyday life, like an old truck
frame.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of both museums expressed delight with the response to
the exhibitions. (The posters o the sides of city buses for
Stella's show, whose design was supervised by the artist himself,
may have helped.) For Stella's Feb. 12 public lecture at the
450-seat Kobens Center at Florida International University, a live
video feed to another hall had to be set up to accommodate the huge
turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Just what impact these museum shows will have on Miami's own
artists is yet to be gauged. But their presence adds to the
community's growing sense of self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   This was on the mind of Amy Cappellazzo, visiting curator at the
Palm Beach Institute of Contemporary Art, who attended the opening
at the Rubells' warehouse gallery. ``To be able to attract two
exhibitions of this caliber at the same time is a tribute to how
this city's art world is maturing,'' Cappellazzo said. ``It's a
good moment to be in Miami.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
