<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINDEN CHECKING HIS PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ No matter what happens with Marty McSorley
at his disciplinary hearing this morning, it was clear long before
he went off the deep end Monday night that the Bruins were a team
in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   There are 23 games left in the regular season, and the way the
club is playing right now, it seems they will miss the postseason
for the second time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns, who has been embattled for several weeks, is
trying everything in his bag of tricks to turn the team's fortunes
around. The players are saying all the right things _ ``We have to
get something going'' _ but they were saying that when there were
40 games left and then 35 and then 30 and then 25.
</P>
<P>
   President/general manager Harry Sinden, who flew to New York
Tuesday for McSorley's hearing, sees two possible reasons behind
the team's ineptitude: the players aren't good enough or they're
underachieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to assess whether or not we have a bunch of
players who are playing right up to their level and that's the best
they can do,'' said Sinden. ``If that's the case, we sure as hell
have got the wrong bunch of players because look where we are. Or,
we've got a bunch of players who are playing way below and are
underachieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to assess whether all these players we put
together a couple or three years ago are this bad because this is
pretty bad. We win one game every three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have 18 wins all year, and only five in their last 21
contests as they head into a game against the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're underachieving, then that's another problem,'' said
Sinden. ``It's hard to determine. We try to go by what you see is
what you get and that's not very much. We try to look back at last
year and the year before and we got a lot more last year and the
year before than we're getting now. Should we discount those two
years and just say, `This is it. This is as good as they are'? If
it is, we sure as hell missed on almost all these players, almost
all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden wasn't critical of his players' work ethic, saying he
hasn't detected any laziness. It appears the players simply don't
get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel in many ways bad for them,'' said Sinden. ``I really
didn't think they were capable of playing this loosely. We can't
win a game. They've forgotten how to play. If we keep playing like
this, we'll lose a lot of games. You know how everyone says, `If we
play like this, we'll win a lot'? Well, if we keep playing like
this, we'll lose a lot. We've really lost our way. We're all over
the ice. This is pretty bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5156 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-1STLD     02-22 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE LAWYERS ASK JURY TO SEE DIALLO SLAYING AS TRAGIC ERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (recasts last 650 or so words of story _ after trim indicator
beginning `STORY CAN END HERE ...' _ with different details,
lawyers' names, quotes from their final arguments, etc.)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT11-12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JANE FRITSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With raised voices and emotional appeals, lawyers
for the four New York City police officers charged with the murder
of Amadou Diallo pleaded with jurors Tuesday to see his shooting as
a tragic mistake brought on by Diallo's actions.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Eric Warner, responded with an equally
impassioned argument. ``Amadou Diallo never had a chance,'' Warner
said. ``In the mind-set they had, that man was doomed from the
minute they saw him.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' summations came after three weeks of a trial that
was, at times, racially charged. The four officers, who are white,
fired 41 shots at Diallo, a black man who was standing, unarmed, in
the vestibule of his apartment building in the Bronx on Feb. 4,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   In their arguments Tuesday, the defense lawyers stressed the
state of mind of the officers, who they said shot Diallo out of
fear. They believed Diallo was pulling a gun out if his pocket and
intended to shoot them, the lawyers said. The officers, who
happened to be driving down the street where Diallo lived, said
they approached him because they thought he might have been a
rapist or a robber.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner argued that the officers thought the worst of Diallo
for no good reason and that their judgment was flawed from the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were willing to write him off on such flimsy
suspicions,'' Warner said. ``He was one of the people they were
supposed to protect,'' he added, but the officers ``took a dim view
of that block and everything went downhill from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury of four black women, two white women and six white men
is to begin deliberating Wednesday, after hearing instructions on
the law from Justice Joseph C. Teresi of the Supreme Court. The
officers could be convicted of second-degree murder, first-degree
manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide in relation to
Diallo, and reckless endangerment of bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants _ Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Richard Murphy
and Kenneth Boss _ all pleaded innocent to the two counts of
second-degree murder that each is charged with in the killing of
Diallo, a 22-year-old immigrant from Guinea. The first count is for
Diallo's death and the second for depraved indifference to human
life.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Their minimum penalties, if they are convicted, range from
probation to imprisonment for 15 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the officers were charged with any crime at all
has enraged many police supporters, including the police officers
and relatives who pack the courtroom every day. The trial was moved
from the Bronx because of concerns over pretrial publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district attorney asks you to judge them and what they did
that night,'' Steven Brounstein, who represents Boss, told the jury
Tuesday. ``That is arrogance and that is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The main defense argument, generally, is justification, and it
rests chiefly on the testimony of the four officers. Under New York
law, a killing can be justified if a reasonable person in the same
circumstances would have believed his life was in danger. Each
officer said that he believed that Diallo had a gun; it turned out
to be a wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the officers, there was one eyewitness to the
shooting, Schrrie Elliott, but her testimony was contradictory on
many critical points. She said, for instance, that she heard one of
the officers shout, ``Gun!'' but she also said that it could have
been Diallo himself who said it. And she said that Diallo fell to
the ground immediately when the shooting started, but also said
that he remained standing through many of the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the defense lawyers relied heavily on her
testimony in their summations Tuesday. ``She destroyed their
case,'' said James Culleton, who represents Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Worth, the lawyer for McMellon, called her ``the key
witness in this case,'' who had provided the most important
testimony in the case, the word ``gun.''
</P>
<P>
   In their opening statements, the defense had blamed Diallo for
the shooting, but their attacks on him were much harsher Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went through every body motion and conveyed with every
nonverbal cue that he had a gun,'' said John D. Patten, the lawyer
for Carroll, who led the four in their attack on Diallo and fired
16 shots. ``Why didn't he talk to them?'' Patten demanded, his
voice rising. ``Why didn't he stop? Why did he reach into his
pocket? Why did he turn his back to them?''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``When that man turned around, that was it. You can't
ask them to stand around and get blasted away.''
</P>
<P>
   Culleton was somewhat gentler in his assessment of Diallo's
behavior, but said he had been acting suspiciously, peering out
from the stoop of his building. The officers, he said, ``had an
obligation to stop and ask, `Who are you? What are you doing here
in this high-crime area?''' The incident escalated, Culleton said,
``for reasons we will never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers had said in their opening statements that
they would present evidence to show why Diallo might have wanted to
flee from the police, but, as Warner pointed out, they never
offered any such evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In Warner's view, it was Diallo, not the officers, who logically
had reason to be afraid. At 5 foot 6 inches and 160 pounds, Diallo
probably felt terrified and overpowered by the four large men in
plainclothes who were armed and wearing protective vests as they
confronted him, Warner said. It was very likely, Warner added, that
when Diallo reached into his pocket he was either looking for money
to surrender to what he perceived as a group of robbers or
identification to show them.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, . Warner said, the officers never paused to view
the situation from Diallo's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it was unavoidable,'' Warner said. ``But it was a
terrible series of conscious decisions that fell far short of
protecting his life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
