<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DOW-EXCITE-NYT &LR;      02-22 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-EXCITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW JONES AND EXCITE PLAN WEB VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Note (at) in parens designates the `at' sign in Excite
company name.)  
(jw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move combining the news resources of Dow Jones &AMP; Co. with
the technical expertise and audience reach of Excite(at)Home, the
two corporations plan to create a new Internet site devoted to
business-to-business communications and transactions for small and
medium-sized companies.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, to be called Work.com _ the same name of
Excite(at)Home's current business-oriented site _ would start late
this summer, the two companies said Tuesday, and would carry the
kind of breaking news coverage now available on dowjones.com.
</P>
<P>
   Executives also said they hoped to make an initial public
offering of some shares in the venture after its start. But L.
Gordon Crovitz, a senior vice president of Dow Jones for electronic
publishing, said that the offering would not preclude a possible
separate offering of a stock tracking Dow Jones' Internet assets.
</P>
<P>
   George Bell, president of Excite, said that his company, which
is the biggest portal on the Web with access to high-speed cable
modem communications, could offer small business clients services,
including Web hosting, e-mail and commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Customers in the target market _ companies with 500 or fewer
employees _ could use the site's features to set themselves up for
business on the Internet. In particular, Bell said, Excite(at)Home
could offer services that would both draw potential audiences and
customers to small businesses as they go online and help them
manage Web traffic issues to avoid the system crashes that
sometimes plague small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The new site would initially derive most of its revenue from
advertising, though eventually, as the site's offerings became
richer, other sources, from subscriptions to transactional
revenues, would be expected to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The new company would move into a business niche now occupied by
companies like Office.com, a Winstar Communications site that
packages business news from sources like Reuters and Knight Ridder
with guidance and specialized information on e-commerce; and Penton
Media, which publishes trade magazines, runs conferences and trade
shows and maintains more than 40 Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that owning this business portal franchise is very
important to Dow Jones,'' said Lauren Rich Fine, an analyst with
Merrill Lynch. ``And Excite(at)Home is up against the wall to get
distinguishable content.''
</P>
<P>
   Crovitz said he was not worried about the new company
cannibalizing Dow Jones' existing Internet offerings, which include
The Wall Street Journal online; as of December that site had
375,000 subscribers and accounted for about $32 million of Dow
Jones' estimated $150 million in Internet revenue in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The current offerings on the free dowjones.com Web site, which
would migrate to the new Work.com site, include part of the
material on the Dow Jones wire service and limited selections from
The Journal's online edition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
