<SLUG> BC-ARIZ-PRIMARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
 
McCAIN KEEPS FIRM GRIP ON HOME STATE 
 (See also ARIZ-MCCAIN) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT5-7 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ In the end, the home-state hero more than held his own
here Tuesday night, as Sen. John McCain's resounding victory over
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas cut across virtually all demographic
groups in the Arizona Republican electorate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won despite an unusually divisive campaign in which he
lost the support of his own governor and was outspent roughly
10-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   In surveys of voters leaving the polls, McCain led by about 20
points, losing to Bush only among the quarter of the electorate
that described itself as very conservative, which Bush carried with
just over five in 10 votes, to just under four in 10 for McCain.
Among voters who said that abortion should always be illegal, Bush
barely edged out McCain.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs that Bush's television advertising blitz, and
McCain's 17-year electoral career in which he has made his share of
enemies here, took a toll in a state where the population is
growing dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain beat Bush nearly 2-to-1 among longtime residents,
and won a majority even among those who have moved here within the
last 10 years, Bush ran strongly among the newcomers, taking just
over four in 10 of their votes. And though McCain beat out Bush for
the title of ``the real reformer'' in the race, a plurality of
voters _ nearly a third _ said both were. That apparently reflected
the success of Bush's post New Hampshire claim to be a ``reformer
with results.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain seemed to have had the upper hand all along. Three
quarters of voters said he had the temperament to be an effective
president (though the one quarter who did not voted overwhelmingly
for Bush), and a majority of voters who made up their minds Tuesday
decided for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The senator has long tended assiduously to the retirement
community of Sun City, and he won overwhelmingly among voters who
said that world affairs, campaign finance reform or the combination
of Social Security and Medicare were the most important issues. He
also prevailed among those who cared most about moral values or
education, though by smaller margins. Bush easily won among those
who picked abortion or taxes as the most important issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Dee Hull, whose history with McCain includes hectoring
phone calls from him, bolted last year to Bush. When she went to
the polls Tuesday, she was joined by a brace of other Western
Republican governors, Marc Racicot of Montana and Ed Schafer of
North Dakota. Ms. Hull had said McCain needed a 30-point victory to
be seen as winning.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday evening, at what was billed as a ``primary night
celebration'' at a downtown hotel, she was philosophical about his
victories here and in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain's national exposure has been unbelievable, and I
think we all admit that it's been something you can't buy,'' Ms.
Hull said, adding that she thought Bush's overall national effort
would not be derailed. `I think Bush can appeal to Democrats'' in a
general election, she said. ``I'm not sure that appealing to
Democrats in a Republican primary is the place to be doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even McCain aides doubted that Hull's decision to back Bush
would have any political ramifications for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it'll matter one way or the other,'' said Wes
Gullett, a longtime McCain adviser who oversaw the campaign here.
</P>
<P>
   And no one seemed inclined to claim that the results portended
anything particular for this once-ironclad Republican state, which
in recent years has seen such an influx of younger, more liberal
residents that President Clinton carried it in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't say much,'' said Pat Murphy, a former editor and
publisher at The Arizona Republic who is often critical of McCain.
``Unless you look at it the other way, which is that he didn't get
30 (percent), which isn't great for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he explained the victory margin, despite the spending
imbalance, Gullett said: ``John said it best when he said, `We
haven't run one television ad in Arizona because people know me.'
People do know him, and they support him. Now, you know, you'd
always like to do better, but I think today looks like a good
victory. We accomplished our objective,'' which was to win the
state's 30 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last fall, polls showed Bush holding a slight edge
over McCain here, and the Texan devoted considerable resources to
an effort to embarrass McCain on his home turf. McCain aides
estimate that in the end, Bush outspent them about 10-to-1, with $2
million worth of television advertising and direct mail to $200,000
in radio ads for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a difference of a few zeroes,'' the Arizona Republican
Party chairman, Mike Minnaugh, said dryly Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
