<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-MCSORLEY-SUSPEND-     02-22 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MCSORLEY-SUSPEND-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McSORLEY, BANNED, FACES HEARING WEDNESDAY IN STICK ATTACK  
(lh) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two investigations began Tuesday following the stick
attack by Boston's Marty McSorley against Vancouver's Donald
Brashear.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley, suspended indefinitely for striking Brashear in the
head with 2.7 seconds remaining during Vancouver's 5-2 victory
Monday night, is scheduled to appear Wednesday morning at a
disciplinary hearing at National Hockey League headquarters in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Brashear was released from a Vancouver hospital Tuesday, a team
spokesman said, and is being treated for a Grade 3 concussion, the
most serious level. The recommended period of recuperation is 14 to
21 days, the Canucks said.
</P>
<P>
   Three detectives for the Vancouver police force were assigned to
the case. A police spokeswoman said they will view videotape and
conduct interviews before presenting their findings to a
prosecutor, who could charge McSorley with assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a standard, thorough investigation into an assault,''
said Constable Anne Drennan, speaking for the Vancouver police
department. ``We are in the evidence-gathering stages.''
</P>
<P>
   The longest suspension in league history for an on-ice incident
was 21 games, and that infraction did not involve the use of a
stick. The longest suspension for a stick-related foul was 15
games, given to three players in three different incidents.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley and Brashear, among the toughest and most penalized
players of this era, had fought early in the game with Brashear
winning the bout.
</P>
<P>
   Brashear declined McSorley's invitation for a second fracas,
even after McSorley was penalized for cross-checking and roughing
him. According to Pat Burns, the Boston coach, Brashear may have
angered some Bruins by flexing his muscles in front of the Boston
bench.
</P>
<P>
   With both players skating on the game's final shift, McSorley
swung his stick and connected with the right side of Brashear's
head, below the bottom of his helmet.
</P>
<P>
   As Brashear fell, his helmet came off and the back of his head
hit the ice. He lay unconscious, blood flowing from his nose, while
McSorley taunted him, briefly. As doctors rushed to Brashear's aid,
the Vancouver goalie Garth Snow attacked McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans fought in the stands and many spectators threw debris.
Brashear was carried from the ice on a stretcher, his neck in a
brace, and was revived in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the game, Boston goalie Byron Dafoe left on a
stretcher after Brashear fell into him, resulting in an
interference penalty to Brashear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in shock at what I did,'' McSorley said shortly
after the game. ``I have to come to terms with what I did. There's
no excuse. I got way too carried away. It was a real dumb play. I
apologize to Donald Brashear and all the fans who had to watch
that. I embarrassed my hockey team. I don't know what was going
through my mind at that time. It was a stupid mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   McSorley, 36, broke into the NHL in 1983-84 with Pittsburgh. He
has been suspended seven times in his career, five of them for
stick-related infractions, the longest of them six days. With 3,381
penalty minutes in regular-season play, McSorley is third in league
history behind Dave ``Tiger'' Williams, with 3,966, and Dale Hunter
with 3,565. Hunter, then with Washington, was suspended 21 games
for checking and injuring Pierre Turgeon of the New York Islanders
after Turgeon scored a goal in the 1993 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley's best-known involvement with a stick violation
involved the curve of his blade. During the 1993 Stanley Cup
finals, when McSorley was with Los Angeles, the Kings were leading
the Montreal Canadiens by one game in the four-of-seven-game series
and were ahead late in Game 2 in Montreal. But the Canadiens
requested a measurement of McSorley's stick, which was found to be
illegally curved. He was penalized, and the Canadiens scored on the
power play, sparking a game-winning comeback that led to a Montreal
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Brashear, 28, broke into the league with Montreal in 1993-94 and
has 1,278 penalty minutes in 386 regular-season games. Brashear is
one of 16 black players who have played in the NHL this season, the
most in league history. McSorley is white. There were no reports of
any racial undercurrent to the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to go with complete physical inactivity, not even
skating,'' said Rob Viccars of the Canucks media relations
department.
</P>
<P>
   Many players on both teams reacted with revulsion. Vancouver's
Mark Messier, a friend of McSorley's and a former teammate of his
in Edmonton and New York, said: ``We can't allow that to happen in
the league. It's really tough. Something like that takes the air
out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bourque, the veteran Boston defenseman, said: ``It was a
shocker. It just blew me away. It's not a good night to be a hockey
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin Campbell, the NHL's executive vice president and director
of hockey operations, will conduct Wednesday's meeting with
McSorley. Frank Brown, a league spokesman, said it is not certain
that a league ruling will be announced. Incidents resulting in
suspensions of four games or fewer are discussed only by telephone.
Players who appear in person are those suspended for longer
periods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
