<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Presses Defense As Trial Draws to a Close
</P>
<P>
   After 16 months of testimony and argument the antitrust suit
against Microsoft drew to a close. A verdict is expected in the
next few weeks, but even then the court is likely to hold separate
hearings on remedies if, as expected, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
rules that Microsoft violated antitrust laws. As Microsoft and the
government concluded the trial, their representatives were still
continuing to meet in Chicago in search of a settlement in
mediation talks.
</P>
<P>
   Sealing the Deal Over Raw Caribou
</P>
<P>
   He met his wife in the Sunday school class that his parents
taught, and he has never lost his deep faith. But God helps those
who help themselves, as Archie Dunham, Conoco's chief executive,
discovered on a business trip to the frozen wastes of northern
Russia. There, he was offered an unusual appetizer by the local
chieftain: raw caribou meat dipped in caribou blood. The morsel
held little appeal, but Dunham gulped it down and sealed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Chip Stocks Recover Slightly
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks finished higher as concern about the impact of
rising interest rates eased and the market got a lift from news of
stock buybacks by companies, including the drug producer Merck. The
Dow Jones industrial average finished up 85.32 points, or 0.83
percent, at 10,304.84. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose
slightly, closing up 6.08 points, to 1,352.17. The technology-laden
Nasdaq composite index finished down 29.62 points, or 0.67 percent,
at 4,382.12.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle to Pursue Wireless Internet
</P>
<P>
   Oracle's chief executive, Larry Ellison, announced the formation
and spin-off of a new business to capitalize on the industrywide
push to make the Internet accessible over wireless phones and other
portable devices.
</P>
<P>
   Finnish Paper Company in U.S. Deal
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish paper company Stora Enso said it would acquire
Consolidated Papers, based in Wisconsin Rapids, Wis., in a move
that marked the fourth major paper-industry merger or acquisition
in less than two weeks. The deal is valued at $3.9 billion, plus
the assumption of $900 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   SBC to Acquire Sterling Commerce
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications said it had agreed to acquire Sterling
Commerce for almost $3.9 billion in cash in the biggest move by a
major local phone company into the electronic commerce business.
Sterling's shareholders were pleased as the company's shares rose
$12, to $43.5625. But shareholders of SBC had doubts about the
deal, sending SBC shares down $2.25, to $36, despite the company's
assurances that the acquisition would not dilute SBC earnings.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P Is Concerned About Japan
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's, a leading credit-rating agency, delivered a
thinly veiled warning to the Japanese government that its economic
policies and rising levels of debt could threaten Japan's triple-A
credit rating. The admonishment from S&AMP;P was not as blunt as a
warning delivered less than a week ago by Moody's Investors
Service, S&AMP;P's chief rival in evaluating the creditworthiness of
countries and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Euro Rises and Jumps to a Dollar
</P>
<P>
   The euro climbed sharply, closing above the psychologically
important level of parity to the dollar for the first time in a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Climbs 38 Percent at Home Depot
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot, the chain of home-improvement stores, said its
fourth-quarter profit rose 38 percent as it sold more water
heaters, appliances and other big-ticket items. Sales increased 26
percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance Capital's Cautionary Ads
</P>
<P>
   Alliance Capital, which has $368 billion in assets under
management, is showing a series of commercials using dark humor to
depict investors who lose their life savings after playing the
market on their own. Their message is an old-fashioned one: Invest
for the future with a long-term strategy using a financial adviser.
</P>
</TEXT>
