<HEADER>
A5163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BUSINESS-RECRUIT-ART-     02-22 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-RECRUIT-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS AND CONSULTANT BRANCH OUT IN SEARCH OF TOP GRADS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Calif., Mass., Mo., Ind., Ga., Ill., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Two graphics
are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, America's big-name investment banks and consulting
firms considered it a waste of time to send recruiters to
second-tier business schools. Harvard, Stanford, the Wharton School
at Penn and a handful of others supplied the talent they needed.
</P>
<P>
   MBA candidates at large state schools or lesser-known private
schools could not expect to see many blue-chip recruiters on their
campuses. They had to send in their resumes and hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, that elitist approach is fading, another
consequence of the Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the long economic boom has increased demand at banks and
consulting firms for new hires, many of the brightest students at
the top business schools are joining Internet start-ups instead. As
a result, prestigious firms are descending on many schools that
make the Top 50 lists compiled by Business Week and U.S. News &AMP;
World Report but are nowhere near the top.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, students and administrators at the newly
initiated members of the club are ecstatic. ``The top firms are
coming up empty more often at the top schools,'' said Stuart I.
Greenbaum, dean of the Olin School at Washington University in St.
Louis. ``It's opened a whole new tier of opportunities for our
students.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last year alone, 17 companies, including CIBC
Oppenheimer, have started recruiting at the Kelley School of
Business at Indiana University, increasing the number of on-campus
recruiters there by about 15 percent. A.T. Kearney has gone to the
Cox School of Business at Southern Methodist University for the
first time. Chase Manhattan is recruiting at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers went to the University of Georgia. And
Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette made a visit to St. Louis to talk to
Greenbaum's students. Andersen Consulting, Goldman Sachs and Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter are also among the firms expanding their pools.
</P>
<P>
   And recruiters say they are having little trouble finding
qualified candidates, so long as they focus on the best students at
the second-tier schools. ``The notion that all the world's talent
comes out of three business schools I find hilarious,'' said Lenny
T. Mendonca, a director in the San Francisco office of McKinsey &AMP;
Co. Three years ago, McKinsey began using the Internet to reach
campuses where it does not send recruiters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shift could not have come at a more opportune time for
second-tier schools. At some of them, applications have leveled off
in the last year as the booming economy has kept in the work force
people who may otherwise have taken time off to give their careers
an MBA boost. Many deans also fret about the long-term threat of
the top schools' cutting into the second-tier schools' revenue by
offering programs over the Internet. Being added to the recruiting
lists, the deans said, will help their marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Life just got easier for the recruiters, too. Accustomed to
wooing freshly minted Harvard and Stanford MBAs caught up in dreams
of Internet riches, they are suddenly encountering students who are
generally thrilled to see them and eager to sign up at their firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tremendously excited,'' said Vivian Chen, 29, a
second-year student at Washington University, who recently accepted
a job at Salomon Smith Barney. When recruiters for the firm came to
her school for the first time this year, but did not interview for
the kind of job Chen wanted, she used connections through an
alumnus and her internship at another firm last summer to land an
interview at a Salomon office. ``It was a joint effort,'' Chen
said, a combination of ``a firm willing to expand its horizons''
and ``my tenacity.''
</P>
<P>
   When recruiters do find what they are looking for, a bonus often
comes attached: cheaper labor. Students at lower-ranked schools _
whose average starting pay packages are about $80,000, some $30,000
less than the typical student at the top schools would draw _ are
less likely to have lucrative competing offers that would force a
firm to bid up their salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The big uncertainty now is whether the trend will reverse when
the economy slows or Internet businesses go through a retrenchment.
Deans at the second-tier schools say that the students of today are
the recruiters of tomorrow and that the current wave of hiring will
allow the schools to establish a long-term presence at the firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I have my people on the inside,'' Greenbaum said, ``I
don't expect to get pushed out.'' If that is the case, middling
students at the top schools could eventually lose out to star
performers at lesser-ranked institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Others looking at the trend are not so sure, though. ``I'm
hoping they'll come back to us'' and try to hire as many graduates
in future years as they now are, said Roxanne Hori, the director of
career management at the Kellogg School of Management at
Northwestern, a top-ranked school. ``But I don't know. That's sort
of the million-dollar question.''
</P>
<P>
   The elite firms' deployment of recruiters to second-tier schools
began in earnest a couple of years ago to fill double-digit
increases in their staff openings. Bain &AMP; Co., for example, says it
will hire about 250 MBAs this year, up from 180 two years ago.
``The top seven or eight schools,'' said Stan Miranda, a director
in charge of the firm's recruiting, ``just cannot satisfy our
needs. We're growing very, very fast and cannot find enough people
to support the growth.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The supply squeeze has worsened in the last year, as dot-com
frenzy has gripped many business-school campuses. ``Historically,
when you got an offer from Morgan Stanley or J.P. Morgan, you just
took it. End of story,'' said Meyer Feldberg, dean of the Columbia
Business School, another traditional recruiting ground of the top
firms. But now, ``in some circles, there is a panic over not being
able to hire a sufficient number of talented people,'' Feldberg
added, as many of the most promising students rush to join Internet
start-ups or venture capital firms.
</P>
<P>
   As one stark example, the proportion of Stanford MBAs taking
jobs with either consulting firms or investment banks dropped to 33
percent last year from 43 percent in 1998. For the first time in
memory, people in business-school placement offices say, some firms
are having trouble filling out their on-campus interview schedules.
``People who typically had long waiting lists now have shorter
lists,'' Hori said. ``People who had full schedules now have
holes.''
</P>
<P>
   The response of Andersen Consulting, the world's biggest
consulting firm, illustrates the urgency recruiters feel. Andersen
has expanded the list of schools where its ``strategy group''
recruits to 15 from 12, said Bill Copacino, a managing partner. And
at the original 12, it is giving more presentations to students
this year, taking them out to more dinners and trying to make
stronger connections with student clubs. ``We had to work harder on
the campuses because there are more options'' for students,
Copacino said.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing a golden opportunity, second-tier schools and their
students are becoming more aggressive about selling themselves.
After attending a recruiting conference and hearing a manager from
Salomon Smith Barney describe the banking industry's hiring woes,
Kim Gattiker, the assistant director of the University of Georgia's
MBA career services office, organized a promotional campaign. She
and her colleagues pitched Georgia's students and the school's
highly regarded information systems to the big investment banks and
consulting firms, called Georgia alumni already working at some of
those companies and sought out recruiters at other conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Gattiker thought that adding just one or two corporate blue
bloods to the list of Atlanta companies like Delta Air Lines and
United Parcel Service that traditionally scour the University of
Georgia's graduating class would give her big marketing leverage.
Signing up just a few new firms allows her to mention their names
to other recruiters, who then will be more likely to come to
Georgia as well, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this year, for example, McKinsey invited
Georgia's MBAs to send in their resumes. ``McKinsey, up until this
year, had not had anything to do with us,'' Gattiker said. One
student received an invitation to travel to Florida for an
interview. She did not get the job, but when she told
Pricewaterhouse, which had not shown interest in her before, about
the interview, it also decided to talk to the student.
</P>
<P>
   To students and administrators at places like Georgia, the
new-found interest is overdue recognition for a level of excellence
that they believe is a near match for Columbia or Wharton. ``I have
these incredible students,'' said Jennifer Lawrence, an assistant
dean at Boston University, ``who have been severely undervalued by
the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters, however, are not so easy to convince. ``You can't go
any deeper'' than the very top students at second-tier schools,
said Miranda at Bain &AMP; Co. ``We're already pushing the boundaries
at those schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the boundaries or not, they still sometimes have to do
battle with the lure of technology. Students at Boston University,
for example, are delighted that Boston Consulting Group, Chase
Manhattan and McKinsey are all doing more to recruit them than they
did in the past. ``There's definitely a happiness about their
coming to campus,'' said Moshiko Levhar, a second-year student who
survived the interviews and got a job offer from McKinsey, which
is, he declares, ``as good as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Levhar says he may not accept the offer. After all, he
said, the telecommunications industry, where he worked before
entering graduate school, looks very exciting right now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
