<P>
   &UR; IRAN'S NEW DAWN MAY END U.S. INFLUENCE IN PERSIAN GULF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEHRAN _ The overwhelming victory of President Mohamed Khatami's
democratic ``reformists'' in the new Iranian parliament is already
being portrayed by Washington as a ``hopeful sign for the West.''
But the new Iran emerging from last week's poll is likely to
diminish rather than increase American influence in the region...
In Tehran, they are recalling once again the era of Mohamed
Mossadeq, freely elected but swiftly overthrown in 1953 by a coup
d'etat funded by the CIA and British intelligence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., Feb. 22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-KHATAMI-COUP-D'ETAT?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN IRAN, THEY'RE ALL REFORMERS NOW _ EVEN THE HANGMEN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEHRAN _ Last week's parliamentary election in Iran was like a
Persian tale of hope and love. It was also, like all Persian
stories, not as simple as it seems; a trifle opaque perhaps,
elliptical, full of heroes who might not all really be heroes after
all. And it may yet prove to have an unhappy, tragic ending.
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., Feb. 22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 300-word trim at 675; total uncut is 1,175) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-`NEW-IRAN'-ANALYSIS-675&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNDER HOUSE ARREST, KHOMEINI'S BETRAYED SUCCESSOR SPEAKS OF
IRAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EXCLUSIVE) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QOM, IRAN _ It was an eerie experience. To interview the man
whom Ayatollah Khomeini once anointed as his chosen successor is
one thing. To talk to him through a wall after he has spent more
than two years under house arrest in this gold-domed holy city of
Iran was positively surreal. ``Welcome to my home,'' the Ayatollah
growled at me in English. It was one of the few kind things he
said. Understandably, because the reasons for Montazeri's house
imprisonment _ and the contents of his extraordinary first
interview in captivity _ go to the very heart of the crisis behind
last week's parliamentary elections in Iran. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EXCLUSIVE Interview _ Attn: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., Feb. 22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 400 words; total uncut is 1,275) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as
BC-AYATOLLAH-TALKS-EXCLUSIVE-825&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IRANIAN REFORMIST SPELLS OUT LIBERALIZATION PLANS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEHRAN _ Reza Khatami _ booming voiced, grey-bearded, flabbier
in the face than his presidential brother, Mohamed _ Tuesday
sounded like the president himself when he insisted that at the top
of his party program lay human rights for Iranian citizens. But the
West _ which has been applauding the stunning victory of Khatami's
party and democratic ``reformists'' in last week's parliamentary
elections _ should perhaps study his last words before assuming
that Iran is about to become just another client nation in the
Middle East. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Fisk, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., Feb. 22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-BROTHER-KHATAMI-TALKS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOZAMBIQUE'S DREAM WASHED AWAY IN FLOODS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHIBUTO, MOZAMBIQUE _ Four days ago in Washington, U.S.
President Bill Clinton proclaimed Mozambique the world's
fastest-growing economy. At about the same time, Tiago Chauque, 35,
was up a tree, saving himself, but none of his hard-earned
belongings, from the country's worst floods in living memory. For
all of Clinton's fine words, an African economic dream _ which
enjoyed three successive years of GDP growth exceeding 10 percent
less than a decade after the end of a 16-year civil war _ has
tragically been swept away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Alex Duval Smith, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., Feb. 22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-MOZAMBIQUE-DROWNS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WEST WON THE WAR IN KOSOVO, BUT IT'S LOSING THE PEACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Editorial) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Eight months later, opponents of NATO's war in Kosovo
could not have imagined more bitter vindication of their dire
warnings than events in the city of Mitrovica, where Serbs and
Albanians confront each other, kept apart only by the Ibar River
and the increasingly desperate efforts of the overwhelmed NATO-led
peacekeeping force. There is plenty of fault to go around but at
the heart of the matter, Mitrovica reflects the ambiguities and
confusions that still dog the entire Kosovo enterprise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By The Editorial Board of The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., Feb. 22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
