<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI ACCUSES CLINTON OF PUSH-POLLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Officials with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's Senate
campaign on Tuesday accused Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign of
engaging in manipulative telephone calls to spread negative
impressions of the mayor. Clinton's campaign immediately responded
that the charges were untrue, and that the mayor was a hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Teitelbaum, Giuliani's campaign manager, made the
accusations of ``push-polling,'' a practice in which callers posing
as pollsters spread negative and often false information about
candidates, based on an article in this week's issue of New York
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The article reported that on Feb. 14, a Westchester County
resident received a call from a man identifying himself as an
employee of Global Strategy Group, a Democratic polling firm. The
magazine said the caller made such statements as, ``If elected,
Rudy Giuliani said he would vote for Supreme Court judges who are
against abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   The caller then asked the resident, according to the magazine,
if that changed how the resident felt about Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Giuliani said that he would not require a
``litmus test'' in voting on Supreme Court justices as a senator.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Teitelbaum described the call as ``the
latest outrage'' from the Clinton campaign, which he said was
``push-polling in the most negative and pejorative sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Clinton's press secretary, responded that ``the
Clinton campaign has never push-polled, and we never will.''
Wolfson also said that the Giuliani campaign had evidently not
ruled out its own push-polling. Teitelbaum was quoted in the
article, and then said again Tuesday, that ``we have no current
intentions to do push-polling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another example of their hypocrisy,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   Push-polling became an issue in the last few weeks of the South
Carolina Republican presidential primary as Sen. John McCain
complained bitterly that Gov. George W. Bush used the tactic
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, push-polling occurs in the closing days of a
campaign. The calls are usually made to thousands of voters and
last only a few minutes each.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said Tuesday that the call was in fact made by the
Global Strategy Group, a firm that has in the past worked for New
York's State Democratic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said similar calls were made to 800 voters, lasting 25
minutes each, and were for the purpose of what they described as
general research. Clinton's campaign said Tuesday that she was not
the client and had no connection to the polling group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
