<HEADER>
A5174 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-REAL-EVENTS-THEATER-$     02-22 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-EVENTS-THEATER-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRINGING THE HIGH DRAMA OF REAL LIFE TO THE STAGE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theater, a medium reliant on flights of imagination, is not
exactly a place where precise depictions of real events are common.
</P>
<P>
   But this season, a handful of plays on New York stages and
beyond are demonstrating a strong adherence to the facts, with
documentary-style texts that have been drawn verbatim from
interviews and transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most well-known proponent of this style is Anna
Deavere Smith, the author of the acclaimed plays ``Fires in the
Mirror'' and ``Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992,'' which, through the
words of individual citizens, examined racial unrest in Crown
Heights, Brooklyn, and in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Her latest work, ``House Arrest,'' an examination of the
American presidency, opens at the Joseph Papp Public Theater next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The monologues from the recent one-man show ``Another American:
Asking and Telling,'' by Marc Wolf, were taken from a series of
interviews the author held on the subject of gay members of the
military.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Laramie Project,'' directed by Moises Kaufman and now at
the Denver Center for the Performing Arts, is based on extensive
interviews with residents of Laramie, Wyo., where Matthew Shepard,
a gay college student, was murdered in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And ``The Vagina Monologues,'' Eve Ensler's current Off Broadway
hit, takes many of its stories and anecdotes from interviews
between the author and a wide variety of women.
</P>
<P>
   This form of you-are-there theater is also being used to
illustrate topics that would seem more suited to tabloid
television. ``Charlie Victor Romeo,'' with its re-creations of
airplane crashes and close calls using pilot voice-recorder
transcripts and realistic sound effects, has become a hit at the
tiny theater Collective Unconscious on the Lower East Side of
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Berger, one of the show's directors, contrasted true-life
television action shows like ``Cops'' with ``Charlie Victor
Romeo.'' ``When you see `Cops,' you're just seeing the spectacle of
the arrest,'' he said. ``But with our show you're watching how real
people dealt with the most intense experience of their lives.'' The
show, which opened just before the crash of EgyptAir 880 in
October, has been extended twice and is now running through April
1.
</P>
<P>
   While the subject matter of ``Charlie Victor Romeo'' might be
sensational, practitioners of this type of theater _ and their
audiences _ seem to find great appeal in the relative authenticity
of the material. Smith suspects this appetite derives from a
perception that coverage of events by the news media can be
unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we pursuing the authentic?'' Smith asked rhetorically
in a recent interview. ``I think it's because we are trying, and
not necessarily succeeding, to find truth and authenticity in a
time when masks have overwhelmed us.''
</P>
<P>
   While Smith believes the current interest in reality-based forms
of entertainment has been spurred by the 20th-century technology of
tape recorders and television, her own fascination has its roots in
an earlier source: the Russian director Konstantin Stanislavsky,
who championed a realistic style of acting.
</P>
<P>
   Stanislavsky, she said, was trying to elicit authentic behavior
from his actors, and her plays strive for the same thing. Where she
differs, Smith noted, is that she is ``interested in the other
rather than the self.''
</P>
<P>
   In performance, the characters she mimics have all their tics,
pauses and ``ums'' intact. There is a reason for this, Smith said:
today's audiences, surrounded by television and film, don't always
believe language written for the stage, which in many cases
consists of complete sentences and perfect grammar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody talks all the way across the page,'' she said,
``particularly if they are saying something good.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Martin, a professor of drama at New York University who is
writing a book about documentary theater, said that plays of this
type strike a nerve because, ``The performer is implicated in the
subject matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach also seems to offer a degree of objectivity for
politically charged issues, even if the author's underlying
position remains evident. Though, of course, the creator has the
power of omission and compression, which can risk compromising a
verbatim text's authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Another American,'' for example, Wolf recorded more than
400 hours of interviews, but the show's running time was less than
two hours. Opinions and characters, by dramatic necessity, had to
be cut.
</P>
<P>
   In Kaufman's 1997 Off Broadway hit, ``Gross Indecency: The Three
Trials of Oscar Wilde,'' actors cited the sources of the play's
historical accounts and transcript excerpts during the performance.
Kaufman is using a similar method for ``The Laramie Project.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the director said, his mission has had more to do with
finding strong theatrical moments than with chronicling facts.
``Our questions are somewhat different than just `documentary
theater,''' he said. ``We are interested in what is uniquely
theatrical.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, most of these plays seem to discard traditional
narrative structure for cinematic collage. ``I don't have to worry
about plot,'' Wolf said, ``and I don't think audiences worry about
plot. They can piece the story and the ideas together.''
</P>
<P>
   The logic is simple. ``These are good stories,'' Wolf said.
``Why make something up?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
