<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-DEBT-1STLD-WRIT     02-22 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-DEBT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S&AMP;P REAFFIRMS JAPAN'S TRIPLE-A RATING AFTER MOODY'S WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Tightens lead, clarifies Standard &AMP; Poor's position) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Standard &AMP; Poor's, a leading credit-rating agency,
delivered a thinly veiled warning to the Japanese government
Tuesday that its economic policies and rising levels of debt could
threaten Japan's triple-A credit rating.
</P>
<P>
   The admonishment from S&AMP;P was not as blunt as a warning
delivered less than a week ago by Moody's Investors Service, S&AMP;P's
chief rival in evaluating the creditworthiness of countries and
corporations. Indeed, S&AMP;P reaffirmed Japan's high rating and said
the country's outlook was stable.
</P>
<P>
   But in the financial markets, Standard &AMP; Poor's critical
assessment was viewed as another negative for Japan, which has been
languishing amid its worst economic performance since the end of
World War II. After a period of meager growth last year, evidence
has been accumulating that the country may have technically slipped
into another recession in the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P's evaluation carried an implicit criticism of the
government's economic policies, which have depended largely on
pork-barrel projects and other spending aimed at avoiding the
structural adjustments many economists advocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's failure to bolster economic prospects by
allowing the pace of structural reform to slip and by faltering in
its efforts to boost consumer confidence suggests that the economic
sluggishness could continue indefinitely, with the government debt
burden rising to levels inconsistent with a triple-A rating,'' S&AMP;P
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although a lowered credit rating would not necessarily cause
economic harm in Japan, it could help raise the cost of borrowing
and would be an enormous embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been troubled by the potential of an increased
discrepancy between Moody's and Standard &AMP; Poor's assessment of
Japan's ability to handle its mounting debt, which currently stands
at 100 percent of its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   ```Inconsistent with a triple-A rating,''' said Robert Alan
Feldman, chief economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in Tokyo,
quoting an S&AMP;P news release. ``That is a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   While the market has long been aware of Japan's debts, a recent,
subtle campaign by the Finance Ministry to increase awareness of
the problem with politicians and the public has raised anew
questions about whether Japan has a strategy for ending its
decade-long slump.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Moody's raised the possibility that it would
downgrade Japan's credit rating yet again, having lowered it in
November 1998 to Aa1, one level below its top rating. It cited
Japan's rising debt as a major reason for its review.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things Moody's was talking about was a lack of
gross philosophy, meaning how Japan intends to get its economy
moving and deal with the fiscal issues it faces,'' Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa has warned repeatedly in recent
weeks that Japan cannot continue to expect to borrow at the low
interest rates it currently gets. Japanese government bonds with a
duration of 10 years have for some time traded within an
interest-rate range of 1.6 percent to 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Ministry officials have also quietly and persistently
reminded journalists and others that tax revenue is falling
significantly as companies lay off workers in an effort to overhaul
their operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the ratings agencies would be too concerned if
Japan were spending money to bolster structural change and promote
long-term growth,'' said Ron Bevacqua, chief economist at Commerz
Securities. ``But Japan is spending money in a way that delays the
need for structural adjustment, and in that case, the money is
wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
