<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDEAVOUR CREW ENDS SUCCESSFUL MAP MISSION OF EARTH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The shuttle Endeavour and its crew of six astronauts
returned to Earth on Tuesday, ending a successful 11-day effort to
create the highest quality map of the planet ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's return ended a successful, $570 million mission in
which the Endeavour crew scanned the Earth with a massive radar
system, gradually fabricating a near global, three-dimensional map
of unprecedented detail and accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   The new topography will be used for a range of military and
civilian purposes, including missile guidance, flood control and
urban planning.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour touched down at 6:22 p.m. EST at NASA's Kennedy Space
Center in Florida, with commander Kevin Kregel and pilot Dominic
``Dom'' Gorie at the controls.
</P>
<P>
   High crosswinds in Florida forced the astronauts to wave off an
earlier landing opportunity at Kennedy. The space agency was
prepared to divert Endeavour to Edwards Air Force Base, Calif., if
conditions did not improve on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The space agencies of Germany and Italy joined with the
Department of Defense and NASA to produce the mapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin, congratulations to you and your crew for a highly
successful mission,'' Rick Sturckow, the shuttle crew's liaison in
mission control, said in greeting the astronauts as Endeavour
rolled to a stop on the long Kennedy runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really proud to be a part of this mission,'' said
Kregel. ``I think the radar images we brought back will help out
mankind from all countries for many years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Kregel, Gorie, flight engineer Janet Kavandi, payload commander
Janice Voss and astroauts Mamoru Mohri of Japan and Gerhard Thiele
of Germany were to undergo routine medical examinations and rest
overnight in Florida before returning to their Houston-area homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson Space Center in far south Houston planned a
welcoming ceremony for the six astronauts at 2:30 p.m. EST
Wednesday at Ellington Field.
</P>
<P>
   Kregel and his crew blasted off Feb. 11. The mission was delayed
by five months so ground technicians could inspect and repair
electrical wiring throughout Endeavour's fuselage and replace a
faulty computer component.
</P>
<P>
   The Endeavour crew successfully charted more than 99 percent of
the 47.6 million miles of mapping goal. Nearly 95 percent of the
territory was scanned twice, ensuring the accuracy that scientists
desired.e shuttle returned to Earth with 356 tape cassettes of
recorded radar data. The tapes will be duplicated and transported
to NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Using high speed computers, experts there will convert the
recorded data into a digital topographical map of the regions
scanned by the shuttle. The process will take one to two years.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's next shuttle flight is scheduled for lift off no earlier
than April 13.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis, with a seven-member crew, is slated to dock with the
unstaffed first components of the new international space station.
The Atlantis crew plans to repair electrical power storage
batteries and deliver supplies for the station's first resident
crews.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
