<SLUG> BC-U.N.-MONITOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP U.N. MONITOR NAMED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A management expert from Singapore has been
appointed the United Nations' second inspector general, a spokesman
for Secretary General Kofi Annan said Tuesday. The nominee, who
must be approved by the General Assembly, is Dileep Nair, a former
chief operating officer of Singapore's National Savings Bank.
</P>
<P>
   He will replace Karl Theodor Paschke, a German foreign service
officer and the organization's first inspector general, whose
nonrenewable five-year term ended last November.
</P>
<P>
   Annan spent months searching for a successor to Paschke,
rejecting several batches of nominees before settling on a
candidate from Singapore, a country with a reputation for clean
government and a virtually incorruptible civil service.
</P>
<P>
   A group of developing nations opposed the appointment of a
Westerner to the position, officially titled under secretary
general for internal oversight services. Paschke was chosen by
Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali when the job was created as
a reform measure in 1994 under pressure from the United States and
European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Paschke established rigorous auditing and inspection systems for
the organization, and published reports exposing illegal or
unethical practices. The United Nations began taking legal action
in cases of fraud and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Nair, born into Singapore's minority ethnic Indian community,
was educated at the Raffles Institution, Singapore's leading
secondary school, then studied engineering at McGill University.
Later he received a master's degree in public administration from
Harvard's Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MICHIGAN-NYT &LR;      02-22 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MICHIGAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MICHIGAN'S SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Feb. 23:
</P>
<P>
   Early returns and exit polls showing a victory for Sen. John
McCain in Michigan portend more blistering battles to come with
Gov. George W. Bush. Even before the votes were counted, Bush was
taking solace Tuesday night in his strong showing among
Republicans. The exit surveys do indeed suggest that McCain won
because of independents and Democrats, with the Texas governor the
undisputed choice of the GOP faithful. In future primaries, where
such crossover voting is barred, Bush may have an easier time. At
some point McCain will have to demonstrate that he can draw
majority support among members of his own party, as he did in his
home state of Arizona in its primary Tuesday. And Bush, sooner or
later, will have to show he can win decisively without being
propped up by local bosses.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the most striking aspect of the Republican
race is its increasingly nasty and personal nature. A new tone of
religious animosity has crept in, especially as several spokesmen
for the Christian conservative movement in the South have rallied
to the cause of the Texas governor. Supporters of McCain say that
Michigan has been swamped with recorded telephone messages from the
religious broadcaster Pat Robertson, singling out former Sen.
Warren Rudman of New Hampshire, who happens to be Jewish, as ``a
vicious bigot'' for criticizing the Christian Coalition. Bush
supporters, for their part, accused the McCain campaign of
condoning other calls suggesting that the Texas governor is
anti-Catholic because he launched his South Carolina campaign at
Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   All primary campaigns expose internal differences within
political parties that the eventual nominee must paper over before
the general election. But the warfare between Bush and McCain has
an especially rough edge, and it could open wounds that will not be
easily healed. An orgy of religious-based accusations in a
heartland state like Michigan harks back to a kind of bigotry that
most Americans have long ago rejected as an acceptable part of
presidential politics. At their best moments, both candidates have
appealed to the idealistic and, in Bush's term, compassionate side
of the American electorate. But Bush failed in South Carolina and
again in Michigan to criticize those who used the politics of
bigotry in his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan results once again demonstrate that Bush's strength
lies within the traditional conservative base of his party. The
governor may be able to get the GOP nomination by appealing to that
base, and it is too soon to say that he cannot parlay it into
national success. There were those nearly 20 years ago who assumed
that Ronald Reagan, who also came out of the party's conservative
base, could not reach beyond it to win in November. But Bush has
yet to prove he has a gift for base-broadening on a national scale.
Certainly, his showing in the open-primary states raises questions
about his overall appeal. He began by taking moderate positions on
some critical issues and has survived only by adopting a steadily
harder conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has once again shaken up the Republican contest, but he
also has much work to do. The next big mountain for both candidates
to climb _ and also for Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley _ will be the nationwide ``Super Tuesday'' primaries of
March 7, with special focus on California and New York. With his
Michigan upset, McCain has a shot at even more striking surprises
on that day. By the end of it, either Bush or McCain will begin to
look like their party's nominee, ready to take on the task of
overcoming both ideological and religious divisions brought out in
an unusually brutal contest. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-2NDTAKE-     02-22 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WASHINGTON: West said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the Gore camp has a strong sense that it should not let
Bradley control the conversation. That is one reason, say those
close to him, that Gore gave a surprisingly strong anti-Bradley
speech at the San Jose convention. Bradley had been attacking Gore
before the convention, but when he arrived, he had little to say
about the vice president; Gore then went on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley can't unilaterally dictate the rules,'' Shrum said,
explaining Gore's response. ``It's like assuming you could play
chess with no opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   The chess-playing image is intentional _ that of an academic or
``philosopher king'' who is too impractical to govern. In promoting
that image of Bradley, the Gore camp hopes to solidify Gore's image
as the opposite _ a realist, someone willing to roll up his sleeves
and ``fight for you!''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Gore tries every now and then to modulate this
image. After a commercial break in the debate at the Apollo
Theater, both Gore and Bradley toned down their attacks. And in an
interview on CNN after that, Gore softened even more. Instead of
his usual response of denying his past voting record _ in this case
against gun control _ he acknowledged that he had, in fact, changed
his position from when he represented a rural district in
Tennessee. He said he changed when he began ``seeing the problem
through the eyes of constituents'' in urban areas. ``All of us grow
and learn as we encounter people with experiences in life,'' he
said, notwithstanding his attack on Bradley for changing his view
of ethanol from when he represented New Jersey in the Senate to
when he began running for president in the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   But the raucous audience in Harlem almost demanded a sharper
approach. And Gore advisers said their man had little to lose by
going on the attack, particularly since the debate had limited
reach. The political world has been consumed by the Republican
contest. The debate started late, at 9 p.m., and was shown on cable
television.
</P>
<P>
   The forum gave Gore a chance to sharpen his claws for the fall
campaign. His advisers say he is always better when he can define
himself against someone else, and through scalding references to
Bush and McCain, Gore is already serving notice to Republicans that
Bradley is just a warm-up act. And with Republicans steeped in a
fight, Gore may not look so bad.
</P>
<P>
   Some Gore loyalists say that Gore's campaign moves are being
overanalyzed and that there is no grand strategy behind, say, his
aggressive performance in debates. He just wants to win, they say,
and he is moved by a competitive spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Gore would want to hammer Bradley even though Gore
seems so close to the nomination, one said simply, ``A corpse can't
take too many bullets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
