<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 11 YEARS, PETE ROSE IS STILL KNOCKING ON THE DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost 11 years to the day he was first summoned to appear
before the baseball commissioner about his alleged gambling, Pete
Rose Tuesday staged his latest public effort to sway the thinking
of the current commissioner. By the close of business at Bud
Selig's office in Milwaukee, Rose had still not succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything compelling about an 11th anniversary,
but it is instructive about Rose's credibility to recall his
reaction to the meeting that marked the beginning of the end of his
baseball life.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was summoned to New York to meet with Peter Ueberroth, then
the commissioner, and A. Bartlett Giamatti, the commissioner-elect,
on Feb. 20, 1989. Rose, the Cincinnati Reds' manager, returned to
the team's spring training camp in Plant City, Fla., the next day,
preceded by word that the topic of the meeting had been Rose's
alleged gambling. Rose, however, denied that gambling had been
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the reason,'' he said that day in Plant City. What
was? ``He asked me to come there,'' Rose said, referring to
Ueberroth. ``He and Giamatti were both there. They wanted my input
and advice on a couple things. I gave it to them; it took an hour.
I left, and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. According to Fay Vincent, who participated in the
meeting as Giamatti's deputy commissioner-to-be, Rose's gambling
was very much the subject, the only subject. Recalling the meeting
Tuesday, Vincent said he asked Rose if he had ever bet on baseball
and elicited this reply: ``No, I'm not that stupid. I've bet on
everything else but not on baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   An admission that he bet on baseball would have earned Rose an
instant one-year suspension; if he had acknowledged wagers on the
Reds, he would have incurred a lifetime ban. Though he continued to
deny having made such wagers, he wound up agreeing to a lifetime
sentence six months later. Nevertheless, he has stuck to his story
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Selig, among others, doesn't believe him. That's why he has not
altered Rose's agreement with Giamatti.
</P>
<P>
   On a telephone conference call Tuesday, Rose said he continues
to have hope that someday he will gain reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a society that is known for giving people a second
chance,'' Rose said. ``From everyone I talked to, George
Steinbrenner on down, they relate to me that Bud Selig is a very
fair man. I have total confidence that someday he'll give me a
second chance. I don't say it will be this week, this month, but
stranger things have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose's lawyers met last month with baseball's chief lawyer and
presented him with what they say is evidence that counters the
evidence baseball amassed in 1989. This was the private part of
Rose's comeback strategy. The conference call was the latest step
in the public part.
</P>
<P>
   A new Internet sports Web site hired Rose to promote the launch
of the site, sportcut.com, last Nov. 30. Rose apparently served the
intended purpose because the site experienced a record number of
hits for the launch of a sports Web site. In return, the site
served Rose's purpose because it posed a question and invited
visitors to answer it: do you think Pete Rose should be in the Hall
of Fame?
</P>
<P>
   The question, of course, was a simplistic one. It didn't begin
to get into the reality of Rose's plight. If Presidential
candidates were chosen on a similar basis, George W. Bush would
have been nominated as the Republican candidate months ago without
a challenge from John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-two percent of the 230,906 who clicked on an answer to
the question over a two-and-a-half-month period said yes, Rose
should be in the Hall of Fame. Rose took the results as a positive
development. He wasn't asked for and he didn't offer an opinion of
the nearly 500,000 more visitors to the site who didn't vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we decided to do this launch with sportcut we were as
interested as everyone else to find out what the reaction of people
would be,'' Rose said. ``You don't know what to expect from fans,
although in my travels I get a lot of feedback that is positive.
It's exciting to see the results of the poll. I don't know where
the results will lead but I'm very happy the results were favorable
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But were they? Two-thirds of the site's visitors during the
voting period apparently didn't care enough to cast a vote. Rose
may want to reflect on that massive slight.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he will continue to wage his public campaign
and his lawyers will submit additional ``evidence'' to baseball's
lawyers. Neither the voice of the people nor the belated efforts of
his lawyers will sway the only person whose vote counts. All the
king's horses and all the king's men will not put Humpty together
again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
