<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RETAINING-WORKERS-NYT     02-22 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAINING-WORKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TOOLS FOR EMPLOYEE MAINTENANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOANNA L. KROTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wage inflation may have all but disappeared from the economic
map, but for companies looking to grow, there is' another side to
that good news. Just about any worker with a marketable skill has
by now caught on to corporate America's worst-kept secret: managers
are desperate to attract talent and even more desperate to hold
onto it.
</P>
<P>
   Mambo.com, a start-up events-planning Web service in Menlo Park,
Calif., for example, hired a longtime Internet recruiter last
spring before it even thought about hiring a vice president for
business development, according to Madeline Schroeder, Mambo's
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   And when the computer networking company Cisco Systems moves
into a market and needs staff, it often hires trucks to be driven
around town with billboards that flash the company's Web site and
plead: ``Talk to us at Cisco.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We like people to know we're there,'' said Randall Birkwood,
Cisco's senior employment manager.
</P>
<P>
   The latest innovation to persuade midlevel and senior managers
to turn down rival offers is one borrowed from addiction treatment:
an intervention by those in the workplace who are nearest and
dearest. James Boone, president for operations in the Americas at
the recruiter Korn/Ferry International, said that besides ``hard
offers of compensation, position and title immediately, you have to
hit at the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as a manager announces he's leaving,'' Boone added,
``you get his team in a room to say things like, `We need you to
succeed' or `What can we do make you stay?' People don't usually
leave just for money. It can be just as effective to tug at the
emotions to get them to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of pleading puts employees in a strong position.
Colleen McGrath, 26, had been at Monster.com, an Internet career
and recruitment site, for almost four years last September. Though
she had worked her way up to the position of project manager, she
said, ``I felt stale; the job wasn't much of a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath went job hunting, and soon got an offer from another
Internet company with comparable benefits and a $5,000 raise. She
accepted and gave notice.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Jeff Taylor, Monster.com's founder and chief
executive, asked why she was leaving. Then he made a counteroffer:
he would promote her to manager of special projects and give her an
immediate $4,000 raise, with the likelihood of more to come.
</P>
<P>
   She accepted because she was shedding the old routine job and
preferred Monster.com to the new company, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't leaving because I hated the job so much,'' McGrath
said, ``but because the company had turned formal and corporate in
the past three years _ titles and what size cube you have. So I
wanted more money. Jeff got me to stay by making me feel like a
change agent again.'' Two months later, she snared an additional
$2,000 raise.
</P>
<P>
   For Taylor, grabbing people on their way out the door has become
a way of life. Monster.com began with a staff of 70 in 1997, grew
to 500 by the end of 1998 and doubled again last year. Competition
for skilled workers from other dot.com start-ups is fierce, so he
pays close attention to his employees' needs and makes sure the
workplace reflects Net speed and culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``My employees get shot at regularly by recruiters,'' Taylor
said. ``And money rocks people's worlds, so almost always, I'll
make a counteroffer. They wouldn't be here if they weren't great at
their job. But I like to counter opportunity, not offers.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies are becoming increasingly inventive when it comes to
incentives, either by dangling special premiums over compensation
or by bumping up the role and autonomy of the job. Counteroffers
now often include letting managers exercise stock options at
earlier dates or at lower prices than the contracts call for and
guaranteeing juicy bonuses for employees who stay a specified
number of years, even if their performance fizzles along the way.
Recruiters and human resources professionals have even coined a
term for these gun-to-the-head elevations: battlefield promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Managers are also more willing than ever to cut special deals.
Daphne Matalene, 26, an advertising account manager at a travel
magazine in New York, turned down an unexciting offer from a rival
company last June. But when she mentioned it to her boss, he
immediately withdrew an earlier suggestion that he might have to
reduce her commission from 10 percent of sales to a rate more in
line with the industry average of about 2 percent. Then, a few
months later, an attractive job offer came her way from a
prestigious business publication, and she was leaning toward
accepting it.
</P>
<P>
   But when she informed her boss, he countered by raising her base
salary by $17,000, a 75 percent increase. To do that, he said, he
would have to lower her commission rate, but he awarded her some
plummy extra accounts and some added responsibilities to compensate
for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to stick around,'' Matalene said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey by Development Dimensions
International, a consulting firm, most companies will be enhancing
stock options, benefits packages and salaries this year to attract
qualified applicants.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to the survey, workers want more than just money.
Organizations with the most effective recruiting strategies,
according to the survey, were more likely to offer potential for
advancement, a solid reputation, learning opportunities and a
positive corporate culture as well as stock options and competitive
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   That means employees across the board can expect more and better
job offers and increased leverage with their current employers,
said Jeffrey Christian of Christian &AMP; Timbers, an executive search
firm. ``Today, the best talent wins,'' Christian said. ``So if you
haven't had a counteroffer, you're probably not working.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
