<SLUG> BC-DUNHAM-CONOCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH AND LOYALTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla.)  (Archie Dunham is the chief executive of Conoco, a Houston-based
oil company. This article was written with David Leonhardt.)  
(lh) 
 By ARCHIE DUNHAM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I grew up in Ada, a community of about 17,000 people in the
southern part of Oklahoma. We spent weekends walking up and down
the creek looking for rocks, fossils and Indian artifacts. So,
growing up, I had a great interest in archaeology, paleontology and
geology.
</P>
<P>
   No one in my family had ever attended college, but I always knew
I would go to college and major in one of those three fields. Later
in high school, I realized that engineering would be a better
career.
</P>
<P>
   I met my wife, Linda, in church. I was 15, and she was 13. She
was actually in the Bible class my mom and dad taught in church. I
guess you could say they picked her out for me. When we started
dating, we had to walk to the movies because we were too young to
drive. It was a wonderful time to be growing up in small-town
America in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   After four years in the Marine Corps and business school, I
interviewed with 17 companies and was fortunate to receive 16 job
offers. I'm not going to tell you who didn't offer me a job. It was
1966, and I had decided to accept a job with IBM. But one of my
professors had told a young vice president from Conoco about me,
and the VP called and asked if I would have dinner with him while
he was on campus. I was a graduate student with a working wife and
two children. We were on a near-starvation diet, and the idea of a
free steak dinner sounded pretty good. He convinced me that Conoco
had the best management-training program, and I've been here ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   I almost never became the chief executive of Conoco. In the fall
of 1995, I was an executive vice president, and a search firm
wanted me to become the chief executive. of another Fortune 100
company. Since childhood, a Christian faith has been an important
part of my life, so I spent time praying about whether I should
accept this opportunity and leave Conoco. I try to spend time in
prayer and Bible study every day. Finally, I told God I was going
to accept the position unless he stopped me.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later the phone rang. It was the head of the search
firm asking me to put my decision on hold because the board was
talking to someone else. That was a clear signal for me to remain
at Conoco. A few weeks later, I was awakened by a phone call
telling me I was going to be elected chief executive. I really
don't believe it was a coincidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
