<SLUG> BC-HELLMAN-HELLMAN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Financier Hellman Buys Stake in Formula One Racing Events  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
San Francisco buyout firm Hellman &AMP; Friedman LLC has paid $712.5
million for a 37.5 percent stake in Formula One Holdings, which
puts on the world's most watched annual sporting events.
<P>
   ``I want to move in faster company,'' joked Warren Hellman,
chairman of the firm which recently raised $2 billion of private
capital and already has invested about half of it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its investment in Bernie Ecclestone's
London-based Formula One grand prix auto-racing events, which draw
more than 300 million viewers worldwide for each event, Hellman &AMP;
Friedman announced yesterday that it has bought Mitchell
International for an undisclosed price. The San Diego company is a
leading software information services provider to the insurance and
automobile collision repair industries.
</P>
<P>
   Both investments deal with cars but that is not what makes them
attractive to Hellman and his investors, who include the California
Public Employees Retirement System, city of San Francisco,
government of Singapore and Stanford and Dartmouth endowment funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investments fit a template,'' said Hellman. ``We like
businesses with a major franchise. We like businesses with
substantial cash flow and we don't like to invest in firms with a
lot of fixed assets like factories or forests.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellman declined to discuss what sort of cash flow is generated
by grand prix events featuring the best drivers and racing cars in
the world. Formula One Holdings does not pay the cost of sponsoring
the racing teams and high-priced drivers. That is paid by Ferrari,
McClaren and other manufacturers and their sponsors. Hellman &AMP;
Friedman is banking on lucrative revenue from TV broadcast,
promotional rights and CD-Rom games.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1984, the firm has invested more than $4.8 billion in 39
companies, with generally impressive results. Hellman &AMP; Friedman
invested $223 million for close to 40 percent of Young &AMP; Rubicam
and cashed out of the advertising firm late last year for a total
gain of more than $800 million. It enjoyed a similar gain on its
$125 million investment in the predecessor of Western Wireless and
Voice Stream.
</P>
<P>
   But not all investments have won a checkered flag. The firm lost
$130 million on its investment in Mobile Media, another
communications company.
</P>
<P>
   And not all of Hellman &AMP; Friedman's money is on the fast track,
either. The company has a minority stake in Power Bar, the Berkeley
company started by University of California at Berkeley track coach
Brian Maxwell. The maker of all-natural nutrition bars is expected
to announce its sale today to a large food products company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GAS-GAS_SFCHRON &LR;      02-22 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-GAS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Legislation Tackles Inflated Gas Prices  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
With gas prices at record high levels, several bills are being
introduced in the state Legislature to increase stability in the
California gasoline market.
<P>
   San Francisco Assemblywoman Carole Migden introduced a bill
yesterday that would promote construction of a pipeline from the
Gulf Coast to boost California's gas supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a crisis in California,'' Migden told The Chronicle.
``We've all been frustrated, especially in the Bay Area, with
fluctuating gas prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the works are a bill from San Francisco Assemblyman
Kevin Shelley to establish a strategic gasoline reserve in the
state, and a separate bill from Hillsborough Sen. Jackie Speier to
limit the ability of oil companies to own and operate retail
service stations.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for submission of the new  &LR; proposals to the
Legislature is Friday.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Bill Lockyer said the bills being
introduced will be studied by his office as part of a continuing
investigation into California's sky-high gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer has blamed the state's soaring prices on a lack of
competition among leading oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   The California State Automobile Association reported last week
that Bay Area gas prices had reached their highest level for any
February, with the average cost of a gallon of unleaded regular gas
standing at $1.50 _ up 4 cents from January and 32 cents, or 27
percent, from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Migden said her bill would authorize a study on the feasibility
of a pipeline from Texas to California. In the event of a fuel
shortage, she said, additional supplies of gas could be quickly
piped to the West Coast in a matter of days, as opposed to shipping
them in by tanker truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would provide a greater source of gas and it would get
here faster,'' she said. ``Therefore, prices would probably go
down.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Chevron Corp. declined to comment on the
pending legislation.
</P>
<P>
   However, Severin Borenstein, director of the University of
California Energy Institute in Berkeley, questioned whether
sufficient supplies of the cleaner-burning gas required by
California authorities would be available in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear whether such a pipeline would get much use,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other bills coming before the Legislature,
legislature,  &LR; Borenstein said that while a reserve supply of
gasoline would help to prevent price swings, the idea could prove
impractical in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gasoline, unlike oil, doesn't store very well,'' he said.
``You have to make it and then use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein also had doubts about the idea of limiting oil
companies' ownership of service stations _ ``divorcement,'' in
industry parlance. ``There is no evidence that divorcement actually
lowers prices for consumers,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Borenstein said, is that oil prices are now
going through the roof. Until oil prices come down, he observed,
California drivers should not expect gas prices to return to earth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
