<SLUG> BC-TAXES-TAXES </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Court Rejects Out-of-State Income Tax  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The U.S. Supreme Court yesterday unanimously struck down a disputed
portion of the California tax law, ruling that the Franchise Tax
Board unconstitutionally taxed income earned by corporations
outside the state.
<P>
   Franchise Tax Board spokesman Jim Shepherd said the ruling will
force the state to refund up to $95 million in taxes it collected
from approximately 800 corporations during the past four years. The
four-year period represents the statute of limitations on disputed
tax claims.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, future corporate tax collections will be
reduced by an estimated $13 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt-Wesson, now a subsidiary of Nebraska's -based  &LR; ConAgra
Inc., a food processor, brought the case against the FTB during the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Moll, a partner with the Morrison &AMP; Foerster law firm in
San Francisco, which represented Hunt-Wesson, said his client will
collect about $3 million in back taxes and interest as a result of
yesterday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   California is entitled to collect taxes from out-of-state
corporations that do business in the state. Under the unitary tax
system, the state has a well-established right to tax these
corporations on their California income.
</P>
<P>
   But the case decided yesterday centered on a 1937 statute that
appeared to extend the state's taxing powers to out-of-state
income.
</P>
<P>
   The statute limited the amount of interest payments that
out-of-state corporations can claim as deductions on their
California tax forms.
</P>
<P>
   The statute compelled the corporations to reduce the deductions
from their California income by the amount of dividends and
interest they received from sources outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   In yesterday's ruling, Justice Stephen Breyer wrote that the
statute thus, in effect, allowed California to tax out-of-state
income earned by out-of-state corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Previous cases settled before the Supreme Court have established
that this is an ``impermissible'' tax that violates the U.S.
Constitution, Breyer said.
</P>
<P>
   California argued that the rule was designed to prevent '`tax
arbitrage,'` in which companies cheat the taxman by borrowing money
for business operations outside the state, then deduct the interest
from their California income.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Miller, the FTB's counsel for multistate tax affairs,
said yesterday that it is difficult to pinpoint which interest
expenses are properly deductible in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to physically locate interest expenses for
corporations,'' Miller said. ``They occur wherever the corporation
is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
