<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RIPKIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFRESHED RIPKIN SET FOR QUEST FOR 3,000 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ The inner peace that Cal Ripken
experienced during a particularly emotionally tugging 1999 season
is still there, the Baltimore Orioles' third baseman says. So bring
on the scrutiny and glare that will accompany his April pursuit of
3,000 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel any pressure right now,'' he said Tuesday at the
Orioles' spring training base. ``I thought I would, but I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken is 9 hits short of becoming the 24th player in major
league history to reach 3,000. He'd like to do it at friendly
Camden Yards, where the Orioles play their first six games.
``Nothing like putting pressure on yourself to start the season,''
he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Ripken will be glad to take the achievement when it
comes, in deference to baseball decorum. No sitting out to wait for
another home stand. He'd just like the suspense to end early, ``so
you can get back to some routine and normalcy.''
</P>
<P>
   At 39, he says he is enjoying baseball these days for the simple
pleasure of playing it. It's a carry-over from last year. He lost
his father, Cal Sr., to cancer in March. Then he went on the
disabled list for the first time in his 18-year career _ and twice,
for periods of 22 and 28 games.
</P>
<P>
   Just when a growing number of people were wondering if his
career might be over, Ripken did some of his best career hitting
between layoffs. In 86 games, he had career highs for batting
average (.340) and slugging percentage (.584).
</P>
<P>
   Of his rejuvenated hitting, he said, ``I started waiting on the
ball to come to me and started hitting the ball in the gaps. Even
after I came back from the disabled list, somehow the magic was
still the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more important than adjustments in the batter's box, Ripken
was able to play with a focus and calm that he had not often
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``A certain peace and a joy came over me last year that I don't
know where it came from,'' he said. ``I was at a position where I
just enjoyed myself and played the game. I didn't feel any added
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, Ripken had to make a difficult decision: try to
persevere with nerve root irritation in his back or have surgery.
On Sept. I just enjoyed myself and played the game. I didn't feel
any added pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, Ripken had to make a difficult decision: try to
persevere with nerve root irritation in his back or have surgery.
On Sept. 23, he underwent surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrifying alternative,'' he said. ``But it was a
risk I was willing to take to play a full season. And now I've
weathered all the uncertainties, all the doubts. I'm meeting it
head on. Let's find out what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, just for fun, Ripken participated in several drills
at first base. Several media types saw him and began speculating
that he might play some first base this season, to save his aging
body. Never mind that he participated in the drills wearing a third
baseman's glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, I'm penciled in as a third baseman until I
guess I prove I can't do it,'' he said. ``I'm not afraid of coming
in and laying it on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Retirement is not presently a consideration for the man who
holds the major league record for endurance by playing in 2,632
straight games. He laughed when he heard that pitcher Mike Messina
predicted he might play until he is 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing for sure: I can't come in here and say I'm
going to retire. I can't say this is my last year. I have to go out
there and find out.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that while the window of opportunity to play in the
majors is small for anyone compared to his life span, ``I plan to
max that window as much as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At this level you have to prove yourself day in and day out in
front of everyone,'' Ripken said. ``So there are no secrets. You
can't hide from it. You have to lay it on the line and find out
what you can do. That's what I'm going to do as long as I can.
Retirement will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Orioles, Ripken, gray at the temples, can be like
having another coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably the most intelligent player in the game today,''
shortstop Mike Bordick said. ``If you just listen to him, you're
going to learn. He knows players' tendencies and that's a big part
of the major league game _ knowing everybody's tendencies and
getting yourself in the right position.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaching is fine, but one thing is clear from Ripken's demeanor:
he's not ready to be a coach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
