<SLUG> BC-SEAGATE-SEAGATE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Seagate's New Cheetah Outruns the Rest  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Upping the ante in the high-end hard drive market, Seagate
Technology today announced the first drive ever that spins at
15,000 rpm _ 50 percent faster than most previous high-end drives,
and almost three times faster than the typical PC drive.
<P>
   Called the Cheetah X15, the new 18-gigabyte drive is designed
primarily for servers that have to respond to very frequent
requests for data, such as commercial databases and e-commerce
sites. It won't ship in volume until this summer, according to the
company. Final pricing hasn't been set, but Seagate said it's
expected to be just under $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most PC drives today spin at 5,400 rpm, while high-performance
desktop systems increasingly come with 7,200-rpm drives. The
fastest drives made by most manufacturers, designed for servers and
workstations, spin at 10,000 rpm, although Hitachi offers a
12,000-rpm drive for its servers.
</P>
<P>
   Extra spindle speed helps reduce average access time _ how long
it takes to reach desired data on the drive _ and increases the
sustained transfer rate _ the speed with which the drive can
deliver large blocks of data.
</P>
<P>
   The new drive can read, on average, 42.5 megabytes of data per
second. According to Seagate, that's equivalent to a person reading
the entire works of Shakespeare in less than a quarter of a second.
It's also about 25 percent faster than Seagate's current
10,000-rpm, 18-gigabyte drive, the Cheetah 18XL.
</P>
<P>
   Seagate, based in Scotts Valley, shares leadership in the
high-performance drive market with IBM, with Quantum and Fujitsu
not far behind, according to Jim Porter, president of Disk/Trend, a
Mountain View market research company that specializes in storage
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Seagate's announcement puts it ``at least one, and maybe two
quarters ahead'' of its rivals in reaching the 15,000-rpm plateau,
said Shaun Hook, product manager for the Cheetah X15.
</P>
<P>
   But Disk/Trend's Porter wasn't so sure: ``They're all working on
such drives,'' he said. ``Who's first depends on when they actually
ship, not on when they put out the press release.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, drives with higher spindle speeds have usually
required more power, genmore heat and made more noise than
otherwise comparable drives at a lower rpm. But in those respects,
Seagate said, the Cheetah X15 is no worse than its 10,000-rpm
cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Seagate shares yesterday fell 69 cents to $44.31. After trading
between $25 and $35 for most of 1999, it rose sharply beginning in
November.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
