<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-ORACLE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Oracle Dials Up Internet  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
In its highest-profile foray into the consumer market, Redwood
City's Oracle Corp. yesterday spun out OracleMobile, a independent
company aimed at turning cell phones into Internet-cruising
devices.
<P>
   Oracle, the No.1 maker of database management software, said
OracleMobile will tackle both the consumer and corporate markets.
</P>
<P>
   Using Web-enabled phones (or those capable of receiving pages),
consumers can dial into the OracleMobile portal and browse the
scaled-down Web sites of about 12 companies, including eBay, Zagat
and MapQuest. The results of a search for, say, directions to a
restaurant, are displayed onscreen. If the phone is fitted with
voice recognition technology from Motorola _ a partner in the
venture _ users can orally request information, minimizing the need
to type on the phone keypad. Information from the Web sites can
then be read back to phone users.
</P>
<P>
   On the corporate side, Oracle offers two options to potential
customers like Amazon and Etrade.  &LR; E-Trade. They can buy Oracle's
portal software, which lets them boil down their regular sites to
phone-friendly tidbits. Or, as Oracle hopes, it can both supply the
technology and host the site on its servers.
</P>
<P>
   In making the announcement yesterday in New York, Oracle chief
executive Larry Ellison said the venture is aimed at the exploding
Internet appliance market, which is expected to balloon to $13.2
billion a year by 2003, according to Boston research firm Yankee
Group, as consumers turn away from personal computers and toward
cell phones and other Internet-enabled devices for access to
e-mail, driving instructions and airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PC is going to be overwhelmed by Internet appliances, Web
phones, whatever you want to call them _ simple devices with access
to the Internet,'' Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer portal also represents a shift of sorts for Oracle
_ which primarily supplies complex database software to large
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect them to get into'' a consumer-oriented
business, said Bruce Raabe, chief investment officer for Collins &AMP;
Co., which rates the stock a hold. ``But you have a lot of
business-to-business companies trying to take advantage of consumer
spending. Like a lot of other companies, (Oracle is) seeing growth
in their traditional business slowing down and they have to branch
outward.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, OracleMobile.com, which will be the portal through
which consumers will access the Web, has been registered by another
organization, forcing Oracle to use OraMobile.com, Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
   But Oracle's lawyers ``are chatting with them right now. We'll
have both URLs shortly,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison named Denise Lahey, a software engineer and head of
Oracle's mobile products division, chief executive of OracleMobile.
</P>
<P>
   Lahey said OracleMobile will make money in several ways:
advertising, hosting fees, subscription fees for some premium
services and by taking a piece of e-commerce transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's premiere dovetails with a similar venture Oracle
launched Friday with Swedish telecommunications company Telia AB.
That company will develop and market wireless Internet products
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In both markets, Raabe said Oracle will face stiff competition
as more and more companies announce initiatives to Webify handheld
gizmos.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Corp. is already using technology developed by Redwood
City's Phone.com to allow consumers to surf the Web using cell
phones; and Bell Atlantic Corp. announced a similar initiative in
November.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Microsoft Corp. recently invested about $600
million in Nextel Communications to develop online services for
wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   All of these companies may face some acceptance problems from
consumers who balk at many devices' tiny screens and even tinier
keypads.
</P>
<P>
   In yesterday's conference, Ellison conceded ``Yes, (cell phones)
do have smaller screens, but your PC can't call you up and tell you
something important just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Lahey said the 25-employee company, located on Oracle's
sprawling campus in Redwood City, is `'in negotiations'' with
potential investors and expects to offer its shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take the company public as soon as possible,''
Ellison said.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle shares, which have tripled since September, edged
slightly higher yesterday, closing up 75 cents at $59.31.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
