<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHOME-ATHOME </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Small Business Web Sites to Join  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
ExciteAtHome and Dow Jones, publisher of the Wall Street Journal,
unveiled plans yesterday to combine their fledgling
small-business-oriented Web sites and sell stock in the joint
venture later this year.
<P>
   The spin-off company, called Work.com, will be based in Redwood
City, where ExciteAtHome has its headquarters, and begin life with
16 workers (eight from each firm) and $20 million to - &LR; $25 million
in annual sales, mostly from online ads.
</P>
<P>
   Excite, which runs Excite.com and other popular consumer Web
sites, started Work.com last September to crack the small-business
market; it offers news and a directory of Web sites for more than
two dozen industries, ranging from accounting to utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones, meanwhile, started dowjones.com, a similar
small-business portal, in June. It features selected headlines and
articles from both the Wall Street Journal and its wire service,
where reporters electronically file quick dispatches to alert
investors and newspapers within minutes and hours of an event,
instead of waiting for the Journal to arrive the next day. Work.com
will now be able to offer some of that news.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome chief executive George Bell said the deal makes
sense for both firms. Excite couldn't reproduce the Wall Street
Journal's articles on its own, and Dow Jones didn't have Excite's
experience fighting with other portals for Net users. ``Each
company is getting something,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also comes at a time when interest in
small-business portals is heating up. NBCi bought San Francisco's
-based  &LR; Allbusiness.com, a news site for small businesses, this
month for about $225 million in stock. Onvia.com, an online
marketplace for smaller firms, plans to sell stock to the public
for the first time as early as this week. And Inc. magazine has won
fans by stocking its Web site with advice on starting and running a
business.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Excite and Dow Jones face stiff challenges. Neither
Work.com nor DowJones.com has attracted much interest or enough
users to crack Media Metrix's monthly list of the top 500 Web
sites, noted Jim Nail, an analyst from Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass. ``Excite doesn't seem to have much traction, and
Dow Jones definitely doesn't have any traction,'' Nail said. ``Does
taking two sites that don't have any traction give you one that
does?''
</P>
<P>
   And there are other factors. Dow Jones only plans to make
headlines and a handful of stories available on the free Web site,
because it charges subscribers to access the full Wall Street
Journal newspaper and archives on www.wsj.com. Meanwhile,
ExciteAtHome said it could potentially refer 5 million users to
Work.com from its other Web sites, but will charge Work.com for its
marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ExciteAtHome sees potential. Citing Nail's research firm,
Forrester, it noted that business information could become an $11
billion market worldwide in four years. And while Work.com garners
sales today from advertising, Bell believes the future is
e-commerce _ selling software and other products through the Web
site. Work.com also plans to create additional co-branded Web sites
with additional partners.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome shares edged up 13 cents, to $34.19. DowJones
closed at $62.56, up 63 cents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
