<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON  &HT;     Finding Reality Checks for That Fantastic Idea 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I feel that I have a blockbuster concept for an Internet
business and have a business license and two registered domain
names. But how do I find out if it will fly? There must be a
process for exploring ideas before going too far out on a limb.
<P>
   I currently work for a large company, but am committed to doing
something where I can tap my creativity and be in control of my own
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: No doubt you know other entrepreneurs or Internet experts you
could talk to about your concept in confidence. You might also
discuss it with some of the angel investors who host forums around
the Bay Area, or visit Web sites like www.garage.com and
www.vfinance.com.
</P>
<P>
   David Cowan, general partner with Bessemer Venture Partners in
Menlo Park, suggests a few other sites for information. One is
EXP.com (www.exp.com), which connects individuals to experts in
nearly 100 categories. Signing up is free, and all transactions
between experts and members are completely secure, confidential and
personalized. Cowan is not exactly an unbiased observer because
since  &LR; his venture capital firm has a stake in EXP.com and he
occasionally offers his services online (for about $200 an hour).
</P>
<P>
   Cowan also likes Silicon Valley Bank's online site for
entrepreneurs (www.esource.svb.com). It offers free articles for
entrepreneurs to help them assess their needs on everything from
marketing to private equity placements. Bank customers can receive
even more services online.
</P>
<P>
   Business Week Magazine recently tested new online advice
services and called Exp.com ``the most efficient, time-saving, and
personalized service.'' It allows info-seekers to do a keyword
search of the site _ for example, ``startup,'' to find advisers
with the right expertise. The service also invites visitors to post
questions on a general bulletin board to which any adviser might
respond. Fees might  &LR; range from $20 an hour on up. Note: Users must
register and submit a credit-card number before asking any
questions.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like going online for advice, you can find plenty
of business consultants, lawyers, accountants and other experts
with real offices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Software Sources
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: My company creates online documentation solutions for software
companies. I would like to contact more companies, but I find that
mailing list providers work by SIC codes which do not zero in on
what I want (they include software retailers). How can I get my
message about the service I provide to my target audience? I would
especially like to contact the CEOs of startup software companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: It's not surprising that you are having a hard time finding what
you are looking for. The Software &AMP; Information Industry
Association in Washington, D.C., (www.siia.net) has about
 &LR; approximately  &LR; 1,400 members but a lot of the startups you are
looking for are not members yet and may never be.
</P>
<P>
   SIIA spokesman Stever Bowers concedes ``No good list of software
startups exists.'' He said the problem is ``A) there are thousands
of startups, and B) their life span is often very short.'' Some
fail and many others get gobbled up by their competitors so names
and faces change quickly.
</P>
<P>
   You might just have to sift through standard industrial
classification (SIC) codes, as imperfect as they may be. InfoUSA of
Oklahoma puts out books of businesses and their key decision-makers
based on such codes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
