<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN SHOCKS BUSH WITH WINS IN MICHIGAN, ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH AND JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Senator John McCain's campaign roared back to
life Tuesday with wins in Michigan and his home state of Arizona.
McCain beat George W. Bush in the open Michigan contest by cobbling
together a combination of moderate Republicans, independents, and a
surprisingly large number of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, after easily winning South Carolina on Saturday, had hoped
to dispatch McCain in Michigan, where the Texas governor was backed
by the political machine of the state's controversial governor,
Republican John Engler. But Engler's efforts may have backfired by
bringing out Democrats to vote for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In a symbol of this topsy-turvy election, McCain's Michigan
victory came as the ink was barely dry on many ``Bush comeback''
stories. Exactly three weeks earlier, McCain won by 18 points in
New Hampshire. Then Bush won South Carolina. Now the McCain
comeback launches the Republican contest into a dramatic two-week
dash toward the March 7 blockbuster round of more than a dozen
primaries and caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   An ebullient but soft-spoken McCain accepted his victory as a
sign that his insurgent campaign is taking root with the national
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reformers, Republican reformers who can make this party
bigger and change politics for future generations,'' McCain said.
``Don't fear this, my fellow Republicans, join it. This is where
you belong. We are creating a new majority my friends, a McCain
majority . . . and we are Al Gore's worst nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, reacting to the news that several television networks had
called the race for McCain, said Tuesday night in Kansas City, Mo.,
``My reaction is, if that is the case, I congratulate him. I want
to thank all the Republicans that supported me. I won
overwhelmingly among the Republicans in Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush then implied that many upcoming races will be easier for
him, noting especially the GOP primaries which don't allow
Democrats or independents to participate. ``There is a lot of
contests coming up,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, the presidential campaign had been conducted in
the smaller states of Iowa, New Hampshire, Delaware, and South
Carolina. McCain's performance in the much larger and more
urbanized state of Michigan and his easy win in his home state of
Arizona give him a legitimate claim to being a serious contender in
the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ambassador Alan Keyes finished a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed that Bush got about two-thirds of the
Republican vote, as he did in South Carolina. But the similarities
ended there. While 60 percent of the South Carolina vote came from
Republicans, only 49 percent of the Michigan vote came from within
the GOP. A third were independents. But the big difference was that
18 percent of Michigan voters were Democrats, twice the percentage
of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won the Democratic vote by a 4-to-1 margin, justifying
McCain's gamble to go for the crossover vote. Bush had hoped that
McCain's appeal for Democratic votes would backfire, as it did in
South Carolina, and result in a larger turnout by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, which sends 58 delegates to the Republican National
Convention, was supposed to be not only a firewall for Bush, but
one made of fireproof asbestos, as Republican Governor John Engler,
a Bush backer, put it. But Engler's power is double-edged,
attracting many supporters but also repelling others. The 15
percent of those surveyed who said Engler's endorsement meant a
great deal voted by a 2-to-1 margin for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Engler Tuesday night accused McCain of ``renting Democrats for a
day'' to beat Bush. ``John McCain isn't party building, he's
party-borrowing,'' Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   The black vote, which was only 1 percent of the turnout in South
Carolina, was 5 percent in Michigan, and it went overwhelmingly for
McCain, the exit polls showed.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won all 30 convention delegates in Arizona, by virtue of
his win there. In Michigan, the delegate picture is murkier. The
state sends 58 delegates to the Republican National Convention,
most of them apportioned according to who prevailed in each of the
state's Congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   The road remains tough for McCain. His defeat in South Carolina
underscored his weakness in the South, where many states have a
strong constituency of religious conservatives who so far have seem
inclined to support Bush. Moreover, a number of large upcoming
states, including New York, do not allow Democrats and independents
to vote in the primaries, which will likely hurt McCain's chances.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's primaries came 72 hours after Bush's huge win in South
Carolina, where Christian conservatives massed against McCain. At
times, the brief battle in Michigan took on the tone of a religious
war, with McCain appealing to Catholic voters to express their
displeasure with Bush for visiting Bob Jones University in South
Carolina, an institution that views Catholicism with suspicion and
bans interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on the other hand, was aided by phone calls from the Rev.
Pat Robertson, the founder of the Christian Coalition, and by phone
calls and postcards from the Right to Life antiabortion group of
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, however, fundamentalist Christians are far less of
a force than in South Carolina. About 13 to 17 percent of the
population considers itself part of the Christian right, compared
to more than a third in South Carolina. And about 25 percent of
Michigan voters are Catholic, unlike in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, meanwhile, benefited from phone calls to voters that
said, ``This is a Catholic voter alert,'' describing Bush's visit
to Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Jones has made strong anti-Catholic statements, including
calling the pope the anti-Christ, the Catholic Church a satanic
cult,'' the recording said. ``John McCain, a pro-life senator, has
strongly criticized this anti-Catholic bigotry, while Governor Bush
has stayed silent, while seeking the support of Bob Jones
University.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush complained that McCain first compared him to President
Clinton, and now is paying for phone calls calling him an
anti-Catholic bigot. ``This is shameful politics,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has vowed to stay in the race through March 7, when more
than a dozen states hold primaries and caucuses. Tuesday, McCain's
campaign issued a news release touting a new CNN-USA Today poll
that shows McCain beating Vice President Al Gore in a general
election matchup, 59 percent to 35 percent, compared to Bush's more
tepid 50 percent to 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cloak of inevitability that once hung about Governor Bush
has frayed away, and Republicans are starting to realize that John
McCain is the only candidate who can and will win against Al
Gore,'' said Dan Schnur, McCain's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Schnur said the pillars of the Bush candidacy _ inevitability,
electability, and money _ are rapidly crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, 58 delegates are at stake, and a total of 1,034 are
needed to win the Republican nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
