<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5199 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-REWARDSIDE-REWARDSIDE     02-22 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REWARDSIDE-REWARDSIDE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Palo Alto Firm Encourages All to Share Ideas  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Many local companies do a good job encouraging teamwork and
focusing their competitive efforts on beating their external
rivals.
<P>
   At Ideo, the Palo Alto industrial design company that helped
create the Apple mouse and the Palm V handheld computer, teamwork
is the name of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this mythology in America about the lone genius. We
love to personify things,'' said Ideo general manager Tom Kelley.
``But Michelangelo didn't paint the Sistine Chapel alone and Edison
didn't invent the lightbulb light bulb  &LR; alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideo has 350 people in seven offices around the world and has
built a $60-million-a-year business by getting people to work in
groups, to share ideas and build on them.
</P>
<P>
   This often starts with brainstorming sessions where employees
sit around and throw out ideas. The rules to encourage the free
flow of ideas are stencilled on the walls of all Ideo brainstorming
rooms:
</P>
<P>
   _Defer judgment
</P>
<P>
   _Encourage wild ideas
</P>
<P>
   _Build on the ideas of others
</P>
<P>
   _Stay focused on the topic
</P>
<P>
   _One conversation at a time
</P>
<P>
   Stanford professor Jeffrey Pfeffer applauds Ideo's brainstorming
approach because ``it is built on participation and getting work
done, not title or credentials.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; c,12p2  &LR;  To encourage team spirit, Ideo breaks its employees
down by ``studios'' and project groups. At the home office in Palo
Alto, for example, there are about 100 employees and six studios
with their own names and themes. One adopted a Ronald Coleman goes
to Shangri-la Shangrila  &LR; ``Lost Horizon'' theme and is nestled
nestles  &LR; beneath a DC-3 wing. Another decked out in velvet curtains
looks like a supper club.
</P>
<P>
   Ideo is big on establishing group identity with its own office
design, outside retreats and a bonus system based on the
performance of the company, the studio and the individual. Each
employee must pick two peers to help in his or her annual
evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is relatively easy to fool the boss but it's
hard to fool other members of the project team,'' explained Kelley.
``You can't be like Eddie Haskell in `Leave It to Beaver' and just
be on best behavior for a few minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every company starts out fostering teamwork. Some, like
Guidant Corp., found they needed to change their self-destructive
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Guidant, which makes devices for life-saving medical procedures,
realized in the mid-1990s that internal competition was killing its
efforts to foster teamwork and get new products to market quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to stay focused on the customer,'' said Ginger Graham,
president of Guidant's $1.2 billion Vascular Intervention Group in
Santa Clara. ``So we developed a team bonus structure that rewards
employees for delivering great solutions, not for what area of the
company they work for or what they do alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidant's bonus system is now based one-third on reaching
product milestone goals and two-thirds on performance of products
in the market. All employees get the same bonus, which is based on
a percentage of their base salary. Last year it was 28 percent. In
1998, a banner year, it was 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, before Guidant adopted its team-based approach,
different groups of employees worked against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in R&AMP;D liked playing with new ideas and making the best
product possible,'' said Peter McInnes, an R&AMP;D vice president at
the time. ``On the manufacturing side, engineers focused on
producing and were resistant to changes that involved new processes
and training.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, McInnes recalls that ``people tried to optimize
performance within their departments,'' sometimes at the expense of
other groups.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, R&AMP;D groups even worked on the same problem, like
finding better coatings for catheters, without knowing it. (The two
units only discovered they were going over the same ground when a
prospective customer brought it to their attention.)
</P>
<P>
   To align everyone around the common goals of creating the best
products and getting them to market quickly, Guidant restructured
around business units where research and manufacturing teams had to
work together and were measured by getting products to market and
having them accepted.
</P>
<P>
   McInnes, now vice president of the unit that makes angioplasty
catheters, said it takes a year or less to get a new product to
market, about half the time it took in the previous era. Since
teamwork has been encouraged, Guidant sales have doubled over the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   A beneficial byproduct of Guidant's shared goals and rewards
structure is that Graham says the company only loses about two to
five percent of its workforce a year and less than 10 percent of
its technical talent. In hotly competitive Silicon Valley, where
job-hopping is the norm and typical employee attrition is 20
percent a year, that's an impressive retention rate.
</P>
<P>
   Another star in professor Robert Sutton and Pfeffer's management
pantheon is Men's Wearhouse. The company headed by TV pitchman
George Zimmer rewards team selling because shoppers are interested
in the total store experience, not their dealings with a single
salesperson.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage collaboration, Men's Wearhouse tracks transactions
and average sales dollars per transaction for each ``wardrobe
consultant.'' If someone has substantially more sales than his or
her colleagues _ say 25 percent or more _ that is taken as a signal
that the person is probably not sharing walk-in traffic but is
hogging it.
</P>
<P>
   Men's Wearhouse has even fired at least one of its most
successful salespeople because he refused to conform with the
firm's cultural values. The move, which was not designed to stifle
individual performance, apparently worked. After the self-centered
salesman was canned, none of his colleagues matched his individual
sales figures but total sales volume of the store still increased
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``To dominate a declining industry means you're doing something
right,'' said Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford professors also have good words for SouthWest
Airlines. The airline, which demonizes external competitors, relies
on collective rewards internally such as profit sharing and stock
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   An unlike some other airlines, it doesn't waste time assessing
and placing blame for problems but focuses on solving them. For
example, if a flight is delayed, SouthWest crews can check the box
``team delay'' rather than blame someone on the ground or in the
cabin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
