<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PRIMARIES-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-940(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN SEEN AS VICTOR IN BOTH ARIZONA AND MICHIGAN  
 (Subs for updating and rewriting throughout) 
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Sen. John McCain scrambled back into contention in the
Republican presidential race on Tuesday, capitalizing on his
home-state advantage to trounce Gov. George W. Bush in Arizona and
riding a wave of independents and Democrats to gain an edge on Bush
in Michigan, polls of voters indicated.
</P>
<P>
   The voting in Michigan has been watched closely not only because
the campaign here was marked by bitter accusations of unscrupulous
tactics on both sides, but, more important, because it is the first
large-state showdown of the campaign with 58 delegates up for grabs
.
</P>
<P>
   Although early returns showed the race extremely close, McCain
clearly regained some of the footing he lost on Saturday in the
South Carolina primary by running well ahead of Bush among
independents and Democrats here _ as well as many people who had
never before voted in a Republican primary. Those voters poured to
the polls, swelling turnout estimates to at least one million, more
than double the totals in primaries here four and eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bush drew his strength from a different pool of voters: he
attracted far higher proportions of conservatives and Republican
loyalists _ a margin of more than 2 to 1 _ than McCain. But those
voters helped Bush more in South Carolina than here in the Midwest,
where the electorate is far less Republican _ and far less
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   With 37 percent of the precincts reporting in Michigan, McCain
had 50 percent of the vote while Bush had 44 percent. In Arizona,
with 2 percent of the precincts reporting, McCain had 53 percent
and Bush 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief news conference in Kansas City on Tuesday evening,
shortly after the polls closed in Michigan, Bush said,
``Republicans overwhelmingly supported my candidacy. It seems I'm
getting stronger and stronger with Republicans as the primaries go
on.''
</P>
<P>
   And he seemed to recognize the possibility that McCain would
continue to impede what many had once considered an inevitable
march to the nomination. ``This is a long process,'' he said.
``This is a marathon. And I'm going to be in it all the way to the
end. And some primaries you win, and sometimes, you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The two contests on Tuesday were especially critical for McCain
because after Bush's 11-point victory in South Carolina, he has
sought to demonstrate that he is not a one-state wonder who could
only win a primary in a tiny state like New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Bush's advisers had hoped that they could
effectively knock off McCain after Tuesday. And even McCain's aides
had acknowledged that a lopsided defeat in Michigan would have
shattered the chances for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's voting assured that what McCain called ``a wonderful,
wonderful ride'' after his defeat in South Carolina will not be
over. It means that a Republican nominee would probably not emerge
at least until after the candidates sprint through 16 primaries and
caucuses over the next 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the outcome on Tuesday will intensify the focus on
the races next week in Virginia, Washington state and North Dakota.
But the most important voting will be on March 7, which is
something of a national primary, with voters going to the polls in
New York, California, Ohio, Missouri, Georgia, Connecticut and
several other states.
</P>
<P>
   After South Carolina, Bush and McCain rushed to concentrate on
Michigan because the outcome here is far more important. There are
58 delegates at stake in Michigan; 30 in Arizona. McCain was also
widely expected to win in Arizona because he is the favorite son
there who has served three terms in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bush's defeat in Arizona, according to the polls,
underscores how the primary season has been far rockier than he or
his advisers had anticipated. Bush enjoyed the energetic backing of
the Republican governor, Jane Dee Hull. And for a time last year,
surveys in Arizona showed Bush ahead of McCain. That led some of
the Bush's advisers to happily predict that they would humiliate
McCain in his own state.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush advisers now insist they never intended to win in
Arizona, they poured as much as $2 million into smothering the
state in television commercials and direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   The see-saw nature of the Republican competition _ while McCain
has won New Hampshire, Bush was victorious in South Carolina and
Delaware _ leaves Bush appearing far less invincible than he seemed
for much of last year when polls showed, month after month, that he
towered over the Republican field and could easily defeat a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the McCain campaign has fastened onto the theme that Bush
is such a weak candidate that he could lose a general election.
</P>
<P>
   But the voting in Michigan pointed to larger difficulties for
both Bush and McCain. Bush's constituency is predominately from his
party's conservative wing, according to the surveys of voters,
conducted by a consortium of the television networks and The
Associated Press. Those so-called exit polls showed McCain with a
slight edge over Bush; McCain also held a narrow leade with with
about a third of the actual votes counted.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls also showed that if Bush is the Republican
nominee, it might be difficult for him to attract Republican
moderates, independents and Democrats in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for McCain, the surveys showed, is that he
encountered difficulty attracting members of his own party. That
could be perilous because many of the coming contests are in states
like New York, where, unlike Michigan, only registered Republicans
can participate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
