r f BC-REWARDS-REWARDS_SFCHR     02-22 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REWARDS-REWARDS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Feuds in the Cubes Drain Energy From Pursuit of Profit  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Entrepreneurs and managers have plenty of knowledge about how to
run companies, including reams of computer data, piles of
management books, loads of high-priced consultants and their own
experiences. But many still do stupid things to undermine teamwork
and performance.
<P>
   In their new book, ``The Knowing-Doing Gap _ How Smart Companies
Turn Knowledge Into Action,'' Stanford organizational behavior
professors Jeffrey Pfeffer and Robert Sutton focus on management
practices that sabotage success.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most common and most insidious, they say, is ``when
internal competition turns friends into enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   Management practices that produce counterproductive internal
competition are incredibly common. They can include recognition
awards such as employee-of-the-month programs, contests between
departments and individuals for prizes and published rankings of
individual or unit performance.
</P>
<P>
   Pitting employees against each other is a common phenomenon at
large companies. But the impetus can take hold at very small
businesses when the entrepreneur at the helm figures survival of
the fittest is the law of the office as well as nature.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton and Pfeffer have nothing against free enterprise or
rewarding individuals for their work. Sales commissions are
effective in spurring brokers, real estate agents and many others
to greater glory for themselves and their companies. The Society of
Incentive Travel Executives in New York figures incentive sales
programs boost revenues of companies that use them by nearly 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Internal competition is only counter-productive when it involves
``zero-sum contests'' where the success or rewards of one person
come at the expense of someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeffer and Sutton talk about management marvels and miscues
with the same exuberance that Tom and Ray Magliozzi discuss
clunkers on their popular ``Car Talk'' show on National Public
Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Near the top of their list of misguided managers is James
Halpin, CEO of Comp USA, who was featured in the Academy of
Management's ``Executive'' magazine last May.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the big Dallas computer retailer, whose stock has
lost three-quarters of its value since 1998, tells his employees to
ask themselves at the end of each day: ``What did I do today to put
myself above my co-workers? If you can't come up with anything, you
wasted a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton derisively calls Halpin ``a piece of work.''
</P>
<P>
   At quarterly meetings, Halpin makes 20 regional managers sit by
order of profitability with the weakest earners in the front
``because they've got to listen to everything we've got to say.''
At other meetings, employees must wear name tags marked with their
store's unaccounted for, or missing, inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeffer calls Halpin's division of employees by ``lifters'' and
``leaners'' and other tactics ``management through humiliation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford professors say the effectiveness of incentive
programs depends on how they are implemented.
</P>
<P>
   If bonuses go to salespeople with specific territories and
little need to cooperate _ ``low task interdependence'' in business
school jargon, they say such rewards might be fine. On the other
hand, ``if employees need help from one another, if they need to
learn on the job, then I-win, you-lose contests can undermine
company performance,'' Sutton contends.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton and Pfeffer say Microsoft fits in this mold and is
``notorious for releasing software with a large number of bugs.''
Microsoft's culture puts a premium on individual expertise. That
leads to high salary and bonus but creates ``an incentive to
prevent others from uncovering your deficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the dangers of unbridled internal competition is that it
can lead to ``information hoarding'' as everyone strives to be an
expert who is more knowledgeable than his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Internal competition also can drive good employees out the door.
Even worse, say Sutton and Pfeffer, it can create so much tension
and stress that employees resort to faking sales numbers and
accounting fraud to meet or surpass expectations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2227EST &QL; 
