<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-PRIM-BUSH23-COX     02-22 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIM-BUSH23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain takes Michigan, Arizona primaries
 &HT;    By Jena Heath and Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Gov. George W. Bush got the news on stage and
on camera, but was ready with the quick spin when told that he lost
Michigan's presidential primary on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank all the Republicans who supported me,'' Bush
said at a news conference after a rally en route from Michigan to
California. ``I won overwhelmingly amongst the Republicans in
Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Arizona Sen. John McCain, somebody other than
Republicans are helping pick the GOP presidential nominee. And,
exit polls show, those somebodies tend to be big fans of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Only 47 percent of the Michigan vote on Tuesday came from voters
who identified themselves as Republicans. Bush won that group by a
65 percent to 28 percent margin.
</P>
<P>
   But 35 percent of the voters said they are independents, and
McCain won that segment by the same 65 percent to 28 percent
margin. McCain's winning formula also included a whopping 80
percent to 11 percent margin among the 18 percent of the voters who
identified themselves as Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose overwhelming gubernatorial re-election effort in
1998 was built on a bipartisan coalition, is now in a political
death match against those forces.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday night whether it's a good idea to have open
primaries that allow Democrats and independents to vote in
Republican contests, Bush came down firmly on the side of maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they are and sometimes they're not,'' he said,
adding that he remains convinced that some Michigan Democrats voted
in Tuesday's GOP primary just to mess with the system.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Bush _ and perhaps the advantage for McCain _
is that the remaining pre-Super Tuesday (March 7) primaries are all
open contests. The next contests are Feb. 29 in Washington state
and Virginia. North Dakota Republicans will hold caucuses that day
to pick their White House favorite.
</P>
<P>
   California, characteristically, has the weirdest deal. All
registered voters are eligible to participate in its March 7 GOP
contest. But only the votes of registered Republicans will be used
in determining how the state's 162 delegates are divided.
</P>
<P>
   If current trends hold, McCain could win the popular vote but
Bush could win the lion's share of the delegates. It takes 1,034
delegates to win the nomination. When the voting ends March 7 _ a
week before Texans vote _ 89 delegates will have been awarded.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who might have been able to knock McCain from the race by
beating him by a large margin in Michigan, declined to say he was
disappointed by the missed opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with the Republican vote,'' said Bush, ever on
message. ``This is a long process. This is a marathon and I'm going
to be in it all the way to the end. Some primaries you win and
sometimes you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, Ariz., on a night when he won two Republican
primaries, McCain found himself in the peculiar position of making
a ``special plea'' for GOP votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't fear this campaign, my fellow Republicans, join it, join
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas government Professor Bruce Buchanan on
Tuesday night acknowledged the strangeness of the process and the
strange turns it has already taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``It leaves McCain back in business with some strengths and some
weaknesses,'' he said of the senator's wins in Michigan and
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's muscle is in his ability reach across party lines and
pull in the kinds of voters a candidate needs to win in November.
His weakness is his relative inability to draw votes in his own
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the front-runner is still Governor Bush because of
all the horsepower he has got lined up behind him,'' said Buchanan.
``But McCain has a moment, and the question is whether he can seize
it. I still give our local boy a slight edge.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Michigan Gov. John Engler, Bush's top backer in that
state. Engler doesn't buy the argument that McCain is engaged in an
incredible mission to broaden the GOP's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald Reagan used to go try to recruit Democrats to become
Republicans,'' said Engler. ``We've never seen a candidate like
John McCain who went out to rent Democrats for a day to get himself
the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
