<HEADER>
A5214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ADVISER-AD-COLUMN-NYT     02-22 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVISER-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NEW CAMPAIGN ABOUT ONLINE TRADING HAS TRADITIONAL
MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hype is everywhere: stories about 22-year-old Internet
millionaires, clerks in start-up companies with stockholdings that
rival those of a typical CEO and TV commercials about fortunes made
in online trading.
</P>
<P>
   In short, everyone is getting rich _ except you.
</P>
<P>
   Now a mutual fund company is sounding a big note of caution in a
new advertising campaign. Alliance Capital, which has $368 billion
in assets under management, is showing a series of commercials
using dark humor to depict investors who lose their life savings
after playing the market on their own. Their message is an
old-fashioned one: invest for the future with a long-term strategy
using a financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the advertising behind online day trading _ of guys in
pickup trucks owning islands _ it's like Las Vegas in your living
room and, we felt we needed to make a statement,'' said Richard
Khaleel, Alliance's senior vice president fpr marketing and
advertising. ``There's this feeling that it's easy to make money in
the market, but that's not the experience of users.''
</P>
<P>
   The pro-adviser message comes at a time when buying online for a
reduced fee and without using a broker has become the news of the
industry. It has also prompted a huge battle among some 55
companies ranging from old-line brokerage houses to complete
upstarts. Even Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the nation's largest retail
brokerage firm with 14,000 brokers, recently announced a discount
online trading venture.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance has good reason to promote the use of advisers. Its
funds are sold almost exclusively through advisers and major retail
brokers like Merrill Lynch and the Salomon Smith Barney unit of
Citigroup. The funds can be purchased online through a service like
Etrade.com, but the ould still include the fee someone would
pay a broker, said Shira Zackai, an Alliance spokeswoman. ``So it
makes sense to buy it through a broker where you can get advice,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the TV spots show plans going awry after investors put
their money in the wrong stocks. The TV commercials are fictional
to dramatize the risks of going it alone. The company has no hard
evidence showing that people are losing fortunes on bad trades,
although Khaleel said everyone had heard stories to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   One spot, for instance, shows a teenager joyously announcing
that he made it into medical school only to hear his father say, in
a nonchalant way, that he lost his son's college fund by day
trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it'd be fun,'' the father says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about it, honey,'' the mother says. ``You never
looked good in white anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other commercials show elderly people announcing that they
lost their retirement savings. And another shows a little boy whose
parents are renting out his room to offset their losses in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is suggesting all you need is an Internet hook-up to
make a fortune,'' said John Ferrell, president and chief creative
officer of Ferrellcavillo, New York, the Alliance ad agency.
``We're the only contrary voice out there right now that says you
do need some guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brad Silberling, who is best known for his work for
shows like ``NYPD Blue,'' the campaign depicts the bad investor as
cavalier, even a bit nutty, to get people to chuckle. Inside the
company, the ads are referred to as the ``Investors Behaving
Badly'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't make it humorous, people could just not want to
think about it,'' Ferrell explained.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance came up with the campaign after its own research with
consumers and brokers found that investors were beginning to think
they could make a killing in the market without any help from a
financial expert, Khaleel said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Burke, an online brokerage industry expert with Gomez
Advisers in Lincoln, Mass., an e-commerce research firm, said the
bull market was probably what was enticing some investors away from
mutual funds into what they hope are faster-growing individual
stocks, like technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's happening is that some individuals might be
looking more to the equity market, and that's not solely related to
day trading,'' Burke said. ``It's more about going to individual
stocks _ that's the bigger story.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Alliance is trying to deter Internet trading, its own
proprietary research conducted last May by Louis Harris &AMP;
Associates, New York, showed that only 4 percent of the adult
population trades online. And most Americans are not willing to
trade more than $4,500 without consulting an adviser, it found.
</P>
<P>
   The research also pointed to what Khaleel said was an
information overload. The heaviest Internet users were more likely
to consult a professional adviser before making a decision. Over
all, 57 percent polled said they planned to consult an adviser
whether they traded online or not, Khaleel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you have all this information doesn't mean you
know how to make a decision,'' he said. ``You can get so much
information, and can have too many good choices _ that's where a
good adviser can help out.''
</P>
<P>
   Alliance will spend about $15 million on advertising this year,
a 50 percent increase over last year's spending, Khaleel said. The
company increased the budget to promote its important new message,
he said. But, oddly, another reason the budget increased was
because the cost of media have jumped _ partly because of all those
dot-com companies rushing into TV advertising with money from their
initial public offerings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
