<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DIALLO-SUMMARY-NYT     02-22 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-SUMMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 OFFICERS, 41 SHOTS, 2 EXPLANATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-DIALLO-TRIAL) 
 (lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEFENDANTS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officer Sean Carroll, 37, a six-year veteran who first noticed
Amadou Diallo standing in his building's vestibule and led the way
up the steps. He fired 16 of the 41 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Edward McMellon, 27, a six-year veteran, also fired 16
shots, falling backward down the steps and continuing to shoot from
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Richard Murphy, 27, a six-year veteran who was behind
them, fired four times after the shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Kenneth Boss, 28, an eight-year veteran and the driver,
was the last to leave the car. He fired five shots.
</P>
<P>
   THE CASE FOR CONVICTION
</P>
<P>
   PROSECUTION BASICS: Four days of presentation; 12 witnesses; 28
exhibits, including Diallo's wallet and 41 discarded shell casings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two prosecution witnesses who were on Wheeler Avenue the night
Diallo was shot testified that they did not hear the officers say
anything to Diallo before the shooting began. Three prosecution
witnesses testified that there was a pause in the shooting, raising
the possibility that the officers had time to reassess the
situation during the fusillade.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr. Joseph Cohen, a former New York City medical examiner,
testified that one of the first of 19 shots that struck Diallo hit
him in the chest, piercing his aortic arch and spine, which would
have instantly paralyzed him and dropped him to the ground. Thus
one shot _ traveling up the calf _ definitely hit Diallo as he was
on the ground, Cohen testified, and two others may have.
</P>
<P>
   _ At least four witnesses who were at the scene _ including two
police officials _ testified that the vestibule at 1157 Wheeler
Ave. was reasonably well lit, undermining the defense's claim that
the officers could not clearly see Diallo's actions or his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   _ During cross-examination of the four officers, prosecutors
established that Diallo was not committing a crime when the
officers stopped him, and that they did not consider the
possibility that he lived at 1157 Wheeler Ave. or did not
understand their commands.
</P>
<P>
   THE CASE FOR ACQUITTAL:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE BASICS: Nearly five days of presentation; 19 witnesses,
including the four officers; 26 exhibits, including Diallo's right
sneaker and the 40-watt lightbulb from the vestibule.
</P>
<P>
   _ Schrrie Elliott, who was walking down Wheeler Avenue when the
shooting began, testified that she heard an officer yell ``gun''
before the shooting started, bolstering the defense's claim that
the officers truly feared being shot.
</P>
<P>
   _ A wound ballistics expert and a medical examiner testified
that they believed the shot to Diallo's chest was one of the last
to strike him, after he had sustained 15 or 16 wounds to his left
side. They said that one or none of the bullets struck him while he
was on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   _ A former New York City police officer and criminologist who
customarily testifies against police officers testified that the
officers were following their training in deciding to approach
Diallo for an investigatory stop and were correct to pursue him
into the vestibule.
</P>
<P>
   _ In strikingly consistent, often emotional accounts, the four
officers gave their first public version of the shooting. In sum,
they said Diallo had acted suspiciously, that they identified
themselves, that Diallo had refused their requests to show them his
hands, that he appeared to be digging in his waist with his unseen
right hand, that the vestibule was dimly lit, that they mistook his
black wallet for a gun, that they incorrectly thought an officer
who had fallen had been shot, that Diallo had stayed upright until
the final shot had been fired.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE'S RULINGS:
</P>
<P>
   The judge agreed to prosecution and defense requests to have the
jury consider charges less than murder, including criminally
negligent homicide, which could be punished with as little as
probation. The judge also decided to tell the jury that police
officers are justified in using deadly physical force to defend
themselves or another person if they are in the course of making an
arrest or preventing an escape from custody. This was viewed as a
victory for the defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
