<HEADER>
A5217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ORACLE-PHONES-NYT &LR;      02-22 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-PHONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ORACLE SPINOFF WILL STRESS CELL PHONE ACCESS TO THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Oracle Corp.'s chief executive, Lawrence J. Ellison,
announced the formation and spinoff Tuesday of a new business to
capitalize on the industrywide push to make the Internet accessible
over wireless phones and other portable devices.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, to be known as Oraclemobile.com, will be headed
by Denise Lahey, Oracle's former vice president for mobile
products. Ellison said the company would create partnerships with
electronic commerce sites like Amazon.com or Travelocity to help
translate their Web pages and transaction software into products
accessible on cellular phones and personal organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The company is joining a rush already under way to develop
technology to make Internet access viable on wireless devices so
that people can trade stocks, obtain driving directions, buy books
or music, and conduct similar transactions wherever they happen to
be.
</P>
<P>
   That effort was given added fuel Tuesday as Texas Instruments
introduced a microprocessor intended for cellular phones called the
C55x, which is faster yet uses less power than other processors now
available and should thus extend the battery life to several days.
Texas Instruments said large cellular telephone makers, including
Nokia and Ericsson were planning to use the chip, which is
scheduled for shipment later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is going to have a cell phone, and every cell phone
is going to have Internet access,'' Ellison said at a news
conference. ``By 2002, a lot more cellular phones are going to have
Internet access than PCs.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Ellison predicted the death of the personal
computer by 2000, and the emergence in its place of inexpensive,
ubiquitous ``network computers'' that could call up personal
information anywhere in the world over the Internet. Having missed
his mark in 1996, Ellison Tuesday positioned his new effort as a
sort of revised vision of a post-personal computer world.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle will face competitors already seeking different pieces of
the wireless Web market. For example, Microstrategy in Vienna, Va.,
offers consumer- and business-based content for mobile devices, and
Phone.com, in Redwood City, Calif., has technology for translating
Web pages for wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle's plan differs by being more comprehensive than any
single competitor's technology. What all these companies share,
industry analysts say, are substantial challenges in making rich,
colorful Web content easy to read and navigate on mobile devices,
which are hampered by small screens, slow speeds for gaining access
to data and limited battery life.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking standard keyboards, they also make it hard for users to
enter requests for information. Oracle will provide software to
make it easier and less expensive for e-commerce sites to
automatically translate their content for use on a variety of
wireless devices, Lahey said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Redman, associate director of the Yankee Group, a
Boston-based technology research and consulting firm, said it
remained to be seen whether Oracle would really be able to
automatically translate rich, textured Web pages into bare-bones
content for mobile devices.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he and other analysts said they saw Oracle's entry into
the market as an important endorsement of the concept. ``The fact
that Oracle is doing this is significant,'' said Berge Ayvazian,
chief executive of the Yankee Group. ``The mobile hand set and
mobile device is likely to be the point-of-sale terminal of
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee Group projects that by the end of this year, 15
million phones in the United States will be able to use the
Internet, rising to 150 million by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle opened a Web site Tuesday, www.oramobil.com, featuring
content ready for mobile devices from some of its initial partners.
The name ``oraclemobile.com'' is owned by someone Ellison described
as a ``squatter,'' but he promised that Oracle would get that Web
address ``very shortly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
