A5218 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-SPI &LR;      02-22 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT INSISTS IT BROKE NO LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In hours of legal rhetoric capping 16 months of
courtroom wrangling, Microsoft Tuesday told a federal judge that it
broke no laws to become the dominant seller of operating-system
software for Intel-based computers.
</P>
<P>
   David Boies, representing the Justice Department and 19 states
who brought the federal antitrust case against Microsoft argued
``It is simply impossible to imagine'' that the Redmond software
company hadn't violated the nation's laws against anticompetitive
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who in November 1999 declared in
harsh language that Microsoft is a monopolist, may rule by as early
as April whether the company's monopolistic acts broke the law.
Then, in separate proceedings, he'll determine what punishment, if
any, is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   While, by some accounts Tuesday, it appeared the government's
case held the upper hand, Microsoft did not yield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law supports Microsoft's position in this case,'' said
John Warden, Microsoft's lead attorney, at the conclusion of the
arguments. ``The government has failed to prove any market impact
of any acts by Microsoft. ... Microsoft's actions resulted in
greater innovation, lower prices and better quality. The creation
of commerce itself cannot violate the Sherman Antitrust Act.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge gave Microsoft little comfort. At one point Tuesday,
he dismissed a key Microsoft defense by comparing the company to
John D. Rockefeller's Standard Oil monopoly, the subject of the
first major antitrust case, in 1906, that resulted in a breakup of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really see a distinction,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   At times, rhetoric in the ceremonial courtroom at the E. Barrett
Prettyman Court House was mind-numbingly arcane. And it ran far
longer than its scheduled three and a half hours.
</P>
<P>
   But several legal experts said questions the unusually
vociferous Jackson posed hinted at the issues that may most heavily
influence the case's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are at least five separate antitrust allegations
before him in the case, Jackson focused on two: whether Microsoft's
copyright on its Windows software excused its behavior under
federal antitrust law, and whether Microsoft unlawfully tied the
sale of Internet Explorer to that of Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's findings of fact, issued in November 1999, strongly
suggest he views the fact Microsoft integrated its Internet
Explorer browser with its Windows operating system as a tying
arrangement. That's unlawful under the antitrust laws. That point
is one of Microsoft's most vulnerable spots, said Glen Manishin, a
McLean, Va., antitrust specialist.
</P>
<P>
   But Warden argued Microsoft has done no wrong, because the
integration benefits consumers. He asserted a June 1998 appellate
ruling to that effect in the Microsoft case, which reversed a
holding by Jackson, is binding on Jackson in these proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you read the Court of Appeals' decision as controlling on
me about this?'' Jackson asked Warden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, if there's a plausible benefit, I read it that way,''
Warden answered.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court for the D.C. Circuit in June 1998 found
combining Windows with the Internet Explorer browser did ``some
plausible good,'' and that's all that's required to survive an
antitrust claim, Warden said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson questioned Boies closely on the tying issue. Boies
argued that Microsoft's decision was not really a product design
decision, but more a mere ``bolting'' together of the browser and
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Boies was trying to recast the tying charge as a
contract restriction _ that is, PC makers who wanted Windows had to
take its Internet Explorer browsing software whether they wanted it
or not.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jackson appeared to be skeptical. What about the benefit,
he asked Boies, of the increased distribution of browser technology
resulting from Microsoft's decision to fold its browser into
Windows? ``I can't offset that _ one plausible benefit,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lande, a law professor at the University of Baltimore,
said he noted Jackson taking careful notes whenever the tying issue
was addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very complex issue, and very, very important to the
case. I don't think the judge understood it at first,'' Lande said.
</P>
<P>
   As another tactic to persuade Jackson that it is blameless,
Microsoft asserted that its copyright in Windows shields it from
antitrust liability for forbidding computer makers from changing
the number and placement of icons on Windows-based machines and the
computers' boot-up sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Warden denied that he was claiming copyright law prevails over
antitrust law. But then he cited a federal district court ruling
that once a copyright has been acquired, subsequent conduct under
copyright law ``cannot give rise to any liability under antitrust
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as a copyright holder asserts only its rights to the
copyright and doesn't extend them to another market, immunity from
antitrust exists?'' asked Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a good working proposition,'' Warden answered.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kovacic, an antitrust expert at George Washington law
school in Washington, D.C., said there is no caselaw directly on
this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the judge is troubled by it,'' Kovacic said. ``I don't
think it's easy to conclude how he feels about these issues, but
it's clear he is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Other potential bases for Microsoft's antitrust liability in the
case include predatory pricing, exclusionary agreements, and
threats to withhold information from partners.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Microsoft and the government concluded this phase of the
trial, their representatives are continuing to meet in Chicago in
search of a settlement, in mediation talks overseen by Richard A.
Posner, chief judge of the 7th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals. The
two sides reportedly remain far apart, but government officials
note that the fact they are still meeting at this late date
suggests a willingness on both sides to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to work hard with Judge Posner,'' said
William Neukom, Microsoft's general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The court is likely to hold separate hearings on remedies if, as
expected, Jackson rules that Microsoft violated antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   A strong verdict against Microsoft could well lead to harsh
sanctions against the company, including breaking it up. If,
however, Jackson agrees with some of the government's legal
allegations but rejects others, the sanctions against Microsoft
could be less severe, prohibiting it from some practices but
leaving the company intact.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Justice Department and state attorneys general
pressing the case insist they will not settle for a mild sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remedies have to be drastic and far reaching,'' Richard
Blumenthal, the attorney general of Connecticut and one of the
plaintiffs, said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Wire service material was included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
