u p BC-GOP-MCCAIN-ANALYSIS-H     02-22 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MCCAIN-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
PRIMARY WINS BREATHE NEW LIFE INTO McCAIN CAMPAIGN 
 
(Eds.: This is an analysis) 
(Eds: Optional ending included) 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Democrats and independents in Michigan handed John
McCain a double-edged sword on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They breathed new life into his race for the Republican
presidential nomination but left the Arizona senator open to
renewed attacks that he isn't his own party's real choice for the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it means for McCain is a few more weeks of staying in the
fight and keeping hope alive for his troops out in the field,''
said University of Texas at Austin government professor Bruce
Buchanan, a specialist in presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said McCain's victory in Michigan and his easy win in
his home state of Arizona, which also held a primary Tuesday, also
may give McCain another boost in fund-raising before the March 7
Super Tuesday lineup of primaries in New York, California and
several other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's got a major task ahead of him to try to convince
Republicans who will dominate most of the rest of the primaries
that he is conservative enough to be their nominee,'' Buchanan
added.
</P>
<P>
   L. Tucker Gibson, a political science professor at Trinity
University in San Antonio, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson said McCain's support among Democrats and independents
may suggest that the senator ``doesn't have much depth of support
in the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls indicated that as few as 49 percent of voters in
Michigan's Republican primary were actually Republicans. Some 33
percent were independents, and 18 percent were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush won as much as two-thirds of the Republican vote.
But McCain, who had wooed Democrats and independents, beat Bush 2-1
among independents and captured more than 80 percent of Democrats'
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Engler, Bush's Michigan chairman, said that McCain,
unlike former Republican President Reagan, didn't try to recruit
Democrats into the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen a candidate like John McCain who goes out to
rent Democrats for a day to win the Republican nomination,'' Engler
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to hurt him in some of the Republican states coming
up.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, in his victory statement in Phoenix, defended his
Republican credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a proud Reagan conservative. I love the Republican party.
It is my home,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reformers; Republican reformers who can make our party
bigger and change politics in this country for generations. Don't
fear this campaign, my fellow Republicans. Join it.''
</P>
<P>
   In taking a swipe at Bush without mentioning him by name, McCain
said that Michigan had ``sent a powerful message across America, a
message that our party wants real reform from the real reformer.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain spokesman Todd Harris said Engler had ``absolutely
nothing'' on which to base his comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Engler is doing everything he can to avoid the shame and
embarrassment of his firewall state getting tip-toed over by Sen.
McCain,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Koopman, a government professor at Calvin College in Grand
Rapids, Mich., said McCain wisely campaigned in areas of the state
Sunday and Monday where the Republican establishment's influence
was weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demographically, this is not South Carolina,'' Koopman said,
comparing Michigan to the state where Bush, aided by the GOP
establishment, scored a big victory over McCain on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Michigan) Republican Party is not John Engler's party to
do with as he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said McCain benefited from an effort by some Democrats
to cross party lines so that they could embarrass Engler by voting
against Bush. But, he added, McCain also won the votes of many
Democrats and independents simply because he reached out to them,
and they were attracted by his maverick style and reform message.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan said Bush is still the front-runner for the GOP
nomination, in large part because McCain, by attracting so many
Democratic and independent voters, has made his nomination task
more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   A major test for the Arizona senator, Buchanan added, will come
March 7 in delegate-rich California. Although anyone can vote in
that state's primary, only the votes of Republicans will count
toward delegate selection.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said McCain also will need to improve his fund-raising
and campaign organizations in upcoming primary states to remain
competitive with the better-funded and better-organized Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the professor added, Bush likely will renew his
attacks on McCain's Republican support, much as he did in South
Carolina after independents helped the senator win the New
Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, the Trinity University political scientist, said McCain
may be in ``real trouble'' in states that have closed primaries or
that choose their nominating delegates in conventions.
</P>
<P>
   But, Gibson added, McCain's second and third primary victories
also could bode ill for Bush. Party regulars ``who thought that
this (the nomination) was an easy run are going to get very anxious
about this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, he said, is going to have to work to avoid any
``attrition'' of his party organization, including defectors of key
endorsements to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
