<HEADER>
A5220 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-WILD-MAN-ART-2TAKES-$     02-22 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILD-MAN-ART-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ART'S MEANING DRIFTS WITH THE TIDES OF HISTORY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Ken Shulman's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about the
artist May Stevens.  
 By KEN SHULMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. _ The piece is called ``The Wild Man,'' and
it comes from a late-14th-century choir stall in Cologne, Germany.
Human in form but animal in its sculptured curly hide, the 11}-inch
oak figure is a denizen of the medieval imagination.
</P>
<P>
   For Germans in the Middle Ages, this figure, seen in its
ecclesiastical setting, evoked the fond myth of the German people
descending from a land of rural tribesmen in prelapsarian synthesis
with nature. For Germans in the 1930s, ``The Wild Man,'' isolated
and abstract in its Bauhaus-style museum case, appealed to other
sentiments, including a visceral resentment of Christianity that
was channeled into bellicosity and a hatred of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of context is what this show is all about,'' said Nancy
Netzer, director of the McMullen Museum of Art at Boston College.
Netzer is one of five Boston College professors who organized the
show ``Fragmented Devotion: Medieval Objects From the Schnutgen
Museum in Cologne,'' which opened at the McMullen Museum earlier
this month and is there through May 22. ``We are trying to
demonstrate that an artwork has no single meaning, that meaning is
always dependent on context.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fragmented Devotion'' includes 62 objects of medieval
religious art drawn from the collection of Alexander Schnutgen, a
Cologne priest who in 1906 donated his extensive collection of late
medieval Christian art to the museum that bears his name. The
exhibition is intended to compel the viewer to consider how an
object's original meaning can be altered _ and in some cases
dangerously subverted _ by the manner in which it is displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Netzer and her colleagues have recomposed three distinct
historical moments in the lives of these objects: ``The Middle
Ages,'' in which crucifixes, chalices, chasubles, monstrances and
reliquaries are deployed in settings resembling public and private
medieval devotional spaces; ``Fragments of Fragments,'' a stylized
reconstruction of late-19th-century collections, like Schnutgen's,
in which the same objects are displayed on crowded shelves and
bookcases and classified according to function or theme; and
``Museum Installation: The 1930s,'' a room that recreates the
abstract, art-historical exhibition style of Weimar Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The three historical contexts are visibly different. Yet in
keeping with the show's theme, each represents an age's attempt to
construct a spiritual or philosophical unity from a series of
disconnected historical fragments. The typical medieval devotional
space, where religious functions were celebrated, was animated with
images of far-flung saints and often with fragments of their
martyred bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Even the medieval Mass, the central ritual in the Roman Catholic
faith, was a ceremonial reweaving of certain fragmented elements in
the life of Jesus, most notably the Last Supper.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the medieval devotional scheme was not seen at the time
as being fragmented or reassembled. ``Medieval believers had a way
of looking at fragments and then deducing the entire saint,'' said
Virginia Reinburg, a professor of European religious history at
Boston College and one of the show's curators. ``They were aware
that these saints' bodies had been disturbed, and believed that
their holy power was now dispersed through these relics. Regarding
the Catholic Mass, it may indeed be a patchwork of biblical and
pre-Christian fragments. But when ordinary people went to Mass in
the middle ages, they saw that Mass as seamless.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, the social disorientation caused by
industrialization and war generated a widespread desire for
spiritual renewal in much of Europe. At the same time, the
destruction of ecclesiastical institutions following the Napoleonic
wars made the troves of medieval religious collections available to
individual collectors, casting them, in the words of Netzer, ``like
spores into the vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   Schnutgen began collecting after attending an auction of
religious paintings in 1867, when he realized that sacred art could
easily lose its religious value in a secular context. His motto was
``colligite fragmenta ne pereant'' _ collect these fragments so
they do not perish. For decades, he kept the objects in crowded
rooms at his Cologne residence at Margarthenkloster 7. Schnutgen
had no training in the history of art. His interest in the objects
was spiritual and nostalgic; these were his fragments, shored
against the ruins of his devotional world.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century section of the Boston College show does not
quite attain the clutter of Schnutgen's overburdened home. But it
does capture the spirit of longing _ and fear _ that propelled
Schnutgen and other collectors into their conservation quests. It
also captures the self-deception inherent in those clerics and
collectors who sought refuge from a bewildering industrialized
present in a romanticized vision of the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
   The identification with medieval forms as an expression of piety
was so widespread that in 1913 the archdiocese of Cologne mandated
that all new churches be built in the neo-Gothic style.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That Gothic is a predominant style in the architecture of many
colleges and universities _ including Boston College _ repeats the
equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both medieval and 19th-century faithful loved allegory,'' said
Patricia DeLeeuw, a medieval church historian at Boston College and
another curator of the show. ``But the medieval faithful truly
believed that the symbols and objects surrounding them were
representations of greater teachings. The 19th century strikes me
as more nostalgic and less real, as if they were trying to
allegorize themselves into a world that no longer existed.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1932, the Schnutgen collection was moved from the Museum of
Applied Arts in Cologne into the cloisters of the Church of St.
Heribert in Deutz, which is across the Rhine. Deutz is also the
community where most of Cologne's Jewish population took up
residence after they were expelled from Cologne in 1424.
</P>
<P>
   The juxtaposition, across five centuries, is somewhat ironic if,
as Netzer and her colleagues suggest, the 1930s Bauhaus style of
the Schnutgen collection helped legitimize the brutal bigotry of
the National Socialist regime.
</P>
<P>
   In Deutz, where the Schnutgen Museum currently resides, the
objects from the priest's collection were exhibited according to
20th-century museum canons. No longer were Schnutgen's fragments
perceived as portals into a world of spirit, or as the shattered
archaeology of a more pious, vanished world. Stripped of function,
mounted on pedestals, these sculptures, censers, portable altars
and rosary beads took on a new incarnation as things to be looked
at.
</P>
<P>
   The only devotional scheme the Bauhaus display supported was the
relatively new discipline of art history, which at the time strove
toward the charting of an orderly, triumphant evolution of style.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the complete erasure of context left these objects open to a
broader spectrum of interpretations, which were in turn open to
exploitation by forces including National Socialism. Statues like
``The Wild Man'' and the 15-inch marble ``Moses'' from the Cologne
Cathedral, both on display in the show's Bauhaus section, reminded
some of the suffering and spiritually restless inhabitants of
Weimar Germany that Christianity had been thrust upon them by Rome,
that this faith _ this womanizing, passive, defeatist faith, as
they saw it _ had had its origins in Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   These sentiments, and others, may have funneled the German
desire for spiritual leadership into the adoration of a belligerent
despot, and distorted the Germans' need for transcendence into a
national obsession with death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still asking ourselves what was so weak in
Christianity,'' said the Rev. James Bernauer, another curator of
``Fragmented Devotion.'' A professor of philosophy at Boston
College and a Jesuit priest, Bernauer has written widely on the
Holocaust. ``How did it get so deflected into this militaristic
Christianity?'' he went on. ``There is a liturgical, ritual
dimension to National Socialism, a cloying type of spiritual energy
that people evidently needed in their lives. But even so, we don't
understand why this Nazi thing didn't seem stranger than it did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Third Reich clearly understood the incipient power of
fragments, and was masterly in manipulating them. In ``Inside the
Third Reich,'' Albert Speer, Hitler's architect, recalled how he
often presented Hitler with sketches of their never-built Berlin as
it might look to future generations when it lay in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   He writes that he decided to avoid using reinforced concrete in
Reich buildings in order not to leave a rusty legacy of twisted
metal bars. It was the ultimate perversion of meaning, a fragmented
deception conceived for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fragmented Devotion'' hardly implies that the symbolic looting
of Schnutgen's collection led directly to the Holocaust. The show
instead illustrates the process of linguistic abuse, in which
objects are first dismembered, then disenfranchised and then used
to stimulate an atavistic reflex that can compel a people in myriad
directions, including that of collective folly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
