<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5222 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-EISEMAN-ARCH-2TAKES-$     02-22 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EISEMAN-ARCH-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON STATEN ISLAND, THE NEW MEDIA ARE THE MESSAGE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter Eisenman's design for the Staten Island
Institute of Arts and Sciences brings into focus a theme that has
preoccupied him in recent years: the relationship between the
history of places and the history of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The $65 million project, which partly straddles the St. George
terminal of the Staten Island ferry, is a favorite of the borough
president, Guy V. Molinari. The building will house a new branch of
the Staten Island Institute, called the Center for Electronic
Culture, and will feature displays on the new media that are
helping to bring a global culture into being.
</P>
<P>
   Situated near the mouth of New York Harbor, the center will
honor a city that began to expand the circulation of Western ideas
more than three centuries ago. It offers a microcosmic version of
the global forces that are reshaping the contemporary urban
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Many museums today use advanced media technology in the
presentation of shows, the creation of Web sites, the expansion of
programs outside the museum's stone and mortar walls. At the Center
for Electronic Culture, these new media become the message.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the center include these exciting upgrades: an
Infohall, described as an electronic town square, with games,
projections and other media attractions; a museum, featuring five
long, serpentine galleries with interpretative displays, along with
a library, bookstore and cafeteria, and an Industrial Documentary
Center, with research stations for new developments in high-tech
communications.
</P>
<P>
   Now, check out these deflating downgrades: our central cities
and their architecture, an ancient communications medium that will
remain with us so long as people don't tire of ruins. There's no
longer any doubt that cities, buildings and interiors are being
rapidly affected by new media.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Castels, the urban theorist, has charted what he calls
the space of flows, the global network through which information
and money are transmitted in ever-shifting patterns without regard
for traditional boundaries of city, state and nation. Tourism is
the social equivalent of this electronic space. The tourist
attraction is one of its architectural devices. The Center for
Electronic Culture will be a new attraction for a city that
increasingly relies on tourism to shore up its economic base.
Eisenman's design gives the space of flows an architectural shape.
</P>
<P>
   The center is integrated with the ferry terminal building and
the transportation systems that converge there: boats, trains,
buses, cars as well as the parking lots, roads, platforms and piers
that serve them. The center's most conspicuous form is a large
rotunda, made of intersecting, twisted, tapering oblongs, which
rises 44 feet above ground level.
</P>
<P>
   The curving shapes recall the sculptures of Clement Meadmore,
while the building skin, slit with openings for skylights, will
remind some viewers of the steel and concrete roof designed by Eero
Saarinen for his Trans World Airlines terminal at Kennedy Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Saarinen or Meadmore, however, Eisenman asserts that he
arrives at his forms by a systematic design process. The process
starts by draping a two-dimensional grid over the site. The grid
assumes the contour of the site's topography. It is then
superimposed with shapes derived from the transportation systems:
ferry lanes, train platforms, bus ramps and so on. These shapes are
extended into three dimensions and then packed with the building's
program: galleries, library, cafeteria, offices and anything else
that fits.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt there's a certain amount of gimmickry, not to say
hocus-pocus, involved in this process. The point is that, once
again, Eisenman has convinced himself of the logical basis for his
forms. They are not to be seen as willful, Expressionist shapes but
as emanations of a site, its natural topography and its patterns of
social use, frozen in architectural form.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the design bears no resemblance to contextualism, in
the customary sense of the term. Unlike the 1992 design by Venturi,
Scott Brown for the Manhattan terminal of the Staten Island ferry,
for example, Eisenman's plan does not mimic the surfaces of
adjacent or prior structures. Rather, it links the specifics of its
physical location to the larger grid of Western ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenman has been using this design method at least since 1982,
when he designed the Wexner Center for Art in Columbus, Ohio. In
that project, the particulars of place are represented on an
organizing grid derived from the city's street system and the
partial reconstruction of an old armory building that had once
occupied the site.
</P>
<P>
   The history of ideas is represented by the expansion of the grid
into an abstract, three-dimensional form of white painted steel.
This form, which resembles a scaffold, contains the Wexner's
gallery spaces. It signifies the classic framework of Cartesian
thought.
</P>
<P>
   The scaffold also brings to mind the roughly contemporaneous
work by Sol Lewitt and is thus a clear indication of the source for
Eisenman's topographical method of design. Like Lewitt, Eisenman is
a Conceptual artist, but one who happens to work in the
architectural field.
</P>
<P>
   Like Frank Gehry, who has derived inspiration from Robert
Rauschenberg, Ellsworth Kelly and other artists, Eisenman has drawn
architecture into a wider frame of cultural reference. This is a
natural move for architects of cultural institutions, and one that
should be welcomed by those who esteem Beaux Arts edifices for
incorporating painting and sculpture into their designs. In this
sense, Eisenman's Staten Island project must be seen as a
legitimate heir to the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the New York
Public Library and other landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since Eisenman is our foremost anti-Classicist, this line of
descent is not easily apparent. Nor is Eisenman's work routinely
discussed in the context of Conceptual Art. This is partly a result
of the gap that divides architecture from other art forms, and
partly a result of the modern attachment to originality.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenman himself is hardly innocent of this attachment. He has
always wanted it both ways. He likes to startle viewers with novel
forms and with claims that his projects are helping to undermine
the grand Western tradition. At the same time, he is possessed by a
deeply conservative craving to belong to that tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he's entitled to have it both ways. Even so, the
contradiction needs to be clarified. Eisenman is what used to be
called a New York Intellectual. But he's working at a time when
that species has become nearly extinct. There is, for now, no
community of informed opinion to give his work either support or
ctive resistance.
</P>
<P>
   If there were such a community, the Conceptual roots of
Eisenman's architecture would be less obscure, and his forms would
appear less startling. He would not have been branded a theorist
nor would the audience for his work been largely confined to
academia. In fact, the principal interest of importing
Conceptualism into architecture lies with the potential to extend
that movement's intellectual framework beyond the art world
cloister into the larger public realm.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenman is not the only contemporary architect who draws on or
parallels Conceptual themes. A significant strain of contemporary
architecture comes out of what Harold Rosenberg called the
dematerialization of the art object. John Hejduk, Diller and
Scofidio, Bernard Tschumi, Lebbeus Woods, Neil Denari and others
have created memorable projects relying on conventional building
materials. The emerging generation of computer-based architects are
Conceptualists, whether they're aware of it or not.
</P>
<P>
   This work stands in a critical relationship to the conventions
of mainstream practice, but it also reveals the extent to which
even traditional architecture is conceptually based. Architects
produce ideas, plans, blueprints _ concepts _ that, like Lewitt
wall paintings, will be realized by others: executive architects,
space planners, construction companies and such.
</P>
<P>
   The completed building, in turn, takes on an expanded life in
the mediated form of published drawings, photographs and other
images (like those published here). At both ends, that is to say,
architecture is a medium of consciousness. It can transform our
inner as well as our outer landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Conceptual art is thus an ideal form for reckoning with the
pressures of globalization. The space of flows does not reside
solely in software, streams of electrons, and pixels on a screen.
It also exists in the realm of information and ideas. It lives,
that is to say, in the head. Architecture like Eisenman's
capitalizes on information as the international currency of the
global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The design vocabulary of the Staten Island project _ the grid,
the diagrammatic abstraction _ points to another consequence of
globalization: our increasing awareness of the distinctiveness of
Western thought. In the emerging global culture, the West has begun
to look at itself with an anthropologist's eye.
</P>
<P>
   We walk down streets full of buildings, advertisements, fashions
and window displays designed to appeal to normal tastes, and say to
ourselves: ``How weird! Somebody thought of that.'' Seen in this
way, Eisenman's Staten Island design does not seem weird at all.
Mediating between places and ideas is a natural, even an essential
function for architecture to take on in changing times.
</P>
<P>
   New York intellectual life was created by immigrants, and the
global network made possible by tourism and the media has gone far
toward compensating for its erosion. As an enduring cultural
center, New York deserves a place where this history can be told.
Thanks to the Staten Island Institute, we will have one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
