u s BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-DELAHOYA     02-22 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-DELAHOYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD ATTEMPTS TO DIM DE LA HOYA'S SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Felix Trinidad and Oscar De La Hoya were in Manhattan
Tuesday, each doing his own thing. The proximity was not by
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad was working out at the Church Street Gym trying to drum
up attention for his bout in Las Vegas on March 3 against David
Reid, the World Boxing Association superwelterweight champion.
Trinidad was hoping his presence would take a little attention away
from De La Hoya, who fights Derrell Coley on Saturday night at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad's presence only begged the question of why he was
fighting Reid instead of setting up a rematch against De La Hoya,
whom he defeated in a controversial decision Sept. 18 in Las Vegas
to win the World Boxing Council welterweight title.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was simple and readily available from the two people
who should know: Trinidad's promoter, Don King, and De La Hoya's
promoter, Bob Arum. King was with his man at the Church Street Gym,
while Arum was holding court with reporters at The Friars Club for
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   King and Arum, rivals who have feuded for years, took turns
trying to kill each other's coming fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``His fight is a nothing fight,'' King said of the De La
Hoya-Coley match. ``It doesn't segue into anything. He has nothing
after this. The fight Tito is fighting is a something fight. He's
fighting a world champion with a gold medal. There's no upside for
De La Hoya. The guy he's fighting is a bum.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum threw cold water on Trinidad-Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not chortling,'' Arum said. ``It's a lot like a guy who
breaks up with a woman and rushes into another affair without
thinking. It generally ends up a big disaster. King's losses in
this fight will be the biggest losses in the history of boxing.
He's going to lose between $6 million to $7 million.''
</P>
<P>
   King said if he loses money, he loses money. He said he would
need about 400,000 pay-per-view buys on Showtime Event Television
to break even.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the fight, and I'm going on with it,'' King said.
``Money is incidental to me in this. When we knock out Oscar, I'll
make up for it.''
</P>
<P>
   King has presented a rematch deal to Arum that he thinks will
work. King's proposal has De La Hoya and Trinidad each making $20
million and fighting at a catch weight, possibly 150 pounds (3
pounds over the welterweight limit). King said that under his plan,
De La Hoya could keep the WBC welterweight championship belt win or
lose. Trinidad doesn't want to have to fight at welterweight again,
because he is having trouble making the weight.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said they talked about the deal two weeks ago and it seems
workable. He said if they could reach an agreement, the fighters
could be in the ring for a rematch on June 17. That is the date
that De La Hoya had reserved for Sugar Shane Mosley, but Arum
hasn't been able to reach an agreement with Jack Mosley, the
fighter's father, manager and trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said he has not discussed King's proposal with De La Hoya,
who has been concentrating on the Coley fight. He said he would
talk to him about it once De La Hoya gets past Coley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that the only issue is the weight and I can't
speak to that,'' Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The economic issues have all been addressed. I said
we wanted the fight at Mandalay Bay, because we're loyal to them.
King wanted the fight at Caesars. Dr. Ghanem said the fight would
be at Caesars and a third fight would be at Mandalay Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elias Ghanem is the chairman of the Nevada State Athletic
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing both King and Arum readily agreed on is that
Trinidad and De La Hoya have to win their respective coming bouts
to keep this shaky rematch deal from falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that if this guy doesn't fight Trinidad, then he is
truly Chicken De La Hoya, and no one should support him,'' King
said.
</P>
<P>
   King Clears the Air
</P>
<P>
   Don King said he doesn't understand how the FBI can be chasing
him for making payoffs to the International Boxing Federation while
other promoters and managers have admitted to federal authorities
that they made bribes to advance their fighters in the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got about five or six confessors,'' King said. ``How do
they look past the confessors and look for the ghost?''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had ever paid a bribe to the IBF to have one of
his fighters ranked, King said: ``No. No. No. No. No. No.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of making financial contributions to the various boxing
sanctioning organizations, King said he treats them as he treats
the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get goods and services without paying your taxes,''
King said. ``I don't look for tax loopholes. I pay what I owe. I
paid $34 million in taxes, and I sent out a release to tell
everyone that I had paid my taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum was one of the people who gave affidavits to the FBI
detailing what he knew about bribes to the IBF for rankings. Arum
said he has never made a payoff to any sanctioning organization for
a ranking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
