<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN-1STLEDE     02-22 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN-1STLEDE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: 1ST LEDE WRITETHRU
 &HT;    
 &HT;    McCain proves ignoring center can be risky
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the past decade, presidential politics has pivoted
around the man in the middle, and Tuesday's results from Michigan
and Arizona confirm that the pattern is being repeated this year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, and with more modest results in 1996, the man in the
middle was Ross Perot, with his wry denunciations of both the
Democrats and the Republicans. Perot's Reform Party has become a
sideshow, but the political urge for a candidate who avoids the
extremes of either party remains strong enough for the century to
begin with a professional wrestler in the Minnesota governor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The wrinkle this year has been that the man in the middle also
happens to be running for the Republican Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   By ``middle,'' incidentally, we're not necessarily talking about
people who are moderate on every issue, but those who inhabit the
territory between the parties: independents, those disgruntled with
their parties and those who just don't vote.
</P>
<P>
   Without an appeal to those who fit that category _ and a healthy
turnout from those who consider themselves Democrats, as well _
Arizona Sen. John McCain would not have been able to crawl back in
the ring as he did Tuesday after the thumping he took in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   These outsiders have caused some discomfort within the
Republican Party, but in many cases the complaints are coming from
those who were outsiders themselves when Pat Robertson, one of
McCain's most outspoken foes this year, was trying to elbow his way
into the party in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   With wins in his home state and in Michigan, the man in the
middle is back in the thick of the race. But what does that mean,
exactly, in terms of his realistic chances to win his party's
nomination?
</P>
<P>
   It would be something if McCain and Texas Gov. George W. Bush
could go on swapping victories in spotlight states, as they have
for the past month. It's hard to remember two candidates exchanging
volleys as these two have, with Bush's Iowa caucuses win, McCain's
stunner in New Hampshire, Bush's strong response in South Carolina
and McCain's rebound Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the March 7 voting in 13 states will force McCain to make
some strategic choices, hoping to find the states that could be the
tinder to keep his insurgency alive.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has to start making tough choices as well. He still has a
money advantage over McCain, but he can't spend full-bore in
California, New York, Ohio and Georgia as he has in New Hampshire
and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bush-friendly states of Texas and Florida coming up the
following week, it still is hard to imagine a scenario in which
McCain pulls off his Republican insurgency, although Tuesday's
outcome could bring more money and endorsements his way.
</P>
<P>
   That tension between a candidate on a hot streak and a long-shot
chance at nomination makes it inevitable there should be talk of
McCain taking his crusade outside the party, whether McCain at this
stage encourages it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore has had to run to his left to secure the Democratic
nomination, and Bush has had to run to his right to nail down the
Republican nomination,'' mused GOP pollster Whit Ayres before
Tuesday's vote. ``You know at a certain point they're going to come
charging back to the center, but right now there's this huge
opening, right up the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   So long as the middle is attracted to this Republican
competition, incidentally, there will be record turnout in GOP
primaries as there was in Michigan and South Carolina. Which, while
it may not be to the liking of some Republicans, is not a bad thing
for their party.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
