<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5228 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JARMUSCH-FILMS-ART-2T     02-22 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JARMUSCH-FILMS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARMUSCH STILL FILLS THE ROLE OF FAVORITE OUTSIDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27)  
 (af)  
 By LAURA WINTERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One day a few weeks ago, the filmmaker Jim Jarmusch
was hunkered down in a corner of the Pink Pony, a favorite hangout
near his Lower East Side home, trying to have a quiet conversation.
But a steady flow of colleagues and well-wishers kept wandering by
_ drawn, it seemed, by his signature silver hair, as well as by his
laid-back manner.
</P>
<P>
   After the umpteenth interruption, Jarmusch smiled wryly. ``It's
still odd to me if somebody on the street knows who I am,'' he
said. ``I'm not interested in the whole celebrity cult thing. Is it
better to be semi-known or semi-unknown?''
</P>
<P>
   Jarmusch, 47, personifies this riddle better than almost any
other American director today. An intensely private man, he became
a downtown celebrity with his second movie, the art house hit
``Stranger Than Paradise'' (1984). With its throwaway but graceful
style and no-budget economy, ``Stranger'' helped pioneer the
American independent film movement. ``When Jim hit with that film,
he forged the way for all of us,'' says Spike Lee, who attended
film school with him at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jarmusch is still an emblem for many younger filmmakers,
his path after ``Stranger Than Paradise'' has not always been easy.
His last few films have drawn only modest audiences in the United
States _ though abroad they draw crowds and his laconic humor is
admired as deeply American.
</P>
<P>
   An industry outsider, he has become a world-cinema insider, with
a loyal band of A-list collaborators _ ``a strange, international
biker club,'' says his friend, the musician Tom Waits. His
reputation has drawn Hollywood stars like Winona Ryder, Johnny Depp
and now Forest Whitaker, who stars in Mr. Jarmusch's new film,
``Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ghost Dog,'' which opens on Friday, is Jarmusch's first
non-documentary in four years. Like much of his work, it weaves
together strikingly disparate elements: he calls it a ``gangster
samurai hip-hop eastern western.'' And yet, despite its oddness,
``Ghost Dog'' has a wild-card commercial potential _ both because
of its star, Whitaker, and because of the film's highly bankable
soundtrack, created by the hip-hop master the RZA, of the Wu-Tang
Clan.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows an urban loner named Ghost Dog, played by
Whitaker, who makes his living as a Mafia hitman. A modern-day
samurai, he follows the precepts of the ``Hagakure,'' the
early-18th-century Japanese warrior codebook. Every samurai swears
undying loyalty to a master, and Ghost Dog's master is Louie (John
Tormey), a small-time mobster who once saved Ghost Dog's life.
</P>
<P>
   When one of Ghost Dog's missions goes awry, Louie's own bosses,
a comical bunch of aging mafiosi, decide that the lone gunman has
to be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Jarmusch began writing the film, he says, with the idea of ``a
character who was a likable killer.'' He tends to write with
particular actors in mind, and in this case he was thinking about
Whitaker: ``Forest is very gentle and soulful,'' he says, ``but
there's a dark side to his presence which I haven't seen used very
often. I wanted to make a character who had that contradiction.''
</P>
<P>
   When the filmmaker Sara Driver (``When Pigs Fly''), Jarmusch's
longtime girlfriend, gave him the ``Hagakure,'' the book became
``Ghost Dog's'' spiritual well. Jarmusch has aphorisms from the
``Hagakure'' written out onscreen _ solemn lines like, ``The end is
important in all things.'' But the film has his signature zany
humor as well, in his portrait of America as a place of crossed
cultural wires. The mafiosi can't afford to meet in an Italian
restaurant, so they hold court in a fast-food Chinese joint. ``Jim
likes to put things together that might explode,'' says Waits. ``He
may be a white-haired beatnik from Ohio, but he knows how to rub
two sticks together.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker, whose implacable presence anchors the film, has long
been interested in Eastern philosophy and spent many hours
discussing his character with Jarmusch. ``It was one of the most
collaborative experiences I've had with a filmmaker,'' Whitaker
said. ``Jim really pays respect to his inspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Jarmusch decided to make ``Ghost Dog'' an outright
homage to certain gangster classics. The film is punctuated with
direct references to films like Jean-Pierre Melville's ``Samourai''
and Seijun Suzuki's ``Branded to Kill.'' But Jarmusch pays homage
as well to whole cultures that he admires. ``I didn't cast Forest
because he was black,'' Jarmusch said, ``but having a black
character created a lot of nuances that I wanted in the story. I
wanted hip-hop culture to be in the film.''
</P>
<P>
   The director, who used to play in a downtown band called the
Del-Byzanteens, was struck by the Wu-Tang Clan's synthesis of
African-American and Asian motifs. So he tracked down the RZA,
their elusive leader, to do ``Ghost Dog's'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three weeks later I get a call,'' he recounts. ``And RZA says,
`Meet me in a blacked-out van at 3 a.m. on 50th Street and
Broadway.' I go there and he gives me a tape and says, `Yo, check
this stuff.' I ask if he has any directions for me and he says:
`Nah. This is hip-hop style! Try it in the film, juice pieces
together.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the film's playfulness, however, lies Ghost Dog's pained
awareness that his code of honor is vanishing in the modern world.
This melancholy comes directly from Jarmusch. ``I've tried from the
beginning to have a code,'' he says, ``but you learn real fast in
the film business that that's a good way to get eaten alive.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He grew up far from the film business, in Akron, Ohio, where his
father worked for B.F. Goodrich. After attending Northwestern
University for one year, Jarmusch transferred to Columbia. When he
spent a semester in Paris, he discovered the Cinematheque and the
films of Yasujiro Ozu, Carl Dreyer and Robert Bresson.
</P>
<P>
   Returning home, he entered film school at NYU and became the
assistant to the filmmaker Nicholas Ray, who in turn introduced him
to Wim Wenders.
</P>
<P>
   When Jarmusch finished his student film, ``Permanent Vacation,''
Wenders gave him some leftover film stock, which Jarmusch used for
part of ``Stranger Than Paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of two investors, Jarmusch completed the film, a
deadpan, black and white feature about three drifters on an
impromptu road trip. It went to the Cannes International Film
Festival in 1984 and stunned Jarmusch by winning the Camera d'Or
for best first feature. ``We were at Cannes, sleeping on the floor,
and then the water got cut off,'' he remembers. ``When I had to do
a television interview, I shaved using leftover tea water.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Stranger'' was released later that year, Jarmusch saw
himself hailed, at 31, as the creator of a new film style. The
film's influence extends even to directors today like Kevin Smith,
who directed ``Clerks'' and ``Dogma.'' ``Seeing `Stranger Than
Paradise' is an empowering experience,'' said Smith. ``Here was a
movie that they made for a hundred, two hundred grand, and suddenly
the power was in the hands of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarmusch found all the attention rather overwhelming. But at
another film festival, he met a young Italian actor named Roberto
Benigni. He asked Benigni to star with Waits and John Lurie in his
next movie, in which they would play three innocents who escape
from a Louisiana jail.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Benigni spoke no English. During the shooting of
``Down by Law,'' Jarmusch and Lurie patiently taught him their own
version of the language. ``I learned that a cup was a `clamp,''' .
Benigni said, laughing, on the telephone from Rome, ``and that `to
urinate' was `to flame.' The entire set used these words.''
</P>
<P>
   Benigni credits Jarmusch for having introduced him to America.
``I love really Jim's way to live and to direct actors,'' he says.
``He let me improvise during rehearsal time and then left me an
open door.'' He adds, mysteriously, ``He is a real poet, a cross
between brains and beauty _ between Orson Welles and Brigitte
Bardot.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarmusch's fascination with the coexistence of cultures
permeated his two next films, ``Mystery Train'' (1989) and ``Night
on Earth'' (1992). ``Mystery Train'' is set in a seedy but
evocative Memphis, while ``Night on Earth'' was shot nocturnally in
five cities around the world. Rather than accept Hollywood
production money, Jarmusch began at this point to seek foreign
financing. ``I've been stubborn, but I've kept artistic control
over my films,'' he said. ``I see them through every step of the
process, even owning the negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   This involvement explains the occasionally long stretches
between films. With ``Dead Man,'' his most ambitious project, he
shot a hallucinatory black-and-white period Western with Johnny
Depp as a fugitive befriended by a Native American.
</P>
<P>
   The film was panned by critics when it was released in 1996, but
it has recently undergone a startling renaissance, with many
end-of-century wrap-ups (including a current series at the Film
Society of Lincoln Center) naming it one of the best films of the
1990s. Jarmusch is typically modest about this. ``If it goes
through the culture in some minor way, I'd be glad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Ghost Dog,'' he shot a concert film/documentary of his
friend Neil Young and his band, Crazy Horse, called, simply, ``Year
of the Horse.'' And he has appeared in cameos in some of his
friends' films, including Billy Bob Thornton's ``Sling Blade'' and
Wayne Wang and Paul Auster's ``Blue in the Face.''
</P>
<P>
   The acting is a lark for him, whereas his own films are deeply
personal. The sympathy for the outsider which has inspired all of
his work is especially clear in ``Dead Man'' and ``Ghost Dog.'' ``A
bunch of old white men have run things so far,'' he said. ``That's
why I've always been interested in people who don't fit in. I have
friends who are in prison, off the grid, living on reservations. I
learn more from them, somehow, and I respect them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many people know that before making his name as a filmmaker,
Jarmusch worked as a factory welder, a hydraulic drill-gun
operator, a moving man and a process server for Legal Aid. He would
be the first to admit that the people he encountered in these
professions would not, probably, go to see his films.
</P>
<P>
   But his far-flung experiences have shaped his concerns as a
filmmaker, just as they have shaped his desire to reach an
audience, whether it be big or small. ``It's very important to me
that the audience completes the electric current, because otherwise
a film is just a dark lamp sitting in a corner,'' he said. ``I'm
not trying to teach a lesson to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to make a world which they can enter and
observe, bringing with them whatever has shaped their own lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
