<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0477 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-HOUSE-ARREST-THEATER-     02-22 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-ARREST-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MS. SMITH, ALONE AGAIN, IS GOING TO WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 27)  
 (af)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   She tried not to get up there onstage and do it herself. For the
first time since she became famous for recreating _ to the last
gesture and vocal tic _ dozens of real-life individuals based on
her actual conversations with them, Anna Deavere Smith decided not
to perform her own work. Instead, she cast actors in ``House
Arrest,'' her latest foray into the nation's psyche, this time
focusing on the role of the American presidency, from Thomas
Jefferson to Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   When the play was performed in Washington in 1997 and then in
Los Angeles last spring, critics called it overlong and said they
missed Smith's presence onstage. Then George C. Wolfe, the producer
of the Joseph Papp Public Theater, suggested to Smith that if she
brought the show to New York, she should do it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe had directed Smith's acclaimed 1994 play about the Rodney
King riots, ``Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992,'' and he was one of the
people she interviewed for her ``Fires in the Mirror'' in 1992,
about the Crown Heights disturbances in Brooklyn the previous year.
And so, on March 27, under the direction of Jo Bonney, ``House
Arrest'' is scheduled to open at the Public Theater with just Smith
onstage, flying solo again.
</P>
<P>
   The journey would seem to involve a message: that Smith, 49, was
meant to perform her own work, whether she wants to or not, and
that whatever particular blend of inquisitiveness and insight she
brings to the process of drawing people out in interviews is
ultimately essential to bringing those people to life onstage.
</P>
<P>
   The success of Smith's last two projects would indicate as much.
``Fires in the Mirror'' told the story of the racial flare-up in
Crown Heights that followed the death of a 7-year-old black boy,
Gavin Cato, and the subsequent killing of Yankel Rosenbaum, a
Hasidic scholar. Alone onstage in a white shirt and black pants,
Smith inhabited nearly 30 characters _ from a rabbi to a rapper _
with monologues culled from her interviews. In The New York Times,
Frank Rich called the play ``quite simply the most compelling and
sophisticated view of urban racial and class conflict, up to date
to this week, that one could hope to encounter in a swift 90
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   And of ``Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992,'' which explored the
aftermath of that city's riots following the first Rodney King
verdict, David Richards wrote in The New York Times, ``One person
at a time, one idea at a time, one temperament at a time, she
builds up a rich, panoramic canvas of a national trauma.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe describes Smith's approach as singular. ``She has crafted
this extraordinary technique _ art form _ of both embodying a
person and illuminating their language,'' he said. Of the previous
productions of ``House Arrest,'' Wolfe said, ``I saw a lot of
talented actors playing the roles, and they were acting the roles
in a way that you were witnessing the emotion instead of in a way
that the language was swirling up and popping around you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Davidson, the artistic director of the Mark Taper Forum
in Los Angeles, where ``House Arrest'' was done last spring,
suggested that the decision to use actors had been a worthwhile
experiment, even though it proved less effective than a solo show
would have been. ``I think it was a necessary thing for this artist
to do this,'' he said. ``She didn't want to repeat herself.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Davidson continued, the dramatic effect of Smith onstage is
almost impossible for others to approximate. ``Because of her
particular interviewing technique, the audience becomes Anna _ they
sit in for her because Anna is talking to them as if she were
asking the questions,'' he said. ``She creates a level of reality.
When you have actors doing it, it removes it one more step. They
were second generation and it lost something.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, listening to Smith talk about reaching this point _
poring through dossiers of material she gathered with the help of
her research associates to prepare for interviews with the former
presidents Jimmy Carter and George Bush, as well as historians,
journalists and government aides; meeting face to face with
well-known figures like the historian Studs Terkel and the
political columnist David Broder; delving into past scandals, from
Thomas Jefferson's affair with Sally Hemings to Bill Clinton's with
Monica Lewinsky; winding up with 10,000 tapes to cull from _ it is
hard to imagine anyone else being able to convey the color and
cadence of Smith's 425 interviews as well as the intense woman who
conducted them.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the other side of an interview in a bare dressing
room at the Public on a break from rehearsal on a recent Saturday
afternoon, Smith played down the decision to do the show solo as
little more than a matter of logistics, as if she herself had given
it hardly any thought. Wolfe, she noted, simply said it seemed like
a good idea, and she trusts his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said she enjoyed seeing actors perform her material
and that working with them had forced her to deconstruct what she
does instinctively. ``Is that good?'' she asked. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether being onstage again felt like a step back,
she said: ``How can it ever be a step back to be in front of people
willing to come to you with an open ear? I love it. I love the
audience. So how could I call that a step back? That wouldn't be
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   But while she had little to say about her performance, she
clearly warmed to the topic of her process. In 1995, Smith, a
tenured drama professor at Stanford University, began to immerse
herself in the ways of Washington _ visiting the White House,
flying on Air Force One, meeting with government officials,
scholars, pundits.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was initially intrigued by the intersection of
politics and the press, and grew increasingly fascinated by whether
the constant photo opportunities and other media events leave the
president with any time to actually run the country.
</P>
<P>
   What she generally tries to do in interviews, she said, is to
get people off their center, to get them to a ``state of abandon,''
when their words transcend mere information and ``sing.'' She
described the phrases she was looking for as ``bouncy ...
utterances that just don't make it all the way across the page.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This kind of spontaneity, Smith said, was harder to come by in
Washington power circles known more for caution than candor. ``In
Washington,'' Ms. Smith said, ``everybody rephrased my questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheer organization of the project was daunting. Whereas
``Fires in the Mirror'' and ``Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992'' _ which
was recently made into a film that had its premiere at the Sundance
Film Festival _ had clear beginnings, middles and ends, ``House
Arrest'' explores a subject, not an incident. And the scope of the
topic made it especially difficult to narrow to some kind of
narrative.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Smith pointed out, she wrote both of her previous
works in the aftermath of events. Here, events kept changing under
her, prompting constant revisions. ``In this case, there was no
aftermath,'' she said. ``The project became an amazing moving
target. I wrote more drafts of this than I have of anything ever.''
As she was bringing one version to Federal Express, for example,
Smith said, there was a debate going on in Congress about whether
to release the Starr Report.
</P>
<P>
   While it would seem frustrating to be forced to constantly
adjust to breaking news _ Smith said she had to cancel scheduled
productions in Chicago and Seattle because the show was overtaken
by events _ she instead called the process of trying to capture
history even as it was being made ``a magnificent opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said she did not relish rewriting. ``I don't like
seclusion,'' she said. ``But that's a necessary thing that one must
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she interviewed President Clinton on two occasions
before the Lewinsky scandal broke _ once off the record and once
on. She did not interview him afterward. ``For me, this whole
project closed when he was acquitted in the Senate,'' she said. ``I
wouldn't have approached him when that was going on. I wouldn't
have wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite witnessing the president's obvious foibles, and
confronting the inevitable humanness of those in power, Smith said
she surprised herself by coming away impressed by the people who
govern. ``In the end, I have more awe than I had thought I would,''
she said. ``As a child of the '60s, I was never interested in the
establishment. We were all about trying to bring the thing down.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she had come to believe while working on the play
that pivotal events like the Vietnam War, the women's movement and
the death of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. have ``bred a very
dangerous cynicism, an overinfatuation with the shadow side, the
darker side of individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   At one of her post-show discussions, Smith recalled, a man in
the audience stood up and said he thought the next century was
going to be about putting the shadow and the light together. ``That
was one of the more inspiring things I've heard,'' she said. ``I
want to be part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The pre-Monica version of ``House Arrest'' opened at the Arena
Stage in Washington in November 1997 and ran until January 1998. It
was when the later version opened at the Taper, Smith said, that
she and Davidson, the artistic director, decided to present the
play as a performance by actors, followed by a discussion with the
audience. ``I'm pleased we decided to do that,'' she added. ``To
use theater as a way of framing the conversation that's already
going on in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also one performance at the American Repertory Theater
in Cambridge, Mass., in the summer of 1998, as part of Smith's
Institute on the Arts and Civic Dialogue, now in its third and
final year. The summer theater institute at Harvard University _
which aims to strengthen the role of the arts in civic discourse _
was started with a grant from the Ford Foundation and is sponsored
by the W.E.B. Du Bois Institute and the American Repertory Theater.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Smith has compiled a book version of the project,
scheduled to be published by Random House this fall, called ``Talk
to Me.''
</P>
<P>
   As to which of her many characters will make the final cut in
New York, Smith said the lineup will not be decided until opening
night because elements of the play will keep changing through the
previews, scheduled to begin on March 7. But she said there were a
few sure bets, including Franklin Delano Roosevelt's cook, Lizzie
McDuffie, Anita Hill, Ed Bradley and Arianna Huffington.
</P>
<P>
   How does she decide which people to include in the first place?
``I divide the interviews into parts that I think I can become,''
she said. ``And I create these stories.'' Beyond that, Smith said,
it was difficult to put her criteria into words. ``It's what's
pushing the narrative forward,'' she ventured. ``It's who I can do,
it's who speaks in a way that gets right to your soul, it's who I
remember.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
