<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-POLL-METHOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE POLLS WERE CONDUCTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (With REPUBS-PRIMARIES and ARIZ-PRIMARY) 
 (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Election Day polls were based on questionnaires completed on
Tuesday by voters leaving voting stations throughout Michigan and
Arizona. The poll was conducted by Voter News Service, an
organization created by ABC News, CBS News, CNN, Fox News, NBC News
and The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan results are based on 1,358 Republican primary
voters in 45 randomly selected sites statewide. The Arizona results
are based on 1,671 Republican primary voters in 40 precincts.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, in 19 cases out of 20, the results from such polls
should differ by no more than plus or minus four percentage points
from what would have been obtained by seeking to interview all
primary voters who turned out on Tuesday in Michigan and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Results based on smaller subgroups have a larger potential
sampling error. In addition to sampling error, the practical
difficulties of conducting any survey of voter opinion on Election
Day, like the reluctance of some voters to take time to fill out a
questionnaire, may introduce other sources of error into the poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
