<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TELEVISION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE PERILS OF VOYEUR TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Feb. 23: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality-based television'' would seem to involve the very
thing that television entertainment was designed to relieve _
reality. So it should not be particularly surprising that the
marriage of two strangers on the Fox Network's ``Who Wants to Marry
a Multimillionaire'' last week foundered before the honeymoon was
over. After flying into the sunset, the bride and groom came home
separately, the groom facing questions about a police restraining
order against him issued nine years ago after a former girlfriend
complained that he had physically threatened her. Also, there are
some troubling concerns about a good chunk of his autobiography,
including worries that maybe he was not exactly a multimillionaire.
So how many of the 22 million viewers are really surprised that
after a few public minutes of courtship, this instant marriage
instantly hit a snag? Even Cinderella and Prince Charming had until
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   More distressing than the matrimonial flop is the news that the
television industry seems to adore this kind of entertainment.
Company lawyers may fear the potential for a multimillion-dollar
lawsuit in every participant's disappointment. But network
programmers see these shows as a ratings and revenue-producing
bonanza at a time when their less flamboyant productions are losing
ground to cable channels and the Internet. Fox canceled a rerun of
the marriage show Tuesday night and said it would not air another
version of ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire.'' However, Fox
executives, like others, have no plans to desert ``reality
programming'' as a lucrative genre.
</P>
<P>
   Already American networks are adapting European experiments. One
Dutch program, aptly called ``Big Brother,'' featured the
long-running, unscripted saga of 10 young people living in a house
wired with cameras that revealed everything that happened,
including sex and showers. The American version scheduled this
summer on CBS is not expected to reveal all. Another more troubling
CBS show called ``Survivor'' will take a group of contestants to
Borneo for a survival course. The group will vote to exclude one
person in each round until the survivor wins $1 million. A Swedish
version of this show resulted in the suicide of one dismissed
contestant.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Thompson, founder of the Center for the Study of Popular
Television at Syracuse University, fears that this live and
unpredictable peeping-Tom programming will continue because most
viewers are thrilled by risks and rewards offered to ordinary
people. Moreover, Fox and other outlets are trying to wean
themselves from violent programming, using reality-based television
as a substitute. ``For those of you who think this is the end of
the civilized world as we know it, I don't think we've seen
anything yet,'' Thompson predicts. If the appeal to good taste is
fruitless, perhaps the only hope for discerning viewers is the
zapper, the off button or the liability lawyers who may give the
networks pause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
