</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI DEFENDS THE POLICE AT ACADEMY GRADUATION
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-DIALLO-TRIAL, NY-DIALLO-SUMMARY) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, drawing repeated cheers
Tuesday from graduating police cadets and their families and
friends, called police officers ``civil rights workers'' who are
too often unfairly vilified and subject to prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's remarks, at Police Academy graduation ceremonies at
Madison Square Garden for 1,224 cadets, were made as closing
arguments were under way in an Albany courtroom in the trial of
four New York City police officers charged with murdering Amadou
Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani did not specifically mention the trial or Diallo, but
he told the cadets that he appreciated the difficult situation
officers sometimes faced that required sudden life-or-death
decisions, like whether to use their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get to make a tough decision, I get a lot of time to
think about it,'' the mayor said. ``I get a lot of memos and I have
a lot of meetings and I listen to a lot of advisers and even then I
don't always pick the right decision. You have to make more
important decisions in a split second without any advice.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the mayor said, he has always been careful to
avoid acting hastily when police officers are charged with
wrongdoing or unnecessary use of force.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are in an ambiguous but difficult circumstance and
when others are pointing the finger of blame on you, I give you the
benefit of doubt,'' the mayor said, drawing extended applause.
``The worst criminals that you arrest get the benefit of the doubt.
So it would seem to me that we could give to the men and women who
put their lives at risk for us, the men and women who make it
possible for our children to grow up with security and freedom, it
would seem to me we should at least give them the benefit of the
doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor insisted to reporters after the ceremony that he was
not alluding to the Diallo case. But several of the newly sworn
officers and their families said they had interpreted Giuliani's
remarks that way, and that they welcomed his words of support
during a time when the Police Department is under such intense
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just lets you know that you are not going to get in trouble
for doing your job,'' said Timothy Brown, 22, who is joining the
13th Precinct, which patrols the Gramercy Park area in Manhattan.
``That is extremely nice to know. You are out there trying to help
people. You don't want to get hurt for helping them.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Nasso, whose 26-year-old son, Dominick M. Nasso,
graduated Tuesday, added: ``I don't want my son sent out to the
wolves. It is good to know that the mayor is standing behind
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani noted that his remarks Tuesday echoed comments at
previous academy graduation ceremonies, including his assertion
that New York City police officers are civil rights workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are entrusted with protecting the most important civil
right we possess,'' the mayor said. ``Safety and security.''
</P>
<P>
   He also reiterated his previously stated belief that police
officers, like members of some of the city's religious and ethnic
minorities, are often the subject of prejudice. ``Prejudice against
race, prejudice against religion, prejudice against ethnic
background, prejudice against police officers,'' comes from the
same origin, the mayor said. ``It is the same kind of hateful,
vicious, irrational thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone at the ceremony was impressed with the mayor's
comments. One graduate, Pedro Diaz, 26, who is joining a Brooklyn
precinct, said it sounded like a campaign speech by the mayor, who
is a candidate for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, spent part of the ceremony simultaneously
listening to the speakers at Madison Square Garden and to a live
radio broadcast of the Diallo trial. Siegel called the mayor's
suggestion that police officers were civil rights workers and
subject to prejudice ``unreal'' and ``bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor is trying to equate criticism of police or even cop
bashing with racism and anti-Semitism,'' he said. ``It is clearly
not apples and apples. It is a distortion of history. Civil rights
workers generally are advocating for minority rights, usually for
groups who have been discriminated against. Police enforce
majoritarian mandates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
