<SLUG> BC-GLF-MATCH-PLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPONENT FOR WOODS IS ALSO HOT RIGHT NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ At the Andersen Consulting Match Play
Championship, your first day could also be your last.
</P>
<P>
   That is part of the intrigue surrounding this week's
single-elimination match play event, which begins Wednesday at La
Costa Resort &AMP; Spa, featuring an elite 64-player field that
includes Tiger Woods, David Duval, Colin Montgomerie, Davis Love
III, Ernie Els, Sergio Garcia, and Greg Norman. Only the top 64
players in the world ranking through Feb. 14 qualify for this
event, the first of four tournaments in this year's World Golf
Championship series.
</P>
<P>
   With a total purse of $5 million, including $1 million for the
winner, Jumbo Ozaki was the only player eligible for the tournament
who decided not to play. However, Wednesday's first-round action is
almost certain to produce some big name casualties. Last year, five
of the top 10 seeds were knocked out in the first round, including
Love, Els, Mark O'Meara, Montgomerie, and Lee Westwood. Woods
didn't make the Final Four either, and the championship match
featured two names that hardly anyone expected _ Jeff Maggert, the
24th seed, vs. Andrew Magee, who was seeded No. 50.
</P>
<P>
   Maggert defeated Magee in a splendid championship match,
chipping in for a birdie on the second hole of a playoff. It was an
unexpected ending to an unpredictable week. And as players prepared
for this week's action, they all had the same motto. Either be
ready to play, or be ready to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like playing one set of tennis, it's over very quickly,''
said Montgomerie, who will face Dennis Paulson in a first-round
match. ``Anybody is capable of beating anybody. I enjoy the
challenge of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods, a master at match play, faces a difficult challenge
on Wednesday against Michael Campbell of New Zealand, who has won
three of his last four starts. One of the world's hottest players,
Campbell has revitalized his career after suffering a serous injury
to his left wrist in 1995. As recently as June of 1998, Campbell
was a lowly 465th in the world ranking, and he was contemplating
quitting golf. However, Campbell rebuilt his swing and his
confidence, and after beating Woods at the Johnnie Walker Classic
in Taiwan last November, Campbell vowed that he would not be
intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to win, not to make up the field,'' said Campbell,
who qualified for the field on the strength of his recent surge.
``My confidence is very high and I'm very focused. If I keep doing
what I'm doing, tomorrow is going to be very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who advanced to last year's quarterfinals before losing
to Maggert, was looking forward to a rare opportunity to engage in
match play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely makes your excitement level go up a little
bit,'' said Woods. ``It's exciting because of the momentum swings
in a match. In stroke play, you can start looking ahead. In match
play, if you look in the future, you're going to find a ticket
counter somewhere and catch a flight home. `'
</P>
<P>
   While long hitters who make frequent birdies like Woods and Love
have an advantage in match play, it is also important not to give
away holes by making mistakes. Steadiness was the key to Maggert's
victory last year, as he constantly hit fairways and greens and
capitalized on opponent's mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my game is not going to allow myself to make
mistakes on this golf course,'' said Maggert. ``I feel like I can
compete against anybody. I don't get intimidated by who I'm
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The eventual champion must win six consecutive matches,
including a 36-hole match for the championship. That is a grueling
task for any player, so those who are in excellent physical
condition may have a slight advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The local forecast for the week is not good, and the course is
already wet from recent rain in the area. But everyone in the field
was eager to get started, looking forward to see which players
would last as the field was reduced to 32, then 16, then eight,
then four, then two, until a champion was crowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more upsets,'' said Maggert. ``I'm sure everyone
is pulling for Tiger to play on Sunday. It's good for the sponsors
and the television ratings. But there's a lot of good players out
here. Who knows? It could end up with a couple of nobodies like
myself again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
