<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MOLEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CALL DORMITORY ASSAULT SUSPECT A SHREWD PREDATOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J.)   (jw) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Internet as his guide and a knife in his pocket, a
drifter suspected in a series of sexual assaults made his way to
elite prep schools and leafy suburban campuses, sheltered places
rarely visited by violent crime, the authorities said. Sneaking
into dormitory rooms, they said, he placed the blade at the throats
of his young victims, all boys 12 to 16 years old, before abusing
them.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, the authorities said, the suspect,
Michael Lee Allen Jr., 24, terrorized five private schools in New
Jersey and New York, although they believe that he is responsible
for as many as a dozen other attacks.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, the Nassau County police on Long Island
arrested Allen, and within hours, law enforcement officials from
across the metropolitan region were interviewing him about
strikingly similar, unsolved attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we came in he just told us everything,'' said Sgt.
Rick Warshany of the Police Department in Hightstown, N.J., where
the most recent attack took place. ``He was all very matter of fact
about what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   An immigrant from Vietnam, the son of an American serviceman and
a Vietnamese woman, Allen has been described by detectives as a
drifter, a troubled man who went through a half dozen foster homes
after arriving in this country as an 8-year-old orphan. He survived
on odd jobs and stolen credit cards. At night he slept in his car
or at motels on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The police say Allen found the schools he targeted on the Web
using computers at a Kinko's copy shop in Garden City, N.Y., and at
public libraries. To help him find his way to his destination,
police said, he would download directions from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is shrewd, intelligent and a master of the Internet,''
said Detective Sgt. Albert Ciaccio of the Nassau County police.
</P>
<P>
   Ciaccio said he believed that Allen was responsible for attacks
across the country, and he urged other victims to come forward.
``We believe Mike is a serial predator,'' he said. ``He was very
well traveled around the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, police have linked him to five attacks in New York and
New Jersey, most of which also involved robbery. In the most recent
case, at the Peddie School in Hightstown, Allen sneaked into a
dormitory on the 175-acre campus around 4:40 a.m. on Feb. 11,
Warshany said.
</P>
<P>
   He pried open a window in a common area of the dormitory and
took items, including credit cards, from the unlocked rooms of
several sleeping students, Warshany said. Allen then entered the
second-floor room of a 16-year-old boy, woke him and sexually
assaulted him while threatening him with a knife, Warshany said.
</P>
<P>
   After the attacker fled the room, the boy called school security
guards, who spotted a man walking away from the building's side
entrance. The guards gave chase but did not catch him, Warshany
said. Allen has been charged with sexual assault, burglary and
other crimes, according to the Mercer County prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, on Feb. 9, police said, Allen staged a similar
attack at the Millbrook School, a prestigious private high school
in Dutchess County, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Allen assaulted a 16-year-old boy and stole
property from the rooms of several students as they slept, the
police said. Investigators said they were not sure how Allen
entered the residence hall, which is locked at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like this has never happened here,'' said Drew
Casetano, the headmaster of Millbrook, which sits at the end of a
mile-long driveway and is surrounded by woods, meadows and
farmland. The doors to the students' rooms, however, do not have
locks on them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Anderson, the Dutchess County sheriff, said Allen would
probably be charged with sodomy, burglary and grand larceny. ``He's
already confessed to everything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen has also been accused of molesting a boy who was attending
a baseball camp last summer at the C.W. Post College campus of Long
Island University in Old Brookville. In that case, which occurred
at 4 a.m. July 5, police said the attacker tapped the boy on the
shoulder, threw a towel over his head and threatened to kill him if
he screamed. After sealing the boy's mouth with duct tape, the man
sodomized him and then threatened to kill the boy's parents if he
told anyone about the incident, investigators said. The Nassau
County police have charged him with burglary and sodomy.
</P>
<P>
   The Suffolk County police said Allen was also believed to be
responsible for two attacks there, one at La Salle Military Academy
in Oakdale and another at Stony Brook Preparatory School.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how Allen managed to evade the authorities for
so long, but investigators said his decision to target schools in
numerous jurisdictions prevented officials from linking the
incidents. Only after the Peddie School attack was publicized by
the news media did the authorities begin connecting the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Allen brought himself down by using a credit card
stolen from one of his victims, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   In September, he was arrested and charged with stealing an
identification card from a student at Hofstra University on Long
Island. He was released, but he gave the police his beeper number.
On Friday, after linking him to a credit card taken during the
Millbrook incident, the Nassau County police paged him, and, when
he called, they asked him to come to a police station to pick up
personal property. When he showed up, he was arrested. He is being
held without bail in the Nassau County jail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
