u f BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      02-22 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: TREND-SPOTTER AMONG TRAVEL AGENTS FOCUSES ON
INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JOE SHARKEY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among travel agents, Rosenbluth International gets credit,
though sometimes very grudgingly, for having anticipated several of
the economic trends that have shaken that industry recently. In the
early 1990's _ years before the airlines enraged travel agents and
even drove some out of business by slashing commissions on tickets
sold _ Rosenbluth began sharply reducing its dependence on
commissions and instead started charging corporate clients fees for
providing travel-management services.
</P>
<P>
   So it is probably worth briefly examining the latest business
idea by Rosenbluth, a Philadelphia-based travel agency with 1,300
offices worldwide. Last month, its Rosenbluth Interactive
subsidiary rolled out a business-to-business travel-booking service
that sets up custom online travel-booking sites, with off-line
travel-agent telephone assistance, ``tailored specifically for
small, midsized and emerging-growth companies,'' said Justin Shaw,
the vice president and general manager of Biztravel.com, a division
of Rosenbluth Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can book a trip online on dozens of different sites,
including Biztravel.com, which Rosenbluth bought last year. What's
different here is that Rosenbluth will design a site _ the company
refers to it generically as biztravel(at)mycompany _ individually
for a company. The site will accommodate a company's employees'
travel profiles and allow travelers wide flexibility not only in
making airline, hotel and other bookings, but in making last-minute
changes by speaking with someone on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you're en route and something changes _ the weather, a
meeting is rescheduled, the boss calls and says they want you in
North Dakota tomorrow,'' Shaw said. ``These are times when it's not
easy to access the Internet and making a phone call is the way to
get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   About 35 companies are now clients of the service. They pay
nothing for the custom site, and pay fees, which Shaw says are
lower than typical travel agencies charge, for having Rosenbluth's
agents provide telephone assistance in changing tickets, available
around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   How does Rosenbluth make money at this? Well, besides the
telephone-service fees, much of the revenue comes from ``certain
payments from the suppliers whose products we sell, such as an
airline,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, that would be commissions. Oddly enough, as many
struggling small travel agencies were forced to impose fees for
face-to-face transactions to make up for the reduced commissions,
big-brand agencies with huge volumes were negotiating bulk
commissions for bookings from airlines and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that with some of the commission cuts, a lot of local
and regional agencies were getting to the point where they had no
choice but to charge all of their customers a transaction fee,
maybe as much as $20, for booking a ticket,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now obviously with the economics of an Internet business, we
can do the booking online and not charge anything'' for selling the
ticket, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   AIR FARES AND ANTITRUST CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of travel agents and online competition, last week the
American Society of Travel Agents petitioned the Justice Department
to look into possible antitrust violations by major airlines who
announced last month that they would participate jointly in a new
Web site that would offer low-cost tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The travel agents' trade group called the site, scheduled to
start this spring, an anti-competitive ploy to ``lure consumers
onto the Web with lower prices.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Web site said there was no merit to the
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The travel agent group, which has been dismissive of online
booking sites until the airlines started getting into the act, said
travel agents still book 80 percent of airline tickets, 95 percent
of cruises and 90 percent of package tours, and most continue to
prosper as overall travel spending increases in a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   AIR FARES AND OIL PRICES
</P>
<P>
   Now that oil prices are wedged in the $30 a barrel range,
airlines are scrambling _ a bit frantically at times _ to keep
profits up as fuel costs soar. Last Friday, Continental Airlines
increased domestic fares by as much as $15. The next day, Delta Air
Lines and American Airlines also raised fares, followed on Sunday
by US Airways, United Air Lines and Trans World Airlines. But
Northwest Airlines stubbornly refused to get on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind!'' yelped the others, fully aware that mischievous
Northwest would undoubtedly get a lot of mileage out of ads
trumpeting that it alone had refused to jack up fares. One by one
on Monday, the others dropped their price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see what happens  &UR; next &LR;  week.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled British Airways, meanwhile, raised trans-Atlantic
fares by 3 percent earlier this month, after earlier increases on
those routes by American competitors. And since January, major
American carriers have been adding a $20 fuel surcharge to most
domestic tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the cost of oil, American Express says, ``typical''
business air fares will rise this year by 3 to 4 percent, to an
average of more than $1,000 round trip _ a higher rate than it
forecast last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flying for business will get more expensive than many expected
this year,'' said Rusty Carpenter, vice president of American
Express Consulting Services. He said the predictions on air fare
costs might have to be revised upward later in the year if the
airlines maintained their fuel surcharges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
