<HEADLINE>
MY JOB: RESORTING TO TYPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Ann Berrios is a secretary at the State University of New York at
Stony Brook.)  
(lh) 
 By ANN BERRIOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a secretary, it never seemed to matter where or even that I
had gone to college. My college's name on a resume did not exempt
me from the grammar, spelling and typing tests that aspiring
secretaries must endure. Nor did it open doors for me. When I get
my college alumnae magazine, I catch up on classmates who are
physicians, lawyers and late-blooming social workers. I never read
about the secretaries or clerks, though I know they exist. In
college, there were premeds, prelaws and those who did not know
what to do with their lives. It was what I learned in secretarial
school, not college, that has sustained me the last 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   I never bothered to learn my class rank since I thought that
knowledge would do little to make me happy. I left my senior thesis
behind with the professor who was kind enough to read it five
months after it was due.
</P>
<P>
   My mother sent me to an entree program that taught recent
college graduates practical skills like typing and taking
dictation. We new recruits, gleaned mostly from fancy women's
colleges, were thinking that we might have to start as secretaries
but it would not be long before we would either become moguls or
marry moguls.
</P>
<P>
   I have had my share of adventures. One employer's identity
relied largely on his friendship with a king in exile. He once
called me from my desk to meet his friend. After the introduction,
my boss sent me to buy the king a sandwich. I remember two things
about this event: that the king was a lovely person and that my
employer never reimbursed me for the sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, my boss sent me to find a belt as a Christmas
present for the company president, a man of great girth. I soon
found out that most stores sell men's belts only up to size 42, and
this man was a 48 or more. Dispirited, I bought a calculator
instead. My boss laughed; it was the one gift he knew the president
would hate.
</P>
<P>
   I enjoyed watching another boss lead a former first lady across
a crowded ballroom. He looked so proud, his chest swelled. Trouble
was, the first lady stopped to talk with someone along the way. My
boss did not know this but continued stepping grandly as if she
were still behind him and the whole room were still admiring them.
This was his moment _ and mine too.
</P>
<P>
   I have come to the rescue more than once. I remember the day my
boss appeared holding his natural teeth. He had made the unwise
choice of walking up the subway stairs with his hands in his
pockets. I found the surgeon who saved my boss' teeth and, as an
added bonus for me, wired his jaw shut for a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   Secretaries enjoy hearing phrases like, ``We have to move the
office by Wednesday.'' Translated, this means you have to move the
office by Wednesday. Hauling computers, shoving heavy furniture and
squeaking file cabinets across an unforgiving floor can be all part
of the job. Some days I wish I had worn my construction boots
instead of my pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two years down; 22 to go. I just may be a lifer of the
secretarial pool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
