<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-PRIM-MAIN23-COX     02-22 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIM-MAIN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crossover votes help McCain capture wins in Michigan, Arizona
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT, Mich. _ Arizona Sen. John McCain on Tuesday scored
convincing wins in Republican primaries in his home state, where
victory was expected, and in Michigan, where he got overwhelming
support from Democrats crossing over to vote in the Republican
primary, exit polls showed.
</P>
<P>
   Independent voters in Michigan also favored McCain, but he would
have lost to Bush if only independents and Republican votes had
counted, the poll results showed.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Bush emphasized his strength among Republican
voters, but McCain predicted that will change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the Republicans in the state of Michigan, among those
independents who share our philosophy, our compassionate
conservative philosophy ... There's no question who the winner is
in Michigan tonight and you're looking at him,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain said, ``As I look more electable, we'll start drawing
more Republicans. Michigan sent a powerful message across America,
that our party wants real reform from the real reformer. We're
creating a new majority, my friends, a McCain majority.''
</P>
<P>
   With 37 percent of the vote counted in Michigan, McCain was
leading about 50 percent to 44 percent for Bush. Alan Keyes was
running a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won all of Arizona's 30 delegates with his victory there.
His statewide victory in Michigan earned him 10 at-large delegates,
with the remaining 48 delegates to be allocated according to the
winner of each congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   An exit poll conducted by the Detroit News showed McCain getting
about 26 percent of Michigan's Republican vote, about 66 percent of
the independent vote and 86 percent from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the Voter News Service showed Republicans made up just
49 percent of those who voted Tuesday. Voters who described
themselves as independent cast 33 percent of the votes, while 18
percent said they were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine percent of voters surveyed said they had not
previously voted in a Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine (R-Ohio), a national McCain co-chairman, hailed
the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are Reagan Democrats and Reagan independents who are
going for McCain, which is very significant,'' he said. ``It means
we have rediscovered the recipe for winning in November and John
McCain is the cook.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed happy to be out of Michigan, where he and McCain
campaigned at a frenetic pace after last Saturday's South Carolina
primary. Bush won in that state and appeared to regain momentum
from McCain, who earlier had won New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with the Republican vote,'' Bush said at a stop in
Missouri on Tuesday night, on his way to California. ``God, this is
a long process. This is a marathon and I'm going to be in it all
the way to the end. ... I'm not doing well among liberal Democrats,
but you know, I didn't expect to.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting was heavy in what passed for a balmy February day in
Michigan, with the temperature reaching 50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   McCain openly appealed to Democrats, independents,
``libertarians and vegetarians'' as he crisscrossed the state from
picturesque Traverse City along Lake Michigan in the north to the
Detroit suburbs in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley
were not on the Democratic ballot, making it tempting for Democrats
to cross over.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in the race was Michigan's third-term Republican
Gov. John Engler, head of Bush's campaign. Engler's Democratic
opponents urged voters to cross over and pick McCain to spite
Engler.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain isn't party building. He's party-borrowing,''
Engler said in a television interview. ``There's a big
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who has been mentioned as a possible vice
presidential candidate on a Bush ticket, said he was pleased with
the Republican turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is Democrats and independents showed up in record
numbers,'' Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan provided a better test of the candidates' national
appeal than earlier primaries, said DeWine, one of four Republican
senators who has endorsed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I find most significant is that this is a big state, a
state that is a must-win state in the fall and the first (primary)
state that is a microcosm of the country,'' DeWine said.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain's backer rejoiced at the outcome, political
analysts cautioned that McCain still faces an uphill fight,
particularly with so-called Super Tuesday coming up March 7 with
primaries in 13 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really relying on the momentum. The good news coverage
communicates to voters that his campaign is viable. That can make
up for lack of organization,'' said John Green, director of the Ray
C. Bliss Institute of Applied Politics at the University of Akron.
</P>
<P>
   McCain still is a long shot for the Republican nomination,
lacking the grass-roots organization that Bush has in the remaining
states, said Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point he has to have the resources to compete in a lot
of states. The more victories he racks up, the more likely he is to
get them,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, the campaigning became increasingly negative
leading up to Tuesday. Phone calls supporting McCain were made to
voters suggesting that Bush is anti-Catholic because he sought the
support of ``anti-Catholic'' fundamentalist Protestants in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In return, religious broadcaster Pat Robertson made calls in
support of Bush accusing former New Hampshire Sen. Warren Rudman, a
McCain national co-chairman, of being prejudiced against
conservative Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by what he considered low blows by the Bush campaign in
South Carolina, McCain stormed around Michigan accusing the Texas
governor of being a ``low-road'' campaigner who would stoop to
anything _ including ``character assassination'' to win.
</P>
<P>
   McCain depicted himself as Luke Skywalker from ``Star Wars''
trying to fight his way out of the Death Star. He said he was
surrounded by enemies shooting at him but added ``We're going to
kill 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush kept a busy campaign schedule here, he made less
mention of his Republican opponent. Instead, he lashed out against
the Clinton-Gore administration and regularly listed the number of
days until voters would chase the Democrats from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking Bush's money and organizational strengths, McCain plans
to pinpoint his political activities. California and Ohio will be
major McCain targets, as he tries for come-from-behind victories in
two states that award all their delegates to the winner.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of delegates are up for grabs later this week in
America Samoa, Guam, the Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico. On Feb.
29, Republicans in North Dakota, Virginia and Washington state will
make their choices.
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath of the Cox News Service and The Associated Press
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
