u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      02-22 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN BOUNCES BACK IN MICHIGAN 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ John McCain, powered by votes from Democrats and
independents who made up half the record turnout, won the Michigan
Republican presidential primary Tuesday, robbing George W. Bush of
momentum he had counted on before the glut of voting over the next
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also won his home state primary in Arizona, handing Bush
a double loss just as the Texas governor was attempting to build on
his comeback victory Saturday in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   With more than half of the precincts reporting in Michigan,
McCain led Bush 50 percent to 44 percent. In Arizona, with only a
handful of precincts counted, McCain led 67 percent to 29 percent.
Former Reagan administration official Alan Keyes had 4 percent in
Michigan and 3 percent in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, Bush held sway with traditional Republicans,
especially anti-abortion conservatives, according to exit polls.
McCain won enough Republicans to spell victory when they were added
to his strong support from independents and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, telling supporters in Phoenix that he was ``a proud
Reagan conservative,'' predicted he would draw more Republicans as
he looks more electable. The Michigan result, he said, was a sign
``our party wants real reform from the real reformer. ... I'm going
to give your government back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't fear this campaign, my fellow Republicans. Join it,''
McCain urged fellow party members who have shunned his candidacy.
``We are creating a new majority _ a McCain majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush fell back on his claim, used when McCain won in New
Hampshire Feb. 1, that the nomination season is ``a marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm going to be in it all the way to the end _ and some
primaries you win and sometimes you don't,'' Bush declared at a
rally in Kansas City, Mo., where he was refueling his campaign
plane on his way to California as polls closed in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush quickly slapped at McCain's dependence on Democratic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the Republicans in the state of Michigan, among
independents who share our philosophy ... there's no question who
the winner is in Michigan, and you're looking at him,'' he told
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The result was sweet revenge for McCain, who won big in New
Hampshire three weeks ago but faltered badly in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The result, however, also represented a problematic turn for
both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's victory in Michigan, the first populous, industrial
state to sound off in the presidential race, allows the Arizona
senator at least a momentary rebound. But his continued failure to
generate significant support from Republicans points to a sharply
limited appeal with voters who will control the delegate selection
in the most important primaries immediately ahead, including the
megacontests in California, New York and 11 other states March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's double loss not only dampens any momentum he had picked
up out of South Carolina but also highlights his failure to attract
significant Democratic crossover and independent support in any of
the open primaries so far. That points to problems ahead if he wins
the Republican nomination and must compete in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush retains a lead among Republicans in national
polls, soft spots for the Texan are appearing in the short-term
primary calendar. A new University of Massachusetts survey of
Republicans and independents likely to vote in the GOP primary
there March 7 gave McCain 58 percent to 34 percent for Bush.
Analysts said McCain's strength was based in part on the sizable
number of Democrats who have changed their voter registration to
Republican since McCain won the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan exit poll by Voter News Service, a consortium of
The Associated Press and major television networks, found that Bush
was winning more than 6 in 10 Republican voters while McCain was
winning a big majority of independents and more than 8 in 10
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   McCain ran especially well with black voters, perhaps because
some minority leaders advocated support for the Arizonan as way of
striking out at Bush's Michigan leader, Republican Gov. John
Engler. But only one in 20 participants in Tuesday's GOP primary
was black.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a chance for a payback,'' Engler said in a CNN
interview. He accused McCain of a cagey strategy to ``rent
Democrats for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   There was technically a Democratic primary in Michigan, but Vice
President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley removed their names
from the ballot to comply with national party rules that allow only
Iowa and New Hampshire to hold binding nominating contests before
March 1. Michigan's Democratic National Convention delegates will
be chosen on the basis of caucuses to be held March 11. Arizona
also holds its Democratic primary March 11.
</P>
<P>
   That left the Republican balloting as the only game for all the
state's 6.7 million registered voters regardless of their true
party leanings and offered McCain another whack at independents and
Democrats who have been the most fertile ground for his insurgent
message.
</P>
<P>
   With the close vote, analysts focused on the prospect that
McCain could carve out a narrow victory in the popular vote and
Bush could triumph in the separate race to win delegates to the
Republican National Convention at Philadelphia this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The victor in each of the state's 16 U.S. House districts is
entitled to three delegates, meaning that if McCain's vote is
concentrated in the Democratic-rich Detroit metropolitan area, he
could leave Bush to pick up the district delegates from the
remainder of the state. The statewide popular vote winner gets an
additional 10 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Engler estimated that Bush would win 36 of the 58 delegates at
stake, adding to his small but growing advantage over McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In the brief Michigan campaign, Bush sounded general-election
themes and concentrated his fire on President Clinton and Gore, the
front-runner for the Democratic nomination. McCain, even though he
has sworn off negative ads on television, sharpened his own attack
on Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also railed against Bush's almost solid backing from the
Republican establishment, both in Michigan and nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all against me,'' McCain said of Bush's support by a
majority of the party's governors and member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The heated campaign in Michigan was marked by charges from both
sides about religious intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was ``a little disappointed'' by calls he said the
McCain campaign made to voters, ``calling me an anti-Catholic
bigot'' for his address to Bob Jones University in South Carolina,
a fundamentalist Christian school that rejects Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
