<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZ-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN, BACK IN THE RUNNING, REACHES OUT TO GOP LOYALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ With his insurgent campaign brought back to life
Tuesday night by victories in the Michigan and Arizona primaries,
Sen. John McCain reached out to loyalists in his party, imploring,
``Don't fear this campaign, my fellow Republicans _ join it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three days after a drubbing in South Carolina looked like
it could be the death knell for his campaign, McCain was exuberant,
grinning and saying, ``What a difference a couple of days make.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that his victory in Michigan relied on his crossover
appeal to Democrats and independents, he immediately began trying
to shore up his support from Republicans in preparation for the
next round of primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make a special plea tonight to my fellow
Republicans,'' he said in a hotel ballroom in his hometown here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who rule the establishment who want more than
anything to defend Washington's big money, big spending status quo.
They want to fool you about me. Well, here is some more straight
talk: I am proud Reagan conservative. I love the Republican Party.
It is my home.''
</P>
<P>
   The night's victories _ most particularly the one in Michigan _
made McCain viable again and propelled him and Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas forward into a fierce cross-country struggle for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule ahead still presents a formidable challenge to
McCain's underdog campaign, which largely lacks institutional
support as Bush has piled up the endorsements from governors and
has a national apparatus in place.
</P>
<P>
   Showdowns loom next Tuesday in Washington, Virginia and North
Dakota. And on March 7, the delegate rich powerhouses of California
and New York vote, as well as Ohio, Georgia and a host of New
England states.
</P>
<P>
   Asked as he voted Tuesday morning whether the Michigan primary
was ``do or die'' for him, McCain said: ``Every day is do or die.
We're a high-wire act and an insurgency campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again Tuesday Bush won handily among Republicans in
Michigan while McCain drew independents and Democrats into the GOP
primary. While that shows McCain's potential appeal in a general
election, it also represents a challenge for him. (In his home
state, the results were somewhat different, with Bush winning
support only from the most conservative Republicans.)
</P>
<P>
   While some of the states ahead have open primaries, like
Michigan's, others only allow party members to vote. And while
California has an open primary, its 162 delegates are allotted only
on the basis of how Republicans vote.
</P>
<P>
   In order to shore up his support among Republicans, McCain began
Tuesday night trying to hammer home the theme that he is the one
who can best propel his party to victory in November. ``We are
creating a new majority, my friends, a McCain majority,'' he said,
``and we are Al Gore's worst nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was also preparing to begin airing a new commercial in
California, Washington, and Virginia, perhaps as early as Thursday,
to try to pick up ground with Republicans, his aides said. Striking
similar tones as his victory speech, the advertisement will likely
feature McCain looking into the camera and saying that the
establishment is running ads to fool voters about him.
</P>
<P>
   It will then stress his economic message of fighting against
pork-barrel spending, and his plan for tax cuts for the middle
class while devoting much of the surplus to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to end Washington's outrageous pork barrel spending,''
McCain said Tuesday night. ``I want to rebuild our military,
strengthen our families, protect the unborn, and cut your taxes. I
want to use the surplus the right way, by keeping our obligation to
shore up Social Security, fix Medicare and pay down our debt.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's aides argue that Washington, California, New York and
New England now represent fertile ground for McCain's message of
reform Republicanism and that Bush will be haunted by the tenor of
his South Carolina campaign and his close alliance with the
Christian right. ``South Carolina did not define this campaign,''
said Davis, the senator's campaign manager. ``Unfortunately for
Bush, he got defined in South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Evans, Washington state's former governor, recently switched
from Bush to endorse McCain, as did Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y., who
criticized Bush's appearance at Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   And though the pace now becomes punishing and the campaigns have
to be waged simultaneously coast to coast, McCain's aides said that
Bush's vast spending in South Carolina, Michigan and Arizona has
virtually eliminated his fund-raising advantage and that they could
now come closer to matching his television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that, Carla Eudy, McCain's finance chairwomen, said
the campaign was sending out new direct mail, telemarketing and
Internet appeals for cash and that fund-raisers were planned for
Thursday in San Francisco and Friday in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
