<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN STEALS VEHICLE, DRAGS BOY CAUGHT IN SEAT BELT TO HIS DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ A man driving a stolen Chevrolet Blazer
dragged a 6-year-old Blue Springs, Mo., boy about five miles to his
death Tuesday before a group of horrified motorists chased and
caught the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday night, police had not released the name of the man
arrested in the death of Jake Robel.
</P>
<P>
   Independence police said the incident started about 4:15 p.m. at
a sandwich shop. Employees there became suspicious when they
noticed a man loitering outside.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, a woman pulled up to the restaurant, left her
Blazer running and went inside, leaving her son inside the vehicle.
Police Sgt. Gregg Wilkinson said the man outside then jumped into
the sport-utility vehicle and tried to shove Jake out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably thought he'd gotten the kid out, because then he
took off,'' Wilkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jake was tangled in the seat belt and was left dangling from
the driver's side rear door.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Thompson, 38, of Independence, was heading south on
Missouri 291 when the thief sped past him. Something caught
Thompson's eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, that's a baby!'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   He chased the Blazer, honking his horn and trying to get the
driver's attention. He said he was traveling at least 80 mph but
couldn't catch up. He followed the driver onto Interstate 70.
</P>
<P>
   Fred and Brad Byam, two brothers from Oak Grove, Mo., were
driving west on I-70 a half mile from the Noland Road exit when the
Blazer sped by. They saw the boy being dragged and joined the
chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought somebody's kid had fallen out the door, so we were
just trying to stop him and alert them,'' Fred Byam said.
</P>
<P>
   The thief sped up an exit ramp and headed north. Just then the a
stoplight turned red, and the Blazer stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The Byam brothers pulled their truck in front of the Blazer to
block its path.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were still thinking it was just an accident,'' Brad Byam
said.
</P>
<P>
   The thief got out of the Blazer, saw Jake dangling from the seat
belt, muttered something, then jumped back into the Blazer, Brad
Byam said.
</P>
<P>
   The thief drove forward and rammed Fred Byam's truck in the rear
left side. Then the thief backed into a car that also had joined
the pursuit, Brad Byam said.
</P>
<P>
   The Byam brothers ran to the truck, yanked the keys out of the
ignition and threw them on the ground. The two pulled the driver
out of the Blazer.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to escape, Fred Byam said. By then, other men who saw
the commotion joined the struggle and wrestled the man to the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fought like a wildcat,'' Fred Byam said. ``The four of us
were having trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Byam yelled at John Rodgers, who had joined the struggle,
to get some rope from his truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tied his feet up,'' Fred Byam said. ``We didn't think we
could hold him until the police got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence police arrived shortly before 4:30 p.m. and took
the man away.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-year-old boy from one of the pursuing vehicles took a
large white blanket from his mother's car and placed it over the
young victim.
</P>
<P>
   Jake's body lay at the side of the stolen Blazer until about
5:50 p.m. Most of the boy's clothes had been ripped away.
</P>
<P>
   Independence police were examining videotape from the restaurant
in hopes that some of the thief's actions were caught on tape.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second dragging death in as many weeks in the Kansas
City area. On Feb. 14, Sandra L. Roberts, 41, of Kansas City, Mo.,
was dragged to death as a man driving a stolen car fled police.
Nobody has been charged in that death.
</P>
<P>
   Long after police took charge at Tuesday's accident, the Byam
brothers lingered and stared blankly at the white blanket that
shielded the victim from the eyes of onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just terrible,'' Brad Byam said, tears welling in his
eyes. ``I don't see how people can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a helpless feeling seeing that kid,'' Fred Byam
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was his wedding anniversary, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, all I'll remember is that this is the day I saw
that kid dragged.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
