A5390 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     02-22 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
THEY CAN'T PUNISH McSORLEY ENOUGH 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marty McSorley, who made his NHL bones as Wayne Gretzky's
bodyguard during the Great One's Edmonton Oilers heyday, has
finally picked a fight with a bully bigger than he is: the entire
National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   He's about to find out what it feels like to be pummeled
senseless. He deserves no less.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Bruins' bad boy, immediately suspended indefinitely
yesterday after NHL execs saw the tapes of his unprovoked assault
and battery on Vancouver's Donald Brashear late Monday night, is
expected to be banished for at least the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   He could get life without parole and may yet, if the legal
authorities get involved in Vancouver, as they have been
threatening to do.
</P>
<P>
   You know the Mounties: They always get their man.
</P>
<P>
   By now, you've heard what happened and it's no laughing matter:
The final few seconds of a tough, physical game between the Canucks
and Bruins were ticking off the clock when McSorley, skating up
behind Brashear, swung his stick two-handed like a broadsword,
chopping it viciously into the side of the unsuspecting Canuck's
head.
</P>
<P>
   Brashear was unconscious before he even knew what hit him. His
helmet flew off and his head snapped sickeningly against the ice.
His eyes glazed and blood dripping from his nose, Brashear lay
helplessly as McSorley skated in a circle, taunting him.
</P>
<P>
   It was the act of a coward and one that will surely brand the
36-year-old McSorley for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   He is lucky that Brashear is still alive; lucky that the Canuck,
who was carried off on a stretcher, somehow walked out of the arena
and into a hospital on his own feet. Brashear has a concussion from
the attack, but it could have been so much worse.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the NHL has to consider when it hands down its
ruling. They got lucky this time. But what about the next time some
goon decides to ambush another player? What if the stick connects
with the temple, or cracks someone's spine? What if an almost
unimaginable tragedy occurs right there on the ice?
</P>
<P>
   It can't, and that's why McSorley will almost surely get the
longest suspension in league history. If he's banned only for the
rest of the season, that's 23 games. The previous longest
suspension in league history is 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   Even that might not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If McSorley plays another game in this league, then this
league is a joke,'' Canucks defenseman Mattias Ohlund told the
``Vancouver Sun'' after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst thing I've ever seen. That guy \RMcSorley\S
should be treated the same as if he tried to kill a guy on the
street, because that's what he could have done had he hit Brash
across the neck with his stick.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what the NHL doesn't want to happen. It's why it
will react quickly and decisively to deal with the incident. The
attack itself, which might have stemmed from a first-period fight
in which Brashear got the best of McSorley, the third
most-penalized player in NHL history, is bad enough. But from an
image perspective, the last thing the league wants is to have the
police and court system get involved.
</P>
<P>
   It has happened before, but it's something the NHL would much
rather avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of incidents happen, hopefully seldom, but they do
happen,'' Stars general manager Bob Gainey said yesterday. ``The
league has handled them in a way that make people feel they get
handled promptly and that the parties involved, whether you're the
guilty party or the victim, feel that they've been taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we felt that way when Derian Hatcher was suspended here
a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher was suspended for seven games at the beginning of the
playoffs last season for a devastating hit that broke the jaw of
Phoenix center Jeremy Roenick. One big difference: Hatcher didn't
use his stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if the NHL monitors and regulates and disciplines the
players in the league, as they have, they should be allowed to do
that,'' Gainey added. ``The fact that he's been asked to go to New
York to discuss the case indicates that this will be similar to
disciplinary actions that have happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Gainey said, ``is not a good sign'' for McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there haven't been many good signs for McSorley for
a long time now. He is an anachronism in a sport trying desperately
to clean up its image and convince people that the game itself is
worth watching, and that this isn't just the Friday night fights on
ice.
</P>
<P>
   Even McSorley's teammates were stunned at the sneak attack that
came with just 2.7 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good night if you're a hockey player right now,''
said Bruins captain Ray Bourque in the subdued Boston locker room
after the game. ``You don't want to be a part of anything like
that. There is no room for it and you can't justify it.''
   Goalie Byron Dafoe, who suffered an injured knee when Brashear
fell on him in the first period, couldn't believe what he'd seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not acceptable,'' he said. ``It's just not hockey.
It's the worst thing I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   These were McSorley's teammates and friends. You can imagine
what the Canucks were saying in the other locker room.
</P>
<P>
   There's no place for that kind of thuggery in the NHL any more,
and there's no place for a dinosaur like McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky doesn't need him any more. Neither does the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few minutes after the game had ended, the gravity of
what he'd just done had began to sink in with McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be repercussions, but that's the last thing I'm
thinking about right now,'' he said with obviously sincere remorse.
``We've got to be proud to play in the NHL. That's not proud.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not. For a long time, McSorley has stood up to anyone
who dared to drop the gloves with him. He took on one and all. Now
he must stand and accept responsibility for his own despicable
actions.
</P>
<P>
   He should not only quietly and without protest accept whatever
suspension the NHL hands him, he should then hang up his skates and
walk away.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been worse. He could have killed someone.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-22-00 2336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
