<DOCNO> NYT20000222.0501 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5391 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-PRIM-MCCAIN23-1STLEDE     02-22 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIM-MCCAIN23-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: 1ST LEDE WRITE-THRU; updates throughout
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Insurgent now must mend GOP fences, experts say
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John McCain has now won three out of the four
primaries in which he has campaigned against George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's victories in Arizona and Michigan on Tuesday gave him a
desperately needed boost 72 hours after Bush won the South Carolina
primary.
</P>
<P>
   But his .750 batting average gives McCain a powerful new
argument to take to Washington state and California, where he will
campaign for the next three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are creating a new majority my friends, a McCain majority.
And we are Al Gore's worst nightmare,'' McCain said at his victory
celebration in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's top communications aide put it more bluntly. ``It's
clear that South Carolina was an aberration,'' said Dan Schnur,
McCain's communications director. ``Bush has not demonstrated that
he can win a contested primary in a state not dominated by
religious conservative voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if one of McCain's wins _ in his home state of Arizona _
was expected, McCain recorded victories in states in which the top
elected Republicans were arrayed against him. (Bush also won the
Iowa caucuses and the Delaware primary, but McCain did not campaign
in either state.)
</P>
<P>
   He will face the same obstacles in most other states as he and
Bush duel in 16 contests over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had hoped to cut off McCain's campaign in Michigan, one of
his so-called firewalls. Michigan Gov. John Engler had boasted that
his state would be the asbestos that would contain McCain's fire.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's performance Tuesday poked another hole in the Bush
campaign's argument that their man is best suited to take on the
Democrats in the general election, said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a
political scientist at the Claremont Graduate University in
suburban Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's opportunity is to take advantage of some nervousness
that might exist on the part of California Republicans that perhaps
Bush isn't what they thought he was going to be, that he is not the
stronger candidate against Gore or Bradley,'' Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, national polls show that McCain performs much better
than Bush against Vice President Al Gore. Oddly, McCain increased
his lead over Gore in the Gallup Poll that followed Saturday's
South Carolina primary, while Bush's narrow advantage over Gore
remained steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with inevitability is that you're only inevitable
until you aren't,'' Schnur said.
</P>
<P>
   But the results in Michigan, in particular, point up a looming
problem for McCain. At some point, he has to begin to impress
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain himself was aware of his dilemma. ``Don't fear this
campaign, my fellow Republicans. Join it. Join it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain continued in Michigan to rack up overwhelming numbers
among the independents and Democrats who voted in the Republican
primary.
</P>
<P>
   But exit polls in Michigan indicated that George W. Bush beat
McCain by more than 2 to 1 among Republicans, roughly the same
picture that emerged from South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The peril for the Arizona senator is that upcoming primaries in
California and New York on March 7 will count only Republican votes
for the purposes of allocating delegates to the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   There is no path to the GOP nomination that does not include
winning key states on the basis of Republican _ not independent or
Democratic _ support. Ultimately, the race will become a battle for
the 1,033 delegates that are needed to secure the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain appealed to rank-and-file Republicans, he again
jabbed at the Republican leaders who oppose him. ``They want to
fool you about me,'' he said. ``Here's some more straight talk. I'm
a proud Reagan conservative. I love the Republican Party. It is my
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffe suggested that McCain could begin to repair his image
among Republicans in California by toning down his reform message
and campaign rhetoric that portrays him as an outsider. ``He has to
show Republicans that he is a true conservative,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That task may be harder after the campaigns in Michigan and
South Carolina. In both states, McCain was practically in open
warfare with the Republican establishment, which was strongly
supportive of Bush in both states, and with religious
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But Californians probably will see McCain television ads that
make use of images of McCain with Ronald Reagan, a California
Republican icon. And in California, core Republicans who watched
Democrats take over all but two statewide offices might be prepared
to vote for a candidate they think can win, even if they find him
occasionally irritating.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will be trying to walk a fine line in coming weeks,
seeking more Republican votes without diminishing the enthusiasm of
independents who have turned out to support him in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In several states, including Virginia next week, the Republican
primaries are open to independents, and in some cases, Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The cluster of March 7 primaries includes Georgia, where the
primary is open to all voters, and much of New England, where
independents can vote in the GOP contests.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts provided more powerful evidence of McCain's appeal
across party lines when Secretary of State William F. Galvin
announced this week that nearly 30,000 people had changed their
party registration to make themselves eligible for the March 7
Republican primary. A new University of Massachusetts poll shows
McCain with a sizable lead over Bush, 58 percent to 34 percent,
among Republicans and independents who are likely to vote in that
primary.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
