<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-POWER-PLAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWILDERED STARS WINGER HULL FEELING POWERLESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Brett Hull said he wasn't concerned about the Stars'
struggling power play. But he is.
</P>
<P>
   Hull said some of the blame should go to the coaches. But he
blames himself as much if not more.
</P>
<P>
   Hull said a lot about the power play after Monday's 5-2 loss to
Nashville, which said Hull is just as frustrated as the rest of the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a scorer, and we're not scoring,'' Hull said. ``What do
you think?''
</P>
<P>
   With the Stars struggling to score goals, as they have been all
season, the power play can provide the gap between winning and
losing. Scorers such as Hull feel pressure, maybe more than others,
when it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   He had 15 power-play goals last season. He has 17 goals this
season, nine on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the frustration, when you have people who expect to
score and contribute in that way,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``When they aren't, they are not happy people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull certainly isn't the only one feeling the power outage. The
Stars scored on 18.8 percent of their power plays during the
1998-99 regular season. The numbers bumped to 12.1 percent in the
playoffs. They've scored on 14.3 percent this season, dropping to
10.8 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the playoffs last year, it hasn't been going,'' said
Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor, who plays the point on the power
play. ``It's the guys on it who have to take all of the blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Blame, of course, can be a dangerous thing in a locker room.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Stars sat down after Monday's game and talked
about what was going wrong. Not just on the power play, but with
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we did talk,'' Sydor said. ``But our biggest thing is
we've got to get our power play going because we're going to need
it.''
</P>
<P>
   How big can one power-play goal be?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are 22-5 this season when scoring a power-play goal.
The Stars have played 60 games. They've won 33 of them. Do the
math. Only 11 times this season have they won without the benefit
of a power-play goal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just about every team in the league can say they're better
when their power play is working. But the Stars are definitely much
worse when theirs isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it's just the power play, and that's the
primary focus,'' Hitchcock said. ``That's too easy. That's an easy
out.''
</P>
<P>
   They're called a strong defensive team, holding opponents to 2.2
goals a game. They've had to be. They've scored only 14 goals more
than they've allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose that in our game with the goals we are scoring we
would really be in trouble,'' Stars center Mike Modano said of the
defense. ``We picked up in that area, knowing that we're not
scoring many goals, two or three.''
</P>
<P>
   The gap between two and three goals a game is huge. The Stars
are 22-1 this season when scoring three or more goals. The gap, the
Stars say, could be provided by the power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can ride the power play,'' Stars captain and defenseman
Derian Hatcher said. ``I know you don't want to rely on it, but
it's nice once in a while to be able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoring on the power play should be easy, right?
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help, too, when you have power-play units that you
practice with and you go out in a game and Coach puts different
people with you,'' Hull said. ``Mike knows what I'm going to do. I
know what Zubie's \RSergei Zubov\S doing and Syd's doing and right
now Brenden Morrow, and then you're thrown out there with two other
guys. You don't know what side you are working or who is going
where on the breakout.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have used basically the same power-play unit all
season, with Hull, Modano, Sydor and Zubov among the mainstays.
Hitchcock said he would've used the same group on their fourth
power play Monday, but some of the key personnel had just come off
the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's frustration talking.
</P>
<P>
   `` I think it's not just the power play,'' Hitchcock said.
``It's when you feel a responsibility to score and to be
responsible in that area and don't get the job done and it's not
getting done, then frustration sometimes sets in. Everybody goes
through it. The frustration is not there when the team wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull said nobody talks about the struggling power play when the
team is winning. But he, like his teammates, realizes they might
need it to win.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
