r a BC-PIRATE-AZR &LR;      02-22 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIRATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX WRITER LOGS A PIRATE'S ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - It's not laden with doubloons or rubies or silver
ingot, but one of the world's most famous pirate ships may have
been found off Madagascar by a crew that includes a Phoenix author.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed, the discovery of Capt. William Kidd's Adventure
Galley could be a treasure trove for historians, despite its lack
of obvious valuables.
</P>
<P>
   The wreck does, however, appear to contain Ming dynasty pottery,
ship fittings, cannons and possibly the ship's bell, which could
confirm its identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``History is kind of a treasure in itself,'' author Paul Perry
said of the find's significance. ``That's really what this is
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry, who chronicled the expedition for the pirate ship Whydah
off Cape Cod, Mass., is serving a similar role in the Adventure
Galley expedition. He is one of nine crew members and two
filmmakers to explore the remains of Kidd's flagship and the nearby
island of Sainte Marie, a haven for pirates three centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   The crew, led by noted pirate-ship hunter Barry Clifford, set
out in late January and returned last week. Perry wrote daily
dispatches that were posted on Discovery Online, the Web site of
the expedition's financial backer, the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
   In them, Perry details the Kidd ship's final days before it was
scuttled by a mutinous crew in May 1699, the character of the
island, the pirates' descendants who still live there, and the
expedition itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who is part of the Clifford expedition is in awe of
what they see, and these are guys who don't awe easily,'' Perry
wrote before the wreck was found.
</P>
<P>
   Their awe stemmed from the untouched beauty of the bay where the
ship was found a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the pirates' Miami,'' Perry quotes Wesley Spiegel, the
dive supervisor for the expedition.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the island isn't crude and rustic in many
ways. The mostly poor villagers live in huts elevated by platforms
to keep out bugs.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a pirate cemetery; some headstones are even
inscribed with the Jolly Roger, the familiar skull and crossbones. &QL; 
HARBORING HOPE &QL; 
Sainte Marie features a labyrinth of caves, presumably to hide loot
taken from ships traversing the Indian Ocean. Kidd had been
commissioned by the king of England to raid French and Spanish
shipping, but the crown later turned on the privateer and declared
him a pirate.
</P>
<P>
   Although Perry is interested in the ``back story'' of the island
and its people, the expedition focused on finding the Adventure
Galley.
</P>
<P>
   The crew began by getting the permission of local authorities.
It already had pinpointed where to look by studying the transcripts
of the pirate trail of Kidd in London, which resulted in his
hanging in 1701 over the Thames River.
</P>
<P>
   In the transcript, a sailor had said Kidd's disgruntled crew
sank the already-damaged ship in a spot ``convenient to the
careening area'' in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Now on the island, the expedition quickly narrowed the search
site to the size of a football field. It rented a 21-foot outboard,
filled it with diving equipment and headed to the spot where the
ship was burned and sunk.
</P>
<P>
   Within 30 minutes, they found what they believed was the ballast
pile from the Adventure Galley. But it turned out to be a false
lead.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day, the crew found the ship about 30 feet below
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really exciting in one way, but in another way, it was
anticlimactic,'' Perry said. ``It was really just a confirmation of
four months of research.''
</P>
<P>
   The following day, the expedition found the November Galley, a
small Dutch ship that Kidd had captured in 1697. It was originally
named the Rupparell and carried drugs, clothing, sugar and coral.
</P>
<P>
   The proximity of the November Galley to what is believed to be
the Adventure Galley was further evidence of its find. Records show
that Kidd's crew had burned both ships next to each other. &QL; 
CONFIDENCE IN THE FIND &QL; 
John de Bry, the expedition's marine archaeologist, also helped
authenticate the find by analyzing the porcelain, oarlocks and
other artifacts at the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not a single element that tells me this is not the
Adventure Galley,'' said de Bry, director of the Center for
Historical Archaeology. ``I didn't see a single artifact that
didn't fit with that time period.''
</P>
<P>
   After the expedition, de Bry stopped in Paris and found
supporting evidence in the way of maps and manuscripts that
indicate two ships sank there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be darned if it's not the Adventure Galley,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, de Bry said the ship must undergo a second phase of
archaeological excavation to know for sure and to document the
find.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the crew plans to return this summer to retrieve
some of the artifacts from the ship, which is believed to be 100
feet long and 30 feet wide. Clifford wants to establish a museum in
the Boston area, which is where Clifford is based. The island also
has offered him an old colonial governor's house for another
museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything we find belongs to the government of Madagascar,''
Perry explained. ``But we might be able to take a few pieces back
to Boston for another museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Perry is considering writing a book about the
expedition and the ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like finding the George Washington of pirate ships,'' he
said. ``It probably was the most famous pirate ship and clearly
Kidd's most favorite ship.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Kerry.Fehr-Snyder(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8975. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Capt. William Kidd's favorite pirate ship has been found off
Madagascar, according to an expedition that includes a Phoenix
author. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
