<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-22 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5399 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOL-550     02-22 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHARTER-SCHOOL-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARTER SCHOOL OPERATOR FACES CHALLENGES IN NEW EDUCATIONAL
VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Freedom from the educational bureaucracy.
Emancipation from cramped, inadequate buildings. Liberty from
incompetent teachers.
</P>
<P>
   As an advocate of charter schools, Steven B. Klinsky embraces
those promises. But as the founder of Victory Schools Inc., soon to
be New York state's largest operator of charter schools, Klinsky
acknowledges that the reality of running such schools is far more
challenging than the slogans suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Victory's experiences with the Sisulu Children's
Academy in Harlem, which opened in September as one of the state's
first three charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   The last bimonthly check due to Sisulu for its allocation of
public school money arrived a month late from the New York City
Board of Education, which blamed a citywide computer foul-up.
</P>
<P>
   Space is so tight at Sisulu's current building that it may have
to forgo plans to add another grade in the fall to its student
body, kindergarten through second grade.
</P>
<P>
   And when members of the State Board of Regents visited in
October, they found a teacher who had misspelled the word
``strawberry'' three times on a chalkboard.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky says that far from being free of the challenges that
bedevil the administrators of most public school systems, operators
of charter schools _ particularly those that like Victory aim to
earn a profit _ face as many hardships, perhaps more.
</P>
<P>
   How Victory responds to those challenges could be crucial to New
York state's fledgling charter school movement, which aims to offer
alternatives to public schools by setting up schools that benefit
from state financing but are freed from many union rules and have
some leeway to set their own curriculums. Next fall, the number of
charter schools statewide will soar from 4 to at least 20, with
Victory operating 4 of them.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of this growing number of charter schools,
moreover, will answer many questions about whether the politicians
who are eagerly promoting charters are also giving them the
resources necessary to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it is the largest charter school manager in the
state, Victory expects to lose money on each of its three charter
schools in New York City for at least five years, and maybe longer.
A fourth Victory school, in Roosevelt on Long Island, might earn a
tiny profit in its second year, according to Victory's estimates,
but only because that school will receive 33 percent more money per
student than its New York City counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky said that all of Victory's schools will become
self-sufficient but added that he was not worried about whether he
makes a profit. He said it was a philanthropic urge that led him to
education in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   While making millions of dollars as a Wall Street investment
specialist, Klinsky set up a nonprofit after-school program for
poor elementary school students in East New York, Brooklyn. Now he
is aiming for a network of charter schools to serve similarly poor
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say that entrepreneurs like Klinsky aim at the
dismantlement of public education. The New York State United
Teachers union estimated that the opening of the Victory charter
school in Roosevelt next fall would result in a 5.5 percent cut in
the budget of the Roosevelt Union Free School District.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Carl T. Hayden, chancellor of the state Board of Regents, said
the Roosevelt district, a 2,900-student district that was taken
over by the state in 1995, is barely able to keep its doors open
with its current tax base.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a charter school taking money out of the system, I fear
for the ability of the Roosevelt public schools to continue,''
Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Klinsky said. He says the competition from charter
schools will press the local schools to improve. That Klinsky is
willing, if necessary, to invest up to $1 million in start-up funds
for each charter school does not hurt his chances for success.
</P>
<P>
   But it also demonstrates that the original idea of charter
schools _ a sort of educational co-op set up by community groups
and overseen by a board of parents and local leaders _ is perhaps a
quaint notion that fails to take into account the high cost of real
estate in a state like New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sisulu receives roughly $6,200 for each of its 247 students, far
less than the $7,200 the Board of Education spends on each
elementary school student. New York's charter school law, like
those in some other states, provides no support for building
expenses or capital funds.
</P>
<P>
   Even the money to which Sisulu is entitled takes a long time to
arrive. Klinsky complains that the school has not yet received any
federal funds for poor children despite Sisulu's calculations that
70 percent of its students qualify for federal free-lunch programs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arthur Greenberg, supervising superintendent for new school
development for the Board of Education, acknowledges that there
have been bureaucratic delays in transferring the funds but said,
``We've tried to be good neighbors to these schools, and we've made
it clear that we want to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``there's a learning curve going on on both
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Academically, the learning curve at Sisulu was in clear evidence
when members of the Board of Regents, the state's education policy
making board, visited last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found practices that seemingly replicated those at some
lower-performing schools in New York,'' said Sheila Evans-Tranumn,
associate commissioner of the state Education Department.
</P>
<P>
   The department raised questions about some classroom management
techniques and whether the school's curriculum was properly
balanced.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators also noted that the school had no room to add
another grade, as planned. After Sisulu made some changes to its
curriculum and personnel, including firing the teacher with
spelling problems, the Regents granted approval in December for the
Harriet Tubman Charter School to open in the Bronx next fall, to be
managed by Victory.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky says that since the changes, parents of Sisulu students
have given the school high marks. A recent survey of the parents of
100 Sisulu schoolchildren found 98 percent of them satisfied with
the school, Klinsky reports. (The findings echo national studies,
which have found that parents often rate their own children's
schools highly, even while disparaging the quality of education
generally.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Victory Schools will open two other charter schools in the fall
as well, the Merrick Academy-Springfield Gardens charter school in
southeast Queens and the Roosevelt Children's Academy on Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Victory has outpaced bigger, nationally known
school operators like Edison Schools and Advantage Schools. But
none of the companies nationally that have sought to make a profit
from public education have succeeded, and some have been
spectacular failures financially.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky attended public schools in the Detroit suburbs and
graduated from the University of Michigan, and he received both a
law degree and an M.B.A. from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   He then went to Wall Street, working at Goldman, Sachs and later
with Forstmann Little &AMP; Co., the leveraged buyout firm headed by
Ted Forstmann, the conservative philanthropist who also favors
educational causes.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky's management experience includes little in the field of
education. But he has surrounded himself with education and
financial experts, including Margaret R. Harrington, the former
superintendent for Queens high schools at the Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky, 43, was long inspired by education, an interest he
credits to the memory of his brother Gary, who was seven years
older and who died in 1978 at the age of 29 of Niemann-Pick
disease, a genetic enzyme deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Steven Klinsky established and named for his brother
the after-school program for elementary school students in East New
York.
</P>
<P>
   This experience taught Klinsky a few lessons he used in forming
a charter school company. Most important is that the operation
needs to be concentrated in a small geographic area, so it can hire
educators who can easily visit the schools to deal with problems.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the company can then spread those costs across
several schools, giving each a better chance of earning a profit
than it would have alone.
</P>
<P>
   The company charges Sisulu 15 percent of revenue for curriculum
development and overhead costs, and hopes to keep up to an
additional 7 percent of revenue as its management fee, or profit.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky also plans to continue investing, looking to buy
companies in communications and education, although he will not
invest in charter schools, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky's business acumen and his dedication to education, as
well as his company's ability to provide start-up money, is what
attracted Alma Alston, the founder of the Merrick Academy, to
Victory Schools. ``I'm pretty astute in terms of operating a
school,'' said Alston, who will be leaving her job as principal of
St. Peter Claver School in Queens. ``But someone has to look at the
business component of things as well.''
</P>
<P>
   With seven months to go before Victory is scheduled to open
three more new charter schools, Klinsky is upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My optimism comes from the belief that someone who has not
spent his entire career as part of the formal Board of Education
system can create a team of educators and business people to
energize something,'' he said. ``I could make a lot more money if I
was spending my time on the Internet than taking the subway back
and forth to 115th Street. But I have a social goal here. I want
this to be a sound enterprise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
