<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO INDUSTRY UNFAIRLY IS A TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Perhaps the most destructive aspect of the anti-smoking
campaign is how it undermines reverence for the truth.
</P>
<P>
   No deceptive claim, it seems, is too grotesque if it's in the
service of demonizing tobacco to legitimize plundering the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The president, for instance, recently trotted out what's perhaps
the most grotesque distortion of the truth while making a pitch for
boosting the federal tax on cigarettes by 25 cents a pack. ``Every
year,'' he lamented, ``more than 400,000 Americans die from
tobacco-related diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   This dubious claim has been bandied about for so long it's
accepted as gospel, which it's not. A couple of years ago, Robert
A. Levy and Rosalind B. Marimont did an analysis for Regulation
magazine exposing this highly questionable statistic for what it
is.
</P>
<P>
   Levy is a senior fellow in constitutional studies at the Cato
Institute and adjunct professor at Georgetown University Law Center
teaching Statistics for Lawyers. Marimont is a retired
mathematician who spent her career at the National Institute of
Health and the National Institute of Standards and Technology.
Their analysis can't be adequately explored in a column, but a
couple of their points are worth revisiting.
</P>
<P>
   The ``400,000 deaths a year'' claim emerged as a flawed
government assumption of what constitutes a smoking-related
disease. If the official death count excluded statistically
questionable causes, the number would have been about 40 percent
lower.
</P>
<P>
   Levy and Marimont also noted that another key study extrapolated
from a relatively small survey and ascribed the results to the
entire population. This method subtracted the deaths of those who
had never smoked from the total deaths and assumed the remainder to
be smoking-related. This study, they said, involved subjects with
atypically low death rates. When its result was applied to the
whole population, it created the illusion of more deaths from
smoking than could be realistically expected.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the deceit that involves creating the impression
that smoking causes widespread death at an inordinately early age.
Nobody would deny smoking presents the risk of a shorter life, but
the statistical difference is not as dramatic as implied.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in life expectancy, according to a 1991 Rand
study, is about 4.3 years at age 20. Another study showed that
tobacco was not responsible for any deaths below the age of 35. To
put this finding into perspective given all the talk about ``saving
the children,'' consider these numbers from the National Center for
Health Statistics: In 1992 more than 21,000 people below age 35
died from motor vehicle accidents, nearly 17,000 were homicide
victims and more than 11,000 were suicides. More than half these
deaths had a link with alcohol or drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to say smoking is good for you or to endorse its
use. Rather, it's to ask why, given all the other equally injurious
threats to our national health, the tobacco industry has been so
single-mindedly made the target for demonization.
</P>
<P>
   Think money. The crusade has much more to do with financial gain
than saving lives. Big Tobacco has deep pockets, and everyone wants
to get its Big Money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
