<SLUG> BC-SEX-SLAVES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL PANEL HEARS TESTIMONY ON INTERNATIONAL SEX
TRAFFICKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Duped into thinking they are leaving their home and
country for work and a better life, a million girls and women are
being forced into sexual slavery around the world every year,
witnesses told a U.S. Senate subcommittee Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sad fact that at this moment in history, people
still inflict on each other unspeakable and unbelievable horrors,''
said Frank E. Loy, undersecretary of state for global affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, a Kansas Republican, asked Loy and others to
testify at a hearing of the Senate Subcommittee on Near Eastern and
South Asian Affairs, of which he is chairman.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to India, Pakistan and Nepal, Brownback talked
to teen-age girls who had been tricked into leaving their homes for
domestic or nanny work, and then were held captive in brothels in
Asia, Europe and elsewhere. Their captors take their passports so
they cannot return home.
</P>
<P>
   About 50,000 women a year also are being brought into the United
States from Mexico and other countries, according to the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee heard Tuesday from a woman who was talked into
leaving Mexico in 1997 at age 18 to work in the United States. Two
men told her they would take care of her immigration papers and get
her a job at a Texas restaurant, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying herself only as Inez and shielding her face with a
scarf and large sunglasses, the woman said she was sent from Texas
to a trailer in Florida and told she would have to pay off a
``smuggling fee'' of $2,500 by selling her body for sex.
</P>
<P>
   If she refused or tried to escape, she would be beaten and her
family in Mexico would be harmed, the men told her. The woman said
she was forced to work six days a week, 12 hours a day, having sex
with 32 to 35 clients daily for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually federal agents raided the brothel. The women were
released to a domestic-violence center.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback and Sen. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota, ranking Democrat
on the subcommittee, said legislation was needed. Brownback has not
yet proposed anything, but Wellstone has a bill.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone proposes an interagency task force to monitor the
problem, stronger penalties, more services for victims, letting
victims stay in the United States on visas and allowing the
president to impose sanctions on countries that do not stem
trafficking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
