for the four New York City police officers charged in the death of
Amadou Diallo. Diallo, a black man, was standing, unarmed, in the
vestibule of his apartment building in the Bronx on Feb. 4, 1999.
The four officers, who are white, fired 41 shots at Diallo, killing
him and consequently sparking a wave of racial controversy over his
death. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ALBANY, N.Y. -- Feb. 22, 2000 -- NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-1 --
Kadiatou Diallo and Saikou Diallo, mother and father of Amadou
Diallo, leaving the Albany County courthouse with supporters on
Tuesday. Lawyers' summations came after three weeks of a trial that
was, at times, racially charged. The four officers, who are white,
fired 41 shots at Diallo, a black man who was standing, unarmed, in
the vestibule of his apartment building in the Bronx on Feb. 4,
1999. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LAKE WALES, Fla. -- Feb. 22, 2000 -- ORANGES-2 -- Driver
Doug AshIey, unhooks his truck cab from a full trailer at a fruit
yard in Lake Wales, during his second trip of the day from the
groves of N.R. Willimas, in Lake Wales. Today, Valencias are the
world's most popular orange, and they grow in every part of the
world where oranges thrive. (Ricardo J. Ferro/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) AUBURNDALE, Fla. -- Feb. 22, 2000 -- ORANGES-1 -- Jim
Walker, 70, owner of WalkerUs Groves in Auburndale in one of his
Valencia orange groves. ``They have about one more week to go
before they turn real sweet,'' says Walker. Today, Valencias are
the world's most popular orange, and they grow in every part of the
world where oranges thrive. (Ricardo J. Ferro/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Feb. 22, 2000 -- CITRUS-EATING-WELL -- Front,
from left: Meiwa kumquats, blood orange, limequats. Center: Sarawak
pomelo, blood and Seville oranges, cocktail grapefuit and
Oroblanco. Back: Oroblanco pomelo, Wong pomelo and pomelo. All make
for pleasurable eating, but also significant levels of vitamin C,
folic acid and potassium. (David Corio/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PHOENIX -- Feb. 22, 2000 -- REPUBS-PRIMARIES-7 -- Sen.
John McCain and his wife Cindy voting at the Veterans Memorial
Coliseum and Exposition Center in Phoenix on primary day, Tuesday.
McCain, a three-term senator from Arizona, is expected to win his
home state but desperately needed a victory in Michigan as well
after losing to Texas governor George W. Bush in the South Carolina
primary Saturday by 11 percentage points. (Chang W. Lee/The New
York Times)
</P>
