<P>
   (NYT4) DETROIT -- Feb. 22, 2000 -- REPUBS-PRIMARIES-4 -- Gov.
George W. Bush speaking on some local talk radio shows in Detroit
on a cell phone over breakfast this morning at Jimi's restaurant on
primary day, Tuesday. Early on, Bush predicted ``a close race'' in
Michigan's Republican presidential primary and slammed his rival
John McCain for engaging in ``shameful politics.'' (Andrea
Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DETROIT -- Feb. 22, 2000 -- REPUBS-PRIMARIES-3 -- Gov.
George W. Bush, with his wife Laura is at right, speaking with the
media on primary day in Michigan, as he arrived to greet breakfast
diners at Jimi's restaurant in Detroit on Tuesday. While the
Michigan primary is open to Democrats and independent voters, who
may make up as much as half the electorate, giving McCain some
hope. The Arizona primary is open to Republicans only. McCain voted
for himself Tuesday in Phoenix and said Michigan, like every other
state at this stage, was crucial. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. -- Feb. 22, 2000 --
MUSTSUB-REPUBS-PRIMARIES-2 -- Gov. George W. Bush and his wife
Laura at a rally at the Seidman Center of Youth Commonwealth in
Grand Rapids, Monday. The Michigan campaign ended in acrimony with
Bush accusing the McCain campaign of making thousands of telephone
calls to voters claiming that he was anti-Catholic. The McCain
campaign denied the charge. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
Attention editors this photo was taken at a rally on Monday, Feb.
21, 2000 not primary day, Tuesday, Feb. 22, 2000
